<HEADLINE>
WORST WATER-MAIN BREAK IN MEMORY CRIPPLES KC'S SUPPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL, LYNN HORSLEY and CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A water-main break believed to be the worst
in Kansas City's history cut service to 150,000 people, closed
businesses and forced residents to boil drinking water Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though workers restored service in a few hours, a boil-water
order remained in effect Monday night from the state line to
Eastern Avenue and from the Missouri River south to 63rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Officials cautioned against drinking unboiled tap water until
the lines had been fully flushed of pathogens. The boil order was
expected to be lifted later Tuesday. The Kansas City Water Services
Department believed it was the first such order in more than 100
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had major water-main breaks in the past, but none as
severe as this,'' Gurnie Gunter, Water Services director, said.
Officials were still trying to determine Monday night what caused
the break in the West Bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   There were no reported fires or injuries in the water outage.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 10 a.m. a 48-inch pipe near 25th and Allen
streets ruptured.
</P>
<P>
   An employee of Metals USA about two blocks away ran into the
warehouse, shouting, ``You guys better get out of here. The water's
coming up pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Water was gushing into the street, and a greenish-brown swamp
rapidly filled the low-lying area.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of past floods, Charles Donnelly, Metals USA president,
ordered employees to pile sandbags at doorways and activate sump
pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got a little scary,'' said Donnelly, adding that his
business was not damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the break, water pressure trickled to a halt
all over the city's center, and the effect was immediate. It forced
officials to shut down the Turkey Creek pumping station, one of the
city's primary stations.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial air-conditioning units dependent on water tanks
fizzled out. High-rise office buildings downtown, including City
Hall, were evacuated because fire sprinklers became inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   A few guests at the Kansas City Marriott Country Club Plaza were
caught midshower without water and had to rinse with bottled water,
said Craig Johnson, hotel general manager .
</P>
<P>
   The problem did not last as long as water department officials
had feared. Crews isolated the break about 11:50 a.m. and gradually
restored water pressure by 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By then, however, city officials had recommended that buildings
of more than four stories close, because there would be no water to
put out fires in high-rises. In addition to City Hall, the Jackson
County Courthouse closed, as did the U.S. District Courthouse, the
Bolling Federal Building and the Missouri State Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark Cards Inc. offices near Crown Center closed by noon,
and the 5,700 employees were sent home. Most seemed happy at their
unexpected day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of smiles for a Monday,'' one man said.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department moved its dispatchers to a backup location
at 1328 Agnes Ave. that had water service. The Fire Department also
moved some of its dispatchers to the same building. Both agencies
let some employees go home early.
</P>
<P>
   Across the affected area, tens of thousands of people suddenly
had to cope with the loss of a basic resource usually taken for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   At Penn Valley Community College, students stood in line for
registration while rest-room doors nearby were posted with white
signs and black letters: ``Out of order. No running water.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Missouri-Kansas City canceled summer classes.
</P>
<P>
   Across Oak Street at the Twin Oaks Apartments, a
university-owned complex, UMKC brought in portable toilets and
bottled water for residents.
</P>
<P>
   UMKC student Erin Skornia came to her boyfriend's aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to get him to take him to my place so he can take a
shower,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems touched neighborhoods too.
</P>
<P>
   Iona Kopp of the 4100 block of Genessee Street said she did not
know the water was off until she went to the sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to do my dishes, and there was no water,'' she said.
``You never miss the water until the world runs dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The water-main break was good news for restaurants on the Kansas
side, which did a brisk lunch business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy,'' said Scott Gipson, general manager of
Applebee's Neighborhood Grill &AMP; Bar on Rainbow Boulevard. ``The
people kept on coming.'' Gipson said the restaurant served an extra
150 customers from 11:30 a.m. to 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With water at no more than a trickle, several hospitals tapped
emergency supplies of bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Mercy shut off water elsewhere to maintain pressure
to an operating room where a lengthy operation was under way.
Truman Medical Center and St. Luke's Hospital diverted ambulances
from their emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's maintained rest-room sanitation by lining toilets
with red plastic medical-waste bags that could be easily disposed
of.
</P>
<P>
   To get through surgeries and dialysis treatments scheduled in
the morning, Veterans Hospital used three tanks of water on the
hospital's roof. By afternoon, however, the tanks were empty and
the hospital brought in bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Staffs at the affected hospitals kept their hands germ-free by
using waterless disinfecting hand cleansers or soap and bottled
water.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping patients cool became a serious issue. Trinity Lutheran
Hospital turned lights off to reduce the strain on its
air-conditioning system. Children's Mercy called in a water truck
to pump water into its cooling towers. And Truman brought fans out
of storage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, a lot of this stuff we ordered for Y2K''
preparations, said Truman spokeswoman Jennifer Sykes.
</P>
<P>
   Water department employees worked in water above their knees to
shut off the valves leading to the leak. By then, several million
gallons had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Officials first had to turn off the six to eight large pumps at
the Turkey Creek station. Meanwhile, engineers pulled out an atlas
of the city's network of water mains and shutoff valves and located
the ones closest to the break.
</P>
<P>
   Workers had to clamp two valves to the south and one to the
north to isolate the break, but the northern valve was hidden
underneath water.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the pumps off, workers had to wait nearly an hour
before the water drained sufficiently to expose the northern valve.
Crews finally found the valve's cast-iron lid, pulled it off and
used an 8-foot pole to reach in and turn it off.
</P>
<P>
   With that done, workers slowly restarted pumps, to restore
pressure gradually.
</P>
<P>
   City officials did not know what caused the break.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Goold, Water Department assistant director for distribution
and collection, said he had never heard of a 48-inch main breaking.
Although the main was about 40 years old, Goold said the age should
not have been a major factor, because concrete pipes usually last
100 years or more.
</P>
</TEXT>
