<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: EMPLOYEE OWNERSHIP DOESN'T SOLVE LABOR WOES AT
UNITED  AIRLINES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How bad are relations between United Airlines
and its pilots?
</P>
<P>
   On one United flight last week, a pilot got on the intercom to
explain why the plane was more than two hours late taking off.
</P>
<P>
   First, he denied media reports that pilots were calling in sick,
using his presence as living proof. Instead, he blamed the delay on
the fact that someone from United had scheduled only nine minutes
for an airport turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Then he ``joked'' that he hoped the same person wasn't
scheduling maintenance workers. To the astonishment of some
passengers, he continued making negative remarks about United and
its problems.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the kind of comments you'd expect to hear from the
cockpit of an employee-owned airline and spotlights the question:
Why hasn't United's employee stock ownership plan _ once praised to
the skies _ prevented its noisy labor dispute. Many of the
company's pilots and mechanics have refused to work overtime since
their contracts expired earlier this year, leading to delays and
flight cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   To find out, I called Corey Rosen, director of the National
Center for Employee Ownership in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons, Rosen says, are complex, but boil down to two
things: drawbacks in the plan's design, including a provision that
prevents employees from cashing in their stock until they leave the
company; and the lack of a long-term commitment to change United's
``militaristic'' corporate culture into one that truly puts
employees first, a la Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Established in July 1994, the ESOP gave employees, excluding
flight attendants, 55 percent of the company's stock in exchange
for pay and benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots were big proponents of the ESOP and ended up with 25
percent of United's stock, although they make up only 10 percent of
the workforce. They also made the biggest financial sacrifices,
says Ken Bradley, a United pilot and spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, the ESOP was hailed as a success, and it was
a success,'' Rosen says. ``In the first year, they set up BOB (best
of business) teams to look at basically everything the company did,
from fuel utilization to pass policies (which govern free tickets
for employees' families).''
</P>
<P>
   The teams came up with cost savings and morale-boosting measures
that boosted the bottom line. United's stock soared from $23
(split-adjusted) when the ESOP began to $98 in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step would be to institutionalize these ad hoc
teams,'' Rosen says. ``That didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As time went on, ``management got its back up about how they
would deal with pilots'' in their next contract negotiations. ``And
they stopped advertising themselves as an employee-owned company
(because) if you advertise yourself that way, customers are going
to expect employees to behave that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen says the failure to include flight attendants in the ESOP
was a near-fatal flaw. The attendants opted not to join because
they couldn't reach agreements with management on key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else there should have figured out a way to get the
flight attendants in,'' Rosen says. ``They're the face of the
airline to the public. If you'd had the flight attendants involved,
you might have had a more positive customer response and there
might have been a perception (among employees) that the ESOP was a
more-effective instrument for moving the company forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan also had certain design deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most ESOPs, United required participants to take a pay
cut, so some employees may not have perceived a net benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Second, whereas most ESOPs are ongoing, United only contributed
to the plan for five years and nine months.
</P>
<P>
   It worked like this: In 1994, the ESOP borrowed money to buy
United stock on behalf of employees. During the next five or so
years, United contributed money to the plan, and that money repaid
the loan. As the loan was repaid, shares were allocated to workers.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the period, contributions ended and employees had
their full allocation of stock. The end came in April for pilots
and July for mechanics. At that time, pay scales bounced back to
1994 levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees won't see any additional contributions made to the
account,'' Rosen says. ``The only change now is the increase or
decrease in value of the shares.''
</P>
<P>
   New employees are not part of the plan, and as participants
leave the company and sell their stock, the collective stake of
employees will shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Workers everywhere greet cultural change with a
``this-too-shall-pass'' attitude, and the ESOP's limited life span
``reinforced that problematic attitude,'' Rosen thinks.
</P>
<P>
   But the ESOP's biggest drawback, from a motivational standpoint,
is that employees can't cash in their stock until they leave the
company.
</P>
<P>
   This is standard for ESOPs, but most ESOPs are used by private
companies that don't have marketable securities.
</P>
<P>
   Most public companies use stock-option plans, in which employees
are periodically granted blocks of stock options. Each year, they
can cash in a portion of their options.
</P>
<P>
   But ESOPs have better tax advantages for employees and employers
than stock option plans. A spokeswoman for United says the company
chose an ESOP in part because ``the tax savings were tremendous for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike stock option plans, ESOPs also let employees aggregate
voting control, which gives unions more power.
</P>
<P>
   James Higgins, an analyst with Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette,
estimates that the average United pilot might have stock worth
about $120,000 in the ESOP, equal to about one year's salary. Not
bad, but he or she ``can't sell United shares and buy a
refrigerator.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen says United could amend its plan to permit payouts while
an employee is still with the company. ``I recommended they do
it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The United spokesman wasn't sure that's legally possible. And
even if it is, she says, the ESOP was designed to provide for
employees' retirement, not their immediate needs.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the United pilot, says the ESOP has ``zero intrinsic
value,'' because current employees can't sell their stock and have
no control over its price.
</P>
<P>
   Since its peak in late 1997, United stock has fallen by almost
half to $51 _ the result of competitive pressures, rising fuel
costs, uncertainty over United's bid for US Airways and its current
labor problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the pilots' perspective, the ESOP was a failure,''
Bradley says. ``Cultural change has been very limited ... and
management has reverted to an adversarial mode.'' In response, he
admits, the union ``has reacted in an adversarial way.''
</P>
<P>
   United management sees the ESOP as a success.
</P>
<P>
   It let United reduce its cost structure and immediately
strengthen its competitive position, says spokesman Matt Triaca. It
also led to ``fairly stable relations'' with unions. As part of the
deal, during the five-plus years the ESOP was active, no union
contracts expired except for one with the flight attendants, and
they agreed to a new 10-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also allowed United to set up its lower-cost Shuttle
service, which gave the airline a presence in important new markets
like the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen believes the ESOP has been a ``qualified success'' for
labor and management. ``Who it has not worked for is the customer
and the shareholder. United has been more or less as good an
investment as any other airline,'' he says. ``But most companies
get a lot more mileage out of employee ownership than United did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Neidl, an analyst with ING Barings, agrees. ``At one time, I
was in favor of the ESOP. I thought if you gave employees ownership
they'd act more like owners than typical unionized employees. I
haven't seen it at United.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that United pilot who criticized the company from the
cockpit, Bradley says the union does not condone such behavior.
But, he explains, ``the frustration levels are very, very high.
Pilots have been subjected to a lot of abuse'' by passengers and
the public.
</P>
<P>
   The company's response: ``The vast majority of our employees are
continuing to perform their jobs as professionals,'' Triaca says.
</P>
<P>
