 &HT;    CROSSING THE BORDER TO ABSURDITY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Turns out they don't take volunteers for jury duty.
I called down to the federal courthouse in Tucson to offer my
services as a juror in the case of a lawsuit filed by a Javier
Bencomo Arreola of Chihuahua, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, I was told. First, I live in Phoenix, which is far enough
away to be considered ``an undue hardship or extreme
inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't mind the drive, I said. Not for this case.
</P>
<P>
   Second, federal law requires the jury pool for any given case to
be filled by ``random selection of citizens' names.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier Bencomo Arreola is not a citizen of the United States. He
is, however, suing a pair of U.S. citizens - Linda Louise and
Andreas Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I'm volunteering for jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   Bencomo Arreola wants the Muellers to forfeit $300,000 for
having scared the bejabbers out of him April 5. It seems Bencomo
Arreola was part of a group of undocumented immigrants passing
through an area near the Muellers' property in southern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   All along the border, ranchers and farmers and other ordinary
folks have gotten the feeling that they are under siege. Probably
because they (beginitalic)are (enditalic)under siege.
</P>
<P>
   The border is less like a border these days and more like the
front lines of a battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people crossing into Arizona from Mexico are not
evil or dangerous. But that doesn't mean they can't do harm to
people or property. And it doesn't mean they can't be frightening
to those who hear them and see them passing through in the night.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Border Patrol can't stop the flow, American citizens
now patrol their properties with guns. Sometimes, they detain
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Bencomo Arreola's lawyer, Fernando Gaxiola, says the Muellers
went too far down the dangerous road of vigilantism. He says the
couple set a dog on the group, and that Andreas Mueller cornered
the border crossers and threatened them with a rifle, even though
his client was not technically on his property. For now, the
parties involved in the lawsuit aren't talking. The courts are a
slow grinding machine. If, however, the case ever goes to trial,
I'd like to volunteer my services as a juror.
</P>
<P>
   The laws of the United States are available for use by everyone,
even those who aren't citizens. That makes it possible for Bencomo
Arreola to file suit and even to win.
</P>
<P>
   Unless I am on the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration policy is not always fair and reasonable. Many good
folks are kept out. Still, breaking into a country is a lot like
breaking into a house. The people in the house have no right to
harm you, unless you threaten their lives. But they must have a
right to shoo you off, to detain you, to scare the living daylights
out of you.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the neighborly thing to do, but it's difficult to
be hospitable with uninvited guests, let alone uninvited guests who
return again and again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Javier Bencomo Arreola deserves the benefit of the doubt, of
course. He deserves an opportunity to make a better life for
himself and his family, if he does so legally. He deserves our
attention. He deserves our concern. He deserves our best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   And he deserves not one red cent of the Muellers' money.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (a)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8978.
</P>
</TEXT>
