<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-WELCOMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES MAYOR WELCOMES DELEGATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was California's day in the sun at the opening
of the Democratic National Convention with Mayor Richard Riordan
heading a contingent of local, state and federal officials in
welcoming delegates to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, a Republican treading in enemy territory, appeared with
about 30 L.A. children Monday, sounding very like a Democrat in his
impassioned speech calling for higher teacher salaries and
repudiating the notion minorities cannot learn because of their
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles and our country are enjoying prosperity unknown in
the history of the world,'' Riordan said. ``However, too many
people, particularly minorities, have been left behind. We owe
everybody the tools to get and keep high-quality, high-paying
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   For Riordan, the speech also gave him an opportunity to boast of
the city and its economy over the past several years, accompanied
by a fast-cut film with hard-driving rock music showing off
different areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was but one of many California officials and others
who addressed the standing-room-only crowd at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Los
Angeles, provided the opening invocation at the afternoon session.
</P>
<P>
   He asked God to ``keep us ever committed to protect the life and
well-being of all people, but especially unborn children, the sick
and the elderly, those on Skid Row and those on Death Row.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahony also said he hoped candidates would embody values that
``protect all human life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis and California's two U.S. Senators, Barbara
Boxer and Dianne Feinstein, as well as Los Angeles County
Supervisor Gloria Molina also addressed the crowd, and they were
not afraid to attack Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is (Vice President) Al Gore country,'' Davis said.
``Californians welcome the party of President Bill Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore. I ask you if you are better off today than you
were eight years ago. You better believe you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer and Feinstein also struck out against Republicans,
particularly on school vouchers and the right for women to choose
on abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer also offered a direct challenge to the GOP assertion that
the Clinton administration has missed an opportunity during the
economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were given a chance, we led,'' Boxer said. `They had
their chance and they were unsuccessful. That's why they were
defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   And Molina, speaking in both English and Spanish, said the city
and the Democratic Party offered similar opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``With dreams, hard work and a desire to succeed, everyone can
be successful,'' Molina said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, a Republican treading in enemy territory, appeared with
about 30 L.A. children and sounded more like a Democrat with an
impassioned speech calling for higher teacher salaries and
repudiating the notion that minorities cannot learn because of
their environment.
</P>
