<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEMS1STLEDEWRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CVN-DEMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  1stLEDE WRITETHRU 
 
Tightens; adds graphs on protests; Gore watching proceedings from
St. Louis 
 
CLINTON BIDS GOODBYE TO PARTY, PASSES MANTEL TO GORE 
 
By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declaring that prosperity during his administration has made the
United States ``more decent, more humane, more united,'' President
Clinton bid a long goodbye to his party Monday and extended credit
for his success to his would-be successor, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be the last major address of his presidency, Clinton
starred on opening night of the Democratic National Convention,
revisiting the ``bridge to the 21st century'' theme of his 1996
campaign, and saying the nation is better off now than it was eight
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1992, America has grown, not just economically, but as a
community,'' Clinton said. ``We are growing more diverse and more
united. But we're not just better off, we're also a better country
_ more decent, more humane, more united. Now, that's the purpose of
prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke at Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles, however,
a nearby rock concert for convention protesters erupted into a
violent confrontation. Demonstrators threw chunks of concrete and
police responded with pepper spray and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Police herded the demonstrators to the far end of a designated
protest area, pushing them away from the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, as he prepared to pass the mantle of party leadership to
Gore, Clinton praised the vice president's tenure amid sustained,
enthusiastic applause from the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al and I have worked closely together for eight years now. In
the most challenging moments, when we faced the most difficult
issues _ of war and peace, of taking on powerful special interests
_ he was always there,'' according to the text of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., watched
the evenings proceedings together in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great speech,'' Gore said afterward. ``I
appreciated the generous and kind words he said about me and
Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than five months left in his second and final term as
president, Clinton said, ``we built our bridge to the 21st century.
We crossed it together. And we're not going back.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the timeline of the 2000 presidential campaign, Clinton's
speech _ his fourth before a national convention audience _ served
as a transitional moment as 4,370 delegates stand poised to
nominate Gore for the presidency on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton also seized what may be his last chance
before a national audience to take credit for the country's
economic prosperity, rebutting claims by Texas Gov. George W. Bush
and Republican leadership that his policies have been meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of these eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear: America's
success was not a matter of chance, it was a matter of choice,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's address capped an evening of speeches and
tributes on the theme of ``prosperity and progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights included a video honoring former President
Carter, the only other living Democratic president, appearances by
female U.S. senators, and a brief address by first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, herself a candidate for an open U.S. Senate seat in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The opening day of the convention also included the first
significant confrontation between police and a portion of the
estimated 50,000 protesters converging on the city for the four-day
event.
</P>
<P>
   Blocks from the Staples Center, hundreds of protesters clashed
with police in riot gear, resulting in 10 arrests. The
demonstrators, environmentalists objecting to Gore's ties to
Occidental Petroleum Corp., blocked a downtown intersection and
taunted police who ordered them to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, protests around the convention hall had been
raucous but largely without confrontation. For several days, the
police presence around the convention facility has been highly
visible and large in number.
</P>
<P>
   In protests of a more political nature, Republican leaders
joined together to scoff at Democratic claims of achievement on
Monday, saying Clinton and Gore are building themselves up to be
something they're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a candidate for the Democrats who can't lead, is
hesitant to take a position, and America's surveys are showing
consistently they can't wait until Nov. 7 so we can have a change
in direction in this country,'' said U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this reinvention convention, Al Gore is trying to rewrite
history,'' Bonilla said.
</P>
<P>
   In her address to the delegates, Hillary Clinton stuck largely
to the softer themes of children and families.
</P>
<P>
   In 20-minute remarks, the first lady thanked the nation for her
time in the White House, touched on key Democratic campaign themes
and made a single reference to her own campaign against Republican
Rick Lazio back in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it will be up to the people of New York to decide
whether I'll have the privilege of serving them in the United
States Senate,'' Clinton said, adding ``I will always be profoundly
grateful to all of you and to the American people for the last
eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the title of a book she authored on raising children,
the first lady said, ``You know, I still believe it takes a
village.'' She went on to say that Gore and his running mate,
Lieberman, ``have what it takes, and they'll do what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The departing first lady, whose tenure has at times been stormy,
controversial and unpopular with the mainstream American public,
said, ``Really, the most important thing that I can say tonight is:
Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the convention, both Clintons have
come under fire from within their own party for failing to stay
sufficiently out of sight during what should be Gore's moment to
shine.
</P>
<P>
   The high-wattage Clinton duo have been mingling with Hollywood
celebrities and raising millions of dollars in campaign funds since
arriving in Los Angeles over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, struggling to come out from behind Clinton's shadow
and establish himself as a viable next leader for the nation, their
activities have proved a persistent distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic advisers and leadership are hoping the Clinton factor
will diminish as the week progresses and momentum builds toward
Gore's nomination speech on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country wants to hear from Gore,'' said Democratic
strategist James Carville. ``Between now and November, it's Gore's
turn. But the president sometimes has a hard time keeping his
opinions to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   According to some accounts, Clinton has been kept largely out of
the loop by the Gore campaign, and is not privy to its strategies
and machinations.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll released by Fox News/Opinion Dynamics cited 68
percent of Americans who thought Gore should ask Clinton to stay
home from campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to leave Los Angeles early Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter, in an interview with NBC, said Gore is
coming into his own in the minds of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the escapades of President Clinton in the White
House are still in people's memories but I think that time is
passing by,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning in Missouri as the convention got under way in
California, continued to stress his key commitments to fixing
Social Security and Medicare, but avoided direct confrontation with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people on the other ticket are good men, I'll never attack
them personally,'' Gore said, referring to Bush and running mate
Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Gore said, ``The American people need to know the
specifics of how the American people would be affected if the other
side won.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to arrive in Los Angeles Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
