<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS15-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLICE, PROTESTERS CLASH OUTSIDE CONVENTION
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS and SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Police in riot gear clashed Monday night with
protesters outside the Democratic National Convention after
demonstrators pelted officers with chunks of concrete and steel
balls fired from slingshots.
</P>
<P>
   Police responded with pepper spray, rubber bullets and finally a
charge on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they moved on the crowd after protestors started
fires and refused to clear an area near where the presidential
motorcade was expected to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to tolerate lawlessness,'' Sgt. John
Pasquariello of the Los Angeles Police Dept told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The clash occurred in an area near the Staples Center designated
for protests and involved about 300 of 8,000 people gathered
outside the convention hall. The altercation began as thousands
began to leave a rock concert by Rage Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble then spread as more police rushed to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters with bandannas over their faces lit several fires in
the concert area. The ground around police was littered with rocks,
broken bottles and sticks thrown over a fence by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against The Machine is anti-authoritarian and has
campaigned in support of such figures as Mumia Abu-Jamal, who is on
death row for killing a Philadelphia police officer in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the trouble started quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw no particular provocation,'' said homeless activist
Robert Norse, 53. ``Suddenly, the crowd started to run in my
direction. The police were shouting 'Move. Move.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Cruz resident said bedlam then broke out. A friend was
clubbed in the back, Norse said, and people were hit with rubber
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Johnson, a 46-yeard-old journalist from Santa Cruz, also
said the onset of trouble came suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was eating a hot dog,'' she said, ``and all of a suddden
people started rushing and screaming in panic.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was clubbed in the back by police.
</P>
<P>
   Before the melee, the mood had been festive.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, hundreds of environmental activists jammed
intersections near the convention site to demand that Vice
President Al Gore sever his ties to the Los Angeles-based
Occidental Petroleum Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, featuring giant puppets portraying the evils of
capitalism, proceeded peacefully from a downtown park to the
designated dissent site near the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   But after some protesters refused to leave the area, police
locked batons to herd them away and clear the streets. About a
dozen protesters were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Atossa Soltani, founder of the environmental group Amazon Watch,
told the gathering that the Gore family ties to Occidental ``makes
him no better than Bush.'' He challenged Gore to ``show us you are
an environmental champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Occidental has rights to conduct exploratory drilling a few
miles outside the legal boundaries of the U'wa Indian reserve in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's late father, Al Gore Sr., served on the Occidental board
after losing his Senate re-election bid in 1968. Between $500,000
and $1 million in Occidental stock is currently held in trust for
Gore's mother, Pauline.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon Watch released a letter to Gore signed by singer Bonnie
Raitt and actors Martin Sheen and Susan Sarandon suggesting that
Gore's decision to retain his Occidental ties was not only a matter
of environmental concern but ``a question of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway dismissed the protests, saying,
``Al Gore has been a champion of the environment his entire public
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush, the governor of
Texas, and Bush's running mate, Dick Cheney, both have professional
and political ties to the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the environment wasn't all protesters were concerned
about, judging by the variety of messages on the signs they
carried. They ran the gamut from ``One Nation Under Corporation''
to ``Stop Patents of Indigenous Medicines.'' One sign read: ``All
government is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
