<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-ASSESS-1STLD-WRIT     08-15 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: CLINTON SEEKS BALANCE OF LEAVING AND HELPING GORE
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS with updating thruout including quotes from Clinton that were
slight deviations from prepared text) 
By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The transfer of power is one of the key tests of
democracy. At the governmental level, the United States has managed
it exceptionally well ever since George Washington, hero of the war
that brought the nation into being, handed over to John Adams in
1797.
</P>
<P>
   But before the reins of government can pass from one hand to
another, party leadership must be transferred, in a process for
which there is no set of statutes and no rulebook. It has often
proved difficult for sitting presidents, especially in the modern
era, when vice presidents more or less automatically seek the
presidency. So it has proved for President Clinton, despite largely
cordial relations with Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Clinton sought to lift the Gore campaign onto a
new, smoother road. He described Gore as ``a profoundly good man''
whom he had come to know well in eight years. But his words about
Gore did not form the emotional climax of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Gore takes over the leadership of the
Democratic party this week. That was decided when he saw off his
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, in the primaries.
But what remains to be decided is how thoroughly he can put his
stamp on the party. Can he make it his own? Or will he be deemed
only second-best by the party faithful?
</P>
<P>
   Another question: Will Clinton really let go of the baton? The
Clintons hope, of course, to retain a presence in Washington in the
form of a New York Senate seat _ something the delegates here were
constantly reminded of _ and if they do so Clinton will surely be
part of that presence.
</P>
<P>
   That was the subtext Monday night as the president, wildly
popular among his fellow Democrats through the ups and downs of the
last eight years, appeared before the convention. The hard fact is
Gore needs help, most of all from Clinton. Paradoxically, he needs
both the enthusiastic endorsement of the president and his help in
escaping the long presidential shadow.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that seemed at times more like a State of the Union
address than anything else, Clinton was unstinting in his praise of
his vice president. During ``the most difficult days,'' the
president said, Gore ``was always there.'' He added: ``More than
anybody else I've ever known in public life, Al Gore understands
the future and how sweeping changes and scientific breakthroughs
will affect ordinary Americans' daily lives.'' But unlike Ronald
Reagan, who promised at the 1988 convention that he would gladly
serve as ``a foot soldier'' in George Bush's forthcoming campaign
if needed, Clinton studiously avoided a pledge to crisscross the
country this fall for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking also to the television audience, he made an untypically
restrained comment that stopped short of a direct appeal for votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how I feel,'' he said. ``But it's not my decision to
make. That belongs to the American people. I just want to tell all
of you gathered in this great arena a few things I know about Al
Gore.'' All in all, the Clintons will have spent more than three
days here by the time they leave on Tuesday morning. Before he
spoke Monday night, Clinton had delivered seven other officially
announced speeches Monday, and no doubt some off-hand remarks as
well. He and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who have raised
money with a zeal unmatched by any first family in history,
apparently saw no need to deviate from their routine during Gore's
big week here, even when the people closest to Gore gnashed their
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   They were almost as omnipresent as the morning mist this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast with Reagan's 1988 behavior was sharp. He spent
only 48 hours at the New Orleans convention that year, scheduled
only three public appearances and made a determined effort to
transfer some of his inner fire, and a bit of his electoral appeal,
to his more diffident No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, when Reagans again slipped offstage quickly and
quietly, leaving Washington without even staying for the
post-inaugural lunch at the Capitol, Elaine Crispen, Nancy Reagan's
press secretary, explained their attitude this way: ``It's a sense
of what's right. It's their party. It's the Bushes' victory. Let's
let them enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   After initially giving him only a lukewarm endorsement, Reagan
had campaigned hard for George Bush, the father of this year's
Republican nominee, emerging in the final days of the campaign as
Bush's main surrogate. He traveled some 25,000 miles.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Late in the 1960 campaign, after describing himself as ``just a
spectator,'' Dwight D. Eisenhower leapt into the fray in a bid to
save the day for his vice president, Richard Nixon. It was a
stirring sight, James Reston wrote in The New York Times that fall,
``the old pro coming off the bench and swinging for the fences for
the last time.'' John F. Kennedy won anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton will do the same remains up in the air.
Democratic state chairmen from New Jersey to Wisconsin to Oregon
have been pressing Clinton to stump hard for Gore, in the hope that
he could brighten a campaign that has often seemed inert and
uninspired. The White House has said it will let Gore make the
decision, but the chairmen, by and large, think the president's
presence on the trail is worth the gamble that he might well remind
voters how much more exciting than his protege he can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have the president in this state every chance I got,''
said Kam Kuwata, a California campaign consultant. ``We need the
energy, and he's the one who has the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds are Clinton will answer the call. Sooner or later, as
election day approached, each one of the presidents since World War
II whose vice presidents were seeking to succeed them has felt the
pull of the stump.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates on the floor lustily cheered both the president and
the first lady Monday night. But they were divided in another
respect. Some, like Eleanor Sobel, a state representative from
Hollywood, Fla., said Gore could carry the party banner as well as
Clinton, and argued that it was time now for the president to move
on. Others, like Greg Salazar from Las Vegas, N.M., expressed
concern that Clinton would overshadow Gore. But even Salazar said
that if the race looked close, ``the president should come out in
public and ask the people to vote for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has never had a coup d'etat. It shares that
distinction with Britain and only a few other countries. In fact,
only once in more than two hundred years has the outcome of a
national election, and hence the right to the presidency, been
disputed beyond the Electoral College's verdict. That was in 1876,
when the Democrats charged that the Republicans had stolen the
election for Rutherford B. Hayes, and even then, the inaugural went
ahead right on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But president after president has wrestled with the question of
his own succession. Eisenhower tried in 1955 to ease Nixon out of
the Cabinet, toying with the names of Henry Cabot Lodge and Nelson
A. Rockefeller as possible replacements. Asked five years later to
name ``a major idea'' of Nixon's that he had adopted,'' the
president answered, in a tone of overwhelming boredom, ``If you
give me a week, I might think of one. I don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   In his turn, Nixon decided in the spring of 1971 that John
Connally, the former governor of Texas, should be his successor,
not Spiro Agnew. But when Agnew was forced to resign in 1973, Nixon
was unable to win assurances of confirmation by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was as conflicted as Lyndon B. Johnson. He was
furious that his vice president, Hubert Humphrey, harbored doubts
about the Vietnam War, and he told friends that ``Hubert cries too
much.'' For a time, he toyed with the idea of trying to get himself
drafted for another term in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Only on Nov. 3, 1968, at the tail-end of the campaign, did he
give his full-throated backing to Humphrey, standing next to him at
the Astrodome in Houston and shouting, ``That man, my friend and
co-worker for 20 years, is a healer and a builder and will
represent all of the people all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The tensions between Clinton and Gore never became as severe as
those in some past administrations. But this handoff has not been
without significant friction, and Gore can afford little of that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0032EDT &QL; 
