<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1952 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-HILLARY-CLINTON-A     08-15 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-HILLARY-CLINTON-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON REVELS IN THE ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs for earlier version to include speech coverage, tone and
reaction on convention floor)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ CVN10,13 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Rodham Clinton celebrated her husband's
years in office and proclaimed her faith in Al Gore to an audience
of thousands of cheering Democrats Monday night. She also used the
moment to advance her bid for the Senate as she luxuriated in a
level of attention unimaginable for a candidate conducting her
first campaign for public office.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Clinton arrived at the Democratic National
Convention hall here, she had already been interviewed by all three
network anchors for segments on the evening news, as well as by
CNN's Larry King. It was a feast of prime-time exposure that left
her aides ecstatic, surpassed only by the 17 minutes in prime time
she enjoyed before a partisan audience that applauded her review of
her years in the White House and her mention of the political
career she has embarked upon in running for senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill and I are closing one chapter of our lives, and soon,
we'll be starting a new one,'' she said. ``For me, it will be up to
the people of New York to decide whether I'll have the privilege of
serving them in the United States Senate. I will always be
profoundly grateful to all of you and to the American people for
the last eight years. Really, the most important thing that I can
say tonight is, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also benefited from the lagging pace of the first night
of the convention: she started 20 minutes late, assuring live
coverage by all three networks.
</P>
<P>
   In her speech and in her interviews with the networks, Clinton
went to considerable lengths to praise the record of her husband
and the credentials of the man seeking to succeed him, fulfilling
the typical role of a prominent convention speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to stand here at this extraordinary moment _ the
most peaceful, prosperous, promising time in our nation's
history,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was no ordinary surrogate, talking about the party's
standard-bearer. Throughout her speech, she framed her praise of
Gore and the Democratic Party in ways that served to reinforce the
issues and attacks on her opponent in New York, Rep. Rick Lazio.
They were issues that she has raised over the summer in both
campaign speeches and in her television advertisements. She
discussed her support for raising the minimum wage, new gun-control
laws, abortion rights, and even her ill-fated advocacy of a
national health care program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a few ideas about health care,'' she said. `` I've
learned a few lessons since then. But I haven't given up on the
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also interspersed her speech with details about her life
growing up, and suggested that she played a key role in the White
House in the enactment of legislation expanding foster care,
reinforcing what has been one of the dominant themes of her
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With her speech Monday, Clinton ended one of the more unusual
political trips undertaken by a candidate running for office from
New York. She spent four days in California, and while the purpose
of the trip was to accompany Bill Clinton for his last convention
as a sitting president, she turned almost every moment toward
advancing her own campaign for Senate: raising money, giving
interviews to New York newspapers and television stations and,
Monday, giving the speech and sitting down for interviews with
Peter Jennings, Dan Rather and Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's schedule contrasted sharply with that of her opponent
during the Republican convention just two weeks ago, when Lazio
spent just one day in Philadelphia. In New York Monday, Lazio went
to Planet Hollywood to mock Clinton's efforts, and his aides
discouraged the argument that it would do her any good in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important is being here in New York,'' Lazio said,
standing in front of a cut-out photograph of Sylvester Stallone.
``I think the most important thing is to be in New York and talk
about New York issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady viewed tonight's speech as a key moment in her
national life, as well as her Senate campaign. And she could not
have asked for a more receptive audience. When she spoke at the
Democratic convention in 1996, in a year in which she had been a
target of Republican attacks, delegates had offered her an ecstatic
reception. This time, after four years marked by the impeachment of
her husband and his public acknowledgment of an extramarital sexual
encounter, the crowd was once again exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to quiet the crowd several times, and remained relaxed
and poised throughout her speech. At times, she spoke passionately
about favorite topics, like child health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may not have been necessary, there were elaborate
preparations to get the crowd warmed up for Clinton and the
president. Thirty minutes before she was to speak, young aides
circulated through the arena passing out arm-loads of Hillary
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get it together,'' one woman called out in the
New York delegation. Another tried to get a chant going _ ``We need
a woman senator in New York state now'' _ prompting Sen. Charles
Schumer, who was elected in 1998, to stand and say, ``At least you
didn't say it two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort worked: On the floor, the aisles were packed to the
point that it was nearly impossible for anyone to move _ even
senators, like Tom Harkin of Iowa, who entered under the escort of
several aides, or Sen. Robert Torricelli, who entered with his
wife, Patricia Duff. In the New York section, 14 delegates stood
with signs that spelled `Senator Hillary.'' and thousands more
waved ``Hillary'' signs. For the first time of the evening, the
arena exploded with flashbulbs. Hardly a single Gore-Lieberman sign
could be seen throughout her address.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took the podium to the sounds of the song, ``New York,
New York,'' and delegates in the hall sang along as Clinton
prepared to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made no mention of Lazio in her speech. She was more
discursive in the interviews she taped during the day with the
network anchors, using a question about why some voters dislike the
Clintons as a way of hitting the issues with which she has sought
to distinguish herself from Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not people that are ever going to vote for me and
what I stand for,'' she said on CBS. ``You know, they aren't
pro-choice, they are happy to let the gun lobby, you know, decide
what our laws are. They have a very different view of where we
should go when it comes to the future of New York and America.''
</P>
<P>
   That Clinton agreed to such an extensive schedule of network
interviews was notable. Clinton has until now resisted interviews
with the national media, as her aides argued it would not help _
and might actually hurt _ her effort to transform herself into a
candidate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, though, Clinton's advisers have concluded that the
key to winning the contest with Lazio, given the registration
advantage Democrats have in New York, is to present the contest
partisan, Republican-Democratic terms, rather than as a referendum
on Clinton herself. Thus, they said Monday, they have decided to
encourage coverage of Clinton attending what is in effect a
four-day celebration of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Lazio paid only a cursory visit to the Republican
convention, and did not participate in any of its official events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
