<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN ROCKED IN LOSS TO MARLINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There is this team that sometimes provides hope, but
every time you believe in the players, they give reason to say,
``nope.''
</P>
<P>
   They had their ace on the mound, but he got knocked all around,
and in the end there are answers for which you grope.
</P>
<P>
   The team? The Los Angeles Dodgers, who lost to the Florida
Marlins 11-2 Monday at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With distractions supposedly out the way, right-hander Kevin
Brown kicked off a three-game series against the afterthought
Florida Marlins with one of the shortest outings of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The defense didn't help by committing three errors in the first
two innings, but Brown (10-5) certainly wasn't even close to sharp
as he allowed nine runs (five earned) in 1 innings in one of the
more shocking days this season. One of the errors occurred after
Carlos Perez relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the errors they made might have gotten him mad,'' said
Florida left fielder Henry Rodriguez, who had two hits and three
RBI in the first two innings. ``Maybe the (57-minute) rain delay
got him mad. His fastball wasn't sinking as much as it usually
does. Maybe he got upset or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't wait around afterward to speak, instead saying ``If
I wanted to talk, don't you think I'd be waiting in the
clubhouse,'' as he left the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson voiced concern about Brown's right
side. Brown has a rib irritation on his right side, which bothered
himafter his last start. He received a cortisone shot Friday in
Atlanta, and didn't go in for treatment after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was feeling good,'' Dodgers trainer Stan Johnston said.
``He reported to me after (the game) that he didn't feel it at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson remains concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He warmed up good. That's what (pitching coach) Claude
(Osteen) told me,'' Johnson said. ``He wasn't throwing the ball
where he wanted to, and that's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not what the Dodgers had in mind after what they thought
could be a lightning-rod kind of day.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Dodgers entered the day having won just two of
their last eight, there was a strong feeling things were about to
turn around. They were coming off a win at Atlanta and were only
4games behind San Francisco in the National League West despite
playing poorly for the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Management also tried to ease the collective mind of the
clubhouse by publicly stating after Sunday's game against the
Braves that Johnson and his staff would remain for the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still battling and trying to turn things around,''
Dodgers right fielder Shawn Green said. ``We'll try to win the
series and salvage the road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed four runs in the first and five more in the
second. Errors by Kevin Elster, Adrian Beltre and Mark Grudzielanek
contributed to the dismal outing as the Dodgers trailed 4-2 after
the first inning and 9-2 after the second.
</P>
<P>
   Of Brown's 371 career starts, only four have been shorter. Only
once did he allow more runs. It was his shortest outing since June
22, 1995, when he lasted four outs against Boston when he was
pitching for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very painful injury,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley
said. ``I had (a rib injury) earlier, but I go by his stuff and he
didn't look like he was injured tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
