<SLUG> BC-DEM-JACKSON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THIS CONVENTION, IT'S JESSE JACKSON JR. IN THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 6th graf and add new 7th and 8th grafs about concerns of
black delegates) By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At Democratic conventions past, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson wrote a compelling piece of the story line. The 1988
convention in Atlanta, for instance, was consumed with the question
of how warmly Jackson would embrace Michael Dukakis, who had
defeated him in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's convention, however, Jackson's son and namesake,
Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., is the one making waves by giving public
voice to the concerns within the party's left wing about its
centrist ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It began on Saturday, at a forum at the University of Southern
California, when the third-term Chicago Democrat was asked whether
people should vote for Vice President Al Gore. ``The only option is
Al Gore,'' he responded. ``But if there was another campaign that
was speaking to our issues that had the possibility and
plausibility of winning, we should support that campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, at another forum, this one part of the ``Shadow
Convention'' organized by a coalition of left-leaning groups,
Jackson made it clear that he would campaign aggressively for the
Gore-Lieberman ticket. But he continued to cast his decision as one
driven more by his fear of the alternative _ electing Gov. George
W. Bush and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference after the speech, Jackson said: ``I am
supporting Mr. Gore and Mr. Lieberman and I'm doing it as
enthusiastically as I can. But Jackie Wilson is not on the ticket,
and Elvis Presley is not on the ticket, so Mr. Excitement is not
running for president. This is about pragmatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there has been low-level tension among Democrats,
tension that has surfaced anew since Gore's selection of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as his running mate _ that pits centrists against
Democratic liberals. While a moderate message is seen as necessary
to win undecided independent voters, the party's left wing argues
that a more traditional agenda is needed to excite minorities and
other voters from the Demcrats' base. Some liberals have complained
about Lieberman's support for federal vouchers to pay for private
school tuition and about his statements in opposition to
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lieberman is expected to address some of those
concerns at a meeting of black delegates here, and several Gore
campaign officials have been acting as ambassadors to concerned
black Democrats, assuring them that Lieberman's record is
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns are something the Gore campaign could do without
as it tries to generate enthusiasm for its candidate, and seeks to
motivate a traditional base that include minorities, women and
union members.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would try to persuade disillusioned liberal
Democrats from defecting to Ralph Nader and the Green Party. And he
criticized the Gore campaign's recent emphasis on restoring the
country's sense of morality, something his vice presidential
choice, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, has emphasized throughout his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we start getting into this personal-life litmus test we
are deep in Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson territory,'' the
younger Jackson said, ``and that is unfamiliar Democratic real
estate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Jackson, meanwhile, has not stayed silent, and on
Monday made essentially the same point as his son. ``If it means we
have to hold our noses and take castor oil, do it,'' the elder
Jackson urged a group of voters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Minority voters, the elder Jackson said, would become enthused
about voting Democratic when they begin to view the campaign as a
choice not just between presidential candidates but between
distinct ideologies. ``Gore and Lieberman are quarterbacks but the
team is much broader than that,'' he said in an interview. ``And
when I see what our alternatives are I am inspired to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reverend Jackson is scheduled to speak at the convention on
Tuesday night. Though he has had starring roles at past
conventions, he said he was not bothered by the fact that he was
slated to appear before network television coverage begins.
``Whenever I speak,'' he said, ``it's prime time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
