<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TOO MANY CHICKENS IN THE ROAD  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Why did the chickens cross the road?
</P>
<P>
   To get to the middle, where it's safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats now execute their half of the Chicken Run, in
which compassionate conservatism meets puritanical liberalism in
the center divide, from where they can panhandle the traffic from
both directions.
</P>
<P>
   There should be a ceremony, like the one at Promontory Point in
Utah when the Union Pacific RR met with the Central Pacific RR and
they drove a golden spike.
</P>
<P>
   The Repubs and Dems could bury a golden hatchet and form a
Gore-Bush ticket. Al and W would win in a landslide, after
campaigning from the back of what Lotta Dotz calls a Gore-Bush
truck. Then they would take turns being president.
</P>
<P>
   IT WAS SAD when Gore snubbed the political fund-raising party at
the L.A. mansion of Hugh Hefner, who has always been a crusading
liberal. I didn't read any reaction comments from Hefner, which is
too bad, because he would have made hot news:
 &UR; Hef in huff over Demo rebuff! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the irony. The Democrats stiffed Hef because they're
stressing family values. Don't they realize that Hefner's
girlfriends are twins? The man is  &UR; dating  &LR; a family.
</P>
<P>
   Family values are important. Los Angeles hookers have declared
this ``Family Values Week'' and are giving discounts to convention
delegates who show a wallet photo of the wife and kids.
</P>
<P>
   WHILE AL is wallowing in his own virtue, Gar Smith brings up an
interesting point. Says Gar:
</P>
<P>
   ``In his book, `Earth in the Balance,' Gore calls auto exhaust a
deadlier threat than any military enemy we are ever again likely to
confront.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al inherited $500,000 in Occidental Petroleum stock. What do
you call a politician who calls himself an environmentalist and is
a major shareholder in Occidental Petroleum?
</P>
<P>
   ``An Oxy moron.''
</P>
<P>
   MR. SHOP got his first taste of Emeryville's new Ikea store, and
says:
</P>
<P>
   The place has a shrine-like aura I haven't seen since In-N-Out
opened its first Bay Area franchise a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Man, the place is swarming with shoppers. If you want
inexpensive assemble-it-yourself furniture, you have to pay the
price.
</P>
<P>
   I accidentally bought the wrong item, phoned the store, got this
recorded message: ``Due to overwhelming response to our recent
store opening, we are technically unable to provide information ...
over the phone. We are also unable to transfer any phone calls to
the sales floor.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words: ``We've been open for four months, but we are so
busy baling our money that we don't have time to hire operators and
salespeople who would let you know if the item you're looking for
is one of the very many items that you will find in our showroom
tagged `Temporarily oversold.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Temporarily oversold?'' Al Gore has the same tag tied to the
lapel of his suit this week.
</P>
<P>
   RUNDOWN shoppers, recharge.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Johnstone reports that the newly enlarged Banana Republic
store at Sutter and Grant aims to please. If you hand your cell
phone to the store's concierge, he or she will plug it into a
battery-charger while you shop.
</P>
<P>
   The charge for the charge: No charge!
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO isn't the only city-by-the-Bay that is growing
cold and unfriendly to scuffling little arts groups and assorted
non-profits.
</P>
<P>
   Those little guys being forced into the streets of S.F. by the
dot.com money invasion, many of them were fleeing to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Now: The Oakland East Bay Symphony is being booted from its
offices in the Kaiser Building at Lake Merritt, because of rising
rents due to dot.com invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Man, you hate to see a tuba player huffing ``Stairway to
Heaven'' on a street corner for spare change.
</P>
<P>
   XTREMELY HANDY: The Triple-A Auto Club is using bicycles to
patrol parking areas for the X Games. These chivalrous knights on
yellow bikes carry tools to fix flats, unlock doors and jump dead
batteries. For free.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists are asked not to run down these specially marked
bikers.
</P>
<P>
   MAILBAG: ``Thanks for the laugh ... (and) for me spraying a
mouthful of grapefruit juice all over the paper.'' (Anon.)
</P>
<P>
   Management is not responsible for readers' drinking problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
