<HEADLINE>
SPARKS DON'T MIND ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks love the road. And
that's exactly where they'll be as they continue their Women's
National Basketball Association playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who had Monday off after completing a two-game sweep
of Phoenix Sunday in the best-of three series, will be at Houston
on Thursday night in the first game of the Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Sheryl Swoopes scored a career playoff-high 27
points as the three-time champion Comets advanced with a 75-70
victory over the Sacramento Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets won two games to end the first-round, best-of-three
series, thus earning their berth with tthe Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Though a matchup with the Comets would not seem to bring a smile
to any opponent, the Sparks actually look forward to playing on the
road. They seem to find more peace on the road, few distractions
and plenty of time to focus.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were 13-3 on the road during the regular season,
finishing with a 5-1 mark away from the Forum. After losing the
season-ender to Utah, they opened the playoffs with a resounding
win at Phoenix Friday to take the lead in that series. They simply
have no qualms playing on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some statements about us being 'road warriors,'
and I think that's a good name for us,'' Sparks coach Michael
Cooper said. ``We feel very confident and comfortable on the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The other Cooper: Houston Comets guard Cynthia Cooper gave
her perspective on the playoff race in her guest column in USA
Today. In short, she said she's looking forward to cheering on
teammate Sheryl Swoopes in the Olympics after the Comets win their
fourth WNBA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time WNBA MVP remains confident that the Comets can pull
it off as a coronation to her planned retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been talk whether it would be good for the league if
we were to win a fourth title,'' Cooper wrote. ``The league's front
office would probably prefer three or four different champions. But
as players, we're out to win a championship every single year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be rewarded for our consistency with some type of
respect for winning three championships and in a position to win
our fourth.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Lisa Leslie and Tamecka Dixon had a chance to
rest their bruised knees on the team's day off Monday, but Dixon
wasn't so sure that's a good idea. ``I don't really like taking
days off with Coop because the next practice is hell,'' she said. .
. . New York's center Tari Phillips was selected the league's most
improved player, which should come as no surprise to anyone who saw
any ABL games. Therein lies the problem, because the ABL was rarely
televised, which helped led to the grass-root league's demise in
1999. But Phillips was a dominant post player for the Colorado
Xplosion. Why she didn't make an impression on Orlando's coach
Carolyn Peck is Peck's loss and Rich Adubato's gain. Phillips could
possibly play her old team. Orlando and Cleveland play in the
decisive third game tonight and the winner will play New York in
the Eastern Conference Finals.!dlim!!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
