<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i BC-SUBMARINE-NIGHTMARE-S     08-15 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBMARINE-NIGHTMARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY SUBMARINE CAPTAIN SAYS CLOCK IS TICKING FOR
RUSSIAN  SUBMARINERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL NOLTE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What happened to the Russian submarine Kursk is
the submariners' worst nightmare _ trapped on the bottom of the sea
in a crippled boat with hope running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for them,'' said Len Vaden, who spent years as an
electrician on U.S. Navy submarines during the Cold War. In those
days, the enemy was the Soviet navy, and Vaden, who served on two
nuclear subs, will not talk about any encounters submarines he
served aboard may or may not have had with the Russians. ``I can
neither confirm nor deny anything about that,'' he said carefully.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands what it must be like to be aboard the trapped
submarine. ``Submariners are a strange breed, they say. People
always ask what it's like to be serving in steel coffins,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure what happened to the Kursk when it
apparently collided with another vessel or an object on Sunday and
plunged to the bottom of the icy Barents Sea not far from the
northern Russian port of Murmansk.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 Russian seamen are aboard, and Adm. Vladimir
Kuroyodev said Monday that the chances for a successful rescue
``are not very high.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the chances are very, very low,'' said retired
U.S. Navy Capt. Edward L. Beach, an author, former submarine
skipper and one of the most respected authorities on undersea
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Beach's 27-year Navy career ranged from World War II diesel
boats _ he wrote the submarine classic ``Run Silent, Run Deep'' _
through command of a nuclear submarine. He was skipper of the USS
Triton, which in 1960 was the first vessel to circumnavigate the
world submerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something went radically wrong,'' he said of the Kursk. ``It
must have happened fast. My guess is that they were getting ready
to surface, and a surface ship was coming fast. Maybe they didn't
see them; maybe the ship didn't see the sub. It's happened
before.''
</P>
<P>
   A submarine is always at its most vulnerable just as it surfaces
or submerges; those are the moments submarine crews fear most.
</P>
<P>
   Beach thinks it must have been a Russian ship that hit the
Russian sub, although some Russian sources are hinting that the
Kursk collided with a foreign submarine.
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, U.S., British and other Western naval
vessels were known to stalk Soviet subs, and there were said to be
several close calls or even collisions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this is described in the book ``Blind Man's Bluff,''
which describes many supersecret encounters and a spy operation in
which a U.S. sub tapped a Soviet underwater telephone cable in the
foggy, bleak and forbidding Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Rapid Sinking
</P>
<P>
   But Beach thinks that scenario is improbable. Whatever happened,
the Kursk was damaged in the bow and went down at a 60-degree
angle, very quickly and very steeply. Apparently the nuclear
reactor shut down, or so the Russians say.
</P>
<P>
   Vaden, now a civilian electrical contractor, remembers how
sometimes his own subs would temporarily go out of control. The
stern planes that control the angle of dive ``would go out of
whack,'' he said. ``You are so busy trying to get control you don't
think. ... But we trained hard. We trained for emergencies. We knew
our boat.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kursk, for whatever reason, went to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Beach said a damaged U.S. submarine can be assisted by a
deep-sea rescue vehicle, a kind of diving bell that can use an
escape hatch to rescue trapped crews.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors can't use the torpedo tubes to escape, Beach said.
``At that depth, using the tubes to escape would be certain
death,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Beach's view, there was speculation that the Russian
sailors might be able to escape from the vessel on their own and
float to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   British Royal Navy submarines are equipped with a kind of escape
mechanism that has been used in training up to a depth of 600 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it hasn't been tried for real,'' British Navy spokesman
Jim Jenkin said. ``And their escape facility may be nothing like
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beaver of Jane's Information Group, an authoritative source
in the military and defense field, said he expects the news will be
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this submarine has a lot more damage than we think,
and I think there are probably already people dead from the impact
of the collision,'' he said. ``It seems to be more of a calamity
than the Russians are letting on.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaver said that if the submarine is fitted similarly to British
vessels, the crew would be able to make oxygen for themselves for
about a month, which means they probably would have enough to last
until a rescue could be mounted.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the Russian submarine was equipped with
such devices. The Kursk is among the Russian navy's newest vessels,
and presumably has the latest emergency equipment. The submarine
was commissioned in 1995 by then President Boris Yeltsin and is
among the most modern vessels in the Russian fleet. However,
maintenance and training standards in the Russian navy have
reportedly declined markedly in the last few years. According to
some reports, naval personnel have not even been paid in some
months.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no way to help, the crew of the trapped vessel will
surely die as the air is used up. ``As you get more and more carbon
dioxide and less oxygen,'' Beach said, ``you get sleepy. It takes
more and more of an effort to stay awake. Finally, you simply go to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaden hopes that doesn't happen. ``Maybe,'' the Cold War veteran
said, ``there is some way. Maybe the the U.S. Navy can help them
out. I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle news services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
