r a BC-WEBWATCH-CONVENTION-S     08-15 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBWATCH-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW MEDIUM STRUGGLES WITH THE MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By VLAE KERSHNER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet coverage of the Republican convention didn't fully live
up to its promise, a new report says. Don't look for much of an
improvement this week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite laying over 6,600 miles of cable and the equivalent of
70,000 high-speed lines from Philadelphia, Web sites were neither
as popular nor as effective as they could have been, according to a
study for Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government Vanishing
Voter project. It's available at
 &UR; www.vanishingvoter.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PC Data Online ratings for major Web news sites were actually
down 14 percent the week of the the GOP convention, the study
noted. The four highest-rated sites were  &UR; msnbc.com, &LR; 
 &UR; cnn.com, nytimes.com and washingtonpost.com,  &LR; drawing slightly
fewer than 10 million users among them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study said, coverage was often disjointed and
technical glitches were widespread. Those are problems I
encountered again Monday, for example with the youth-oriented
 &UR; www.pseudo.com site,  &LR; which has had a makeover since the GOP
convention but still isn't very reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Anything really new in L.A. this week?
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC offered a video feed called ``From the Streets'' with
highlights from the demonstrations outside the convention hall.
That's an improvement _ the major media had little in the way of
video or photos from the demonstrations in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the coverage is similar to two weeks ago.
No surprise. If the major news organizations tried to beef up their
coverage this week, they would run the risk of heightening
suspicions they are slanted toward the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Those suspicions were voiced this week on  &UR; www.grassroots.com &LR; 
by Christopher Buckley, admittedly a GOP partisan. He argues that
the New York Times' political coverage is slanted against the
Republicans. Hardly a new argument, but he has some recent examples
of coverage of George W. Bush's convention speech that will get the
blood boiling among the distrust-the-media crowd.
</P>
<P>
   DIALING DOWN THE CLINTONS: Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton's
convention speeches got a lower rating than any Republican
convention address, according to an instant meter survey.
</P>
<P>
   The MSNBC/SpeakOut.com survey displays a dial with a scale of 1
to 100, initially set at a neutral level of 50. Users move the dial
to to register agreement or disagreement with the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bill and Hillary Clinton scored an average of 52 last
night. By comparison, George W. Bush rated a 55. John McCain has
the highest score so far, a 62.
</P>
<P>
   The scores are not a scientific sample of all voters, but they
are adjusted so that the gender and party affiliation of the users
match those of the voting public.
</P>
<P>
   WAGGING THE DOG: Also on San Francisco-based  &UR; grassroots.com &LR; 
are Emil Guillermo's audio clips from a Santa Monica party for
so-called Blue Dog Democrats (the party's more conservative wing).
He asks various partygoers what the difference is between the blue
dogs and yellow dog Democrats, and their colorful attempts to
explain will leave you scratching your ... head.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
