<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROTESTS-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 RAGE AGAINST THE CONVENTION  &HT;     By NEVA CHONIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As President Clinton spoke inside the Staples
Center Monday night, police fired tear gas, rubber bullets and
charged on horseback to disperse an unruly crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The altercation broke out as thousands were leaving a concert by
the rock band Rage Against the Machine in a protest area near the
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Police herded protesters to the far end of the area and away
from the convention after a running battle along a fence directly
across from the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Officers fired at protesters after they threw pieces of concrete
and water bottles, sprayed police with ammonia and fired steel
balls and rocks from slingshots. Protesters with bandanna-covered
faces lit fires in the concert area.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation initially involved about 300 people out of a
crowd of 8,000, but then spread as more officers rushed to the
scene. The ground around them was littered with rocks, broken
bottles and sticks thrown over the fence from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton began speaking inside the convention
center, pepper spray wafted over the crowd outside, stinging noses
and throats.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates and members of the media were caught up in the melee.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation took place beneath a huge TV screen outside of
the Staples Center displaying a live video image of the convention
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, 10 people were arrested when police and
protesters clashed near the center as about 200 environmental
demonstrators blocked an intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Police in riot gear used batons to push back the demonstrators
from the intersection before making their arrests. About 400 others
watched from the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what a police state looks like,'' one shouted.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was aimed at Occidental Petroleum's plans to begin
exploratory drilling near an Indian reservation in Colombia.
Environmental activists have called on Vice President Al Gore to
sell his family's Occidental stock, valued at up to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, hundreds staged a ``March of Corporate Shame''
through downtown Los Angeles in which some called for campaign
finance reform, and others condemned alleged corporate abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was to culminate with a concert outside the
convention by Rage Against the Machine, a popular rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to beat, beat back, the corporate attack,''
chanted protesters, some of whom wore pig costumes to symbolize
corporate greed.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting police, demonstrators used their own bullhorn to
taunt officers and danced in front of them to the beat of a drum. A
pungent odor permeated the air from the vinegar demonstrators
poured on cloths to withstand tear gas, although none was fired.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a line of officers charged, knocking people down.
Some yelled, ``We're nonviolent!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The police are acting in a very aggressive way,'' said Medea
Benjamin, a Green Party activist and founding director of the San
Francisco-based activist group Global Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Police defended their response.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were here, you saw there was a lot of restraint and
that all the training has paid off,'' said Sgt. Michael Barela, who
was at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested and handcuffed the 10 protesters on charges of
failure to disperse. With their hands bound, they chanted, ``Al
Gore cut your ties, stop the drilling, stop the lies.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, Gore has been dogged by protests of his
connection to Occidental. His father, the late Sen. Albert Gore
Sr., served on Occidental's board, owned stock in the company and
was chief executive of a subsidiary. His family inherited the stock
when he died in December.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have urged Gore to divest his family of that stock.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's government has granted Occidental the right to
conduct exploratory drilling a few miles outside the legal
boundaries of the U'wa Indian reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The U'wa believe oil exploration would bring violence and
destroy their culture. In 1997, the group threatened mass suicide
to discourage drilling in the South American country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore bills himself as an environmentalist, but he's not
putting his money where his mouth is,'' said Michael Mossberg, a
protester from Seattle. ``What I'd want him to do today is use his
power to get Occidental to stop drilling on U'wa land.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle news services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
