<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-WILLIAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ERIK WILLIAMS TO END 4-WEEK HOLDOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ In what seemed only a matter of time,
Dallas Cowboys offensive tackle Erik Williams has ended his
four-week holdout and will be at Midwestern State University for
the final four days of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys reported Monday night that Williams was making the
120-mile drive from the Metroplex to Wichita Falls along with
teammate Leon Lett. He is expected to be on the MSU practice field
Tuesday afternoon with the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Thursday, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said that he
would not trade Williams, 31, who probably will not be fined for
his absence, although Jones has not been willing to address that
issue one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   According to league rules, Williams could be fined $5,000 a day
for as long as he was away from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also saves another $1.6 million by coming back, as he
would have had to pay the Cowboys $800,000 of already paid signing
bonus money in each of the next two seasons if he retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great news,'' Jones was quoted as saying on
dallascowboys.com, the team's official Web site. ``Erik can really
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' return also ensures the Cowboys will have the
offensive line they were counting on at the beginning of the
season. Though the Cowboys are comfortable with the group they have
been playing with the past few weeks, they have said all along that
Williams was one of their best five offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, 0-3 this preseason, played Sunday night with only
one offensive lineman _ left tackle Flozell Adams _ starting at his
projected position. Solomon Page has replaced Williams at right
tackle but now probably will move back to right guard.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams back in the fold, Page can move back to right
guard, which would likely move Jorge Diaz to the bench as a solid
veteran backup.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Williams has missed so much time, it is unlikely
that he will play against the Broncos on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   However, he might get into some action against the Rams on Aug.
24 and almost certainly should be ready for the season opener Sept.
3.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
