<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1978 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION     08-15 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATIC-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPENS CONVENTION WITH ROUSING DEFENSE OF HIS
EIGHT-YEAR  TERM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton opened the Democratic convention
Monday night with a ringing defense of his eight years in office
and a warning that booming times could all end unless Al Gore is
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``To serve as president at the dawn of a new era in human
history has been an honor, a privilege and a joy,'' Clinton said in
an emotional speech on the opening night of the Democrat's national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done everything I could to empower the American people
... to turn our country around and move us forward together. But
the best is yet to be _ if we make the right choices.''
</P>
<P>
   That choice is Gore, Clinton said, calling the vice president
``a profoundly good man,'' who throughout the eight years of his
administration has been ``the greatest champion of working
families.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that brought delegates in the Staples Center to
their feet time after time, the president also took direct aim at
GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush, who suggested Clinton
had little to do with the country's growing prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you heard it said sometime in the past two weeks that
the progress of the last eight years was an accident, that we just
coasted along,'' Clinton said. ``Let me be clear: America's success
was not a matter of chance, it was a matter of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Last night was Clinton's last hurrah, his final opportunity to
address as president a Democratic Party he led out of the political
wilderness with his 1992 win over President George Bush. After
their prime-time speeches, Clinton and his wife, Hillary, prepared
to depart Los Angeles, leaving the convention to Gore, the party's
hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton didn't leave quietly. Time and again in his
41-minute speech, the president worked to show that ``the stars
have never shined more brightly on any nation, at any time,
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made it clear that any success was in spite of the
Republicans in Congress, not because of itthem &LR; , as Bush has
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their leaders said (the 1993 budget) would increase the
deficit, kill jobs and give us a one-way ticket to recession,''
Clinton said. ``Time has not been kind to those predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans said then they would not be held responsible
for the results of our economic policies. I hope the American
people will take them at their word.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``face a fundamental choice,'' Clinton warned. ``Are
we going to keep this progress and prosperity going?''
</P>
<P>
   With Gore as president, the country will be ready to deal with
the different challenges a booming economy can bring, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anybody else I've ever known in public life, Al Gore
understands the future and how sweeping changes can affect
Americans' daily lives,'' the president said. ``I think we need
someone in office at the dawn of the 21st century who really
understands the future.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, he said, Gore and Lieberman will continue the
fight for civil rights and equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this may be the most important of all,'' Clinton said.
``They believe the people you're buying your soft drinks and
popcorn from here at the Staples Center deserve the same chance
they have to send their children to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is only the third president since the end of World War
II to make his farewells to a party after having served two full
terms. The others were both Republicans _ Dwight D. Eisenhower, who
succeeded Truman in 1953, and Ronald Reagan, who ousted Democrat
Jimmy Carter and took office in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   For Hillary Rodham Clinton, her run for a New York Senate seat
was almost an afterthought in her speech last night. Speaking right
before her husband, she was interrupted by wild applause as she
talked about the need to provide for the nation's children and
looked back with nostalgia at eight years of good times and
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for giving me the most extraordinary opportunity to
work here at home and around the world on the issues that matter
most to children, families and women,'' Hillary Clinton said.
``Thank you for your faith and support in good times _ and in bad.
Thank you, from the bottom of my heart, for the honor and privilege
of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Echo Across Convention Floor
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message was echoed Monday by a partisan parade of
Democratic politicians who credited Clinton and Gore with
everything good that's taken place in the country over the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in education, a dropping crime rate, fewer teen
pregnancies and continuing job growth: To giddy Democratic
delegates, it's all part of the Clinton-Gore legacy and a blueprint
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the story they came to Los Angeles to hear.
</P>
<P>
   The theme for the convention's opening night was ``Progress and
Prosperity,'' and the Democrats brought out a lineup of regular
people who were winners from the past eight years: a couple who
bought their first home, a man who started his own business,
another who has seen the steel plant he works in expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stories like these are commonplace,'' said New Hampshire Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen. ``In Al Gore, we will have a president ... to keep
the prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing that theme, thousands of delegates and guests waved
signs declaring ``America: Better Than Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   The upbeat mood as Clinton's hour approached was characterized
by Steve Alari, who sat near the front of the hall holding a huge
sign that said, ``Thank you, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to thank him for all the years of service as we watch
him pass the torch,'' said Alari, a delegate from Long Beach.
``Look at the economy and what he's done for people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   And Robert Rankin, a steel worker from nearby Carson, said
Democrats were united in their sentiments at the convention:
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need eight more years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   California senators Barbara Boxer and Dianne Feinstein,
co-chairs of the convention, pounded home the theme of a
Democratic-led prosperity in their brief remarks to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've turned around the economic lives of American working
people,'' Feinstein said. ``Unemployment is at the lowest level in
30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer turned around Bush's acceptance speech at the Republican
convention two weeks ago, arguing that Democrats have made their
most of the last eight years in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their chance and they failed,'' she said. ``We had
our chance and we led.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Gray Davis, the host governor, also got his moment in
the spotlight _ and a standing ovation. Standing under the massive
backdrop proclaiming ``America 2000,'' Davis said he represents ``a
state that personifies the new moderate direction in American
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to put on an act to appear like the party of
compassion,'' he said. ``We are the real thing. That's why
California is Al Gore country.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone echoed the good feeling coming out of the
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets near the Staples Center, police clashed with
demonstrators for the first time. When environmental protesters
blocked a busy downtown intersection Monday afternoon, officers in
riot gear removed them and arrested 10 people for failing to
disperse.
</P>
<P>
   Police also were kept busy with a variety of other marches
through the city, but there were no reports of serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle news services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
