<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CLINTON-CONVENTION-SF     08-15 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONVENTION-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: SUPPORT FOR CLINTON UNWAVERING AS HE TRANSFERS POWER  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The man from Hope isn't going away. And the
Democratic faithful couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Bill Clinton addressed a Democratic convention,
delegates were so anxious for him to leave they gave him an ovation
when he uttered the words: ``In closing ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, had Clinton decided to defy the Constitution and
seek a third term, there is little doubt that delegates would have
given him their unanimous support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-four years ago this week, I was born in a summer storm
to a young widow in a small southern town,'' Clinton said 40
minutes into what some believed would be a farewell opus.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of Clinton's stealing the spotlight from Vice
President Al Gore's convention. Indeed, Clinton strode the podium
in dramatic fashion, emerging from a televised stroll through the
back corridors of the Staples Center as piano music played and the
delegate's roared in anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton could hardly have done more to share the glory. From
reminding American's about Gore's tie-breaking vote to implement
his first budget in 1993, to declaring Gore a ``profoundly good
man,'' Clinton did everything that could be asked of a political
patron.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, a reporter asked President Eisenhower if he could think
of a single major idea advanced by his vice President, Richard
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give me a week, I might think of one,'' Eisenhower
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a single sentence, credited Gore with fighting for
welfare reform, protecting the environment, closing the digital
divide, and creating millions of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anybody else I've known in public life, Al Gore
understands the future and how sweeping changes and scientific
breakthroughs affect Americans' daily lives,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   As much as it was a full-throated endorsement of his vice
president, the speech was also a celebration of the peace and
prosperity the nation has enjoyed during his administration, and a
pointed rebuttal to the Republican allegation that he had little to
do with it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a speech that articulated more clearly than any he has
yet delivered where he sees his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton boasted of 22 million new jobs, the elimination of
deficits, rising wages, new teachers, improved test scores, child
care tax credits, reduced crime, improved medicine, cleaner
environment, peace in Northern Ireland, and the expansion of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, I have waited over 30 years to see my
country once again in a position to build the future of our dreams
for our children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's remember the standard the Republicans used to have for
whether a party should continue in office _ my fellow Americans,
are we better off today than we were 8 years ago?'' Clinton asked.
``You bet we are.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter that the most comprehensive initiative of his
presidency, a plan to restructure the health care system, was
rejected by a Democratic Congress. And no matter that Clinton is
the first president since Andrew Johnson in the 1860s to be
impeached .
</P>
<P>
   Few Democrats really believe he will go down in history, as one
of the greatest presidents ever, as Gore once said of him.
Nevertheless, Clinton stood before 5,000 adoring Democrats Monday
as nothing less than their political savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy is brilliant,'' marveled Bob Mulholland, a long time
consultant to the California Democratic Party. ``Clinton taught
Democrats that it's more important to be in office than outside,
yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't come from the same wing of the party as Bill
Clinton,'' said Assemblyman Antonio Villaraigosa, the liberal
former Assembly speaker. ``But let me tell you, Bill Clinton saved
the party. We were becoming an irrelevant party.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton won the party's nomination in 1992, Democrats had
lost three consecutive presidential elections and had been shut out
of the White House for 20 of the previous 24 years. Clinton took a
decidedly centrist posture, grabbing issues like welfare reform,
crime and a balanced budget, which had long been Republican
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went straight up against Democratic orthodoxy,'' said Al
From, president of the Democratic Leadership Council, a group which
Clinton helped found and tugged Democrats from their liberal
moorings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton redefined the party as a centrist party,'' From said,
noting that he spawned similar political success in Great Britain
and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton has really been the modernizer of progressive
politics, not only in this country, but around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has never said what will come when his term ends five
months from now, but it is hard to imagine him fading quickly from
the political spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think think it is going to be much more difficult for him to
leave political life,'' observed former President Jimmy Carter, who
called his post presidential life ``the best part of my
existence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that President Clinton is
much more of a political animal than I am,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Clinton accepted his party's nomination saying
he still believes in a place called Hope. There is no doubt that he
still believes in politics, and the party still believes in him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
