r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-INDISPENS     08-15 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-INDISPENSABLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S FIVE `INDISPENSABLE' PLAYERS FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Injuries are part of football. Some are
just more of a hardship on the team than others.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys received a major scare against the Oakland
Raiders on Sunday when Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail, Dallas' leading
receiver last season, sprained his left thumb while trying to make
a diving catch on the Cowboys' first offensive play.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail was done for the night, although X-rays were negative. He
will be evaluated day to day.
</P>
<P>
   So, who could the Cowboys least afford to lose this season?
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind the depth chart, i.e., who is backing up whom, and
what can be done to adjust the game plan for fill-in players for
the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' ``Top Five Indispensables,'' although everyone
seems to come up with a different list when asked, are: 1) Jackie
Harris, 2) Joey Galloway, 3) Ryan McNeil, 4) Troy Aikman and 5) Dat
Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the top three has yet to appear in a
regular-season game for the Cowboys, Harris, Galloway and McNeil
were acquired during the off-season to fill major holes. Aikman
runs the offense. Nguyen sets the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons the Cowboys can ill afford to lose these players:
</P>
<P>
   _ Harris is a Jay Novacek-type tight end. He's a perfect fit for
this Jack Reilly/Ernie Zampese offense. Disregard that he has only
four preseason catches for 37 yards. He, obviously, is being saved
for the games that count. Harris can split a zone and work the
middle of the field as well as the best possession receiver, and he
does it at 6-foot-4, 250 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   David LaFleur, a three-year starter, is more of a blocker at
6-7, 272. A big part of this offense is to use both tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Galloway averaged 15.7 yards per catch in his first five NFL
seasons at Seattle, with 5,688 all-purpose yards in 71 NFL games.
He also returns punts. But it's his ability to catch and make
defenders miss that makes him nearly irreplaceable. In the Cowboys'
timing-route offense, he's becoming automatic on the quick turnouts
and slants. No one is better on the go routes.
</P>
<P>
   James McKnight (August 1999 knee surgery) played Sunday night
for the first time since December 1998 with Seattle. He is the
likely replacement for Galloway or Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   _ McNeil, a corner who defends ``and'' tackles, has the savvy
and confidence of an eight-year veteran with 91 NFL starts. That's
79 more than Kareem Larrimore, Mario Edwards, Duane Hawthorne,
Dwayne Goodrich and Charlie Williams put together. Williams, who
has all 12 of those starts, is sidelined with a staph infection
following off-season knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aikman finally has a backup _ Randall Cunningham _ who can win
games and force opposing defensive coordinators to tear up game
plans if Aikman is unable to play. Still, in the NFL, you don't win
without your No. 1 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nguyen is more than even the Cowboys' coaching staff imagined
when training camp began. He never leaves the field now. He was
supposed to be in a battle with Barron Wortham, who started at
middle linebacker in Super Bowl XXXIV for the Tennessee Titans, but
Wortham has been injured and Nguyen has been making plays _
instinctively, that's his game _ and making the calls for the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether this list is accurate or not, the Cowboys can
only hope they never have to know.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
