<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIM-LEDE-TEX     08-15 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO `WONDERWOMEN' FOIL TAPPIN'S COMEBACK EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ By most swimming standards, Ashley Tappin has had
an exceptional meet in this _ as she calls it _ her ``third
comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   In the women's 100-meter butterfly last week, in her first
Olympic trials after undergoing rotator cuff surgery, Tappin
lowered her personal best by nearly a full second. She finished
third.
</P>
<P>
   And Monday night, at the age of 26, she equaled her best-ever
time in the 100 freestyle. And finished third again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, look at them,'' instructed Tappin, who won a relay gold
medal at the 1992 Olympics. ``Look at their body structure,
compared to mine. They have, maybe, 20 pounds on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the luck of the draw. I just happen to be swimming
against two people who are stronger than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger, stronger, faster.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in these U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, those
two wonderwomen at large, Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres, led the
race to the wall Monday night. In a churning fashion that was
impressively similar to their one-two finish in the 100 butterfly,
Thompson shattered the American record in the 100 freestyle in
54.07 seconds, with Torres one wake behind.
</P>
<P>
   Tappin's 55.28 got her only third, with a spot on the 400 free
relay team as a consolation prize. Veteran and four-time gold
medalist Amy Van Dyken could do no better than fourth, but she,
too, will head to Sydney on the sprint relay team.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago in this same Indiana University Natatorium pool,
no American records were broken during the selection meet.
</P>
<P>
   In this meet, eight American records have fallen. In addition,
17 Olympic trials records have been set.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Thompson in the American record book Monday night was
19-year-old Kristy Kowal, a native of Reading, Pa., who swims for
the University of Georgia. After finishing a heartbroken third in
the 100-meter breaststroke in 1996 and again last week, Kowal won
the 200 breaststroke in 2:24.75.
</P>
<P>
   Her time eclipsed Anita Nall's 2:25.35 American record set in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hard after the 100 to get over that,'' a happy
and relieved Kowal said. ``People say lightning doesn't strike
twice, but it did to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew that this was my last shot to make the team. I
think I started crying as I got near the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200-meter backstroke finals, Lenny Krayzelburg of
Hollywood, Calif., set a trials record and made it a sweep of the
men's backstroke events. Krayzelburg, who set the existing world
record (1:55.87) in the event 12 months ago, swam a meet-record
1:57.31 with the jingling of his father's tambourine ringing in his
ears _ and he promptly pronounced himself displeased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have won, but I was a little disappointed with my
time,'' said Krayzelburg, who confessed much the same thing after
he won the 100 backstroke. ``I don't know what's going on with my
200-meter backstroke. I'm just struggling to find my perfect
stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Peirsol, 17, who set a trials record in the semis,
finished second in 1:57.98.
</P>
<P>
   In the night's remaining final, 1996 Olympic gold medalist Tom
Dolan of Arlington, Va., won the men's 200-meter individual medley
in 2:00.81.
</P>
<P>
   Austin resident Ron Karnaugh, a 1992 Olympian attempting a
comeback at age 34, finished fourth. Karnaugh became one of the
tragic stories of the '92 Games when his father died of a heart
attack during the opening ceremonies in the Olympic Stadium.
Karnaugh competed _ and finished sixth _ six days later.
</P>
<P>
   In these trials, meanwhile, the story has been the two rival
wonderwomen, Thompson and Torres. Amid the hype surrounding their
rematch and the ongoing stories about their frosty relationship and
the curious training program that they share, Thompson felt pleased
that she was able to keep the wheels on long enough to sprint to
Monday night's record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt proud of the way I turned that around and was able to
maintain my composure,'' said the Menlo Park, Calif., resident. ``I
was really pleased to get a win in such a high-profile situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It can't hurt for Sydney, she acknowledged, where a
Thompson-Torres showdown in the sprints with reigning world record
holdess Inge de Bruijn of The Netherlands could be the highlights
of the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who was clocked in 54.62 Monday night, was not pleased
with her race and noted that she was swimming faster just three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs gave out at the 75-meter mark,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, whose legs were beginning to cramp, excused herself and
headed back to the warmdown area. Thompson, relaxed and secure, a
far cry from the defeated jangle of nerves that she was in 1996,
allowed her 3-year-old niece to join her at the interview table.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl's name, Thompson said without blushing, is
Sydney. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
