<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TRADE-T     08-15 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR-TEAM DEAL TO BRING EISLEY, BARROS AND CURLEY TO MAVERICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Relatively quiet since a flurry of Draft Day trades,
Dallas Mavericks owner Mark Cuban played the lead role in a
four-team, nine-player deal agreed upon Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban expects the deal to be consummated Tuesday after gaining
approval from the NBA. Before the deal, the only thing the
Mavericks had done after the start of the free-agent signing period
was sign their own free agents: Gary Trent, Hubert Davis and Greg
Buckner.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs pick up guard Howard Eisley from Utah, guard Dana
Barros from Boston and forward Bill Curley from Golden State, Cuban
confirmed. Eisley is a safe bet to be on the roster opening night,
while the Mavericks might only be a stopping-off point for Barros
and Curley.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will send center John ``Hot Rod'' Williams and
guard Robert Pack to Boston, and center Bruno Sundov to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Boston also gets $3 million in cash from
the Mavs, plus a conditional first-round draft pick from Utah. The
Jazz receive Donyell Marshall from Golden State. The Warriors land
Danny Fortson from Boston and Adam Keefe from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Though the trade for the Mavs is their first since the
free-agency period began Aug. 1, Donnie Nelson said Cuban has been
working behind the scenes trying to broker a major deal. And Nelson
expects this deal to be just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in, and a part of, a bulk of the deals that have
gone down this summer,'' said Nelson, the Mavs director of player
personnel and assistant coach. ``And we'll continue to be active,
I'm pretty sure about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the deal for the Mavs is the sign-and-trade for
Eisley. A backup to John Stockton in Utah the last five seasons,
Eisley is expected to push Mavs incumbent point guard Steve Nash
for the starting spot.
</P>
<P>
   Eisley agreed to sign with the Mavs last week for the team's
$2.25 million exception after negotiations with the Jazz fell
apart. Utah offered Eisley a five-year deal worth $20 million,
while Eisley was asking for $30 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Had Eisley signed with the Mavs for the exception, Utah would
have lost him without compensation. Instead, the Jazz signed Eisley
to a multiyear deal, starting at $4.25 million yearly. Eisley, 27,
averaged 8.6 points and 4.2 assists last season.
</P>
<P>
   Barros, a Boston College product, has played for three teams in
an 11-year career. Cuban added that at least one team has shown
interest in Barros, leaving the possibility open for another trade.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Curley, a 6-9 five-year veteran, also from Boston
College, could be ``serviceable backup center'' who is ``smart, can
shoot it and tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of the often-injured Pack and Williams had been a
goal of Cuban's this summer. The two players never really made an
impact with the Mavs, spending most of their time on the injured
list.
</P>
<P>
   By working the sign-and-trade for the Eisley, the Mavs keep
their middle-class exceptions for this year and next. Nelson said
the next year's exception is expected to be around $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big things that we gained out of this was our
exception this year and our exception next year,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who said the team still hopes to find a backup center
for the $2.25 exception, praised Cuban for his ability to make
things happen.
</P>
<P>
   On draft night, Cuban helped put together deals that landed
rookies Courtney Alexander, Donnell Harvey and Eduardo Najera, in
addition to the Mavs pick, Etan Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really been able to pick up this stuff quickly,'' Nelson
said. ``I admire what he's done with the team since he's been
here.''
</P>
<P>
   After the completion of the four-team trade, the Mavs would have
17 players under contract. The NBA allows 12 on the active roster
and up to three on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Others rumored to be on the Mavs' trading block are Cedric
Ceballos and Shawn Bradley. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
