<HEADER>
A1988 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-T     08-15 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAPLER EXTENDS HITTING STREAK TO 27 IN RANGERS' LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The first-place Texas Rangers used to find
that beating the New York Yankees was difficult at best during the
regular season and almost impossible in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the last-place Rangers, well ... how about that Gabe Kapler
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Kapler went 2-for-4 on Monday night to extend his hitting streak
to 27 games, but it did the Rangers little good in a 7-3 loss to
the Yankees at The Ballpark in Arlington. The Yankees built a 7-0
lead through 71/2 innings then held off the Rangers' last-ditch
rally in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have won 38 of their past 49 games _ regular-season
and postseason _ against the Rangers going back to the 1996
playoffs. But that seems sadly irrelevant now that there's no real
chance of the two teams meeting again in the playoffs this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go through what we're going through now as a team
in general,'' Rangers outfielder Rusty Greer said. ``But three out
of the last four years, this was basically two first-place teams
playing. This year, it's not the case. When we take the field, we
still believe we can win. We're not playing bad baseball, but we're
not playing consistent winning baseball. That's how you compete
against a team like the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of winning baseball, the Rangers have lost 11 of 15 and
are 12-19 since the All-Star break. At 54-62, they are also eight
games under .500 for the first time since the end of the 1997
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made some changes, and they've had a lot of
injuries,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``You lose (Juan
Gonzalez) and you lose Pudge (Rodriguez), and that's totally
different. I'm sure it's frustrating for Johnny (Oates). You can
only do so much as a manager. You have such high hopes in spring
training, then when you lose players like that, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler kept his hitting streak alive by drilling a grounder
through the middle in the second inning, then lined a single to
center field in the fourth. But, with the Rangers down 7-2, he
popped out with the bases loaded and no outs in the eighth against
Yankees reliever Jeff Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we played a pretty ugly game tonight,'' said Kapler,
who also got picked off first base and had a throwing error in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he had no interest in talking about the hitting
streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about anything but the game,'' Kapler
said. ``Tonight we flat-out stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Oates was a little more positive than that about
starting pitcher Matt Perisho, who gave up six runs in six innings
to take the loss. Perisho, with eight strikeouts, showed some
flashes of what the Rangers hope is potential.
</P>
<P>
   But Jorge Posada's two-run home run in the first and Derek
Jeter's two-run homer in the sixth crushed any chance of it being a
winning effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he threw the ball OK,'' Oates said. ``You look at
their lineup, he had some success against some pretty good hitters.
If Matt were to throw the ball every time out like he did tonight,
he'd win a few ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Perisho has lost five consecutive decisions and is
winless in 10 starts since beating Tampa Bay on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, overall, I can take a lot of positives out of this,''
Perisho said. ``I threw a lot more strikes and was a lot more
aggressive. But there's a reason why they're in first place: They
hit my mistakes. If I minimize my mistakes, it's a different
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had a much tougher time against Yankees starter Andy
Pettitte, who held them scoreless on four hits through seven
innings before faltering in the eighth. But by then the Rangers
were too far behind to have a realistic hope of coming back against
the Yankees' bullpen. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
