<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PITCHER GLYNN SCRATCHED FROM SCHEDULED START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers, still unsure what caused
Ryan Glynn to faint in the dugout Friday night, want him to undergo
more tests and have scratched him from Wednesday's start against
the New York Yankees. The Rangers expect to put him on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers internist Dr. Scott Hunter said Glynn is suffering from
syncope _ sudden lost of consciousness _ which has more than 50
possible causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt uncomfortable letting him get go back out there
until we get all the tests done,'' Hunter said. ``I'm not convinced
we've looked at everything that needs to be looked at before we let
him go back to a high level of athleticism. It can be a nebulous
problem. That's why we need to slow down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said the testing could take another seven to 10 days.
Glynn, who has a history of occasional fainting, passed out after
pitching 42/3 innings on the hottest day of the season. But Hunter
said, ``The heat may have provoked it, but I don't think that was
the source.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will pitch Jonathan Johnson in Glynn's spot. The
Rangers ruled out Darren Oliver, who is on the disabled list with
weakness in his left shoulder and on a medical-rehabilitation
assignment with Oklahoma. MEANINGLESS SERIES
</P>
<P>
   A Rangers-Yankees series used to mean something around here. It
also brought out the inevitable questions about the Rangers'
inability to beat the Yankees. But that has been completely missing
from this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about that,'' Rangers outfielder Rusty Greer
said. ``We don't have the same things we've had to deal with in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Rafael Palmeiro said, ``I guess they don't expect
us to beat the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro said he misses the constant questions about the
Rangers' troubles against New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss winning so, yeah, I miss that,'' Palmeiro said. ``That
comes from winning.'' CURTIS STAYS IN LINEUP
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates wants to see how right fielder
Ricky Ledee and designated hitter Frank Catalanotto, both young,
left-handed hitters, do against left-handed pitchers down the
stretch. But Oates always wants to give Chad Curtis as much playing
time as possible against left-handers, as he has all year.
</P>
<P>
   So Oates said when left-handers face the Rangers, he'll likely
alternate Curtis, a right-handed hitter, between filling in for
Ledee and Catalanotto. Monday, Catalanotto sat against Yankees
left-hander Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure Curtis gets as many at-bats as possible
against left-handers,'' Oates said. ``We're trying to win as many
games as we can, and he's a valuable part of our ballclub. Chad
Curtis can help us win ballgames, and, last I heard, that was the
objective.'' LAMB SITS
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Mike Lamb, in a 1-for-18 slump, got a day off
Monday with Andy Pettitte pitching for the Yankees. But shortstop
Royce Clayton, 1-for-21, is still in the lineup, and Johnny Oates
isn't ready to sit him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``His defense has been very good,'' Oates said. ``He's doing
what he's supposed to do. He has hit a couple balls hard.'' TOP
HITTERS
</P>
<P>
   Rangers designated hitter Frank Catalanotto went into Monday
night's game hitting .362, the fourth-highest batting average in
the majors for players with at least 150 at-bats. The top five:
Player, Team AB-H Avg. Todd Helton, Colorado 411-161 .392 Nomar
Garciaparra, Boston 367-141 .384 Jeffrey Hammonds, Colorado 328-120
.366 Frank Catalanotto, Texas 152-55 .3618 Carlos Delgado, Toronto
426-154 .3615 RING CEREMONY
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are planning to present Chad Curtis with his World
Series ring when the Rangers play at Yankee Stadium next week.
Yankees spokesman Rick Cerrone said the club wants to have a nice
ceremony at home plate in front of the home fans. Curtis played for
the Yankees last year, hitting a game-winning home run in the 10th
inning of Game 3 of the World Series against the Atlanta Braves. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
