<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PITCHING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE STRUGGLING ROTATION, YANKEES SAY THEY CAN WIN ANOTHER
TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Chad Curtis spent a few minutes before
batting practice yesterday saying hello to his old teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers outfielder saw Bernie Williams, the New York
Yankees' magnificent center fielder, and Derek Jeter, their
fabulous shortstop, as well as third baseman Scott Brosius, first
baseman Tino Martinez, right fielder Paul O'Neill and catcher Jorge
Posada.
</P>
<P>
   All played key roles as the Yankees won the American League East
and destroyed the Rangers, Boston Red Sox and Atlanta Braves in the
playoffs last season to win their third World Series title in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Add newcomers David Justice, Jose Canseco and Glenallen Hill,
and the Yankees that began a three-game series against the Rangers
with a 7-3 victory Monday night at The Ballpark in Arlington look
like an imposing bunch once again.
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for one nagging little matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's any question at all is if some guys who
have pitched well in the past are going to pitch that way again,''
said Curtis, who played with the Yankees the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 64-50, the third-best record in the American
League. Before Monday night, they were fourth in the league with a
.282 team batting average, and third with a 4.55 earned-run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they don't quite resemble the juggernaut of the past few
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have been inconsistent all year,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, as Curtis pointed out, it's the starting pitching that
has been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won the World Series last year on the strength of
their starting pitching. Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez was 3-0
with a 1.20 ERA in the playoffs. David Cone was 2-0 with a 1.29
ERA, Roger Clemens was 2-1 with a 3.24 ERA, and Andy Pettitte was
2-0 with a 3.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   However, only Pettitte and Clemens are pitching well this
season. Pettitte is 14-6 with a 4.19 ERA after defeating the
Rangers on Monday night, and Clemens is 10-6 with a 3.62 ERA and
hasn't lost since June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who pitches tonight, is struggling through the worst
season of his career. He's 2-10 with a 6.56 ERA. He lost eight
consecutive decisions before beating the Oakland Athletics in his
most recent start.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is 8-9 with a 5.06 ERA. He was on the disabled list
from July 19 until Aug. 6 because of a sore elbow and back spasms,
and is 0-2 with a 10.45 ERA in two starts since returning.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle, expected to bolster the rotation after coming over
in a trade with the Cincinnati Reds, won his first two starts but
is 0-2 with a 15.96 ERA in his past two.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the pitching problems, Curtis isn't expecting his
old team to relinquish its title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know El Duque,'' Curtis said. ``You can throw him in Game 1
of any series in the playoffs, and he's going to shut down the
other team. David Cone has been the same way. If he can still
believe that about himself, I think he can do it. And Clemens is
throwing good, Andy's throwing good, and they've got Neagle. I
think they're just as good as they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is shared in the Yankees' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coney's coming back, and Roger's throwing the ball as good as
he's been throwing it the last couple of years,'' Neagle said. ``El
Duque, it's always tough when you come back off the DL to try to
get out there and feel comfortable again. He'll be OK. And Andy's
Andy; he's one of the most consistent pitchers around. I definitely
think you can see the rotation shaping up and getting to where we
want to be going into the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, the Yankees have no doubt that they'll be back
in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not overlooking the regular season,'' Tino Martinez
said. ``By no means do we have this sewn up. We still have our work
cut out for us the rest of the way. But our goal is to win the
World Series. Anything short of that is a disappointment because
we've done it the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense remains formidable. The Yankees scored 189 runs in
their first 30 games after the All-Star break, the most in the
majors. That should be good enough to carry them to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they've got a little more than seven weeks to get the
pitching figured out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to come together,'' Martinez said. ``When
everybody gets healthy, and with Coney coming around a little bit,
we're going to be tough to beat. Last year, there were a lot of
questions about our staff, and we had all of our guys healthy going
into the postseason, and we won the World Series. There's always
going to be question marks, but, as long as our guys are healthy, I
don't think we're going to have any problems.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
