   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PEARSON-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Since January 1997, when she
took charge of Pearson PLC _ a British publisher whose holdings
include Penguin Books, The Economist, The Financial Times and a
major educational publishing operation _ Marjorie Scardino has
overhauled the formerly sleepy company, engineering major
acquisitions and asset sales as well as smaller deals. The result,
Scardino contends, is a media company poised for growth by
extending its books, newspapers and magazines into online,
interactive communications. But the dizzying pace of change has
made it difficult for even sophisticated analysts to gauge the
impact of the makeover. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-PLANT (Decatur, Ill.) _ Larry Werve, a 29-year veteran of
the Bridgestone/Firestone tire-manufacturing facility here, says he
can't make sense of the reports that point to his factory as the
main source of a problem that led to the recall of more than 6.5
million tires last week. He and his fellow workers say there has
been something strange about the whole ordeal. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Siemens, the German electronics
giant, has reserved 8,000 of the choicest tables in France this
summer. Foie gras and fine wines, however, are not on the menu.
Siemens is more interested in consumer eyeballs. It is using the
tables _ modified versions of the ubiquitous Parisian bistro table
_ to display advertisements for a new line of cellular telephones.
By Eric Pfanner.
</P>
<P>
   TOOTH-TECH (Undated) _ The business of straightening teeth has
always been a small-scale, fairly low-tech affair _ a one-on-one
interaction between orthodontist and patient. It seems a stretch
that a classic Silicon Valley startup could create a role for
itself in this highly local profession, but that is exactly what
seems to be happening with Align Technology, a manufacturer of a
clear plastic alternative to braces aimed at appearance-conscious
adults. Now, armed with promising early results and backed by
venture capital on a scale that has stunned the industry, Align is
unrolling the most aggressive consumer advertising plan the
industry has ever seen. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
