<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-MEDIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU PLAYERS REMINISCE ABOUT HOW FAR THEY'VE COME
</HEADLINE>
 DAY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU coach Dennis Franchione enjoys telling
the story of changing expectations and mindsets.
</P>
<P>
   Inheriting a 1-10 Horned Frogs football team and turning it into
a winner wasn't an overnight process, though he admits the job
wasn't as daunting as might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   That's something Franchione wasn't prepared to say in December
1997, but taking over a program that hit rock bottom gives a coach
a blank slate and a group of players ready to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had they won four or five games, then maybe they think they're
doing some things right,'' Franchione said Monday at TCU's annual
media day. ``But those freshmen were willing to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Garner, a reserve freshman lineman in 1997, remembers what
that was like. He signed with TCU after the Horned Frogs' 6-5
season in 1995, the second consecutive winning season under Pat
Sullivan. The Horned Frogs slumped to 4-7 in '96, Garner's redshirt
year, before bottoming out at 1-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a young team, and we needed a total attitude change,''
said Garner, who is entering his third season as the starting
center. ``We needed a leader to show us how. We had the raw talent,
we just needed some sculpting and maturing.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of that sculpting has been in the weight room. Two years
ago, only four players on the team could bench press 400 pounds,
Franchione said. Now, 51 players can including quarterback Casey
Printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That reflects how far we've come,'' Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   With consecutive bowl victories, the Frogs have matured into a
top-20 team heading into Garner's senior season. A Western Athletic
Conference championship and entry into the Bowl Championship Series
have become the team's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we wanted to do but didn't know it could be
done this quickly,'' Garner said. ``We have a lot of goals this
year, and that's something that has been growing each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than the obvious team goals, Garner and the rest of the
offensive linemen have a personal interest in one individual honor.
The self-named ``Big Uglies'' are ready to wage their own weekly
Heisman Trophy campaign on behalf of senior tailback LaDainian
Tomlinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``With LT getting all the recognition, it makes us give that
much more effort,'' Garner said. ``The better job we do, the better
game he has and the better his chances of winning the Heisman.''
FRESHMAN UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The incoming freshman class has gone through five practices, and
Franchione said ``they've lived up to their billing.''
</P>
<P>
   The class was rated by many as the third best in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has redshirted the vast majority of his first two TCU
recruiting classes. He did, however, indicate Monday that two
players _ defensive tackle Brandon Johnson (Carrollton Smith) and
receiver Reggie Harrell ( Lamar) _ have a chance to contribute this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans join the newcomers in two-a-day practices Tuesday.
RECEIVER BATTLES
</P>
<P>
   With the graduation of Mike Scarborough, speedster LaTarence
Dunbar (20 catches for 315 yards in '99) is the Frogs' top
returning receiver. Franchione would like Dunbar to take a ``bigger
role'' and labeled him a potential ``playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Franchione also said someone from the group of Cedric James,
Kevin Brown and Tim Maiden has to step up as the No. 2 receiver. In
previous seasons, Franchione had hoped James would make that
transition, but James is ``a guy that can't seem to turn his
springs into falls,'' Franchione said
</P>
<P>
   Franchione added that ``if you drew up bodies, you'd draw them
up like Cedric James.'' James is 6-foot-2, 200 pounds and runs a
40-yard dash in between 4.3 and 4.4 seconds. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ UCLA is no longer an option for the 2001 schedule. The Frogs
and Bruins couldn't shuffle dates to make it work, and UCLA settled
for a game with Kansas. Louisiana Tech, Marshall and Pittsburgh
remain the leading possibilities for TCU's two openings next
season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Franchione said he hopes receiver Ahmed Kabba returns to TCU
in the spring. Kabba, who transferred from Oklahoma and sat out
last season, left the team for personal reasons last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ As of Monday, close to 9,900 season tickets had been sold for
the upcoming season. Since the school began keeping season-ticket
figures in 1961, the school record is 12,056 in '85. The current
total is the sixth highest. TCU's home schedule kicks off Sept. 16
against Northwestern. For ticket information, call (817) 257-7967.
</P>
<P>
   _ Four temporary suites will be erected this season above the
stands in the north end zone, next to the scoreboard. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
