<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY SLEUTH KNOWS RANGERS' WOES NOT IN BOOTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way the newspaper reports have been reading the past week,
some jobs are apparently on the line after all in Arlington. Prime
suspects may have finally surfaced in the collapse of the Rangers
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't I think of this?
</P>
<P>
   Blame the team broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, it all makes good sense, too. For example,
there's Eric Nadel. Despite being immensely respected nationwide
for his 22 years in the local radio booth, Nadel has simply not had
a good season with the home-run inning. Or Bill Jones on TV _ his
``call to the bullpen'' has repeatedly been a bad connection.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us had failed in doing our homework on these kind of
broadcast negatives until it was reported that Nadel and radio
partner Vince Cotroneo, along with Jones and his TV analyst, Tom
Grieve, were all still working without contracts for next season.
And also had been given no assurances they would be back in 2001.
Very suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Then the quote last week from team president Jim Lites that all
the broadcasters would have to be ``evaluated,'' sounded rather
threatening where future job security is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I feel like a member of the Boulder Police
Department. How did I miss such obvious suspects? Was it a case of
simply chasing the wrong clues? Instead of shaking down the
broadcast booths, I had a totally different list of Mr. and Mrs.
Ramseys to bring in for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin had been handcuffed and read his rights, but team
owner Tom Hicks made bail for the general manager. Hicks cleared
Melvin of job-loss repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same for Johnny Oates. He also will be working here
again in 2001, so sayeth Judge Hicks. The manager walks on a felony
charge of his team playing bad ball.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland? To suggest _ no, make that ``demand'' _ the
closer be traded at the end of July almost was turned into a
federal case. Everybody except the ACLU jumped to Wetteland's
defense, despite Wetteland having no defense. See blown saves.
Wetteland is still here, too. And figures to be back next season,
with a nice raise and an extended contract. How comforting.
</P>
<P>
   On and on it goes. Hicks said Melvin and Oates would skate for
this season, then Melvin and Oates have allowed most of the
clubhouse to do likewise. At least that's the way it looks.
</P>
<P>
   But, by gosh, when it comes to the broadcasters, hey, let's get
tough out there in Arlington. Fire 'em all. Or fire some of them.
And if that's too extreme, then at least make them all sweat new
contracts like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, before this latest evidence surfaced, the way I had it
figured was the radio guys and the TV guys had had a much better
season than any of the baseball types. And also a much better
season than Lites and his business-side staff, too. Junking up the
ballpark with that outfield advertising is a crime against good
taste and should be punishable by doing two-to-10, hard time.
</P>
<P>
   Or can that also be blamed on the broadcasters?
</P>
<P>
   Nadel refused comment when asked about his situation Monday, but
please give me the name of one team official who would actually
have the gall to look a pro like Nadel in the eye and tell him he
won't be coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Lites answered Monday. ``I don't mind getting
bad publicity when we deserve it, but there are no hidden agendas
with our broadcasters. I think we've got a quality group. I like
them. The broadcasters are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   They are?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have new contracts to work out with them, and those have to
be resolved to everyone's satisfaction,'' Lites added. ``That would
be a possible hangup, but I'm not anticipating it.''
</P>
<P>
   To me, Lites has been craw-fishing on the subject, based on his
comments the past week in two different papers. But again, Jim says
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chain of command here which leads to Mr. Hicks,''
Lites answered, ``and getting everyone in town at the same time has
been a problem. But give it a week, and we'll have everything
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Lites added, ``This is really a nonissue.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, that's good. If so, it needs to stay that way. There is
plenty of 2000 blame to go around in Arlington, but let's keep that
blame where it belongs. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
