<HEADLINE>
RAVING MAD ABOUT THE RAVENS' CHANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Baltimore Ravens are Super Bowl-bound.
</P>
<P>
   OK, you can stop laughing now. Really. Put away the
straitjackets and call off the guards.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL these days, at least one team rises from the ashes
every season. In 1996, it was the second-year Jacksonville Jaguars
and the second-year Carolina Panthers. The next year, it was the
lowly Tampa Bay Buccaneers. In 1998, the Atlanta Falcons made it to
the Super Bowl. And if, before last season, you predicted the St.
Louis Rams' victory against the Tennessee Titans in Super Bowl
XXXIV, well, then, enjoy your early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, history repeats itself. Again. And again. And again.
</P>
<P>
   So why not the Ravens in 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore has had 11 Pro Bowl selections over the past two
seasons. It will start nine first-round draft picks. It has an
offensive genius as head coach. It has a defense that puts the fear
of Ray Lewis in opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Ravens. Super Bowl champions. It has a nice ring to
it, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that's pressure,'' Ravens coach Brian Billick said.
</P>
<P>
   These are not your father's Cleveland Browns. They are not your
Baltimore Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Since giving up their name, colors, heritage and Cleveland in
1996, the Ravens are 24-39-1. They have the worst TV ratings in the
NFL, and 69,084-seat PSINet Stadium has drawn more than 69,000 only
twice since opening in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Baltimore hasn't had a team this good since the Colts won
their third consecutive AFC East title in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the most ardent Ravens' supporters _ even those
secure enough in their manhood to drive around in a purple van
complete with a Ravens' head _ have not made their reservations for
Tampa, Fla., yet. Not only do they refuse to believe, but they
label anyone who picks the Ravens to represent the AFC in Super
Bowl XXXV as ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's optimistic,'' said Dave McGettigan, a
season-ticket holder and the proud owner of the Ravens' party van.
``But I hope you're right.''
</P>
<P>
   Champions are built on hope ... and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's defense ranked second overall last season and was
sixth in points allowed. Only six teams scored more than 20 points
against the Ravens last season. Only five times did the Ravens
allow more than 300 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get the offense putting up just 20 points a game, we
can do a lot of things,'' Ravens linebacker Jamie Sharper said.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one thing not to love about the Ravens: Tony
Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Billick loves Banks, but he understands the lack of confidence
everyone else has in his starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you play defense the way we play, people are going to
take notice,'' said Billick, who was the offensive coordinator in
Minnesota two seasons ago when the Vikings set an NFL scoring
record with 556 points. ``I think that's what everybody's optimism
is based on. Offensively, we have some weapons. The biggest
question mark people are going to qualify it as: Well, what will
Tony Banks do? We've got some weapons, but that's going to be the
qualifier.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks' passing statistics are almost the same as Tennessee
quarterback Steve McNair over the past three seasons. McNair, who
has had running back Eddie George behind him, has completed 692 of
1,238 passes (55.9 percent) for 8,072 yards with 41 touchdowns and
31 interceptions. Banks, who has had a committee of journeymen
running behind him, has gone 662-for-1,215 (54.5) for 7,925 yards
with 38 touchdowns and 35 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the Ravens' 35-8 loss to the Kansas City Chiefs on
Oct. 21 that Banks replaced Stoney Case as the team's starter.
Banks went 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens were 6-3 in their last nine games, scoring 229 points
after scoring only 95 in the first seven.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time in his playing career, Banks will have
the same offensive coordinator and the same offense for successive
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but feel better,'' Banks said.
</P>
<P>
   You can take this to the bank: The Ravens are Super Bowl-bound.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
