<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS &LR;      08-15 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Set for last Olympic shot, Thompson wins 100 freestyle
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Jenny Thompson came to the U.S. Olympic Swimming
Trials four years ago thinking it would be her last time at the
event. Her plan was to qualify for the Olympics, take her best shot
in Atlanta and get on with her life.
</P>
<P>
   But when she made the team only as a relay swimmer, a role that
did not measure up to what she had expected, she was hurt and
confused, wondering whether her career should end in such a sour
way.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quick, Thompson's coach, remembers telling Thompson
before the Games she could ``go through the motions'' and still
take home some relay medals or truly enjoy the experience as well
as win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day in practice, there was fire in her eyes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The passion that kept Thompson, 27, in the pool the last four
years has raged at the 2000 trials, pushing her to victories in the
100-meter freestyle and 100 butterfly and giving her the chance to
accomplish in Sydney all the things she missed in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the 100 freestyle Monday, Thompson broke her own
month-old American record and touched ahead of 33-year-old Dara
Torres for the second time at the trials. Thompson and Torres, both
of whom train with Quick at Stanford University, also were one-two
in the 100 butterfly finals last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson now has the opportunity to end her career in Sydney by
winning the individual gold that has eluded her (she won a silver
medal in the 100 freestyle eight years ago in Barcelona and five
gold medals in relay events in Atlanta and Barcelona).
</P>
<P>
   ``After the fly, I felt so much relief,'' she said. ``I was
definitely going (to Sydney). This race was more of a dress
rehearsal for Sydney. I felt like I managed the crowd well. It'll
be 10 times louder in Sydney, but that's something I'll be
preparing for.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson led wire-to-wire and won in 54.07 seconds, improving on
the 54.27 she recorded in July. Torres was second in 54.62. Third
place went to Ashley Tappin, who won a relay gold medal in 1992;
fourth went to Amy Van Dyken, who won four gold medals in Atlanta
but now must overcome the effect of two shoulder surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   With Tappin, 25, and Van Dyken, 27, joining Thompson and Torres
as relay competitors, the United States will have a relay team with
an average age of 29, veritable golden girls in swimming years.
</P>
<P>
   Also winning in American-record time Monday at the Indiana
University-Purdue University Natatorium was Kristy Kowal, who took
the 200 breaststroke and gained a place on the team after finishing
third in the 100 breaststroke, missing a berth by one-hundreth of a
second. She had also been third in the 100 breaststroke at the
trials in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal won in 2:24.75, breaking an American record set eight
years ago by Anita Nall. Second in 2:26.79 was Amanda Beard, who
won silver medals in both breaststroke events in Atlanta at the age
of 14 but has not competed at that level since.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, Lenny Krazelburg and Tom Dolan both won for
the second time. Krazelburg took the 200 backstroke to complete his
anticipated sweep of the backstroke events. Dolan won the 200
individual medley, adding that victory to the 400 IM title.
</P>
<P>
   The freestyle duel between Thompson and Torres lacked the energy
of the butterfly, largely because Torres did not challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swam faster at a meet a few weeks ago, so I'm not exactly
pleased with my time,'' said Torres, who is making a comeback after
being out of swimming for seven years. ``My legs were pretty much
gone in the second 50. I'll have to make some adjustments in the
next four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick, who is serving as the coach of the U.S. women's team,
said one thing that needs to change is Torres' tendency to burn
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mentality is to go and go,'' he said. ``It looked like
Jenny was letting Dara do some of the work on the first 50.''
</P>
<P>
   After the butterfly, Quick had been critical of both Thompson
and Torres, saying the race was slow because the two swimmers had
been paying too much attention to each other and not focusing on
their own efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently taking those words to heart, Thompson concluded her
portion of the trials with her best performance. She was entered in
the 50 freestyle but will not compete in the event because she will
have a full plate in Sydney, where she could have five medal
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really pleased with it,'' she said of her effort in the
100 freestyle. ``I felt it was a well-managed and well-executed
race. I'm pleased to get a best time in such a high-profile
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
