<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     08-15 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holt gets show of support as Astros clobber Pirates
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know any better, you'd think Chris Holt had been
the victim of some sort of violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, justice was served to the benefit of a pitcher who
all too often has been a victim of poor run support. The Astros
made up for past neglect Monday night, delivering one big inning
after another in a 16-2 slaughter of the Pittsburgh Pirates at
Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou led the attack as he became only the fourth Astro to
achieve back-to-back two-homer games. The last to do it was Glenn
Davis in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's eye, still a bit discolored from the line drive that
smacked him 10 days earlier, looked like something you might find
on the menu at a Cajun restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he carved up the Pirates, pitching six no-hit
innings before Brian Giles broke up the gem with an infield single
to lead off the seventh inning. Enrique Wilson's sacrifice fly with
one out in the ninth ended Holt's bid for a second career shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling in about the second inning that Holtie was
doing something special,'' Astros shortstop Tim Bogar said. ``(The
hitters) had no idea what was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Pirates pitchers had no idea what hit them. The Astros
established a season high for runs in a game and tied their best
effort in the hit column; they had 19 hits and 14 runs in Sunday's
victory over the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 runs are the most the Astros have scored in consecutive
games since they scored 30 on successive nights in June 1995. The
14-run margin of victory was their largest in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Six Astros had at least two hits, and four had two or more RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reminds me of 1997 when I was still playing with aluminum
bats (at Rice),'' left fielder Lance Berkman said. ``Our offense
has been pretty potent. There's not a letdown in the order.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Tony Eusebio and Bogar _ the Nos. 7 and 8 hitters
_ led the assault with four hits apiece, and Alou tied a career
high with five RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt locked in,'' said Alou, who is hitting .383 with seven
homers and 18 RBIs in his last 22 starts. ``I go through periods
like this every year. I'm seeing the ball very well. The whole team
is hitting; hopefully, we'll keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder the abundance of run support didn't send Holt
(5-12) into shock. The Astros have averaged just 2.4 runs in his 12
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris' stuff is so good that with just a little refinement, he
could turn his 12 losses into 12 wins,'' manager Larry Dierker
said. ``Jeff Bagwell told me a couple of weeks ago that guys on
other teams come down to first base and say, `How does (Holt) ever
lose?'''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who improved to 2-1 with a 1.11 ERA in seven career games
against the Pirates, has three of the Astros' four complete games
this season. The other was turned in by Scott Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what happened to him in his last start, you
wouldn't have thought Chris was a candidate for a complete game,''
Dierker said. ``But he did a great job. I'm proud of him for being
able to go all the way, especially considering how much we used the
bullpen (6 innings) Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring five first-inning runs in Sunday's rout at
Philadelphia, the Astros greeted Pennsylvania's other team with
four runs in the first inning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman hit an RBI double, Richard Hidalgo and Eusebio drove in
runs with singles, and Alou added a sacrifice fly in the fast
start.
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio extended his hitting streak to 17 games _ longest ever
by an Astros catcher and the longest for any Astro since Luis
Gonzalez's club-record-tying 23-game streak in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros topped their first-inning outburst with five in the
third as Eusebio and Bagwell contributed two-run doubles and Bill
Spiers drew a bases-load walk.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Jose Silva (7-7), to whom the Astros showed no
more respect than a pitching machine, saw his night end mercifully
in the third. He allowed nine runs on nine hits and three walks in
2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about our offense,'' Holt said. ``My job
is a lot easier when we score 16 runs and get 19 hits. I felt good
out there. I was working both sides of the plate with my fastball,
and I went back to my strength and tried to get ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little timid early because of last time. But I was
itching to get back out there. I actually wanted one hit back to
me, just so I could see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou hit the first of his homers _ a solo shot off reliever Marc
Wilkins _ in the fourth inning, and his second homer cleared the
railroad tracks above the left-field wall in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
