<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2008 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-15 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS MAUL MARINERS FOR 18 HITS, 15 RUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's basically a simple game.
</P>
<P>
   Pitch the ball, catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   And, just for variety, hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners haven't made it simple in the past few days. But
they've made it simple for the Indians. All Cleveland had to do
Saturday and Monday was wait for a Mariner mistake, then
capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the worst, a four-error, three-wild pitch, one-balk
performance in a 10-4 loss so thoroughly atypical of what the
Mariners and their fans are used to seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as bad baseball as we've played all year,'' shortstop
Alex Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez didn't get slapped with an error himself, but he spent
considerable time after the game slapping himself for not cutting
off a throw from center fielder Al Martin, a play that resulted in
Martin get charged with a needless error and starting pitcher
Freddy Garcia getting charged with an unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have cut the ball off,'' Rodriguez said. ``We know
the formula to win. The last couple of days we haven't paid
attention to the formula. So in that sense it's a positive. It's
not that it's a mystery why we've lost. We know what we've done
wrong and we know how to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first inning set the tone when Kenny Lofton was safe on the
first of two errors by third baseman Carlos Guillen. Lofton was at
second base with one out when Manny Ramirez hit a fly ball to deep
center. Martin made the catch and got the ball back to the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez let the ball go, and the throw skipped by second
baseman Mark McLemore, too. Lofton, who was tagging up on the play
not only made it to third, but he came around to score as the ball
rolled around the infield.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the kind of play that's typical of the Mariners _ but
it is the kind of play that's typical of the Indians. The top three
men in the Cleveland batting order _ Lofton, Omar Vizquel and
Roberto Alomar _ are fliers, and they combine that speed with
daring on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton forced that error, and Vizquel's dancing off third base
forced Garcia into a balk that scored the first of three runs in
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is in the midst of making a run for the playoffs,
having moved into a tie with Oakland for the wild card Monday, and
the Indians and Mariners could be first-round opponents.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the Mariners have adjustments to make. Containing that
speed is priority one.
</P>
<P>
   As egregious as the seven errors made in the three-game series
are, there is every reason to believe the Mariners _ second in the
league in defense _ will bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   A more pressing concern is the lack of control shown by the
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners walked six batters Monday, and four of those were
instrumental in producing Cleveland runs. Add to that the two
eighth-inning walks issued by Brett Tomko on Saturday that led to
two runs, and there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to throw more first-pitch strikes,'' Garcia said.
``When I don't, that's when I get in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   That logic is good, as far as it goes. But pitching coach Bryan
Price said Garcia is putting too much pressure on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddy's out there trying to make the perfect pitch,'' Price
said. ``When he doesn't, he gets so locked into the frustration of
it. I don't think I've been able to help him as much as I should in
the middle innings when that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have high hopes for Garcia, who was a 17-game
winner as a rookie last season. He spent most of the first half
this year on the disabled list, and pitched well in his first few
games back. But his past three starts have seen him walk 12 batters
in 17 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The concern is such that manager Lou Piniella and Price are
discussing whether or not to skip Garcia once in the rotation. The
Mariners have a day off on Thursday and another off-day next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a managerial decision,'' Price said. ``If it happens,
we'd take advantage of it by working some things out in the
bullpen. We can iron out Freddy's delivery a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia would just as soon skip being skipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can work in the bullpen,'' Garcia said. ``I need to get out
there again and throw first-pitch strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
