 BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB SITE &AMP; MAGAZINE REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAY HAVE MIISED THIS)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVID WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Website and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   www.inside.com
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who aspires to be an entertainment executive - and
don't we all? - this cool but slow-loading site reads like the
syllabus for Major Player 101. Launched just a few weeks ago,
Inside.com has quickly become an authoritative source for news,
analysis and smarty-pants commentary on the music, movie, TV and
publishing industries. (beginitalic)T(enditalic)here's lots of
full-text content available for the cost of a click, including such
oddball features as Ask Bernie, a career-advice column written by
megamanager/producer Bernie Brillstein. (Last week's question
began, ``I am a network executive. On one of the shows I oversee
{hellip}'') Inside.com reportedly intends to make its fortune via
subscription access to vast databanks, though you'd have to really
be an entertainment executive to care. Meanwhile, There's lots of
good free stuff, and we mere flyover-state lurkers get to enjoy the
experience of a virtual primo table at the hot Hollywood bistro of
the moment. Ciao, baby!
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``ROLLING STONE''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Horton takes a gander at George W. Bush's environmental
record as Texas governor; Wil S. Hylton profiles Hugh Hefner (an
assignment that - surprise - requires extensive research at Playboy
mansion parties); Barry Walters surveys a slew of Beach Boys
reissues; and Chris Heath examines the Tao of Keanu, which is -
surprise again - way heavy. At one point, Heath asks the shirtless
cover-boy actor/bassist a vague question about wanting to direct.
``He lets out a kind of quiet sigh,'' Heath writes. ``At its worst,
it's like this. You ask Keanu Reeves a question and {hellip} just
wait. Out in space, planets collide, stars go supernova. On Earth,
forests fall, animals screech and roar. People shout and rant and
weep with anger and joy and just for the hell of it. And, all this
time, Reeves sits there, entirely silent.'' For 72 seconds. Then
comes the answer: ``No, not really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN DEMOGRAPHICS''
</P>
<P>
   The cover story examines the marketing competition for the
adventure-travel crowd, a demographic growing wider and deeper and
more sore by the second. Cash-heavy seniors are indulging in the
boonie-based perspiration arts as are footloose boomers and their
skateboard-toting kids. Sales of recreational gear and togs now
reportedly top $80 billion. Two-thirds of all Americans wear or use
such goods at least once a month, up from 50 percent just six years
ago, the magazine says. (Presumably freeing up a lot of room in
bowling alleys, perhaps a fine topic for an upcoming report.) The
second feature looks at domestic migration trends among the
rootless-professional class, concluding that consumption habits of
New Economy workers will enhance greatly the quality of life for
aficionados of quaint ethnic restaurants. (beginitalic)Opa!
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   ``AIR &AMP; SPACE''
</P>
<P>
   Earthbound readers will enjoy the high-flying features about
colorful commercial paint jobs on airliners, the Northrop F-20
Tigershark and a brief history of America's pre-NASA space program.
The cover story isn't really about the goofy car-plane hybrid
pictured there but rather an overview of the aviation photography
of Ben Ross. As it turns out, an airborne Ross shot of the Convair
adorns the studio wall of writer Chad Slattery. The 1948 photo
``captured something essential about postwar America.'' Slattery
writes. ``I look at that picture today and feel the era's
confidence, its faith in technology, its extravagant and often
reckless consumerism.'' The issue's don't-miss feature, though, is
a collection of pre-World War I letters from Marine Corps pilot
Francis Evans to his lady friend, Elizabeth Kibbey, who would later
become Evans' wife. It's a lovely time-capsule look at the
open-cockpit days.
</P>
<P>
   ``BRILL'S CONTENT''
</P>
<P>
   A small box floating on the cover says, ``Skepticism is a
virtue.'' We're down with that. Other cover words reference stories
about dishy (beginitalic)New York Times (enditalic)media writer
Alex Kuczynski, a David Halberstam update of (beginitalic)The
Powers That Be (enditalic)and a detailed look at Joan Didion's
influence on a bunch of contemporary writers, including Maureen
Dowd and Anna Quindlen. In the cover story, Seth Mnookin looks at
George W. Bush's relationship with the press and concludes that the
candidate's sometimes-goofy affability is winning the affection of
at least a few members of the traveling press corps. One conclusive
pull quote sums it up best: ``Bush has neutralized the biggest
question about his candidacy, his perceived lack of intelligence,
by letting reporters see that he is a sharp enough guy when engaged
in casual conversation.'' The skeptical cover headline labels
Bush's chummy tactic ``The Charm Offensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
