<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORTHODOX-AZR </SLUG>
  
Orthodox Judaism
<TEXT>
<P>
   Developed in the 19th century, this branch's followers consider
it the only true form of the faith.
</P>
<P>
   Followers believe that the Torah, the first five books of the
Bible, contain God's own words and should be followed exactly.
</P>
<P>
   For Orthodox Jews, who call themselves ``observant,'' the Torah
affects all aspects of life, demanding adherence to kosher dietary
laws, daily prayer, traditional Jewish liturgy and Sabbath
observance.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews place heavy emphasis on education and traditional
teachings and highly regard rabbis and teachers as interpreters of
the law.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews believe adjustments to the modern world can be
made as long as they don't contradict the teachings of the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)(enditalic)Halachah(beginitalic),(enditalic) the
body of laws that govern civil and religious practices in the
Jewish faith, is to be strictly followed.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews sometimes live apart from the rest of the
community and may wear dark clothes.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sources: (beginitalic)Everything You Need to Know About
Religion (enditalic)(Pocket Books, $12) and
(beginitalic)Illustrated Dictionary of Religions (enditalic)(DK
Publishing, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   boxrule tag with dummy text.
