<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-N     08-15 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL DRUG WAR UNDERMINES LEGITIMATE MEDICAL ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His email address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1996, when California voters passed Proposition 215, which
made the use of marijuana legal for legitimate medical purposes,
federal law enforcement agencies began a new war on drugs targeting
both the sick and their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents have arrested and charged AIDS and cancer
patients in California, who used medical marijuana to ease their
pain and nausea, with violating federal drug laws. And the federal
government has threatened sanctions against California doctors who
provide candid medical advice to patients about the medical use of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   It is a two-pronged attack that is meant to indirectly
intimidate voters who are compassionate enough to want medical
marijuana available for those it helps deal with their illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana has been documented to relieve nausea and some levels
of pain in cancer and AIDS patients. Cancer patients taking
chemotherapy can suffer from intense bouts of nausea. AIDS patients
swallow a cocktail of drugs that can cause almost immediate nausea
and the inability to hold the drugs down. In some cases, the
usually prescribed drugs for nausea do not help, not even the
$40-a-pill, so-called Cadillac anti-nausea drug _ but a little
marijuana does.
</P>
<P>
   Before Proposition 215 was passed, California doctors routinely
encouraged some of their patients to try marijuana to relieve their
symptoms when traditional drugs didn't work effectively. But when
California and other states began to pass medical marijuana laws,
the Clinton administration panicked. The administration decided to
make an example of California by cracking down on its doctors and
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have been threatened with the loss of their prescription
drug licenses, suspension of medical licenses and even criminal
prosecution _ all for telling a patient that, in the doctor's best
medical judgment, the patient may benefit from the medical use of
marijuana and that from a medical perspective it would be advisable
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, possession of marijuana is illegal. Under
California law, medical use of marijuana is legal. Most Western
states have passed medical marijuana laws. There's a tug of war
going on between the federal government and the states on this
issue. Doctors and their patients are being trampled in this
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Under California's Proposition 215, marijuana distribution
centers will give certain patients medical marijuana without a
written recommendation from a doctor. Some centers only require a
diagnosis. A doctor's recommendation is not a prescription for
marijuana, but a doctor's recommendation does exempt a patient from
prosecution under state drug laws. Doctors can neither prescribe
nor dispense marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, the American Civil Liberties Union filed a
class action lawsuit in a federal district court on behalf of a
number of California doctors and patients. The lawsuit named Barry
R. McCaffrey, director of the U.S. Office of National Drug Control
Policy, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and Secretary of Health
and Human Services Donna Shalala as defendants. The lawsuit
requested a preliminary injunction against the defendants to stop
them and their agents from enforcing or threatening to enforce
federal laws that would penalize doctors for communicating with
their patients concerning the risks and benefits of medical use of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors and patients won the lawsuit. On April 30, 1997,
U.S. District Judge Fern M. Smith issued a preliminary injunction
to stop the federal government from threatening or prosecuting
doctors for recommending medical marijuana to their patients, for
providing a copy of the patient's medical chart to that patient or
for testifying in court regarding a recommendation that a patient
use marijuana to treat an illness.
</P>
<P>
   The judge wrote in her decision: ``Because the First Amendment
protects physician-patient communication up until the point that it
becomes criminal, defendants may not prosecute California
physicians unless the government in good faith believes that it has
probable cause to charge under federal aiding and abetting and/or
conspiracy statutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The injunction was ineffective. The difficulty arose in defining
``recommendation.'' The federal government continued to contend
that a doctor can discuss medical marijuana, but not recommend it.
Nor would the government explain the difference between discussion
and recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after winning the lawsuit, doctors still felt they
would be prosecuted if they talked to their patients about the
medical use of marijuana. Therefore, they have remained silent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lawsuit, the federal government had managed to
insert itself between doctors and patients and erect a wall of
silence under the threat of prosecution or sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   So, on Aug. 3, Graham Boyd of the ACLU's Drug Policy Litigation
Project urged a federal district court to permanently block the
federal government from gagging California doctors who think it is
good medical advice to recommend marijuana for specific patients.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Aug. 9, Boyd explained the reason for this
new legal action, ``When the government regulates in the area of
speech, it has to do so very carefully. When it tells us there are
certain things that we can say and other things that we are
forbidden to say, it needs to be very clear about where that line
is. Otherwise people, in order to make sure they don't violate the
law, will often steer well clear of the forbidden zone. So if the
government draws a line that is not clear, if they make
prohibitions that are vague, then it leaves the person who is being
regulated, leaves the doctor, really unable to determine what is
safe to say and what is potentially quite dangerous to say in terms
of their livelihood and staying out of prison. And therefore,
doctors will just avoid the subject altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in California simply want to know what they can say
about the medical use of marijuana and where it might be advisable
and still remain safe from prosecution. That's the reason for this
follow-up litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors are requesting a bright line, a clear demarcation
between legal speech and unlawful speech. Boyd spelled out the
ACLU's proposal for a bright line: ``The exact kind of
communication a doctor can make and the context in which he can
make it. So if a doctor says to a patient in the examination room,
'I recommend marijuana,' that's protected. It doesn't matter what's
in the doctor's head. It doesn't matter what the patient ends up
doing. That speech is protected. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   It is doubtful that even that bright line will solve the problem
with a determined drug czar and a recalcitrant administration.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has done everything it could to block the
implementation of California's Proposition 215.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, with the number of states having passed medical
marijuana laws and states considering it on this November's
ballots, it is time for Congress to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could create an exception to the prohibition on the use
and possession of marijuana. It has done so for another Class I
drug, peyote. Peyote may be used by members of the Native American
Church _ for religious purposes only. Certainly, Congress can _ in
its concern for those who are seriously ill _ create a federal
medical exception for the possession and use of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a federal exception would be the compassionate thing to
do. The right thing. And it would derail this intensifying clash
between states' rights and federal authority. One would think that
a conservative Republican Congress should want to give states their
proper due on this important issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 0820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 09:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK15-COX     08-15 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONVENTION NOTEBOOK: GOP IN THE ENEMY'S LAIR
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Seen threading his way through a bevy of Democrats
at their annual convention: Republican National Chairman Jim
Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson has taken on the role of ``rapid-response attack dog''
in responding to the Democrats' sallies. But he also made some
now-it-can-be-told news of his own.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a reporter's query, he confirmed that the
Republicans chose Philadelphia as the site of their 2000 convention
to pre-empt the Democrats from holding their convention there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure if we hadn't have moved, Al Gore would have gone to
Philadelphia,'' Nicholson said. ``Pennsylvania is in play in
November. Fortunately, we got to pick first.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the Democrats could have trailed the GOP parade into
the City of Brotherly Love. Both major parties held their
conventions there in 1948. But the city's host committee, led by
former Philadelphia mayor (and current Democratic general chairman)
Ed Rendell, had only enough money in the till to support one such
mega-event.
</P>
<P>
   From delegates to media, most people here complain about how
little access they have to the convention floor, the hot parties
and the celebrities who attend them.
</P>
<P>
   Not Aaron Harber. If anything, he's got too much access.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get double invitations to everything,'' Huber sighed Sunday
night, knee-deep in celebrities at a party sponsored by People for
the American Way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Harber is a triple threat here. The host of a Boulder,
Colo., TV show, ``Spontaneous Combustion,'' Harber may be the only
person at this convention _ or any other, in fact _ who is a
credentialed member of the media, a delegate (from Colorado for
Gore) and a member of the electoral college.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a delegate twice before, for Gary Hart in 1984 and
Bill Clinton in 1996. He has figured out how to use his power here
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have unlimited floor privileges and I'm going to abuse
them,'' Harber said with a grin. ``I'll use them about half the
time and then share them with alternates, friends and anyone
willing to pay $100.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a pleasant outdoor lunch at a Santa Monica watering hole,
Arianna Huffington, chief organizer of the so-called Shadow
Conventions in Philadelphia and Los Angeles, wondered why Sen. Russ
Feingold, D-Wis., co-author of the McCain-Feingold campaign reform
bill, wasn't speaking at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   After all, she noted, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who had also
spoken to her group, got a prime-time slot in Philadelphia. And had
not Al Gore recently pledged to make the McCain-Feingold bill ``the
very first piece of legislation I will submit to Congress'' as
president?
</P>
<P>
   Her lunch companion suggested Feingold hadn't exactly helped his
standing with party regulars by coming before Huffington's group
Sunday and blasting the upcoming convention, which is being
</P>
<P>
   held just down the street, as (along with the Republicans) as
``the worst display of money and corruption in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been saying that while George Bush may outshine
Al Gore on the personality meter, when it comes to the issues
voters care about most, Gore will come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is not an instinctive politician,'' Stan Greenberg, the
prospective nominee's official pollster for strategic planning,
told reporters Monday. ``I have no doubt he'll be heard on the
issues, but it won't be as easy as it is for a more glib
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's most recent national poll, taken Aug. 8-10, found
Gore running nine points behind Bush _ about mid-range in the
current basket of presidential match-ups. Perhaps more significant
</P>
<P>
   was the poll's list of issues that prospective voters think the
government should deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Eight: education (20 percent), moral decline (17),
health care (16), retirement and Social Security (14), taxes and
crime (8 points apiece), the economy and the environment (5 each).
</P>
<P>
   But then came some worrisome news for the Democrats: by a margin
of 39 to 38 percent, slightly more voters trusted the Republicans
more to do something about these key issues than the
</P>
<P>
   Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As Georgia Democrats gathered in Los Angeles, the newest
addition to their delegate list _ Sen. Zell Miller _ was back in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Miller became an automatic delegate to the 2000 gathering after
being appointed earlier this month to succeed the late Sen. Paul
Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who delivered a keynote speech in 1992 that gained
national attention, and listened to a convention radio broadcast
during the birth of one of his sons, chose to spend this convention
week in Georgia, touring military bases.
</P>
<P>
   Miller spokesman Rick Dent said the two-term governor who left
office in 1998 never planned to go to this year's convention even
before the Senate appointment.
</P>
<P>
   But political scientists say the strategy of running his own
campaign in Georgia rather than mingling with party leaders and
raising money in the land of Hollywood legends is also a strategic
move that makes it harder for Republicans to tie him to President
Clinton and other national Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was in Washington last week, taking care of his Senate
transition, when the Democratic ticket made a highly-publicized
stop in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``His priorities right now are the bases this week and spending
as much time as possible on policy and getting up to speed,'' Dent
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic party officials won't be able to seat an alternate to
substitute for the absent Miller, who toured Fort Stewart in
Hinesville on Monday and was scheduled for trips to Augusta's Fort
Gordon and Warner Robins Air Force Base on Tuesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathey Pruitt and Jill Vejnoska of the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
