<HEADLINE>
EYAK POURS FUNDING INTO CONFERENCE CALL SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With another $60 million in venture funding in hand, Boston
telecommunications start-up eYak Inc. is finally ready to tell the
world what it's up to: a low-cost way of offering telephone
conference calls through Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   eYak has made a long run in ``stealth mode,'' punctuated only by
announcements that it landed former Federal Communications
Commission chairman Reed Hundt for its advisory board and ex-New
England Telephone chairman Paul C. O'Brien as a director.
</P>
<P>
   The record of eYak's founders, David Friend and Jeff Flowers,
has excited curiosity in local telecom circles about the new
venture. The two men have started four other companies, including
FaxNet, sold last year for $240 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $60 million funding round being announced this week brings
the company's total backing to $76 million. The new funds are being
poured into building what eYak officials call one of the world's
largest ``telecom bridge'' facilities at a Somerville, Mass.
location to serve up to 100,000 participants in conference calls by
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   While market prices will be determined by phone companies that
buy access to eYak and resell services, Friend last week said he
expects they will charge far less than the current range of 20 to
50 cents per minute per participant that industry leaders such as
AT&AMP;T, Sprint, and WorldCom charge for prearranged conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   Friend said eYak's technology can handle calls at about
one-fifth the cost of standard conferencing systems, which should
allow carriers to slash prices substantially. In time, Friend said,
arranging eYak casual conference calls _ such as a chat among
several family members _ should cost no more than placing a
long-distance call to one person now.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen-month-old eYak is using an Internet protocol system to
connect callers to each other. The system can handle far more calls
than traditional voice-circuit bridges and can offer innovative
services such as ``streaming'' live recordings of calls to
listeners' computers through their Web browsers.
</P>
<P>
   The system can also support conference callers sharing images
from their computer screens while they speak, through the eYak Web
page, as well as other enhanced calling services.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, most users of eYak will have their calls from the
phone network converted through a Cisco Systems gateway device into
Internet format for conferencing. But as more and more carriers
build Internet-protocol data networks supporting voice, those calls
can be fed directly into eYak and at lower cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're positioning ourselves a little bit ahead of the wave,
but we think in the future voice is going to be just another
application on IP backbones,'' Friend said. The company plans to
add another domestic conference bridge site, probably in the
Midwest or Texas, as well as sites in Asia and Europe, where use of
conference calling sharply lags the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Friend's view has found widespread agreement on Wall Street,
where shares of Sonus Networks of Westford, a leading start-up
maker of voice-over-Net switches, have soared more than 900 percent
since the May initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Unisphere Solutions of Chelmsford, Mass. and Convergent Networks
of Lowell, Mass., which also offer converged voice-data switching
gear, are aiming for public offerings this year and hope to match
Sonus's market success.
</P>
<P>
   eYak's new funding round is being led by $20 million from UBS
Capital Americas. Also participating are meVC Draper Fisher
Jurvetson, Tudor Investment Corp., Deutsche Bank Alex Brown,
Siemens, and iBasis Inc. of Burlington, Mass., a leader in
international calling routed over the Net. Earlier funders Venrock
Associates, Zero Stage Capital, and Bain &AMP; Co. have also put in
more money, eYak said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Chip Moore, an eYak board member and UBS Capital partner:
``We think eYak's technology is revolutionary and will take over
the enhanced voice market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
