<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE THE MONEY'S PUMPED IN, THE RESTRUCTURING BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Once the money arrives, the ax can fall swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 45 days after Boston's Bain Capital pumped $50 million
into a high-tech spinoff of Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co., the company
has a new strategy, a new CEO, and 80 fewer jobs _ the result of a
24 percent job cut.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Interpath Communications Inc., is an application
service provider, or ASP, which runs Web applications and provides
data services for large and midsize companies. It is now 65 percent
owned by Bain Capital, a powerful private-equity firm. The other 35
percent stake is held by Interpath's former parent, a Raleigh,
N.C.-based utility, which also invested $50 million in late June.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fox, Interpath's executive vice president in charge of
strategy and alliances, calls the firings a ``final transition
step'' after two months of rejiggering strategy and stripping away
anything at the company not related to the ASP business.
</P>
<P>
   Who led the process? Not just the investment guys at Bain, but
their cousins at Bain Consulting, who sat by the Interpath
executives and helped them develop their new business plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a very targeted plan right now, which is something
we haven't had before,'' Fox says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it hasn't been an entirely enjoyable process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very challenging,'' Fox concedes, ``and it's been
very encouraging.'' He says cutting costs and duplication are
important under the new regime, especially with $100 million at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the most prudent deployment of that funding
commitment,'' Fox says. ``We don't want to be another one of these
Internet companies just bleeding money left and right.''
</P>
<P>
   While start-ups with venture backing lately have been feeling
pressured to spend more cautiously, that pressure has always
existed in the private equity realm. There, firms like Bain Capital
make big bets to acquire a controlling interest in a company, with
a goal of quickly improving its performance.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Barry, senior editor at the Private Equity Analyst in
Wellesley, notes that in most private equity deals, ``They're
investing because there's something wrong.'' He adds: ``They're
doing what needs to be done and turning it around.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at Interpath must be aware they're not part of a big,
old-economy utility any more. Bain recently installed its pick for
chief executive, Joel Schleicher, a former Nextel president. And
the spinoff recently acquired a leading Australian ASP, Alta
Internet Business Centres, as part of a new plan to expand
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   If Bain has its way, Interpath will surely go public down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Names are a funny thing in the new economy. They can be clumsy,
as start-ups settle for odd domain names. They are sometimes
lucrative. Or cute. And occasionally they're something to fight
about.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Wine, the New York restaurateur who ran the famous Quilted
Giraffe in the go-go '80s, has bought up dozens of domain names
that he thinks could pay off, from the quirky to the outright
funny.
</P>
<P>
   He has names from EatCaviar.com and EatOlives.com to
BakeCake.com and GrillSteak.com. He's also got SipCognac.com and
DrinkSake.com.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, it gets better. He also owns WirelessDonuts.com,
WirelessCurry.com, and WirelessBurgers.com. Perhaps easier to
understand are WirelessBars, Hotels and Inns.
</P>
<P>
   Wine, a Tufts grad, envisions a world where, if you were in San
Francisco on business and wanted to find a burger joint, you could
simply consult the Web device you carry around with you. Granted,
the information you'd get might be biased. A burger seller could be
a candidate to get behind Wine's burger site, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a technology guy,'' Wine says. But, as he sees it,
``wireless is kind of a brand of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fighting end of the name business, note that the eRoom
Systems Technologies Inc., a Las Vegas room service company that
went public recently without a bang, is not the eRoom Technology of
Cambridge, Mass., with lots of venture backing, a trademark on the
name, and a Web-based project-management product.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beir, CEO of the Cambridge eRoom, says names matter more
than they ever did before, because ``the Web puts more information
at everybody's fingertips.'' He's confident the two companies are
so different they won't be confused. But, he notes: ``They should
have been more careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
