<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-INDREMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART LOOKS TO UNSEAT GAMING'S GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; OAKLAND, Calif. _ Every once in A while, a plan comes along
that seems so outrageous and suicidal that it forces people to pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   John T. Gildred, 29, has come up with such a plan.
</P>
<P>
   A nobody in the clubby world of Silicon Valley, Gildred is
starting Indrema Corp., a company making the first video game
console to use the Linux operating system. Linux is known as the
renegade software credited with loosening Microsoft Corp.'s iron
grip on the market for computer operating systems. It is also known
for its cuddly penguin mascot.
</P>
<P>
   And Gildred is Mr. Penguin on his wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   He is taking on Sony Computer Entertainment, Microsoft, Sega
Enterprises Ltd. and Nintendo Co. _ Goliaths in the video game
business.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the Valley of Dreams, where people are encouraged to
think big, brash, and bold. Gildred's plan is nothing if not bold.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what he's up against. Microsoft recently said it will
spend half a billion dollars just to market its game console, the
X-Box, due out in the fall of 2001. Sony, the Godzilla of gaming,
will unleash its much-anticipated next-generation console, the
PlayStation2, in October. Sega has sold 2 million units of its
DreamCast console, and expects to sell another 3 million in the
next year. In Nintendo's arsenal are Pokemon, the cartoon
sensation, and a new console currently under tight wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indrema clearly has its challenges lined up,'' said P.J.
McNealy, a senior analyst with the Gartner Group.
</P>
<P>
   It's entirely possible Indrema will crash and burn, even before
next year when its console is scheduled to hit store shelves. The
Valley is littered with similarly quixotic efforts. But this is
also a Valley of Dreams populated by a handful of unlikely
survivors, including Apple Computer Corp., once an unruly upstart
in an IBM-dominated world. And there is, of course, Napster Inc.,
which is turning the entire music industry upside down.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Indrema have going for it?
</P>
<P>
   In a word: Linux. The operating system has a fanatical following
of engineers who work tirelessly to crank out Linux software.
Gildred is betting the grass-roots Linux crowd will come up with
the Blair Witch Project of video games. Gildred also says the
Indrema platform will be easier than other closed, proprietary
platforms for developers, making it cheaper and faster to make
games for the Indrema. The typical video game takes 18 months and
several million dollars to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Indrema is also lining up support from other companies,
including Red Hat Inc., Linuxcare Inc., and CollabNet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is enable innovation and creation, so developers
can make it to market without spending a lot of money,'' said
Gildred, who founded OpenSoft Corp., an Internet software company.
``We're reducing the barriers to entry for developers, and that
changes all the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   To have half a chance, Indrema has to change the rules, which
are heavily stacked against the start-up. One rule is that it takes
a fortune to build a brand name. It's unclear whether Indrema,
backed by angel investors who typically don't invest more than $1
million each, has the resources to go up against Microsoft's
upcoming $500 million marketing blitzkrieg.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge has to do with the console itself. Billed as
an ``entertainment system,'' the Indrema is expected to be able to
play digital MP3 music files, browse the Internet, play digital
video discs, record television programs, support interactive
television programming, as well as play video games such as Quake
III Arena and Unreal Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``A platform needs focus,'' said Ed Fries, vice president of
games publishing at Microsoft. ``If it does everything but bake
bread, is it necessarily going to be the best gaming console?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Indrema has to find developers who will make
blockbuster games, said McNealy. With fewer than 50 employees,
Indrema is battling companies with hundreds, if not thousands, of
in-house game developers.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Linux comes in, said Gildred. The open source
operating system makes it easier for independent developers to
create games for Indrema than for proprietary systems of their
rivals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a new player with no name recognition, the only way
to get in is to change the rules,'' said Gildred. ``We're going to
redefine what it means to develop software for games.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
