<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT: GOING INTERACTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Couch potatoes beware. Interactive television is coming.
</P>
<P>
   A whole industry is emerging on the notion that people will want
to click, surf, and shop on their TVs. Its members met this month
in Los Angeles at the eTV World convention.
</P>
<P>
   While keynote speaker and Liberate Technologies CEO Mitchell
Kertzman enthused over the future of interactive television, most
attendees were still trying to defend against the obvious question:
Do people really want to interact with their TVs?
</P>
<P>
   Television is a passive technology. Turn on, tune out.
</P>
<P>
   It's true industry-sponsored research shows that a majority of
interactive TV viewers will click on their screens. But most do so
only out of curiosity and return to their programming, said Dennis
Marshall, market development manager for a San Francisco cable
channel experimenting with the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want to see what happens,'' said Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, very little happens. That's because programming for
interactive television is still embryonic. Aside from the ability
to play virtual Jeopardy and buy cookbooks, the iTV landscape is
still pretty bare, even in Europe, where there are about 7 million
users. That's all going to change, according to Forrester Research
in Cambridge, which projects interactive TV to become a $20
billion-a-year industry by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous stabs have been made at iTV, starting in 1979 with
Warner Amex's service in Columbus, Ohio. In 1995, both GTE and Time
Warner made separate failed attempts. This time, executives say the
Internet will change everything. It will enable viewers to rent
movies or games whenever they want. Users will also be able to
teleconference, get sports statistics on demand, choose camera
angles during sports broadcasts, send e-mail, surf the Web, and buy
that lovely pink sweater Jennifer Aniston wears on her TV show,
``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but will viewers want to do any of that after a hard day in
their interaction-packed jobs? A recent survey commissioned by Red
Herring magazine shows ambivalence. Consumers liked choosing camera
angles, ordering movies, video conferencing, and being able to
watch their favorite programs whenever they wanted. Dead last on
their list of likes: shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a company to keep an eye on, literally. PacketVideo, the
first company in the world to transmit video over a cellular
network, is now giving consumers something to watch: Marvin the
Martian. In a deal with Warner Bros., PacketVideo in San Diego will
be distributing four animation series over its wireless technology,
with Marvin as the extraterrestrial spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For now, only consumers who buy Compaq's iPaq Pocket PC can see
the cartoons by using a wireless Internet connection. But Rob
Tercek, PacketVideo's president and a former Sony Corp. executive,
envisions a future in where videos can stream wirelessly to any
gadget, including cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, few will want to watch full-length movies on a
three-inch screen, Tercek acknowledges. There will be other uses.
Among them are news clips, music videos, short films, animation,
games, and checking on ``traffic cams'' or ``nanny cams,'' Tercek
predicts. While Finland and Japan are already capable of wirelessly
transmitting Internet data at speeds comparable to dial-up
connections, the United States is at least 18 months away from
being able to support wireless streaming video on a mass scale. In
other words, don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the tethered populace can watch the first cartoon
series on traditional network television that began as an Internet
``webisode.'' Called ``Starship Regulars,'' the science fiction
spoof started as a cartoon on Icebox.com, a Los Angeles-based Web
site that develops original animation. The series debuts this month
on Showtime's Sci-Friday lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-QUICKDOT-BOS &LR;      08-15 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-QUICKDOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE START-UP QUICKDOT QUIETLY ROARS TO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Flying under the mass media's radar, a little
start-up company here has quietly attracted nearly 5 million global
subscribers for a new Internet communications service that melds
instant messaging, traditional e-mail, and the digital equivalent
of Post-It Notes.
</P>
<P>
   QuickDot.com has employed ``viral marketing'' _ or friends
getting friends to sign up _ to enroll 4.8 million users for its
messaging service, the company is reporting. It plans to bring the
service to wireless phones later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Similar in some ways to free Internet-based e-mail systems such
as Microsoft's Hotmail, Quickdot offers the equivalent of a
no-charge Web-based blackboard on which people can leave short
notes for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Based on new subscribers inviting other people to ``dot'' with
them, people can create a messaging system separate from their
often spam-laden e-mail inbox to focus on a small group of friends,
family members or business associates with whom they most want to
communicate over the course of a day.
</P>
<P>
   After assembling one or more groups of people, such as a work
group and a social-life group, users log in to the Quickdot page
and get a two-column display. The left side shows
</P>
<P>
   the most recent message written by a sender, and the right side
shows the most recent response the subscriber has sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem that we're solving is really pretty simple: Make
it easier to stay in touch with that core, inner-circle group of 10
or 20 people that most matter to you,'' said John Wang, Quickdot's
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quickdot doesn't replace e-mail for me'' or many other users,
Wang acknowledged. But it simplifies talking to ``the top of my
pyramid or my innermost circle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Quickdot subscribers may use the system to post a
note to 10 friends (such as, ``Do you want to meet at the movies
tonight at 7?'') and check the site to see who has responded they
are coming. Or a group of people working at a company can use it to
post short reminders or sales leads for each other.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Gardner, director of messaging and directory services with
the Aberdeen Group, a Boston consulting firm, said: ``It has some
of the virtues of instant messaging, but it doesn't require the
other person to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner says he thinks the service could prove especially
popular among people under 30 who are most likely to have joined
the instant messaging craze _ especially teenagers who these days
may be far more likely to spend an evening ``I-M-ing'' with friends
rather than talking over the phone as their parents might have at
their age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole young-adult class of user is much more in tune with
it, but I appreciate the value of it in the overall spectrum of
communicating,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Quickdot's rapid growth is comparable to Hotmail, the free
Web-based e-mail service launched in California on Independence Day
1996. In little over a year, before the Net was as widely accepted
a phenomenon as it is today, Hotmail attracted 5 million
subscribers. That drew the eye of Microsoft, which bought the
company for an undisclosed sum in December 1997 when it was up to
10 million accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, under the aegis of Microsoft's MSN portal, Hotmail
has grown to 67 million active users globally, subscribers who used
the account at least once in the last three months. As of May, MSN
Hotmail said it was signing up new users at the rate of 270,000
accounts per day, driven in part by the same word-of-mouth
phenomenon as Quickdot.
</P>
<P>
   Wang came up with the idea of offering the equivalent of
Web-based Post-it Notes while awaiting the birth of his daughter
two years ago. He founded the company in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It has been backed by $6 million from Charles River Ventures and
Comdisco. By relying on no-cost recruitment by existing members
instead of advertising campaigns, it hopes to be able to turn a
profit from business partnerships and banner ads shown at the top
of its page.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Quickdot, which uses the Exodus Web page
hosting service in Waltham, has deliberately been trying to avoid
publicity in order to make sure its technology can accommodate
rapid growth. It has also sought to amass a large subscriber base
before a bigger player such as America Online or MSN caught on and
decided to offer a similar service.
</P>
<P>
   Quickdot officials now feel confident they are ready to begin
trying to match Hotmail-like growth. Given the rate of growth so
far, Wang is bold enough to say: ``If you do the math, eventually
we touch the whole human race.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next phase of growth, Quickdot has developed a system to
bring its technology to wireless phones. Already being used
internally by the company's 35 employees, Wang hopes to launch it
commercially this fall. Quickdot estimates that more than 50
percent of its users already own a wireless phone.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Microsoft and Yahoo have launched efforts to make their
e-mail service available over Net-connected wireless phones from
AT&AMP;T Wireless, Nextel, Sprint PCS, and Verizon Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   But using a phone screen to scroll through an e-mail inbox laden
with junk mail to open worthwhile messages can be frustrating, and
composing responses with the keypad is tediously slow.
</P>
<P>
   Quickdot's wireless version has been configured to show first
the most recent new messages received from ``dotting partners,''
and would allow users to send back precomposed responses such as
``Acknowledged _ will get back to you later.''
</P>
<P>
   Another feature would allow a user checking Quickdot messages to
press a single key to place a call from the phone to the sender,
based on people listing phone numbers with the service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
