r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0816-CO     08-15 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funny you should ask
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Kristofor, my son and only child, insists
that his frequent phone calls home are nothing less than an
adventure into never-never land where he often hesitates to ask me
what I'm up to fearing that I'll answer him
</P>
<P>
   truthfully. He does assure me, however, that my ``differences''
are entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I know of no differences, and I tell him so. Unless,
of course, this morning counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Mum,'' he chirps from his end of the long distance line.
``What's shaking?'' I ask him if he can hold. He says he can.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty seconds later, I'm back. ``Nothing,'' I tell him. He's
confused. ``I'm answering your question. Nothing's shaking around
here.'' He wants to know why I'm chuckling and I tell him it's
because of all the times I asked him the same
</P>
<P>
   question and he gave me the same answer. Kind of like the son
becoming the father of the woman _ or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, he wants to know why, if I'm doing nothing, I'm
breathing so hard. I should have lied, but it's not my style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to crawl back in the office window and I was afraid I'd
drop the shovel,'' I explain. There's a moment's silence which
means he's waiting for more, so I keep going. ``When you called, I
was head-first out the office window
</P>
<P>
   with a shovel in my left hand, and at the same time trying to
get a grip on the sill with my right. I didn't think it would be a
good idea to let go of either one, so I wrapped my left leg around
the shovel thinking that would give me a
</P>
<P>
   free hand to reach through the window and pick up the phone.
Then, when I tried to crawl back in to talk to you, somehow the
shovel got cross-ways in the window and I had to mess with it to
get it back in. It's heavy, and that's why
</P>
<P>
   I'm breathing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   When he doesn't say anything right away I figure he's trying to
visualize the situation before he hollers at me. It doesn't take
long. ``Mom,'' he says sternly, ``haven't I told you to stay off
the porch roof _ with or without a shovel...or a broom...or
whatever else you might have decided to carry out the window with
you? You're going to roll off and mess up your new landscaping.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the reason, I explain, that I couldn't let go of the
shovel _ because it would have slipped down the roof and landed on
a holly bush. Then it occurs to him to ask what exactly I was
intending to do with the shovel.
</P>
<P>
   The raccoon is back, I tell him, and has chosen a spot on the
roof, right next to the downspout, for his outhouse. Delicacy keeps
me from even trying to describe the foul heap of droppings directly
under my bedroom window, but at
</P>
<P>
   least now I know where my raspberries have gone.
</P>
<P>
   When the phone rang, I was crouched on the roof trying to figure
out what to do with the mess once I had it on the shovel. I
couldn't very well dump it into the newly-planted front yard. How
would that look? Holly, hosta, and a pile of
</P>
<P>
   raccoon doo? Nor could I give it a good fling and run the risk
of hitting a neighbor out for a morning constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   I'd thought about maybe shoveling it into a bucket and lowering
it over the roof's edge on a rope, but quickly realized the odds of
my following the bucket over the gutter were tilted in favor of
gravity. I imagined the headlines in
</P>
<P>
   tomorrow's paper: Gibsonburg eccentric maimed in fall from porch
roof _ mysterious substance in bucket under analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor suggested I call someone. And say what, I asked him.
``Hello? 9-1-1? Can you come right over? I'm having a raccoon doo
doo emergency.'' I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, my situation brings to mind the old pilots' lament
about running out of ideas and altitude at the same time _ which is
exactly what I have done.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with the raccoon, it's business as usual _ on my
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
