<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX     08-15 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sen. Ellis asks right questions about criminal justice in Texas
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oliver Cruz was all of 12 mentally when Texas stuck a poison IV
in him last week.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he had 33 years to grow up didn't make it so. With
an IQ of between 64 and 76, his body was all man, but his mind was
wedged somewhere between Pokemon and Inspector Gadget.
</P>
<P>
   Retarded though he was, Cruz was bright compared to Felipe
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has an IQ between 40 and 50. A functional
kindergartner, he spent 13 months in jail without legal
representation _ unable to read, unable to understand the charges
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Rodriguez was released from a Panhandle jail when a
judge dropped charges of burglary and arson. It is unclear exactly
what the man did. Without counsel, he had confessed to burning two
vacant buildings in Tulia, Texas. Ultimately he was ruled
incompetent to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Two retarded men, one flushed away, one locked away for a year
without representation. Texas justice.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Cruz's crime _ a rape and stabbing _ was horrific. The
jury ruled he knew right from wrong. A 12-year-old ought to.
</P>
<P>
   In its last session the Texas Legislature came close to passing
a bill sponsored by State Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, to prohibit
executions of the retarded. Twelve states do. Gov. George Bush
opposed the bill, saying current laws suffice to establish mental
competence. But competence and retardation are separate issues. The
question: Do we execute a child trapped in a man's body?
</P>
<P>
   Thus far Texas' response: Don't bother us with such questions.
</P>
<P>
   One who won't stop asking is Sen. Ellis. He has been one of
Texas' chief advocates for better criminal representation for the
poor and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Rodriguez, the mental kindergartner jailed for more
than year without legal representation, reminded observers of
another Ellis bill, this one vetoed by Bush. It would have required
an attorney for indigent defendants within 20 days of being
charged.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would have allowed counties to set up public
defender offices.
</P>
<P>
   Legal representation of the poor is strictly a local matter in
Texas. The state spends no money on it. It also has no minimum
standards for when someone without representation must be assigned
an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The more one examines the situation, the more one realizes that
the two chief benefits of having lackluster court-appointed
attorneys are (1) dollars and (2) cents. They save taxpayers money
by not presenting a zealous defense, not straining the docket with
appeals, sometimes not even showing up.
</P>
<P>
   It is so easy to let these things slide. Unless someone has a
loved one thrown in jail or has his own hide hanging, why should
one worry about the rights of the accused?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately we have someone like Ellis. He was front-and-center
pressing for a re-examination of the case against Roy Criner,
convicted in connection with a 1986 rape and murder in Montgomery
County. DNA tests found that the semen in the victim wasn't
Criner's. The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals refused to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Recently a district judge requested a pardon for Criner. Monday,
Bush said that he will grant it.
</P>
<P>
   Why aren't more people asking the questions that Sen. Ellis
asks? Why are rights of the accused such a hard sell? Expedience,
expedience.
</P>
<P>
   As for the execution of one more retarded individual, the act
reveals the death penalty to be as much a matter of disposition as
it is justice.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
