<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BLUEOCTOBER-HNS     08-15 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BLUEOCTOBER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON'S BLUE OCTOBER TAKES ANTHEMS OF ANGST AND HOPE TO A
NATIONAL STAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
HOUSTON _ Blue October lead singer Justin Furstenfeld offers a
variety of reasons for writing more than 200 songs in just 12 years
about pain and emotional loss. If you have enough time, he'll tell
you every last one.
<TEXT>
<P>
   High school loneliness, dalliances with drugs, depression and
hospitalization are a few of the factors he cites for his expansive
output.
</P>
<P>
   One need know little else about the 24-year-old Houston
songwriter/vocalist than his musical role model: morose alt-rocker
Morrissey, former lead singer of the Smiths, whose hit songs bear
titles like ``Girlfriend in a Coma,'' ``Heaven Knows I'm Miserable
Now'' and ``Unloveable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say that Morrissey taught me about lyrics,''
Furstenfeld says. ``I feel like he personally gave me permission to
write music.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands about opening your closet and getting into some
really dirty (issues). Why be fake?''
</P>
<P>
   Furstenfeld has heeded the advice since he started writing at
age 12. He admits to lashing out and feeling awkward as a kid,
closing up with drug experimentation as a young adult, and creating
drama in his life so he could fall backward into it right into his
early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he picked up a pen, however, that the outlet for
personal salvation, as well as his career, became apparent. It
started as poetry he would shape in creative writing classes at
Houston's High School for the Performing and Visual Arts, but soon
turned into song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   After playing with the well-received but unpolished Houston band
Last Wish, he teamed up with fellow student and violinist Ryan
Delahoussaye to form Blue October in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   With one independently released album, ``The Answer,'' that sold
thousands of copies locally, and hundreds of songs still in the
vault, it appears Blue October is poised to perform on the national
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Furstenfeld and his bandmates _ Delahoussaye, drummer
(and brother) Jeremy Furstenfeld, guitarist Brant Coulter and
bassist Matt Novesky _ were signed to Universal Records. Universal
released the group's major-label debut, ``Consent to Treatment'' on
Tuesday. The band will kick off its national tour with a hometown
performance Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Furstenfeld's closet will be open for all to see.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you exactly the first time I saw Blue October,''
says Michael Rand, the Michigan-based manager who secured the deal
with Universal. ``I was actually at a restaurant in Houston to see
another group. These guys were also on the bill, and the songs just
blew me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical for Furstenfeld _ a handsome guy who wakes up every
morning stressing over how ugly or heavy he perceives himself to be
_ he remembers that night about 18 months ago with less confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a seafood restaurant, and I was so upset because I
thought we were selling out,'' Furstenfeld recalls. ``I really
didn't want to play for people eating shrimp, but it turned out to
be the best show we could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, Rand asked Furstenfeld how many other songs Blue
October had like the ones it had just played _ moody art-rock songs
with a pop edge that create dark pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds, Furstenfeld told him. Rand asked Justin to come to New
York and play them. All of them.
</P>
<P>
   The group was signed to Universal four months later.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Furstenfeld knew early on that he was not the kind of kid who
was going to end up in a cubicle wearing a suit and tie. He was
born in the Heights neighborhood of Houston, and was drawn to the
city's artsy, open-minded Montrose art and coffeehouse community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for my experiences and this band, I would
probably be somewhere like . . . college,'' Furstenfeld says,
emphasizing the word as if it were synonymous with prison or
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Every year at HSPVA, he auditioned for the choir ensemble, the
Singing Boys of Houston. He didn't make the choir cut, but always
felt at home in the more liberal ``high school with ashtrays''
approach to artistic education.
</P>
<P>
   Some students didn't wear shoes. Others didn't wear shirts. Many
kids smoked cigarettes. More important, he felt the curriculum
better fit his interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do sports, I got a 500 on my SAT, and I was always
sitting around writing poetry,'' Furstenfeld says. ``I knew I
couldn't go to a regular school. I wanted to write plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Playwriting wasn't available until his senior year, so he spent
the next three years learning to open himself up to expression in
the HSPVA theater department.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people taught me how to take my guard down,''
Furstenfeld says of his teachers. ``I wouldn't have (graduated high
school) without them.''
</P>
<P>
   With little interest in college, Furstenfeld took to hanging out
around Houston's downtown warehouse district. His old haunts
introduced him to drug culture.
</P>
<P>
   He describes his lifestyle back then: sitting around, doing
psychedelics and then writing about it.
</P>
<P>
   To clear his head, and keep Blue October together, he moved to
San Marcos, where he took a job at the San Marcos Treatment Center.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Furstenfeld found himself hospitalized. His life
``completely broke apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I worked in a mental hospital, and the next day I'm a
patient,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed with depression, he now takes medication to regulate
his body and emotions. The medication makes him groggy on occasion,
but he is easier to be around these days. It's less difficult for
him to keep friends and communicate with his girlfriend, Mamie. Yet
sometimes, he lets doses slide just so the emotions so vital to his
creative process have time to well up inside. His favorite illicit
drug now is his own untreated emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the things Furstenfeld takes on the road with him, the item
he cherishes most is his confessional altar. A childhood friend got
Furstenfeld the mini-enclosure for disclosure and redemption and
attached his phone number to it.
</P>
<P>
   The simple message: Call anytime you need to talk. Furstenfeld
has used the number many times since work for ``Consent to
Treatment'' began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost touch with my life a long time ago and now feel like
kind of a nomad,'' Furstenfeld says. ``If I fall, I get back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Blue October's album, you can almost go through the
steps of addiction, submission and rehabilitation with Furstenfeld.
The band's locally produced album, ``The Answer,'' was a slow,
loping, downbeat set inspired by Furstenfeld's uncontrollable
post-high school malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consent to Treatment'' brings us along to the realization of
his depression and his seeking help. One song, ``Retarded
Disfigured Clown,'' is spoken-word poetry about embracing the weak
and outcast. It gives way to tightly wound guitar self-analysis
that stretches to string-quintet symphonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independently Happy'' spins around a live-wire spark from
speaker to speaker with the gradual scaling of a U2 ``The Joshua
Tree''-era anthem. ``Libby I'm Listening'' and ``Amnesia'' sound
like updates of Peter Gabriel's best pop hits. The album cover,
featuring Furstenfeld's face covered in fake grass and miniature
street signs, evokes the images of Gabriel's ``Sledgehammer''
video.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the album could keep Blue October on the road for a
year or more. Many rock stars see touring as a chance to break away
from past acquaintances. Not Furstenfeld. It's clear life away from
Mamie could give way to a whole new trail of songs about loneliness
and grief.
</P>
<P>
   He has done a lot of growing up, but he talks about Mamie like a
swooning high school freshman, still not convinced that the popular
senior girl would date him.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure if he'll be moving to L.A. immediately with her,
or if he'll return to Houston for his next break.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my soulmate, and I know we'll be together,'' he says.
``I'm not sure where I'll be returning to, but at least I'll have
plenty of places to couch-surf between here and California.''
</P>
<P>
   To learn how the saga ends, we'll just have to wait for the next
Blue October album.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   For more information, check www.blueoctober.com. Tour details:
Aug. 30, Rodeo 2000, Bryan; Sept. 3, Executive Surf Club, Corpus
Christi; Sept. 5, Brewster's Pub, Amarillo; Sept. 6, Liquid 2000,
Lubbock; Sept. 9, Gordo's, San Marcos; Sept. 22, Caravan Of Dreams,
Fort Worth. Dates outside of Texas to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
