</P>
<P>
   ECOM-NET-ARTISANS _ In Berea, Ky., a center of traditional
Appalachian crafts, artists are slowly coming to terms with
e-commerce. For example, Virginia Petty, who makes one-of-a-kind
baskets, says, ``I put the pictures up (on my site), and if anybody
wants to buy them, they can,'' she says. ``I'm not into
marketing.'' Del Martin, who has been selling Mission-style antique
furniture and high-end rugs from his living room since 1995, uses
his Web site, www.jaxrugs.com, to show his customers new designs
and to link to eBay. ``Jax Rugs could survive without the
Internet,'' he says, ``but I'd have to stop buying and selling the
antiques, which I love doing.'' A report on how one small town is
approaching cyberspace. By Emily Yellin. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   THREE ROADS INTO CHINA: B2B, B2C and C2C
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-CHINA-E-SECTORS _ It may be a while before China's
e-commerce sector can support more than a few big companies. But
things are changing. China is relaxing central government control
over its vast export machine, and the Internet is linking that
machine to buyers worldwide. Furthermore, e-commerce is cutting
through China's archaic distribution system. The government is also
bringing the country's growing online population new services, from
Internet auctions to electronic matchmaking. Here, a report on the
state of e-commerce in China for business-to-business,
business-to-consumer and consumer-to-consumer sites. By Craig S.
Smith.
</P>
<P>
