<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Tuesday, Aug. 15, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Eric Rosenberg or Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-THEORY (San Francisco) _ Jon Entine, a Jewish American, and
Alondra Oubre, an African American, have little in common
physically, but they're on the same page, mentally _ and it's
causing problems for both. They've had the temerity to publicly
identify themselves with an unpopular, politically incorrect theory
some hail as courageous, but many call racist. Both say blacks are,
in fact, biologically different. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   KILLER-LAWYER (San Francisco) _ The California Supreme Court
says a San Francisco man who bludgeoned his sister to death in
1975, and served prison time for manslaughter, is morally unfit to
practice law in California despite numerous testimonials of his
rehabilitation. By BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-KIDS (San Francisco) _ Posing a persistent and
staggering challenge to California, results of a statewide
achievement exam show that public schools are failing to educate
immigrant kids who are not fluent in English. By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BIG-BUCKS (Los Angeles) _ After thanking AT&AMP;T, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson and other big-money special interests for the scrambled
eggs that Democrats were about to eat, California party Chairman
Art Torres had one more important corporate donor to praise: ``And
also the great company that has brought joy across America _
Pfizer.'' By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   Financial (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-REAL-ESTATE (San Francisco) _ Nearly empty and derelict, two
undeveloped sites in the heart of San Francisco's financial
district have posed a quandary for some two decades. Now, with near
Gold Rush conditions prevailing in a real estate market that
promises an owner sky-high rental profits, the quandary shows signs
of easing. A real estate has filed applications to build office
structures on both sites - the only two undeveloped plots in this
historic square mile. By GERALD D. ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BLUEOCTOBER (Undated) _ Blue October lead singer Justin
Furstenfeld offers a variety of reasons for writing more than 200
songs in just 12 years about pain and emotional loss. If you have
enough time, he'll tell you every last one. On Aug. 15, Universal
releases the group's major-label debut, ``Consent to Treatment''
today. The band kicks off its national tour with a hometown
performance Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIMMING (Indianapolis) _ A friend told Kristy Kowal to puff
out her cheeks, wide enough so he could see, while she waited be
hind the starting blocks for the 200-meter breaststroke at the U.S.
Olympic Trials. A few nights before, waiting for the 100
breaststroke, she had looked as if she couldn't breathe. And
everyone knew how that had worked out. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MORSE-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ Downtown Los Angeles is the
perfect urban setting for the Democratic National Convention.
There's nothing there. This week there's an even bigger nothing
there. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If Al Gore wants to waltz to the
music of the Catholic Church, he might think twice about penciling
in Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights so high on his
dance card. Based in New York, the league bills itself as ``the
nation's largest Catholic civil rights organization,'' which may or
may not be true. It certainly is the most hyperbolic and vocal. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
