<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-HARLEY-U-TURN-HARVARD     08-15 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEY-U-TURN-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REVIEW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEY'S LEADERSHIP U-TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Monday, Aug. 14, 2000, or thereafter.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is from the July-August
issue of issue of HARVARD BUSINESS REVIEW, the premiere source of
information on the art and science of business and management. For
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or about The Syndicate's new offerings from HARVARD BUSINESS SCHOOL
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICH TEERLINK  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When I became president and COO of Harley-Davidson's motorcycle
division in 1987, the hard work of saving the company was done. We
had survived seven arduous years of crisis. But we faced an
altogether new challenge _ sustaining progress. How to do that?
</P>
<P>
   For me, the answer was clear. We needed to create an environment
where everyone at Harley took responsibility for the company and
its future. I believe that a leader should mind the interests of
all stakeholders, of course, but also be an outspoken advocate for
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are hardwired, like me, to be a leader who shares
rather than exerts power, the command-and-control model is hard to
avoid. The top management job carries certain expectations on
behalf of employees, colleagues and the outside world. It takes
trust on the part of employees and discipline on the part of the
leader to push back on those traditional expectations and create a
company where everyone owns decisions and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL MODE
</P>
<P>
   My career with Harley-Davidson dates to August 1981 when I
joined as CFO, just two months after a group of 13 Harley managers
had bought the company from AMF in a leveraged buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson had a poor reputation for quality and
reliability, and it was behind the curve on product design and
development. Break-even points were high; market share was falling.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the company faced tough competitors: Honda and
Yamaha. It's no wonder that in 1980, when AMF engaged an investment
bank to sell the division, it found no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, Vaughn Beals, formerly AMF's group
executive for the Harley division and now chairman and CEO of
Harley-Davidson Inc., and the leadership team (of which I was
member) cut the overall workforce by 40 percent _ affecting
salaried and hourly workers. All remaining salaried employees
agreed to a 9 percent pay cut, frozen for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, it appeared that Beals and the team might pull
off a miracle. The company had introduced its Evolution Engine in
1984, and that, combined with the new Softail product line, began
to make some money.
</P>
<P>
   Harley was also having some success with special programs
started to help its dealers attract and retain customers. Important
improvements were made on the operating side of the business, and a
financial restructuring positioned the company to go public.
</P>
<P>
   By 1986, the prognosis looked good. Manufacturing costs were
falling; reductions in in-process inventories and associated
carrying costs saved about $40 million a year. Our quality had
improved. Our dealer network was revitalized and growing. When we
went public in July, the offering raised $25 million more than the
underwriters had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ENGINES OF CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   Once it was clear the present was in good order, it was time to
think about the future. I didn't have a plan beyond knowing that
capturing the ideas of all the people at Harley was critical to our
future success.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gelb, then vice president of manufacturing, and John
Campbell, vice president of human resources, and I were meeting a
lot back then to talk about how to improve operations. One idea we
came up with was gain sharing _ a program to allow all employees to
share in the company's financial success. But organizational-change
consultants quickly explained that the gain-sharing program had
been created at the top and was about to be imposed from the top.
So much for inclusive leadership!
</P>
<P>
   GOOD INTENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   We explored several other ideas and posed many questions: How
does constant crisis management affect a workforce? How _ in the
absence of a crisis _ can we create an environment where employees
care about the company on a personal level and work together to
improve individual and overall performance?
</P>
<P>
   One consultant, Lee Ozley, talked a lot about the psychologist
Abraham Maslow. Maslow had a theory that absent a crisis, people
rarely commit to a program imposed on them. But they will willingly
commit to a program they help create. That thought made a huge
impression on me. In late 1988, we agreed to start a series of
programs intended to elicit ideas from our employees.
</P>
<P>
   First we approached the union leadership of the roughly 700
employees in the Wisconsin operations and asked them to help us
create a vision for the business. Ozley had warned us that it would
take 12 to 18 months to prepare people for such a process. But I
decided we couldn't wait. I wanted a new labor-management
relationship approved before our union contracts expired, in three
months.
</P>
<P>
   We were able to put in place one-year contracts with each local
union that included the joint vision-building process. Over the
next several months, many people in the Wisconsin operations worked
hard to craft a joint vision. First, about 70 leaders, union and
management, wrote down ideas for what Harley should become. Then a
facilitator met with them in groups to build consensus. Finally,
all 70 people met for three days to forge a shared strategic vision
for Harley-Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   When we rolled the ideas out to the rest of the company _ an
audience mainly of salaried employees _ one asked, ``Who
represented us in this process?''
</P>
<P>
   I was ashamed. Once again, we had behaved like traditional
managers by not including everyone. But we quickly set up two
groups of salaried employees to share the making the vision work.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, our leaders weren't prepared to implement the
dramatic change the plan called for. In fact, the implementation
came off like a forced march, sending mixed messages and causing
confusion on both the shop floor and in the offices.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the largest local union opted out of the
process after two years. Although the joint visioning process did
not succeed as we had hoped, it laid the groundwork for shared
leadership agreements with the unions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT DOES RICH WANT?
</P>
<P>
   In March 1989, I became CEO. I soon decided that it was time to
bring together the company's 60 senior executives at an offsite
meeting. I wanted them to get to know one another and begin to work
as a truly unified team.
</P>
<P>
   We developed a program featuring two expert speakers on the
issue of change and one outside CEO who had led a major change
effort. After the presentations, we broke into smaller
cross-divisional, divisional, functional and cross-functional
groups to talk about what we'd heard, what we thought we could
accomplish and how we could do it. I visited each cluster with the
speaker so people could ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   On many easels that groups were using to record their ideas, I
was dismayed to notice the question ``What does Rich want?'' I
thought we had been so clear that the point was not to figure out
what I wanted but to figure out what everyone wanted for the
company. At the closing session, I let loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a revolution, and I'm not going to lead it,'' I said.
``You need to lead it.''
</P>
<P>
   When I returned to the office on Monday, a colleague was waiting
for me. ``You know, you really stuck a pin in our balloon at that
session,'' she said. ``We were doing fine. We were getting to know
one another, expressing our fears as well as our thoughts about
what we wanted for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   And then I realized my mistake. What was important were their
expectations. And they were happy. Too frequently, we as leaders
try to satisfy ourselves rather than others.
</P>
<P>
   The second session went well. By the third, we had jettisoned
our facilitators _ as had been the plan _ and took responsibility
to teach one another instead of listening to the experts.
</P>
<P>
   ONGOING PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   I retired as Harley's CEO in 1999, and I now serve on its board.
Looking back, I believe I succeeded in my journey to be a different
kind of leader. Harley's culture has changed, but the work is not
done.
</P>
<P>
   Transforming a culture takes time. Everybody hasn't fully bought
in to the inclusive approach. We still have people who think they
know all the answers, but they are getting fewer in number. We
still have people who just want to bring their bodies, and not
their minds, to work. But their ranks, too, are dwindling, too.
</P>
<P>
   We've been transforming ourselves since the buyout and will
still be at it 10 years from now. It is a journey that will never
end unless we let it.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Teerlink is the retired chairman and CEO of
Harley-Davidson. Since retirement, he has been speaking
internationally to corporations, industry organizations and
educational institutions.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
