<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MED-BUDGET &LR;      08-15 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MED-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Here is TUESDAY'S package of Medical News Today health stories
and features prepared by HealthScout.com and distributed to clients
by The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   For questions and comments please call The New York Times
Syndicate at 212-499-3331 or e-mail vancepw(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   VITAMIN-SOURCES-MED _ Steak may contain plenty of vitamin B-12,
but your body can absorb the critical nutrient more easily from a
bowl of cereal or a cheese sandwich, says a new study.
</P>
<P>
   That's critical information for the nearly 40 percent of
Americans who the study says may be on the verge of vitamin B-12
deficiency. A lack of B-12 puts people at risk for problems such as
pernicious anemia, loss of sensation, balance disorders and
dementia. A B-12 deficiency also can increase the risk of heart
disease and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a really serious problem nutritionally and one
that's under-recognized by doctors,'' says lead researcher
Katherine Tucker, an associate professor of nutritional
epidemiology at Tufts University. The findings, based on a study of
3,000 adults from their mid-20s to age 80, are reported in a recent
issue of the American Journal of Clinical Nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-BRAIN-MED _ It's one thing to have a song in your heart,
but you might have one in your brain, too. Musical hallucinations
experienced by a man with brain injury have led researchers to
identify a part of the brain where they think familiar songs might
be encoded.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual case study -- about a German man with a lesion on
his brain who reported hearing ``Our Beautiful Country of
Brandenburg,'' a popular song about his birthplace -- was described
in this month's Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   ZINC-COLDS-MED _ High doses of zinc may cut how bad your cold is
and how long you have it, but taking so much for too long may
affect blood production, among other things, says the latest study.
</P>
<P>
   People who took 80 milligrams of zinc -- more than five times
the recommended daily amount of 15 milligrams -- for up to five
days had cold symptoms for 4 1/2 days; people who didn't take the
zinc had cold symptoms for eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything below 15 to 30 milligrams of zinc (per day) isn't
harmful,'' says Dr. Ananda S. Prasad of Wayne State University
School of Medicine, who co-authored the study. ``But we have to
have some education (about the uses of zinc), because taking more
than that over a long period of time is not recommended. Too much
zinc abuses copper in the body and therefore needs to be monitored
very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Results of the study appear in the Aug. 14 issue of the Annals
of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   LASER-PSORIASIS-MED _ For the millions who suffer from psoriasis
and vitiligo, swift and complete relief may have finally arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The source of hope for people with the two disfiguring skin
diseases is a new hand-held device called the eximer laser. Apart
from working quickly, it seems to have no side effects because it
targets only damaged skin, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   The eximer laser, which uses ultraviolet-B light, can clear up
the conditions in a fraction of the time required by older
ultraviolet laser treatments, doctors say. It also reduces the risk
of skin cancer, a problem with the older lasers.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIN-MARROW-MED _ Feeling something in your bones may be more
than an expression. A new study claims that stem cells from your
own bone marrow might someday help repair your brain and central
nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean significant improvement for people with
neurological diseases such as Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and multiple
sclerosis and people who've had strokes and traumatic brain
injuries, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers at the University of South Florida College of
Medicine say they have induced stem cells from human bone marrow to
differentiate into neural cells, at least in the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT HEALTHSCOUT:
</P>
<P>
   HealthScout (http://www.healthscout.com) is a service of Rx
Remedy, Inc., a leader in the field of health information and
publisher of REMEDY Magazine, a prize-winning health publication
read in 2.2 American homes.
</P>
<P>
   -- All of HealthScout's original stories are based on primary
sources: reports in refereed medical journals and interviews with
the medical researchers who authored them. Fact-checkers
independently confirm reporters' work on sensitive stories.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's medical writers and editors have previously
worked at many of the nation's most respected newspapers and
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   -- HealthScout's Scientific Advisory Board includes leading
authorities in more than a dozen disciplines.
</P>
