Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DOMINICAN-FUGITIVES (Undated) _ On the case of Pablo Almonte,
who, with a fellow gang member, killed a New York Police Department
officer in 1988 and has been hiding since then in the Dominican
Republic. But a new government that has promised to fight crime and
corruption will come to power Wednesday, and it has already held
talks with U.S. officials about fugitives in the Dominican Republic
and has signaled that it will be more responsive to requests for
finding fugitives. By Juan Forero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news category)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Crude oil prices rose above $32 a barrel
Tuesday for the first time since the Persian Gulf War in 1990 on
worries about low petroleum inventories in the United States and
frank talk by Venezuela about OPEC's thirst for petrodollars. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ Mexico will report its
second-quarter growth rate Tuesday. Economists believe that the
economy grew at a rate of 6.9 percent, compared with 7.9 percent in
the first quarter. Mexico also said strong oil prices had helped
the government achieve a budget surplus in the first half of the
year. (Staff byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-AMERICA-DELIVERY (Undated) _ A look at the delivery
services in Latin America, which are ill equipped to handle the
economic growth and an expected surge in e-commerce that is
expected in a few years. Big global delivery companies such as
United Parcel Service and Federal Express are moving to strengthen
their networks in Latin America ahead of an anticipated expansion
in their business. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
