Festival. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-THEATER (London) _ A Critic's Notebook: On London theater
this summer, where midlife resurrections are translating into big
box office hits with widely varied degrees of artistic success. On
the stage, at least, women rule, and not the fantastical, mannered
Mames and Dollys who have traditionally governed musicals. By Ben
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-KINETIC-SCULPTURE (London) _ The British art scene is so
heady with hype, gimmickry and self-promotion these days that it
comes as something of a relief to discover the long lost world of
kinetic art at the Hayward Gallery on the south bank of the Thames.
By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   WAINEWRIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Andrew Motion's unusual
biography of Thomas Griffiths Wainewright, a minor English painter
of the first half of the 19th century who was convicted of forgery
and transported to Australia, where he did hard labor for seven
years. He was an unusual criminal in that he knew people like
Samuel Taylor Coleridge, William Blake and Lord Byron, and when his
term of hard labor was finished he gained recognition in Tasmania
as a portrait painter. Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   XO-SAUCE-SOLVED (Undated) _ Dining out has its pleasure and its
mysteries. XO sauce is both. I recently developed an infatuation
with it. The flavor was intriguing: salty and sweet, hot and sour.
In it I could see tiny bits of dried shrimp, garlic, chilies and
scallop. There were very thin chopped-up noodles, too, and nearly
microscopic chips and flecks of unknown ingredients. If this was
XO, I had to get to the bottom of it. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   FLAVORED-ALCOHOL (Undated) _ Restaurants are borrowing a page
out of the Absolut book and infusing their vodkas and other alcohol
with an array of flavors. By Matt Lee and Ted Lee.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ The Wine Talk column, on Riojas that are
worthy of the new pride their makers take in them. By Frank J.
Prial.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   FAUCHON-OPENING (New York) _ On the opening in New York of a
branch of the legendary Paris food shop, Fauchon. By Florence
Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `d' category)
</P>
<P>
   MYANMAR-SALADS (Undated) _ Salads are always cooling, of course,
and in countries with tropical climates hot spices are frequently
used because they make people perspire, another technique for
cooling off. The Burmese, like the Thais and Laotians, love raw
vegetables and greens and eat them with a pungent dipping sauce
that usually contains chilies. By Marian Burros.
</P>
