<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-CVN-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-15 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL VOID 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Downtown Los Angeles is the perfect urban setting
for the Democratic National Convention. There's nothing there. This
week there's an even bigger nothing there.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Los Angeles sprawls around downtown like vibrant
little nations of every conceivable ethnic group, and do they care
about Al Gore, politics and the convention?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said businessman Max Chung, standing outside the
HK Market in the San Gabriel Valley suburb of Rowland Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a little of Bush's speech a couple of weeks ago,'' said
software engineer Kumar Kobi at the nearby China Muslim Restaurant.
``Now where did he give that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that kind of thing,'' said Norma Marin at
her family's restaurant, Maria's Corner, in East L.A. ``I care
about work, family and my life. I don't get into politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, from my point of view, the convention might as well be
happening on the surface of the moon,'' said Arnold Herr, owner of
a bookstore on Fairfax Avenue. ``I'm here seven days a week. It's
hard for me to get excited. Who gives a Fig Newton?''
</P>
<P>
   I drove for hours around Los Angeles to find out three things I
already knew.
</P>
<P>
   One: Nobody cares about the Democratic National Convention, even
though the nothingness of it dominates the news.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Nobody cares about politics, George W. Bush or Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Three: L.A. is very, very big.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. also has to be the most American place there is, despite
all the bad things people say about it.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman who works in a clothing store along Pacific
Boulevard in Highland Park told me, ``I don't care about politics.
I'm too busy partying.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked her where to find the best partying, and she waved her
arm toward the steaming sidewalks teeming with people, and she
said, ``Everywhere. Wait till later. Things will really get
hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that the folks in Highland Park drink Corona and
Negra Modelo while the folks at the Skybar of the ultrahip Sunset
Strip Mondrian Hotel drink $1O pina coladas?
</P>
<P>
   No, they're all partying, and doing a better job of it than the
delegates at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all the delegates. As I drove through West Hollywood,
I saw a party down an alley and crashed it.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a party at the gay community center for the
more than 200 gay and lesbian delegates. They care about politics
and they know how to party.
</P>
<P>
   While the crowd ate amazing food catered by the highly rated
Border Grill, a band played so loudly people had to back into the
art gallery to continue schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its reputation for partying and smooth surfaces, L.A. is
famous for violence and riots. But as I cruised by the Staples
Center, all I saw was a sort of a movie set for a riot. You see all
kinds of commercials and shows being filmed around L.A., but those
seem real, unlike the demonstration I saw. Not to mention the whole
convention.
</P>
<P>
   There were more cops and police cars than in all the movies and
TV shows ever filmed. While police helicopters provided an ominous
reverberating soundtrack, hundreds of protesters against the death
penalty and police brutality drifted by at the end of their
free-Mumia march.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100-degree heat, they looked like they would have been
glad to have the fire hoses turned on them. They at least needed a
good party, with lots of cold ginseng soda.
</P>
<P>
   The real protest against the political system and politicians is
the cold shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all the same,'' said Whitney Day, standing outside the
Traveller's Rest Baptist Church in the Florence neighborhood.
``They just want to get in office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so many people are distrustful of government today,''
said Jessie Payo, a student at Burbank High. ``Things have changed.
We're cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my school, we've had all our funding cut for the arts,''
she said. ``Still, we have the best bands in the state. That's
because we care about music.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Los Angeles and American dream, and it's hard to see
what politicians and conventions have to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
