<HEADLINE>
PETTIJOHN DIDN'T HAVE A FIGHTING CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ It is amazing what you stand to lose when
someone decides to end an argument with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard ``Duke'' Pettijohn, 23, has a degree in child and family
studies from Syracuse and wants to be a mentor someday. The
Mattapan, Mass., resident also has worked for theater groups and
performed at the local civic center, and sees acting in his future
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn was the 1995 Boston Globe Defensive Player of the Year
as a linebacker for West Roxbury High and All-Big East as a junior
defensive end last year at Syracuse. It's difficult for him to keep
visions of the NFL at bay as he approaches his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine having all that going for you as you run down dark
streets, fleeing a knife-brandishing attacker _ the fallout from a
heated discussion, then a brief skirmish, between groups at a
tavern moments earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine noticing _ while running _ that your neck feels warm.
You place your hand over the spot and your palm becomes covered
with blood. It is then you realize that one of the guys got to you
with his knife, slashing you behind the left ear and stabbing you
in the shoulder blade.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine losing your would-be assailant in the chase, being
picked up and placed in a truck by a woman driving by, then, while
going past the scene of the altercation seeing your teammates and
friends still being attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get out to help, actually, and she locked the doors
and took off and drove around,'' said Pettijohn of the incident
that occurred near campus last Oct. 31, hours after Syracuse's
24-23 loss to Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   The fight erupted outside Sadie's Place, a bar Syracuse
officials had warned students about. Pettijohn and his teammates
and friends had stopped by to pick up another teammate before
heading off for an early-morning snack.
</P>
<P>
   The club was emptying out, and while patrons were milling
around, words were exchanged between the Syracuse contingent and
local residents reportedly involved in a street gang. Things
quickly became heated, then turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn was chased for about 40 yards before being picked up,
and the woman drove around a corner near the site of the melee just
as police and ambulances arived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got out,'' said Pettijohn, ``and (teammate David Byrd)
was sitting on the curb. I thought he was all right, just tired or
something. But he was, like, delirious, because his ear was almost
cut off. He was stabbed in the back. My friend Myles (Thomas) was
in the street and he got the worst of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I went to him and tried to comfort him, and I also tried to
calm my friend Danny (Moore) down, because he had a third-grade
concussion. He was out of it. I had to be calm, because I wasn't
even thinking about the fact that I'm bleeding, trying to stop him
bleeding. So (paramedics) told me to stop and took me in one
ambulance and him in another ambulance.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a senior cornerback, suffered severe neck and shoulder
wounds, reportedly losing nearly 60 percent of his blood. Offensive
tackle Giovanni DeLoatch suffered cuts to his back, right arm, and
right ear.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Pettijohn's friends, who had come from Boston for the
game, were wounded. Moore was hospitalized briefly with a stab
wound to the back, but Thomas, a teammate of Pettijohn's at West
Roxbury High and a 1996 Globe All-Scholastic, was hurt badly. His
liver reportedly was lacerated and bled into the sac surrounding
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   En route to the hospital, said Pettijohn, ``He went into cardiac
arrest three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn was fortunate that all he lost that night was a desire
to frequent such night spots. His desire and ability to play the
game he loved remained intact. He missed the game against Temple
the following week but came back and played strongly in the final
three.
</P>
<P>
   His friends pulled through, too, though he said Thomas must have
additional surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is doing outstanding,'' said Pettijohn. ``We just went away
and he was back to his old self again, bugging out and having fun.
That motivates me and that makes me focus and work hard this summer
just seeing how close he was to dying to where he was now and how
hard he fought. It moves me to work hard and try to better
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn, who is already known for an all-out, aggressive
approach to football, has recommitted himself to a successful
campaign and dedicated the upcoming season to Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sept. 2, when Syracuse opens against Buffalo, Pettijohn
will try to improve on a 1999 season that established him as one of
the top defensive linemen in the game, even though he is small by
standards for the position (6 feet 1 inch, 244 pounds). He led the
team with 10.5 sacks (for losses of 72 yards) and had 45 tackles
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing with Duke is the intensity level he
brings,'' said Syracuse defensive ends coach Jerry Azzinaro,
formerly of the University of Massachusetts and BC. ``He brings the
same level on every snap, for four quarters, for 12 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Azzinaro said Pettijohn also is excellent in pass coverage, and
his ability to both rush the quarterback and defend receivers was
key in the Orangemen's 20-17 Music City Bowl victory over Kentucky
last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my size, I start off at a disadvantage going against big
offensive linemen,'' said Pettijohn, who had 10 tackles in the bowl
game. ``I have to play as hard as the person in front of me, if not
harder. I have to play 125 percent throughout the game just to have
some type of advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I like winning. I'm overly competitive. I leave the
bowling alley sweating.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn enters this season with 17 career sacks, tied for
sixth in school history. He tied a school and Big East record with
four sacks against Pittsburgh last season.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who played his first season in college as a
linebacker, was asked move to defensive line because of the team's
lack of depth there, then was relegated to third string _ behind a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was frustrated and nobody would hear me,'' he said. ``Nobody
was telling me what I was doing wrong, and I felt like I was alone.
I figured if I had to go through another year of this, ain't no
need of me being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn considered transferring but changed his mind after a
conversation with his mother, Vera.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just frustrated because he knew what he could do,''
said Vera Pettijohn. ``He talked to the coaches at UConn, but he
stuck it out. It's not like him to quit; he just wanted some
encouragement to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I stuck it out,'' said Pettijohn. ``The freshman went down in
the Rutgers game (third game of the season). I went in and just
played, and the rest is history. I just showed them what I could
do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pettijohn said the incident last October has made him more
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out, but I'm more wary of my surroundings and people
around around me,'' he said. ``I just like stay to the back. I
don't go out as much now. I chill with my girlfriend more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Azzinaro said, ``I think anytime anybody goes through something
like that _ when you're talking about injuries to our football
family as well as injuries to friends _ there's a healing process
that goes on.'' He said the coaches ``left it up to Duke'' to
decide whether he wanted to continue playing.
</P>
<P>
   In his first game back after the incident, Pettijohn was
outstanding in a three-sack effort against Rutgers. But the
incident haunted him for a while, and he had nightmares that would
wake him up in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   At one point while recounting the incident, he paused and said,
``Can we talk about something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Pettijohn wanted her son to seek counseling for the
nightmares, but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple bad dreams,'' he said. ``But it's not a big
deal. I was scared, but it was just dreams and they're not going to
last that long, not as long as everybody's all right. Everybody got
better, and I stopped having them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
