<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATING-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH OIL, GAS PRICES FORECAST FOR WINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHRYN TONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New Englanders can expect to pay as much for heating
oil this winter as they did during last winter's painful price
spike _ about $2 a gallon. What's more, natural gas prices are
forecast to be considerably higher than last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, natural gas bills could be more than 50 percent
higher this winter than last, a US Energy Department forecast says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are projecting that natural gas prices at the wellhead will
increase by about 55 percent this winter . . . compared to last
winter,'' said the report. Those wholesale price increases will
probably be passed on to retail customers, the report added.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: low inventories that cannot meet growing demand.
</P>
<P>
   Last month five Massachusetts gas companies _ Bay State Gas,
Berkshire Gas, Boston Gas, Colonial, and Essex County Gas _
received approval from the Massachusetts Department of
Telecommunications and Energy to raise rates. The increases range
from 30 percent to 51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of Bay State Gas, for example, are already paying 51
percent more, said Rob Wilson, a spokesman for the agency. That
means an average household, using 200 therms a month in winter,
will be paying $44 more a month. (A therm is a unit of volume by
which gas is measured.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many oil consumers have switched to gas heat
or are contemplating doing so, due to last winter's high oil costs.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale natural gas prices in the United States have increased
65 to 75 percent since last year, causing consumer prices to rise,
said Demetri Karousos, associate director at Cambridge Energy
Research Associates.
</P>
<P>
   But natural-gas customers are not the only people affected by
dwindling stock, he said; homeowners who use oil can expect high
prices if inventories don't increase in time and the winter brings
normal cold temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have the same conditions as last winter; the signs
are already there,'' said Kevin Lindemer, senior director at
Cambridge Energy Research Associates. ``Where we are right now,
inventories are low, and it could be a challenge for the industry
to build stocks this winter.''
</P>
<P>
   During last winter's oil price spike, New England consumers were
paying as much as $2 a gallon, and prices could hit the same level
this year, said Bill Veno, director of the oil and environment
group at Cambridge Energy Research.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil prices in New England are significantly higher than
the nationwide average, which is projected to be $1.15 per gallon
by February, according to the Energy Information Administration,
part of the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of inventory has caused so much concern that US Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson met with 300 New England oil dealers late
last month to discuss ways to prevent another price hike.
</P>
<P>
   East Coast oil inventories are 45 percent lower than they were
last year, Richardson said at the meeting, held in Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, industry leaders proposed tax incentives for
distributors who store more oil on site in order to increase
inventories, said Michael Ferrante, president of the Massachusetts
Oil Heat Council, based in Wellesley.
</P>
<P>
   But even with Richardson's support, Congress is unlikely to pass
such tax incentives in time to increase inventories for this
winter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because heating oil production historically kept pace with
demand _ which is no longer the case _ US oil refineries have
focused on churning out gasoline for summer travel, instead of
generating heating oil, Ferrante said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have higher reserves of oil during the summer to
tide us over as we go into the winter,'' Ferrante said.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' cut in
production early last year also contributed to dwindling supplies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil prices for this winter partly depend on whether
Saudi Arabia follows through on its promise to increase crude oil
production to 500,000 barrels a day, Ferrante said.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Saudis break away from the other OPEC countries and
increase production, heating oil prices should decrease because of
increased inventory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies such as Amoco, Exxon, and Shell have cut back on
exploration for both gas and oil because of two globally warm
winters and the aftermath of the Asian financial crisis, said James
Sinclair, director of public affairs at Holyoke-based ISO New
England, which administers the wholesale electricity market in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   But while stockpiles of natural gas have been dwindling, demand
for the fuel has shot up because electricity plants have been using
more gas to generate power, he said. All of the 10 new electric
power plants springing up in New England will be using natural gas
as their primary power supply, Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   Although natural gas reserves have been discovered in Nova
Scotia, they won't push down prices this year, said Tim Evans,
senior energy analyst at IFR Pegasus, a financial publishing
company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated with last winter's oil prices, some consumers
switched to gas heat. Boston Gas has received double the usual
conversion requests since last winter, said Michael Connors, a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   John Krukiel of Rockport took advantage of Boston Gas's offer of
free heating equipment, which did not include $3,000 in labor
costs, to replace his 45-year-old oil furnace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've experienced sharp price increases, like this last
winter,'' said Krukiel, a self-employed carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on last winter's oil price spike, Boston Gas, Essex
Gas, and Colonial Gas are offering free furnaces to homeowners
converting to gas.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates warn that converting to gas will not
bring down energy costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural gas is going to be expensive for at least another
couple of years,'' said Larry Chretien, executive director of the
Boston Oil Consumers Alliance. A nonprofit organization based in
Jamaica Plain, it is not affiliated with either the oil or gas
industry, Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
