<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-MADAM-PRESIDENT0814-C     08-15 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADAM-PRESIDENT0814-COX-1STLED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Fixes lede
 &HT;    Madam President?
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's next, ``Vice President Ken''?
</P>
<P>
   The joking perhaps was inevitable when the nonprofit group the
White House Project teamed up recently with Mattel and Girls' Inc.
to launch a President Barbie doll. With a politically correct
helmet of hair seemingly able to withstand nuclear war and an
unintentionally funny advisory on the back of her box _ ``Podium
not included. Doll cannot stand alone'' _ this Leader of the Free
(Doll) World could be viewed in a humorous light.
</P>
<P>
   But only if that's what you're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew you have to start with what exists,'' explained Marie
Wilson, president of The White House Project, which aims to
``change the political climate'' so women can mount successful
campaigns for U.S. president and other high offices. ``What exists
is eight Barbies in every little girl's bedroom. She's not a
throwback to them, she's serious.''
</P>
<P>
   So are a lot of people these days when the subject turns to a
woman's chance of becoming president. Women were heavily
represented among delegates and speakers at the Republican
convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago, as they will be at the
Democratic gathering beginning Monday in Los Angeles; and both
George W. Bush and Al Gore reportedly included a woman on their
``short list'' of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's been 16 years since Democratic presidential nominee
Walter Mondale made New York Congresswoman Geraldine Ferraro the
first _ and only _ female candidate for vice president. Since then,
the only woman to contend for the top spot on either major party's
ticket, former Republican Cabinet member Elizabeth Dole, couldn't
muster enough money or support to stay in the race through the
first primary.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro is surprised no other woman has joined her in the
history books as a major party's nominee for president or vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would be this long,'' Ferraro said last week
from the Virginia offices of her employment consulting firm, where
she was also preparing to be a Fox News commentator on the
Democratic convention. ``I don't find it disheartening. But I do
feel we need more women than we have in the Senate and the
governors' mansions, and that's disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to the idea of Madam President? That's the
question being pondered by political observers everywhere who, like
Ferraro, are somewhat bewildered by the fact that one ultimately
unsuccessful run at No. 2 is all American women have to show in the
year 2000. It's even the focus of a new book _ ``Madam President:
Shattering the Last Glass Ceiling'' _ in which co-authors Eleanor
Clift and Tom Brazaitis come to this conclusion:
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a woman president of the United States. When?
Soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nearly anyone asked predicts a woman president will
happen _ eventually _ but that's pretty much the only point of
agreement among them.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who express cautious optimism _ ``I think a
woman is going to pop up at the right time and be a really viable
candidate,'' said Georgia insurance consumer's advocate Cathey
Steinberg, who represented DeKalb County as a Democrat in the state
Legislature for 14 years and lost a close congressional race to
U.S. Rep. John Linder in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   'GLASS CEILING IS STILL THERE'
</P>
<P>
   Others contain a certain amount of pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone always talks about the glass ceiling,'' said Matt
Towery, the author of ``Powerchicks: How Women Will Dominate
America'' and a former Republican lieutenant governor candidate and
Georgia state representative. ``The glass ceiling is still there.
There just needs to be a bubbling up that will cause it to shatter.
What I didn't realize was how long it was going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are those who sound downright ticked off by the
whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's something very sad about us still having this
deep-seated ambivalence about power in the hands of women,'' said
(presidential historian) Carl Anthony, pointing out that Turkey,
Pakistan, Ireland and other nations where women have far fewer
rights than their American counterparts all have elected female
presidents or prime ministers. ``This is sort of mind-boggling. It
throws all the statistics out the window and puts it on an
emotional and irrational basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since, when it comes to presidential elections these
days, women seem to do everything except actually take the oath of
office. Bush's campaign press secretary and Gore's campaign manager
both are female, and the two men rely heavily on their wives for
everything from making convention speeches (Laura Bush, notably,
told the GOP delegates she hoped there'd be a female president
someday) to helping them pick a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are some who say that the country has squandered
valuable time by focusing more on first ladies instead of potential
female presidents. Yet there's notnge,'' said Anthony. ``That's not
to say that, like, in 24 years we might not have a stay-at-home
presidential spouse. But generally speaking, we will be seeing more
and more women who have had careers in the White House. That could
get us more used to the idea'' of a woman president.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLING COMPETING MYTHS
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, from ``Gender Gap'' voters in 1992 to ``Soccer M
contend with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a myth to say that there are no qualified women,'' said
Stacy Cordery, a Monmouth (Ill.) College associate history
professor who's writing separate biographies of President Theodore
Roosevelt and his daughter, the legendary Washington political and
social figure Alice Roosevelt Longworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women run up against circular logic and competing argumentur
or five, you can finally get to discussing agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   RAISE WOMEN'S POLITICAL PROFILE
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says the solution lies in everything from increasing the
numbers of and awareness culture with images such as Glenn Close as
the highly competent vice president in the film ``Air Force One.''
Or, yes, bombarding little girls' bedrooms with ``President
Barbie,'' available inr, the only credible candidates who emerged
were in governor's offices or Senate seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Dole. She had the background and the guts to get into
the race, Ferraro said. Unfortunately, she also had the Texas
juggernaut to contend with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do think if Elizabeth Dole hadn't run into George W.
Bush's political swallowing of the entire Republican part of the
cs, the more I've become convinced that timing and luck are a lot
of it,'' Steinberg said. ``It will take timing, the right
personality and wanting to do it. And I think when those pieces fit
together, there will be so many women running, we'll wonder why it
was ever a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
