<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCATTER' NEARLY PULLS IT ALL TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it receives scant attention in the United States, there
is a Triple Crown in Canada, too. There are major differences in
the way the Canadian Triple Crown is conducted, as compared to the
US version, but the two had one similarity this year: a son of Mr.
Prospector lost out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter The Gold, like Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus,
is an offspring of the late, great sire, who was an awesome
sprinter. Scatter The Gold may not be anywhere near the same class
as Fusaichi Pegasus, whose stud rights were sold for $70 million,
but the Ontario-bred won two legs of his Triple Crown, losing his
bid in Saturday's Breeders' Stakes. Fusaichi Pegasus won only one
leg, losing the Preakness to Red Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Triple Crown is run over two tracks and two
surfaces. The Queen's Plate at Woodbine is raced first, followed by
the Prince of Wales Stakes at Fort Erie, both on dirt. The third
leg, the $500,000 Breeders' Stakes, returns to Woodbine and is
raced over turf, which provides a stiff test of a horse's
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter The Gold was a maiden, with several near misses, when he
took the Queen's Plate June 25 by better than 4 lengths. He then
captured the Prince of Wales July 23 by a neck, and earned a chance
to become the seventh Canadian Triple Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Scatter The Gold camp was confident going into the finale.
``He gave a pretty good indication in his one start on the turf
(finishing second in a maiden affair) that he likes the grass,''
said trainer Mark Frostadt. ``He got in a lot of trouble and came
with a big run at the end. I think he'll get better hold of the
grass. I'm pretty happy with what our situation is now. I thought
the real test would be the Prince of Wales, and he had a rough trip
and overcame it. I'm more confident coming into this race than I
was the Prince of Wales.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Scatter The Gold, sent off at 3-5, finished third behind
Lodge Hill (7-2, $9 to win) and Master Stuart (who went off at
7-1). Scatter The Gold stalked the early pace from the outside, but
when the real running began, Lodge Hill came flying from sixth
place and drew off to win by 3 lengths in the time of 2:28 4/5.
Master Stuart outfinished the favorite by a neck to gain the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wasn't the same horse I've gotten used to,'' said
Scatter The Gold jockey Todd Kabel. ``He washed out in the post
parade and just didn't give me the turn of foot he usually does
when I ask him to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Lodge Hill, trained by Todd Pletcher, is a more accomplished
turf horse than Scatter The Gold, having previously run five times
over the grass. A son of Cozzene, Lodge Hill had also been a maiden
when he ran sixth in the Queens' Plate. He won a maiden race at 1
1/4 miles at Belmont July 9 impressively enough to make him a
threat in the Breeders' Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great trip,'' said Mike Smith, who rode Lodge Hill.
``He was a little confused early. But once he got among horses on
the backstretch, he jumped right into the bridle and took me
anywhere I wanted. I think it was better for him being on the
inside because he tends to look around. The only anxious part was
when I had to find a place for him to run. Once I did, he exploded.
When he made the lead, he put his ears up, so I stayed busy on him
just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a race we've been pointing for all along,'' said
Pletcher, one of the top trainers in the US. ``The distance and the
turf were what he wanted. We decided to experiment in the Queen's
Plate, and he actually ran a pretty decent race, considering he
broke poorly and spotted the field several legnths. He was closing
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Scatter The Gold is no Fusaichi Pegasus, and Lodge Hill is no
Red Bullet, but they are two nice horses and will be heard from
again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rock washed out
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rain in Salem, N.H., forced the cancellation of
Monday's card at Rockingham Park following the second race. Safety
became a concern as the surface turned sloppy, and the jockeys and
management agreed to call it a day. Live racing is expected to
resume Wednesday . . . The Travers, to be held at Saratoga Aug. 26,
is starting to shape up as a strong race, as both Red Bullet and
Dixie Union, winner of the Haskell at Monmouth Aug. 6, are pointing
toward the $1 million contest. Red Bullet has been idle since
running a disappointing third in the Dwyer at Belmont July 9. After
the race, it was found Red Bullet was suffering from a virus. On
Aug. 10, Red Bullet zipped 5 furlongs in 1:00 4/5 over the Oklahoma
training track at The Spa, pleasing his connections. ``He's almost
over the virus,'' said trainer Joe Orseno. ``He looked super
galloping out. He wasn't blowing at all. Obviously, we were
disappointed we had to skip the Haskell, but I have plenty of time
to get him ready for the Travers.'' Dixie Union will continue to
train at Monmouth. ``It's quiet at Monmouth, and he's doing well
there,'' said trainer Richard Mandella. ``I think he'll recover
better and get a better start on his training there.'' . . .
Fusaichi Pegasus will not race again until the fall, but he did
pass the veterinary examination that will allow the $70 million
stud deal to go through. The agreement calls for him to stand at
Ashford Stud in Versailles, Ky., after he completes his career,
with the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs Nov. 4
scheduled to be his last start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Daily Racing Form and from publicity
departments at various racetracks was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
