<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-15 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE SHOULD BID THIS CATHOLIC GROUP ADIEU 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Al Gore wants to waltz to the music of the
Catholic Church, he might think twice about penciling in the
Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights so high on his dance
card.
</P>
<P>
   Based in New York, the league bills itself as ``the nation's
largest Catholic civil rights organization,'' which may or may not
be true. It certainly is the most hyperbolic and vocal.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, when William A. Donohue took over stewardship of the
Catholic League, it has become increasingly sensitive _ and shrill
_ about any and every possible utterance or event that could be
interpreted as ``anti-Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   One example, from its 1999 annual roundup of victimization, is
an item about former Spice Girl Geri Halliwell in the
``overwhelmingly Catholic nation'' of the Philippines. During her
appearance, Halliwell reportedly advised her audience to use birth
control to help limit population growth. She also made a pitch for
safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic League's conclusion: Halliwell ``offended the
sensibilities of Filipino Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   It is to such sensibilities that Gore has surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The group's remarkably wordy Web site brags that the league was
behind the decision by Gore and the Democratic National Committee
to punish Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., for planning a
fund-raiser at the Playboy mansion in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sanchez knuckled under late last week, Donohue demanded
that the congresswoman ``should be fired by Vice President Al Gore
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Absent Donohue's keen nose for Catholic bashers, one might
wonder why the league believes that ``Catholics have every right to
object'' to a bipartisan fund-raiser for Hispanics at Hugh Hefner's
house.
</P>
<P>
   According to Donohue: ``The Playboy Foundation has written huge
checks to Catholics for a Free Choice, a front-group for
anti-Catholics trying to get the Vatican kicked out of the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Most people think that Catholics for a Free Choice
exists primarily to help keep abortion safe, legal and private.
They think that the group's beef with the Vatican's United Nations
seat is because Rome continually blocks U.N. support for
contraception.
</P>
<P>
   But William A. Donohue and the Catholic League are not most
people. They see unabashed Catholic bashing everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in a Daily Catholic newspaper press release
trumpeting Donohue's selection as one of the top 100 Catholics of
the century, he was described as ``the 52-year-old thorn in the
side of Catholic bashers everywhere, from ABC Network to Disney to
the print media.'' In a three-page biography, posted on the paper's
Web site, Donohue emerges as the John Wayne _ or maybe Charlton
Heston _ of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Before Donohue came along, says the bio, the Catholic League was
run as a ``grass-roots program without ever gaining any real
credibility or clout with the all-powerful media.'' But ``almost
immediately after assuming his new position . . . Donohue went into
action.''
</P>
<P>
   That action was based on Donohue's realization that ``the
Catholic League had to be a greater force to offset today's brand
of anti-Catholicism so prevalent in print and broadcast media, as
well as a powerful voice to convey . . . that Catholics have had
enough and are no longer going to stand for the defamation that has
become more virulent and more pervasive than in any time in
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his many achievements, says the bio, is Donohue's
``attack'' on the short-lived ABC series, ``Nothing Sacred.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Though ABC and Disney won't admit it, it was the pressure of
Donohue's criticism and call for a nationwide boycott that finally
axed the show,'' the bio crows.
</P>
<P>
   When Donohue became director, he ``wanted to take the Catholic
League to the prestigious status enjoyed by such organizations as
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and
the Jewish Anti-Defamation League,'' the bio says.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has he done this, ``he has forged this status without
catering to the political and special interest groups as the NAACP
and ADL and a plethora of other civil rights groups have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the bio further insists of Donohue:
</P>
<P>
   ``Under his leadership, the Catholic League has intensified its
efforts to defend Catholics in all walks of life, in school, in the
workplace and in politics without getting politically involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Gore, take a hard look. The folks at the Catholic League
only lead when they dance. Break out of lock-step with them and
they'll step on your toes. Real hard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
