<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SEND BRISBY ON HIS WAY, SIGN EX-GIANT CALLOWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Gone is Drew Bledsoe's security blanket, Ben
Coates. Gone, too, is deep threat Shawn Jefferson. Gone, now, is
Vincent Brisby, a receiver Bledsoe came into the league with in
1993 and a player he was very familiar with and confident in.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Brisby seemed ready to assert himself as a starter, the
Patriots pulled the rug out from under him. Monday, they released
Brisby and signed receiver Chris Calloway, a 10-year NFL veteran
who had been released by the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots aren't making this easy for Bledsoe. He's had to
get to know his offensive line all over again, he's working in his
fifth offensive system in eight years, and now he'll have to get to
know another new receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was somewhat surprised to learn that Brisby was one of
eight cuts made by the team, including fifth-round pick Dave
Stachelski, a tight end out of Boise State who never got on the
field after various injuries and homesickness made it clear to the
brass that he might not want to play professional football for a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Three other receivers were cut _ Tony Gaiter, Matt Bumgardner,
and Aaron Bailey _ along with defensive backs Cory Gilliard, Rodney
Rideau, and Mike Woods.
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe's play has been a little unsteady in the preseason,
consider that his offensive line has been in shambles, he's had no
tight end to speak of, and the running game, as usual, has been
almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby joins fullback Sam Gash, running back Curtis Martin,
center Dave Wohlabaugh, and receivers Jefferson and Coates as key
offensive personnel who have departed Foxborough in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby, who declined to speak on the record, was beside himself.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Michael George, said, ``It was a shock to Briz. He
thought he'd had a very good camp and preseason, and he was playing
with the first unit. There were no signs that the team was
displeased with him in any way. He was working hard, and it seemed
the Patriots were going to get good production out of him. It's
hard for him because he's been with the team so long.''
</P>
<P>
   George said he was already negotiating with the Colts and Jets
for Brisby, who had survived one renegotiation after another in New
England. He was the insurance in case someone went down, and, as
George said, he was working with the starting unit. But things
seemed to change in Friday's exhibition game against Washington. He
saw some action in the first half but didn't reenter until the
third quarter, when he made a 35-yard reception down the left
sideline in the two-minute offense.
</P>
<P>
   The only hint of dissatisfaction with his receivers given by
coach Bill Belichick was that he said some were running poor
routes. He never specified which ones. But when asked about the
receiver situation after Friday's game, the coach said it was
``Brisby's job to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Brisby was scheduled to earn $1.5 million this season before he
renegotiated to reduce the team's salary cap hit. In the new deal,
he was scheduled to earn $750,000 with incentives that could bring
the salary up to $2.3 million. The Patriots are responsible for his
$750,000 signing bonus, which counts against their cap.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby was told that the Patriots have seen enough of Tony
Simmons to believe he can be a starter along with Terry Glenn, with
Troy Brown staying in his third-receiver role.
</P>
<P>
   There's obviously a role for the 32-year-old Calloway, who got a
one-year deal at the minimum salary of $440,000. He was released by
the Falcons in the offseason after they signed Jefferson. A
fourth-round choice of the Pittsburgh Steelers in 1990 out of
Michigan, Calloway had his best years with the Giants (1992-98) and
is third all-time in receptions for New York. Patriots quarterbacks
coach Dick Rehbein was an assistant with the Giants during
Calloway's time, and he obviously had a big say in bringing
Calloway here.
</P>
<P>
   Last year with Atlanta, Calloway appeared in only 11 games,
making six starts. His play deteriorated when a streak of 120
consecutive games was broken when he was deactivated for a game
against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving the wide receiver purge was Sean Morey, who hasn't
gotten many reps the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Stachelski, from Marysville, Wash., was going some personal
problems in addition to being homesick. He had left the Patriots
during rookie camp and decided to have his surgery on his balky
right knee. He returned to camp and suffered a toe injury. By then,
Harvard's Chris Eitzmann had passed him on the depth chart.
Stachelski allegedly was involved in a one-car accident in
Foxborough after falling asleep at the wheel, but the details were
never confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The eight cuts came nine days before the Patriots have to reduce
their roster to 65.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
