<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLPEN IS THIS TEAM'S SAVING GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be shocked, but the Red Sox have the best bullpen in
baseball. They've found a formula for success and they're sticking
with it, no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the formula came in handy Monday night in a 7-3
victory over Tampa Bay that seemed improbable when ace Pedro
Martinez left the game with stiffness in his shoulder after just
four innings. The combined efforts of Hipolito Pichardo, Rod Beck,
and Derek Lowe kept the Devil Rays off the scoreboard for the next
five innings. That gave the offense time to rally _ with three runs
in the sixth and four more on a dramatic grand slam by Rico Brogna
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It was that simple. Lowe (3-4) got the victory and the Red Sox'
bullpen lowered its collective ERA to 3.71 _ best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those outs were precious outs,'' said manager Jimy
Williams. ``Our pitchers were able to keep the game close.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's departure came at a particularly bad time for the
Sox. Tampa Bay had taken a 3-0 lead in the third inning, and two
members of the bullpen, Rich Garces and Bryce Florie, were
available for only limited duty after a two-week road trip.
</P>
<P>
   But Pichardo held the fort for two innings (two hits, no walks,
three strikeouts), and the Sox tied the game in the sixth. Beck
took over for the seventh and eighth (one hit, one walk, two
strikeouts), getting Tampa Bay to hit into an inning-ending double
play in the eighth. Lowe allowed two hits in the ninth but escaped
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job again today,'' said pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. ``Pichardo came in and did a great job. He settled our
club down after the loss of Pedro. That helped get momentum back on
our side. Beck did an outstanding job as well. You know, these guys
are all gamers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, some fans were clamoring for Lowe to be a starter
and turn over the closer role to somebody else. That might happen
one day, but not as long as the formula still works.
</P>
<P>
   ``A closer is only as good as the guys who pitch in front of
him,'' said Lowe. ``It's a great confidence-builder to know that
you can go to the bullpen at any time. We were able to put up five
zeros and keep the team in the game, and then come up with a
dramatic victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garces had trouble yesterday and Florie the day before. It was
really up to Rheal Cormier or myself. This was a big win. I imagine
that if Cormier was in there, he would have done the same kind of
job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen works as a team,'' said Kerrigan. ``There is a
real good mix here. They kind of take care of each other. You try
to get guys settled into their roles as quickly as possible.
Pichardo is not quite like he was before, but he can still throw
91-94 m.p.h., with movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garces has been at it for three years. Cormier and Florie are
in their second year in a support role. Beck has filled in nicely.
We never said there would be a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Garces, who is 7-0, said, ``It was harder earlier in the season.
The starter might only go 4-5 innings and the bullpen had to take
over the rest. But we keep battling. You never know what is going
to happen. You've got to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've learned how to get ready mentally to play for what
their particular roles were,'' said bullpen coach John Cumberland.
``Anytime you get into postseason, the bullpen is usually the key
to winning or losing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
