<HEADLINE>
AN OBERAMMERGAU PILGRIMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OBERAMMERGAU, Germany _ Mary Magdalene is having a beer. A large
delicious draft Weihenstephaner Weissbiere. She's sitting at the
bar in a jolly restaurant, the Zauberstub'n, chatting with Vladimir
Zerebni, the resident man for all reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir, the nimble, mustachioed owner, tends bar, waits on
table, and has better hands than your usual barmeister. Throughout
the evening he takes time to display his legerdemain by performing
very entertaining interludes of magic. He says he ``worked as a
magician in Las Vegas for 10 years but I wanted to come home and
have my own place.''
</P>
<P>
   I had asked him if there were any prominent biblical figures in
the joint, and he introduced Mary Magdalene, whose lovely chestnut
hair trails well below her shoulders. She wouldn't be weeping and
wailing for doomed Jesus the next morning _ her day off _ so, ``I
like to have a night out. But,'' she says with a smile, ``please
don't take my picture drinking beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. Everybody deserves privacy on a night on the town,
and this is one of them for Mary Magdalene, a local woodcarver
whose straight name is Helga Stuckenberger. A couple of beers, an
evening meal with friends listening to recorded country and western
music. Presently Helga/Mary will return to an emotional, clamorous
Jerusalem, a few blocks down the street. She will be there in an
indelible drama of salvation depicted movingly on the stage of the
Spielhaus (theater).
</P>
<P>
   Oberammergau's Jerusalem has been re-created as the Jerusalem of
Jesus for nearly four centuries. Mary Magdalenes come and go. Helga
gets into her skin and psyche every other day, alternating with
Ursula Burkhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not acting, I'm carving,'' she says. ``In the 1990
play I was Veronica. I guess I'll always want to be in it, whatever
part they give me. Even a bystander in a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Oberammergau, a spotless, charming Bavarian village of 5,300,
mostly farmers and woodcarvers, seems a stage set itself. With
brightly-painted stone houses, the gaudily rococo, domed church of
St. Peter and Paul and a mountainous backdrop, it's a magnet
pulling visitors on a sort of pilgrimage from across the planet.
The religious, the curious, the theatrically-minded pour in to
witness the ``Passion Play'' that runs for just five months (164
performances through Oct. 8), but only every 10 years. This is the
year again, launching, as you may have heard, a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Justly proud of their prized theatrical possession, portraying
the last days of Christ's life on earth, the good burghers throw
themselves into the production as though their own last days
depended on it. Some 2,200 men, women, and children of the village
(only Oberammergauers need apply) are the cast, earnest _
well-coached _ amateurs, from stars to extras. Plus amateur sheep,
goats, horses, chickens, doves, and the Palm Sunday donkey.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a compelling spectacle (with orchestra and chorus)
long before anybody ever heard of Cecil B. DeMille and Hollywood
``spectaculars'' _ 1633, to give you the inaugural date. Then the
townsfolk fearfully prayed that if spared from the bubonic plague
ravaging the land, they would offer this dramatic tribute to God.
</P>
<P>
   Although Oberammergau's isn't the world's only ``Passion Play,''
it has endured the longest (with a few time-outs for such
scene-stealers as a couple of world wars), and had perhaps the best
results. After one incursion, prompting the villagers' vow to take
the stage, the Black Death did stay away. No more plague deaths
were reported in this tranquil valley that is guarded by snowy
ranges and a peak called Kapel, built like Gibraltar. And the show
went on. And on. And on.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everybody beyond the cast has some involvement: ushers,
ticket-takers, stagehands, and cogs in the local economy, keeping
4,200 daily invaders fed and housed. You can't stay for more than a
night. Check into a hotel or bed-and-breakfast, see the play the
following day, and get out of town to make room for the next
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The drive from Munich proceeds across lumpy green hills, meadows
illuminated by wildflowers and pastures munched in by cows. From
the skiing village of Garmisch Partenkirchen, scene of the 1936
Winter Olympics, the last six miles twist through a chocolate and
vanilla landscape: dark peaks decorated by snow.
</P>
<P>
   The B &AMP; B operated by Ursula Heber and Karl Behner is roomy and
immaculate, the breakfast sumptuous. ``You need a good breakfast,''
says Ursula. ``It's a very long day at the playhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But a short walk to get there. A pleasant and amusing stroll
populated by such fairy tale characters as Little Red Riding Hood,
Hansel and Gretel, Puss-in-Boots _ early Disney? _ who peer down
from vivid murals on stone-walled, wooden-balconied homes. Kitsch,
but nicely done. Relax _ the Trapp family never appears.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the play, stretching from 9 a.m. to 6:30 p.m. (with
an ample luncheon intermission), is a marathon sit, it grips you
throughout. It's all in German, but brisk mountain air, flowing
into the barrel-roofed auditorium from the open stage, is a helpful
stimulant. Bring scarf and coat, as well as a libretto.
</P>
<P>
   A chorus of 50 voices robustly sets the scenes. Some of them are
preceded by brief, stunning Old Testament tableaux (called
prefigurations) to allow changes of scenery. In lavish colors, the
actors perfectly still, they seem freeze-frames. Among them: Daniel
surrounded by four lions and protected by an angel; Moses with the
tablets, later at the burning bush; Cain and a flattened Abel; the
suffering Job.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus arrives in Jerusalem on the Palm Sunday donkey, and the
familiar, timeless tale begins to unfold. Throngs of common people
love him. The council of priests, apprehensive that he may cut in
on business, hate him. The occupying Romans are indifferent,
although their boss, Pontius Pilate, accedes to the demands by the
high priests, Annas and Caiaphas, that Jesus has to go _
permanently, on a cross.
</P>
<P>
   Costuming is brilliant. Contributing to a dazzling atmosphere
are the priests in rich robes and lofty, wide-topped tubular
headgear, vain King Herod sporting royal purple, breastplated Roman
soldiers. The Last Supper is eaten, Judas hangs himself starkly,
and finally Annas and Caiaphas have their way.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus is flogged and crowned with thorns. He struggles and falls
beneath the weight of his cross, and is helped by Simon the
Cyrenian on the awful way to Golgotha. The sound of nails being
hammered is chilling. Then the three crosses of Jesus and his
criminal companions in agony are lifted upright by the soldiers.
The condemned three are cleverly, realistically attached to the
timber. Their ache is genuine, however, if not fatal. Hanging there
for more than a half-hour is a tremendous physical strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be in great shape,'' says the other Mary
Magdalene, Ursula Burkhart, whose family is prominent. One of her
brothers, Anton, is Jesus. Another, Stefan, is a Jesus antagonist,
the ranting demagogue Caiaphas.
</P>
<P>
   Anton Burkhart and Martin Norz take turns as Jesus but the
thieves, Stefan Muller and Thomas Steidle, are crucified every day.
Some of the moonlighting thespians in leading parts do get paid.
Jesus tops the payroll. Norz, a laborer, and Burkhart, a forester,
make $21,000 apiece for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are demanding roles,'' says an elder with a fluffy white
beard, Karl Fuhrler. He plays Gamaliel, a priest who defends Jesus.
``They need the rest days. But I work in my woodcarving shop on the
day Karl Hartle is Gamaliel.''
</P>
<P>
   The day that began in the warmth of summer sunlight darkens and
cools as the crosses are raised. A scowling sky unleashes rain.
Appropriate, almost on cue from producer-director Christian Stuckl.
Are these special effects? An Oberammergau theatrical shtick?
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened like that, too, when I was here in 1990,'' says my
friend, Aurelio. ``Maybe every 10 years the late afternoon weather
accommodates mournfully for the crucifixion scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the resurrected Jesus is momentarily back on stage, and
Mary Magdalene will declare, ``I know that my savior lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Believer or not, you are stirred.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $3.5 million to put on the show, and $7 million more
was spent on renovating and enlarging the theater. A profit is
made, plowed back into the production and various civic projects of
the village.
</P>
<P>
   Aurelio, wanting something carved by Mary Magdalene
Stuckenberger, finds a small, handsome lamb at Fuhrler/Gamaliel's
store. ``We're coming back in 2010,'' she says to Fuhrler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they rewrite the plot?'' I ask. She frowns.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrler says, ``Why wait that long? We're here, and it's just as
beautiful the other nine years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-HADDAM-BOS &LR;      08-15 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HADDAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST HADDAM: AMERICA, EARLIER, WITH SONGS IN ITS HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HADDAM, Conn. _ When you cross the old, steel swing bridge
over the Connecticut River, you enter the village of Goodspeed
Landing and another era: the sunny, upbeat and supremely confident
one of turn-of-the-20th-century America.
</P>
<P>
   That was the age (and outlook) of George M. Cohan, the ``Yankee
Doodle Dandy'' showman of old-time Broadway. It was also the heyday
of The Goodspeed Opera House, a white, wooden wedding cake of a
building that has been a riverside landmark here since 1876.
</P>
<P>
   Close to being demolished at one time, the Goodspeed was rescued
and restored in the 1960s and is dedicated to the preservation and
advancement of American musical theater. On the boards now and
through Oct.7 is ``George M,' a revival of the 1968 Broadway
musical about the ebullient Cohan, who composed the show business
anthem ``Give My Regards to Broadway,'' as well as such sentimental
ditties as ``Little Nellie Kelly'' and rousing patriotic songs like
``It's a Grand Old Flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Unabashedly old fashioned even when they were written, Cohan's
songs and sentiments certainly harmonize beautifully with the
Victorian decor of the Goodspeed, a jewel box of a theater, and are
still capable of bringing tears to the eyes of supposedly jaded
21st-century theatergoers. The Goodspeed has superb acoustics and,
as in Cohan's day, no microphones are used _ or needed _ to fill
the theater with music.
</P>
<P>
   The Lower Connecticut River Valley has some of the oldest towns
and villages in the country, most remarkably well-preserved and
redolent of an historic past. One of the sights of East Haddam, and
a patriotic shrine of sorts, is the ``Little Red School House''
where Nathan Hale taught school for a year. Hale was the young Yale
graduate who declared ``I regret that I have but one life to give
for my country'' just before his execution by the British as a spy
during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   The area also has a long theatrical as well as patriotic
tradition and a reputation for being ``Broadway with trees.'' When
the Goodspeed Opera opened, for instance, many of its patrons and
performers arrived from New York City by steamboat, disembarking at
the theater's own landing. Excursion and sightseeing boats, most of
which are designed to resemble 19th-century vessels, still ply the
river. One of the pleasures of attending a performance at the
Goodspeed is mingling with other theatergoers on the opera house
terrace at intermission and watching the river traffic pass by.
</P>
<P>
   The five-story opera house, the tallest building on the banks of
the Connecticut, is one of the sights always pointed out to
sightseeing boat passengers. Another, also a kind of theatrical
landmark, is Gillette Castle.
</P>
<P>
   A fantastical fieldstone building standing on a high bluff
overlooking the river, the castle was built by the actor William
Gillette who made a fortune portraying Sherlock Holmes in a
melodrama that he toured the country with for more than 30 years.
Gillette's 125-acre estate is now a state park. The castle _ which
has hidden passageways, secret rooms, and a replica of Holmes's
cluttered study at 221B Baker St. _ is currently closed for
renovations. But the beautiful grounds of the estate, which has
sweeping views of the river and valley, are open for walking and
picnicking.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger boats no longer operate between Manhattan and East
Haddam, but the Big Apple is only about a two-hour drive away, and
the opera house can draw on the full resources ofthe New York
theatrical community to stage productions of Broadway quality.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the East Haddam theater, there is also a
satellite company in the posh neighboring community of Chester.
While the Opera House specializes in classic musicals, Goodspeed's
Chester venue, the Norma Terris Theatre, showcases new and
experimental productions, some of which go on to larger venues.
(Among the past Goodspeed productions that made the big time are
``Annie'' and ``Man of La Mancha.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now having its world premiere through Sept. 3 at the Norma
Terris is the new musical ``Summer of '42,'' based on the 1971 film
and earlier novel by Herman Raucher. The Goodspeed produces three
musicals a year and is open from April through December.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional summer stock also flourishes in the area. The
Ivoryton Playhouse on Main Street in Ivoryton, a village of the
town of Essex, is said to be the nation's oldest professional,
self-supporting theater.
</P>
<P>
   As the name suggests, Ivoryton used to be in the ivory business:
it manufactured piano keys, letter openers, fans and assorted
bric-a-brac from imported elephant tusks. Built in 1908 as a
community center by the ivory company, the barn-like but endearing
playhouse has helped launch many show business careers. Among them,
that of local resident Katherine Hepburn, whose home is in nearby
Old Saybrook at the mouth of the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   A summer stock theater since 1930, the Ivoryton Playhouse for
the past 14 years has been the home of the River Rep, a repertory
company that presents a mix of comedy, drama, and musicals from
mid-June through Labor Day. Children's Theatre is presented Fridays
at 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing through Aug. 19 is a production of ``The Heiress,''
an acclaimed play based on the Henry James novel of family intrigue
and set in 19th-century New York. River Rep will finish its season
with a contrasting period piece,``The Mystery of Irma Vep'' a comic
Victorian murder mystery that will run Aug. 22 to Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone in patriotic fervor by the Goodspeed Opera
House, the River Rep's production that preceded ``The Heiress'' was
a rollicking, highly professional performance of ``1776,'' a
musical about the signing of the Declaration of Independence. This
is the Lower Connecticut Valley, where yesterday and today
comfortably coexist, and so the show was sponsored by the Griswold
Inn in Essex _ which opened its doors in 1776.
</P>
<P>
   Now as then, the rambling Griswold, known locally as ``the
Griz,'' is the social center of Essex. An an affluent town with
lots of unpretentious charm, Essex routinely makes lists of ideal
places to live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
