<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MINORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJORING IN THE MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a record, and you can look it up: nine New England minor
league baseball parks in eight days, a meandering July journey
covering 1,218 highway miles, assorted rain delays, a gaggle of
fuzzy mascots, and too many hot dogs. You might say I majored in
the minors this summer.
</P>
<P>
   I started in Portland, Maine, (Sea Dogs) and ended a week later
in Pawtucket, R.I., (Red Sox) but the route was decidedly indirect.
It took me to Burlington, Vt., (Expos) and Pittsfield (Mets) before
leading me on a five-stadium Connecticut ramble through Bridgeport
(Bluefish), New Haven (Ravens), Waterbury (Spirit), New Britain
(Rock Cats), and Norwich (Navigators). True, scheduling conflicts
kept me away from Lowell (Spinners) and Nashua, N.H., (Pride) but
the former was the visiting team when I was in Pittsfield and the
latter in Bridgeport. So I figure I scored a perfect 11.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of statistics, I sat through 76 innings, 78 runs, 14
home runs (including one inside-the-park job), and a one-hitter. I
viewed prospects, castoffs, phenoms, has-beens, rookies, and
veterans. I sat in crowds that ranged in size from the 60 or so
souls who watched the independent Spirit on a drizzly Thursday
night to the 9,230 faithful who cheered for the triple-A PawSox on
a muggy Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The journey happened because my wife and teenage son wanted to
go to Hawaii. Hawaii, which I've visited, is a nice enough place,
but it hasn't had a professional baseball team since 1988. The
importance of this fact cannot be explained to someone who isn't a
ball fan. So my family went to Maui and I motored off to see, among
other sights, the last-place team in the northern division of the
Eastern League and the second-place team in the northern division
of the eastern division of the Northern League. You got that?
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just baseball that hooked me. It was minor league
baseball. When you're comparing the minors to the majors you're
talking chummier parks, more convenient and often free parking,
lower ticket prices ($5 to $11 in my case), folksier fans, and
friendlier help. At Portland's 6,860-seat Hadlock Field, where many
of the Sea Dogs' Eastern League games are sold out, I watched an
usher voluntarily fetch a new box of popcorn for a little girl who
had spilled hers during the fervor of a late-inning rally. Quick
now: Could such a thing happen at allegedly Friendly Fenway? Not
likely.
</P>
<P>
   But if the players one encounters on New England's minor league
fields vary widely _ from can't-miss 21-year-old New Britain third
baseman Michael Cuddyer to former National League gold glove winner
and current 36-year-old Bridgeport second baseman Jose Lind _ so
does the ambience.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Burlington:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the experience,'' Bill Barry, a Vermont Expos
follower, said in urging me to eschew the $2 parking near
4,000-seat Centennial Field on the University of Vermont campus and
instead take a shuttle bus from a free lot about a mile away. He
was right. I bumped along local streets with other jabbering fans
before being deposited near Centennial's 78-year-old grandstand.
``Did you know Birdie Tebbetts was born right here in Burlington?''
one rider asked me, referring to the 1940s major league catcher. I
had to allow as how I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   My seat for the New York-Penn League night game was behind home
plate, but I immediately carved out some turf at the Hot Corner Pub
&AMP; Grill, next to the left field foul line. Only a chain link fence
separated me from the conversation of the young players in the
visiting Batavia Muckdogs' pullpen, dialogue that dealt exclusively
with baseball and young women, although not necessarily in that
order. Nearby, a group of locals wouldn't let Muckdogs coach Dan
Roberts, son of Philadelphia Phillies hall of fame pitcher Robin
Roberts, walk past without a howdy-do and a welcome to the Queen
City. Meanwhile, the public address announcer revealed the winner
of the dirtiest-car-in-the-parking-lot contest. The atmosphere was
akin to a community picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider Bridgeport:
</P>
<P>
   The reading material for visitors to the executive offices of
the Bluefish isn't periodicals such as The Sporting News or
Baseball America. Instead, it's Chief Executive and Fast Company.
And why not? The Ballpark at Harbor Yard is as slick as they come
in the minors, a $19 million, 5,300-seat, city-owned edifice with
20 luxury boxes that lease for $25,000 per annum, a spacious
Bluefish Gear Shop, and a private Harbor Club for folks who've
ponied up $1,100 for season tickets. ``The amenities and facilities
are a large part of our success,'' Bluefish assistant general
manager Steven Schoenfeld said, adding that the team is averaging
about 4,200 fans per contest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I arrived in Connecticut, the state was experiencing
monsoon season. So the game I attended at Harbor Yard was a rainy
seven-inning make-up of the previous night's washout. It started at
5 p.m., two hours before the regularly scheduled game, and only a
handful of fans were in the spiffy park. The Bluefish are part of
the three-season-old unaffiliated Atlantic League, which means
their players, unlike most minor leaguers, are not under contract
to major league clubs. They range in age from 23 to 36, from former
prospects who never rose from the minors to onetime major leaguers
taking their last cuts. As they played, they were saluted by toots
from passing Amtrak trains. Meanwhile, Butch Hobson, manager of the
visiting Nashua Pride and onetime skipper of the Boston Red Sox,
did his arm-waving best to persuade the umpires to call off the
game, in no small part because his team was losing badly. He was
unsuccessful. The umpires and the players endured the rain for more
than two hours, as did the rest of us. Final score: 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   It was my longest day. It had begun at 6,200-seat Yale Field in
New Haven with a 90-minute rain delay of an afternoon Eastern
League game between the Ravens and the Reading Phillies. (Park and
Recreation Day! Hundreds upon hundreds of screaming kids!) After
the home side lost, 2-0, I made my way 19 miles southwest to the
game in Bridgeport (Cap Night!) before heading 27 miles north to
Waterbury, where the Spirit were hosting the Catskill Cougars for
two games (Lebanese Night!), one of them another make-up contest
from the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   Except the Lebanese had the good sense to stay out of the rain,
which was falling yet again. ``They called at 2 p.m. and opted for
a rain date,'' lamented Kevin Walsh, the Spirit's business manager,
as he stood in near-empty, 3,000-seat Municipal Stadium, hard by
Steele Brook. Even Sammy Spirit, the team's costumed eagle, had
stayed home. ``I've got three-quarters of an inch of water in the
outfield,'' Walsh fretted. ``This better stop soon, because
tomorrow is Italian-American night, and we're giving away Beanie
Babies, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spirit are another independent team. They operate in the
16-team Northern League, and they suffer small crowds and bad
lighting. But I also learned this in Municipal Stadium as midnight
approached and I sat with about 30 other baseball nuts in a heavy
mist while watching the home team win the nightcap, 4-1: They serve
major league homemade french fries here, the best on the New
England baseball circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, each park I visited had its small and not-so-small
quirks. In Portland, fans attempted to inspire the locals by
stomping their feet on the metal grandstand and thereby creating a
sound akin to rolling thunder. In Pittsfield's funky 4,500-seat
Wahconah Park, the sun set behind the centerfield fence, directly
above the Bettinger Lumber sign, where it has been known to blind
batters, catchers, and umpires to the point that games have been
delayed until it has dropped below the treetops. At remodeled Yale
Field in New Haven, which dates back to 1927, the original
hand-operated scoreboard still graces the original 35-foot-high
green centerfield fence, which is constructed of metal taken from
old battleships.
</P>
<P>
   But there are enduring similarities among minor league
ballparks, too. You are unlikely to attend a game that lacks 1.) a
local amateur singer warbling ``The National Anthem,'' 2.) an
assortment of fan participation contests, especially a sack race
and a dizzy bat race, 3.) Queen's ``We Will Rock You'' played over
the public address system, 4.) an advertisement on the outfield
fence that implores players to ``Hit It Here!'' 5.) a slingshot
T-shirt giveaway, and 6.) a dancing, prancing, high-fiving,
hand-jiving, toe-tapping, hand-clapping mascot.
</P>
<P>
   I found baseball away from the field, too. Winding through
Montpelier, Vt., I made my way to a small but thorough exhibit at
the Vermont Historical Society titled ``Baseball in Vermont: An
Endearing Love of the Game.'' In Brookfield, Conn., I pulled off
the highway to take 40 whacks at the All-Star Indoor Batting Range
and Baseball Academy. And at Mystic Seaport on the Connecticut
coast, in a restored 19th-century print shop, I perused a specialty
of the house: ``The Rules and Regulations of the game of Base Ball
as adopted by the Mystic Oceanics Base Ball Club in the 1860s.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it went. As I headed east, the skies began to brighten.
In sweet little 6,146-seat New Britain Stadium, I saw the Rock Cats
lose to the Altoona Curve, 7-4, and stayed to watch the sky light
up. (Postgame Fireworks Night!) At 6,270-seat Senator Thomas J.
Dodd Memorial Stadium in Norwich, where the Navigators beat the
Reading Phillies, 1-0, in 10 innings _ the Phillies seemed to be
following me _ the first 2,000 kids received free bats (Bat Night!)
and I discovered the perils of being in a place where 2,000 kids
have bats in their hands. And finally, at 10,031-seat McCoy Stadium
in Pawtucket, where folks fished for autographs by dangling
programs and other objects into the dugouts from above, I snoozed
on the grassy berm in left-center field as the PawSox fell to the
Columbus Clippers, 8-6. I was plumb baseballed out.
</P>
<P>
   Total cost of the eight-day trip: $947.75 including tickets,
programs, souvenirs, motels, food, gas, tolls, and parking. I
figure such a bankroll would last about two days on Maui. And you
can look that up, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to New England's 11 minor league baseball teams can, and
often should, be purchased in advance by phone or through the
teams' Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport Bluefish (Independent), 203-345-4800,
www.bridgeportbluefish.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Spinners (Short-season A, Red Sox affiliate),
978-459-1702, www.lowellspinners.com.
</P>
<P>
   Nashua Pride (Independent), 603-883-2255, www.nashuapride.com.
</P>
<P>
   New Britain Rock Cats (Double A, Minnesota Twins affiliate),
860-224-8383, www.rockcats.com.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven Ravens (Double A, Seattle Mariners affiliate),
203-782-1666, www.ravens.com.
</P>
<P>
   Norwich Navigators (Double A, New York Yankees affiliate),
860-887-7962, www.gators.com.
</P>
<P>
   Pawtucket Red Sox (Triple A, Red Sox affiliate), 401-724-7300,
www.pawsox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsfield Mets (Short-season A, New York Mets affiliate),
413-499-6387, www.pittsfieldmets.com. Note: The New York Mets'
affiliation with Pittsfield will end at the conclusion of this
season, and the future of professional baseball in the city is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Portland Sea Dogs (Double A, Florida Marlins affiliate),
207-874-9300, www.portlandseadogs.com.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Expos (Short-season A, Montreal Expos affiliate),
802-655-6611, www.vermontexpos.com.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury Spirit (Independent), 203-419-0393,
www.waterburyspirit.com.
</P>
