<HEADLINE>
IDEAS FOR QUICK, FUN GETAWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Labor Day is on the horizon, vacation season isn't
over. Here are a few ideas for quick getaways:
</P>
<P>
   Vacation close to home. In Boston, the Colonnade Hotel offers
the city's only rooftop pool _ a great place to relax or even dine.
Daily passes are available to those not staying at the hotel just
off Copley Square. Call 617-424-7000.
</P>
<P>
   Head to the suburbs. The Sheraton Braintree offers a quick
``Perfect for Families'' package that includes overnight
accommodations in one of its just renovated rooms, use of the
indoor/outdoor pool, four movie passes to the General Cinema (which
is within walking distance), and an in-room Pizzeria Uno pizza
party. The package is $159 plus taxes. Call 781-848-0600.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Take a sail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vintage schooner Wendameen offers a relaxing overnight sail
out of Rockland, Maine, for $170 a person. Carrying just 14
passengers and four crew, the schooner leaves the shipyard at 1:30
p.m. Once the schooner is underway, guests can join in the hoisting
of the sails or just relax. In the evening there's dinner on deck,
then conversation while anchored in a quiet cove. Captain Neal
Parker serves breakfast before returning by 10 a.m. For
information, call 207-594-1751.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ride a bike &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like joining a bike tour for an up-close and
personal vacation experience. Bike Riders Tours is a small company
with a world of adventures awaiting. The Boston-based firm
(800-473-7040 or www.info(at)bikeriderstours.com) covers New
England, Canada's Atlantic provinces, Italy, France, Spain and
Portugal, and Ireland. The company specializes in small group
sizes, exceptional inns and restaurants, and discovering the little
things on tour like enjoying genuine espresso in Italy or learning
how to crack open a lobster in Maine. The company also has a guest
chefs' series in Europe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Take off
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   El Al is offering two passengers traveling together a good deal
in September. Buy one New York to Israel ticket for $1,090 and get
a companion ticket at a 50 percent discount. For details, call El
Al at 800-223-6700.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Get grossed out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ontario Place in Toronto is offering ``Grossology _ The Impolite
Science of the Human Body,'' and reportedly kids can't get enough
of it. The exhibit explains just how the body creates all that
oozy, mushy, crusty, scaly, and stinky stuff. But hurry: Learning
about all that gross stuff, from burping to barfing, ends Sept. 4. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bermuda getaway &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a new casual, natural Bermuda to discover at Daniel's
Head, the island's newest resort with some 50 freestanding cottages
along _ and over _ the water. TNT Vacations has a three-night
package at $579 including air fare from Boston. For information on
this or other ``out of the blue'' Bermuda offers, call 888-468-6846
or see a travel agent. And if you are heading for the island, check
out the Fifth Annual Bermuda Jazz Festival Sept. 15-16. For details
and packages call 800-BERMUDA. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Olympic tickets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the 2000 Olympics are now available on the Web.
While some popular events are sold out, a good selection of tickets
is still available. Check out www.olympics.com. Hotel rooms in
Sydney are also said to be available; the only catch may be finding
space on an airline. Tickets are also available from Cartan Tours,
the exclusive Olympic ticket agent in the United States. The
California travel agency also sells packages including air, hotels,
and tickets. For information, call 800-818-1998 or visit
www.cartan.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Monument reopens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Monument has reopened after a two-year
restoration project. Entry is controlled through timed-entry
tickets. Free tickets will be distributed at the kiosk on the
monument grounds each morning. Advance tickets are available
through Ticketmaster at 202-432-7328 (service charges apply). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Movie festivals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every city seems to be holding movie festivals these days. Here
are three with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   The second annual B-Movie Film Festival is set for Aug. 26-27 in
Syracuse, N.Y. This celebration of low-budget flicks from around
the world will offer awards to the top films presented by film star
Roxanne Michaels. For information, call Sub Rosa Studios at
315-454-5609 or visit www.b-movie.com/hof/fest.html.
</P>
<P>
   For the world's longest film festival, head to the Fort
Lauderdale Int'l Film Festival Oct. 16-Nov. 12. Screenings are also
in Miami, Hollywood, and Boca Raton, Fla. Festival organizers say
it's an opportunity to see great films that may never reach
theaters or video stores and a chance to meet up-and-coming
filmmakers and celebrities. The film schedule will be announced on
Sept. 1. For the listing, call 954-760-9898 or visit www.fliff.com.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, the second annual Little Italy Open-Air Film
Festival continues through Sept. 29. Feature-length Italian-themed
films will be shown every Friday at 9 p.m. The films are projected
out of Little Italy resident John Pente's third-floor bedroom
window onto a blank billboard ``screen'' across the block. The
screenings are at the intersection of High and Stiles streets in
the heart of Baltimore's Little Italy (more than 20 Italian
restaurants are in the area) in an open-amphitheater style. Folding
chairs are provided. For Baltimore information, call 888-BALTIMORE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
