<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS &LR;      08-15 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STROLLING IN BOSTON WITH A RED HOT MAMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was big in voice, big in size, and big in heart. And when
she belted out her signature song, ``Some of These Days,'' the
audience would cheer and clap, and that applause was like food to
her.
</P>
<P>
   She was Sophie Tucker, known as the Last of the Red Hot Mamas.
But she wasn't always Sophie Tucker, the wonder woman of vaudeville
and burlesque. She was once little Sonia Kalish Abuza, a
Russian-Jewish immigrant who spent most of the first eight years of
her life in Boston's North End, beginning in 1884.
</P>
<P>
   Sophie, as admirably portrayed by actress-historian Linda Myer,
takes us back to the North End, as one of several stops in a weekly
walking tour conducted by Historical Entertainments. While doing
so, she tells us not only about her career but also about the
city's Jewish immigrant experience, an important and sometimes
overlooked part of the story of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The tour begins at the International Institute of Boston at 1
Milk St., downtown. Sophie _ Myer never steps out of her role, so
we'll call her Sophie _ is wearing a frilly dress, pearls, long
gloves, and a hat festooned with flowers, feathers, and
butterflies. She sets the scene: It is 1928, she's been a
singer-comedian for 20 years, and she's back in Boston to do some
shopping before heading out to Hollywood to break into the
newfangled ``talkies.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sophie and her visitors stroll downtown, she tells how many
of Boston's Jewish immigrants initially became merchants and
tailors, and evidence of that is visible today. She pauses across
from a large department store, started by the sons of a peddler
whose name in the old country was William Katz. But, Sophie tells
us, he wanted to Americanize that name and came up with ``Feline''
because cats (Katz) are felines. The immigration officer, though,
spelled the name ``Filene.'' And that's how one of America's most
famous stores came to bear the name Filene's.
</P>
<P>
   She next stops across from a trio of downtown buildings that are
now dingy and empty but once were dream palaces that, according to
Sophie, represented ``the theater history of Boston in a
nutshell.'' One was B.F. Keith's Savoy, the first vaudeville
theater in the nation, where immigrants wouldn't need much English
to enjoy the elephant acts, jugglers, dancers, and singers. Next to
that was the Bijou, where Sophie got her start doing four shows a
day _ in blackface. And next to that is a building that symbolizes
what ``completely destroyed the vaudeville scene'': the Paramount
movie house.
</P>
<P>
   It's on to once-wild Scollay Square (now the colorless
Government Center), where because her luggage containing her makeup
arrived late, Sophie stepped onto the stage of the Howard Athenaeum
_ better known as the Old Howard burlesque house _ one night in
1908 with no blackface makeup and sang as herself for the first
time. ``The house went wild,'' she happily reports. (She did get
into trouble with Boston's censors occasionally; some of her lyrics
could be interpreted more than one way.)
</P>
<P>
   The walk, during which Sophie breaks out in song occasionally,
continues into the North End, with its red-brick buildings and
narrow streets. Today, visiting the North End is like stepping into
Italy, but when Sophie lived there, the area was populated
principally by 7,000 Jews, 7,000 Italians, and 6,000 Irish. Sophie
and her family lived on Prince Street, in the area bounded by
Hanover, Endicott, and Flint streets known as the Jewish Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   She offers lots of detail about the old days in the North End
and the immigrant desire to succeed. But before we adjourn to the
historic Union Oyster House for lunch, she walks up Copp's Hill
Terrace and looks out at the sea. ``To think,'' she says, ``I came
over in steerage in my mother's arms. But now I sail first class
and entertain royalty.'' Then she utters a phrase that has been
said by many people about many things:
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sophie Tucker walk, the first of four planned Immigrant
Trail walks, takes places Thursdays from 9:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.
through Sept. 1; walks will then resume in mid-September through
foliage season. Tickets are $39, including the walk, the ample
lunch, taxes, and tips. For more information about this and walks
with Benjamin Franklin, Abigail Adams _ also portrayed by Myer _ or
Calvin Coolidge, call 781-648-0628.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is the largest American island on the East
Coast? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Denver's lower downtown section is nicknamed LoDo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``The greatest practice for a traveler is to meditate on
nature'' _ Yogi Bhajan. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: All fire hydrants in Danville, Pa., must be
checked one hour before all fires. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The name's the same, but . . .: Why is it that the French seaport
Calais is pronounced Cal-AY but the Maine city with the same name
is pronounced CAL-is? &QL; 
 &QL; 
What does it all mean? Originally, London's Millennium Dome had
projected an attendance of 12 million this year. That figure has
been revised downward to 7 million. Now comes word that if
attendance at Expo 2000 in Hannover, Germany, continues at its
present rate, the year's attendance will be 12.5 million, compared
with an initial projection of 40 million. Do these figures sound
the death knell for such fairs of the future? Is the gee-whiz
element gone in this age of computers? It's a possibility. &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's contest time: Got a wacko idea for a trip anywhere in the
world? Something like visiting every Elvis memorial, for instance.
Your outrageous fantasy could win you up to a million flier miles
with a travel rewards program called WebMiles. The deadline is Aug.
31, and the judge will be David Phillips, known as the Pudding Guy
because he earned a million miles by buying 12,000 cups of pudding
in a different promotion. For contest details, visit
</P>
<P>
   www.webmiles.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? New York's Long Island, at 1,732 square miles. &QL; 
