<HEADLINE>
WHEN CULTURES CROSS BEHIND THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Mann, who is white, will direct the much-anticipated
film biography of boxing legend Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee, who is black, has a major problem with this.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-pugnacious filmmaker has long-believed the telling of
black stories is best left to black people. Said an unnamed source
quoted in the (N.Y.) Daily News, ``Spike felt that only a black man
could do justice to the story of (Ali).''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Lee has expressed this particular
viewpoint. A few years before he got the nod to direct his 1992
epic, ``Malcolm X,'' he told the New York Times that he had ``a big
problem'' when it was announced that Norman Jewison would direct a
film aboutthe slain civil rights leader. Never mind that Jewison
had on his resume two stellar films dealing with race relations and
starring African-Americans _ 1967's ``In the Heat of the Night''
and ``A Soldier's Story'' in 1984. With regard to the Malcolm X
story, Lee still maintained ``blacks have to control these films.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's comments again raised the prickly question of who ``owns''
certain stories. Can a white filmmaker properly portray the lives
of African-Americans? Should a black filmmaker be allowed to tell
the story of a Puerto Rican family, or a tale set in an Asian
community?
</P>
<P>
   Though Lee won't be there, several filmmakers will gather to
discuss so-called cross-cultural filmmaking at the second annual
Roxbury Film Festival, which kicks off Thursday at Northeastern
University in Boston. The three-day event will feature screenings
of more than a dozen full-length films, documentaries, shorts, and
animated films, as well as a panel discussion on cross-cultural
filmmaking Saturday in NU's Raytheon Amphitheater in Egan Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Rumblings about cross-cultural filmmaking come at an intriguing
time in the movie business. This summer has been an especially
successful time for African-American filmmakers and actors with
three films _ ``Scary Movie,'' directed by Keenan Ivory Wayans, and
starring his brothers Shawn and Marlon, who also wrote the film;
Martin Lawrence's ``Big Momma's House,'' and ``The Nutty Professor
II'' starring Eddie Murphy _ all topping the magic $100 million
mark.
</P>
<P>
   But some worry that recent successes can overshadow the daunting
issues still facing filmmakers of color. Blacks, for instance, are
still more likely to curry widespread favor in comedic, not
dramatic, roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same stereotypes being born over and over again.
Martin Lawrence is doing the same laughing and dancing character,
and unfortunately, that's the perception (mainstream audiences)
have of us that sells,'' said Andrew Millington of Jamaica Plain,
whose film, ``Guttaperc,'' will be shown at the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not down on them because they have to work, but as a
community we have to think seriously about how we will marshal our
forces to present different perception of who we are,'' Millington
said. ``And it's something which has to come from the community. We
understand best how to present ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Millington, who was born in Barbados, finds suspect films about
African-American lives and history directed by white filmmakers.
Having worked with Ethiopian-born Haile Gerima on his 1996 slavery
film, ``Sankofa,'' Millington believes such films as Steven
Spielberg's ``Amistad'' and Jonathan Demme's adaptation of Toni
Morrison's ``Beloved'' missed the mark. (Both films faltered at the
box office, though it likely had more to do with the public's
aversion to films dealing with slavery than the skin color of the
filmmakers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They both had the perspective of white directors,'' he said.
``And I'm not sure they could come to grips with the traumas the
(African-American) culture has endured, and has emerged from.''
Although films like ``Amistad'' and ``Beloved'' may never have been
made without Spielberg and Demme, Millington said, ``Sometimes I'd
rather they not touch it. We have to consider whether or not we are
better served by these films.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, filmmaker Natatcha Estebanez contends a culturally
collaborative process can yield rich, provocative films. Her film,
``Blue Diner,'' tells the story of a Puerto Rican woman who
mysteriously loses her ability to speak her native language.
Estebanez, who is Puerto Rican, coproduced and cowrote the film,
with director Jan Egleson, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can Caucasians tell the story of a Puerto Rican family? Well,
no. But we collaboratively can do that, and that's the only way in
which that can be done,'' Estebanez said. ``I, as a Puerto Rican
woman, feel 100 percent confident of the authenticity of the
language and the story line of our film. This is a perfect example
of how two people from different cultures can build on each other's
strengths in telling a powerful, dramatic story while keeping a
very authentic voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are always exceptions such as Wim Wenders's
enchanting documentary, ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' which
highlighted some of Cuba's great musicians in their homeland. At
first, Estebanez wasn't sure if she should like the film because
Wenders is German, but ultimately, she told herself, ``This is a
beautiful, honest piece'' regardless of who directed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt that Spike is right in many ways in saying there
has to be a place for us folks to tell our own stories. I feel very
empowered that I've told my own story,'' Estebanez said. ``But I
think we're in transition. I think the arts have to reflect how our
culture is opening to collaboration. I say if you bring people
together from different cultures with different strengths, and you
can combine them and enhance the story.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
