<SLUG> BC-KILLER-LAWYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT RULES EX-CONVICT UNFIT TO PRACTICE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California Supreme Court says a San
Francisco man who bludgeoned his sister to death in 1975, and
served prison time for manslaughter, is morally unfit to practice
law in California despite numerous testimonials of his
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Since kicking a drug habit in the early 1980s, Eben Gossage has
graduated from Sonoma State and Golden Gate University Law School,
done volunteer work for an environmental law foundation, a
battered-women clinic and a project for young addicts, started a
successful real estate business, and lined up character references
from such notables as District Attorney Terence Hallinan, San
Francisco Supervisor Sue Bierman and state Senate leader John
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   But in a unanimous ruling Monday, the court said a series of
run-ins with the Department of Motor Vehicles in the late 1980s and
early 1990s for offenses such as driving without a valid license or
proof of insurance, and failure to pay the fines promptly or appear
in court, showed Gossage's rehabilitation was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pattern of misconduct suggests a conscious and habitual
lack of respect for the judicial process,'' the justices said in an
unsigned ruling. ``The fact that Gossage has so recently disobeyed
court orders, and has sustained several new convictions for such
conduct, indicates that meaningful rehabilitation has not yet
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also said Gossage failed to list the vehicle offenses,
or three of his four forgery convictions from the early 1970s, on
his 1994 application for State Bar membership, which specified that
all crimes had to be listed. Gossage said he had forgotten about
the forgery cases and hadn't realized the vehicle crimes were
misdemeanors that had to be reported.
</P>
<P>
   Gossage passed the bar exam on his first try in 1993, but the
Committee of Bar Examiners found that he lacked the moral character
to practice law, a profession that now has nearly 170,000 members
in the state. The bar's disciplinary court ruled in Gossage's
favor, over the dissent of one judge. Monday's ruling endorsed the
dissenter's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``They missed an opportunity to send an important message, that
in our system we appreciate it when people come back,'' said
Gossage's lawyer, Ephraim Margolin. He said Gossage wasn't
available to discuss the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   However, a legal ethics expert, Jerome Fishkin, said a would-be
lawyer's failure to disclose past crimes is a common reason for
rejection. ``Ultimately the system will fall apart if judges can't
rely on the basic honesty of lawyers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
