<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEE SEASON' SPELLS AGONY FOR AN UNHAPPY FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AMY GRAVES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BEE SEASON 
By Myla Goldberg 
Doubleday, 304 pp., $22.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eliza is 9 years old. She's not crazy about the fourth grade,
and when she comes home, she watches a lot of after-school specials
(it's the 1980s, so that's all there is on TV). There's nothing
remarkable about Eliza. At school she is neither picked on, like
her older brother, nor picked out for achievement as a ``talented
and gifted'' student, in the parlance of that era.
</P>
<P>
   One day she finds her metier: She can spell better than anyone
in her class _ anyone in her school, in fact. After winning all of
her school's spelling bees, she moves on to the district-wide bee,
and wins that one too. She advances to the New Jersey statewide
competition.
</P>
<P>
   With each successive step she grows more consumed by her
newfound talent. Soon she's looking at word lists in class, at
recess, and (more important) at home. There her father, a cantor
and a student of Jewish mysticism, welcomes her into the sanctum of
his study, where they ponder words and quiz each other spelling-bee
style.
</P>
<P>
   This is the outline of Myla Goldberg's ``Bee Season,'' her first
novel. But what starts as a story about the uneasy world of
spelling competitions becomes a riveting family drama in which
almost everyone _ mom, dad, brother, and sister _ ends up feeling
alienated and betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Here the nuclear family is given a twist: It's mom who's absent
and erratic, dad who's frantically trying to keep home and family
together. Mom in this case is Miriam, an estate lawyer who's in
charge of making money while Saul stays at home to cook and manage
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam is not a typical mother. An eccentric woman with
rudimentary social skills, she devotes her free time to reading,
writing letters to the editors of obscure publications, and
deep-cleaning the kitchen. She rarely sleeps. Glimpses into her
past reveal the death of both parents during her college years and
a lifelong fascination with perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Her few awkward attemps to relate to Eliza include the gift of a
kaleidoscope she'd saved from her own childhood. Hoping to share
with her daughter her fascination with how the colors and shapes
change with each turn of the toy, she withdraws as if stung when
Eliza's response doesn't match her own. Miriam copes with the
disconnection in her life by shoplifting, which, although it takes
a dangerous turn, attracts scant attention from her family _ until
she gets arrested.
</P>
<P>
   All the family members are caught up in their own problems, at
the center of which is the competition between Eliza and her
brother, Aaron, for Saul's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron had been his father's star pupil. His belief that he's
special, destined for a life connected to his family's synagogue,
is threatened by the reality that beyond this world, he's
overmatched. His lowly status among schoolmates, overly cautious
driving, and shame about his changing body mark him as not merely a
teenager but someone for whom growing up is a form of torture.
</P>
<P>
   His breaking point comes when Saul's focus shifts to Eliza, to
the exclusion of the guitar lessons that once served as his bridge
to his father. Questioning his father's love leads Aaron to
questions of religious faith. A chance meeting with a stranger in a
park leads him to Hare Krishna, which he practices with all the
passion and energy he can't otherwise channel. This he manages to
conceal from the family until he decides to leave home.
</P>
<P>
   Saul is not the family savior, though that's the role this
character casts for himself. His single-minded devotion, first to
Aaron and then to Eliza, comes from a typical parental ambition to
see his children excel where he failed. After trying to change
Aaron's mind about giving up Judaism, Saul reaches his breaking
point in an argument with his son over Miriam's arrest. Aaron
refuses to believe the real reason for her absence from the family;
Saul's rebuke gets personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not true? God, Aaron, if you want proof, just look at
yourself. Like mother like son. For the past few weeks you've been
going around in an orange robe telling me about the heavenly
planets and rebirth and sniffing the hand you use for your prayer
beads like it had been touching a woman. . . . When I was your age,
I had friends. Real friends, not religious freaks who only saw me
as one more body to sell flowers in an airport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bee Season'' offers glimpses into the worlds of mysticism,
Jewish and otherwise, and paints a very convincing portrait of
mental illness. But its real power lies in its ability to convey
the story of a family on the point of collapse. There are sweet
moments, especially in the closeness between Aaron and Eliza. As
brother and sister confide worries about their parents, Eliza calls
up a memory that fixes Aaron's place in her world. And as Goldberg
spins this kaleidoscopic story until the pieces fall satisfyingly
into place, it becomes a lot less relevant whether Eliza wins the
spelling bee than whether her family stays intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
