<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGING IN PAST GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good thing boxing has a grand past.
</P>
<P>
   The present is just too cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Even usually bland blow-by-blow announcers are expressing
unbridled opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case Saturday night, when John Ruiz hung tough
against Evander Holyfield but lost a controversial unanimous
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime announcer Steve Albert called it ``highway robbery.''
Albert's colleague, Bobby Czyz, was equally disenchanted; the
former light heavyweight champion had Ruiz winning five of the
first six rounds and 9 of 12 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime gave viewers a chance to score each round via an
Internet poll, and they too had Ruiz winning, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's not the first time boxing announcers have gone
haywire. Howard Cosell was at his best when denouncing the
barbarity of the sport. More recently, HBO's Jim Lampley has been
openly disdainful. After Lennox Lewis and Holyfield fought to a
controversial draw on March 13, 1999, Lampley said, ``Boxing's
cesspool has opened up once again to emit an unconscionable odor.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though boxing hasn't had glory days. HBO, in fact,
airs a documentary Thursday at 10 p.m. on what many believe to be
one of the greatest fights of all time: the first bout between Joe
Frazier and Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier beat Ali fair and square in that one. There was no
controversy, no cries of ``I was robbed'' by Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali and Frazier stood for much more than prizefighters,'' said
Ross Greenburg, HBO Sports senior vice president and executive
producer. ``This fight, five years in the making, clearly
positioned Ali as the symbol of the civil rights struggle and
anti-Vietnam movement, while Frazier was unfairly viewed as the
symbol of the pro-war, conservative segment of American society.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier didn't see it that way; he wanted only to knock out Ali.
His son, Marvis Frazier, told HBO about his father praying before
the fight: ``I said, `What did you pray?' He said, `I asked the
Lord, Lord help me to kill this man because he's not righteous.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong documentary also details how Frazier lent Ali money
and Ali repaid him by calling Frazier an Uncle Tom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really, I believe, hurt my dad, he gave his
heart and soul to help a brother and then that brother comes back
like a knife and cuts him,'' said Marvis Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Joe Frazier admits that he has said some cruel
things about Ali's present battle with Parkinson's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swallowed a lot of razor blades, and sometimes they cut
inside, you know?'' Frazier told HBO. ``I would live rambunctious
and would say some of the things I shouldn't say . . . I want to
throw the towel in. I am willing to say . . . to all the fans, all
his family, if I have done anything wrong to him, `Hey, man,
forgive me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No Tiger pause
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Golf Channel took some heat for airing taped coverage of
Tiger Woods instead of live coverage of the Buick Open's first
round last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cable station had three hours dedicated to tournament
coverage, 4-7 p.m., and spokesman Dan Higgins said the goal was to
have a mixture of highlights from the morning and live coverage of
the afternoon. What actually aired was about two hours of Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little too much,'' Higgins said. ``We wanted more
balanced coverage. But we went a little too far on Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's weekend coverage of the Buick Open had decidedly
un-Tigerlike numbers. Saturday's coverage earned a 2.2 rating and 7
share, while Sunday's earned a 4.3 rating and 11 share.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has the PGA Championship this weekend, and rest assured
Tiger will be the focus. CBS Sports president Sean McManus has said
in the past that he privately roots for Tiger because of the
phenomenal ratings he generates.
</P>
<P>
   CBS's coverage airs Saturday and Sunday from 1:30 p.m. to 6:30
p.m., with early-round highlight shows on Thursday and Friday
nights after ``Late Show with David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Numbers game
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC women's basketball commentator Ann Meyers came down hard on
the Houston Comets' Cynthia Cooper for taunting the crowd during a
playoff game at Sacramento Saturday. ``She's knocking down some big
shots and playing some good defense,'' Meyers said. ``The one thing
I don't appreciate is taunting the opponent, taunting the crowd. I
think you lose a lot of respectability as a player when you do
that, and she's got one of the best games around in this league.
But to be embarrassing your opponent like that . . . I've never
appreciated that in a player. You know what happens. It comes back
to haunt you.'' . . . ESPN's ``2-Minute Drill'' game show, with
host Kenny Mayne, debuts Sept. 11 and continues every Monday, with
a Thursday edition added beginning Oct. 12. The championship airs
on Christmas Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
