<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     08-15 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT COULD BE SEASON'S BEST NIGHT _ OR WORST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thick fog enveloped gloomy old Fenway and the Citgo
sign served as a lighthouse while the SS Jimy Williams threatened
to sink into the Mystic River.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox trailed the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 3-0. Pedro Martinez
left after four innings with stiffness in his pitching shoulder.
The Yankees were winning in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Could it get any worse? Just when the staggering Sox finally
make it home _ miraculously afloat in the American League East and
the wild-card hunt _ Pedro gets hurt and the Sox fall behind the
bottom-feeding Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Then the skies cleared and the world was righted as New England
homeboy Rico Brogna came up in the bottom of the ninth and hit a
walk-off grand slam to propel the Sox to a 7-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Rico's ``welcome home'' shot will help heal Pedro.
The Sox simply can't afford to lose their ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it feels tomorrow,'' Pedro said through Sox
spokesman Kevin Shea before departing Fenway. ``I just had a stiff
shoulder. It just didn't feel right. It got to a point where I
didn't want to chance it. It's not worth it, going out there and
getting hurt again and going on the disabled list. Especially
now.''
</P>
<P>
   This team has overcome a lot of adversity. The Sox have proven
they can win with key people on the shelf. They've ignored the
clubhouse turnstile (Lou Merloni Monday became the 48th teammate),
exiles of respected veterans, the suspensions of Pedro and Carl
Everett, and the rift between the manager and general manager. They
lost John Valentin for the season and never had Bret Saberhagen or
Tom Gordon. They even survived Nomar Garciaparra's stint on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   They've stayed in contention despite a salami-bat offense that
has them next-to-last in runs in the American League. The Red Sox
are stayin' alive even with fewer runs than the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   But they cannot survive a new injury to Pedro. Not now. It would
be too much to ask. Pedro has already done a shift in the penalty
box and spent time on the DL with a strained oblique muscle on his
left side.
</P>
<P>
   This was Pedro's 21st start. He started 29 games in 1999 and 33
in '98, his first season with Boston. The Sox need him every fifth
day from now through October. That's why the Nation held its
collective breath and hoped Jimy &AMP; Co. were just being overly
cautious with The Franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro had no-hit stuff at the start. He struck out the side in
the first and the red guys in center field prepared for a long nite
of K-posting. Did they bring 27 Kards, just in case? Pedro had five
strikeouts after two.
</P>
<P>
   Then came trouble. With two on and one out in the third,
Venezuelan second baseman Miguel Cairo lofted a 325-foot pop fly
into the second panel of the left-field screen. It was not unlike
Bucky Dent's season-killer of 1978. It was Cairo's first home run
in 522 at-bats, going back to July 20, 1999. It was the first
three-run homer allowed by Pedro since Sept. 19, 1998 (Mike
Cameron).
</P>
<P>
   Pedro faced eight batters in the third and gave up a double in
the fourth. That was his last inning. The Sox trailed, 3-0, when he
departed. He threw 63 pitches, 43 for strikes. It was his shortest
starting appearance since July 18, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said he noticed something in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've seen a guy pitch as many games and innings as I've
been privileged to see him, you just know when something's not
right,'' said Kerrigan. ``The ball just wasn't coming out right.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Williams, there was little discussion about the
move to remove.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just came out of the game, that's all,'' said Williams. ``I
went back to the clubhouse to see him after he came out. Now we'll
just wait until tomorrow and see how he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kerrigan, Martinez was examined by team physician
William J. Morgan before leaving the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same problem as in Toronto (June 25),'' said
Martinez. ``I didn't want to pitch with it like I did before. But I
feel a lot better now and, hopefully, it's just from the jet lag
and I'll feel better tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an occupational hazard,'' said Kerrigan. ``When you
consider the travel and where we've been and the conditions he had
to pitch in tonight. Let's see how it is tomorrow. Hopefully, it's
just a one-day thing. He was fine yesterday and he was fine in
between starts.''
</P>
<P>
   We won't know for a while, that's for sure. There's no sense in
the Sox announcing what they plan to do, and we'll probably go into
the weekend still uncertain of Pedro's status. Kerrigan said it's
quite possible that Martinez would take his regular turn Saturday
against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   So for now it goes down as the best night of the year. And as
long as Pedro Martinez is OK, it could go down as the season
highlight. But if Pedro doesn't recover immediately from the
shoulder stiffness that took him out of the pulsating victory, it
becomes the worst night of the year. Plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at dshaughnessy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
