<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2221 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AIR-WOES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-AR     08-15 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-WOES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 HERNDON, Va.: ... Controllers Association.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of the nation's commercial airline traffic is concentrated
east of the Mississippi, and the FAA and the airlines have
identified seven choke points in a triangle from Boston to Chicago
to Charlotte, N.C. Officials hope to have procedures in place later
this year to deal with some of the choke points. Other strategies
will take longer to implement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these choke points are caused simply by the increased
air traffic. As a result, at airports such as Chicago's O'Hare,
planes are forced to wait until an opening in an air corridor is
available.
</P>
<P>
   When there are ground holds for congestion, or because of bad
weather, the arrival rate at airports is also reduced. The FAA sets
the reduced number of arrivals in Herndon, and allocates slots to
the airlines based on their share of the schedule. Airlines then
decide which planes will use the slots.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the slots go to general aviation, which includes
business jets. That a plane with three people gets a slot while 250
people on a jumbo jet wait strikes some as inefficient _ and
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, where the FAA would not have to provide
equal access to airports, we would be able to send them someplace
else,'' said the Massport aviation director, Thomas Kinton.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term solution would be to change the way the system works
so planes are no longer guided by older ground-based navigation
aids, but rather by satellites, which would allow pilots to fly
outside air corridors and in most cases take more direct routes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a program by Raytheon Co. of Lexington, Mass. to develop a
highly reliable system to augment the accuracy and reliability of
global position system signals is way behind schedule and over its
original budget.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the project, known as the wide area
augmentation system, was supposed to be available next month. But a
test last December to determine if the system could detect errors
in the signal failed three times. While that is not a problem for a
motorist using the global positional system, for an airplane on
final approach with limited visibility, it could be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear when the wide-area system will be operational,
but FAA officials insist it will anchor the system of the future
and will help alleviate congestion once planes are at cruising
altitude. Yet it will not end delays. It is a big sky, but there
are only so many airports where planes can take off and land,''
said Schwitz of the controllers union. ``Satellite-based navigation
will reduce fuel burn and flight time en route, but it is not going
to help when those planes need to get on the ground. If you have 50
planes trying to land at the same airport at the same time, we'll
still have to line them all up and put them in a holding pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA estimates the nation's 25 busiest airports will handle
63 percent of the 670 million passengers who will fly this year and
experience 86 percent of all delays. Of those airports, 15,
including Boston's Logan International, are considering adding a
runway between now and 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``More pavement helps, but it will not be the silver bullet,''
said Paul Galis, the FAA's deputy associate administrator for
airports. ``Most of the plans are designed to accommodate more
traffic, and in that respect Boston is sort of unique.'' He said
that Boston would increase capacity by only about 5,000 operations
a year, while a new runway in St. Louis is expected to generate
more than 200,000 additional operations.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's schedule, like any aiport's, is built around ideal
operating conditions. And in good weather, the airport can handle
about 120 planes an hour by using three, or even four, runways. But
because planes must land and take off into the wind, when the wind
is from the northwest Logan drops to two, and sometimes just one,
runway.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed runway would be designed for smaller, slower planes
to land in northwest wind conditions, increasing the rate at which
larger, faster planes can land on Logan's existing northwest
runway. ``We have snow, ice, fog, and wind _ and the wind is the
one delay condition that we can do something about,'' said Kinton,
Massport's aviation director.
</P>
<P>
   But community opposition to Logan's proposed runway is strong,
as is oppostion to runway projects nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard choices will have to be made at all levels of government
with communities around the country to ensure that we have the
infrastrcture in place to accommodate anticipated demand,'' Garvey
said recently. Garvey has asked for a study of the Logan runway
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the FAA, NASA, and the Volpe Center in Cambridge,
Mass. are working with Flight Safety Technologies, a company based
in New London, Conn., to increase efficiency by letting planes fly
closer together on final approach.
</P>
<P>
   A major concern on final approaches are so-called wake vortices,
small horizontal wind spirals that extend back from a plane's
wingtips. The larger the plane, the larger the wake vortex, which
are powerful enough to force small planes out of the air. The
system under design would draw on previously classified technology
used to locate submarines to detect when the vortices are present,
and when wind conditions are such that they would dissipate more
quickly. With no vortices present, the separation between planes on
final approach could shrink, allowing a few more aircraft to land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, even if the wake vortex detection system works, it will
improve efficiency only marginally. Increasingly, air
transportation officials say the airlines must take responsibility
for simply placing too many demands on the system.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, congestion in the sky has reached
unprecedented levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some times of the day we have more demand than we can handle,
and the number of hours in the day when that is true is
expanding,'' said Steven Brown, FAA's associate administrator for
air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has started offering lower flying altitudes to avoid
delays. While aircraft may not operate as efficiently at 24,000
feet as they can at 32,000 feet, that program is being used more
frequently, Kies said.
</P>
<P>
   A relatively new phenomenon in aviation is the use of regional
jets, and they are also causing some delay problems. The regional
jets, which are replacing slower and lower-flying turboprops, fly
at the same altitude as bigger jets but at a much slower speed.
``It is like coming up on a tractor on the interstate,'' Schwitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives and passengers, however, love the regional
jets because they have greater range than turboprops and provide
jet service to many new markets.
</P>
<P>
   And executives say it is unfair for the FAA to blame airline
scheduling for delays. ``That is such a red herring,'' said David
Fuscus, spokesman for the Air Transportation Association. ``Every
one of those people knows that if 20 planes are scheduled to depart
at 8 a.m., that is not a wheel's-up time. They can all push back at
8, then taxi out and get in line to take off.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Fuscus said, ``the government has a responsibility
to meet the travel demands of the public _ that is a basic
underpinning of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Garvey, however, insists the airlines must do their share in
helping to solve a problem with no simple answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our great challenge is: Can we keep up with the growth we are
seeing?'' she said in a recent interview. ``Some of the discussion
is focusing only on air traffic control. This is a multifaceted
problem with lots of causes . . . and it has to have a multifaceted
solution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
