<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Sunday was a bad day for the third person, notes John
Carroll, managing editor of WBGH-TV's ``Greater Boston,'' who found
two novel errors in that one day of newspaper reading.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the item in the Boston Herald on Louis Markakis:
``The ex-Big Dig `liaison' apparently loves himself, hates his
former bosses and speaks of himself in the second person.'' The
example? ``Markakis, who in Boggsian fashion often refers to
himself as Lou . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Hello, editors: That is not ``second person.'' Markakis (and
Wade Boggs and Bob Dole) are using third person when they refer to
themselves by name, as if they were other people: He, she, they,
them are third person pronouns. Second person, grammatically
speaking, is you (or thee, thou, youse, or y'all, depending on your
idiolect). True, Jay McInerney managed to write all of ``Bright
Lights, Big City'' in second person _ ``When the acrobat passes the
hat you throw in a buck. You walk west, without any firm
destination in mind'' but it's not easy. Unless you're in front of
a mirror, telling yourself what a jerk you were last night, you
rarely refer to yourself in the second person.
</P>
<P>
   What next? On the same day, The New York Times offered a brief
profile of The Rock, after the pro wrestler's appearance at the
Republican National Convention. Quoth the reporter: ``He speaks of
himself almost entirely in the first person. As in, `The Rock says
. . .' ''
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe second person is a bit obscure, but first person, as
surely almost everyone knows, is I, me, we, and us. The Rock is
using not first person, but third.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary citizens don't need to know these labels to speak
English; when there's a pronoun problem, it's usually whether to
say I or me, her or she, not whether I am he or you are he and you
are me and we are the walrus. But for journalists, there are some
special situations to consider.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the news writer's standard third person, meant to
communicate objectivity and distance, can sound bizarre in a
column, where the author may have to refer to himself: Suddenly the
subject of the piece is speaking to ``a reporter,'' who sounds like
a shady third character on the scene. H.W. Fowler, no advocate of
the new journalism, hoped English would move beyond this
awkwardness: There is ``no sound reason'' for saying the present
writer or your reviewer, he wrote in the second edition of Modern
English Usage. ``Writers are showing a disposition to be bolder . .
. in the use of I and me, and the practice deserves
encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   The first person plural also provokes a certain skittishness in
newsrooms. The editorial we is fine in editorials, which are meant
to represent the collective opinion of the institution _ a sort of
democratized version of the royal we. But some journalists dislike
the ``indefinite we,'' the pronoun that presumes to include the
audience; they fear that pronouncements like ``We're an overweight,
sedentary, TV-addicted nation'' will offend readers who are not
overweight, sedentary, or TV-addicted.
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I think those newspersons underestimate the power of
denial: Even readers who are plump couch potatoes won't necessarily
see themselves in that generalized we. In any case, this usage is
long established, and the experts have never had a problem with it,
as long as the scope of the writer's we is both clear and
defensible. We rest our case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One giant step
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enormity has been one of the bloodiest usage battlegrounds of
the past half-century, and the holdouts are losing. Most people now
use enormity to mean ``immensity,'' despite the insistence of usage
handbooks that it connotes immense wickedness, and not simply
``enormousness.'' Word maven William Safire conceded the battle
nearly 20 years ago, though The New York Times style guide still
insists on the ``monstrous'' meaning.
</P>
<P>
   So does my friend Betsy _ but she says the end must be near now
that Lynne Cheney has joined the revisionists. ``The enormity of
the honor . . . is just sinking in,'' Cheney said, both at the
Republican convention that nominated her husband as the
vice-presidential candidate and in later interviews.
</P>
<P>
   When a conservative supporter of rigorous education _ and one
with a doctorate in literature, at that _ goes around rejoicing at
the ``enormity of the honor,'' it's probably time for the
preservationists to abandon hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Word appears every other week through summer. Jan Freeman's
e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her at The Boston
Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
