<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-DISEASES-JEWS-BOS     08-15 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DISEASES-JEWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWS FEAR STIGMA OF GENETIC STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researcher Ann Pulver thought she was doing American Jews a
favor when she recruited them for a genetic study of schizophrenia
and manic depression. She felt it could give Jews a head start in
knowing their risk for two potentially devastating mental
illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boston and elsewhere, many Jews saw this as yet another
chance for the public to stigmatize the genetic health of Jews _
and now in the murky world of mental illness. Some Jewish leaders,
already worried about discrimination against Jewish women who test
positively for a breast-cancer gene mutation, reacted anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are we being singled out?'' said Nancy Kaufman, director
of the Jewish Community Relations Council of Greater Boston.
``These studies have created an enormous amount of anxiety in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Jewish leaders complain that these studies trigger horrific
reminders of Nazi mass murders based on the notion of Jewish
genetic inferiority. Others are quick to emphasize that today's
genetic studies are intended to help people, not hurt them, but
genetic privacy is a touchy subject for many Jews: Jewish groups
led the recent passage of a Massachusetts genetic privacy law.
</P>
<P>
   While at her lab at Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine
in Baltimore, Pulver heard a woman over the phone scream at her,
``How dare you do this to the Jewish people!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Jew,'' replied Pulver, a response that has often quieted
her critics. ``Please don't speak for me.''
</P>
<P>
   American Jews are reassessing their role in today's frenzy over
genetic research, trying to decide just what the impact will be if
they continue to allow their relatively homogeneous genes to be
used in laboratory studies.
</P>
<P>
   What scientists so often seek are the blood samples of Ashkenazi
Jews, which represents 90 percent of this country's 6 million Jews
who emigrated from eastern and central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Like other isolated groups, such as the Icelanders, Finns,
American Indians and the Amish, Ashkenazi Jews have a rather
homogeneous gene pool because they descended from common lineages
and tended to marry within the same group.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the genetic similarities between members of the
group, patterns of genetic mutations are easier to spot, improving
the odds that researchers can find the genetic roots of disease.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists also like to study American Jews, in particular,
because, as a group, they tend to be pro-science and cooperative
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews in general are eager to do for the next generation,''
said Jane Matlaw, chairwoman of the Jewish Women's Coalition on
Breast Cancer in Boston. ``If it's going to help my children and
grandchildren, take my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   While Jews understand the cool rationale as to why their genes
are so coveted by scientists, they worry the reasoning will be lost
on the public who may be misled into believing Jews have more
genetic disorders than other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society doesn't do well with subtleties,'' said Judith Tsipis,
a biology professor at Brandeis University. ``We live in an era of
one-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazi Jews have been the focus of genetic studies
investigating cancers related to the breast, ovaries, prostate
glands and colon, as well as Pulver's study into schizophrenia and
manic depression. Other studies have focused on autism and deafness
among Ashkenazi Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But the popularity of Jewish genes for study should be a plus,
not a negative, for the community, said Nancy Tung, director of
cancer risk and prevention at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``How lucky for the Jewish population that we're learning so
much about our illnesses,'' said Tung, who is of Ashkenazi Jewish
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Tung said she bristles at the ``anti-genetic study'' bias that
she thinks is developing in Boston, as too many people raise fears
about discrimination in insurance and employment. While these are
real fears, she said, they should not stop some women with a
significant family history of cancer, for instance, from securing
medical information that can save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Ashkenazi Jewish women have a 2.5 percent chance
of having one of three known genetic mutations that predispose a
woman to breast cancer. On average, women have less than a 0.1
percent chance of having one of these genes.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman has this mutation, Jewish or not, her chances of
developing breast cancer by age 70 ranges from 55 percent to 85
percent, compared to 10 to 12 percent for noncarriers.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who knows she has that genetic mutation has options,
such as increasing the frequency of mammograms and testing, or the
extreme measure of a double masectomy, Tung said. Still, these
women at least have the option of doing something that could save
their lives, she said, while most breast cancer gene mutations
affecting other groups have yet to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should consider it a good thing that we know more about our
population,'' Tung said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Delman, 41, wanted to help advance science when he
rolled up his sleeve and participated in Pulver's study. He said he
wanted to do what he could to advance research into manic
depression, which has hobbled him since his teenage years and
throughout his studies at Tufts University and the University of
Pennsylvania Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Delman, who heard about Pulver's study through an ad in the
Jewish Advocate, said manic depression appears to run in his
family, as a grandmother also suffered from manic depression. He
declined to say what side of the family this grandmother is from,
saying he doesn't want to risk stigmatizing one side of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that he has some concerns about how genetic
findings _ some of which could be released from Pulver's lab as
early as this fall _ will be reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashkenazi Jews might become associated with manic-depressive
illness and schizophrenia,'' said Delman, a mental-health advocate
who recently got married and now works for the Massachusetts
Consumer Satisfaction Team, which assesses mental health services.
``That can be a danger. Information has to come out the right
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stigma issues intensify as genetic studies on Ashkenazi Jews
move from rare disorders that do affect them disproportionately,
such as potentially lethal Tay-Sachs disease, to more common
cancers and illnesses. It's quite another issue when they choose
Ashkenazi Jews as targets of research simply because they are a
convenient homogeneous ethnic group residing within the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews could become stigmatized as having high-risk gene
pools,'' said Michael Grodin, director of medical ethics at Boston
Universty School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   To address stigma issues and more, the National Institutes of
Health is holding its first conference, at the end of next month,
on ``responsible collection and use of samples'' for
population-based genetic research.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of a variety of ethnic groups, including
Americans of Jewish, African, Asian and Latin ancestry, are being
invited to attend, said Judith Greenberg, the NIH organizer of the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, synagogues and Jewish organization have taken part in
educational campaigns to explain the flurry of information about
genetic diseases in the Jewish population. Still, many are cautious
about this new wave of research and screen carefully what
information comes through the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not open the door to let anyone waltz in,'' said Rabbi
Gershon Gewirtz of Young Israel in Brookline, an Orthodox
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lewis, cofounder of Refuah, a Massachusetts-based support
group for families with mentally ill members, mostly of Jewish
descent, said these genetic studies can trigger painful memories
for many people. While she credits Pulver with a ``low-pressure''
approach, she said many possible recruits turn away, not wanting to
divulge family histories, some of which can be quite painful,
particularly when mental illness is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Pulver said she recognizes the courage it takes for people to
take part in her study, but she firmly believes Ashkenazi Jews will
utimately be helped, not harmed. She calls her project the ``family
study,'' with hopes that Jews will see this as an effort to learn
more about their genetic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my Orthodox Jewish grandfather would be proud of the
work of his granddaughter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
