<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE DEAL WITH FOOD DYES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I just noticed that my multivitamin contains dyes _ yellow 6
lake, blue 2 lake, and red 40 lake. What are these? Are they
harmful? Why are they necessary?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  M.C., Peabody, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Most vitamins are colorless _ that is, white _ with a couple
of exceptions, such as riboflavin, or vitamin B-2, which is
yellowish-orange, and vitamin B-12, which is dark red. For some
reason, people like to take pills that have more interesting
colors, and dyes like the ones you mention are added. Many dyes are
harmful and the only ones permitted by law in food products are
ones that have been shown to be quite safe. Dr. Knowledge avoids
vitamins with spurious coloring agents, but it's just a matter of
personal taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to: 617-929-9263, or a
letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston Globe,
Health/Science Section, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107. Please include
your initials and hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
