<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEAMSTERS-LAW-BOS &LR;      08-15 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION TACTICS: LEGAL LINE IS THIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A movie producer's car with its windows shot out. Not-so-subtle
threats to shut down a movie set with car horns and bullhorn-toting
pickets. Two-thousand-dollar-a-week union drivers with criminal
records sitting around doing nothing for most of a workday. A
250-pound union negotiator's menacing stare as he cryptically says
a production will include members of his local or else.
</P>
<P>
   Both inside and outside the entertainment industry, many people
find such tactics and practices _ allegedly employed by Teamsters
in Massachusetts and nationwide _ distasteful and troubling. As a
result, a federal grand jury is scrutinizing the practices that
Teamsters Local 25 in Charlestonw, Mass. has used in dealing with
filmmakers trying to get movies shot in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Yet labor law experts say federal authorities have their work
cut out for them _ not only because cases against union officials
are difficult to prove, but because it is not certain that many of
the hardball union tactics movie industry executives complain about
are even against the law.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between what is unlawful and what is not, the
experts say, is often celluloid-thin. The same activity that a
filmmaker might brand intimidation, union officials call legitimate
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fine line between what is legal what might cross
the line and be improper,'' said Lewis Smoak, a nationally known
Washington labor lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a moral law here, and the moral law says it's a fight
of survival,'' said Domenic Bozzotto, the former head of Local 26
of the hotel and restaurant workers union.
</P>
<P>
   The law, in many cases, appears to favor the unions. Under a
1973 US Supreme Court decision, U.S. v. Enmons, union officials
cannot be prosecuted for extortion under the federal Hobbs Act for
tactics _ even illegal ones like vandalism and violence _ that
further legitimate union objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can picket and burn equipment or beat people, you can't
charge them under the federal statute,'' one former federal labor
official said recently. ``It's remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians and business leaders have decried Enmons, but
have been unable to get it overturned. In 1997, for example,
Senator Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) unsuccessfully tried to push a
``Freedom from Union Violence Act'' through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Vandalism and assaults can still be prosecuted as state crimes,
but a study in the mid-1990s by the National Institute for Labor
Relations Research showed that such cases are rarely prosecuted
successfully. Out of more than 8,700 incidents of union-related
personal injury and property damage reported since 1975, fewer than
300 of the cases resulted in convictions, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   The Enmons decision appears to raise the bar for at least one
prong of the investigation by US Attorney Donald K. Stern's office
and the US Department of Labor _ allegations by movie producers
that they are threatened and harrassed into hiring Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but some of the harrassment is legal, experts
say. Noisy picketing _ a tactic Local 25 reportedly used against
the producers of the movie ``Next Stop Wonderland'' _ can disrupt a
movie set, but in many cases it is protected as free speech under
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Disruptive picketing can sometimes be declared an illegal
practice, said Ronald Cohen, regional attorney for the NLRB in New
England, but only under the National Labor Relations Act, which is
a civil statute, not a criminal one.
</P>
<P>
   The Enmons decision does not, however, cover corruption by union
officials, such as bribery or kickbacks or other attempts to line
their own pockets at the expense of their members, experts say.
Federal investigators locally, for example, are investigating
whether Local 25 movie transportation coordinator James Flynn
forced movie producers to rent trailers and equipment from Location
Connection, a company he controls.
</P>
<P>
   The last attempt by federal officials to go after Local 25
officials for enriching themselves at their members' expense ended
with a mixed result.
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Christmas of 1994, transportation coordinator
William Winn was convicted of taking accepting a bribe from an
undercover FBI agent posing as a Hollywood movie producer. Local 25
vice president James Moar, however, was acquitted of similar
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other allegations against Flynn _ that he has padded
payrolls and hand-picked friends with criminal records to work
movie crews _ may be difficult to translate into criminal charges
because they ultimately relate to attempts to help union members
get work. In that context, a threat to shut down a movie set if
Teamsters are not hired, may not be criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of threats in this world that there are
absolutely nothing wrong with,'' said Flynn's attorney, Richard
Egbert.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts also said there is also nothing illegal about
Flynn allegedly selecting friends to work on lucrative movie jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is not technically even against the Teamsters' rules. A new
national Teamster's ``Code of Conduct'' that would make the
selection of members for coveted work like the movie jobs is still
months away from being ratified, union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even the new code of conduct recognizes the reality
that ``you are never going to turn the Teamsters into a Boy Scout
troop,'' said Edwin Stier, Special Counsel to the union's
anti-corruption effort, Project RISE.
</P>
<P>
   The draft code, for example, even tells members the proper way
to act toward a mobster who might be a member of one's own family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maintaining a relationship with a racketeer who is a member of
one's immediate family is permissible if it is limited to lawful,
social interactions that do not relate to Union matters,'' it
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
