<HEADLINE>
WHEN CANCELLATION STRIKES: A WAR STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar with AIR-WOES)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of passengers on all airlines is higher now _ more
than 70 percent of the seats on every flight are filled with
passengers who paid for their ticket _ than at any time since World
War II, when commercial aviation was in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy humming and the Internet enabling airlines to
sell open seats at last-minute discounts, planes are routinely full
and airlines never make money by parking airplanes, so fleets are
being fully used.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, when a flight with 150 people on it is canceled,
finding 150 additional seats on other airplanes is challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly higher frustration levels among passengers
than at any time in recent memory,'' said David Fuscus, a spokesman
for the airline industry's trade association, the Air Transport
Association. ``It used to be, you'd get on a plane and there would
be no one in the middle seat. Now, there is someone there and
sometimes it is you.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than being stuck in the middle seat that has
passengers up in arms. It's being told you can't get home anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Ernie Paicopolos and Karla Buhsmer with
Opinion Dynamics Corp. in Cambridge, Mass. The two were in Orlando,
Fla., for a three-hour meeting on Friday, July 14, and they
expected to be back in town that night. Although they were flying
on different airlines at different times, neither got back to
Boston until Saturday, because of thunderstorms en route.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, one of the ticket agents on Saturday said to me,
`I can get you out at 11 a.m. on Sunday.' And she said it as if she
was doing me a favor,'' said Buhsmer, who eventually got home by
connecting through Washington.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for her plane at Dulles Airport on Saturday
afternoon, she saw a fellow stranded passenger from Orlando
suddenly appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works for EMC and he said he got so frustrated in Orlando
he rented a car and started driving. At 7:30 in the morning he was
so tired, he stopped, called Delta and said `Where is the nearest
airport?' And he turned the car in at Dulles.''
</P>
<P>
   Paicopolos, who was flying US Airways Metrojet, rebooked on
American. ``I wanted to find a flight that had a first-class
compartment because I figured they would be less likely to cancel
that plane and tick all those people off,'' he said. His hunch paid
off: The American flight arrived on time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
