<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (With sidebar: AIR-DELAYS)  
 FRUSTRATIONS AT THE GATE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERNDON, Va. _ The line of thunderstorms that had blossomed in
the Midwest was meandering toward the East Coast. Rising up to
50,000 feet, the storms had severed major East-West air routes,
creating havoc in airports from St. Louis to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At the Federal Aviation Administration's air-traffic control
system command center in this suburban Washington town, air-traffic
controllers, airline industry officials, and meteorologists were
trying to make the best of a bad situation. But one of the 11
enormous television screens at the center showed the carnage:
Hundreds of flights along the East Coast were being delayed because
the arrival rate at many airports had been cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, which bore the brunt of the most vicious
thunderstorms on July 28, more than 170 flights were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how things were going, Jack Kies, the center's program
manager, said with a growl: ``Not very good if you are trying to
get somewhere by airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   Such episodes have become common in this summer of 2000. No one
who flies with any regularity has been immune from the delays and
cancellations that are plaguing an air system that is bursting at
the seams with travelers. But the problems this summer have been
compounded by a spate of bad weather that has exacerabated flaws in
the system ranging from a lack of enough runways at many airports
to overscheduling by airlines to the reliance on a 50-year-old
national air navigation program.
</P>
<P>
   United, the world's largest airline, has been particularly hard
hit. Labor unrest with pilots has forced the airline to remove
thousands of flights from its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of the airline, the summer of 2000, indeed the
entire year, is shaping up to be the worst for delays and
cancellations, shattering records set last year. With traffic
expected to increase by about 4 percent a year, many specialists
say that the system is likely to get worse, with scheduling
problems that will leave passengers in the lurch, before there is
any marked improvement.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the FAA has spent $3 billion upgrading
equipment at 20 centers that handle air traffic. That effort has
paid some dividends as equipment-related delays have declined by
more than 8 percent in 2000. Still, through July of this year, the
FAA said, more than 250,000 flights have been delayed, about 10
percent more than last year at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Delays are up from last year for every month except May and
July, which were down 7.5 and 1.7 percent respectively, according
to the data. Delays through July have surpassed the number for all
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   What has many passengers seething is that planes are now so full
that when a flight is canceled airline employees will report that
it could be days before a seat becomes available on another flight
home.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the frequent business travelers, known as road
warriors, who have faced hours of delay, frustrating lines at
ticket counters or the chagrin of seeing their flights disappear
from departure boards. In New York, Leo Mullin, chairman and chief
executive of Delta Air Lines, was trying to get home to Atlanta on
July 28. He was one of tens of thousands of grounded passengers
that Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in it up to my eyeballs,'' Mullin said. ``This has been
a particularly difficult time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Federal Aviation Administration chief, Jane Garvey, has
faced delayed flights and has given up trying to get home to New
England some summer weekends. Garvey's most recent flight, from
Dallas to Washington, was delayed an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a passenger and you're stuck, as I was, it's very
frustrating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pinpointing the exact number of delays and cancellations is
impossible because the FAA not does include cancellations in its
figures, and the Department of Transportation, which ranks airlines
by on-time performance, does not count a flight delayed if it
leaves the gate within 15 minutes of schedule _ even if it then
sits for an hour waiting to take off.
</P>
<P>
   That confusion was noted recently by Kenneth Mead, the inspector
general of the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this . . . is resolved, the FAA and the air carriers
will continue to blame one another, and the decision-makers'
ability to address the underlying causes such as runway capacity,
air-traffic control equipment and procedures, weather, and airline
scheduling practices will be hindered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the precise causes for delays may not be known,
specialists say delays are worse in the summer because
thunderstorms make swaths of the sky impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the summer that was supposed to be better than last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, President Clinton announced a collaborative effort
between the airlines and the FAA for weather forecasting and for
alternate route planning that was designed as a short-term solution
to last year's historic delays.
</P>
<P>
   Every two hours, starting at 7 a.m., airline dispatchers in
operations centers, FAA air-traffic facilities around the country,
and officials at Herndon hold a telephone conference call and
discuss a game plan for the following two hours. Frequently, Garvey
listens in to the conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ryan, vice president of air-traffic management for the Air
Transport Association, the industry's trade association, says
collaboration between the FAA and the airlines has never been
better. He and airline executives, like Delta's Mullin, say delays
would be worse this summer without the program, especially since
the weather has been more severe this year.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Thursday, FAA officials defended the
system. They said that about 80 percent of the 14,000 flights each
day depart and arrive on time. But Peter Challan, deputy associate
administrator of the FAA, acknowledged: ``If you are delayed, these
numbers don't mean anything to you.''
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials from Garvey on down say their first consideration
is safety, and that trying to orchestrate collaboration among
fierce competitors is exceedingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines don't give us too many ideas,'' said Kies, of the
FAA's command center. ``They'll say, `That is an awfully long
alternative route, can't you do something else?' They tend to do
more carping than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference calls have led to greater predictability for the
airlines, but the new collaborative program was also supposed to
maximize the use of available airspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not put that into practice aggressively enough,''
Mullin said. ``I don't want to apportion blame, but the FAA is
responsible for managing the airspace.''
</P>
<P>
   The national airspace system is supported by radar and
ground-based radio beacon navigation aids that were designed in the
1940s to control and direct planes.
</P>
<P>
   While the sky may seem limitless, the system is a series of
well-defined corridors, or jetways, that extend from radio beacon
to radio beacon. When one jetway is closed, it is as if a lane on a
highway has been shut down _ all the traffic is forced into the
remaining lanes, slowing everything down.
</P>
<P>
   The new program was supposed to open additional airspace,
including some corridors flying over Canada and into the military
airspace along the East Coast. But that has proven difficult.
Canada's privatized air-traffic control system wants compensation
for handling huge numbers of American planes that are neither
taking off nor landing there.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the military's airspace is also challenging. ``In the
past, it has been real hard to get them to give it up even when
they are not using it. But, they are starting to move off that
some,'' said Randy Schwitz, vice president of the National Air
Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
