<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN L.A., THE NOMINEE TAKES SECOND FIDDLE TO MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After thanking AT&AMP;T, Johnson &AMP; Johnson and other
donors for the scrambled eggs that Democrats were about to eat,
California party Chairman Art Torres had one more important
corporations to praise:
</P>
<P>
   ``And also the great company that has brought joy across America
_ Pfizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the maker of Viagra has a piece of the Democratic National
Convention, which runs through Thursday and includes an estimated
300 fund-raisers and other ``donor maintenance'' parties taking
place from secluded Beverly Hills estates to the Santa Monica Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Even with nearly $450 million raised so far between the major
presidential candidates and their parties, more money will be
collected at the four-day convention. Nominating a president is
only the second most important thing Democrats will accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``As crazy as it may seem given all the money in this
election,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center
for Responsive Politics, which is monitoring fund raising at the
conventions, ``we haven't even reached the peak of the fund-raising
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixing with the powerful and wealthy is Makinson's guerrilla
fund-raising warrior, Holly Bailey. She is spending the entire week
sneaking past the velvet ropes into private fund-raisers to write
daily reports for www.opensecrets.org, the center's Web site
devoted to exposing political fund-raising and corporate
schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   The night before the convention, Bailey found herself at two of
the hottest corporate-sponsored parties, including an event for
``Blue Dog'' conservative Democrats at the Santa Monica Pier, where
blue carpet was laid out and indigo corn dogs were served.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Dog party was sponsored in part by the same Republican
donors that Democrats love to hate: the National Rifle Association,
Philip Morris Cos., US Tobacco and the defense contractor Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Blue Dog Democrats oppose gun-control measures in
Congress and support the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based law firm Verner Liipfert also is sponsoring
a reception at the trendy Skybar on Sunset Boulevard in Hollywood.
A spokeswoman for Philip Morris, which employs Verner Liipfert,
said the party was a chance to ``share ideas'' with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore in particular has fought for regulating
tobacco companies and for stricter gun-control laws. And gun
control will be a central theme of the Democratic presidential
campaign as Gore contrasts himself with Republican Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the issue of hypocrisy,'' said Scott Harshbarger,
president of the campaign finance oversight group Common Cause.
``This is a party that says, `We're going to fight these
interests,' but in the dark of night, who's paying for these
receptions?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other major parties include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Mardi Gras-themed event for Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana
sponsored by defense contractors Lockheed Martin and Northrop
Grumman. Both companies want to keep the Pentagon budget growing
under the next Congress and president.
</P>
<P>
   _ A gala at the Petersen Automotive Museum honoring the Missouri
delegation and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, sponsored by
Daimler/Chrysler and the United Auto Workers Union. The auto
industry is concerned about fuel efficiency standards, the
fluctuation of gas and oil prices and global trade among a host of
issues pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ A reception in Santa Monica for California Rep. Mike Thompson
sponsored by the Wine Institute and several prominent wineries,
which are fighting legislation that would forbid wineries from
selling their product over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Institute spokesman Steve Gross said the Internet bill was
in the Senate, not in the House, where Thompson serves. It is a
stretch, he said, to link the reception to the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike is chairman of the Congressional Wine Caucus,'' Gross
said, ``and it was really kind of a courtesy from us for him, and
to feature the products coming out of his district.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the parties have included a smattering of movie stars.
Low-wattage stars tend to show up at the public events, but people
like Jennifer Aniston and Brad Pitt, John Travolta and Gregory Peck
appeared at a private tribute for President Clinton and a brunch at
Barbra Streisand's Malibu estate for his presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the objects is to make these deep-pocketed donors feel
like kings,'' Makinson said, ``by mixing with politicians and
mixing with the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention is being sponsored by numerous
powerful corporations, despite an attempt in 1974 to outlaw
corporate donations to conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But now, through ``host committees,'' the major contributors can
give freely to the conventions. The Democratic convention sponsors
include BP Amoco Corp., United Parcel Service, Microsoft and
General Motors, which supplied a fleet of cars. The federal
government is providing $13 million in taxpayer money as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
