 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tuesday, August 15, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis or Susie McBee at
213-336-1800.
</P>
<P>
   (All sluglines include the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-CONVENTION-RDP (Los Angeles) _ It's liberal day at the
Democratic National Convention as the delegates hear from leaders
of the gay rights and abortion rights movements, along with members
of the Kennedy family, former Sen. Bill Bradley and union leaders.
Meanwhile, President Clinton and Vice President Gore symbolically
pass the torch of party leadership at a rally in Monroe, Mich.,
with Clinton on his way home to the convention and Gore traveling
here to accept the nomination Thursday night. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GAYS-ABORTIONS (Los Angeles) _ A wag once said the only
difference between the Republican party and the Democratic party is
their respective stands on abortion rights and gay rights. Those
distinctions will be on display at the Democratic National
Convention Tuesday night when Elizabeth Birch of the Human Rights
Campaign and Kate Michelman, president of the NARAL, seek to rally
the delegates. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LIEBERMAN (Los Angeles) _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman seeks to
reassure leading black politicians of his commitment to affirmative
action as he prepares his acceptance speech to the Democratic
National Convention on Wednesday night. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-ALTERNATIVE-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Jesse Jackson speaks
to the Shadow Convention, a gathering of independents and liberals
who say the Democrats and Republicans are ignoring their concerns,
such as their view the federal government should liberalize
marijuana laws. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-CELL-PHONES (Washington) In a victory for privacy rights
groups, a federal appeals court imposes restrictions on the ability
of the FBI to track the whereabouts of cell phone users. The court
also opens the door to additional restrictions on a controversial
FBI e-mail surveillance system known as Carnivore. By ERIC
ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton goes out in a
blaze of glory, leaving the Democrats to carry on the campaign
without their controversial star. For the moment he's only going as
far as the White House, where he still has a few weeks left to
battle those cranky Republicans in Congress. Nobody thinks he will
be quiet in retirement, but the country just won't be the same
without his omnipresent presidential antics. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
