antitrust ruling against Microsoft. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ Mexico will report its
second-quarter growth rate Tuesday. Economists believe that the
economy grew at a rate of 6.9 percent, compared with 7.9 percent in
the first quarter. Mexico also said strong oil prices had helped
the government achieve a budget surplus in the first half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-AMERICA-DELIVERY (Undated) _ A look at the delivery
services in Latin America, which are ill equipped to handle the
economic growth and an expected surge in e-commerce that is
expected in a few years. Big global delivery companies such as
United Parcel Service and Federal Express are moving to strengthen
their networks in Latin America ahead of an anticipated expansion
in their business. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXEC-TURNOVER (Undated) _ The widely publicized ousters of
leaders like Durk I. Jager of Procter &AMP; Gamble, M. Douglas Ivester
of Coca-Cola and Jill E. Barad of Mattel suggest that chief
executives have less staying power than they did just a few years
ago. The reasons seem clear: The stock market is far more volatile
than it used to be, management experts say, and directors punish
poor results swiftly. But a new study concludes that not much has
actually changed at the helm of the nation's biggest companies in
the second half of the 1990s. The median tenure of leaders at 65
large companies was the same at the beginning of 2000 _ six years _
as it had been at the start of 1995. The average term actually rose
one year, to 8.3 years. The results of the study have left
corporate governance experts admittedly puzzled. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC-CASTRO (Undated) _ Ida L. Castro, the chairwoman of the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
