<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOW-COST OHIO SCHOOL LURES BABY BOOMERS, SENIORS
 &HT;    For Sunday, Aug. 20
 &HT;    w/COX-ADULT-STUDENTS, COX-ADULT-TYPICAL, COX-ADULT-STUDENT-DATA
 &HT;    BY JOANNE HUIST SMITH
 &HT;    C.2000 COX NEWS SERVICE
 &HT;    DAYTON, Ohio _ Barb Herzog likes her job. The pay is good and
she's often the person her bosses, 10 years her junior, seek when
they have questions.
 &HT;    But despite her expertise in medical finance, the 46-year-old
felt she was at a disadvantage. She didn't have a college
education.
 &HT;    ``I've got the hands-on experience, now I want the degree,''
Herzog said. ``I need a school that will let me do classwork on
airplanes, in hotel rooms, on the Internet.''
 &HT;    While her work schedule is hectic, Herzog begins this fall to
convert on-the-job training into an associate's degree from
Sinclair Community College in Dayton. She joins about 21,000
students who turn to the two-year college each year to update job
skills, change careers or for personal enrichment.
 &HT;    Like Herzog, many of Sinclair's students, with an average age of
31, juggle jobs and family. Sitting in a classroom during the
traditional work week is not an option. Classes have to be
affordable. Learning has to be molded around already busy lives.
 &HT;    From application to graduation, that's what Sinclair tries to
do.
 &HT;    Named an Adult Learner Friendly Institution by the Washington,
D.C.-based Council for Adult and Experiential Learning, Sinclair
has focused on designing courses for adults that are accessible and
moderately priced. At $29.45 a credit hour for Montgomery County
(Ohio) residents, Sinclair is one of the lowest-cost colleges in
Ohio, according to the study. The branch campus of Miami University
in nearby Middletown charges $114 or $163 a credit hour.
 &HT;    Sinclair wants to remove the ``I can't'' from the going-back-to
school scenario, said Dodie Munn, an admissions officer.
 &HT;    ``Coming back to school is a big deal for adults. They're afraid
of failure,'' Munn said. ``Many who come to us don't recognize the
successes they've had in life. We look at where they are and where
they need to be. Then we show them learning options that fit their
needs.''
 &HT;    It's all about choices, Munn said.
 &HT;    Students may take classes at the college's main campus in
downtown Dayton or opt for a video class at 10 area high schools
and Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in nearby Fairborn. For
students who can't make it to class during the week, classes are
offered evenings and weekends.
 &HT;    Kathy Ragan, 51, of Huber Heights, Ohio, waited until her four
children graduated from high scse semester, dorm rooms, long
registration lines, ostentatious partying, and all-night cramming
for tests that require regurgitation of lecture notes.
 &HT;    To attract adults, some emphasiz Most colleges have decided that
it would be too costly to sponsor a day care center. But many offer
parents a list of respected providers or sponsor special children's
events. In Brunswick, Ga., for example, student activity fees at
Coastal Georgia Community College help pay for free family movies
and for a Saturday cookout at which a magician or other entertainer
keeps children occupied on campus while their parents use the
library.
 &HT;    The Internet helps some adults tuck lessons into niches in
ttudents tend to view things more from a consumer standpoint, and
their biggest concern is the impact on their family in finances and
time,'' DeGabriele said at Mesa State College, where he counsels
transfer students. ``The idea that a professor would try to have
his only office hours at an inconvenient time, or that a bookstore
or finance office wouldn't be open on evenings or weekenhe maximum
allowable in transfer credits and in experiential credits,''
Denison said. ``We are expected to respond to requests for
schedules tailor-made to one individual student's needs (and) to
eliminate any instructor whom students don't feel is teaching what
they want to know.''
 &HT;    As director of the office of adult learning services in the New
York headquarters of the nonprofit College Board, Carol
Aslanian(cq) advises colleges to adjustincome from their investment
in higher education.
 &HT;    In fact, convenience and lower cost are prime reasons why about
55 percent of adult students go to community colleges, which today
have campuses within less than an hour's drive of the vast majority
of U.S. homes.
 &HT;    ``Adults are the most diverse students in higher education,''
said George Boggs, president of Palomar College, who will leave the
nine-campus California institution ton or learn a foreign language
in preparation for a trip.''
 &HT;    To meet the needs of those students, Palomar supplements its
traditional fall and spring semesters with ``fast-track eight-weeTV
college, weekend college, and four-, six-, and eight-week summer
sessions.''
 &HT;     
 &HT;    (Story can end here. Optional add, which can stand alone as a
sidebar, follows)
 &HT;     
 &HT;    At National University, the third largest private universit who
are working full-time,'' McCalla said. Technology consultant who
like the idea of taking a course or two between jobs.
 &HT;    Monique La Chappa, 35, who graduated from National in July, said
she worked full-time when she started 42 months ago. But she
switched to a half-time job after she fell asleep on a freeway and
ran into a roadside reflector on the 60-mile drive from San eople's
life better.'' But, she added, ``In fairness, you'd better warn
anyone who is thinking of doing this that I also put 118,000 miles
on my Toyota Tercel, and I'm $35,000 in debt.''
