 &HT;    MOM, 36, NOW TYPICAL ADULT COLLEGE STUDENT
 &HT;    570&AMP;add
 &HT;    For Sunday, Aug. 20
 &HT;    w/COX-ADULT-STUDENTS, COX-ADULT-SINCLAIR,
COX-ADULT-STUDENTS-DATA
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After breakfast on a school-day morning, Theresa
Johnson double-checks three sets of homework as she packs lunches
into three backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Lindsay, 10, and son Bryantven more than the
national average. Johnson is taking on the heavyweight schedule
because she is growing impatient as she sprints toward the end of a
marathon quest for a bachelor's degree that began
</P>
<P>
   more than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When the College Board drew up a composite of the 42 percent of
the nation's college students who are 25 or older, the New
York-based organization concluded that, like Johnson, the typical
adult student would are so centered on the party-age, beer-drinking
student whose mommy and daddy are paying for their education.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, she added, ``I'm not knocking it. When I was 18, I was
pretty clueless myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She married after high school, worked in sales jobs before
becoming a paramedic, and had two children before her divorce. Her
ex-husband has since died.
</P>
<P>
   When Bring, she resumed her quest in the spring of 1999 at Iowa
State, where she majors in housing and the near environment and
minors in gerontology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the strongest gerontology program in the state, and I
want to work on designs that make it easier and safer for older
people with dementia to function, whether in Alzheimer's care
facilities or their own homes,'' she said. ``Iy seeks high grades.
In her case, high marks also help her retain the merit-based
scholarships that supplement her federal Pell grant and earnings
from her work-study job as a research assistant.
</P>
<P>
   She pinches some pennies. Her lunch consists of leftovers from
the freezer, heated in a campus microwave because that means the $5
a day that would pay for a sub sandwich, soda and chips on campus
can be used instead for ``baseball cleats or lun your life. It
shows your children that a college education is important,''
Johnson said. ``I've found a strength within myself that I never
thought I had.''
</P>
