<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS GROUNDS ITS CONCORDES AFTER REPORT BY INVESTIGATORS
 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways PLC grounded its fleet of Concorde
supersonic airliners Tuesday after investigators said they would
urge the withdrawal of the airplane's airworthiness certification
following the fatal Concorde crash near Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
   A British Airways spokeswoman called the suspension of flights _
which halted a plane even as it taxied for takeoff _ indefinite,
but it was unclear whether the move effectively meant the end of
supersonic trans-Atlantic flights, largely the elite preserve of
executives and celebrities over the airplane's 25 years of
commercial operation.
</P>
<P>
   The July 25 crash near Paris was the only fatal Concorde
accident in the plane's history. When it happened, Air France
immediately suspended flights by its five remaining Concordes, but,
after an initial suspension, British Airways continued to fly the
needle-nosed airliner, which crosses the Atlantic in three and a
half hours. British Airways operates seven Concordes.
</P>
<P>
   British officials declined to say whether Tuesday's suspension
meant that British Airways Concorde flights had also been at risk
since the Paris crash. In that crash, the plane struck a hotel,
killing all 109 people on board and four on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   French investigators concluded five days ago that a 16-inch
piece of metal on the runway at Charles de Gaulle airport probably
slashed a tire as the plane hurtled down the runway on take-off at
about 195 mph, scattering debris that ruptured fuel tanks. The
plane took off with a plume of flame spewing from its wing and
crashed soon afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Air Accidents Investigation Branch and the French
Bureau of Accident Investigations told British Airways early
Tuesday that they would recommend suspending the Concorde's
certificate of airworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   When British Airways learned that the suspension would be
sought, they radioed the pilot of Concorde flight BA 001 as it was
taxiing on the runway for takeoff and ordered it to return to the
terminal, according to British news reports.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We immediately withdrew our supersonic fleet from service this
morning, canceling the Concorde service BA001,'' Rod Eddington, the
British Airways chief executive, said Tuesday. He did not say what
prompted the development, which represented an about-face from the
airline's earlier insistence, after the Paris crash, that its
Concorde fleet should continue flying. A scheduled return flight
from New York Tuesday night was also canceled.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   David Learmount, operations and safety officer of Flight
International magazine, called the suspension of the Concorde's
certification ``very, very rare and very, very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that British Airways had modified its fleet of Concordes
in the mid-1990s to prevent a similar tire-burst from causing
catastrophic damage and, on the basis of that modification, the
airplanes had been permitted to continue flying.
</P>
<P>
   After assessing evidence from the French investigation, however,
British investigators ``must have come to the conclusion that
despite the British Airways modification, the risk is unacceptably
high'' of a crash similar to the one in France, Learmount said.
</P>
<P>
   A suspension of certification, he said, means ``the aircraft is
grounded, and it has to be modified so that the risk is eliminated
or reduced'' to the satisfaction of aviation regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The last such suspension of certification, he said, involved
DC-10 aircraft. The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration grounded
the planes for five weeks in 1979 after the crash of an American
Airlines plane in Chicago killed 275 people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   British Airways says Britain's Civil Aviation Authority
supported its earlier decision to continue flying the Concorde
after the airline undertook a series of tests of the fleet's
airframes, engines, tires, wheels and hydraulic systems.
</P>
<P>
   The British accidents investigation branch, a department of the
transport ministry, declined to say why it would make such a
recommendation, referring callers to the Civil Aviation Authority.
The Civil Aviation Authority declined immediate comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
