<TEXT>
<P>
   LOW-COST OHIO SCHOOL LURES BABY BOOMERS, SENIORS
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, Aug. 20
</P>
<P>
   w/COX-ADULT-STUDENTS, COX-ADULT-TYPICAL, COX-ADULT-STUDENT-DATA
</P>
<P>
   BY JOANNE HUIST SMITH
</P>
<P>
   C.2000 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Barb Herzog likes her job. The pay is good and
she's often the person her bosses, 10 years her junior, seek when
they have questions.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her expertise in medical finance, the 46-year-old
felt she was at a disadvantage. She didn't have a college
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the hands-on experience, now I want the degree,''
Herzog said. ``I need a school that will let me do classwork on
airplanes, in hotel rooms, on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   While her work schedule is hectic, Herzog begins this fall to
convert on-the-job training into an associate's degree from
Sinclair Community College in Dayton. She joins about 21,000
students who turn to the two-year college each year to update job
skills, change careers or for personal enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Like Herzog, many of Sinclair's students, with an average age of
31, juggle jobs and family. Sitting in a classroom during the
traditional work week is not an option. Classes have to be
affordable. Learning has to be molded around already busy lives.
</P>
<P>
   From application to graduation, that's what Sinclair tries to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Named an Adult Learner Friendly Institution by the Washington,
D.C.-based Council for Adult and Experiential Learning, Sinclair
has focused on designing courses for adults that are accessible and
moderately priced. At $29.45 a credit hour for Montgomery County
(Ohio) residents, Sinclair is one of the lowest-cost colleges in
Ohio, according to the study. The branch campus of Miami University
in nearby Middletown charges $114 or $163 a credit hour.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair wants to remove the ``I can't'' from the going-back-to
school scenario, said Dodie Munn, an admissions officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming back to school is a big deal for adults. They're afraid
of failure,'' Munn said. ``Many who come to us don't recognize the
successes they've had in life. We look at where they are and where
they need to be. Then we show them learning options that fit their
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all about choices, Munn said.
</P>
<P>
   Students may take classes at the college's main campus in
downtown Dayton or opt for a video class at 10 area high schools
and Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in nearby Fairborn. For
students who can't make it to class during the week, classes are
offered evenings and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Ragan, 51, of Huber Heigg higher education, even as it
changes them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say 'college student' and most people think of an 18- or
19-year-old. That's because we have a cultural tradition in which
that marks the transition time from adolescence to adulthood,''
said Ken Foster of the University of Utah, who has written four
books on adult learners.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the average age of college students now development class,
seminar or workshop in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the deepest reason they enroll is a hunger for
learning,'' said Janice Gordon-Kelter of Houston, dean of special
programs at the University of St. Thomas, which offers a well-known
degree completion program for adults who have earned at least two
years of credits elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other big reason is, they've been laid off or seen others
promoted ahead of them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earning a degree at any age can pay off monetthe financial
support of their employer, and certainly an appreciation of the
value of an education.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hamby(cq), who directs a degree completion program at
Abilene Christian University for 170 adults up to 72 years old,
said, ``We waste education on 18-year-olds, which I know because I
was once 18 myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He said older students ``absorb new information and theories
like sponges, but they'll challenge the socks off you if yohat
require regurgitation of lecture notes.
</P>
<P>
   To attract adults, some emphasize credit for life experiences
and flexible credit transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Others offer ``stop-out'' policies that retain potential
dropouts by letting a student whose course is interrupted by a
family emergency resume the course when it is offered again.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Denver's Women's Colletertainer keeps children
occupied on campus while their parents use the library.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet helps some adults tuck lessons into niches in their
hectic days of balancing family, work and study. Pat Kapper, a vice
president at the profitable Career Education Corporation, which
offers degrees in 15 states, said, ``Older students also happen to
be disciplined learners (with) son evenings or weekends can bug
them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
