<P>
   WAINEWRIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Wainwright the Poisoner,''
Andrew Motion's unusual biography of Thomas Griffiths Wainewright,
a minor English painter of the first half of the 19th century who
was convicted of forgery and transported to Australia, where he did
hard labor for seven years. He was an unusual criminal in that he
knew people like Samuel Taylor Coleridge, William Blake and Lord
Byron, and when his term of hard labor was finished he gained
recognition in Tasmania as a portrait painter. Reviewed by Richard
Bernstein.
</P>
