<SLUG> BC-CALL-MOM2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF TEEN DRIVERS USE MONITORING TO EASE WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eliminates photo)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most parents in car-crazy America, Stephanie Brown trembled
when her children began to drive. Sure, they were plenty careful
when she rode shotgun. But would her Saturn become a Ferrari in her
absence?
</P>
<P>
   Seeking solace, Brown turned to MyParentsCare.com, one of dozens
of fledgling firms cropping up across the country that promise to
turn teen terrors into responsible drivers.
</P>
<P>
   For $99.95, MyParentsCare.com gave Brown a ``How's My Driving?''
bumper sticker that allows other drivers, pedestrians, and cyclists
to call a 24-hour toll-free hotline if Zachary or Lyndsay Brown
made reckless lane changes, sped, or failed to yield. The company
promised Brown a full report of any calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son didn't like the idea one bit, but that thing is on my
car,'' said Brown, who owns a stationery store in York, Pa. ``The
funny thing is, I find myself cooling it down when I'm behind the
wheel now because that sticker is there.''
</P>
<P>
   But if these start-ups appeal to the scariest common denominator
_ many companies brandish teen highway fatality statistics on their
Web sites _ some mental health specialists question the benefits of
such heavy-handed control tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, insurance companies and safe-driving advocates from
New Hampshire to California say they remain unconvinced that the
bumper stickers work, and have balked at the constant stream of
requests by monitoring companies to endorse and underwrite their
products.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bumper stickers go to the heart of issues of parental
control and trust,'' said Ronald P. Rohner, director of the Center
for the Study of Parental Acceptance and Rejection at the
University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may indeed be many teens with no problem with these
bumper stickers because they already feel loved and trusted by
their parents,'' he said. ``But if the teenagers feel like the
bumper stickers are a sign of mistrust and control, it could have
the exact opposite effect that the parents desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rohner and others say they have a hunch the bumper
stickers will do plenty to moderate bad driving habits among
younger, inexperienced drivers. But even so, Rohner said, the
better driving could come at a price: fractured family relations.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the monitoring companies _ some of which are
nonprofits _ say many parents are using the stickers as positive
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at 1997 highway accident rates lends the programs
moral authority, they say. Teenage drivers are nearly 50 percent
more likely to be in car accidents than the next most
accident-prone age group, according to the National Highway
Transportation Safety Board. They're also 32 percent more likely to
be involved in fatal crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever had to tell a parent their teen was killed in a
stupid car accident, it's all worth it,'' said Tom H. Deats, owner
of the nonprofit, 800-4MYTEEN, and a 26-year patrolman for the
Arlington, Texas, Police Department. ``I think parents are so busy
working they don't have time to take personal responsibility for
their kids. These stickers put more eyes on the kids. It helps
parents parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Deats, who was at the vanguard of the trend when he began his
company in 1994, now has 2,000 bumper stickers on cars from Georgia
to the state of Washington. Convinced that his company is saving
lives, Deats said he has sunk $40,000 into the venture to keep it
afloat. Along the way, he has persuaded 60 municipal court judges
across Texas to offer his bumper sticker program as an alternative
sentencing option for reckless teen drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Donaldson, president of the Vermont PTA, saw a few such
companies offering their services at the recent national PTA
convention in Chicago, including MyParentsCare.com and its
subsidiary, RatMeOut.com. She returned hoping that schools across
her state would promote the companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that anything that encourages more parent
involvement is a positive thing,'' she said. ``This breeds more
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a sense among parents who buy the stickers that they've
placed a governor on their children's driving, insurance companies
say they want empirical proof before they start slashing premiums
to those who slap on the stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these people are well-meaning and they truly want to
prevent teens from being in crashes, but there is nothing to
suggest these programs work,'' said Julie Rochman, a spokeswoman
for the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety. ``Kids think
they're invincible. Perhaps the threat of sanctions will do
something, but stack that up against peer pressure, and you
probably don't have much.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, many of America's truck fleets have
enrolled in vehicle monitoring programs, with results that have
certainly caught the attention of the insurance industry. As a
rule, companies that belong to such programs witness declines in
accident rates of about 20 percent, enough to win reduced premiums.
Most of the time, insurance companies themselves pay for companies
to enroll, said Joe Zingale, executive vice president of Driver's
Alert Inc. of Florida, the nation's largest fleet monitoring
company.
</P>
<P>
   But Zingale said he doubts the viability of the teen driver
monitoring programs. He should know. His company tried it in 1990,
and gave up soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``With teens, they rip the decal off, or they cover it up, and
the prank calls are crazy,'' Zingale said. ``You get a kid who
pulls into the high school parking lot with one of those decals on
his car, and you're telling me all his buddies aren't going to race
over to the pay phone to break his chops? Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Smith, who runs the Exeter, N.H.-based Parents Against
Speeding Teens, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at a similar program, but the phony phone call
factor really troubled us,'' said Smith, whose son, Jason, died in
an auto wreck at age 16. ``This issue is too important for that. We
don't want to cry wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   On top of such credibility problems, many of the for-profit
companies have failed because they have trouble finding repeat
customers _ teen drivers are teens for just so long, after all.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, even though the field of teen driver monitoring
only took off in the past few years, parents can have a difficult
time finding a company to serve them. Of the more than one dozen
companies with Web pages offering such services, more than half
lead to toll-free telephone numbers that have since been
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my wife and me had such an original idea when we
came up with this,'' said Mike Hill, president of the 2-year-old
877-SAF-RIDE. Hill said he works nights as a Wal-Mart supervisor to
make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're over $10,000 in the hole right now,'' Hill said. ``We
have to walk a tightrope between sending out a harsh message and
being a total jerk. You don't want to use scare tactics, but the
truth is, if you watch the news at night, it is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohner, a professor emeritus at the University of Connecticut's
School of Family Studies, said he's not surprised that such
businesses are cropping up at this point in US history. With
frightening stories in the media about school shootings, Internet
predators, and rampant drug use, parents are seeking ways of
feeling they're in control, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are perhaps over-aware these days,'' Rohner said. ``It
sounds like kids are going to hell in a handbasket and that they're
in grave danger everywhere they turn.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, even though the majority of parents in the
United States wield moderate discipline, many families might be
seduced by the bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no fan of Big Brother, but from my knowledge of the
American family, I don't see this trend as a sign that American
parenting is going off in the wrong direction,'' Rohner said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndsay Brown, 16, who still operates under her learner's
permit, said she's not nearly as resentful of the bumper sticker as
her brother was. In fact, she said, it has lent her driving
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only got one report so far, and it was someone saying I was
driving well,'' she said. ``When I get my license, my Mom said,
she'll let me take (the car) out more because she knows she can
trust me. It gives me more privileges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
