<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-RDP-ART-(TRIMS)-N     08-15 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC DELEGATES GATHER TO ADOPT THEIR PARTY PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a
version by Richard L. Berke. That version will be updated later
with quotes from Tuesday night's speeches.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After an emotional night in which President
Clinton offered a political farewell to the Democrats who have
gathered here for their national convention, delegates reconvened
Tuesday to proceed toward formally making Vice President Al Gore
the party's presidential candidate and new leader.
</P>
<P>
   The major order of business for the Democrats Tuesday was
adoption of the platform. The document puts the party in almost a
lockstep with the Republicans on issues like foreign policy,
military deployment and missile defense. But the platform veers
sharply from the rival party on abortion rights, gun control,
campaign finance legislation and laws aimed at extending rights for
gays.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton in his address on Monday night sought to emphasize the
differences between his party and the Republicans. He suggested
that putting a Republican in the White House could threaten the
nation's economic growth. And he criticized Republicans for
opposing the initiatives that he said had strengthened the economy
and helped balance the budget. Most specifically, Clinton ridiculed
Republicans for opposing his 1993 deficit reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It passed by a single vote in both houses,'' Clinton said.
``In a deadlocked Senate, Al Gore cast the tie-breaking vote. Now,
not a single Republican supported it. Here's what their leaders
said. Their leaders said our plan would increase the deficit, kill
jobs and give us a one-way ticket to a recession.''
</P>
<P>
   After pausing to savor the applause of the delegates, Clinton
smiled and added, ``Time has not been kind to their predictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Los Angeles early Tuesday morning, bound for
Michigan, where he was to meet Gore at a political rally in Monroe,
just outside Detroit, and complete the symbolic handing over of
control of the Democratic Party reins.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The prime-time address Monday was a delicate balancing act for
Clinton. He wanted to rally the delegates and the nation's
enthusiasm over the achievements of his administration in the last
year, but at the same time not let his oratorical skills overshadow
Gore. And while Clinton wanted to promote his chosen successor's
talents and link Gore's policies to his own accomplishments, he
also had to give the vice president his political freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton touted Gore as ``one strong leader'' and portrayed him
as being at the center of the policy debates and crusades the
administration has pursued, including welfare reform, environmental
protection and job development for the urban and rural poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anybody else I've known in public life, Al Gore
understands the future and how sweeping changes and scientific
breakthroughs will affect ordinary Americans' lives,'' Clinton
said. ``And I think we need somebody in the White House at the dawn
of the 21st century who really understands the future.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Any question of whether Gore would be the successor to Clinton
as the party's new leader was settled last winter when the vice
president ran up a string of unbroken primary victories against
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But delegates are waiting to see how fully Gore can assume
Clinton's role, not only as the leader on policy matters but also
as the emotional heart of the party. Clinton has long been able to
connect with his supporters in a way Gore has struggled to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will arrive here on Wednesday, the same day that the
convention will conduct the largely ceremonial roll call vote that
will officially make him the Democratic Party's presidential
standard-bearer. The vice president is expected to receive the
backing of all of the 4,339 Democratic delegates here, but it will
be the 68 delegates from his home state of Tennessee who will cast
the votes that put him over the 2,170 he needs to win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will deliver his acceptance speech on Thursday night,
ending the convention. His running mate, Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman,
arrived here Tuesday morning and is to make his acceptance speech
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention opened on Monday to speeches,
pageantry and protests.
</P>
<P>
   Just about the time Clinton was finishing his speech inside the
Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles on Monday night, police
officers were using pepper spray, rubber bullets and officers on
horseback to drive away thousands of protesters on the streets just
outside the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began after a concert that featured the hard-rock
protest band Rage Against The Machine that was attended by about
7,000 people in the area set aside for protests.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The concert ended without incident, but police commanders said
that as the crowd dispersed, at least several hundred protesters
began throwing stones and bottles at police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates and journalists leaving the convention center after
the scheduled events found themselves blocked in by the police
action.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers accused the police of overreacting. But at a
news conference in the Staples Center early Tuesday morning,
Commander David Kalish of the Los Angeles Police Department
defended the police action and said that officers are in ``almost a
no-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some will view it as we waited too long,'' he said, ``some
will view it as moving too quickly.'' But, Kalish continued,
``Today, tomorrow or the next day, or the next day, or the next
week, our response will be exactly the same.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that 10 people had been arrested, but
there were no reports of serious injuries or of major vandalism.
Prior to the disturbance on Monday night, 28 people were arrested,
officials said. On Tuesday morning, the area around the Staples
Center was quiet, without any major protests or confrontations with
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Democrats will feature a list of speakers that
represent the party's traditional base. Gore faces a challenge from
the left in the general election by Ralph Nader, the consumer
advocate. And Gore wants to show the liberal wing of the party that
he has not abandoned them by giving speaking time to the Rev. Jesse
Jackson; Gerald McEntee, the president of the American Federation
of State County, and Municipal Employees; and Kate Michelman, the
president of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, known as NARAL.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats will also seek to engage long-time liberal
supporters with a dose of party nostalgia. In the lead up to the
keynote address Tuesday evening from Rep. Harold Ford Jr. of
Tennessee, the delegates will hear from Bradley and from two
members of the Kennedy clan: Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts and Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the daughter of the
late President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Democrats held their national convention in
Los Angeles, John F. Kennedy received the presidential nomination,
and there has been a concerted effort this week to link Gore to
that legacy. One of the more popular souvenirs being sold here is a
button bearing pictures of both Gore and President Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
