<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2349 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIMMING-HNS &LR;      08-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIMMING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SECOND TIME'S A CHARM FOR SWIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ A friend told Kristy Kowal to puff out her
cheeks, wide enough so he could see, while she waited behind the
starting blocks for the 200-meter breaststroke at the U.S. Olympic
Trials. A few nights before, waiting for the 100 breaststroke, she
had looked as if she couldn't breathe. And everyone knew how that
had worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal, the defending world champion in the 100, had taken third
by a hundredth of a second, touched out by the exuberant Staciana
Stitts from the University of California at Berkeley. Only the top
two finishers go to Sydney. Third place means watching on
television.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal knew all too well what third place meant. Four years
earlier, the same thing had happened. She had been touched out and
aced out.
</P>
<P>
   Now came the 200, her last chance. She should have been tighter
than a childproof cap. But Kowal's friend was right. She always
swims best when she lets loose, dances around before a race,
grooves to some tunes, smiles at the crowd. On Monday, she waved to
people in the stands, looking as if she were about to host a party.
</P>
<P>
   About three minutes later, that's exactly what she was doing.
Kowal won the race, made the Olympic team and set the American
record. All of a sudden, a congregation formed in her lane, a bunch
of young women bobbing, hugging, smiling, crying. The 200
breaststroke had become the feel-good race of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I almost started crying when I was swimming into the
wall,'' Kowal said.
</P>
<P>
   Stitts swam over to Kowal's lane immediately to offer
congratulations, sprinting about as fast as she did during the
race. Stitts finished sixth in the 200, out of the hunt, and she
didn't seem to care a bit. She had her Olympic berth in the 100,
and she desperately wanted the woman she beat to join her in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``She deserves to go,'' Stitts said. ``You know, the 100 was so
close, it could have gone either way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stitts also enveloped the second-place finisher, Amanda Beard,
in her arms. Before the race, Stitts shared a set of earphones with
Beard in the ready room, trying to get her motivated with some rap
music. Like Kowal, Beard had heavy sentiment on her side.
</P>
<P>
   Beard had already been to the Olympics, as a 14-year-old in
1996. She won two individual silvers, a relay gold and countless
hearts. With her teddy bear and her big, round eyes, she was
thoroughly endearing.
</P>
<P>
   She went home from Atlanta and became a full-fledged teenager,
piercing her tongue, plus various spots on her earlobe. She grew up
physically, too, sprouting six inches and adding about 25 pounds.
In any other stroke, her new body could have been an advantage. But
the breaststroke is swimming's answer to gymnastics, cruelly
discriminating against the mature female form.
</P>
<P>
   In the finals Monday, only two of the competitors topped 18.
There are exceptions, including 26-year-old world-record holder
Penny Heyns of South Africa. But as one wag once put: ``You can't
have breasts and swim the breaststroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, after Atlanta, Beard slumped. She might have been
able to handle the biological changes, but she couldn't overcome a
profound case of self-consciousness. Every time she got up on the
blocks, she could feel the audience's scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it was mental,'' she said. ``It was hard to get into
the pool and swim up to people's expectations, or what I thought
were their expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   In another event, she might have been able to muscle her way
through. Not in the breaststroke. More than any other stroke, it is
like hitting a baseball. Too much effort spoils the result.
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200 the night before, Ed Moses, the undisputed
favorite, went out too fast, lost his stroke and took fourth.
Before the meet, he bleached his hair blonde and put in gold
earrings to declare his intentions. If he hadn't won the 100, he
could have been the great heartbreak of these Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal faced the same predicament. At 21, she couldn't count on
any more chances. In the four years between 14 and 18, Beard hadn't
improved. She had added a second to her time. Kowal, tall and
angular, had stayed at her peak far longer than average.
</P>
<P>
   She won in 2 minutes, 24.75 seconds, the seventh-fastest time
ever. Five of the six best times belong to Heyns. Before Monday
night, the Americans appeared to have no chance of knocking her off
in Sydney. Kowal changed that on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   She and Beard emerged from the pool together, then gasped their
way through interviews with NBC. Beard, her body shaking, looked as
endearing as she had in Atlanta, six inches and untold piercings
ago. Back then she told reporters that she loved her silver medals,
that she didn't need to win gold to be happy. She was the perfect
antidote to Nike's triumph-or-disgrace ad campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   She said she appreciated making the Olympics this time more than
she had in '96. It's the struggle that makes it all worthwhile. ``I
can't breathe,'' Beard said, fanning her face happily, unable to
continue the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal must have understood. The Olympic Trials had taken all the
air out of her before. She got it back just in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1505EDT &QL; 
