<SLUG> BC-SF-REAL-ESTATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEVELOPER HAS EYES ON KEY SAN FRANCISCO PROPERTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GERALD D. ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly empty and derelict, two undeveloped sites
in the heart of San Francisco's Financial District have posed a
quandary for some two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with near Gold Rush conditions prevailing in a real estate
market that promises an owner sky-high rental profits, the quandary
shows signs of easing.
</P>
<P>
   Shorenstein Co. President Douglas Shorenstein disclosed that the
company founded by his father, real estate titan Walter
Shorenstein, has filed applications to build office structures on
both sites _ the only two undeveloped plots in this historic square
mile.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans a five-story structure at Pine and Kearny
streets, only a few feet higher than the neighboring St. Mary's
Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   It also proposes a 19-story office tower at 350 Bush St., which
incorporates the now-shabby, 77-year-old San Francisco Mining
Exchange Building (a city landmark) as a galleria of shops and
restaurants as well as entry to the office tower.
</P>
<P>
   In the Financial District, two more environmentally sensitive
sites scarcely exist.
</P>
<P>
   The first, 500 Pine St., is located across Kearny from the
Shorenstein Co.-owned Bank of America Tower. Walter Shorenstein
proposed a 14-story high-rise there in the late 1970s that would
have cast a shadow on tiny St. Mary's Square Park, which with
Portsmouth Square are Chinatown's only parks.
</P>
<P>
   When that aroused fierce opposition, Shorenstein offered to
landscape the roof of adjacent St. Mary's Square Garage to offset
the shadow and add to the park, but the administration of
then-Mayor Dianne Feinstein (now a U.S. senator) rejected that
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The second site, a block away, is co-owned by the Shorenstein
Co. with the Swig Estate of Fairmont Hotel fame. There, too, a
previously proposed 27-story tower would have demolished the
Greco-Roman styled Mining Exchange and blocked sunlight from St.
Mary's Square.
</P>
<P>
   Both locations have historic connotations.
</P>
<P>
   The Pine-Kearny site once held the Kong Chow Temple until its
elders sold the location to Shorenstein.
</P>
<P>
   And reviving proposals for both recalls two of the hottest land
use battles in the city's late 20th century history _ battles so
bitter that they triggered historic changes in San Francisco land
use restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   It was after these proposals failed that voters subsequently
passed Proposition K, the park shadow initiative that bans new
construction from blocking sunlight from public open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Further, at urging of the Landmarks Preservation Advisory Board
and the Planning Commission, the Board of Supervisors later
declared the Mining Exchange an official city landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Feinstein-appointed Planning Commission and
the elected Board of Supervisors of that era passed a new Downtown
Plan, requiring that more than 250 architecturally and historically
significant buildings, including the Mining Exchange, be preserved
in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Walter Shorenstein withdrew both high-rise
proposals, leaving both locations much as they appear today.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Doug Shorenstein and Vice President Thomas W. Hart, both
soft-spoken and diplomatic, both aware of their valuable but fallow
hunks of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   As Hart put it, ``The hot market prompted us to take a serious
look at what can be done. If we're ever going to do it (build), we
feel now is the time,'' he added, referring to current rents.
</P>
<P>
   As to why the sites have been left empty and neglected for
years, Doug Shorenstein said, ``The bottom line was, the market was
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company's latest office building proposals face zoning
restrictions not unlike those that forced the older Shorenstein to
cancel his plans in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's Square, which has long been shadowed by an old
Pacific Telephone building to its south, still must be protected
from further sunlight blockage. And the Mining Exchange must be
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can any new tower on Bush Street be allowed to block
daylight from its neighbor, the historic Russ Building. That
building is owned, incidentally, by Shorenstein's partners on the
proposed Bush Street project, the Swig family.
</P>
<P>
   And the revised Bush Street project entails demolition of the
now-closed Temple Hotel, where at least 17 long-term residents were
evicted last November.
</P>
<P>
   With guidance from architect Jeffrey Heller, who studies
downtown zoning restrictions the way fishermen study tides and
currents, the developers are making a new stab at building, in the
hope that their latest proposals can overcome the same sticky
issues that doomed their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Heller insists the 350 Bush St. proposal can overcome any
questions about shadows on St. Mary's Square because any shadow
would be ``a minor one.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Shorenstein proposes to add some 4,500 square feet to the
little park by landscaping the roof of the company's new five-story
building, and deeding the roof to the city as new public space.
</P>
<P>
   Before the city grants Shorenstein permission to build, the
company must undergo several hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   An environmental impact report will probably be required.
</P>
<P>
   The Landmarks Preservation Advisory Board must approve
alterations to the landmark Mining Exchange; the Recreation and
Park Commission, the means of compensating for new shadows on St.
Mary's Square Park; and the Planning Commission for the
demolitions, design of the two new buildings and decisions to grant
them allotments from annual limits of square footage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
