r d BC-SPAGO0816-COX     08-15 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAGO0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tinseltown's hottest restaurant cool enough to make Ohio
visitors feel welcome
 &HT;    By D.L. Stewart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ In my fantasies, I am walking into
Spago, the celebrity restaurant, and a smiling host says, ``Mr.
Stewart of Dayton, Ohio. But of course. Your table is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In my expectations, I am walking into Spago, the celebrity
restaurant, and a snickering host says: ``Stewart? Ohio? Give me a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Spago is not the most expensive restaurant in the country.
Dinner at Ducasse in New York City, Charlie Trotter's in Chicago or
Ginza Sushiko, right around the corner here in Beverly Hills on
Rodeo Drive, would cost at least twice as much. And it does not
have the fanciest food. Gary Danko's, Mary Elaine's, Seeger's and
plenty of other restaurants you probably never heard of all have
more Mobil Guide stars.
</P>
<P>
   But Spago arguably is the most famous restaurant in America. It
is this generation's version of 21, the Stork Club and the Brown
Derby. A restaurant known not just for what it serves, but whom it
serves. Its reputation and its success are inextricably linked with
movie stars and millionaires. No report on Academy Awards night is
complete without listing who scored a table at Spago. No edition of
In Style magazine would go to press without at least one Spago
name-dropping article.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads me to suspect that my reception will range somewhere
between desultory and ``fuggedaboutit.''
</P>
<P>
   So when we walk in and a smiling hostess immediately leads us to
a table in the middle of the restaurant, I figure there can only be
one explanation: We are at the wrong Spago.
</P>
<P>
   There are, in fact, two of them in Los Angeles. The original
opened in 1982 in West Hollywood. Since then, owner-chef Wolfgang
Puck and his wife, Barbara Lazaroff, have opened Spagos in Chicago,
Las Vegas, Palo Alto and Tokyo. Plus a string of other restaurants
in just about any location where a large number of people can
pronounce ``sommelier.'' Not to mention countless Wolfgang Puck
Cafes and other Spago Lites.
</P>
<P>
   But the flagship of the food fleet is in Beverly Hil Long before
our senses have had a chance to be seduced, special events manager
Franklin Vermillion is at our table with a war
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
