<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MISSION-THEFTS-HNS &LR;      08-15 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSION-THEFTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSION-THEFTS,2TAKES &HT;    
 &HT;    VALUABLE ARTIFACTS STOLEN FROM SAN ANTONIO MISSIONS
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JAMES KIMBERLY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    SAN ANTONIO _ Once the protectors of Franciscan missionaries and
<TEXT>
Coahuiltecan Indians, it is the Spanish missions here that now need
protecting.
<P>
   Someone is breaking into mission sanctuaries and stealing
valuable religious artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The crimes have befuddled police investigators and wrenched
hearts in San Antonio, where the archdiocese estimates nearly half
of the city's 1 million residents are Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us cried about it. It's sad,'' said Beatrice Alanis,
who has lived next to Mission San Juan Capistrano for 45 years and
is a member of the parish that still worships there. ``We're still
in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission San Juan Capistrano was the scene of the first burglary,
which occurred on June 25. Someone entered the sanctuary during the
middle of the day when the mission was open for tourists and pried
from the altar four 19th-century paintings of Juan Diego's vision
of Our Lady of Guadalupe.
</P>
<P>
   Burglars returned to the mission two weeks ago and broke in
sometime after it closed at 5 p.m. The thieves carted off three
18th-century hand-carved wooden statues of Saint Francis of Assisi,
Saint Joseph and Saint Juan Capistrano, the mission's namesake. Art
dealers said the pieces could be worth tens of thousands of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In between the two crimes, the nearby Mission Concepcion was
twice burglarized. First, a wood carving of the Virgin Mary was
stolen. Then, a glass display case was smashed and an incense
burner and a Latin sacramental book, both antiques, were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of took us by surprise,'' admits David Castilleja,
chief financial officer for the Archdiocese of San Antonio. ``To
some extent, it is almost sacrilege if you take something from the
church. God help the people who did this.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who did this remain a mystery, as do their motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can speculate all day long on whether or not there
is anything to indicate there is one particular motive,'' said Sgt.
Gabriel Trevino, director of the public information office for the
San Antonio police. ``I don't know if there is.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio police have been actively investigating since the
first burglary was reported June 30, Trevino said. There are no
suspects, Trevino said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new,'' he said. The investigation ``is still
ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 4, officers discovered a pedestal from one of the stolen
statues in the bathroom of the Mission Espada. The pedestal might
provide a valuable clue that will help detectives solve the case.
It also might be an indication that the thieves were casing another
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The burglaries have caught the attention of the FBI. Special
Agent Darren Holmes, public information officer in the bureau's San
Antonio office, said federal agents are reviewing the case and are
considering whether to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   The burglaries have been strikes not only against the Catholic
church but also the state. The five Spanish missions along the
23-mile Mission Trail are as central to the identity of San Antonio
as the Gateway Arch is to St. Louis and the Golden Gate Bridge to
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2 million people a year visit the city's most famous
mission: Mission San Antonio de Valero, more commonly referred to
as the Alamo. About half that many visit the city's other four
missions each year: Mission San Jose, Mission San Juan, Mission
Espada and Mission Concepcion.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden among heavy woods and sparsely populated neighborhoods of
shotgun shacks, Mission San Juan Capistrano and Mission Concepcion
are less popular than other mission sites. Their remote locations
and infrequent visitors probably provided burglars ample
opportunity to plan and carry out their attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to be a carefully orchestrated thing,'' said the
Rev. James Galvin, an Irishman who celebrates Masses at San Juan
Capistrano in English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent break-in seemed particularly well-planned. The
thieves drilled holes through the wooden church doors and inserted
something to dislodge the wooden slats that were supposed to
reinforce the locks. The burglars also knew the door was bolted at
the top and bottom and used a pry bar to attack both locks, Galvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the church, tire tracks indicate the thieves used a dolly
to remove the ornate wooden statues and their pedestals from their
perches at the front of the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The missions have proved more difficult to secure than other
Catholic churches, Galvin said, because of their status as historic
landmarks. The National Parks Service controls the mission grounds
and must be consulted before any changes are made to the
buildings &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Because the missions are in national parks, San Antonio park
rangers do not police them. The National Park Service only posts
rangers there from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. There is no admission to the
parks and tourists are allowed to come and go from the missions and
other buildings as they please. A sole ranger is responsible for
supervising the park grounds and interpreting for Spanish-speaking
visitors. The missions are locked when the parks are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the burglaries, the archdiocese has taken steps to improve
security. Its officials met this week with the National Park
Service to discuss ways to better safeguard the missions.
</P>
<P>
   The missions are rich pieces of Texas history. Designed by
Franciscan missionaries, they were built by bands of South Texas
Indians collectively known as Coahuiltecans. Spain financed their
construction to protect its claim to land in the New World and to
proselytize Native American souls to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The reverence bestowed on the missions both by San Antonians _
Christian and secular _ probably lured the church into a false
sense of security, the Rev. Galvin admitted. Also, it appears the
church might not have been aware of the growing popularity of
Spanish Colonial Art in the United States and of how valuable the
statues were as art pieces called santos.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
