<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-CONVENTION-PAYOFF-NEW     08-15 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-PAYOFF-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL CONVENTIONS PROVE MIXED ECONOMIC BLESSING FOR HOST
CITIES
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By BRUCE ALPERT  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In the city of movie stars, leasing limousines is
always a big business.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Democratic National Convention, Brett Ohira of
Paramount Limousine said he still has some limousines available and
is ready to ``make a deal'' to get more convention business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have some available this week, and I'm
disappointed,'' he said. ``I kind of thought this would be as big
as the Oscars.''
</P>
<P>
   The major party political conventions still rank among the
country's biggest meetings in terms of attendance, but they may be
losing some of their luster in terms of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials had projected that the convention, which
opened Monday in the city's spanking new Staples Center, would fill
94,500 room-nights at area hotels. But now they concede the number
is likely to be closer to 70,000.
</P>
<P>
   And as in Philadelphia, which hosted the Republican National
Convention two weeks ago, the cost of hosting 15,000 journalists
and 20,000 delegates and visitors has escalated -- largely because
the party events are now attracting larger and more militant
protest demonstrations that require added security.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the city said it has put the entire police force
on 12-hour shifts, and brought in officers from the California
Highway Patrol and other police jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials won't speak on the record but concede
privately that they fear some cities might be reluctant to bid for
the party's 2004 convention. Besides the higher costs and fears of
violent demonstrations, the networks are now covering fewer hours
of the actual convention than ever before -- prompting speculation
that the four-day events might be condensed into two or three days
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans, which hosted the Republican National Convention in
1988 and bid unsuccessfully for the Democratic and Republican
conventions in 1992, 1996 and 2000, is one city that won't be
scared away, said Mayor Marc Morial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll always be interested in bidding for the conventions
because it is not just the money and hotel rooms, it is also the
visibility it gives your city and the fact that you have important
opinion leaders who come to your city,'' Morial said.
</P>
<P>
   William Raabe, a business professor at Sanford University in
Birmingham, Ala., said the big party conventions make sense for
some cities but not others. Even if the conventions are ``money
losers,'' cities like Chicago, which hosted a successful Democratic
convention in 1996 -- a marked contrast to its bloody Democratic
convention in 1968 -- and Philadelphia, with the 2000 GOP
convention, can get a big public relations boost.
</P>
<P>
   A case also could be made for the benefits to Southern cities
like New Orleans because the conventions are scheduled in the
summer when warm weather generally keeps hotel occupancy rates
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in terms of New York or Los Angeles, I have to think a lot
of the Chamber of Commerce types are saying, `Why bother?''' Raabe
said. ``They'd rather have a vacationer from Michigan who is likely
to spend more money than a delegate from Montana. For one,
vacationers and even delegates to other conventions don't have all
these corporate suites and functions thrown by Silicon Valley, oil
drillers and steel companies. They get bigger and bigger every
year, in effect soft money for delegates, which means that the area
restaurants tend not to benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, officials projected that the convention would
generate $132 million in revenue. But some local merchants and
business owners said the estimate seems inflated.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a good lunch business today, but it seems to be
our regular customers, not delegates,'' said Jeff Kavin, manager of
Greenblatt's Deli in Hollywood. ``I think these delegates know
deli, but they might not be able to get away from all their
receptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Donnelly, who has driven a cab in Los Angeles for 15
years, said Sunday was ``a great day'' because many drivers took
the day off, and early convention visitors didn't have access to
the chartered buses rented by the Los Angeles host committee to
shepherd delegates around for official convention events.
</P>
<P>
   ``But today, I can't get many fares at all because many of the
downtown streets are blocked for security and the protest
demonstrations and the delegates are all being chauffeured around
town in buses,'' Donnelly said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia convention officials say they figure they spent $50
million in cash and contributed services for the GOP convention. It
will take another 60 days to complete a study on how much the GOP
delegates and their guests spent during the four-day event, said
Karen Dougherty Buchholz, president of Philadelphia 2000, the host
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no matter how that turns out, I have to tell you that
we're very pleased with how everything came out,'' she said. ``The
audience that came to our city and region left with a great
impression and it is advertising that you just can't pay for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1541EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0174 </DOCNO>
