<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MISSION-THEFTS     08-15 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSION-THEFTS,2ND </SLUG>
 TAKE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MISSION-THEFTS,2nd Take
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO: called ``santos.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew (the pieces) were special and very old,'' the Rev.
Galvin said. ``I thought that nobody would even think of stealing
them because where would they sell them?''
</P>
<P>
   But art dealers know the market for santos and other Spanish
Colonial art is booming.
</P>
<P>
   For years, collectors considered the pieces inferior to the
European sculptures. And Europeans still have no interest in the
works of 17th-and 18th-century Mexican artisans known as
``santeros &UR; ''  &LR; _ artists who makes saints. But Americans have grown
to appreciate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago you could get an excellent piece for $2,000,
$3,000 that piece now is probably $40,000,'' said Marianne
Lixie-Gray, proprietor of Que Milagro Ethnic Art Gallery in
Houston. ``The prices are just climbing, climbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Siegfried is the chief conservator of the Art
Conservation Laboratory in San Antonio. Siegfried restored the
statue of Saint Francis of Assisi in 1994 and had talked with the
archdiocese about working on the others.
</P>
<P>
   The statues were high quality pieces, carved in Mexico during
the middle 1700s, she said. They were carved in meticulous detail
in the baroque style and some were inlaid with 23-karat gold, she
said. The faces and hands of the wooden statues were painted and
polished to such a sheen they appeared to be porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it, they are very valuable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While the statues and paintings might have a high market value,
collecting the money might be difficult unless the burglars already
had an unscrupulous &UR;  &LR; art collector lined up as a buyer, Siegfried
said.
</P>
<P>
   The market for santos is fed primarily by priests who sell
paintings or statues to raise money for their churches. But thefts
occur frequently, said Ray Balinskas, who operates an import
business in Houston. Most often, thieves steal santos from Mexican
churches and bring them to the United States to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens from time to time. For someone who wants an art
object, it doesn't matter if it is a church or a home. The church
is probably the easiest place to steal from,'' Balinskas said.
</P>
<P>
   Reputable brokers will push for details from someone selling a
piece to determine whether it is stolen. Also, news of stolen art
spreads rapidly among dealers, Balinskas said.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried fears the pieces will disappear in a private
collection if word about the statues is not spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they will disappear in some of our larger cities and
in some of our nice homes,'' Siegfried said. ``It's important that
people realize when they see something in somebody's house they
realize, `Uh oh. That could be one of them.'''
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
