<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-OHIO-GARDEN-ART-2TAKE     08-15 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-GARDEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE FIELDWORKERS WEAR LAB COATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURON, Ohio _ A group of chefs from the Ritz-Carlton hotel chain
were sitting on a flatbed pulled by a 1964 John Deere tractor. It
plodded along the field, grumbling the entire way. Off in the
distance, a woman was crouched over a row of herbs with a crisp
white lab coat on her back and a wicker basket at her side. She was
harvesting with scissors.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs, who had come from Washington, D.C., California and
Cleveland, sat in silence, their heads wagging as they took in the
spectacle before them: rows of low bushes, silvery like salmon
skin; delicate pine-green plants; loud-pink flowers; leafy herbs.
The farmer driving the tractor didn't say a word and didn't need
to. This was not like any other farm they had seen before or would
ever see again.
</P>
<P>
   The herbs the woman was harvesting were just one of more than
600 plant varieties on the 70-acre farm. In less than 24 hours
those herbs, meticulously cleaned and gathered in bouquets _ clean,
vibrant, impossibly perfect ones _ would be shipped overnight to
one of the country's top kitchens. For years, Charlie Trotter has
been buying from this farm. More recently, Jean-Georges
Vongerichten and Alain Ducasse have begun ordering. Even Thomas
Keller, whose restaurant rests in what many consider to be
America's fertile crescent, the Napa Valley, orders vegetables from
here.
</P>
<P>
   But this small, fecund plot, called the Chef's Garden, resists
that kind of romance. It's on a flat, humid plain about an hour
west of Cleveland. Here, wedged between vast farms carpeted with
soybeans, corn and wheat, is an extraordinary collection of
culinary delicacies: Mexican tarragon, Vietnamese houttuinia (looks
like basil, tastes like fish sauce), ginger shoots, New Zealand
spinach, purple beans, micro red shiso and melons so sweet you
could cry.
</P>
<P>
   For chefs around the country, this small farm has become their
laboratory, their research and development center and, often, their
trump card. Many farms that sell at the Greenmarkets in New York
City work with chefs to develop new crops and to revive old ones.
But none in upstate New York, or around the country, do it on the
scale that the Chef's Garden does.
</P>
<P>
   Every single sprout that emerges from the farm's rich lake-bed
soil is there for a restaurant. And every one is grown with such
scientific precision and artistic temperament that what comes from
it is something a home cook, even one with a garden out back, will
never see.
</P>
<P>
   When Ducasse calls in an order for 20 pounds of one-inch round
turnips, the farm does not check to see if enough have been
harvested. A team heads out to the field and picks through rows of
turnips, sifting out just the one-inch round ones.
</P>
<P>
   When Douglas Rodriguez, the chef at Chicama, came back from Peru
with a package of seeds for huacaty (a black mint that is as
important to Peruvian cooking as basil is to Italian cuisine) and
culantro (a flat-leaf form of cilantro), he sent them to the Chef's
Garden to have them cultivated. When Andrew Carmellini, the chef at
Cafe Boulud, went to Alsace last year and had a salad of yellow
dandelion greens, he asked the Chef's Garden if it could figure out
how to grow them. (It did.)
</P>
<P>
   Along with 56 varieties of pepper, 11 kinds of melon, 65 of
tomatoes, 27 of lettuce and 16 of eggplant, the farm is developing
varieties of lettuce from Hungary never before commercially grown
in the United States, as well as a blanched mint and a horseradish
shoot that is more gentle than the root itself. And with a moderate
climate and a number of greenhouses, it is harvesting year round.
</P>
<P>
   Without the farm's produce, Rodriguez's fluke ceviche would lack
its beguiling herbal aroma. The Ecuadorean shrimp at Cello would
not have the peppery snap of micro watercress in the first few
bites. And the roasted lupo di mare on braised celery at Felidia
would not have the gentle fresh flavor of chopped micro celery and
wiry garlic roots.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the location is unlikely, so are the farmers.
``We're just a bunch of dumb old farmers,'' says Bob Jones, who
runs the business with his sons, Bobby and Lee. Very few dumb old
farmers, however, have classical music and sharp advertising on
their phone system and refer to their fieldworkers as team members,
let alone do business with Charlie Trotter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chefs really run our business,'' Bob Jones said. ``If we don't
grow it, we try to find it and learn how to grow it.'' Precisely
the way the chefs want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pickers need to know that a chef doesn't like flowers on the
thyme but that another chef appreciates the bud,'' Lee Jones said.
In packing miniature heads of curly red leaf lettuce, a team member
washes and trims them one by one, so they are pristine and
flawless. They are then spun dry, packed in a cushioned container
and placed in a padded box. Ice packs are added if the weather at
the destination warrants it.
</P>
<P>
   The Joneses didn't always farm this way. Two decades ago, they
ran just another commercial farm, growing cabbage, sweet corn,
peppers and soybeans on 1,500 acres. In July 1980, all that
changed. What appeared to be a heavy rainstorm approaching out of
the northwest turned out to be hail _ hail the size of quarters. It
wiped out their entire crop, and ultimately their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost everything,'' Lee Jones said. ``We moved out of our
home. They sold my mother's car. We lost the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually they started over, but this time with just five
acres. They grew vegetables _ zucchini, tomatoes, cantaloupes,
beans _ but this time sold them at the farmers' market in
Cleveland. In the first few years, they often had to borrow money
for gas from their neighbors just so they could get to the market,
and they painted the expired license plates on their market truck
with mud so they wouldn't be pulled over.
</P>
<P>
   At the market, Iris Bailin, then a chef at Prescott Ball &AMP;
Turben, a brokerage firm in Cleveland, became a regular customer.
One day she asked Lee Jones if he would sell zucchini blossoms. ``I
laughed,'' he said. ``I said, `Ma'am, that isn't how you eat
zucchini _ you eat the bulb, not the flower.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Bailin was persistent and after weeks of her requests, Jones
finally took a bunch to her at the market.
</P>
<P>
   Bailin kept buying. And so did many of her chef friends, whom
she told about the Joneses' produce. Pretty soon, half their
business was with chefs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Bob, Bobby and Lee held a family vote to decide whether
they should continue going to the market or try to make a living
selling only to chefs. Lee Jones was adamantly opposed to such a
risk. But he was outvoted.
</P>
<P>
   Their farm has since grown to 70 acres, and they now have 65
employees. The family that owns the farm surrounding theirs has
more than 3,000 acres and only a few people working the land, a
ratio that is about average for a profitable farm today. ``They
think we're nuts,'' Lee Jones said. ``We are, but we're very
committed nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   What made their reputation nationally _ and gave them a weekly
client base of over 200 restaurants _ was the relationship they
developed with Trotter six years ago. Trotter, convinced that
mesclun was passe, called to see if the Joneses could grow
something different, perhaps a mixture of greens like mesclun, but
much smaller. ``They came with their clipboards and tested and
tasted,'' Lee Jones said of Trotter and his cooks. With their
suggestions, microgreens were born. They are now the farm's largest
selling crop.
</P>
<P>
   The old market truck, with dancing vegetables painted on its
sides, is still around. It sits on the farm, bent and rusted, like
an ancient ruin. Around it a cluster of greenhouses has sprung up,
along with a collection of buildings _ offices, packing rooms,
garages _ that is soon to be the world's most complex maze.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, it is like a beehive buzzing with bees. There
are sales representatives and accountants in the offices, packers
out back, maintenance workers, men welding and a group of young
farmers, a number of them interns from Russia, Bulgaria, Slovakia
and Romania, running the greenhouses where the microgreens are
grown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Jones charts out the 2,800 plantings each year and works
with the field crews. Lee Jones handles the chefs. Bob Jones, a
round man with a face like an old apple, is the man behind the
curtain, orchestrating it all. ``He's part scientist, he's part
doctor and he's a great grower, and he reads and reads and reads,''
Lee Jones said. Not just farming manuals, but at least 10
management books a month.
</P>
<P>
   When they want to try something new, they turn to him. ``A lot
of our information,'' Bob Jones said, ``a lot of our help comes
from books about farming 100 years ago. They relate better to our
farm today.'' When a former intern from Hungary sent them four
lettuce seeds, they used old techniques of crop isolation and seed
selection to increase the yield.
</P>
<P>
   They use old tractors, which they say are more gentle on the
soil, and dated ways of creating microclimates. Being just a few
miles from Lake Erie, they already enjoy a moist coastal climate,
but by planting corn around their fields and rye between rows as
natural wind barriers, they have been able to raise the average
field temperatures by five to seven degrees. As a result, though
the farm is nestled in Ohio, it has a growing season identical to
that of Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bob Jones found a way to force a horseradish root to
grow shoots by planting it deep in soil. The shoots, which grow out
the sides of the root, have the sheen of corn silk and the texture
of a water chestnut. They taste like horseradish without the bite.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that success, the Joneses did the same with ginger
roots. Hops shoots are next. Last year, when they were
transplanting young garlic, they noticed that a dense cluster of
long tender roots had formed. They washed and tasted them. They
were like a cross between garlic and scallion, with the thickness
of a chive. Now, Ducasse buys the young plant _ greens, cloves and
roots _ and uses the whole thing like a scallion with its root
attached.
</P>
<P>
   Blanched popcorn shoots have also gone over well, so next year
they are going to try blanching mint and pea shoots. An effort to
grow an asparagus fern _ the frail plant that grows after the
asparagus is finished _ has just begun. So far, it's turned up a
small, needly plant that is chewy but sweet with a faint asparagus
flavor and a dash of bitterness. They have done their own tasting,
but the real test lies with the chefs to whom they will send the
fern for comment. (The Joneses are not tossing microgreens and
vinaigrette for dinner. They eat mainstream vegetables like
carrots, tomatoes and corn.)
</P>
<P>
   This back-and-forth relationship with chefs has accounted
largely for their success. When Rodriguez gave some of his Peruvian
seeds to farms in upstate New York, the farmers didn't follow
through. The Joneses, however, dedicated most of a row to his herbs
and another to a crop of special peppers, which they sell to him
several times a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Joneses will also grow something for a single occasion. If a
chef knows he has a large party two months hence and he wants micro
curly cress for one dish, the Joneses will grow a special crop just
for the party.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many of the chefs who buy from them visit regularly to see
what is growing, to talk about new ideas, to look for inspiration.
The day after the Ritz-Carlton chefs toured the farm, Carmellini,
from Cafe Boulud, stopped by for his annual visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to supply restaurants with their weekly
produce,'' Bob Jones said. ``We want to be there to give them
something that's going to set a dish apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for top restaurants, it's expensive. A 5-by-6-inch plastic
container of microgreens, for instance, is $12 to $26 plus
shipping. Fifty flowerettes of basil tops are $12 to $17.50,
depending on the variety. Cantaloupes average $6 apiece. That's
why, when Carmellini was going around, though he tasted and smelled
everything in sight, he was interested in just a few items. For
certain vegetables, like white asparagus, Carmellini buys as much
as possible when it's in season. But generally, he orders from
Chef's Garden just three or four times a month.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during his visit, Lee Jones took him to the end of
a row where a group of black buckets were overturned. ``Here's an
experiment that flopped,'' Jones said, lifting a bucket. Beneath
was a tight bouquet of white pointy leaves, sad and limp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it!'' Carmellini exclaimed. It was the blanched
dandelion greens he had tasted in Alsace and asked the Joneses to
grow. Weak as they looked, they tasted right. The leaves were
bitter like green dandelion, but less aggressive, and as tender as
a sprout.
</P>
<P>
   Almost giddily, they exchanged ideas on how to improve the
growing method and get the greens going in time for the winter
menu.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Carmellini would stick with his short list of
favorites: New Zealand spinach, heirloom tomatoes, baby basils and
strong, earthy hickory nuts grown by a neighbor of the Joneses. He
uses the hickory nuts with skate sauteed in beurre noisette and
haricots verts. If price were no object, Carmellini said, he would
buy the baby haricots verts from the Joneses, too.
</P>
<P>
   But at $45 a pound, they seemed too indulgent a flourish, even
for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Carmellini will be serving the New Zealand spinach, a
cultivar indigenous to New Zealand that has a small, velvety leaf
with a rounder, less chalky flavor than regular spinach.
</P>
<P>
   He braises sweetbreads in a sauce scented with licorice root, at
the very end tossing in the rigid, succulent leaves. They wilt,
draping themselves over the sweetbreads, and maintaining in every
bite their identity _ a sturdy, minerally leaf that is as integral
and memorable as any luxury should be. Without it, the dish
wouldn't be nearly as good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
