<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-15 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RIOJA, THE GRAPE IS OLD, THE STYLE ALL NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, the last time I was in Rioja, Spain's
best-known red wine region, many winemakers were frustrated by
their apparent inability to crack the American market. They put
much of the blame on rules that insisted they make their wines
exclusively from local grapes, principally tempranillo and
garnacha, which is called grenache here and in France. The Riojans
looked enviously toward Miguel Torres in the Penedes, near
Barcelona, and to Piero Antinori in Italy, both of them moving
beyond local varieties to make exciting wines from cabernet
sauvignon, the noble grape of Bordeaux and California.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent return trip, it was obvious that things had changed.
Business was booming, there was little if any talk of cabernet, and
it was easy to sense a renewed pride in the traditional Riojan
grapes. Sense it and taste it.
</P>
<P>
   Many wines still spend too much time in oak barrels; many still
lack the backbone and body that cabernet imparts. But many are
beautifully structured and much less oaky than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Bodegas are what the Spanish call large wineries like La Rioja
Alta, CVNE, Lopez de Heredia and Muga, all in Haro, and Montecillo
in Fuenmayor. All turn out full-bodied, inky-dark wines with solid
tannic structure, far from the flabby, cherry-colored,
vanilla-tasting varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Since Spain is still the principal market for Rioja wines, the
Rioja bodegas make immense amounts of wine at the lower end of the
price range. Bodegas Campo Viejo, in Logrono, resembles nothing
more than the Gallo winery in Modesto, Calif. Within its massive
walls are some 50,000 oak barrels and 10 million aging bottles of
wine, give or take a million or two.
</P>
<P>
   While there is little discussion of other Spanish wine regions
among the Rioja winemakers, it's difficult to believe they have not
been influenced by the rapid rise of houses like Ribera del Duero
in the Castilla-Leon region and others in Priorato (where some of
the most successful winemakers are from Rioja), Navarra and even
newly emerging areas like Toro. Amost without exception, these
regions produce red wines that are both rich and elegant, and they
do it almost entirely with the tempranillo grape. Tempranillo goes
by other names in other regions, but it is essentially the same
grape everywhere it grows in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Why have Rioja wines improved? At a conference on tempranillo
this year, winemakers and enologists pointed to various factors,
including two that would surprise no one from other wine regions:
lower yields in the vineyards, and less time in oak barrels. To
grow twice as much an acre as one's neighbor is a worthy
accomplishment _ unless you're growing wine grapes. Lower yields in
the vineyard mean more tannin and more intense flavors in each
grape. Costs go up sharply, but so does quality.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Rioja wines aged for exceptionally long periods.
Cheap commercial wines in Spain can be bottled and sold anytime
after fermentation, like Beaujolais nouveau.
</P>
<P>
   One step up are crianza wines, which must age a year in wood.
Reservas must spend three years in wood and another year in the
bottle before they can be released. Gran reservas, the top of the
line, must age in wood for five years and in the bottle for two
more.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the bodegas go well beyond the rules. In 1988, I
remember tasting Rioja Alta's 1975 Gran Reserva 904. It had spent
10 months fermenting (some wineries do it in three or four days),
seven years in American oak barrels and four aging in bottle. An
impressive wine? Yes, but not as impressive as the concentrated
1995 Torremuga Reserve from Muga which spent about three years in
oak _ American first, then French _ and about a year in bottle
before it was released.
</P>
<P>
   The Rioja winemakers rate both 1994 and 1995 as excellent, their
highest praise, giving the edge to 1994, which some claim to be the
best Rioja vintage in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rioja wines were once among the world's best wine bargains. They
are still reasonable compared with the top Bordeaux and cult wines
from California, but the best of them will sell for $25 to $60.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the budget-minded can find some good buys in the $15 to
$20 range. Two examples are Remelluri's 1995 Rioja, which is a bit
oaky but has concentration and good fruit, and Rioja Alta's 1995
Alberdi, which is a little more restrained where oak is concerned
and offers good rich flavors in a lighter-boded wine.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most controversial Rioja winery is Bodegas Martinez
Bujanda, producer of the popular Conde de Valdemar wines, which
closely resemble _ in style, not taste _ Beaujolais made by the
carbonic maceration technique. Even when very young, they exhibit
deep purple color and almost overwhelming fresh fruit flavors.
These are Rioja wines that have little in common with the others
but are attractive on their own terms. There is a crianza and a
crianza reserva. The wood is a bit less obvious in the reserva.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists hate these wines. If you haven't decided whether
you are among them, there are older Riojas around to help you.
Though the astonishing number of old Riojas that used to be in
shops are all gone, it's still possible to find good ones from the
1980s, at about $80 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Do wines from Rioja age well? At a tasting there in April, we
began with 1995's and went back to a 1906 Federico Paternina.
Quality was all over the lot, but some very old wines, including a
Marques de Riscal 1920, a Montecillo 1934 and a couple of 1948's,
one from Montecillo and a Vina Real from CVNE, were in fine
condition. Of course, old wines are like old cars: fun to show off
but not much for everyday driving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
