A2383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SALZBURG-MUSIC-NYT &LR;      08-15 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL CELEBRATES MULTICULTURALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ The Salzburg Festival has long adhered to
the historic idea of an arts festival as a place apart from the
workaday music world. Here artists collaborate in near-ideal
conditions, freed to an amazing degree from the scheduling and
budget constraints that during most regular seasons necessitate
cutting corners and adjusting expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one of the conditions affecting this summer's
festival is the political and cultural upheaval caused by the
ascension of the right-wing, vociferously nationalistic Freedom
Party, now part of Austria's governing coalition. Gerard Mortier,
who in eight years as the festival's innovative artistic director
turned this former bastion of traditionalism into a hotbed of
experimentation, has been appalled by the developments. For next
summer, his last, he promises to make the festival a virtual
celebration of multiculturalism.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, true to form, this summer's offerings, especially the
opera productions, have been stirring debate. One is a fascinating
new staging of Gluck's ``Iphigenie en Tauride,'' heard on Saturday
night at the Residenzhof, a setting like no other.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer the festival's wizards of theater technology turn
the enormous open courtyard of this grand palace, once the
residence of Salzburg's ruling archbishops, into a makeshift opera
house with seating for 780. The stage and seats are placed atop a
steel-framed structure, like some huge Erector set, with a canvas
roof. Only here would patrons dressed in evening finery climb into
what is essentially the world's most lavish metal bleachers to
attend cutting-edge opera productions. It was an inspired site for
the German director Claus Guth's daring production of Gluck's great
opera epitomizing the classical ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, it's difficult for a production to convey the
essential prehistory of this mythological story. To assure success
in his war against Troy, Agamemnon, the Greek king, has sacrificed
his daughter, Iphigenie. But the goddess Diana has rescued her and
brought her to Tauris, where she lives under the rule of Thoas, the
Scythian king, and serves as a high priestess to Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Iphigenie's mother, Clytemnestra, has killed her husband in
grief over what she believes to be her daughter's death. And
Oreste, Iphigenie's younger brother, has killed his mother to
avenge his father.
</P>
<P>
   Guth conveys this horrific background story through enormous
masks that enclose the heads of a group of actors. Like eerie
oversize puppets, the actors appear at strategic moments as doubles
for the members of antiquity's most murderous dysfunctional family.
The puppet-actors trail the singers onstage like doppelgangers who
won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   It's an overtly dramatic and, no doubt for some, a heavy-handed
theatrical device. Masks of any kind can dominate a production. But
the three leading singers here, all Americans, hold their own: the
mezzo-soprano Susan Graham in a fearless performance of the title
role, the baritone Thomas Hampson in a riveting performance as
Oreste, and the tenor Paul Groves as Oreste's loving Greek friend
Pylade.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the production, with sets and costumes by Christian
Schmidt, is vaguely Victorian. The story takes place in a plush
salon with huge tilted walls covered in crimson velvet. Yet the
effect is timeless. The chorus of priestesses who serve Iphigenie
wear flesh-colored masks over their eyes and auburn wigs pulled
back in buns, so that they look eerily like their mistress. On
their dresses, they even have bloody stains above their hearts, as
she does, wounds of sisterly solidarity. Guth has devised highly
stylized but compelling and lifelike movements for the priestesses
and also for the male chorus of Thoas' soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The musical performance, with Ivor Bolton conducting the
Mozarteum Orchestra of Salzburg, was inspired. The role of
Iphigenie is typically sung by a soprano, but Graham subtly altered
the rich mezzo-soprano colorings of her voice, bringing lightness
and clarity to her top range, yet singing with emotional abandon.
Hampson's singing was also viscerally intense, yet poignant and
elegant. Groves pushed his light tenor voice somewhat but still
delivered a vulnerable and impressive performance. The baritone
Philippe Rouillon was a menacing King Thoas.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the festival gave the creative team free rein. Of
course, having to work within limits can often compel artists to
clarify their ideas. In two current stagings of Mozart operas the
directors were allowed, it would seem, to indulge themselves.
Together these productions suggest that in Mozart's hometown,
directors are straining to keep his canonical works interesting,
even if gimmickry is the result.
</P>
<P>
   The director Luca Ronconi's production of ``Don Giovanni,''
heard on Sunday night at the Large Festival Hall, was generally
deemed a failure when introduced last year. It's a cumbersome
staging with a muddled conception vaguely suggesting 1930s Fascist
Italy, with the Don as a dissolute millionaire playboy who seems to
have a thing for leather outfits when he attempts rape. There is a
grimly serious side to ``Don Giovanni,'' but in this production,
with Margherita Palli's charcoal gray and monumentally ugly set,
the opera just seems depressing.
</P>
<P>
   This was sad, for the musical performance was marvelous. Valery
Gergiev conducted the Vienna Philharmonic with a keen ear for fresh
detail, a vivid sense of drama and some boldly magisterial tempos.
In the title role, the resonant bass Ferruccio Furlanetto led a
strong cast that included the powerful bass Rene Pape as,
surprisingly, a vocally agile Leporello; the exquisite soprano
Renee Fleming as a Donna Anna to cherish; and the luminous-voiced
soprano Marina Mescheriakova as Donna Elvira.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at the Small Festival Hall offered the
controversial new production of ``Cosi fan tutte'' by the director
Hans Neuenfels, with sets and costumes by Reinhard von der Thannen.
The staging is over the top and a mishmash of ideas, but at times
intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   The two pairs of confused and inconstant lovers at the center of
this cynical comedy wear matching white jumpsuits, a device that
makes the partner-swapping and games of deception all the more
unsettling. There are unforgettable images, as in the garden scene,
in which the deceiving lovers court one another amid wildly
overgrown exotic flowers.
</P>
<P>
   But Neuenfels must not trust the opera, for he cannot leave the
music alone. Too many arias and ensembles are performed before
self-consciously symbolic and often pointless background action
from a roster of invented silent characters.
</P>
<P>
   The worst such intrusion involves a video projected on a large
screen during the scene in which the audience first meets the two
sisters of the story as they sing in blissful innocence about their
boyfriends. On screen a gorgeous young couple enact a modern-day
version of the Adam-and-Eve tale, complete with an apple riddled
with worms. Standing arm in arm before the screen, the radiant
soprano Karita Mattila as Fiordiligi and the dusky-toned
mezzo-soprano Vesselina Kasarova sang the duet incomparably. But it
was hard not to fixate on this weird movie.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cast was excellent: the lyric tenor Rainer Trost as
Ferrando, the robust baritone Simon Keenlyside as Guglielmo, the
stentorian bass Franz Hawlata as Don Alfonso, and the bright-voiced
soprano Maria Bayo as Despina. The conductor Lothar Zagrosek's
gesticulating baton technique did not elicit the most consistently
incisive playing from the Vienna Philharmonic, but the sound, shape
and character of the music-making were wondrous.
</P>
<P>
   The singers were not just vocally strong, but attractive,
charismatic and good sports. Would that Neuenfels had simplified
his conception and removed the extraneous clutter, which must have
been terribly expensive. What he needed was something not known at
the Salzburg Festival, a tough-guy boss, like Joseph Volpe at the
Metropolitan Opera, to tell him no once in a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
