u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-15 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAISE NOW, BROWN LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lamb with peaches sounds Middle Eastern, but I first came across
the combination in a contemporary German cookbook. It is a logical
pairing and tastes glorious, with the sweetness of the fruit
cutting through the richness of the lamb. But the challenge lay in
finding an efficient way to make it, since the original required
two separate cooking methods, with a resting period in between.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest technique was to grill lamb chops and peaches side
by side. Unfortunately, this yielded essentially lamb with peach
relish, and I wanted the peaches to contribute their juices to the
final product.
</P>
<P>
   So I developed a relatively fast and almost unattended braise.
Most braises begin with browning, but this one ends with it,
reducing both spattering and time: Since the lamb's liquid is
mostly cooked away at the end of the braising, it doesn't go flying
from the hot fat, and the meat browns faster. And the peaches
contribute some of their juices to the pan while browning lightly
and turning tender.
</P>
<P>
   A hint of cinnamon gives the dish a great aroma as it cooks and
a slightly mysterious flavor; I don't think you'd want more than
that. An even smaller amount of allspice, maybe an eighth of a
teaspoon, would also work. A pinch of cayenne or other red pepper
makes a nice addition, and an onion cooked along with the meat
provides just a little more complexity; you could live without it,
but it doesn't take much effort.
</P>
<P>
   One issue remains unresolved, and that is whether to tilt the
dish in a Middle Eastern or a European direction. The first calls
for finishing it with lime and cilantro, the second with lemon and
parsley. I loved both.
</P>
<P>
   LAMB WITH PEACHES
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 90 minutes, largely unattended
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds boned shoulder of lamb, trimmed of fat and gristle and
cut into 1- to 1{-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick or 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 medium to large onion, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   { cup port, red wine or water
</P>
<P>
   4 medium to large ripe peaches, washed
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon or 1 lime
</P>
<P>
   1 cup roughly chopped parsley (for use with lemon) or cilantro
(to go with lime).
</P>
<P>
   1. Place lamb in a 12-inch skillet, and turn heat to
medium-high. Season with salt, and add cinnamon, cayenne, onion and
wine or water. Bring to a boil, cover and adjust heat so that the
mixture simmers steadily. Cook 1 to 1{ hours, checking and stirring
every 15 minutes or so, adding a little more liquid in the unlikely
event that the mixture cooks dry. (This probably means the heat is
too high; turn it down a bit.) 2. When the meat feels tender when
poked with a small, sharp knife, remove the onion and cinnamon
stick, then turn the heat to medium-high, and cook off any
remaining liquid, allowing the lamb to brown a little. Cut the
peaches in half and remove their pits, then cut each of them into
12 or 16 wedges. Stir in the peaches, and continue to cook, gently
tossing or stirring the mixture, until the peaches are glazed and
quite soft but still intact, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in the lemon or lime juice and most of the parsley or
cilantro. Taste, and adjust seasoning. Garnish with what's left of
your chosen herb, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
