<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CLINTON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: A Democratic bid for four more years
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1992, nominee Bill Clinton stood before a stomping, cheering,
crowd in New York City to promise delegates to the Democratic
National Convention that he could recapture the White House. For 12
years, Democrats had been locked out of the presidential residence,
and the delegates lusted at the prospect of occupying it again.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton preached a sermon that night, one that mixed promise and
hope with verbal lashings of the George Bush administration on
which he laid the blame for a flat economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, President Bill Clinton stood before a stomping,
cheering crowd in Los Angeles to once again deliver a sermon that
mixed promise, hope and verbal lashings aimed at George W. Bush,
whose promises he characterized as flat.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from Bill Clinton's last hurrah, but he tried
mightily _ but not punctually _ to relinquish the spotlight to his
vice president. Electing Al Gore will stretch the Democratic hold
on the White House to match the 12-year GOP tenure that began in
1981 with the inauguration of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly 10 p.m. Central Time before Clinton took the
podium to tout the record of his administration and Al Gore's role
in it, but not before taking more than a few bows. Modesty is not
the first choice of any politician, particularly one who is by
virtue of office the country's top politico.
</P>
<P>
   Though a most controversial president, Clinton is a most
eloquent one. Monday's speech, which took 40 minutes to deliver,
was a masterful effort, and he began with a recitation of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago, when our party met in New York, it was a far
different time for America. Our economy was in trouble, our society
was divided, our political system was paralyzed. Ten million of our
fellow citizens were out of work. Interest rates were high. The
deficit was $290 billion and rising. After 12 years of Republican
rule, the federal debt had quadrupled, imposing a crushing burden
on our economy and our children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welfare rolls, crime, teen pregnancy, income inequality _ all
had been skyrocketing. And our government was part of the problem,
not part of the solution,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming Ronald Reagan rhetoric dead at the Bush-Dick Cheney
ticket, Clinton asked: ``... are we better off today than we were
eight years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who say the progress of these eight years was an
accident, that we just coasted along, let's be clear: America's
success
</P>
</TEXT>
