<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALPINE RESIDENTS OPPOSED TO INCLUSION IN TRADE ROUTE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Del Norte and Glass mountains near Alpine don't rival the
Rockies, but in West Texas they look ruggedly handsome and offer a
relief from the scruffy nap of the Chihuahuan Desert.
</P>
<P>
   Alpine is sometimes called the ``Taos of Texas,'' mostly by the
local chamber of commerce. Still, it is a fresh-faced city that
belongs among the state's most valuable tourism treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away near the sag of the Big Bend, its remoteness has
always added to the city's charm, but now that remoteness is being
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   There are thoughts of Alpine's becoming part of a new trade
route that will shuffle goods from Mexico, through West Texas, and
on to Fort Worth-Dallas to the east, and Denver to the north.
</P>
<P>
   The trade corridor, called ``La Entrada al Pacifico,'' would
begin at the port of Topolobampo near Los Mochis on Mexico's Gulf
of California. It would travel northeasterly through the city and
state of Chihuahua, then to Presidio in West Texas and northward
through Alpine on its way to the Midland-Odessa area.
</P>
<P>
   Two trade routes are being proposed. The other, called the
Ports-to-Plains, is planned to come north out of Mexico City, to
Monterrey and Del Rio, then on to San Angelo and again
Midland-Odessa.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily see why the folks in Midland-Odessa are
absolutely giddy about the prospects. The people in Alpine are not.
</P>
<P>
   An organization of Midland-Odessa chambers of commerce and local
government leaders recently went to Alpine to explain support for
the Entrada al Pacifico program, only to be met by a resolute group
of Alpine residents who were steadfastly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Midland-Odessa organization is called MOTRAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people from MOTRAN get very high marks for coming down
here,'' said Brewster County Judge Val Beard, who set up the
meeting. ``They were very courageous to come here to a crowd that
was not very friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   While the proposed trade route is only a concept, and probably
can't become a reality for several years, the Alpine residents were
firm in their disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the meeting gave the MOTRAN folks a clearer message
about how strongly we oppose them,'' said Pam Gaddis, an Alpine
resident who belongs to a local opposition group called Tourists
Not Trucks. ``No one at the meeting spoke in favor of it. We want
them to stop pretending they don't understand us. We don't want
it.''
</P>
<P>
   MOTRAN officials say there are misconceptions about the trade
route, especially the thoughts of four-lane thoroughfares running
through the heart of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the trucks,'' Gaddis said. ``We don't care what
form the road is in, it's the trucks we don't want and the governor
of Chihuahua has been quoted as saying there could be 4,000 trucks
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Midland and Odessa want the business, Alpine
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are very selective about what they want to
encourage to come here,'' said Beard. ``People who live here have
made a lifestyle choice, and that choice does entail making less
money. But they accept that so they can enjoy clean air, clean
water, and a safe small-town atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very protective of that lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Beard says she shares that sentiment and understands that Alpine
doesn't suffer some of the same economic hardships other West Texas
towns are struggling with.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpine economy is healthy, tourism is good, the population
is increasing at a manageable rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have something worth conserving,'' she said. ``We are very
fortunate. We are blessed and we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
