<HEADLINE>
BURMESE SALADS, WITH THE THERMOSTAT ON COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 470 words of recipes appear at bottom of story) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On my first day in most Southeast Asian countries I invariably
have the following conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Guide: I have arranged for you to have dinner tonight in your
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Me: Do they serve local food?
</P>
<P>
   Guide: You won't like that. Maybe you can have Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   A polite argument ensues.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes I get lucky. Last year in Myanmar (formerly
Burma), the Strand Hotel in Yangon (formerly Rangoon) actually had
a small menu of Burmese dishes, mostly salads. They were superb,
with light, bright flavors and a wonderful mix of textures. As I
later learned from Burmese cooks living in the United States, those
dishes had been authentically seasoned and only slightly altered to
suit Western tastes.
</P>
<P>
   I think of those salads when it's really hot, as it is in
Myanmar where the average year-round temperature is over 80
degrees. Salads are always cooling, of course, and in countries
with tropical climates hot spices are frequently used because they
make people perspire, another technique for cooling off. The
Burmese, like the Thais and Laotians, love raw vegetables and
greens and eat them with a pungent dipping sauce that usually
contains chilies. Their daily outdoor markets are filled with
dazzling displays of small pale purple eggplants, tiny fiery green
chilies, tomatoes and green papayas and mangos that are treated
like vegetables. Markets also carry beetel nuts, which produce a
high as well as blackened teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Myanmar sits between India to the northwest and China to the
northeast, with Thailand to the south, and its cooking has been
shaped by its neighbors' ingredients: bamboo shoots and soy sauce;
curry leaves and tamarind; fish sauce and lemon grass. Yet the food
is distinctly Burmese. Despite the use of chilies, the food is
never as hot as it is in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Curries are a staple, but the Indian versions use a far more
complex blend of spices. The Burmese rely on fresh ingredients like
green chilies for additional seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is the mainstay of the diet, but the Burmese love noodles,
too, a notable legacy from China. The Burmese national dish, if
there is such a thing in a country with almost 70 indigenous
groups, is a noodle soup called mohinga. Fish-based and made with
rice noodles, it is served at breakfast and it was one of the most
appealing breakfasts I have ever eaten. Shan State in particular is
noted for its noodle dishes, and I had a wonderfully savory version
at a hotel on Inle Lake.
</P>
<P>
   But the specialty of Myanmar is lephet, or fermented tea leaf
salad. Its appeal lies in the slight bitterness and smokiness of
the leaves, which are mixed with a highly seasoned combination of
fried garlic, roasted sesame seeds, peanuts, fish sauce and lime
juice. In Burma it is served as a snack, a palate cleanser, a
welcome to guests and a stimulant to ward off sleep.
</P>
<P>
   When tomatoes and cabbage are added it is served as a salad.
(That is how it is adapted in the United States. Both Irene Khin
Wong, who owns Saffron59, a catering company in New York, and Pyu
Pyu Win, who owns Myanmar Burmese Restaurant in Falls Church, Va.,
serve it that way.)
</P>
<P>
   Ginger salad is made of peeled, julienned ginger with many of
the same ingredients as the tea leaf salad, but the slightly hot
ginger provides a completely different taste. The recipe is based
on one from Win and Claudia Saw Lwin Robert, who lives in Yangon.
</P>
<P>
   The green papaya salad is similar, but once again, the papaya
enhances the other flavors while adding texture if not taste.
</P>
<P>
   All three salads are easy to put together once you have made a
trip to Indian and Asian markets for the staples, like fish sauce,
ground roasted peanuts and ground dried shrimp. The fermented tea
leaves are probably the most exotic ingredient, and they can be
found at a place on Canal Street in Chinatown, Myanmar Wholesale
and Retail (212) 566-1851. The business also sells packages of
mixed fried garlic, peanuts, beans and sesame seeds in oil to use
in the salad, for $6 plus shipping, but you can buy just the tea
leaves (also $6) and make the salad following the recipe here.
</P>
<P>
   PAPAYA SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Strand Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 very large green papaya, julienne
</P>
<P>
   2 slices lime, plus extra for garnish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons ground roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons ground dried shrimp
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon garlic-flavored oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce (nam pla or nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   \ to { teaspoon minced bird's eye or other very hot green chili
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro leaves and whole green chilies for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Soak papaya julienne in water to cover with 2 slices of lime
for 15 minutes or longer. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine with remaining ingredients and mix well. Arrange on
plate. Garnish with cilantro leaves, lime slices and whole green
chili.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GINGER SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Strand Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup peeled, ginger julienne
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ground roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons whole roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fish sauce (nam pla or nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons ground dried shrimp
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fried garlic slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 plum tomatoes, halved and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup very thinly sliced cabbage
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons toasted yellow split pea flour (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Serrano or other hot green chilies, chopped, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all ingredients except chilies in a large bowl. Mix
well. Divide among four plates and serve, garnished with chopped
chilies.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Split pea flour is available in Indian markets. Spoon
desired quantity onto aluminum foil and bake at 350 degrees until
it begins to brown, just a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   FERMENTED TEA LEAF SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Strand Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ to { cup fermented tea leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dry shrimp powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large plum tomatoes, julienne
</P>
<P>
   1 cup very thinly sliced cabbage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fried garlic (see note)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fried dried peas
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   [ to \ teaspoon minced bird's eye chili or other hot chili, like
a Serrano
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons fish sauce (nam pla or nuoc mam)
</P>
<P>
   Coriander leaves, sliced fried garlic and whole green chilies,
for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all ingredients in large bowl and mix well. Divide
between two plates and serve, with garnishes
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make fried garlic, slice as many cloves of garlic
lengthwise as desired and saute slowly in peanut oil to cover until
garlic is lightly browned on both sides. Remove from oil and place
on paper towels to dry. Store in tightly covered container in
refrigerator.
</P>
