<HEADLINE>
PORTUGUESE WINES UNCORKED 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Portugal is renowned for port and Madeira, and for fizzy roses
like Lancers and Mateus. It is also known for supplying many of the
world's wine corks. But this country also has a thriving table wine
industry, which is so little known it is a paradise for bargain
hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal has long been a wine-loving nation, but only in the
last 15 years, since joining the European Union, has it begun to
join the rest of the wine-making world in modernizing its
agricultural and vinification techniques. Still, Portugal seems to
retain a stubborn sense of wanting to do things its own way, which
for wine lovers has its benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many wine producers hoping for international success,
Portugal has not gravitated to grapes like merlot, cabernet
sauvignon and chardonnay, although you can find small amounts of
these wines. Its red wines are made from grapes like periquita,
trincadeira and even some port grapes like tinta roriz. (No, there
will not be a quiz at the end.)
</P>
<P>
   The best Portuguese reds combine a rich fruitiness with flavors
like coffee and chocolate. Typically, they are aged in oak barrels,
with mixed results. The better wines become well knit, with the oak
augmenting the natural flavors the way the deft use of salt aids in
cooking. In poorer versions, fruit and oak battle in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the excitement is in Portuguese red wines, it is
summer, so I can't ignore vinho verdes, or green wines, which earn
their name because of their youth, not their color.
</P>
<P>
   Vinho verdes can be white or red, but it is the whites that are
imported here and are so delightful in hot weather.
</P>
<P>
   These wines are cheap, low in alcohol and nothing fancy _ simply
a blend of grapes shot with carbon dioxide for a mild fizziness.
</P>
<P>
   Vinho verdes are not even vintage dated, since they're intended
to be drunk immediately. But on a sweaty day, a good vinho verde is
remarkably refreshing, like a great lemonade spritzer
</P>
<P>
   REDS &QL; 
QUINTA DO CARMO, ALENTEJO 1995 $20 &QL; 
Aromas of sweet fruit laced with chocolate and licorice; sturdy and
mouth filling. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUINTA DO CRASTO, DOURO 1998 $14 &QL; 
Like biting into a handful of raspberries; mellow with a tingle of
acid.
</P>
<P>
   JOSE MARIA DA FONSECA, PERIQUITA , TERRAS DO SADO 1996 $9 &QL; 
Ripe and fruity with aromas of cola and licorice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOGRAPE , VINHA DO MONTE , ALENTEJO 1997 $9  &QL; 
Grapey with simple fruit flavors harmoniously cushioned by oak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VINHO VERDES &QL; 
CASAL GARCIA $7 &QL; 
Light, fizzy, peachy and cheerful.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AVELEDA $7 &QL; 
Fizzy and lemony, instantly satisfying. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
