A2392 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SEGA-BASEBALL-TEX     08-15 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-BASEBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA HEAVILY TOUTING `WORLD SERIES BASEBALL 2K1'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's be honest: There were only a couple of reasons to buy a
Sega Saturn machine _ you know, that ``other'' Sega home game
system you bought your kid before the ``new'' one came out last
year _ and ``World Series Baseball'' was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Sony, which loaded ``WSB'' with animated graphics
and all the extras you could imagine, Sega hit a home run with a
simple-to-learn, motion-capture-graphics title that looked as good
as it played. It still ranks as one of the best baseball vid-games.
Ever.
</P>
<P>
   So you can imagine the anticipation for ``World Series Baseball
2K1'' (Sega Sports for Dreamcast), Sega's updated, upgraded version
of ``WSB'' for the Dreamcast. Sega has been heavily touting this
game, saying it's the baseball equivalent to its excellent football
and basketball Dreamcast games.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the graphics are incredibly detailed, from jersey numbers
to facial hair. The players really do look like their real-life
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   And Sega went to a lot of trouble capturing nuances of all the
baseball stadiums, from the lighting to scoreboards to billboards.
The only thing missing from The Ballpark at Arlington is that
``Star-Telegram'' sign that greets you as you s-l-o-w-l-y make your
way through traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But _ and this is a serious flaw _ gamers cannot control the
outfielders, whereas in other baseball games, you can. The computer
does it for you. Oh, that's a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Response times are slow, too. When a player catches a ball or
swings at a pitch, for instance, it takes an unusual amount of time
for the game to react to it. Batting and pitching are difficult to
master, too, a dramatic change from the easy-to-learn techniques of
``WSB'' for the Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Hope they fix this stuff for ``2K2.''
</P>
<P>
   ``KISS Psycho Circus: The Nightmare Child'' (Third Law for PC):
Clown-makeup-wearing rock band Kiss enters the CD-ROM world with
this game that's based on Todd McFarlane's hot-selling ``KISS
Psycho Circus'' comic-book line.
</P>
<P>
   This is the part where we have to warn parents: Just like with
comic books, there's lots of violence and blood and
nightmare-inducing villainous creepoids here. I wouldn't let my
12-year-old play it.
</P>
<P>
   Teens, though, will recognize this as another
``Doom''-influenced, first-person shooter. Players take on one of
the four Kiss members as they walk around and lay waste to various
demonic creatures, a lot of whom resemble the band's fans.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be much of a plot or point, except blowing
away everything. The game's saving grace is the multiplayer
death-match mode in which up to 16 players can play target practice
against one another. Sixteen players _ yeah, that is pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is entertainment critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
