<HEADLINE>
BLASS OF 2000  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ERIC WILSON 
 (Three color slides are available.) 
 From WWD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Quick, what's new in Bill Blass' showroom?
 &HT;    Answer: Lots _ if you take a close look.
 &HT;    There are the familiar, comforting sights of Blass' men's-wear
fabrics, the pinstripes, the double-face cashmere and the silk
satin dresses, but something is not quite the same there either.
The fabrics have been turned just slightly on the bias, and dresses
and jackets have been deconstructed, with bits cut out here and
there.
 &HT;    It's been over six months since Paris ready-to-wear designer
Steven Slowik was named design director of the Bill Blass
collection, following Blass' retirement last year, and his
influence is now being felt in the house.
 &HT;    ``This is just the beginning of what I wanted to show as a
visual vocabulary,'' said Slowik, who landed the Blass job over the
likes of Randolph Duke and Alber Elbaz in February and has since
set up residence in Greenwich Village to take on the job full time.
 &HT;    A Detroit-born and Parsons-trained designer, Slowik closed his
signature business in Paris, where he had also worked as rtw
designer for Ferragamo, before moving back to New York with the
mission to create a collection that retains Blass' stamp of
elegance while attracting the next generation of Park Avenue
clientele.
 &HT;    Earlier this summer, he hired Lars Nilsson, who was design
director of the women's collection at Ralph Lauren, as his senior
designer to help with design and construction.
 &HT;    ``There are various ways you can approach a situation like this
and I think this is the right one,'' Slowik said. ``I know you
can't please everyone. Some customers might walk in here and say,
'Ew. Ick.' Or they might say, 'Ooh. Fabulous.'''
 &HT;    Of the dozen or so pieces Slowik is showing for early spring
deliveries, which will appear in stores in late December, there are
daytime looks such as a gray pinstripe pantsuit, and silk satin
cocktail gowns that have detached, contrasting collars.
 &HT;    ``The first thing I looked at were the classic elements of Bill
Blass,'' he said. ``I literally interviewed Mr. Blass and discussed
what those elements are. Then I brought in what I felt is me, which
is the whole idea of lightening up the construction, bridging what
I call the tradition and the future, bringing in my color sense,
and moving further into spring with bold prints and interesting
combinations of fabrics.''
 &HT;    Slowik tore the classic pantsuit apart at the seams to come up
with an ultra-lightweight construction, so it wears like a sweater,
and he cut heathered cashmere pants with only an internal seam so
that it feels more like a skirt, which he paired with an oyster
walking coat, made in Blass' classic double-face wool crepe.
 &HT;    Little black dresses are cut in elliptical shapes with a sheer
T-shirt overlay, which Slowik described as creating a sense of
geometry combined with one of softness. The feeling is also
reflected in a black wool crepe halter dress with a broad silk
satin ribbon running straight down the front and back.
 &HT;    ``There's definitely an inspiration from nature in this
collection,'' Slowik said. ``This would come in all the red and
pink colors, which literally come from roses, and the way things
are unfolding at the collar and opening up to reveal another color.
 &HT;    ``In general, it was also very important, even in the garments
that were more masculine-looking, to have a more feminine
influence. The idea of the satin linings and the colors are very
feminine, which is a look I feel is going to be strong for this
season.''
 &HT;    Slowik's last signature collection had more technical fabrics
than his work for Blass, and was cut close to the body. Slowik's
new touches include side-button closures, the slight bias cut of
the satin dresses and surprise cutouts, in which ``things look like
they fell apart, but it's definitely very intentional,'' he said.
 &HT;    ``The clothes don't always shout,'' Slowik said. ``But I think
that's what this is about. There's a certain luxury and modernity
about clothes that look stylish in a more subtle way.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eric Wilson is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
