<HEADLINE>
STUPID THINGS THAT MOMMY DOES _ AND WHY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CATHERINE NEWTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many of the stupid things we do as parents, this one was
perhaps prompted by a bloody nose.
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, it was the 6 a.m. kind that involves
one of the little loves of your life, screaming, sobbing and
scared, casting huge globs of red blood all about her new
butterfly-embroidered quilt, down the hardwood floors in the
hallway, across the new white rag rug sent by your sister _ (who
does not have kids but a dog) direct from Nantucket where she has
been spending three glorious comatose weeks worrying about nothing
except gourmet meals and how long it will take the sun to burn off
the morning fog _ and finally, to your own bed. Where small
droplets of blood soak into your white pillowcases.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it wasn't the bloody nose at all. Maybe you just did
this stupid thing because summer sluggery kept you from getting to
work before 10:30 a.m. for the past two weeks and you were starting
to get a little rattled. You cannot budge your sleepy son (though
secretly, not even admitting it to yourself, you may not have been
trying all that hard, thinking the guilty thought that if you
didn't have to work, the poor child could sleep late like all his
friends).
</P>
<P>
   You are stuck in slow motion, making sandwiches. It takes you 20
minutes to jog around the block and another 20 to water the lawn
and the shrubs and the plants you keep buying and that keep dying
on your sun-baked porch.
</P>
<P>
   That could do it. Being late can make you do stupid things.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was just that you were a little distracted. You just
realized that your summer sitter is leaving in three weeks for
college and you have done absolutely nothing to find an afterschool
caretaker for your sweet, sleepy, fluid-leaking babies. You hadn't
bought your daughter the white shoes she needs for the wedding
she'll be in in two weeks, and, come to think of it, you have yet
to get your shoes, too, and you were set on silver sandals, which
this season, seem hard to find, except of course for those Jimmy
Choo ones at Saks, which are still there, not in your closet,
because they cost $565.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the fact that you still had two presents to buy
_ one for a shower, one for the wedding _ and school clothes for
the new year, even though it seems like you just finished
outfitting everyone for camp with their Doc Martens, swimsuits and
Super Soakers. And, of course, toothbrushes, one of which your son
failed to find in his trunk for an entire week.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it was just distraction _ and stress.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of stress. After all, your kids got a new stepmom this
summer, the PTA president announced her imminent departure from the
public school you and a dwindling group of friends are being left
to defend in an increasingly Alamo-like situation and you've only
gotten one donation for the November fund-raiser, though you're in
charge of the live auction, and the only reason you found the time
to solicit that one contribution was because the donor was single
and fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   But really, all this was still no excuse. Just part of everyday
family life. It had more to do with karma.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it. For a month, you'd been sending bad energy into the
atmosphere with your dark thoughts about your friend's fiance, who
asked if he could store some stuff in your garage for a month and
then drove his truck right into the awning that hung over the side
door, effectively destroying it. For a month, you'd been wondering
to yourself, unkindly, how anyone could be so stupid to drive into
your house.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why you did it.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you backed your brand new car right into the side of
your house, causing $1,400 worth of damage to the car and knocking
out a chunk of Austin limestone in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not what you told the insurance adjuster the
next day at 8 a.m. when he asked you how this thing could have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you said. It was a blind spot.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
