<SLUG> BC-FAUCHON-OPENING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS' FAUCHON OPENS MARKET IN MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Fauchon, the legendary Parisian market, has made its
debut in New York. Its first American shop opened Monday at 442
Park Ave,, at 56th Street, in the Drake Swissotel.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the glass display cases, shelves and free-standing
consoles in the 3,600-square-foot store are stocked with pink and
gold packages of fancy jams, chocolates, crackers, mustards, oils,
vinegars, pickles, sauces and 109 kinds of tea. But there are no
cheeses for the biscuits, baguettes for the jam or fancy produce
for the oils and vinegars. These are not what Fauchon is planning
to sell here.
</P>
<P>
   The closest to substantial food in the New York store now are
three kinds of quiche: classic lorraine, Provencale, with tomatoes
and zucchini, and crab meat, all on excellent flaky pastry, priced
at $30 to $40 each, and also sold by the slice.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, the shop will carry other Gallic specialties like
duck and goose foie gras, truffled, in terrines, glittering with
aspic or wrapped in pastry. Smoked salmon will be stocked, and so
will Iranian caviar, now that the United States government has
lifted the ban on it.
</P>
<P>
   Fauchon's chef de cuisine, Jean-Pierre Clement, is training the
American staff to make the prepared food. Another chef from France,
Xavier Mougica, will soon replace him.
</P>
<P>
   The candy counter is laden with chocolates, marrons glaces in
four flavors, pates de fruit and marzipan creations. The jewel-like
glace strawberries ($2 each) are not to be missed. Chocolate Eiffel
Towers are $5 each. The pastry department is limited to delicious
macaroons for the moment, and there are packaged cookies, and
gradually other pastries, ice creams and sorbets will be added.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken Fauchon, which has 800 stores in 33 countries, this
long to open in the United States, because the company's emphasis
was placed on establishing franchises in Europe, Asia and the
Middle East. When Laurent Adamowicz bought the 114-year-old company
in 1998, he set his sights on the American market. The $3-million
New York store is company owned.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the tea salon at Fauchon will open, with a menu of
sandwiches and pastries. It will also serve a complete afternoon
tea for $28 and an all-chocolate menu for $30. It will be open like
the store, every day, from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m., except Thanksgiving,
Christmas and New Year's Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
