<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WAINEWRIGHT-BOOK-REVI     08-15 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAINEWRIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WAINEWRIGHT THE POISONER': GETTING AWAY WITH MURDER (PROBABLY) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Griffiths Wainewright was a minor English painter of the
first half of the 19th century who was convicted of forgery and
transported to Australia, where he did hard labor for seven years.
He was an unusual criminal in that he knew people like Samuel
Taylor Coleridge, William Blake and Lord Byron, and when his term
of hard labor was finished, he gained recognition in Tasmania as a
portrait painter. He was called ``an insufferable fop'' by one
person who knew him, ``a daring and impudent braggart'' by another.
</P>
<P>
   Most important as background to Andrew Motion's unusual
biography of Wainewright, he probably murdered his uncle, his
mother-in-law and his sister-in-law, though he was never convicted
of those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Motion's ``Wainewright the Poisoner'' is an ambitious and
unusual undertaking, a scrupulously factual fiction that puts
Wainewright's story into an imagined confession. It is in this
sense an imagined biography that aims, by having Wainewright speak
for himself, at bringing us closer to the man than standard
biography would allow.
</P>
<P>
   Motion buttresses his approach with many pages of explanatory
notes providing the historical basis for every one of his
imaginative gestures. Helped along in this way by Motion, a
literary biographer who was named poet laureate of Britain in 1999,
Wainewright tell the ``truth'' of his life and his crimes even as
we understand that crucial elements in that ``truth'' are
self-serving falsehoods, or at least convenient omissions aimed at
restoring a tattered reputation.
</P>
<P>
   This is certainly an intriguing exercise, and it does succeed in
bringing the reader into the troubled mind of a figure who would
otherwise be known only through a few fragmentary historical
leftovers. We get a kind of insider's look into early-19th-century
dandyism, art criticism and Wordsworthian nature worship. Still,
one reads this book wondering why it isn't more gripping, more
narratively powerful, more redolent of the spice of human iniquity
or at least enlivened by more mordant wit. The explanation would
seem to be ``Wainewright's'' very stylistic and historical
plausibility and the scholarly care that Motion has taken undermine
the literary and psychodramatic potential of his story.
</P>
<P>
   The early chapters, in which Wainewright introduces us to his
tragedy and describes the world of writers and artists he inhabited
in the London of the first third of the century, have a kind of
pre-Victorian vaporousness that makes them slow going. (``But while
we are passing from moment to moment, we are tossed in the torrent
of a thousand accidents and chances.'') When he gets to the heart
of the story _ the strange deaths of his intimate relations _
Wainewright accounts for himself the way he might have had he
really written this probably dishonest confession.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wainewright was guilty of those poisonings, he isn't
going to let us into his malevolent heart; and if he isn't guilty,
his ``confession'' is false and not wittily false enough to give it
much more than an antiquarian interest.
</P>
<P>
   The critical episode in Wainewright's story has to do with the
death of Helen, the younger sister of his wife, Eliza. Eliza
herself _ first Wainewright's nurse, then his wife _ never comes
across in this confession as anything other than a stock character
described with an earnest sort of 19th-century boilerplate. (``The
nurse who had lifted me from the black waters of my unhappiness
with so sore a struggle had become the whole object of my wish to
please.'') Helen has even less of a profile here, and while this is
historically necessary, given the absence of information about her
very colorlessness, it undermines Motion's purpose in inventing
Wainewright's confession in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Helen bought several life insurance policies, making Eliza and
Wainewright (or Wainewright's creditors) her beneficiaries. The
idea, Wainewright says, was this: ``While Helen was still in
health, it had been my proposal that she, and I, and all of us,
would escape to the Continent, where eventually we would rescue our
fortunes by redeeming our policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen's death would be faked, and the insurance money collected.
But Helen dies a slow and painful death soon after the policies are
bought, a death medically similar to those of Wainewright's uncle
and mother-in-law not long before.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Helen, having witnessed these earlier deaths,
nonetheless agreed to give Wainewright a large financial stake in
her demise. But Motion's historical excavation prevents us from
delving speculatively into the relationship of Wainewright, Eliza
and Helen, even though that would seem to be at the savory crux of
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wainewright moons with romantic-era heartfulness over
her death. (``Our one reality was the fair head of Helen upon the
pillow, her skin blanched to a deadly pallor, and her forehead
sprinkled with the beads of her distress.'') We are left to ponder
whether this mooning is fake or sincere. That is an interesting
question, but Motion's choice of approaches to Wainewright's life
doesn't shed much light on it.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the second half of Wainewright's narrative recounts his
escape to France, his return to England, his trial for fraud (the
murder charges could not be proved) and his dispatch to Australia.
Again Motion provides an entirely plausible account, bolstered with
footnotes, and it becomes strangely more absorbing than the earlier
episodes. One senses that the Wainewright of these later pages,
having less to hide, becomes more open and straightforward. He
tells a story, about the killing of an albatross on board the ship
that took him to Australia, that strips away his usual veneer of
calculation and springs him into genuine passion, real feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Motion's notes on later opinions of Wainewright from the likes
of Edward Bulwar Lytton, a now forgotten writer, and Oscar Wilde,
provide an absorbing epilogue. We never know for sure whether
Wainewright was a poisoner, though the circumstantial evidence
strongly indicates he was. Certainly he was a colorfully dubious
figure, and we learn a great deal about him and his times from this
book, which reveals Wainewright and at the same time coats him with
a layer of prose thick enough to test the reader's patience.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WAINEWRIGHT THE POISONER'
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Motion
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 276 pages. Alfred A. Knopf
</P>
</TEXT>
