<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-JUICE-EATING-WELL-NYT     08-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUICE-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHUGGING JUICE CAN MEAN GUZZLING SUGAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of being conditioned to choose fruit juice over
soda, most people may be surprised to hear that the majority of
fruit juice drinks are only marginally more nutritious than a soft
drink.
</P>
<P>
   Both provide calories from sugar and not much else. In fact,
even plain juices often have more calories than soft drinks. An
eight-ounce Coke has about 130; eight ounces of juice can range
from as few as 110 to as many as 210.
</P>
<P>
   At least when you choose a soft drink you are under no
illusions. You get calories (and caffeine) and that's all. But the
juice aisle in any store promises more. After all, juice is made
from fruit, which is inherently healthful. Some careful study of
the label is needed, though, to discover juices that are worth the
calories because they have some nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you have chosen wisely, fruit juices should not be
guzzled like bottled water. If you drink too much juice, there
isn't much room left in the calorie column for other foods that
will not only fill you up but also provide the nutrients you need.
Even though 16-ounce containers are supposed to contain two
servings, an awful lot of people drink the entire contents. So what
seems innocuous enough at 120 calories a serving becomes the
equivalent of a serving of a rich ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Juice was once for breakfast only, but now it has become an
anytime snack in myriad variations. Size creep is also rampant, and
15 ounces is considered a single serving of some products.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit at least contains some fiber, but it is usually lost when
the fruit is turned into juice. Fiber helps fill you up: Juice does
not, except momentarily. And juices always contain more calories
per ounce than fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The first clue to how nutritious a juice may be is always the
name. If the words beverage, ``-ade,'' cocktail or drink are in the
name the product, is not 100-percent juice. But makers now sidestep
that reality by not calling their products anything. For example,
Mountain Sun has a drink called Cranberry Zip. One look at the
nutrition label and it's clear this drink makes no contribution to
the diet beyond the calories. No matter that the label touts the
absence of added sugar: ``The No-No's: No sugar, no corn syrup.''
Sugar is sugar whether it occurs naturally in the juice or is
added.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the government has required makers to list the
percentage of juice in the product on the label, but that's only
part of the story. The devil is in the details. It's not enough to
know how much of the product is juice; it's just as important to
know what kind of juice is it. All juices are not created equal. If
the first ingredient is apple, grape or pear juice, there is no
nutritional bang for the buck.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the label on Apple &AMP; Eve apple-grape juice says:
``100 percent juice. No sugar added.'' Perfect? Not quite. The
apple and grape juices have so little to recommend them
nutritionally that the company added enough ascorbic acid to
provide 100 percent of the daily requirements for vitamin C.
Otherwise what you have is 130 calories in an 8.45-ounce container
and 28 grams (or one ounce) of sugar from the juices themselves. No
other vitamins, no minerals.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago some companies began producing juices with more
nutrients and fiber, and Nantucket Nectars has added some of these
to its line. The company's Super Nectars Protein Smooth contains 80
percent juice. The first two ingredients are still water and grape
juice, but soy protein isolate has been added along with some fruit
purees and juice concentrates.
</P>
<P>
   One 15-ounce bottle is a single serving and provides 200 percent
of the daily needs for vitamin C, 6 percent of calcium, 12 percent
of iron, 4 grams of fiber, 13 grams of protein and a break-the-bank
410 calories. I guess you could call it a meal in a bottle. But
just a couple of these a day as a snack, and on a typical woman's
1,500-to-1,800-calorie diet, there won't be much room left for
food.
</P>
<P>
   The latest juices have been fortified with dietary supplements.
A handsomely shaped glass bottle of Fire, a product of Snapple,
contains ginseng, guarana and ginkgo biloba, suspended in 10
percent ``juice'' that is water, corn syrup, pear juice, citric
acid and dragon fruit (whatever that may be). Eight ounces has 120
calories. There's a zero beside all the other items on the
nutrition label. Assuming for the moment guarana, et al., are
useful, and that's an assumption that hasn't been proved
scientifically, there is still no indication of how much of these
supplements is provided.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the brand-new honey-flavored grapefruit juice by
Tropicana. Adding honey, which is just another form of sugar,
brings the calorie count of an eight-ounce serving up from 100
calories to 120 in the blink of an eye.
</P>
<P>
   It's a jungle out there. Maybe the best thing to do is cut
orange juice with seltzer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
