<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FLAVORED-ALCOHOL-ART-     08-15 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAVORED-ALCOHOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET SPIRIT OF SUMMER: THE NEW INFUSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (editors: recipes at end of article)  
 By MATT LEE and TED LEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember spiked watermelon, that simple summer
cooler? You take a whole ripe watermelon, gouge a chunk out of the
rind and upend a bottle of ice-cold vodka into it until the melon
has absorbed all the liquor. Slice it and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Messy? Yes, and somewhat crude. But there's an immediate
invigorating power in the spiked watermelon's marriage of late
summer fruit and potent alcohol, not to mention a pleasant
conundrum: Is it a drink? Is it fresh fruit?
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least one Manhattan chef has taken the idea to another
level. Stephen Picker of Good, in Greenwich Village, is steeping
watermelon chunks in vodka, straining the infusion and serving it
chilled, neat, in a martini glass. It packs every last drop of a
spiked watermelon's unbuttoned essence into a sophisticated
cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   And watermelon vodka is just the beginning. All over New York,
chefs are bringing their expertise _ and some exotic ingredients _
to bear on the bar, funneling whole spices into bottles of rum,
tossing peaches into pitchers of sake, packing leafy sprigs of
summer herbs into tequila bottles, soaking sour cherries in
cachaca.
</P>
<P>
   What they are demonstrating is that infusing spirits is as easy
as punching a hole in a watermelon. Maybe even easier (uncap a
bottle, add flavorings, shake and steep). And it's almost as fast.
Most spirits will take on the flavor of anything added to the
bottle in as little as 24 hours. These infused spirits can be drunk
straight, or mixed into sprightly house cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Good's watermelon infusion takes on only the palest pink color
from the melon along with its cucumber-like flavor. It's mixed in a
house cocktail, with lemonade, bitters and Triple Sec, but the
easy-going flavor is most refreshing chilled on its own.
</P>
<P>
   On West 42nd Street, Kazuto Matsusaka, the chef of Above, steeps
fresh peaches, cantaloupe and raspberries in Kaori sake for two
days in the refrigerator. The sunny note of each fruit allows the
slightly grainy finish of the rice wine to show through. The
infused sake is served in a glass pots, with an ice well to keep it
cool. When decanted into tiny glass cups, the sakes look clear, but
each pot contains a small amount of fruit as a garnish. Above also
infuses vodka with ginger and hot peppers to serve alone or in
cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   Roy's New York, in the financial district, makes infusions with
both vodka and cachaca, the South American sugar cane liquor.
Steeping cachaca for 24 hours with a pound and a half of pitted
sour cherries rounds out some of its rough edges. It is then used
with mint in a caipirinha, the sweet Brazilian cocktail. Vodka
infused with mild purple basil leaves lends a lilt to martinis
garnished with yellow heirloom tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Infusing spirits with herbs, fruit, nuts and grains is as old as
tea brewing. Scandinavians have been taming their fiery aquavit
with ingredients like caraway, lemon, aniseed and hyssop since at
least the 15th century. And throughout Europe, brandies have
traditionally been softened with infusions of fresh fruit to make
sweeter, softer drinks that evoke summer all winter long.
</P>
<P>
   The market for commercial flavored vodkas and spiced rums may be
partly responsible for the current interest in infusions. But
restaurateurs and bar managers are eager to put a personalized
stamp on their drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do something different'' said Dan Perlman, the
beverage director at AZ, in the Flatiron district. In the
restaurant's first-floor lounge, three heavy glass kegs with
stainless-steel spigots loom above the bar. One is a tawny Chinese
five-spice rum, with cinnamon stick, cloves, Sichuan peppercorns,
star anise and fennel seeds floating in it. A dozen Meyer lemons
are curing in crystal clear vodka in another. And a third contains
a rusty-tinted Seville-orange tequila. They're dry, razor-sharp
infusions and will be served neat to anyone who asks. But the bar
prefers to mix each infusion into house drinks like the peppery
``dArk &AMP; Ztormy,'' a mix of the five-spice rum and ginger beer.
</P>
<P>
   At Dylan Prime in Tribeca, vodka is infused with with fresh
horseradish, celery seeds and whole black peppercorns. It is the
foundation of what the bar calls a bloodless Mary, served in a
martini glass garnished with a julienne of celery and rimmed with
celery salt. The first evocative whiff is followed by a rush of
sinus-clearing heat.
</P>
<P>
   A pint of boldly flavored fruit, like pineapple, raspberry,
strawberry or peach takes only a day to infuse a bottle of liquor
or sake. More subtle flavors, like celery seed, melon, basil or
blueberry, can take as long as two days. As a starting point,
figure on one tablespoon of a dried spice for a 750-milliliter
bottle of liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, there are just a few guidelines. Don't sweeten an
infusion during the steeping; you can always add simple syrup to
the finished alcohol. And when making infusions with more than one
fruit or spice, you may want to steep the ingredients individually,
in smaller, separate bottles, and then blend them in varying
amounts to reach the perfect balance of flavors. It's your drink,
after all, so adjust it to suit your taste.
</P>
<P>
   PEACH SAKE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Above
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus 24 hours for infusion
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 ripe peaches
</P>
<P>
   1 liter sake, chilled.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut peaches in half and remove pits but not skins. Slice thin
and place in large Mason jar or pitcher. Pour sake over the
peaches, cover and refrigerate 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain sake through cheesecloth into clean decanter,
reserving peaches. Serve immediately, with 3 or 4 peach slices in
each glass, or refrigerate sake and peaches in separate containers
for later. Infused sake will keep 4 to 5 days in sealed bottle in
refrigerator. Peaches will keep 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 liter.
</P>
<P>
   BLOODLESS MARY
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Dylan Prime
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Celery salt
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces horseradish-infused vodka, well chilled
</P>
<P>
   1 Celery stalk
</P>
<P>
   Dip rim of a martini glass in water, then in celery salt to
coat. Add chilled vodka. Garnish with celery cut into very fine
julienne on a mandoline or with a vegetable peeler. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   HORSERADISH-INFUSED VODKA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Dylan Prime
</P>
<P>
   Time: About 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh horseradish root
</P>
<P>
   1 750-milliliter bottle of vodka
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons black peppercorns.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel horseradish and cut into fine shreds with a vegetable
peeler. Uncap vodka, pour off 1 cup and reserve. Using a funnel,
add celery seeds and peppercorns to bottle. Add horseradish, then
top off bottle with reserved vodka. Let stand at room temperature
for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Strain vodka through fine sieve to remove celery seeds and
fine particles. Chill completely before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 700 milliliters.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
