<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HOMEWORK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15 WEB SITES FOR THE HOMEWORK-CHALLENGED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The kids' homework assignments seem harder than they were last
year, don't they? School's just started, and already they're coming
to you with questions you can't answer.
</P>
<P>
   We're here to help you save face _ with the use of the Internet.
You no longer have to hem and haw (or flip aimlessly through heavy
encyclopedias) when the kids ask for help. Use the Web to your
advantage: Dial up, cozy up around the computer and find the
answers together. We've found some of the most useful sites for
homework help.
</P>
<P>
   General help:
</P>
<P>
   1. sunsite.berkeley.edu/KidsClick! _ Compiled by librarians, the
KidsClick! search engine looks a lot like Yahoo!, but the topics
are kid-friendly and mostly academic.
</P>
<P>
   2. www.studyweb.com _ Lightspan's Study Web is also set up like
a search engine; you can do a specific search or browse through
academic categories.
</P>
<P>
   3. www.schoolwork.org _ Also known as Schoolwork.ugh!, this site
lets you click on one of 26 categories (art, science, biography,
religion, math); within each category, you'll find links to sites
that offer more specialized information.
</P>
<P>
   4. www.bigchalk.com _ This site allows you to search for
specific topics or browse by topic. You can also search for
information designed for a specific age group.
</P>
<P>
   5. www.infoplease.com/homework _ The search engine
Infoplease.com offers a homework-help search engine and a page full
of links to useful information, including a kids' almanac, maps,
news and biographies.
</P>
<P>
   6. www.ipl.org _ The Internet Public Library has teen and youth
divisions; both offer links to general (and age-appropriate)
homework-help sites.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For high school students:
</P>
<P>
   7. www.teleport.com/~burrell _ Cool and Useful Student Resources
is maintained by Jenna Burrell, a Cornell University computer
science student. She offers categorized links to topic Web sites,
complete with a star rating that judges the helpfulness of each
site.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For younger students:
</P>
<P>
   8. www.kidport.com _ Kidport provides links for kids in
kindergarten through eighth grade. Select the grade and you'll get
age-appropriate links with helpful information.
</P>
<P>
   9. www.afterschool.to _ Afterschool offers academic information
(including a limited biography section); it also features ``Ask Mr.
Knowitall,'' a service that lets you post a question and get an
answer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For math help:
</P>
<P>
   10. www.math.com _ Math.com offers formulas, free mini-lessons
in any area, and free limited use of a software program that helps
you solve equations.
</P>
<P>
   11. forum.swarthmore.edu/dr.math/dr-math.html _ Ask Dr. Math is
divided by age group (elementary, middle school, high school,
college) and offers an extensive archive of previously asked math
questions. You can also send in your own question, but the site is
so busy, you're not guaranteed an answer.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For science help:
</P>
<P>
   12. www.sciam.com/askexpert _ ``Scientific American'' magazine
offers a well-organized archive of Ask the Experts questions and
answers. You can send in your question, but the site can't reply to
individuals _ and only the most interesting exchanges are posted.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For social studies help:
</P>
<P>
   13. http://www.odci.gov/cia/publications/factbook _ The CIA
offers a comprehensive guide to countries, with maps and
encyclopedic, organized information about any country you can think
of.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Consult an expert:
</P>
<P>
   14. www.askanexpert.com _ Ask an Expert lets you do just that.
An ever-changing appointed ``expert'' fields questions on a variety
of topics _ or you can search the archives to see if your question
has been answered already. This site might be best for finding
trivia.
</P>
<P>
   15. www.askme.com _ AskMe.com consults real people for answers
to your questions. To get to the ``homework help'' part of this
site, go to the main page and select Education, then Homework
Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
