<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IT'S LIBERAL NIGHT IN L.A.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judging from their Tuesday convention lineup, Democrats are
taking a time out from the business of being, or looking, centrist.
Prime time at the Democratic National Convention is turned over to
some of the party's most liberal figures and constituencies:
Leaders of the Human Rights Campaign, which lobbies on gay and
lesbian issues, and the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League speak, as do the Rev. Jesse Jackson, Sen. Edward
Kennedy and two union chiefs. One of the distinctive features of
the Democratic convention is that a portion of the cherished
speaking slots is given to interest groups. Although no less
lobbied by ideological interest groups, Republicans kept them off
the stage at their Philadelphia convention.
</P>
<P>
   RIDING OFF INTO THE SUNSET
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Tuesday flew in to the blue-collar swing
district of Monroe, Mich., for a joint rally with Al Gore to pass a
metaphorical leadership baton before disappearing gracefully into
the background. It was billed as a symbolic moment: Clinton going
east, on his way to a vacation, and Gore going west, on his way to
the convention, where he will accept the party's presidential
nomination Thursday. Gore praised the president and appealed to
voters to elect him president to save the economic gains built up
while he and Clinton were in charge. ``Bill Clinton worked hard to
get the economy right. I'm not going to let the other side wreck
it,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   POINT WELL TAKEN
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Harold Ford Jr. was 4, he made his father's first
radio campaign ad. The ad: ``If you want better housing, better
jobs and lower cookie prices, go to the polls and vote for my daddy
for Congress.'' Ford, a 30-year-old second-generation congressman
from Tennessee and youngest member of Congress, will deliver a
keynote speech that will set the tone of the convention. Ford, the
first African-American to give a keynote at a convention since U.S.
Rep. Barbara Jordan in 1976, said he plans to talk about his
personal relationship with Al Gore and about the future. By
choosing Ford, Gore has named two leading critics of President
Clinton to play prominent roles in the convention. Like Gore
running mate Joe Lieberman, Ford denounced Clinton for his behavior
during the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   THE MONEY MACHINE KEEPS MINTING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush Bush-Dick Cheney ticket is matched against Gore
and Joe Lieberman, the margin was 49-43 percent. The poll of 1,227
registered voters has an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   EASIER SAID THAN DONE
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast speech to Georgia's delegates, former President
Carter said Al Gore's ``biggest handicap'' will be President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, and that Gore somehow
must distance himself from the ic Hall and include performances by
Jimmy Buffett, Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash, Don Henley, Bette Midler, and
Jon Bon Jovi. The show
