<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ENTERGY-LEONARD-NEWHO     08-15 2156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERGY-LEONARD-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER COMPANY CEO SPARKS CHANGES IN CORPORATE VALUES
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, AUGUST 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By KEITH DARCE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLEANS -- Twenty years ago, J. Wayne Leonard's ambition was to
be nothing more than a number cruncher.
</P>
<P>
   When his boss at an Indiana utility asked about his career goal,
the young internal auditor said he dreamed, maybe, of becoming the
company's comptroller. But his boss told Leonard that he had the
brains and skills to be anything he wanted, even chief executive.
``Absolutely not'' was the response of a reluctant Leonard, who was
prone to low expectations for himself after growing up in a
working-class family in a small Indiana town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things where you didn't feel like you
were good enough,'' Leonard recalled in a recent interview. ``It
was probably from always having less than everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard seems to have everything now.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive officer of Entergy Corp., Louisiana's largest
company, Leonard in the past 20 months has orchestrated a dramatic
turnaround at the New Orleans power utility. He makes more than
$1.6 million a year. He has a posh office and lives in an exclusive
subdivision with his wife and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   And if all goes as planned, Leonard, 49, will become the head of
the nation's biggest electricity company in 15 months, when Entergy
expects to complete its merger with FPL Group Inc., the largest
power supplier in Florida, in a $13.9 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't just the story of Entergy.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the latest chapter in Leonard's rapid rise to the top
ranks of his profession. Along the way, he seems to be rewriting
corporate America's values, relying on an extreme range of
personality traits to promote his vision of a better society and
business world.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches or interviews, he's a cheerleader one minute, a
comedian the next, then a motivational speaker, an economics
professor and a classical philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   At his annual employee meetings, which are famous in the
company, Leonard plays the casual master of ceremonies of a
multimedia presentation that draws on rock music, worker photos,
movie clips, classical literature and accounting sheets.
</P>
<P>
   On one such occasion, he delivered a detailed slide lecture on
the economics of merchant nuclear power plants, then reawakened the
audience with video footage from ``The Wizard of Oz'' to illustrate
an allegory about workplace stress.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard has pursued a social agenda at Entergy that borders on
blasphemy in an industry that until recent years was characterized
by stodgy monopolies too preoccupied with the bottom line to care
about the living conditions of their customers.
</P>
<P>
   He has boosted corporate spending on programs to help many of
the poor communities that Entergy's four-state region includes. He
has called on the industry to accept higher standards for reducing
pollution from power plants. He has promised to fill senior
management positions with more women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Leonard ordered that a major hallway at the
Loyola Avenue headquarters be filled with photos of scenes of
poverty in the company's service area. Leonard wanted the pictures
as daily reminders to executives of the plight of many Entergy
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard often makes off-the-cuff comments that even surprise his
company speech writers and public relations specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after being named Entergy's chief executive officer in
November 1998, Leonard stunned observers when he used a
company-sponsored summit on the plight of low-income communities as
a bully pulpit to criticize past company policies and modern
American political culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society, we are demonizing the poor in the most shameless
way imaginable,'' he said. ``In many circles, poor people are being
made the scapegoats for societal problems they didn't cause and
cannot change. We have created a mean-spirited society where hate
crimes no longer seem outrageous, where talk-show hosts can achieve
fame and fortune by distorting the facts and fanning the flames of
hatred for the defenseless, the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this corporate maverick must execute the greatest utility
merger in U.S. history and set a course for the new superutility.
The decisions he makes over the coming months will lay the
foundation for the legacy he will leave when he reaches his target
retirement age in about eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard admits that the task of selling the merger to Wall
Street and a host of federal and state utility regulators will be
difficult. But the former college cross-country runner says he is
ready to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was meant to be a struggle,'' said Leonard during an
interview at Entergy headquarters. As usual, he was wearing a pair
of slacks and a V-neck gray pullover rather than the traditional
starched white shirt, tie and dark suit of corporate America. A
pair of gold-rimmed glasses framed his narrow face and
salt-and-pepper hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man was basically meant to be a warrior,'' he said. ``That's
the great thing about life. That's what makes it fun. Coming out on
the other side is what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken, brainy Entergy chief executive seems a world
away from Greenfield, Ind., a town of 10,000 about 15 miles east of
Indianapolis. He and his four brothers and sisters were raised by
their father, a high-school English teacher, and mother, a
homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   His track career had innocent roots in junior high school. He
couldn't afford to eat lunch in the public school cafeteria like
most other pupils, so every day he would run a mile home, eat and
run a mile back to school all inside the lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   The running paid off. Leonard went to college on a cross-country
track scholarship and earned extra money working as a janitor in a
girls' dormitory. He graduated at the top of his accounting class
at Ball State University in 1973 and later earned a master's degree
in business administration from Indiana University.
</P>
<P>
   He joined PSI Resources in Indianapolis even though the position
paid less than offers he received from Chicago accounting firms.
The job with the local public power monopoly gave him something
more important than a fatter pay check. It offered the stability
and security he craved, something that had eluded his father, who
moonlighted on menial jobs to provide a meager life for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard was right. He spent 25 years at PSI, which became
Cinergy Corp. after a merger with Cincinnati Gas &AMP; Electric in the
early 1990s, rising from an entry-level accounting post to chief
financial officer before leaving the company in April 1998 to
become president of Entergy.
</P>
<P>
   He took over the local company's top spot a few months later
after longtime utility head Edwin Lupberger was forced to resign in
the wake of falling profits from troubled overseas investments,
growing power outages among the company's utilities and a sinking
stock price.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's upbringing is an integral part of his professional
life, providing the framework for the values that have shaped him
as an executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad taught me the value of hard work and that character is
not what you do but how you do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He learned another important lesson later from his boss Al
Barker, the former chief executive of PSI who told Leonard in the
early 1980s that he was destined to lead a power company, whether
he accepted that fate or not.
</P>
<P>
   At Barker's urging, Leonard accepted a special position in which
he spent two years learning the real business of power utilities by
working in the field with line crews, customer service agents,
engineers and power plant operators. Barker, who talked about
Leonard's career move last week during a phone interview, knew the
experience would one day make Leonard a utility chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   If the push had come from anyone else, Leonard probably would
have resisted. But Barker was Leonard's foremost mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard had observed how Barker saved PSI from bankruptcy in the
1980s after the company abandoned construction of a financially
failed nuclear plant. Barker, who took much of the blame for the
boondoggle, was severely castigated by company critics and
eventually forced to step down. Throughout the turmoil, Leonard
said, Barker kept his integrity and never turned against those who
brought him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no regrets because he never made a decision that, as
far as I was aware of, was based on anything other than what he
thought was the right thing to do,'' Leonard said. ``He was a
person who was totally comfortable with his own life. He was
perfectly happy that he had done the right thing at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard had little room for error when he took over the reins of
Entergy.
</P>
<P>
   Customers were angry over years of declining service and
increasing power outages. Investors were disappointed with sinking
profits. Regulators were punishing the company's utilities for poor
reliability. Management ranks were in chaos, and employee morale
was at an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard and Entergy's other new leaders launched a strategy that
refocused the company on its core power generation and nuclear
power plant businesses while selling off billions of dollars in
less essential subsidiaries, such as a home-security business and
overseas utilities as far away as Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard also reduced power outages by boosting maintenance
spending on the company's transmission system and improved customer
service by opening new neighborhood customer centers and upgrading
training for customer service personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has won wide praise from Wall Street, regulators
and even some of the company's harshest consumer advocate critics.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard made the announcement of the Entergy-FPL merger, he
had his work cut out for him. Announcing a merger is only the first
of many steps to making the deal happen.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must be approved by federal and local regulators, a
step that can't be taken for granted because utility commissions in
other regions have been known to scuttle utility mergers in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard also faces adversity on the local level, where the news
stunned the New Orleans business and political community. Though
New Orleans would be the operational center for the new company's
utilities group, the city will lose the corporate headquarters,
which will go to FPL's home in Juno Beach, Fla. Leonard will move
with the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the city's only Fortune 500 headquarters would be
especially painful following thousands of white-collar job cuts in
the oil industry and the takeover of several other locally based
companies in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are hoping to milk as much as $275 million a year
in savings from the merger, mainly by eliminating redundant jobs at
both companies. The cuts likely will cost New Orleans jobs, but it
is unclear how deep those cuts will be.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard defended the job impact and the headquarters move by
arguing that this deal leads to a much better outcome than if
Entergy ``sat on its hands'' and got taken over by a job-slashing
company less sympathetic to New Orleans. The merged company would
be less vulnerable, Leonard said, which would serve New Orleans in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get bigger or you get swallowed up. This prevents the
horror of that,'' Leonard said the day of the announcement.
``Employees had a hell of a lot more to worry about a week ago than
today.''
</P>
<P>
   As Leonard campaigned last week in New York and Boston for his
deal, Wall Street analysts and utility regulators predicted the
merger will win approval from shareholders and federal and local
agencies. By Friday, Entergy's stock price had recouped its losses.
(SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   His mentor, Barker, now 74 and 12 years into retirement, said
Leonard's latest career turn is simply part of his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised at all,'' Barker said. ``Not only is Wayne
extremely intelligent, but he has something else to go along with
it. I call it wisdom. I think he shares my philosophy that real
success is producing someone who is better than you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Leonard pull off the Entergy-FPL merger?
</P>
<P>
   ``My bets would be unhedged on Wayne's ability to succeed,''
Barker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
