<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' STAR: ONE MAN IS AN ISLAND FAVORITE
</HEADLINE>
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is the subject of much outrage and derision on the Internet;
critics have called him a manipulative Machiavellian egomaniac; and
he seems to be especially irritating to David Letterman, who has
labeled him ``that naked fat guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But almost 30 million people are watching him on television
every week: Richard Hatch is a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Heather Locklear on `Melrose Place,''' said Lisa
Miller-Katz, a casting director for numerous television series, but
not this one. ``He's the villain that you love to hate. He's a
casting dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the producer of ``Survivor,'' Mark Burnett, and CBS'
casting executives had no way of knowing exactly what they were
getting when they selected Hatch as one of the 16 original
castaways on what was expected to be a kind of summer curiosity.
About all they knew was that he was a ``corporate trainer'' from
Newport, R.I., with a lot of self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But now ``Survivor'' has become the most talked-about show in
America, a certifiable cultural phenomenon that has set ratings
records and recruited an entire new audience to CBS. And Richard
Hatch is unquestionably one of the biggest reasons the show has
worked so well.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first few weeks, Hatch set himself up as the center
of the drama on the deserted island where ``Survivor'' takes place.
He created an alliance _ and boasted about it on camera _ with
three others who have consistently voted together to eliminate
opponents as designated by Hatch, who seemed to pick his targets on
the basis of who had the most potential to keep him from winning
the $1 million prize that goes to the ultimate survivor.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has proved so effective that every member of the
original opposing tribe has been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very well cast, and he has played his part really
well,'' Miller-Katz said. ``If you can find a villain that makes
people hiss, that's incredibly valuable. Without someone like
Richard, I know I wouldn't be as rapt as I have been every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she especially likes him. ``I think he's incredibly
icky,'' Miller-Katz said, echoing the judgments of many other
viewers who have rooted for Hatch to get his comeuppance and be
eliminated by his fellow castaways. Certainly he made news by
parading around the island naked on several occasions, images that
were tastefully scrambled by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman has made him the target of almost nightly invective,
at one point declaring that if ``the fat naked guy'' wins the
contest, ``there's going to be rioting in the streets, there's
going to be looting.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't prevented Hatch from being the most sought-after
``Survivor'' participant. How hot is he? CBS executives say they
have received a flood of media requests for appearances by Hatch as
soon as he is either voted off the island or wins the game, all of
which will be determined on the show's final episodes, Wednesday
night and next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Until then Hatch is unavailable for comment. CBS's policy is to
forbid media appearances until a contestant's fate is sealed on the
show. Colleen Haskell, a perky student from Miami ousted last week
in Hatch's latest purge, was deluged with dozens of requests for
interviews and offers for appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Previous ``Survivor'' losers have already found outlets. Jenna
Lewis, a college student from New Hampshire, is mulling an offer to
pose nude for Playboy. Stacey Stillman, a lawyer from San
Francisco, and B.B. Andersen, a retired contractor from Kansas,
have already filmed commercials for Reebok. Ramona Gray, a
biochemist from Edison, N.J., is to be a judge at the Miss Teen USA
Pageant on CBS on Aug. 26. Dirk Been, a substitute teacher from
Wisconsin, was hired as a celebrity spokesman for a health-care
remedy. And Gervase Peterson, a youth basketball coach from a
Philadelphia suburb, has taped a guest appearance on the sitcom
``The Hugleys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has already been sought for appearances at colleges and
state fairs. And this is before he has had the chance to go out and
market himself, something he seems to have a talent for.
</P>
<P>
   Just where his skills might be best used is open to question.
Miller-Katz said that the cast of CBS' other summer reality series,
``Big Brother,'' has turned out to be ``totally boring.'' So maybe
his best immediate use for CBS might be as an interloper at that
house.
</P>
<P>
   Now playing the part of George: Richard Hatch. If can make a hit
of that one, he'll be able to name his own price.
</P>
<P>
   Big Prize at Big House
</P>
<P>
   If you like to watch 16 people trying to survive on an island,
maybe you'll be up for 10 people trying to escape from a prison.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has bought the format rights to yet another British reality
series, ``Jailbreak.'' The network seems excited at the prospect of
this one, though it did not intend to announce that it owned the
rights until after the series goes on the air on Channel 5 in
Britain next month.
</P>
<P>
   Even though CBS has had the big success with reality shows this
summer, ABC has been the most aggressive network in lining up the
next generation of the genre, having already acquired ``The Mole''
(a group of people on a sort of scavenger hunt are sabotaged by one
in their midst) and ``The Runner,'' (viewers across the country
hunt for one contestant assigned to perform various tasks in
secret).
</P>
<P>
   The sale of rights to ``Jailbreak'' _ like those to
``Survivor,'' ``Big Brother'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
_ was negotiated by Ben Silverman of the William Morris Agency, who
became an advocate of the reality genre during a four-year stay in
England. ``I really love this one,'' he said. ```Jailbreak' has a
chance to be really huge.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was created by two young British producers, Sebastian
Scott and Henrietta Conrad, who own Princess Productions. Channel
5, which Silverman described as a ``Fox-like, young alternative
network,'' built a prison equipped with cameras and the latest in
electronic devices, like laser-beam alarms, which the contestants
will have to thwart if they are to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Prize money (no specific amount yet) awaits the escapees. The
group will be allowed to work in teams but then must share the
money. If an individual gets out first, he gets it all.
</P>
<P>
   All the prisoners will be given clues on how to escape,
Silverman said, and sometimes they can get a task accomplished only
by working together.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which will run every night for weeks in Britain, is
more likely to be a weekly series on ABC. It will also add some
devilish touches, like having two guards _ one good, one bad _ who
are identical twins.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives declined to discuss the show or the deal. One
reason: they want to get a look at how the format works in Britain
first. Given the need to build the prison, it is likely that the
show will take at least six months to get on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Another Dose of Reality
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Ramona Gray from ``Survivor'' to the judging
panel at the Miss Teen USA contest was the inspiration for that
pageant to change its rules.
</P>
<P>
   Now there will be a ``Survivor''-like vote to reduce the last
five contestants to three. All of the previously eliminated 46
contestants (from the 50 states plus and the District of Columbia)
will be asked to vote for the two contestants they want to
eliminate from the five semifinalists. Then the judges will pick
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick was added to take advantage of the ``Survivor''
phenomenon, but a friend of one contestant said that not all the
participants are thrilled. Some of the participants were troubled,
the friend said, by the prospect of voting to dismiss people to
whom they might become close during the course of the two-week
pageant.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for CBS said the contest would go on with the
rule-change intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
