<SLUG> BC-SECRET-SALAD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets Of Success: Eggplant Cubes and Goat Cheese Team Up in 
 Anjou Salad  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Pierre Morin is a classic French chef who creates
simple, satisfying combinations at his cute restaurant, Anjou,
tucked away in an alley off Union Square.
<P>
   Few dishes are as exciting as his Warm Eggplant with Goat Cheese
Salad. Cubes of eggplant simmer in vegetable broth, infusing the
flesh with flavor and creating a velvet-like texture. Goat cheese
is then coated in nuts and quickly fried to give the contrast of
crunchy/creamy and cool/hot. A drizzle of tangy red wine
vinaigrette completes the dish with an explosion of flavor. You can
use any vinaigrette, but the best is made with 3 parts oil to 1
part vinegar with salt, pepper and Dijon mustard to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Morin hails from Anjou, a province of France known for its
cheeses and vegetables, so the man knows his goat cheese. His
cooking style evolved over many years of cooking all over the world
with the French Navy. He found his way to San Francisco working for
Kennedy's White House chef Rene Verdon at Le Trianon. He uses all
of that to create a casual full-flavored cuisine that bows to
California freshness.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant combines brick walls with gleaming brass on the
two-level interior. A partly open kitchen on the lower level adds a
warm inviting feel to this out-of-the-way place.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Anjou, 44 Campton Place (near Sutter), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 392-5373. Lunch and dinner Tuesday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Poaching the eggplant. &LR;  Simmering eggplant cubes in vegetable
stock adds loads of flavor and gives the flesh a soft, seductive
texture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Making it ahead. &LR;  The cheese may be cut, coated and
refrigerated overnight. The eggplant may be cooked 1 day ahead and
left in the vegetable broth. It needs only quick reheating before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WARM EGGPLANT SALAD WITH GOAT CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11 ounces fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 drops + 11/2 cups olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 drops + 2 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   21/2 ounces chopped blanched almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, halved
</P>
<P>
   4 thyme sprigs
</P>
<P>
   4 parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   3 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 eggplants, peeled and cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Red Wine Vinaigrette (see recipe), or other vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   12 cherry tomatoes, halved
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Dip a sharp knife into hot water, then slice the goat cheese
into 6 equal portions.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the egg with the 2 drops of olive oil and 2 drops of water
in a small bowl. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the cheese portions in the flour, dip into the egg mixture,
then roll in the almonds until evenly coated. Place on a baking
sheet and refrigerate until just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the 2 quarts of water, the celery, carrot, onion,
garlic, thyme, parsley and bay leaves in a large pot. Bring to a
boil over high heat. Reduce heat and simmer for 20 minutes. Strain.
Return the liquid to the pot and bring to a boil over high heat.
Add the eggplants, 1/2 cup of the olive oil and the lemon juice.
Simmer for 5 to 8 minutes, stirring frequently, until the eggplant
is tender. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   (Eggplant may be prepared to this point 1 day ahead. Warm over
low heat before serving.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 cup olive oil in a deep pan over
medium-high heat. Working in batches, gently place the goat cheese
in the hot oil and fry for about 2 minutes per side, or until
evenly browned. Using a slotted spoon, transfer the cheese to paper
towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the eggplant and divide among appetizer-size plates. Add
the red onion and drizzle with Red Wine Vinaigrette. Top with the
cheese, and garnish with parsley and cherry tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 475 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 16 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 41 g fat (12 g saturated), 59 mg cholesterol, 224
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; RED WINE VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon (or more) red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Season the oil with salt and pepper. Let stand for at least 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the vinegar and mustard in a small bowl.
Gradually whisk in the oil until the dressing has a creamy
consistency. Taste, and whisk in more vinegar, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1/2 cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
