</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Lovers of the Grape Debate Rating Wine by the 
 Numbers  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Wine scoring is one of the most contentious issues
circulating in the wine community. At the heart of the controversy
is the question of whether numbers should be used to rate wines.
<P>
   Those who favor numbers, mainly wine publications, say it is the
most efficient way to tell the consumer about a wine's quality. The
more passionate opponents claim that numbers tell the buyer nothing
about a wine. ``You can't give works of art a score _ quick,
where's the Mona Lisa, I'm double-parked,'' quipped British wine
writer Tim Atkin of The Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Atkin opposes what he sees as the tyranny of wine scoring:
``Scores don't describe a wine, they play on people's insecurities.
You should trust your own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkin was a panelist in the spirited debate called ``Scoring,
Rating, Evaluating: Can You Quantify Quality?'' at the World
Vinifera Conference held last month in Seattle. Although nothing
was resolved, the panelists, at the urging of wine writer Matt
Kramer, gave the audience food for thought and a good time.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Australian wine writer James Halliday was more pointed
about insecurity. ``The United States is a culture that seems to
need reassurance. But I think it's hard to argue against using
points because it's easier to give points than words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers demand scores,'' said Steve Tanzer, publisher of
International Wine Cellar. ``Scores force a degree of discipline
and I don't think that writers can be blamed for a wine getting a
specific score.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But how do you find out what people like from a score?'' asked
Ann C. Noble, a professor of enology at the University of
California at Davis. ``Instead of giving scores to wines, we need
to educate consumers to make choices they will like.''
</P>
<P>
   What has everybody so steamed is the so-called ``100-Point
Scale'' that is used by most major wine publications to rate a
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Noted wine writer Robert Parker Jr. is credited with first using
the 100-point system. As his popularity and power rose, many other
writers and wine publications, such as Wine Spectator, got on
board, claiming that to not use the 100-Point Scale would put them
at a disadvantage in a competitive business.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the bar keeps moving up. Not long ago, wines rarely
scored below 50 points, and a wine scoring above 80 was considered
very good. Now, a wine that gets less than 90 points is thought by
many, who rely slavishly on the scoring system, as not worth their
time or money. Nevertheless, many in the wine industry view scores
as the Holy Grail of wine sales. Get a high score from Parker or
Wine Spectator and your sales woes disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is true, said audience member David Lake, winemaker
for Columbia Winery in Washington. ``But it's really hard for
winemakers if the wine doesn't get a 90 or above. Scores are too
final, a snapshot from day and time.''
</P>
<P>
   Noble nodded and added, ``The horrible thing about points is
they drive profits and power.'' Still, the practitioners feel
trapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a former winemaker, I found that a high rating from the
Wine Spectator helped sell the wine,'' added Jeff Morgan, wine
director for Dean&AMP;Deluca and a former staff member of Wine
Spectator. ``A word description didn't get as much attention as a
rating. Still, I wouldn't use scores if I had a choice, but it's
industry demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanzer agreed, stating that although he uses scores, ``I would
rather publish just notes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Chronicle Way &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Word descriptions matched to a rating of one to four stars is
the method used by The Chronicle Wine Tasting Panel. We believe it
is easier for the consumer to distinguish between a two-star wine
and a three-star wine, especially if a description supports the
rating. With the 100-point scale, statistics refute scores, and the
irony of the marketplace is that a wine scoring an 89 is not
thought to be as good as one with a 90 score.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Winery Changes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rarely a month goes by in the California wine industry without a
change. The latest has Arrowood Vineyards &AMP; Winery, in Sonoma's
Valley of the Moon, joining the growing family of Napa's Robert
Mondavi Wines. Arrowood produces super-premium varietal wines from
grapes grown throughout Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   Founder and winemaker Richard Arrowood and his wife and partner,
Alis, will continue in their present roles at the winery, as will
all current Arrowood employees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Events &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Beringer Vineyards will hold its annual Fall Wine Opener
September 22, 5-8 p.m., at the winery, 2000 Main St., St. Helena.
Beringer's new-release wines will be available for tasting, as well
as wine and food pairings. Tickets are $100 per person and may be
ordered by calling (707) 963-8989, Ext. 4443. Attendance is limited
to 400 guests.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 26th Annual Sonoma County Harvest Fair is 10 a.m.-8 p.m.
Oct. 6; and 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Oct. 7 and 8 at the Sonoma County
Fairgrounds, at the intersection of Highway 101 and Highway 12 in
Santa Rosa. Included are wine and food tastings, exhibits, music
and the World Championship Grape Stomp. Admission is $5 for ages 13
and up, $2 for ages 7-12. For more information, call (707)
545-4203.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Appellation Collections &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's not too early to think about holiday wine gifts. The Stags
Leap District Winegrowers is offering its unique Appellation
Collection, a mixed case of Stags Leap District Cabernet Sauvignons
(or Cabernet-based blends) from each of the 12 member wineries,
including Chimney Rock Winery, Pine Ridge Winery, Robert Sinskey
Vineyards, Shafer Vineyards and Steltzner Vineyards. The cost is
$695, plus shipping and tax for California sales.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact Nancy Bialek at (707) 255-1720, or
log on to  &LR; www.stagsleapdistrict.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
