 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: Casa Fiesta Fries the Bean Competition  By Robin Davis  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; If you're making Mexican specialties, refried
beans may be involved, either in the recipe or as a side dish.
<P>
   Today's panel tasted seven brands of refried pinto beans,
including some labeled organic or low-fat. Selections were limited
to those labeled vegetarian and excluded any with specific
seasonings such as chile or lime.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were surprised how much the brands differed in taste
and texture. They also agreed that different brands would be good
for different uses. Some tasted great on their own; others were
bland, but might work well in recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Casa Fiesta &LR;  (16 ounces, 99 cents at Bell Markets) got the top
ranking. Two panelists liked the bean flavor and smooth, creamy
texture. Another thought the beans tasted particularly
well-balanced. However, one dissenter did not like the seasonings.
Two would buy it, two might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Taco Bell Home Originals &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.29 at Safeway) came in
second. Most panelists liked spiciness and aggressive seasoning.
One described the texture as ``slightly mushy.'' Three would buy
it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the rest was  &UR; Bearitos &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.49 at Whole
Foods), in third place. Two panelists liked the smooth texture;
three liked the flavor. Two would buy it, one might buy it, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safeway &LR;  (16 ounces, 99 cents at Safeway) came in fourth, with
tasters disagreeing over appearance and flavor. Some thought the
mixture looked too dark and raw; others liked the flavor, but
thought it needed salt; still others described the flavor as raw
and muddled. Two might buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rosarita &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.19-$1.29 at many supermarkets) was
fifth. Two panelists were put off by the appearance. Three liked
the flavor, but others thought it had a sour aftertaste. One would
buy it, one might buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Albertsons and ShariAnn's, but they scored
too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Marc Halperin,
culinary director, Center for Culinary Development; Shelley
Handler, consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe
For All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe
Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for any prduct would be 100.
All products are tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
