<SLUG> BC-SOURCEGARLIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 At the Source: Galic Grower's Cloves for All Seasons   By Amber Thompson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 OCCIDENTAL, Calif. _  Chester Aaron eats bruschetta for breakfast
every day. His recipe is simple: toast, garlic, olive oil, salt and
pepper. The hard part is choosing the garlic _ he grows 87
varieties.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My former students used to hate it when I came into class in
the morning,'' laughs Aaron, a 77-year-old retired St. Mary's
College professor-turned-garlic-farmer. They wouldn't like it any
better later in the day, either _ in addition to his morning meal,
he eats another 10 cloves of raw garlic a day.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron has been an organic garlic farmer in Occidental for the
past 16 years. Last October, he planted 32,000 cloves. That
resulted in a 11/2-ton harvest last month.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron spends about 25 hours a week growing garlic and the
remaining time writing about it. He has already published two
books, ``Garlic is Life,'' and ``The Great Garlic Book'' (both
published by Ten Speed Press), and is currently working on a third.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron began his farming career by planting California Late, the
variety most widely available. But it was the Russian Red Toch that
really ignited his passion. While working on a sheep ranch near
Bodega Bay, Aaron encountered a Russian-speaking farmer who was
carrying a twisted, ugly head of garlic. He discovered that the
garlic was from his father's birth city, Tochliavri, in the
Republic of Georgia. Aaron immediately planted two bulbs _ and
became a full-fledged member of the garlic-growing community.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Aaron continued to meet growers across the world,
from Paris to Japan, and his collection grew rapidly. Today, he
plants Armenian, Creole Red, Siberian, Xian and 83 other garlics.
</P>
<P>
   Some varieties feature heads that are downright ugly, but
others, like the Siberian, are fit to be centerpieces. The Romanian
Red has large, distinct cloves covered by dull, brittle brown skin.
Leningrad is petite in comparison and has papery-thin purple skin.
The Beijing cloves are a challenge to peel, but the Duganskij are a
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The outer differences don't even hint at the garlic's inner
essence. To taste the difference, Aaron suggests pressing two
tablespoons of each type of garlic into one cup of hummus. The
hummus provides a neutral background that allows the garlic to
speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the heat of the Russian Red Streak strikes right up
front in your mouth. Others, like the Acropolis, hit the back of
the throat, and still others grab the sides of the tongue. The heat
from garlic also comes in different strengths. Whereas Monshanski
makes a bold first impression and dissipates within seconds, the
French Red seems to burn for minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron contends that garlic tastings are similar to wine
tastings. Comparing Creole Red to Russian Red Toch is like
comparing Merlot to Zinfandel. And when it comes to taste, vintage
and terroir both matter. ``Land is the major element in growing
garlic,'' he says. A head of Armenian garlic grown in Aaron's soil
will not have the same nuances as one grown even a few miles north.
</P>
<P>
   Just as wines pair differently with food, so does garlic.
Russian Red Toch's heavy richness and moderate heat is perfect in a
cheesy lasagna. Siberian, with its large, solid cloves, is great
roasted. Persian Star's ``mild, spicy zing'' goes with fish dishes,
and earthy Xian with wild mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   And after you've indulged in any garlicky meal, Aaron
recommends, ``Chew parsley to get rid of the garlic on your breath
and in your sweat.'' He also advises rubbing your fingers with
lemon.
</P>
<P>
   These uncommon varieties can be difficult to find. Aaron's
garlic is available by subscription, and a good selection is
available online from  &LR; www.gourmetgarlicgardens.com &LR;  and
 &LR; www.ashleycreek.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aaron's Garlic, P.O. Box 388, Occidental, Calif. 95465; (707) &LR; 
 &LR; 874-3114. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
