<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2464 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      08-15 1534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 The Working Cook: Making a Meal out of an Appetizer  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Why is it that when you go to fine restaurants the
appetizers always sound the best? They're so delicately appealing,
so balanced in their juxtapositions of hot and cool, sweet and
tart, crunchy and soft _ like seared foie gras with rhubarb compote
or frisee with pancetta dressing. So often I wish I could order
just appetizers. I'd order them all and eat them one by one in
sweet little bites.
<P>
   At Globe restaurant a few months ago, I had a great ahi tuna
tartare. Though ahi usually is prepared with Asian sesame oil, or
Ponzu or pineapple jus, this time it was pared with bits of green
olive; it was an unusual but amazing combination.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since that meal, I have wanted to use that same flavor
combination for a recipe for this column. But all I could come up
with were appetizer-type dishes, and what working cook has time to
make more than one course in this day and age? I decided that the
way around this problem was like going to a restaurant and ordering
only appetizers: Just turn the appetizer into dinner by making more
of it.
</P>
<P>
   Today's 30-Minute recipe, Seared Ahi Tuna with Green Olive
Toasts &AMP; Heirloom Tomato Salad, is like all good appetizers in that
it looks beautiful, which is why the recipe is very specific about
presentation. Try to find heirloom tomatoes in tones of green and
yellow and purple; they will glisten next to the fat slices of ahi,
which reveal ruby-red bellies.
</P>
<P>
   The Cool Soba Noodles with Garlic Pork &AMP; Mushrooms is an easy
dish that you can make in many different guises. Try using chicken
instead of pork, or use no meat at all, just mushrooms, which work
particularly well with the earthy flavor of buckwheat noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Soba noodles are easy to overcook, which is one of the reasons
recipes often call for cooling them under running water after
cooking. But I prefer not to totally douse them under the faucet or
they end up too slippery.
</P>
<P>
   Red Beans &AMP; Rice is the perfect Now &AMP; Later dish because it just
keeps getting better, even if you freeze it. The spices, which in
this recipe were deftly put together by Food Section intern Scott
Clapp, continue to permeate the beans over time. Scott also
suggests serving the sausages on top of the beans instead of
chopping them and integrating them into the beans. This creates a
great contrast in texture. The texture and flavor will be even
better if you decide to throw the sausages on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COOL SOBA NOODLES WITH GARLIC PORK &AMP; MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Soba are Japanese noodles that are gray-brown because they are
made partly of buckwheat flour. They can be found in Asian food
stores, specialty markets and some supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless center-cut pork loin chops
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 package (8.8 ounces) soba noodles
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon + 1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   5 green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 package (6 ounces) sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   about 4 ounces preshredded carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons black sesame seeds, or white sesame seeds, if
black are unavailable
</P>
<P>
   Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice vinegar, or 2 teaspoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chile oil
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of water to a boil over high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cut the pork into julienne strips and place in a
small bowl with the soy sauce. Mince the garlic and stir it into
the pork. Set aside to marinate at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   When the water boils, add the noodles and cook for 3 to 5
minutes, or until just al dente. Drain and lightly rinse, tossing
the noodles as you rinse them. Drain well. Place the noodles in a
large bowl and toss with the 1/2 teaspoon vegetable oil to keep
them from sticking. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the green onions into segments about same length as the pork
strips, discarding rough ends, then slice lengthwise into julienne
strips.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Make the sauce:  &LR; Mix together the soy sauce, vinegar, chile oil
and sesame oil in a small bowl. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 1 tablespoon vegetable oil in a medium
skillet over high heat. Add the mushrooms and stir-fry for about 1
minute. Add the carrots and pork. Stir-fry for 1 to 2 minutes, or
until the pork is no longer pink. Add the pork mixture and sauce to
the noodles, quickly toss, then toss in most of the green onions,
reserving some for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Serve in large bowls, and garnish each with green onions and
sesame seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 510 calories, &LR;   &LR; 34 g protein, 55 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 17 g fat (4 g saturated), 68 mg cholesterol, 1,206
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEARED AHI TUNA WITH GREEN OLIVE TOASTS &AMP; HEIRLOOM TOMATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 thin baguette (not sourdough) (you'll need about three
quarters of the loaf)
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ahi tuna fillets, or other high-quality fresh tuna
fillets
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds mixed-color heirloom tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons green olive paste, or green olive-based
tapenade
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the baguette on the diagonal into 1-inch thick slices; try
to get about 16 long, pointed pieces. Place in a bowl and sprinkle
lightly with 1 teaspoon of the olive oil and a pinch of salt. Toss
to coat. Place the slices on a baking sheet and bake for 5 minutes
per side, or until the toasts are browned.
</P>
<P>
   Finely mince the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the ahi in large pieces. Rub both sides of each piece with
salt, pepper and garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the tomatoes into thin wedges and place in a bowl. Drizzle
with 2 teaspoons olive oil and season with a dash of salt and
pepper; toss gently.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 to 2 teaspoons olive oil in a large skillet over high
heat. Add the tuna and saute for about 1 minute per side for rare
(ruby-red but warm in the middle).
</P>
<P>
   Spread each toast with a small amount (about 1/2 teaspoon) of
the green olive paste. Slice the tuna about 1/2-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the toasts on plates, pointy ends pointing out, then
drape a piece of tuna over each one. Divide the tomato salad among
plates and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 430 calories, &LR;   &LR; 35 g protein, 44 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 12 g fat (2 g saturated), 51 mg cholesterol, 527 mg
sodium, 4 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RED BEANS &AMP; RICE
</P>
<P>
   Food Section intern Scott Clapp helped develop and test this
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups small red beans
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   8 celery stalks, trimmed and cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   3 onions, cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   3 green bell peppers, stemmed, deribbed and cut into medium dice
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds smoked ham hocks
</P>
<P>
   7 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   About 1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 cups long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   6 andouille sausages
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Pick over the beans, discarding any stones and broken or
withered beans. Rinse well. Place the beans in large pot and add
water to cover by 2 or 3 inches. Bring to a boil over high heat,
then cover, remove from heat and let soak for 1 hour. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic powder, thyme, cayenne, black pepper, white
pepper and bay leaves in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in large Dutch oven over medium-low heat. Add the
celery, onions, bell peppers, garlic and the spice mix and cook,
stirring often, for 7 to 10 minutes, or until the vegetables have
softened. Add the beans and stir briefly to coat with the spices.
Add the ham hocks and stock and bring to a boil over high heat.
(Make sure the ham hocks are submerged; if not, find a narrower
pot.) Reduce heat and simmer steadily for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in salt a little at a time until it tastes right to you.
Simmer for about 30 minutes, or until the beans are tender and the
liquid has thickened to a saucelike consistency.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes before the beans are done, prepare the rice
according to package directions. Cut the sausages in half
lengthwise and brown in a skillet or on a grill.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the ham hocks from the beans, cut the meat from the bones
into bite-size chunks and return to the beans.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon rice into bowls and top each serving with a ladle of beans
and a slice of browned sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 785 calories, &LR;   &LR; 37 g protein, 106 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 23 g fat (7 g saturated), 70 mg cholesterol, 1,277
mg sodium, 9 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
