<SLUG> BC-BESTCHIX-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Best Way: Grilling Chicken   By Scott Clapp 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Backyard grilling remains one of life's little
pleasures. Throw the meat on the grill and sit back and relax while
the aromas wafting from your grill make your neighbor's mouth
water. But what is the best way to guarantee that those wonderful
smells result in the perfect grilled chicken?
<P>
   To find out, we grilled lightly seasoned bone-in, skin-on
breasts on a small charcoal grill.
</P>
<P>
   We tried various methods, including searing the chicken over
medium heat and moving it to a warm part of the grill to finish
cooking, cooking it completely over medium coals, and cooking it
over hot coals. We also tried these covered and uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly unanimous winner among the Food Department staff was
the chicken that was cooked on a covered grill entirely over medium
coals. It produced the perfect balance of smoky flavor and moist
chicken, as well as golden, crisp skin.
</P>
<P>
   We then tested two commonly suggested time-saving techniques.
First, we microwaved the chicken for five minutes per pound prior
and finished it on the grill. Second, we seared the chicken on the
grill and then moved it to a 350 degrees oven to finish. Neither of
these techniques proved popular.
</P>
<P>
   The microwaved chicken was inconsistent _ moist and delicious in
one bite, dry and rubbery in the next. And the time saved was
minimal _ 18 minutes for the microwave/grill version versus 26
minutes for chicken cooked entirely on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing the chicken in the oven frees the cook to work on
other parts of the meal, but the chicken, as might be expected,
lacked any characteristic smoky flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The last part of our final test explored when to salt the
chicken. We added salt before, during and after grilling and also
tried adding half of the salt before and half after grilling. Most
agreed the differences were minimal, but the chicken with half the
salt added before grilling and the rest added after grilling was
the slight favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lightly season the chicken with pepper and half of the desired
salt. Using medium heat, grill the chicken directly over the coals,
covering the grill and turning the chicken often until cooked
through, about 25-30 minutes. (Cooking times vary depending on the
size of the chicken and the heat of the grill.) After removing the
chicken from the grill, season with the remaining salt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
