<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS DELEGATION AS DIVERSE AS THEIR STATE
 &HT;    Attn: Texas points
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By statistic and story, the Texans populating
Section 108 of the Staples Center during the Democratic National
Convention are as diverse as the state they represent.
</P>
<P>
   It's a diversity that ranges from the first-time delegate who is
keeping her e-mail network updated on the convention goings-on to
the party's elder stateswoman who attended her first convention in
1928; from the party-switcher who says Republicans inspired her to
become a Democrat to the Army vet who says she was inspired by the
Democrats to come out of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics paint part of the picture. Of the 231 delegates
here, 49 percent are white, 24 percent are Hispanic and 22 percent
are black. Overall, Texas is about 55 percent white, 30 percent Hi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-TEXAS16-COX     08-15 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXAS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS DELEGATION AS DIVERSE AS THEIR STATE
 &HT;    Attn: Texas points
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ By statistic and story, the Texans populating
Section 108 of the Staples Center during the Democratic National
Convention are as diverse as the state they represent.
</P>
<P>
   It's a diversity that ranges from the first-time delegate who is
keeping her e-mail network updated on the convention goings-on to
the party's elder stateswoman who attended her first convention in
1928; from the party-switcher who says Republicans inspired her to
become a Democrat to the Army vet who says she was inspired by the
Democrats to come out of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics paint part of the picture. Of the 231 delegates
here, 49 percent are white, 24 percent are Hispanic and 22 percent
are black. Overall, Texas is about 55 percent white, 30 percent
Hispanic and 12 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only 8 percent of the Texas delegation to the GOP
convention were Hispanic, and only 2 percent were black.
</P>
<P>
   But the stories about how the Texans got to Section 108 tell
more than the numbers do. The stories are chronicled in background
information provided to the party by the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The experience extremes are typified by Houston delegates Billie
Carr, who thinks she is at her last convention, and Catherine Read,
who is at her first.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, long a bulwark of the Texas Democratic Party, tells about
her first convention experience in a release entitled ``My First
Convention, or Can You Top This?''
</P>
<P>
   Carr's first was in her home town in the only year Houston
hosted the Democrats. It was 1928, and Al Smith was the nominee.
Her parents, active in Democratic politics, got two guest passes
from the local fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother planned for me to stay with my grandmother, but my
father said he wanted to take me, this was history,'' Carr
recalled. ``They dressed me up, wrapped me in a blanket and off we
went to the convention. I was 27 days old. I still have the passes
and buttons from this convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, she attended her next Democratic National
</P>
<P>
   Convention, the memorable 1968 event in Chicago. As a liberal
firebrand, Carr wound up involved with a dissident group shut out
of Texas Democratic mainstream activities, including that year's
state
</P>
<P>
   convention. She led a challenge group that eventually sparked
major changes in the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rented a bus and headed to Chicago. Since we were not an
official group, we could not get rooms. I called the YMCA and they
let us rent rooms,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   They lost in a credentials fight, but Carr got to participate in
what made the convention infamous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did get caught up in the police riot and some of us were
maced, hit and arrested, but that's another story,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carr has been a delegate at all Democratic conventions since
1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I am retiring from the Democratic National Committee
and this will probably be my last national convention,'' said Carr,
ailing and participating from a wheelchair at the rear of the
delegation's section. ``I am 72 years old. Baby has come a long way
from 27 days old. I have loved every minute.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the experience spectrum is Read, who was a
sergeant at arms at the Republican National Convention in Houston,
an event _ especially Pat Buchanan's speech _ that convinced her
she was hanging out with the wrong folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the GOP for good in 1994 when the right-wing takeover
of the Texas GOP was complete and my moderate GOP congressional
candidate lost the primary to a far-right opponent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Read now works for Continental Airlines and is using e-mail to
send daily convention updates to her friends back home. Her first
dispatch detailed the long days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone bring me coffee in the morning _ they don't have any
in-room coffee pots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Russell, 62, of San Antonio, is a retired Army lieutenant
colonel who credits the party for helping her to do something she
once thought impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent most of my years in the closet. The Democratic Party
has made it possible for me to be out, open and active in bringing
about change and greater acceptance in our society,'' she wrote.
``For gays and lesbians, it is critical to our future to elect Al
Gore and other
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidates. If the Republicans win in November, I
believe that social issues will be set back at least 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Sidney Schwartz of San Benito, like many Texans,
started elsewhere. Born in New York in 1925, Schwartz helped
develop specialized clothing and equipment for the U.S. Navy. He
helped fit John Glenn for his first space suit and later, while
working for Grumman Aerospace, helped develop the first
zero-gravity toilet.
</P>
<P>
   After retirement, Schwartz and wife Elenore returned to South
Texas, where he had served in the military, 10 years ago and became
active in Democratic politics. They believe Texas Democrats could
begin to reverse the GOP trend by pushing ``winter Texans'' in the
Rio Grande Valley to register to vote in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is a rich area to mine for the long-term
Democratic renewed strength,'' he said. ``Senior citizens have a
great advantage over younger voters in that they have lived and
seen past American political history.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   First-time delegate Kelly Holmes, 22, of Austin is a student who
is using her musical talents to further the Democratic cause. She
contributes to an anti-George W. Bush Web site that uses parody
songs to make its points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a lot of Americans are apathetic about the political
process, so our hope is to engage them with the humor in our songs
and to expose Bush as the idiot he is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Janet Caro Murphy of Dallas found her own way into
Democratic politics as a New York delegate to the 1972 and 1980
conventions. But it was love that got her into Texas Democratic
politics.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1980 convention, while waiting in a long line, she began
chatting with Craig Murphy, a Dallas delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept talking for several months, and, as he tells is, when
the phone bills became excessive, we got married,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Richard Acker III of Houston also traces his party ties
to a profoundly personal event, though it happened in a crowd of
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first experience with the party was when I was 6 years old,
in the first grade, when I attended the parade in Dallas on Nov.
22, 1963 and witnessed the assassination of President Kennedy,'' he
wrote. ``From then until I was able to vote at the age of 18 I
believe I subconsciously sided with the party and its values.''
</P>
<P>
   Cory Rico't(cq), 68, of Odessa, also remembers Democratic
politics played out at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first job as an activist was in 1936 at age 5. My parents
were illegally posting `Vote for Lyndon Johnson' signs on telephone
poles,'' she wrote. ``My job was to honk the car horn when another
car came so they could hide. I have been a Democratic activist ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 68, and suffering from multiple sclerosis and failing
vision, she is ``thrilled'' to be a first &QC; time delegate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked in many campaigns and helped raise many dollars.
Unfortunately, I have slowed down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
