<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-0816     08-15 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH, FRENCH OFFICIALS TO GROUND REMAINING CONCORDES; BRITISH
AIRWAYS CANCELS FLIGHTS
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Three weeks after an Air France Concorde crashed in
flames near Paris, French and British aviation authorities decided
Tuesday to ground the supersonic passenger plane until it can be
made safe to fly.
</P>
<P>
   British and French air safety officials said they would revoke
the Concorde's airworthiness certificate Wednesday. After being
informed of the decision Tuesday morning, British Airways
immediately grounded its seven Concordes. Air France had not flown
its Concordes since the July 25 crash that killed 113.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation officials based their decision on preliminary findings
by French investigators that a burst tire, which sent debris
rifling through the fuel tanks in the left wing, caused the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   French officials said they would explain their unexpected action
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear when the glamorous supersonic aircraft, which
debuted in 1976, will carry passengers again. Only 12 remain in
operation.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways Chief Executive Rod Eddington said the airline
acted within minutes of being told of the impending decision. ``In
those circumstances we must put our fleet on the ground
immediately,'' Eddington told reporters at London's Heathrow
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airline cancelled its morning flight to New York after the
Concorde had begun to taxi down the runway at Heathrow. The 37
passengers were shifted to conventional subsonic aircraft
</P>
<P>
   Air France grounded its fleet of five Concordes immediately
after the crash and said the supersonic aircraft would remain on
the ground indefinitely. British Airways, the only other airline to
fly the supersonic aircraft, resumed its Concorde operations the
day after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, British Airways and aviation officials said there
was no evidence of risk to passengers despite the French disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The British Civil Aviation Authority said Tuesday that it
expects to instruct the airline and manufacturers to take whatever
action needed to make the aircraft safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last few days it has emerged that a single tire burst
was the cause of the accident, and as a result we are of a view
that the certificate should be suspended,'' the spokesman said.
``We expect a formal recommendation from investigators in France
tomorrow morning. We will look at the specific recommendations and
then we will make our decision.''
</P>
<P>
   British Airways modified its fleet of Concordes in the mid-1990s
to prevent a similar tire-burst from causing catastrophic damage
and, on the basis of that modification, the airplanes had been
permitted to continue flying.
</P>
<P>
   However, after looking over the evidence from the French
investigation, British investigators apparently believe the risk of
a crash similar to the one in France to be too high.
</P>
<P>
   French investigators have said that they believe the accident
occurred when a 16-inch metal strip punctured a tire, sending
chunks of rubber into the aircraft's left wing fuel tanks. The
gushing fuel ignited, sending flames trailing some 200 feet behind
the doomed aircraft, which crashed into a small hotel in Gonesse,
France less than two minutes after take-off from Charles de Gaulle
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the first fatal accident involving the elite
Concorde in its 25 years of commercial flying.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview, Eddington said he hoped the Concorde
would fly again. ``We will need to understand the reasons that sit
behind the investigators' concerns, and until we know those reasons
and can reflect on them, we can't talk about when Concorde will be
back in the air,'' Eddington told Sky News.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on everything I know, it is a safe aircraft to fly. But
as I said, at the end of the day, we rest on the information
provided to us by the accident investigators and regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Wilson, a former Concorde test pilot, told reporters that
the revocation of an airworthiness certificate suggests substantial
fundamental problems with the aircraft. ``It's very unusual for
authorities to remove the certificate so swiftly,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do find this very shocking,'' Paul Beaver of Jane's Defense
Weekly told BBC Television. ``Some in-depth research has been done
which says something is wrong with Concorde.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
