<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2476 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHAKESPEARE-BERKSHIRE     08-15 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-BERKSHIRES-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPACIOUS, LEAFY NEW SETTING FOR AMBITIOUS SHAKESPEAREANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By IRIS FANGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ In ``Henry V,'' Shakespeare asked the groundlings
standing in the Globe's pit and the patrons crammed onto the hard
benches to use their imaginations and ``Suppose within the girdle
of these walls/Are now confin'd two mighty monarchies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Packer, the ebullient artistic director of the performing
troupe Shakespeare &AMP; Co., is making an equally audacious request of
her audiences here in Western Massachusetts: to envision an exact
replica of an Elizabethan playhouse nestled among the rolling
Berkshire hills at the company's new home.
</P>
<P>
   Where Shakespeare relied on his verse to conjure up the
illusion, Packer has a real building in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, and perhaps none too soon _ after its wrangles over use of
the Mount, the nearby Edith Wharton estate _ Shakespeare &AMP; Company
will be ensconced on 63 acres in Lenox, near Tanglewood. The
troupe, which has presented a large repertory of Shakespeare plays
in the summer and fall at the Wharton estate since 1978 and which
also runs an extensive school education program, bought the new
property in April for $4.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are 22 buildings on the site in various conditions of
repair, including an estate house, Springlawn, built in 1904, the
same era as Edith Wharton's home a mile away. A boys' school and a
religious organization were among the owners of the property at 70
Kemble St., which was ultimately sold by the National Music
Foundation, a nonprofit organization for the promotion of American
music. The foundation's own plans for a performing arts complex,
which it had shelved before the sale, did not include a copy of a
16th-century English theater.
</P>
<P>
   Given Packer's drive and the plans already in motion, a replica
of the Rose Theater, which once stood in London in Shakespeare's
time, is likely to be the core of what Packer hopes will be a major
center for Shakespearean performance, teaching and scholarship in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conversation at the new property, the director said
she had always wanted an Elizabethan theater. ``If you make
Shakespeare the backbone of what you do, it's a good idea to have
the physical space and condition that the scripts were written
for,'' she said. ``What we love about the Elizabethan playhouse is
the actor-audience relationship. The first half I wanted was the
aesthetic. The other half was that this would put us on the map.
It's a contribution to scholarship and a real contribution to
tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   If a casting director were to choose a Shakespearean role for
Packer, who is 61, it might be that of the vigorous Mistress
Quickly in ``Henry IV, Parts 1 and 2'' or the nurturing,
resourceful Nurse in ``Romeo and Juliet.'' Short and sturdy, with
strands of gray in her red hair, Packer has a wide smile, a laugh
that breaks out often and an English accent that is hard to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, she seems undaunted by the task facing her nonprofit
organization, with its budget of $2.8 million this year and its
staff of 100 artists, teachers and directors. The company has
estimated that the cost of the move to the new property over the
next five years, along with the purchase price, will come to nearly
$17 million, not including the expense of the Rose. Construction of
that building could run anywhere from $10 million to $30 million,
according to Michael A. Miller, the chairman of the company's board
of trustees. ``We don't really know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges are nothing new for Packer, whose energy and
determination tend to attract followers. Several of the company's
founders are still with her in the troupe's 23rd season, including
Dennis Krausnick, the director of training (and her husband); Kevin
G. Coleman, the director of education; John Hadden, a director, and
Mitchell Berenson, a trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Born near Birmingham, in northern England, Packer studied acting
at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art in London, then joined the
Royal Shakespeare Company and performed often on BBC-TV. By the
time she was in her mid-30s, she had determined to start a
Shakespeare theater of her own, where she could train English and
American actors to understand and express the feelings behind
Shakespeare's language.The idea would combine the British approach
to the spoken word with the American freedom of physical action,
enlivened by Packer's probing of the language for emotional truth.
She based her studies in part on the acting techniques developed by
the well-known voice teacher Kristin Linklater, who would later
become one of the founders of Shakespeare &AMP; Company. After several
visits to the United States in the 1970s and the failure of her
first attempt to start a theater in England, Packer came upon the
boarded-up Wharton estate while on an exploratory trip through the
Berkshires in 1978. With her co-founders, she raised the money to
buy it and created two separate entities: the performing troupe
Shakespeare &AMP; Company and, eventually, Edith Wharton Restoration
Inc., which was set up to restore and maintain the historic house.
The chronicle of those early years is told in ``The Companies She
Keeps'' (1985), a book by Helen Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades of critical praise and increasing audiences followed
as Packer directed Shakespeare's plays on the outdoor mainstage
behind the Wharton house, developed an indoor stage at the former
stables and presented adaptations of Wharton's works in the Salon
Theater _ the author's parlor _ with tea and cookies served during
intermission. In the Shakespeare productions especially, readily
accessible language continued to be the goal.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 review of Shakespeare's ``Comedy of Errors'' by the
company at the estate, Ben Brantley wrote in The New York Times
that ``the spoken lines get more laughs than the sight gags.''
Brantley went on to say that ``the director, John Hadden, has also
provided the verbal and aural equivalents of funny costumes and
pratfalls: silly accents, divertingly varied rhythms of speech and
vocally highlighted phrases that force us to listen.'' The result,
Brantley wrote, was that ``you can understand every word'' because
language ``is the unyielding cornerstone for theatrical
interpretation here.''
</P>
<P>
   During its years at the Mount, the company also developed
year-round education and training programs about Shakespeare in
public and private schools mainly in New England. These involve
touring to schools, colleges and community centers; residencies at
schools; and training workshops for teachers and professional
actors. The faculty is drawn from the troupe's artists and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the success of its productions and programs, the
company _ and Packer _ became embroiled in a dispute over control
of the Wharton estate with the group that had been set up to
restore it. The bitter struggle mirrored the rivalries depicted in
many of Shakespeare's plays. After repeated clashes about the use
of the Mount, it had become obvious by 1998 that Shakespeare &AMP;
Company would have to find a new home. ``I never would have left
the Mount if I hadn't been pushed,'' Packer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always known,'' she continued, ``even if we had stayed
at the Mount, that we would have had to buy 50 acres next door to
connect our training and education programs and relate them to the
performances. But the fact that we now have this beautiful new
property means we can put all our energy into it _ and we have a
lot of energy. I think it's a great lesson. Out of adversity come
all sorts of good things.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
