<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2478 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHAKESPEARE-BERKSHIRE     08-15 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-BERKSHIRES-$ADV20-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LENOX, Mass.: good things.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kemble Street campus is a mixture of verdant meadow and lush
woodland, recalling Shakespeare's settings for ``As You Like It.''
The company began the move to the property in April, shifting its
administrative offices to a 1950s library building and its
rehearsals to Springlawn, and housing actors and students in
dormitories for the summer residential training programs.
</P>
<P>
   With the construction of two theaters _ the Salon Theater in
Springlawn and the larger Founders' Theater in a former gym _ the
company will have year-round producing capabilities for the first
time. Currently, the Lenox performances at the Mount are presented
from May to October.
</P>
<P>
   Among the productions now running in repertory at the Wharton
estate are ``Romeo and Juliet'' on the outdoor mainstage and
``Coriolanus,'' directed by Packer, alternating with ``Jack and
Jill,'' a contemporary play by Jane Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The move to the new property has been supported in tangible ways
by private individuals as well as by the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts, which has recently distributed additional money to
support the arts in the western part of the state through a variety
of agencies. A tax-exempt revenue bond was issued by
Mass-Development, a state-chartered finance agency, which allowed
Shakespeare &AMP; Company to secure a low-interest mortgage; the state
Department of Environmental Management gave $500,000 to the company
in exchange for a preservation restriction on Springlawn and 15
surrounding acres; and $4.4 million has been received from private
donations, out of the $5.5 million needed. ``We'll have the rest in
hand by the end of the summer,'' Miller predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Packer has also found an ally in the British theater consultant
Iain Mackintosh, who will design the Founders' Theater (with the
American architect George E. Marsh Jr.) and plan the Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Mackintosh, whose optimism seems to match Packer's, designed the
Cottesloe space at the Royal National Theater in London and the
Glyndebourne Opera House, also helping save the remains of the Rose
when they were discovered in 1989 during excavations for a London
office building.
</P>
<P>
   The Founders' Theater will be modeled after Mackintosh's design
for the Tricycle Theater in Kilburn in northwest London, described
by Packer as ``a tough theater, made out of scaffolds and canvas, a
courtyard theater that can be used in two or three ways.'' In
addition, an open-air theater behind Springlawn is planned to
replace the outdoor mainstage space at the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tina said, `I want to build the Globe,''' Mackintosh
recalled, ``I said, `No, you want to build the Rose. We already
have a Globe.'' He was referring to the American actor Sam
Wanamaker's replica of the Elizabethan Globe theater that opened in
London in 1997 and that is larger than the Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to build the Rose because we know more about it,''
Mackintosh said. ``Finding the foundations gave us the footprint of
the building, its size, dimensions and the way it was sited. The
Lenox Rose will hold 800 people, a good size for Shakespeare &AMP;
Company. But also good for the actors.''
</P>
<P>
   The original Rose was built by Philip Henslowe in 1587 and
flourished as the home of the first productions of plays by
Christopher Marlowe, Thomas Kyd and Shakespeare, whose ``Henry VI,
Part 1'' and ``Titus Andronicus'' were staged there.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Mackintosh will lead a team of British theater
scholars and builders to Lenox for a five-day seminar to advise
Shakespeare &AMP; Company about the Rose. Among the participants will
be Julian Bowsher, the archaeologist who headed the team that
excavated the Rose; Patrick Spottiswoode, director of the Globe
education programs; Peter McCurdy, master carpenter for the Globe,
and Andrew Gurr, a scholar who advised Wanamaker on the Globe's
design.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Epstein, one of Shakespeare &AMP; Company's veteran actors,
sees some changes ahead. ``Right now,'' he said, ``we have two ways
of acting: working on one of the largest stages in the world,
outdoors at the Mount, where we need a kind of ballistic style, and
working on one of the smallest, in the Salon, where you need a
style where delicacy is significant. These things won't be the same
in the new theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a decade, Packer envisions the Rose and the other
theaters operating at Kemble Street, along with a performance space
in the woods for dance, a media center containing a sound stage for
film, a library for scholarly conferences, and year-round
residential education and training programs on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scope of the place feeds my imagination,'' the director
said with a broad grin. ``We'll have enough room to do all our
programming. You know, we're a very ambitious theater company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
