<HEADER>
A2479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-CARTER16-COX     08-15 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CARTER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON 'MISTAKES' A DANGER FOR GORE, CARTER SAYS
 &HT;    By KATHEY PRUITT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In uncharacteristically blunt terms, former
President Jimmy Carter on Tuesday said President Clinton's
``mistakes'' in the White House are among the biggest liabilities
for Al Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, in a speech to Georgia's Democratic delegation,
described Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky in some of the
harshest terms heard this week. He said Gore has to distance
himself from the president's behavior while taking appropriate
credit for the administration's policy successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who believes (Gore) is responsible for what Bill
Clinton did in secret, at night, with a young intern, is absolutely
stupid and ridiculous,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't stand up as frankly as I did and explain to you, but
somehow in the American people's minds, he has to convince them of
that absolute truth.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Carter took swipes at Republicans, who he said
put on a ``false face'' by saying they care about education and
health care for the poor, elderly and minorities, but offer tax
breaks to benefit businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are successful,'' Carter said, ``because their propaganda
efforts are so professional and they put on a nice demeanor and
people believe them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ex-president turned down an opportunity to address the
Democratic National Convention, accepting instead a five-minute
film tribute Monday evening. But in nearly four dozen interviews in
recent days and a 15-minute address to his colleagues from Georgia,
Carter is weighing into the presidential contest to bolster Gore's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks Tuesday reminded those who may have forgotten that
the global problem-solver and humanitarian still has a partisan
streak hidden behind the friendly grin.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's relationship with the Clinton White House has been a
strained one through the years, with indications that the
administration didn't welcome Carter's intervention to resolve
tensions around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter lavished praise on Gore, who made his first bid for
Congress the same year the Georgia peanut-farmer-turned-governor
made his initial bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, said Carter, ``is a man of absolute integrity'' who is
``just as loyal to his wife Tipper as I am to Rosalynn.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech punctuated by applause and three standing ovations,
Carter said Gore has to come out from under Clinton's shadow and
take credit for his role in pushing the country to economic
prosperity and better opportunities for minorities and the working
class. Carter called the convention a ``beautiful liberation of Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates lauded Carter's willingness to address what many said
will be a dilemma for the ticket, especially in conservative,
Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a former president gives him more license,'' said
Georgia state Rep. Doug Teper of Atlanta, a convention delegate.
``He doesn't have to sugar-coat it.''
</P>
<P>
   In carefully chosen words, Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor said Carter's
opinion ``reflects the opinion of a majority of Georgians and a
majority of Americans. We're disappointed in Clinton's personal
behavior, but also proud of his political accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
