   IN WASHINGTON: Rick Christie at 301-809-3419; 301-910-6248
(cellular).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS-$ADV20_ From the tropical coast to the Mayan
highlands, the fever for political change _ through ballots, not
bullets _ is sweeping Mexico's Chiapas state. On Sunday, Aug. 20,
the state famous for its armed Zapatista Mayan Indian rebels will
elect a new governor. In the wake of Vicente Fox's historic
opposition victory in last month's presidential election, polls
show that change could be contagious: Even in Indian communities
once under tight control by the ruling party, posters for a Fox
ally are up on dirt-floor homes. An old man wearing a ruling party
shirt says he's not so sure he'll vote for that party now. Chiapans
appear to be slightly favoring Pablo Salazar, a former ruling party
member who is now representing an alliance that includes Fox's
conservative National Action Party and the left-wing Democratic
Revolution Party. If Salazar wins, one of the main reasons for the
Zapatistas rising in protest is eliminated. Mexico's ruling party
would be ousted from a state infamous for its ruling-party
corruption and grinding social inequality. A historic new
Fox-Salazar combination would be in place that could usher in new
negotiations with the rebels. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO MUGS.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., aug. 16, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-INVEST-$ADV20 _ SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Lured by cheap
land, a gorgeous countryside and pleasant climate, thousands of
U.S. citizens have moved to Costa Rica in recent years. Profile
some of these folks, from retirees to surfers. Have they found the
dream they wanted? Do locals accept them? Has the recent upswing in
crime tainted their tropical paradise? (Williams, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
