<HEADER>
A2496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LONDON-KINETIC-SCULPT     08-15 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-KINETIC-SCULPTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETRO OR NOSTALGIC, THE ARTWORK NEVER STOPS MOVING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British art scene is so heady with hype, gimmickry
and self-promotion these days that it comes as something of a
relief to discover the long-lost world of kinetic art at the
Hayward Gallery on the south bank of the Thames.
</P>
<P>
   True, not very long ago, from the 1920s to the early 1980s,
moving art was also trendy. Yet today it seems dated, rooted in
another age. In presenting ``Force Fields: Phases of the Kinetic,''
the Hayward has dared to be uncool.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the exhibition, which was seen last spring at the Museum
of Contemporary Art in Barcelona and will run here through Sept.
17, is more than just educational for the young and nostalgic for
the less young. It offers a journey through a world in which time
and space are redefined by the simple (and at times complex)
addition of movement. It is funny, clever, bizarre, hallucinatory
and strangely uplifting. But it is not quiet: Movement in art also
produces bangs and bongs galore.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting some 100 works by 40 artists, the show's curator,
Guy Brett, has interpreted the term ``kinetic art'' to suit his
purposes. Although he does not include video or electronic art,
which does move, he includes paintings, drawings and sculptures
that do not move or, rather, do so only metaphorically. The heart
of the show is nonetheless dedicated to wonderful contraptions that
turn, stretch, tremble, swing and float.
</P>
<P>
   Brett sees the exhibition as an opportunity to reawaken public
interest in the ``language of movement'' and, above all, to lift
kinetic art from what he considers undeserved obscurity. Museums
display little kinetic art, he laments, while, by definition, still
photographs of moving objects published in books and magazines
cannot capture the most distinctive feature of this work.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this impoverished visibility,'' he wrote in a catalog
essay, ``must be added the tendency to treat the historical
phenomenon known as Kinetic Art as a kind of sideshow, or
entertainment, in 20th-century art, not to be treated with the same
high seriousness as, say, Minimal Art, Conceptual Art, or for that
matter Pop Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, much of the work produced was pedestrian and boring, but
that is true of any movement, and the result has been that the
radical implications of the best work for the evolution of art have
been ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the rare occasion to present kinetic art in two large
galleries in two major cities, then, Brett has gone for the best.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens with ``Rotary Glass Plates,'' a precursor of Op
Art made by Marcel Duchamp with Man Ray in 1925, in which four
blades spin on a shaft to create the illusion of a solid circle
decorated with circular lines. Also from the 1920s is Laszlo
Moholy-Nagy's magical ``Light-Space Modulator,'' a ``spatial
kaleidoscope,'' in his words, in which two arc lights create
silhouettes of a rotating mechanical object that is itself alive
with moving parts.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby are three of Alexander Calder's earliest mobiles, ``A
White Ball, a Black Ball'' and two ``Untitled,'' delicate as ever,
gently stirred by the movement of visitors, defining space but also
representing space.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of my abstract work,'' Calder wrote, ``even
when it might not have seemed so, I felt there was no better model
to choose than the universe. Spheres of different sizes, densities,
colors and volumes, floating in space, traversing clouds, sprays of
water, currents of air, viscosities and odors of the greatest
variety and disparity.''
</P>
<P>
   If, as Brett proposes, artists as well as scientists create
``models of the universe,'' two of the artists in the show built
theirs with outside assistance. The inspiration for Henri Michaux's
``Mescaline Drawings'' is self-evident, while Wols (the name
adopted by Alfred Wolfgang Schulze) etched under the influence of
old-fashioned liquor. James Whitney's hand-drawn animated films
``Yanta'' and ``Lapis,'' made in the 1950s and '60s, take their cue
from yoga and Eastern philosophy to create what resembles an
LSD-induced cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   Op Art resurfaces in Francois Morellet's so-called ``mesh''
paintings, with tiny designs endlessly repeated to the point that
they move with the eye. Jesus Rafael Soto and Pol Bury both capture
movement in their paintings, but also, more realistically, in their
installations. Soto's ``Penetrable'' is a dense forest of dangling
plastic filaments through which visitors can walk; Bury's kinetic
works include ``Punctuation (White Dots)'' in which a clutch of
painted nylon threads sprouting from a wooden board slowly rotate.
</P>
<P>
   Two artists in particular, though, show why the 1950s and 1960s
were the heyday of kinetic art. Jean Tinguely's approach was to
satirize the consumer society by building immense sculptures of
industrial detritus, all set into comical and noisy motion by a
series of electric motors. Indeed, these are works that only make
sense when they come to life. Of the five Tinguelys in this show,
``Baluba XII,'' made in 1961-62, captures on a small scale what he
later tried to achieve in his later monumental sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Takis, now 75, has long tapped
electromagnetic energy, using this force to create a cosmos of
metal objects in suspended animation, as with his ``Telemagnetic
Sculptures'' and ``Ballet Magnetique,'' which are among 23 of his
pieces on display here. One charming work is ``Musical'' (1974), in
which three foot-long metal ``needles'' hang from a board and are
drawn by magnetic impulses to strike horizontal metal wires. The
resulting bongs echo through the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   These compete with the whacks emanating from Len Lye's
``Blade,'' in which a trembling vertical steel blade is repeatedly
hit by a wooden hammer. An almost otherworldly sound is created by
his ``Universe,'' a large band of polished steel resting on a
magnetized base that bends and lurches in response to interrupted
magnetic impulses.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the cosmos becomes even more real for visitors
entering Gianni Colombo's ``Elastic Space,'' a large dark cube
crossed by vertical and horizontal strings that are pulled in
different directions to disrupt all sense of place.
</P>
<P>
   The show also includes nonmoving works by artists like Yves
Klein, Sol LeWitt, Georges Vantongerloo, Sergio Camargo and Lygia
Clark as well as more orthodox kinetic pieces by Gerhard von
Graevenitz, Dieter Roth, Grazia Varisco and Liliane Lijn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if ``Force Fields'' inevitably looks backward, the youngest
living artist in the show, 58-year-old David Medalla of the
Philippines, is clearly immune to what is considered fashionable.
Among his works on display is ``Cloud Gates,'' a large installation
that stands on an outside terrace. This work creates large bubble
clouds that catch the wind and float away over London. It is proof
enough that something is moving in the Hayward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
