<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2497 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LUNCH-SFCHRON &LR;      08-15 3766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNCH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 A Great City Forced To Skip Lunch: Computer Age takes a bit out  of
tranditional midday meal.   By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Lunch in the Bay Area is dead _ or at least on
life support.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No need to tell that to vending machine mechanic Luis De La O.
All day, on a route that includes offices from Petaluma to Palo
Alto, he stands witness to what remains of the traditional lunch
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's going anywhere except down the hall to the
machines,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   De La O often doesn't have time to break at noon, either. On a
recent Tuesday, he grabbed a slice at Blondie's Pizza on Powell
Street, where 15 minutes is considered a long lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Across Market Street, in the halls of Bay Area dot-com
businesses, stopping to eat is considered a time suck, a ritual for
losers who simply don't have enough to do. Although people may go
to restaurants on special occasions, the lunch business is fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the dot-com environment here in SOMA, lunch is
irrelevant,'' says Jennifer Griffin, a 23-year-old Internet media
planner with Bravo Marketing.
</P>
<P>
   When she and her colleagues get hungry, they don't go to a
restaurant; they order in or go to the kitchen and feed on an
endless stream of company-supplied snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have everything from cookies to java to Rice Krispies
treats to every cereal imaginable. We've got M&AMP;Ms . . . you name
it,'' Griffin says. ``Things get hectic and you can't just go eat
lunch _ it's critical to be in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bye Bye Business Lunch &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For those of you eating at your desks right now, it will come as
no surprise that the lunch hour has been shrinking for much of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The time people spend on a lunch break is down to 38 minutes _ a
number that's expected to continue to drop, according to a study of
eating habits published recently in Food Technology magazine. About
half of the people who responded to a 1999 National Restaurant
Association survey said they had less time for lunch than they used
to. And 40 percent said they don't usually take a real lunch break.
Only a quarter bring lunch from home.
</P>
<P>
   Even that most hallowed institution, the expense-account lunch,
is fading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power lunch went out with Gordon Gecko and slicked-back
hair,'' says Jennifer Johnson, a Utah-based authority on virtual
offices and telecommuting. ``More and more, people see lunch as one
of those trappings of the traditional bricks-and-mortar
environment. It's so restrictive.''
</P>
<P>
   At Stars, where the 1980s power lunch was perhaps not invented
but certainly perfected, the lunch of the new millennium is a more
sober _ and shorter _ affair. On average, people spend about 50
minutes at lunch, says managing partner Stanley Morris. The menu is
simpler _ ``things they don't need to put a lot of thought into.''
By 1:30 p.m., tables are often empty.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Theoharis, president of the San Francisco Planning
Commission and longtime Stars diner, notes the tone and purpose of
lunch has changed. ``The power lunch here used to be to schmooze
people, but now people are so busy you use lunch to get some work
done. After a hearing or a meeting with the mayor, you still come
here. But it's much faster and much more about business. And nobody
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of changing habits, several Bay Area restaurants
have simply given up. Pintxos, a Basque restaurant in the Mission,
opened for lunch just before Christmas 1999, but stopped serving a
couple months later. It was a big stretch for the kitchen and
wasn't worth the money, says co-owner Pablo Zubicaray.
</P>
<P>
   The story is a common one as restaurants grapple with high labor
costs, shorter lunch hours and fewer midday customers.
</P>
<P>
   Says Stars' Morris: ``More and more restaurants are realizing
lunch is a losing proposition. Once they accept it has no value to
them, it takes a lot of stress off a restaurant. It's like you can
hear a lot of sighs of relief from chefs when they decide to stop
lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, restaurants that are national darlings simply can't
make a go of it. For example, Spruce, one of the city's best
restaurants located only a couple of blocks from busy Michigan
Avenue, dropped midday service shortly after starting it.
</P>
<P>
   And if more upscale restaurants haven't dropped lunch, they're
certainly trying everything to appeal to people who simply don't
have much time to eat anymore. At Seattle's tony Painted Table,
where dinner can take two or three hours, the owners are pushing
``express lunches'' which allow people to be out in 45 minutes or
less.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the Bennigan's chain touts its popular ``Time Crunch
Lunch.'' If lunch doesn't arrive within 15 minutes of being
ordered, it's free, well-done steaks excepted. The whole thing is
timed with a tabletop stopwatch.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New York, places like Le Bernardin, a top-drawer French
seafood restaurant, promotes a lunch guaranteed to be served in 30
minutes for $32.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What Killed Lunch? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the traditional lunch hour is tied to the
technological revolution. A set lunch hour mattered when much of
America was working on assembly lines or in buttoned-down offices.
But because technology has changed the rhythm of the work day and
the new online economy is changing corporate culture, workers do
not march to the schedule of the factory or corporate norms.
</P>
<P>
   And workdays will only continue to get more flexible. The U.S.
Department of Labor estimates that by 2020, 40 percent of the
workforce will be telecommuting. As people have more control over
their workday and have the technological flexibility to do their
jobs outside of the 9-to-5 framework, they can eat when they want
to.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, assuming everyone takes a lunch break at noon can hurt
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to stop at noon,'' says Bravo Marketing's
Griffin. When it's noon here, she explains, it's 3 p.m. on the East
Coast. By the time you get back to the office, they're closing up
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Business is still conducted over food, but is more likely to be
a quick meeting for coffee in the morning. If a deal is to be
clinched or celebrated, it's over dinner. If business needs to be
done over lunch, food is often brought in.
</P>
<P>
   Catering and delivery services are thriving. Fernando Hidalgo,
marketing vice president for Waiters on Wheels, says his company's
lunch delivery business has jumped 30 percent over the last two
years. The story is the same for Randy Negi, who owns the casual
Cafe Venue on Market Street. His lunch business has taken a
dramatic upswing in the last eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dot-commers on the other side of Market, we're
delivering every day down there. They're ordering lunch for their
whole staff. Sixty sandwiches, 30 salads _ big orders. That's where
a lot of my business is coming from now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New Lunch &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But don't cancel that lunch reservation just yet. As the
traditional working person's lunch hour crashes and burns, a new
trend is rising from the ashes. People are saving up time and money
to arrange occasional meals out with friends or quiet midday
getaways for themselves. The notion of lunch as a pleasurable
pursuit _ call it the restorative lunch _ is slowly starting to
catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Reichl, Gourmet magazine editor and former food critic for
the New York Times, confesses that lunch is often a quick snack at
her desk in Manhattan. But like an increasing number of people, she
will skip lunch a few days a week and instead take one long,
relaxing food-focused meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is basically have lunch or don't have lunch,'' she
says. ``I would rather have a pint of yogurt at my desk and save up
all the time for one great leisurely meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Caraher, president of the San Francisco online firm Red
Whistle Communications, has abandoned power lunches. Instead, she
uses lunch to celebrate, to relax or to reward employees. Aqua or
Rubicon are favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the Tadich Grill, for decades a classic San Francisco
destination for business, people are eating for pleasure. Anna
Lingley, an insurance company worker who used to go to Tadich only
for business, now uses it as treat. Once a month or so, she and
friend will go to Tadich or another restaurant and have a proper
luncheon. ``Lunch for me is a break away from the world. That's
what I value now. I'm not into rushing through it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new approach allows people to discover favorite neighborhood
restaurants, call a friend for a picnic or simply get outside and
take time for themselves in the middle of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Luis De La O is usually too busy fixing vending
machines to break away, he sometimes finds time to grab an hour to
sit in a park and relax.
</P>
<P>
   When he does, he's likely to find people like Sophia Genetti, a
26-year-old temporary worker, who often spends her lunch break
reading at Yerba Buena Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people I know are taking time out for themselves to
meditate or have a really nice lunch some place,'' she says. ``It's
much nicer this way, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Lunch Isn't Like It Once Was &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How lunch came to be has to do more with class, gender and
nationality than with the biological need to eat.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle Ages, most people ate four or five meals a day to
keep up their strength, but the upper classes ate only two meals a
day. Regardless of class, the big meal of the day came at midday.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16th and 17th centuries, the word ``luncheon'' literally
meant a hunk of cheese or bread, or perhaps a small bit of leftover
meat. These sort of snacks were often eaten in the middle of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch as we know it today has its roots in the behavior of the
Western European elite of the 1700s and 1800s. They began pushing
back the time for both supper and dinner, until in some circles
supper was eaten at 4 or 5 p.m. and dinner late at night after the
theater. A light midday meal became fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1800s in Great Britain and certain parts of
America, only ladies of leisure ate an elaborate, formal luncheon.
Businessmen and professionals ate a big breakfast and big dinner
and little in between. The poorer classes and children still ate
their main meal in the middle of the day and called it supper.
</P>
<P>
   Because breakfasts tended to be large in Britain, luncheon was
light. And one never called it lunch _ that would be considered
vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the midday meal, called  &LR; dejeuner &LR; , took a different
form. The word comes from the Latin phrase for breaking a fast, or
breakfast. At first, when the French were in the habit of eating a
larger, elaborate dinner around noon, it referred to the first meal
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But around the time of the French Revolution, when government
meetings began at midday and ended around 6 p.m., lawmakers started
eating a substantial, late breakfast to get them through the day.
Cafes in the early 1800s started to set food out around 11 a.m. to
accommodate the government schedule, and the French business lunch
was born.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S., lunch has taken many forms. From the early 20th
century's hustling, packed lunch counters and cafeterias and
regimented lunch breaks of factory workers, the American midday
meal has been a harried affair for many.
</P>
<P>
   For others, particularly those of the middle and upper classes,
lunch was a more formal affair. Women in the 1940s and '50s who
were generally not part of the work force fostered a
post-Depression, post-war luncheon boom, and American business
during the period was built on the three-martini lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980s and early '90s were the era of the power lunch _
business lunches where the restaurants and dining companions were
of utmost importance.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: &LR;  ``Larousse Gastronomique'' (Crown Publishers); ``The &LR; 
 &LR; Oxford Companion to Food,'' by Alan Davidson (Oxford University &LR; 
 &LR; Press); and ``A Culinary History of Food,'' by Jean-Louis &LR; 
 &LR; Flandrin and Massimo Montanari (Columbia University Press). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hot Spots for That Restorative Lunch
</P>
<P>
   The following are among the more popular places for a special
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Aqua &LR; . Whether it's for business or pleasure, this four-star
seafood restaurant in the Financial District serves perfect food in
beautiful surroundings with top-notch service.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 252 California St. (at Battery); (415) 956-9662. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bix &LR; . With its retro supper club feel and out-of-the-way
location, Bix is perfect for a lunch escape. Martinis are
especially good here, but optional at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 56 Gold St. (near Jackson); (415) 433-6300. Lunch weekdays; &LR; 
 &LR; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Boulevard &LR; . A dramatic decor by Pat Kuleto paired with Nancy
Oakes' stellar New American cuisine make lunching here a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1 Mission St. (at Steuart); (415) 543-6084. Lunch weekdays; &LR; 
 &LR; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Elisabeth Daniel &LR; . Possibly the ultimate in long lunches,
this San Francisco newcomer offers only a four-course prix fixe
lunch menu. The average lunch ``hour'' here can take two hours or
more.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 550 Washington St. (between Sansome and Montgomery); (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 397-6129. Lunch weekdays; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Farallon &LR; . A stylish deep-sea decor and a wonderful menu
specializing in seafood create a lovely lunch spot near Union
Square.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 450 Post St. (between Powell and Mason); (415) 956-6969. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; Monday- &LR;   &LR; Saturday; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hawthorne Lane &LR; . This splashy venue tucked away on a tiny
street in SOMA is almost as hot for lunch as it is for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 22 Hawthorne St. (off Howard, between Second and Third &LR; 
 &LR; streets); (415) 777-9779. Lunch weekdays; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Kokkari &LR; . Upscale Greek food, including fried smelts and a
decadent moussaka, served in handsome rustic surroundings are the
draw to this restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 200 Jackson St. (at Front); (415) 981-0983. Lunch weekdays; &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ One Market &LR; . A great location at the end of Market Street
plus an eclectic menu make this one of the city's most popular
lunch spots.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1 Market St. (at Steuart); (415) 777-5577. Lunch weekdays; &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Scala's Bistro &LR; . This restaurant with its high ceilings and
dark wood is always packed with a combination of tourists and
locals enjoying the Italian food.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 432 Powell St. (between Post and Sutter in the Sir Francis &LR; 
 &LR; Drake Hotel); (415) 395-8555. Breakfast, lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Slanted Door &LR; . Many go to this creative Vietnamese restaurant
in the Mission for lunch because dinner reservations are so hard to
come by.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 584 Valencia St. (near 17th Street); (415) 861-8032. Lunch and &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Stars &LR; . Some say this is where the business lunch has gone to
die. The creative fare in stylish surroundings is a favorite for
San Francisco politicos.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 555 Golden Gate (between Van Ness and Polk); (415) 861-7827. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch weekdays; dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Tadich Grill &LR; . Customers line up outside the door for the
classic San Francisco seafood, including delicious pan-fried sand
dabs at this old-time favorite.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 240 California St. (between Front and Battery streets); (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 391-2373. Open lunch through dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Zuni &LR; . This corner-space restaurant is a favorite for those
who want a leisurely lunch of oysters and Champagne or a full-blown
meal, including one of the best hamburgers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1658 Market St. (near Franklin); (415) 552-2522. Lunch and &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EAST BAY/CONTRA COSTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Amalfi Trattoria &LR; . Perfectly executed fish dishes are just
one of the reasons this Italian restaurant is always packed at
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1512 N. Main St. (at Bonanza), Walnut Creek; (925) 988-8022. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch Tuesday-Friday; dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cafe at Chez Panisse &LR; . A daily changing menu at this
restaurant located upstairs from Alice Water's landmark restaurant
means customers can find something new to love every day.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1517 Shattuck Ave. (near Cedar), Berkeley; (510) 548-5049. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch and dinner Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cafe Rouge &LR; . The rustic fare and convivial atmosphere make
this one of the most popular lunch spots in the heart of chic
Berkeley Fourth Street.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1782 Fourth St. (at Delaware), Berkeley; (510) 525-1440. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; daily; dinner Tuesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Garibaldi's on College &LR; . Mediterranean food with some fusion
twists draw the lunchtime crowds into the comfortable atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 5356 College Ave. (at Hudson), Oakland; (510) 595-4000. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; weekdays; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mudd's &LR; . Most lunch spots in the San Ramon Valley are casual.
But if executives in suits are looking to make deals, and they want
a quiet retreat with good food and an extensive wine list, you'll
probably find them at this sumptuously landscaped restaurant tucked
off Crow Canyon Road.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 10 Boardwalk (near Park Place), San Ramon; (925) 837-9387. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch weekdays, dinner nightly, brunch Sunday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Oaktown &LR; . In the heart of Victorian Old Oakland, this casual
bistro offers smart food in casual surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 499 Ninth St. (at Washington), Oakland; (510) 763-4999. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; weekdays; dinner Wednesday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Oliveto &LR; . Paul Bertolli's Italian food at his Rockridge
restaurant is some of the best in the Bay Area, especially the
benchmark fresh pastas and house-cured meats.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 5655 College Ave. (at Shafter), Oakland; (510) 547-5356. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; weekdays; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Prima &LR; . Customers haven't tired of this 23-year-old
trattoria-wine shop. A recent remodel leaves it resembling a Tuscan
villa, and lunch people who don't pinch pennies come back for the
lusty Italian food.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1522 N. Main St. (near Lincoln), Walnut Creek; (925) 935-7780. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch Monday-Saturday; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Scott's &LR; . The small office towers around this pricey seafood
outpost are thick with lawyers _ and at lunch, so is Scott's.
Quieter, darker than the flashier downtown spots, but it's
definitely a draw for executives or power-brokers with time on
their hands and expense accounts in their corner.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 1333 N. California Blvd. (between Mt. Diablo Boulevard and &LR; 
 &LR; Bonanza Street), Walnut Creek; (925) 934-1300. Lunch through &LR; 
 &LR; dinner Monday-Saturday, brunch and dinner Sunday &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Townhouse &LR; . Amid artists' studios, high-tech industries and
warehouses, The Townhouse is a wittily remodeled speakeasy with a
great deck. The mini-SoMa hot spot features California and Italian
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 5862 Doyle St. (take Powell Street exit off Highway 80), &LR; 
 &LR; Emeryville; (510) 652-6151. Lunch weekdays, dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Monday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ T. R.'s Bar &AMP; Grill &LR; . If there's a political hot spot at noon
in Contra Costa, this is it. Owned by county supervisor Mark
DeSaulnier, on lively days you'll see union leaders, lobbyists,
political consultants and elected officials checking out the scene
along with the crab cakes or T.R.'s Pro Salad.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 2001 Salvio St. (at Concord Avenue), Concord; (925) 827-4660. &LR; 
 &LR; Lunch Monday-Saturday, dinner nightly, brunch Sunday. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NORTH BAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Alfy's &LR; . Open almost six weeks, this contemporary French
restaurant is already bustling at lunchtime with Marin residents.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; 636 San Anselmo Ave. (near Sir Francis Drake Boulevard), San &LR; 
 &LR; Anselmo; (415) 453-3407. Open for lunch and dinner &LR; 
 &LR; Wednesday-Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bistro Jeanty &LR; . Why not take a culinary trip to the French
countryside for lunch? Chef-owner Phillipe Jeanty prepares
