<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Aug. 16 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service night
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken, 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-BASE (Los Angeles) _ How the Democratic Party base views the
Gore-Lieberman ticket and the party platform. By James Dao and
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PROTESTS-NYT (Los Angeles) _ The day's developments in Los
Angeles. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   KIPP-EDUC (Undated) _ Successful schools for the poor have long
been written off as desert flowers dependent on charismatic leaders
or particular ideology. But Kipp Academy, a pair of extremely
successful middle schools in poor areas of Harlem and Houston, are
something different. Started by two Ivy League idealists and
honored by groups on both the left and right, Kipp is seen as a
model for replication. And now the owners of The Gap have donated
$15 million to create Kipp clones around the country. The process
is starting with a unprecedented year-long training period for the
principals. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ Buffeted by storms, Russian rescuers
battled for a second day to reach 116 sailors trapped in a crippled
nuclear submarine on the sea floor, repeatedly trying to lower an
escape capsule to the stricken vessel. Efforts to rescue the Kursk,
lying motionless below the surface of the Barents Sea, were
hampered most of Tuesday by high winds and strong currents. There
had been no communication with the submarine since it went down,
and conditions inside were not known. It wasn't clear how much air
the crew had left and water appeared to be leaking in, officials
said. (Summary from wires) By Sabrina Tavernise and Christopher
Drew.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CONCORDE (London) _ British Airways grounded its entire
fleet of Concorde supersonic airliners on Tuesday after French and
British investigators said they would urge the withdrawal of the
airplane's airworthiness certification following last month's fatal
Air France Concorde crash near Paris. It would be the first time in
more than 20 years that an airworthiness certificate for a
commercial airliner had been revoked by any country. The
investigators said they would not spell out their reasoning until
Wednesday, and so it was unclear what steps would have to be taken
to reverse the recommendation. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-REUNIONS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Under the watchful gaze of
North Korean minders here, 100 families separated for the last five
decades on Tuesday began the arduous process of rebuilding
relationships torn apart by war. Mothers embraced children long
given up for dead. Brothers and sisters struggled to identify
adults they knew until now only as children. Wives steeled
themselves to meet husbands long since wedded to other spouses, and
vice versa. And underlying all the carefully choreographed drama,
custom-made for tear-jerking footage and heartbreaking copy _
indeed, making it possible _ was the surprisingly sophisticated
political maneuvering of North Korea's leader, Kim Jong Il. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   DISTILLERY-SMUGGLE (New York) _ Over the last two years, a
federal investigation into Russian and Italian organized crime in
the ports of Newark and Elizabeth, N.J., turned up the expected mix
of mundane mob staples: extortion, cigarette smuggling, money
laundering. But federal agents said they also came across a bit of
criminal enterprise that, for pure creative corruption, struck them
as remarkable: a loose-knit web of companies was smuggling tens of
millions of gallons of American-made grain alcohol _ including
millions of gallons from one of the country's oldest distilleries _
to Eastern Europe to slake a seemingly boundless thirst for that
most Russian of spirits, vodka. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
