<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LONDON-THEATER-2TAKES     08-15 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN OF EXPERIENCE AND ELECTRICITY GRAB THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``Look at me!''
</P>
<P>
   The words, echoing what every performer on a stage asks on one
level or another, are sung with particularly sweet
self-satisfaction by the three title characters of ``The Witches of
Eastwick,'' the splashy, hard-working new West End musical, in the
show's concluding anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Since these are creatures who have already hovered perilously
over the audience in midair _ rather like the falling chandelier in
that earlier gothic musical ``The Phantom of the Opera'' _ it seems
unwise to ignore their request for attention. If ``The Witches of
Eastwick,'' which has few substantial thoughts in its head, has a
moral, it is that you should never underestimate the power of being
female, 40-ish and sexually ripe.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to be the lesson of London theater in general
this summer, with midlife resurrections translating into big box
office and widely varied degrees of artistic success. On the stage,
at least, women rule, and not the fantastical, mannered Mames and
Dollys who have traditionally governed musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Mackintosh, the spectacle-loving producer of
``Witches,'' wasn't out of his mind when he chose a trio of
questing middle-aged heroines as a humanizing addition to his
signature series of identifiable flying objects, heirs to the
chandelier in ``Phantom'' and the helicopter in ``Miss Saigon.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, the holdover musical smash from last season, the
endearingly clunky ``Mamma Mia!,'' features an amateur trio of
female singers who reunite 20 years after their salad days to
perform the disco-era hits of Abba, the Swedish pop group. The
stoutest of them now has difficulty falling to her knees in rock
'n' roll fervor as she once did. But that doesn't mean she can't
court a fellow with all-out sexual aggressiveness in the
showstopping ``Take a Chance on Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The robust British veteran Barbara Dickson (``Blood Brothers'')
copped the 1999 Olivier Award for best actress as the life-scarred
but enduringly lusty heroine of ``Spend Spend Spend,'' a purely
British slice of tough sentimentality based on the
good-luck/hard-luck story of the lottery winner Vivian Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   And the most coveted ticket in London still belongs to ``The
Graduate.'' The popularity of this cardboard adaptation of Mike
Nichols' 1967 film would seem to rest almost entirely on a
20-second display of full frontal nudity by the play's jaded
seductress, Mrs. Robinson, after dropping a bath towel. Replicas of
the towel, please note, can be purchased for about $40 in the
theater lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The role, first essayed by Kathleen Turner with a commanding
deadpan languor that edged into camp, was recently taken over by
the ex-model (and ex-wife of Mick Jagger) Jerry Hall, with the
attendant press coverage threatening to eclipse that of that
 &UR; really  &LR; older woman, the Queen Mother, on her centennial.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime the glorious Helen Mirren, a stage and screen
siren in her 50s who somehow looked well seasoned even in first
youth, has turned a more somber analysis of an older woman involved
with a younger man, Tennessee Williams' ``Orpheus Descending,''
into a must-see production at the Donmar Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Theater, unlike film, has traditionally been hospitable to women
well past their ingenue years. And musicals in particular remain a
sort of Never Never Land where actresses are as unlikely to grow
old as Peter Pan, the eternal boy portrayed by Mary Martin when she
was in her 40s.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening in London, however, is a firm departure from
Martin's doing Peter or the aging Katherine Cornell as Juliet. John
Dempsey and Dana P. Rowe, the lyricist and composer, respectively,
for ``The Witches of Eastwick,'' dwell at length in their program
notes on their attempts to make their heroines ``women in the
truest sense'' in ways they ``generally aren't in musicals these
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Hall's hairdresser confided to The Evening Standard,
``Nowadays it's not about looking younger; it's about looking as
good as possible for yourself.'' It seems apt that the most
glamorous photographic image to be found in London subway cars
these days is the honey blonde who gazes confidently from an
advertisement for a menopausal vitamin supplement. And in one of
several editorial essays occasioned by Hall's appearance in ``The
Graduate,'' the novelist Fay Weldon, writing in The Daily Mail,
suggested that harsh criticism of the actress might stem from
today's young people ``feeling threatened by the new `older
women''' and their ``general refusal to lie down and grow old
gracefully.''
</P>
<P>
   That the stuff of theater is also the stuff of newspaper debates
and subway ads testifies to the abidingly vital dialogue here
between the stage and the broader national culture. It is an
exchange that New Yorkers _ whose Broadway theater tends to have
the immediate relevance of the medieval rooms of the Metropolitan
Museum _ can only envy.
</P>
<P>
   This is true even as the West End, at the height of both the
silly season and the tourist-courting season, takes on an American
accent to match that of much of its audience, with no fewer than
four major shows _ ``Witches,'' ``The Graduate,'' Tennessee
Williams' ``Baby Doll'' and the recently departed ``Singin' in the
Rain'' _ adapted from Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the London theater is not unswayed by vulgar commercial
calculation. (Think of those Mrs. Robinson towels.) The current
apotheosis of the older woman surely has something to do with that
favorite science of marketers, demographics, and an awareness that
baby boom audience members, with their children growing up and
their expendable income expanding, are worth catering to. This is
also the summer in which BBC television is devoting 10 weeks to
celebrating the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such systematic nostalgia was anticipated by the hugely
successful ``Mamma Mia!,'' which opened last year under the
astutely naive-seeming direction of Phyllida Lloyd. The show taps
into affection for the disco era with a blithe ingenuity that
thoroughly shames the leaden stage version of ``Saturday Night
Fever.'' ``Mamma Mia!,'' the story of a single mother and the
grown-up, soon-to-be-married daughter who wants to discover just
who her father is, breezily mines this generation gap in sexual
attitudes while cramming in 22 songs first performed by Abba.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect is of a group of jolly tourists in a karaoke
bar, a feeling compounded by the show's setting, a taverna on a
Greek island. The audience inevitably loosens up in this holiday
atmosphere, and when its three middle-aged leading ladies show up
in full Abba regalia to perform ``Dancin' Queen,'' it seems as if
everyone, on stage and off, is happily drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Another trio of harmonizing female friends of roughly the same
age is at the center of ``Witches,'' Mackintosh's bid to secure his
slipping crown as the world's pre-eminent producer of musicals.
Here he de-emphasizes the technological spectacle of his glory
years, presenting instead a character-driven show that deliberately
recalls American musicals of the late 1950s and early '60s, like
``Damn Yankees'' and ``Bye Bye Birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   As staged by Eric Schaeffer, the show still hasn't settled on a
convincing, consistent tone. Both the moody comic darkness of John
Updike's novel and the opulent silliness of the movie it inspired
have been more or less jettisoned. The approach instead veers
between straightforward, sometimes sour satire of small-town
small-mindedness (accented by the set designer Bob Crowley's acidic
evocations of a Norman Rockwell world) and stirring hymns to
feminist self-empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   The satire is old hat and not terribly funny, trying to trade on
affection for a vanished American idyll even as it sends it up. Nor
is Ian McShane, making his musical debut, the ideal choice for the
devil who brings out the woman in each of the witches, a part
played on screen by Jack Nicholson with his trademark mixture of
loutishness and sly, suave charm. McShane, best known here as
television's antiques-savvy detective, Lovejoy, expertly conveys
the loutishness but not the charm, making the women who fall for
him look desperate indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The show's true magic is generated by the witches themselves,
played by Lucie Arnaz, Maria Friedman and Joanna Riding, and
Dempsey and Rowe find their original voice when they are writing
for them. Friedman's Sukie, who has a delightful, self-defining
tongue twister of a number about being tongue-tied, emerges as the
evening's most complete creation.
</P>
<P>
   The other two are undeniably appealing, though, with Arnaz's
easy, earthy sensuality, and Riding giving appetizing bite to the
cliche of the prim woman who takes off her glasses and becomes a
sexpot. They are all at their strongest in their numbers together,
deftly proving the show's rather labored point that sisterhood can
indeed be powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoon vision of Americans as shrill bigots and grubby
materialists, so dear to the hearts of the English, is on pointed
display in ``The Graduate,'' ``The Witches of Eastwick'' and to a
lesser extent in the popular import from the Birmingham Repertory
Theater, ``Baby Doll.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Bailey's stage adaption of the 1956 movie turns Williams'
tale of a slow-witted child bride of the South (Charlotte Emmerson,
with a crawling drawl) and the vengeful Italian immigrant (Jonathan
Cake) who seduces her into a steam-heated sermon in intolerance.
Willliams' Southerners have never seemed so grossly feebleminded,
while Cake's crafty Sicilian is a gleaming paragon of wit and
virtue.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand there is the occasional London production of
an American play that gets everything so right that you feel
slightly embarrassed by memories of recent versions of the same
work back home. Most conspicuously there is Howard Davies'
lacerating production of ``All My Sons'' at the Royal National
Theater, which brings an emotional tension to Arthur Miller's
postwar morality tale that reduces many of those watching it to
sobs. Julie Walters and James Hazeldine lead a high-powered cast
that conveys every painful ounce of the toll exacted by a
life-warping deception.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Nicholas Hytner's refreshingly restrained take on
``Orpheus Descending,'' a work memorably rediscovered just over a
decade ago here in Peter Hall's production with Vanessa Redgrave.
As Lady Torrance, the love-mangled Italian shopkeeper in a
Mississippi town, Mirren doesn't attempt to top Redgrave's all-out
operatic grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she creates a meticulously layered portrait in which a
wary bitterness conceals a wellspring of hopeful sensuality, just
as the character's Italian inflections keeps slipping through the
imposed Southern accent. The delicacy of this lady's gradual
blossoming sets the tone for an exceptionally intimate ``Orpheus''
that emphasizes existential loneliness rather than erotic tragedy
as the work's central theme, the sense of people sentenced to
``solitary confinement inside our own skins for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words come from the problematic hero of ``Orpheus,'' that
virile guitar-strumming poet of the flesh, Val Xavier. Williams
originally wanted Marlon Brando to play Val (he finally did in the
movie version), and every actor who has tried the role has been
measured against that unmatchable image. In this version the part
belongs to Stuart Townsend, a lissome, faintly androgynous young
man and not an obvious choice.
</P>
<P>
   But when you watch this Val responding to the women, you're
aware of how intensely he focuses on them, as though no one else
existed, and how sexy that can be. Few things make a person
flourish more than the undivided attention of others. It is perhaps
simply being in the spotlight for a change that makes those witches
of Eastwick fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
