<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTY BOOP HAS A CUTE CANINE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the name of Betty Boop's dog?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.L.D., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The pet is Pudgy, a creation of Max Fleischer Studios
animator Myron Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boop was once a dog herself, starting out in 1930 as a
cabaret-singing canine sidekick to another dog named Bimbo.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-videotape series ``Betty Boop: The Definitive
Collection'' devotes one 94-minute video to cartoons featuring
Pudgy. Direct Video sells the ``Betty &AMP; Pudgy'' tape for $8.12 at
(800) 461-1651 and the Web site www.directvideo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Barker Animation Art Galleries in Cheshire, Conn., sells several
new sketches of Pudgy and Betty Boop by Waldman, who also created
the donkeys Hunky and Spunky.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, call (800) 995-2357 or visit the Web
site www.barkeranimation.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find copies of Fred Gipson's books ``Old
Yeller,'' ``Savage Sam'' and ``The Trail-Driving Rooster?''
</P>
<P>
   _ P.M., Fort Worth, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: HarperCollins reissued two of those books in the '80s, ``Old
Yeller'' and ``Savage Sam,'' and they are still in print.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find them in the children's section of a bookstore,
you can special-order them from many stores using ISBN
0-0608-0971-X for ``Yeller'' and 0-0608-0377-0 for ``Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson, who lived from 1908 to 1973, was born near Mason, a town
in the Texas Hill Country where he set many of his stories. He
worked as a newspaper journalist before launching a career as a
novelist in the '40s, selling more than 3 million copies of ``Old
Yeller'' after its 1956 publication.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, a statue honoring ``Old Yeller'' was unveiled in
front of the Mason County Library during the first ``Yeller Days''
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I find replacement labels for salt, pepper and
spices?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W., Stephenville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: One mail-order source is Fante's Gourmet and Kitchen Wares
Shop in Philadelphia, which sells 30 self-adhesive spice labels for
$2.99, and 60 labels for $5.49.
</P>
<P>
   There are 54 printed labels and six blank labels in the 60-count
item, while the other contains 30 blank labels.
</P>
<P>
   To order, call (800) 443-2683 or visit the Web site
www.fantes.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia company also sells wooden spice racks, carousel
racks, steel racks and glass-tube spice sets.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
