<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCNEELY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS DELEGATES RAP BUSH EDUCATION RECORD
 &HT;    Attn: Texas points.
 &HT;    By DAVE McNEELY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Democrats at their national convention are
doing their utmost to undermine Gov. George W. Bush's effort to
portray himself, as his father had done, as the ``education
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a lesson from the Republican convention in Philadelphia _
if one was needed _ the Texas Democrats here focus on a message of
the day, and for Tuesday it was education.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic legislators, congress members and teacher
organization members at the Texas delegation's breakfast slammed
Bush for everything from taking credit for education gains launched
by predecessors to trying to trim new kindergarten spending to
enlarge a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chair Molly Beth Malcolm said Republicans
bragged at their convention about Texas education improvements,
citing a recently released Rand study.
</P>
<P>
   But they failed to note, she said, that the study only went
through 1996 _ the second year of Bush's administration _ and the
report credited reforms instituted a decade earlier by Democratic
Gov. Mark White and Dallas billionaire Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited two key factors for the gains: mandated
smaller class sizes and more money for early childhood education.
Bush tried to undercut both, Malcolm and others said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ciro Rodriguez of Texas said as a state House member in
1995 he voted for an amendment ``to make sure we kept the classroom
size at a level where our teachers could be able to teach. And it
won by two votes. Bush and the Republicans were on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said that in the 1999 legislative session,``when
Governor Bush was looking for one more place to get a little more
tax cut so he could run for president, he tried to cut $300 million
out of the budget (for kindergarten funding). And guess what? The
Democrats did not let him. ... So be sure you share those facts
when you talk to people out here.'formance is up across the board,
and Texas education is recognized as a national model.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Donna Haschke, an Austin teacher who is vice president
of the Texas State Teachers Association, said it's true that
student test scores are up and dropouts are down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor takes credit,'' Haschke sai ever came to office.
He was still working on the Texas Rangers (baseball team) and
trading off (slugger) Sammy Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
