<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-COFFER-PHOTOGRAPHY-$A     08-15 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFER-PHOTOGRAPHY-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN ORIGINAL GOES BACK TO THE ORIGINAL PHOTOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ore., N.Y., Fla., Tenn.)   (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By LYLE REXER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNDEE, N.Y. _ Some 140 years ago, the job might have gone
something like this: Word had come that the Union Army was moving
north for a fight, up in Pennsylvania somewhere. You would have
loaded up the small wagon with glass or iron plates, chemicals,
food _ and your best samples, of course, in case the soldiers
wanted to see the quality of your work. You would have set up at
the bivouac, near the enlisted men, like all the peddlers, coffin
makers, provisioners and hangers-on who move with an army, but you
might just have been lucky enough to find space near the officers'
tents. You wouldn't have been alone. There might have been a dozen
other photographers in camp. But there was work enough for all,
taking portraits from dawn till dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted a likeness to send home.
</P>
<P>
   For the wet-plate and tintype photographer John Coffer, it is as
if the 19th century were today and his contemporaries were not
Cindy Sherman and Thomas Struth but Mathew Brady, Timothy
O'Sullivan and a host of itinerant portrait makers who plied their
trade until the dawn of the modern era. Coffer, 48, has for more
than 20 years been practicing one of the earliest methods of
photography and living the life that went with it. He has
crisscrossed the country by horse- and ox-drawn wagon in an
11,000-mile odyssey, making pictures.
</P>
<P>
   He is now ensconced alone on a farm he bought in 1985 in the
Finger Lakes region of New York state, where he lives with his
horses and oxen, without heat, light, electricity, telephone or
running water. His cabin is his darkroom, and his wagon is parked
right out front. Spending time with Coffer, it's hard to sort out
which came first, the lifestyle or the photography. The two seem to
go together, inevitably, as methods of simplification in a complex
world, or as he calls it, ``purity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John Coffer is an American original,'' said Mark Osterman, a
photographic process historian at the George Eastman House and an
accomplished wet-plate photographer himself. ``He was among the
first to revive the wet plate process, and no one has been doing it
continuously longer or better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wet plate is the name of the process that displaced the
daguerreotype in the 1850s and, for a time, paper photography. It
involves coating a glass plate with an ether-based emulsion called
collodion, sensitizing it with silver, and exposing it in the
camera while the emulsion is still wet. The outcome is a negative
image on glass. By one of those paradoxes of light, if it is
underexposed and backed by a dark surface, the image reads as a
positive _ an ambrotype. Collodion can also be poured onto a
japanned iron plate, producing a similar one-of-kind positive. This
is the so-called tintype, although it contains no tin.
</P>
<P>
   Coffer never considered himself an artist and, like his
predecessors, has rarely made a picture he didn't intend to sell on
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   But he came to his hand-made life and hand-made photography out
of a single desire for a way of living without gimmicks.
``Photography and food are a lot alike,'' he said. ``You can't
really appreciate the flavor of a tomato unless you grow your own.
Commercial living and commercial photography have leached out all
the diversity, variety and intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   But commercial recognition, at least, appears to have caught up
with him. Coffer's first exhibition of ambrotypes and tintypes is
on view at Margaret Bodell's Wall Street Viewing Room through Sept.
21, and he has been invited by the South Street Seaport Museum to
photograph the ``old hotel'' memorialized by Joseph Mitchell's
stories before its renovation by the museum. ``Call me an artist if
you want to,'' says Coffer, ``but in the last century, the artist
was usually the amateur and the tintypist was the professional.''
</P>
<P>
   At a rugged 6-foot-3, Coffer seems fitted for the rigors of life
and photography without digital gadgets, but he had to make a long
journey toward both. In 1976, the Bicentennial year, he was living
in Florida, working for a local photo studio shooting everything
from fashion models to graduation portraits and spending his spare
time surfing. Something of a history buff, he heard about a Civil
War re-enactment taking place in Tennessee and on a whim decided to
see what it was like and try out an old camera he had bought.
</P>
<P>
   What Coffer found was, in his words, a collection of ``amateur
historians and cycle gang members.'' They were also resourceful
people who made their own costumes and regarded the past as alive
and important. They studied old photographs as attentively as
scholars do the Talmud. One re-enactor made the casual comment that
``no Civil War encampment was complete without a horse-drawn
photographer,'' and on his way back home, Coffer found himself
looking at roads differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I thought about it, the more I wanted to try a
different way of living,'' he said. ``We're constantly pushed
forward at a faster and faster pace. I wanted to know what we were
giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later he had sold his condominium and was in
Pennsylvania, learning from the Amish how to drive a horse-drawn
wagon. He left there with $125, a horse named Brownie, a covered
wagon, his antique camera, chemicals and a bedroll. He has been
traveling the same way ever since. ``I don't consider myself an
eccentric,'' he said. ``I just find a team of oxen more beautiful
than a John Deere tractor.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen the film ``The Straight Story,'' about an
elderly man who makes a spiritually profound Midwestern journey on
a lawnmower, can begin to understand the sense of freedom and
expansiveness Coffer found on the American road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day was an adventure,'' he said. Traveling by back roads
and pasturing Brownie in farmers' fields, he discovered a still
mostly rural America, by turns generous, amused and suspicious. He
has been arrested, shot at, deliberately run off the road, chased
out of town under suspicion of being a gypsy and hit by a car. He
has also been wined and dined, regaled with innumerable stories
around wood stoves, shown children's moth collections and
photographed as a celebrity. (His travels were covered by network
television, the wire services and People magazine.) He learned how
to do his own smithing and shoeing and raised a pair of oxen during
a stay in Iowa. He even got married during a stopover in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Coffer found people fascinated by his
photography. ``I faced the same challenge as a 19th-century
photographer attracting customers,'' he said. ``Wanted!'' Coffer's
handbill says, ``a hundred thousand men, women and children to go
to the new gallery and get their pictures made in the same day.''
He set up shop where he could at fairs, in people's yards, next to
motels, in back of firehouses, even on main streets in towns with
names like Intercourse and Java. He has also documented Civil War
re-enactments and taught other photographers how to do it. His
images of the 1997 Antietam re-enactment are so meticulous that
only an occasional participant's paunch gives away the contemporary
setting.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   When Coffer started out, most ``antique'' commercial photography
was actually Polaroid, tinted or covered with brown cellophane to
look old. Since collodion is developed on the spot, he, too, could
offer near-instant gratification but with more substantial results.
He learned to make beautiful cases and lockets, turning his photos
into keepsakes, as they would have been presented originally.
Coffer worked initially with commercially coated ``dry'' plates and
tintypes because there was no way to learn the wet-plate formulas
and techniques. He visited the Smithsonian, only to be told, ``Let
us know when you find out how it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   He began to find out in 1980 while wintering in Jacksonville,
Ore. He discovered a cache of old photography manuals and equipment
in the local museum. He also saw a copy of William Crawford's
``Keepers of the Light,'' the first modern book to document
historic photographic processes. ``I realized it was possible to be
truly faithful to past practices,'' Coffer said. Looking at
wet-plate images, one can see why the process is so compelling. The
collodion emulsion produces images of startling precision. There is
complex interplay between background and foreground, detail and
blurring.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Coffer for the first time began to photograph ``as
an artist,'' not as a portraitist. The images _ all taken near the
cabin he built himself _ combine simplicity and clarity. The bough
of an ice-covered pine, for example, is transformed into a
still-life of Japanese delicacy. One has the simultaneous sense of
things seen and things glimpsed at the edge of visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Collodion's uncanny quality of presence and absence has
attracted a growing number of artists, including Sally Mann, Luis
Gonzalez Palma, Mark and France Scully Osterman, who publish ``The
Collodion Journal,'' and the filmmaker Stephen Berkman, who took a
tutorial with Coffer and has made what is probably the first modern
collodion moving picture. In describing her own photographs, Mann
captured the paradoxical beauty of the process: ``They embrace time
and memory, and become the still point at which the two
intersect.''
</P>
<P>
   John Coffer seems to have achieved his own still point where
past and present intersect. But his newfound identity as an artist
may alter that.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of the farm, which he bought at his wife's urging
(they are now divorced), increasingly conflict with the demands of
art. He has written a manual of collodion technique and regularly
gives workshops. ``With the growing interest in my work,'' he said,
``I'm free to think about what I want to shoot. But the farm is
hard work. The animals have to be tended and I don't make back what
it costs to raise them.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes him think again about hitching up the photographic
wagon parked in the front yard. ``Life on the road taught me how
little I need in order to live,'' he said. ``I'm beginning to feel
cluttered here. What's the adage, either the trip serves the thing
or the thing serves the trip? Out there in my wagon, I'm not on a
trip. I'm home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
