</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Titanic salvors say ship's hull is deteriorating quickly
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - An undersea salvage expedition to the Titanic has
found touching new traces of the personal tragedies amid the
wreckage of the doomed luxury liner _ and growing evidence that,
after 88 years at the bottom of the North Atlantic, the hull of the
``unsinkable'' ship is crumbling at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The condition of hull is dramatically different than it was
just two years ago,'' Arnie Geller, president of RMS Titanic Inc.,
the Atlanta company that has exclusive salvage rights to the wreck,
said Tuesday. ``We were surprised by the rate of corrosion. The
wall of Capt. Smith's cabin has split apart and the deck where the
15-ton ship's anchor rests is visibly sagging.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, two Russian-built mini-submarines used by the
company have recovered more than 350 artifacts from the debris
surrounding the ship, which struck an iceberg April 14, 1912 and
sank with a loss of 1,500 lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a new debris field this year and some of the things
we have recovered are very touching and very personal,'' Geller
said. ``We found a leather-covered case of 40 perfume vials
belonging to Adolphe Saalfeld, a merchant from Manchester, England,
who was actually one of the survivors. When we opened one of the
vials in our shipboard laboratory, even after all the years it had
been down there, it filled the room with the scent of flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Geller said other items plucked from the half-mile trail of
debris scattered across the floor of the Atlantic, 12,000 feet
below the surface, include a handbag belonging to an Englishwoman,
a third-class passenger, who went down with the ship; a suitcase of
books and postcards; some ``magnificent'' pieces of unbroken china;
and fragments of the ship's hull stamped with the official ``401''
number given to it by the White Star Line.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's salvage operation, the sixth since the company won
exclusive rights to the wreck in 1987, has restricted its recovery
of artifacts to areas outside the wreck. But Geller said the
condition of the hull, and pressure from company stockholders
demanding a return on their investment, makes it likely that the
firm will begin retrieving objects from the interior as early as
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two weeks, salvage operators will explore the
holds and passageways of the Titanic with a deep-diving robot and
television camera in hopes of locating valuable, high profile
objects for future recovery, including a $300 million shipment of
diamonds that was reportedly aboard the ship when it sank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is ticking,'' said Geller. ``If we don't enter the
ship for salvage purposes soon, ocean microbes will devour the
ship's steel for all eternity. There is incredible value down there
and we are determined to recover as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of continuing salvage efforts puts the company
sharply at odds with some prominent scientists and with an
international agreement being considered by the United States,
Canada, France and England, the four countries that played major
roles in the Titanic tragedy. The proposed treaty, yet to be
ratified by any nation, would give each country the last word in
any future salvage operations on the wreck. Fearful that oversight
by a federal agency would undercut its salvage rights, Geller's
company has sued the federal government to block such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   But oceanographer Robert Ballard, who co-discovered the wreck in
1985, said he is saddened by the continued series of intrusions in
what he feels should be considered a marine graveyard. ``Extensive
salvage operations in the debris field surrounding the Titanic have
scarred that site for many years to come,'' he said. ``It is as if
a fleet of tractors had plowed the battlefield of Gettysburg.''
</P>
<P>
   But Geller said the continued recovery of artifacts benefits
more than the company stockholders. To date, the company has
recovered more than 5,000 artifacts. Exhibits, which currently
provide the company's principal source of income, have been seen by
six million people in more than a dozen cities. For a select few,
first-hand views of the Titanic are available _ at a price. The
Russian Academy of Sciences, which operates the Mir 1 and Mir 2
submarines now engaged in salvage work, charges $30,000 a person
for brief dives to the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   But given the remote location of the wreck, Geller said
recovered artifacts are the only way that large numbers of people
will ever see real pieces of the Titanic. He has pledged that, in
compliance with a federal court order, the company will keep all
historically important artifacts together and, if they are sold, to
sell them as an intact collection to a museum that will assure
continued public access to them.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the company intends to sell any go
</P>
</TEXT>
