r f BC-BELLSOUTH0816-COX     08-15 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T: No long-distance for BellSouth
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - As BellSouth edges closer to a request to enter
long-distance, the company's biggest critic is also its largest
customer.
</P>
<P>
   In this sometimes confused new world, where telecommunications
companies daily compete and do business with each other, BellSouth
each day sells connections to its network _ still the Southeast's
dominant phone system. Buyers are competitors for local service as
well as long-distance companies that need calls carried to homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest company in this category is both local rival and
long-distance customer: AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of declining market share, AT&AMP;T still does nearly
half the long-distance business. Many of those calls start or end
with BellSouth customers, so AT&AMP;T pays BellSouth more than $2
billion a year in fees. But AT&AMP;T also plans to offer local service,
where it needs BellSouth's cooperation in switching retail
customers back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, AT&AMP;T charges that BellSouth isn't ready for real
competition in local service. BellSouth says that isn't so, and the
company accuses AT&AMP;T of canceling meetings with the Georgia Public
Service Commission aimed at solving the problems. AT&AMP;T retorts that
it asked for delay only because BellSouth is so woefully
unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in some ways, a family feud.
</P>
<P>
   After all, BellSouth was created along with six other Bells in
the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T, then often known as Ma Bell. The Bells
were banned from long-distance, which was, in any event, nearly all
in the hands of AT&AMP;T. The Bells won the right to enter the market
from the Telecom Act of 1996 _ but only if they opened their local
markets to competition. That approval has been won by SBC in Texas
and Verizon _ the former Bell Atlantic _ in New York.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T says it fears that once the carrot of long-distance is
gone, BellSouth's cooperation will evaporate. It cites New York,
where Bell Atlantic's long-distance approval was followed by
raucous criticism _ and millions of dollars in fines _ when company
systems were unable to handle an average of 15,000 orders per day.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's systems are about as ready for competition as Bell
Atlantic's were in January, said Ray Crafton, AT&AMP;T vice president,
who has been involved in both states.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth has been saying for a long time that its entry was
imminent and its systems were ship-shape. To prove it, BellSouth
more than a year ago agreed to a test of its system under the eye
of the PSC. The KPMG tests have logged 100 ``exceptions,'' glitches
_ or worse _ in the system. BellSouth says it has fixed half of
those problems and is working on the rest. But AT&AMP;T says that in
ongoing tests of BellSouth systems run by the two companies, nearly
30 percent of mock customer orders at any one time get stuck _ for
more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``BellSouth is not losing orders,'' Crafton said. ``But they
don't seem to know how to process them.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth rejects those numbers. Spokesman Joe Chandler said
BellSouth has handled 90 percent of the orders by the date
specified, averaging 2.57 days per order. BellSouth says it already
treats competitors as well as its own retail unit is treated _ an
assertion that draws scorn from AT&AMP;T and smaller contenders. But
Chandler said complaints are meant to delay BellSouth's
long-distance entry a bit longer, not only to prevent competition
but also to squeeze the most possible cooperation on local service
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is interesting to us that AT&AMP;T is trying to air this in
public, with the press, rather than talk about this with us and the
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stands by its June prediction that a filing for
long-distance will come in August, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with positive results, BellSouth will ask the Federal
Communications Commission for the right to offer long-distance in
Georgia. BellSouth technically does not need PSC endorsement. In
fact, BellSouth's applications in Louisiana and South Carolina were
embraced by regulators, then rejected by the FCC. But the FCC
typically starts its investigations by asking for the judgment of
local regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the PSC will not stamp its imprimatur on a proposal
unless it is confident of approval, said PSC Commissioner David
Burgess. ``We are not going to put ourselves in the position of
South Carolina and Louisiana. When it's right, it's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it happen by the end of August?
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what I am seeing, I think it's extremely optimistic
to say that,'' Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   And all this comes with long-distance itself of increasingly
dubious value. AT&AMP;T has only been the most conspicuously damaged
carrier as profit margins are squeezed by ``nickel nights,''
dial-around offerings and technology changes that drive prices
earthward.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of BellSouth argue that long-distance's diminishing
allure undercuts BellSouth's urgency about opening up its lucrative
near-monopoly in local service. BellSouth just isn't trying very
hard to improve its systems, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But BellSouth argues that long-distance is still viable and
besides, it must have long-distance as part of its ``bundle'' in
order to be a full-service telecom provider. Moreover, even
low-margin services can feed the bottom line if packaged with
other, more profitable services like high-speed access.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, representatives of several competitors told PSC
commissioners that BellSouth had not given them smooth and rapid
access to its network.
</P>
<P>
   ``BellSouth is required by federal law to open its local phone
service to competitors,'' said William Perry, co-chair of Georgians
Calling for Competition, which describes itself as a non-profit
coalition of consumers, businesses and organization. ``Now it is up
to the Georgia PSC to make sure the right standards are in place to
ensure BellSouth does so in a manner that doesn't handicap the
companies trying to offer competitive services.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
