s e BC-ABBIE-HOFFMAN-MOVIE-$     08-15 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBIE-HOFFMAN-MOVIE-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAL THIS MYTH: WHY WE STILL TRY TO RE-CREATE THE RUSH OF THE
'60S 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20) 
 By ELLEN WILLIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The whole world is watching!'' chanted demonstrators outside
the First Union Center in Philadelphia during the Republican
National Convention this month. Many had not yet been born when
that cry first sounded on the streets of Chicago, in 1968, as the
police clubbed protesters during the tumultuous Democratic
convention. This time the words were unwittingly ironic: Most of
the world passed up the opportunity to watch on television, whether
because the convention itself was designed to be noncontroversial
or because today's dissidents have not yet gained the fearsome
reputation of their elders. The police had evidently declined the
role of on-camera head-bashers. But the scene was yet another
tribute to the enduring power of the '60s in the national
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   So is ``Steal This Movie,'' Robert Greenwald's biographical
movie about Abbie Hoffman, that charismatic exemplar of '60s
cultural radicalism, a defendant in the conspiracy trial of the
Chicago Seven _ the leaders of the Chicago protest _ and the author
of ``Steal This Book,'' among other provocations. According to
publicity for the film, which opened on Friday, Greenwald (who had
met Hoffman years ago) was inspired to undertake the project by a
conversation with his teen-age daughters, who were attracted to the
decade's aura of rebellion, as well as its music and fashions, but
knew little about it.
</P>
<P>
   The slogans, sounds and iconic images of the '60s are constantly
evoked. They are romanticized, reviled, embraced by fledgling
movements as their legacy or appropriated for television
commercials (steal this era).
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all their familiarity, the experience that produced the
artifacts eludes replication, in ways that go beyond the usual
problems associated with transmuting lived events into the
historical and cultural record.
</P>
<P>
   The '60s produced such a rush of events that the distinction
between news and daily life seemed to blur. Besides the Chicago
protest, 1968 saw the assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and
Robert Kennedy (the latter knocking the shooting of Andy Warhol off
the front page), the Columbia University student strike, the
student-worker uprising in Paris, ``Prague Spring'' and the ensuing
Soviet invasion, and the launching of women's liberation with a
demonstration against the Miss America pageant. There is also the
difficulty of conveying the spirit of the '60s revolt at a time
when many of its attitudes _ sexual permissiveness, hostility to
politicians, a preference for rawly expressive music _ have been
assimilated into mainstream culture, while the utopian passion that
once pervaded them has vanished.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest obstacle to representing the '60s in more than
cartoonish fashion is that it was thoroughly mythologized even as
it was happening. Mass-mediated images of rock stars, hippies and
new leftists spread the counterculture and anti-war movement from
the East and West coasts to every provincial town in the country.
These images inspired events, like Woodstock or the Chicago
demonstrations, that were not only recorded and mythified but often
designed _ whether by spontaneous improvisation or by deliberate
playing to the press _ to act the images out.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock, perhaps the most famous '60s event-cum-myth of all,
began as a commercial effort to capitalize on the publicity
generated by Monterey Pop, the euphoric free festival that had
introduced Janis Joplin, Jimi Hendrix, flower children and San
Francisco psychedelic lovespeak to a national audience in 1967.
Clearly, the promoters didn't count on the image of Monterey being
so potent that, two years later, it would attract nearly half a
million kids with no intention of buying tickets. But they came,
determined to live out the countercultural fantasy despite
uncooperative weather and crisis-level shortages of food, water and
toilets. ``Woodstock,'' the movie, documented a real experience,
but one that was in crucial respects a performance _ even before
the filmmakers added their own layer of editing.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, on the other hand, was always conceived by its
organizers _ especially Abbie Hoffman and his partner in mischief
Jerry Rubin _ as an opportunity to show new left political theater
on national television. Everything Hoffman and Rubin did, from
nominating a live pig for president to representing their small
contingent of ``cultural revolutionaries'' as typical of a crowd
that was mostly far less militant (and less colorful), was aimed at
drawing the media's attention. Of course, the collaboration of a
paranoid Mayor Richard Daley was essential; but perhaps he, too,
took rhetoric for reality.
</P>
<P>
   The most effective renderings of the '60s have been works of
``new journalism,'' like Tom Wolfe's ``Electric Kool-Aid Acid
Test'' and Norman Mailer's ``Armies of the Night,'' that explore,
with aesthetic and philosophical sophistication, dissolving
boundaries between experience and performance, reality and image,
reporting and mythmaking. The only novel I can think of that comes
close to capturing the '60s imagination is Marge Piercy's ``Dance
the Eagle to Sleep,'' the 1970 tale of a band of underground
revolutionaries. It works because the characters come across as
more mythic, or allegorical, than ``real''; still, I have the
feeling that Greenwald's daughters would find it puzzling. As for
film, whether documentary or fictional, it would seem that endless
replays of demonstrators versus cops, hippies frolicking naked in
the mud, joints passing around a circle, freaked out Vietnam vets
and so on, have had such a numbing effect as to suggest that a
fresh image of the '60s is an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I heard about Greenwald's film, it occurred to me that
a movie about one of the decade's chief image-makers might find a
way out of this bind. Abbie Hoffman self-consciously sought to
bring together the largely separate and sometimes antagonistic
cohorts of bohemia and the organized new left. In his own person he
merged the two central _ if not always compatible _ myths of the
'60s rebels: the myth of cultural liberation through libidinal
ecstasy and fabulous excess, and the myth of a morally righteous
generation rising up against war, racism and materialism
perpetrated by its elders. He was, in short, a primary author of
the '60s narrative that, in its various bowdlerized and canned
forms, is now ubiquitous in our popular culture. And he pulled this
off precisely by his keen understanding of the power of media not
merely to record reality but to create it.
</P>
<P>
   Stunts like scattering dollar bills on the floor of the New York
Stock Exchange, where startled minions of capital scrambled to pick
them up, not only condensed a world view into one arresting image,
but brilliantly satirized the opposition. Hoffman used this
technique to even greater effect during the Chicago Seven trial, in
which he wore a judicial robe to court, insisted he lived in
Woodstock Nation _ in the state of mind of his brothers and sisters
_ and otherwise turned the proceedings into an epic baiting of the
judge unlucky enough to share his surname.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   There are rich possibilities here for avoiding the standard '60s
banalities _ or restoring the power of now-tired images _ by
focusing on the process of their creation. ``Steal This Movie''
adopts a promising strategy for highlighting that process: Vincent
D'Onofrio as Hoffman, having gone underground after his 1973 arrest
for selling cocaine, calls from his hiding place to hector a young
reporter, David Glenn (Alan Van Sprang), into writing his story;
the reporter's interviews with Abbie's wife Anita (played by
Janeane Garofalo), his lawyer Gerry Lefcourt (Kevin Pollak) and
others become, as in ``Citizen Kane,'' the framework for the
unfolding of his life.
</P>
<P>
   That life is portrayed as a creative self-invention in which the
gap between public and private disappears, only to reopen with a
vengeance when Hoffman becomes a fugitive in 1974. While hiding
one's identity is inherently stressful, for Hoffman it signifies
total obliteration. Even in absentia, he can't resist trying to
commandeer the press; but then he hates Glenn's story. He emerges
from a near breakdown only by taking the risk of adopting a new
public persona as an environmental activist, Barry Freed, in
upstate New York, and even that doesn't quite work. In the '80s,
after turning himself in and being paroled, he is portrayed as
reintegrating his past with his present, inspiring a new generation
of activists. But his 1989 suicide, which is only mentioned in the
epilogue, seems to tell another story. While the movie duly records
Hoffman's diagnosis of bipolar disorder and his treatment with
lithium, the thrust of its narrative suggests that mental illness
is never purely organic.
</P>
<P>
   The best scenes in ``Steal This Movie'' focus on Abbie as media
artist. His hilarious demolition of Judge Julius Hoffman's court,
which made his testimony a showcase for the triumph of an
echt-American freedom-loving bad boy over a humorless authoritarian
state, loses none of its resonance in the retelling. His wedding to
Anita _ featuring an ``intimate'' gathering of hundreds of people
and the press, photographs of the happy couple naked with bags over
their heads, and wedding announcements with joints enclosed mailed
to random strangers _ is a lighter but equally witty sendup of
another established institution.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, though, the movie fails to make the '60s live. For
one thing, its basically conventional dramatic form undercuts the
irreverent content. Except for its title and the obligatory
television footage, both real and fake, ``Steal This Movie'' does
not reflect on its own status as a mass-mediated object; perhaps
the reporter who frames the story should have been made a
television producer, allowing an offstage ``Abbie'' or a real-life
Anita to comment on the action and the actors. D'Onofrio plays his
role straight, aiming to be a realistic Abbie Hoffman with the
right accent and mannerisms, with the result that he often conveys
an un-Abbie-like air of trying too hard. He might have done better
to concentrate on getting across his character's antic spirit, as
Jim Carrey did in playing Andy Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that the center of the drama becomes the
unmasking of Cointelpro, the FBI program that subjected the new
left in general, and Abbie Hoffman in particular, to illegal
surveillance and harassment. For most of the movie, Glenn dismisses
as paranoid Hoffman's insistence that such a project exists; but in
the end he comes around and helps Gerry Lefcourt nail down the
evidence. In making this theme so important, Greenwald _ no doubt
taking his cue from his lengthy interviews with Anita Hoffman (who
died last year of breast cancer) _ allows his film to imply that
FBI machinations were responsible for the collapse of '60s
radicalism, as well as for Abbie's travails. As a result, the movie
is ultimately recast in the well-worn mold of a muckraking flick:
'60s myth meets post-Watergate cliche. In fact, the '60s revolt
succumbed as much to its activists' hubris on the one hand, and
their fatigue and confusion on the other, as to anything the
government did. For that matter, the government's most effective
weapon against the movement turned out to be the abolition of the
draft. Cointelpro, however vicious, was a sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Hoffman himself simply a victim of the state. Police
entrapment or no _ the truth remains unclear _ Abbie sold cocaine,
an outrageous risk for someone in his position. ``Steal This
Movie'' glosses over this discomfiting fact. Marty Jezer's
sympathetic 1992 biography ``Abbie Hoffman: American Rebel,'' on
which the movie is largely based, is more forthcoming about Abbie's
dark side: the egomania, foolhardy machismo and increasing
attraction to the violent sectarian left.
</P>
<P>
   Two kinds of voices dominate the present conversation about the
'60s: those who condemn the utopianism of the time as a
totalitarian delusion, and those who sentimentally endow it with a
moral purity unknown to today's era of rampant materialism and
cynicism about politics. What's missing from both accounts is the
'60s as emotional experience: the desire to live intensely, the
hope that people could have more than Freud's ordinary unhappiness.
For my generation, the pursuit of happiness was not a slogan; it
turned our guts inside out and left us with a bone-deep sense of
loss. ``Steal This Movie'' makes a stab at expressing this
dimension, but in the end it sentimentalizes.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, the movie that gets closest to the heart of the
matter isn't about the '60s at all: It's ``Thelma and Louise.'' Two
female outlaws are transformed by unspeakable hopes for freedom,
for a wholly different way of being. They can't go back no matter
what. As they leap to their deaths, for one last defiant (and
mythic) moment, they are complete. I imagine Abbie would have loved
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
