<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-CELL-PHONES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT PUTS LIMITS ON CELL PHONE TRACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for privacy advocates, a federal
appeals court on Tuesday restricted the FBI's ability to track the
whereabouts of cell phone users while opening the door for
first-ever limits on a controversial e-mail surveillance system
known as Carnivore.
</P>
<P>
   The government sought the power to be able to track the location
of suspected criminals via their cellular phones. Privacy groups
and the cellular industry took the government to court, asserting
that the proposed investigative tool _ along with others the
Justice Department had sought to keep up with increasingly
sophisticated criminals in the digital age _ was rife for potential
abuse against law-abiding citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals here said that the need for
investigators to obtain the location of suspects using their cell
phones was ``both reasoned and reasonable.'' But the three-judge
panel erected barriers, ruling that the government could only gain
such information with the approval and oversight of a court that
sanctions surveillance and wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 million Americans use cell phones and an
ever-increasing amount of communications and commerce _ including
Internet activity _ are conducted over cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy organizations had been concerned that the FBI could
acquire the location of cell phone users through what is known as a
pen register, an easy-to-obtain court order that does not require
investigators to present a judge with probable cause as a wiretap
warrant does. The organizations envisioned that investigators would
be able to track the whereabouts of people who are not suspects in
an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision makes it clear: location of cell phone users
cannot be provided under a pen register order,'' said Jim Dempsey,
senior counsel for the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT),
one of several organizations that sued the government.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Olson, who represented the CDT and the Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association before the appeals court,
said the ruling ``protects the privacy and integrity of the
telephone system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a cell phone could be converted into a tracking device,
then that would have been a serious intrusion into privacy
rights,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 16-page decision does not say that law enforcement
officials must now seek a wiretap warrant before tracking a cell
phone user. It says that law enforcement must now seek ``something
more than a pen register order.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also shot down efforts by the government to gain
access to private data that may be punched on a cell phone keypad,
such as calling card numbers or credit card accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that is expected to have ramifications for the
FBI's controversial Carnivore system, the judges ruled that the
government must obtain a court-ordered wiretap to access the
digital ``packets'' of information that travel over the cellular
phone network. These packets are the standard unit of digital
communication and are increasingly used over cellular networks.
</P>
<P>
   The government cannot require cellular carriers to provide
investigators with information that is ``not authorized to be
intercepted,'' the court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling appears to call into question the legality of
Carnivore, which scans the Internet and captures these ``packets.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnivore, which would be installed at Internet service
providers like America Online, searches for the on-line activities
of a target of an investigation. The FBI would obtain a wiretap to
access a suspect's e-mail. But the Carnivore system also would give
the FBI access to the entirety of the Internet provider's
electronic traffic, allowing the agency to sift through the
information in search of a suspect's email.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said the ruling ``raises concerns about this approach
where the FBI says, let us have access to everything and we'll sort
it out ourselves.'' Olson added that the ruling could have ``a very
significant impact'' on the use of Carnivore, which is now under
review by Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   CTIA went further. In a statement, the group, which represents
major cellular phone manufacturers, said the ruling ``may make
illegal the FBI's newest data searching tool, Carnivore.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Colgate, an assistant U.S. attorney general who is
spearheading the Carnivore review for Reno, said the Justice
Department would take the ruling into consideration. ``We'll use as
part of this review the findings of this decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
