<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-SONOMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTEL NETWORKS BUYING SONOMA SYSTEMS FOR ABOUT $540 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sonoma Systems Inc., a builder of systems offering one-wire
Internet, voice, and video connections, is being acquired by Nortel
Networks in a stock deal worth up to $540 million. Sonoma is based
in California but has a significant presence in Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced Tuesday, is Nortel's 12th in as many months
as it moves further into markets offering local ``on-ramps'' to
high-speed nationwide optical networks that have become a major
focus of the Canadian telecom giant.
</P>
<P>
   One of Nortel's locally based competitors in long-distance
optical networking, Sycamore Networks of Chelmsford, Mass., has
made a similar push into local access by purchasing Sirocco Systems
of Connecticut for $2.8 billion earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies and cable broadband system operators use Sonoma
gear to provide business customers with a unified connection
offering telephone service over the Net as well as high-speed Net
access and video services.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 of Sonoma's 125 employees are based in Marlborough.
Nortel counts more than 3,000 employees in Massachusetts already,
through earlier acquisitions of Bay Networks, the successor to
Billerica, Mass.-based Wellfleet Communications Inc., and other
companies including Epicon of Chelmsford, Mass. and Coretek of
Wilmington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel had earlier made a comarketing arrangement to incorporate
Sonoma gear in its networking products. Sonoma gear serves a
``carrier-managed services'' market estimated to be worth $18
billion annually by 2002, according to The Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schilling, Nortel president of access networks, said:
``This acquisition represents another building block in our local
Internet capabilities that will enable service providers to offer
new profitable services directly to businesses and consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Christin Armacost, an analyst at S.G. Cowen, told Reuters news
service the Sonoma acquisition is ``a good product portfolio fit''
for Nortel. But the comparatively modest purchase price suggests it
is only a ``technology extension'' rather than a major new
corporate emphasis, Armacost said.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma had filed for an initial public offering in February, but
it is still a public company. It reported then that it had $7.1
million in revenues last year, about 20 percent derived from sales
to Nortel, and net losses of $14 million. The company said sales
this year could exceed $20 million but gave no indication of when
the company, based in Marina Del Rey, Calif., could be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of Sonoma, which was spun off from Vertel Corp. two
years ago, include FiberNet Telecom Group Inc., Madison River
Communications, Savvis Communications Corp., and Electric Lightwave
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel said it will issue $480 million of stock when the deal
closes and $60 million more if Sonoma reaches sales targets in the
first year under Nortel ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is scheduled to close this autumn subject to antitrust
and Sonoma shareholder approvals. Nortel said the deal will have no
impact on earnings this year and will slightly increase its
earnings per share from operations in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma has also had reseller arrangements for its gear with
Siemens AG, Cabletron Systems Inc., and Alcatel SA. It was not
immediately clear how the Nortel acquisition would affect those
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel shares closed Tuesday at $80.3125, up $1.0625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
