<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MORAL-MUSIC-$ADV20-NY     08-15 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORAL-MUSIC-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING WORKED UP AGAIN OVER POP CULTURE'S GROSS-OUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 20)  
 By JON PARELES   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's an election year without a moral panic? Popular music,
and pop culture in general, are set up to be prime targets this
year, stuck in the crossfire of a battle for the righteous high
ground. Republicans and Democrats are both positioning themselves
as guardians of what George W. Bush, in his speech accepting the
Republican nomination, called ``essential values.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, as everyone remembers, is married to Tipper Gore, a
founder of the Parents' Music Resource Center, which pressured
recording companies to place quasi-voluntary warning labels on
potentially offensive albums. His vice-presidential choice, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, sponsored legislation to require labeling for
recordings, movies and video games, with penalties for selling
taboo material to children. (The bill was defeated.) Both major
parties seem poised to offer cultural clean-up plans.
</P>
<P>
   When the moral-panic soundbites start to fly, artistic subtlety
is the first casualty. Eminem, pop's current chief miscreant, has
already drawn considerable flak for his second album, ``The
Marshall Mathers LP.'' He deserves some of it; when he gets lazy,
he defaults to homophobic slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``The Marshall Mathers LP'' is also an extended, twisted,
hyperbolic diatribe about the gap between fantasy and reality,
persona and personality, word and action. Eminem spends long
stretches telling listeners not to like him, not to act like him
and not to expect him to act like the wild man in his songs. ``Drug
Ballad'' has an infamous line: ``You are now allowed to officially
slap bitches.'' But it follows a description of ``you'' getting
falling-down drunk; four lines later, still drunk, ``you'' drive
your car to ``cause a 42-car pileup.'' It's pretty clear that the
song describes idiotic behavior, but even simple irony is too
complicated for a soundbite.
</P>
<P>
   The million-selling rap-metal band Slipknot, which dresses its
members like clowns and ghouls and draws rabidly slam-dancing
crowds, is just reaching the radar of the censorious with potential
soundbites like ``How many times have you wanted to kill/
Everything and everyone.'' But the songs are blurted confessions of
characters about to crack up or commit suicide; fans use them as an
energy boost and hear them as much-needed company in adolescent
misery. There's context beyond the mayhem, more than the
parental-advisory label suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the busy pop marketplace has no lack of crass,
pandering products. The moral panic is a fitting response to a
grotesque cultural moment. Pop culture's governing intelligence
seems to belong to a hormone-addled 15-year-old boy who can't tell
whether he's horny or furious.
</P>
<P>
   In an article for The New York Times Magazine, RJ Smith
described a confluence of rap-metal, wrestling and pornography in
which rage and sexual confusion reinforce each other and women and
gay men have become fair game. Add in morning-radio shock jocks,
gladiatorial talk shows, ever cruder comedy acts, blood-spattered
action movies and brutal video games, and the spectacle of heavy
breathing backed by hair-trigger force is everywhere. Millions of
people now happily entertain themselves with visions of gross-outs,
punch-outs and shoot-outs. They're ready to rumble, even if they
tell pollsters they're worried about other people's bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   Where did the testosterone frenzy come from? If pop culture is a
barometer of unexpressed desires, then the angry white male, seen
by pollsters as a major factor in 1990s elections, is still gaining
ground. He misses his unquestioned power; he resents the gains of
feminism and gay rights. In a rebellion against liberal tolerance,
he's reasserting longtime rule over all the underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   But since tolerance has become the norm, he also insists that he
has become an underdog himself. He wants to be as cool as any
oppressed minority, even if his main source of oppression is girls
who spurn his coarse advances. Slipknot, or the wrestler called the
Rock (who spoke at the Republican convention), lets him share in a
roar of defiance, or a headlock, applied to enemies real or
imaginary.
</P>
<P>
   But pop culture is a cantankerous, polymorphous critter. It's
just as likely, and perhaps more likely, to be a counterweight,
providing feelings that people are missing in their daily lives.
For the overwhelming majority of people who can distinguish between
fact and fiction, culture can be an escape and a compensation, like
psychological antimatter. Consider that some of the poorest nations
_ Haiti, Congo _ produce some of the world's happiest-sounding
music.
</P>
<P>
   Censorious types envision a monkey-see, monkey-do relationship
between culture and its fans. Imitation and seepage can occur; on
anecdotal evidence, it seems people are more likely to voice
misogynistic or homophobic slurs now than they were a decade ago.
Yet there's also a monkey-don't response: the video game satiates
the mass-murder impulse. A piece of popular culture that touts its
realism _ like recent gangsta rap _ may well be assuming an
audience that's too far from the original scene to check
authenticity, much less participate.
</P>
<P>
   So pop provides both chronicles of the moment and anthems of
wishful thinking. During the late 1960s, when the United States was
conducting the Vietnam War and bitter tensions divided the country,
pop songs called for peace, unity and love. The great mid-1970s
letdown _ Watergate, oil crisis, recession _ sent perky, hedonistic
disco to the top of the charts. In 2000, the United States has
peace, a humming economy and widespread quiescence; there's no
visible enemy, just bland corporate power. And as a balance, pop
culture is a thrashing, belligerent mess, where everyday
frustration and aggression discharge in a jubilant symbolic rage.
It's a strange equilibrium, and applying real-world values might
have unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
