<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-1STL     08-15 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-CONCORDE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-780(2TAKES)-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS GROUNDS ITS CONCORDES AFTER REPORT BY INVESTIGATORS
 
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for writethru to add new information on recommended
withdrawal of airworthiness certificate and to add details and
restructure throughout.) 
(Eds: This story is now on Page 1.) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways PLC grounded its fleet of Concorde
supersonic airliners Tuesday after French and British investigators
said they would urge the withdrawal of the airplane's airworthiness
certification following the fatal crash of an Air France Concorde
near Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first time in more than 20 years that an
airworthiness certificate for a commercial airliner had been
revoked by any country. The investigators said they would not spell
out their reasoning until Wednesday, and so it was unclear why they
were recommending certification be withdrawn, what steps would have
to be taken to reverse the recommendation or how long that might
take.
</P>
<P>
   A British Airways spokeswoman said the suspension of flights was
``indefinite.'' But it remained unclear whether the move
effectively meant the end of supersonic trans-Atlantic flights,
largely the elite preserve of executives and celebrities over the
airplane's 25 years of commercial operation.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways and Air France are the only airlines to fly the
Concorde. Aviation analysts and officials say the investigators'
action suggests that they believe that British Airways' fleet of
seven Concordes faces the same risk of catastrophe as the doomed
Air France Flight 4590.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on everything I know, it is a safe aircraft to fly,''
said the British Airways chief executive, Rod Eddington. ``But at
the end of the day, we rest on the information provided to us by
the accident investigators and regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   The July 25 crash was the only fatal Concorde accident in the
plane's history. When it happened, Air France immediately suspended
flights by its remaining five Concordes. British Airways, after an
initial one-day suspension, continued to fly the needle-nosed
airliner, which crosses the Atlantic in three and one-half hours.
</P>
<P>
   French investigators concluded five days ago that a 16-inch
piece of metal on the runway at Charles de Gaulle airport probably
slashed a tire as the Air France plane hurtled down the runway on
take-off at about 195 mph, scattering debris that ruptured fuel
tanks. The plane took off with a plume of flame spewing from its
wing and crashed less than two minutes later
</P>
<P>
   British officials declined to say whether Tuesday's suspension
of flights meant that British Airways' seven Concordes had also
been at risk since the Paris crash. But Chris Mason, a spokesman
for Britain's Civil Aviation Authority, said that after French
investigators focused on the role of the tire blowout in the
accident, ``We have taken the position that we think it right to
suspend the certificate of airworthiness for Concorde'' in Britain
as well as France.
</P>
<P>
   Helena Bastianelli, a spokeswoman for the French accident
investigation bureau, said a ruptured tire ``should not have such
consequences as the piercing of the tank and the destruction of the
aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing there is something that is not safe there, and
until the safety of the aircraft can be guaranteed, we recommend
that the Concorde stops flying,'' she continued.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Press Association news agency reported Tuesday night
that British Airways Concordes had been fitted with reinforced
flaps above the under-carriage because of the risk of debris from
damaged tires hitting the wings. An alarm system had also been
positioned on the flight-decks to warn crew members of blowouts. It
was not clear if Air France had made similar modifications, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   David Learmount, operations and safety officer of Flight
International magazine, called the recommendation for suspension of
the Concorde's certification ``very, very rare and very, very
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said that British Airways had modified its fleet of Concordes
in the mid-1990s to prevent similar tire accidents from causing
catastrophic damage and, on the basis of that modification, the
airplanes had been permitted to continue flying.
</P>
<P>
   After assessing evidence from the French investigation, however,
British investigators ``must have come to the conclusion that
despite the British Airways modification, the risk is unacceptably
high'' of a crash similar to the one in France, Learmount said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A suspension of certification, he said, means ``the aircraft is
grounded, and it has to be modified so that the risk is eliminated
or reduced'' to the satisfaction of aviation regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The last such suspension of certification, he said, involved
DC-10 aircraft. The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration grounded
the planes for five weeks in 1979 after the crash of an American
Airlines plane in Chicago killed 275 people.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mason at Britain's Civil Aviation Authority said it was ``almost
impossible'' to say how long the suspension would remain in force,
but aviation industry experts said that, whatever the outcome, the
combination of last month's accident and the planned withdrawal of
flying certification could seriously damage confidence in Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Concorde flights account for only a fraction of the earnings of
both Air France and British Airways, although British Airways is
thought to earn slightly more because it usually schedules two
flights a day each way between London and New York, whereas Air
France had one. The service is reduced to one return journey each
day in August, when demand among its usual high-end customers is
low, British Airways said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite high maintenance and fuel costs, the aircraft also act
as prestige emblems, drawing in the well-heeled corporate
passengers that British Airways, in particular, sees as its
principal source of income. Aviation industry experts have
suggested that, if Concorde loses its appeal, then corporate
travelers could move to other airlines or corporate jets,
particularly since a supersonic model for a corporate jet is
reportedly under development in France.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways said it had been told early Tuesday by Britain's
Air Accidents Investigation Branch that both it and its French
counterpart, the Bureau of Accident Investigations, would recommend
on Wednesday that Concorde's certificate of airworthiness be
suspended. When the word came, said Eddington, the British Airways
chief executive, a British Airways Concorde flight, BA 001, was
about to depart for New York on schedule, at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-seat, pencil-thin airliner had begun to taxi after
pushing off from the stand at London's Heathrow Airport with just
37 people on board, a British Airways spokeswoman said. The plane
was ordered back to the terminal and the flight canceled, along
with the return flight scheduled for Tuesday night from New York.
The passengers were transferred to subsonic flights.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Eddington said that British Airways decided
immediately to suspend its Concorde flights. ``We immediately
withdrew our supersonic fleet from service this morning, canceling
the Concorde service BA001,'' he said. In a television interview
later, he said he did not know what was behind the decision by the
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Eddington insisted that after the Air France accident, British
Airways carried out ``an extensive series of checks on the
aircraft's air frame, engines, tires and wheels, hydraulics and
other sustem.'' And, he said, Britain's Civil Aviation authority _
the industry regulator _ had been ``in complete agreement with our
decision to resume Concorde's services shortly after the Air France
crash.''
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Aviation Authority said French and British
investigators would give a full explanation of their action on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday's official silence about the cause of the suspension
infuriated some people living near the Concorde's flight-path at
London's Heathrow Airport. ``The Civil Aviation authority must tell
us, particularly those living near the airport, what has happened
to bring about this reversal of policy,'' said David Wilshire, an
opposition legislator representing the area around Heathrow. ``They
cannot hide behind this simple statement that they have new
information.''
</P>
<P>
   While investigators' attention has centered on the tire blow-out
in the Air France crash, the Concorde's safety record has come
under close scrutiny in the past few weeks. New Scientist magazine
said recently that it had details of a study of Concorde's engines,
commissioned by British Airways two years ago, identifying 55
``significant risks.'' British Airways said, however, that the
Civil Aviation Authority had seen no need for improvement in the
airplane's safety precautions because of the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
