<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS STAGE PLUGGED-IN CONVENTION
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ An Internet-linked computer for each delegation, a
video chat room on the podium, a digital still photo gallery, and a
battery of swiveling video cameras remotely controlled by online
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say these and other touches make this the most
cyberspace-friendly political convention ever held.
</P>
<P>
   When the delegates voted Tuesday to adopt the party platform,
they dispensed with the traditional phone call between the podium
and the state chairpersons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, each delegation site comes equipped with a kiosk that
holds a password-protected Apple iMac unit. The computers run a
$500,000 software package donated by Election.com.
</P>
<P>
   The voting results _ no surprises here _ appeared in real time
on both the Election.com and dems2000.com Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fully committed to this system,'' said convention
spokesman Peter Ragone, predicting that online voting will
``revolutionize'' U.S. elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also sought to one-up the Republicans by offering
online chats with convention speakers as they came off the podium.
These interviews evoked the era when wire service reporters worked
directly on the podium _ except that these online reporters are
Democratic Party employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first gig was with Karenna Schiff Gore,'' said Travis
Berry, who sits toward the back of the dais in a black canvas
director's chair, tapping away with one hand on a laptop while
holding a microphone in the other. ``The only time we halt these
interactive sessions is when he have a really major speaker, like
President Clinton or the first lady,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's laptop indicated hat dozens of questions and comments
had been ``cleared'' by the time the Clintons spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his live streaming video event failed to pass
muster with the ``Energizing the Electronic Electorate'' project of
the Annenberg Public Policy Center at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats didn't deliver,'' said Chris Hunter, an analyst
for the project's NetElection.org Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter claimed that podium chat users who posted questions were
greeted with automated responses. ``This is yet another example,''
he added, ``of the failure of both parties to successfully and
meaning
</P>
</TEXT>
