<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GORE-0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MEETS GORE AND SYMBOLICALLY PASSES THE TORCH
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Mich. _ There was no torch, or even a baton _ just a
handshake and a wave goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   With that, President Clinton walked off a stage erected in the
historic town square here, leaving Vice President Gore and his
wife, Tipper, standing alone and waving to the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The symbolic parting Tuesday, complete with confetti and
streamers, was intended to convey an important message as Gore
heads to Los Angeles to accept the Democratic presidential
nomination: Clinton's political moment was past and Gore's was set
to begin.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton delivered his farewell address to Democrats
at their convention, rousing delegates with the achievements of his
administration and heaping praise on Gore, his loyal vice president
of eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it helped him,'' Clinton said Tuesday en route to
Monroe to stand on stage with Gore. ``We'll see. Maybe it did. I
don't know. But the main thing was I just wanted to thank the
people and say what I believed....I'll never forget this as long as
I live.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, John Podesta, Clinton's chief of staff, said the
president was anxious ``to lay back a little bit and watch Al lay
out his plans for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Podesta said Clinton would continue to raise money for the
Democrats and speak to various constituencies of the Democratic
Party. ``He will do whatever the Gore-Lieberman team thinks will be
helpful, but it's their call,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between the two Democrats was short on rhetorical
flourish and long on political symbolism. Michigan was a decisive
state for the Clinton-Gore ticket when they defeated President Bush
in 1992 during an economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   The two men campaigned frequently in Michigan on the theme of
the economy, successfully portraying Bush as out of touch with the
economic hard times.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gore is campaigning hard on the economy's rebound, trying
to persuade voters that he is best able to lead continued economic
expansion in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   In his brief remarks Tuesday, Clinton noted that unemployment in
Monroe County dropped from 8.8 percent in 1993 to 2.2 percent this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the record is clear,'' Clinton declared. ``This
country is better off than it was eight years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to associate Gore with the nation's prosperity,
telling the crowd that ``every good thing that has happened, that
came out of our administration in the last eight years, Al Gore was
at the heart of.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his own remarks immediately following Clinton's, Gore
appeared reluctant to accept the credit. He referred several times
to the economic policies of the administration as the ``Clinton
program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Bill Clinton worked hard to get this economy
right,'' Gore said. ``And I'm pledging to you here today, I am not
going to let the other side wreck it and take it away from us.
We're going to keep the prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, a Bush spokeswoman, accused Clinton and Gore of
doing little for education and reforming Social Security, calling
their record a ``squandered opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the passing of the baton will work to close the
leadership problem for Al Gore,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of speaking to mostly smaller crowds, Tuesday's
event attracted about 6,000 people to Monroe's town square.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Heidtman, a fifth grade school teacher, drove 140 miles
from her home in Bay Side, Mich., just to catch a glimpse of
Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for Clinton to fade away, go with Hillary to New
York and let Gore be presidential,'' said Heidtman, who waited
three hours for the men to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the crowd was on hand to cheer Gore. Glenn
Haddix said he was moved by the historical moment and wanted his
two boys to see the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Haddix, a member of the National Rifle Association, said he
does not intend to vote for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel Mr. Bush is going to be a little more friendly to us
law abiding gun owners,'' Haddix said.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging Michigan's improved economy, several people
in Tuesday's crowd said the economy alone was not enough for them
to automatically swear allegiance to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of other issues,'' said Dawn Van Slamgrouck
(cq), a special education teacher. ``I'm still listening. I just
want to hear what we has to say and I don't want any lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett can be e-mailed at: kenf(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
