<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-$ADV27-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TOURISTS AT THE GATE, AUSTRO-HUNGARIAN PANNONIA STILL
MAGICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Details on transportation, accommodations, meals and seasonal
attractions at end) 
 By MICHAEL RATCLIFFE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty miles southeast of Vienna, vineyards sweep down from a
line of low, wooded hills to a shallow lake, and Eastern Europe
begins. Austria's present-day frontiers with Hungary and Slovakia
may be a few miles farther on, but the shift from central, Alpine
Europe is sudden, dramatic and unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   This magical landscape is undersung. The reed beds and wetlands
of the Neusiedler See stretch to a skyline that vanishes in the
haze. Cherries, walnuts and almonds flourish; storks nest on the
rooftops; spoonbills and great white egrets gather to breed. The
wines are delicious. You sleep well under wide skies.
</P>
<P>
   The tranquillity is deceptive. The dangers and ironies of
history abound. Until a referendum in 1921, this was not part of
Austria at all, but western Hungary. Citizens of Sopron, handsome
capital of the region, voted to remain in Hungary, but the village
of Raiding, birthplace of Franz Liszt, Hungary's most famous
composer, became Austrian. The Austrians called their new province
Burgenland: to the Romans it was part of Pannonia. It has always
been border country, and until 1700 was regularly raided and
occupied by Ottoman Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, when the Hungarians cut the barbed wire near
Moerbisch to let East Germans into the West, they did so on a site
sacred to Mithras, the Roman god of light who battled against
darkness. Where the Romans have been, their spirit never quite goes
away, and this is where the end of Communist Europe began.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, I wanted to see if Pannonia retained any common
identity, a quest that went out of the window as soon as I
discovered how enormous the region had been. Instead, my friend
Howard and I devised a more local, ragged oblong route of our own _
out of, and back to, the Vienna airport. Four nights near the
Neusiedler See in Austria were followed by four in Hungary, and a
final one back in Austria. We took our time, and drove less than
500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious Neusiedler See _ Lake Ferto to Hungarians _ is
roughly 18 miles long and 4 miles wide. It is the only steppe lake
in Western Europe, rarely more than 7 feet deep, and fed by
underground streams. It has been known to evaporate completely. On
the western shore, we stayed at Kloster am Spitz in Purbach,
halfway between the village and the hills. This is like a French
vineyard-restaurant with rooms _ but properly Austrian, and
seasonal in its cooking. No fewer than six dishes on one menu
honored the high summer rites of the Eierschwammerl, the delicious
wild mushroom of Central Europe, a cross between porcini and
chanterelles. The Eierschwammerl came terrined, roasted, souped,
sauced for pork medallions, sauced for beef, and as a vegetarian
goulash with tiny marjoram dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   With the scents of thyme and sage on the air, and crimson
oleanders in tubs, Purbach begins to feel Mediterranean. Each
evening we walked down the hill after dinner, with planes winking
in to land far above and fireflies round our feet. Ahead, a great
silence settled over the lake.
</P>
<P>
   We were also traveling in the steps of two Pannonian prodigies
who changed the course of Western music: Josef Haydn, last and
greatest of composers to write most of his music as the contracted
servant of one patron; and Franz Liszt, first modern superstar,
forever on the road. There are two delightful small Haydn houses in
Austria, at Rohrau and Eisenstadt, while fabled Eszterhaza, Prince
Nicholas Esterhazy's ``little Versailles,'' where Haydn transformed
the classical symphony and invented the string quartet, still
stands, on the Hungarian side. For 40 years, the Iron Curtain
severed the roads of duty taken by Haydn between the palaces of his
master, and the link between Raiding and Sopron, where Adam Liszt
presented his son in public for the first time. The phenomenal boy
was 9, the acclaim tumultuous.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to lose the Esterhazys for long in this corner of
Europe; they were its little kings. Managing to be both Hungarian
patriots and loyal to the Hapsburgs, they were twice offered the
crown of Hungary by enemies of Austria, and twice turned it down.
Eisenstadt, miniature capital of the kingdom and a 30 minutes drive
from Purbach, sits sweetly among vineyards in a bowl of wooded
hills. The main street of this small town has been anesthetized by
prosperity _ the retail shops could be anywhere _ but just beyond
it are a prince's palace, a composer's home, a merchant's
synagogue, two Jewish cemeteries and the plump little Baroque
church, which shook joyfully through the 1790s with the faith and
passion of new Haydn Masses.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three centuries, the Esterhazys protected ``their''
Jews in seven specific ghetto communities, of which this was one,
safely within view of their own sumptuous palace, inspired by the
Villa Farnese in Rome. Hidden from the street on the first floor of
the merchant Samson Wertheimer's house, an early 18th-century
synagogue survived both Kristallnacht and the community's
destruction, becoming an intimate and tender Jewish museum _
Austria's first _ in 1978. After visiting the synagogue, we went up
the road to its Christian contemporary, the delectably compact
Bergkirche, where Haydn is buried. Attached to the church is the
Baroque Kalvarienberg, whose architect built a staircase past
life-size Stations of the Cross inside a kind of honeycombed
teapot. When you emerge on the lid, or roof, you are met by white
limestone angels and look over folds of russet tiling to glorious
countryside beyond. Despite the grim tableaus within, this is one
of my favorite buildings anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The eastern and southern shores of the Neusiedler See are
largely now part of an Austro-Hungarian national park, and most of
the lakeshore is inaccessible by car. You can walk, bike or ride on
causeways through the reeds to the water's edge. We stayed at the
faintly preposterous Villa Vita and Holiday Resort Pannonia near
Pamhagen, where every building in the compound was a weirdly
perfect imitation of some Pannonian archetype outside.
</P>
<P>
   Villa Vita is only a 15-minute bike ride from a spectacular bird
reserve. Surrounded by wind-swept, silvery grassland, with old
water pumps and observation shelters dotted round the rim, the
Lange Lacke is a large pond, where I saw one of the most beautiful
birds I have ever seen. Over 3 feet tall, dazzling white, with a
lemon yellow beak and long, slim neck, the great egret posed
against a stand of reeds like a figure on a folding screen.
</P>
<P>
   Nearer the Hungarian border is a modest Hapsburg palace by the
great architect of the Belvedere in Vienna, Lucas von Hildebrandt.
Schloss Halbturn stands poised between two worlds: at the top of
the vineyard by the gates you look west and see the faint blue line
of the Alps; in the park below the house is a delightful
neo-Classical church that would be at home in Tolstoy's ``War and
Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning we were there, swallows and martins were diving low
over the vines, and cherries had stained the road to the border a
disturbingly dark red.
</P>
<P>
   On the Hungarian side, we could see a flag, an abandoned shed, a
pole-barrier collapsed on the ground; in Austria, a wheat field
grown to the line was surveyed by a saint on a stone pillar and
three soldiers, armed. This pattern was repeated everywhere: the
Austrians were still watching, the Hungarians were not. It would
have been easy to walk out of the European Union, harder to get
back in.
</P>
<P>
   The transition between the two countries is a real one. For all
its beautiful brochures, Hungarian tourism is only reluctantly
geared to its principal client, the German-speaking market.
Hungarians do not enjoy speaking German, and are often unwilling to
hazard their English. So it is not as easy to move around as it is
in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I retain great affection for Sopron (pronounced
SHOP-ron), a walkable and remarkably well-preserved city of 60,000
people where the sidewalks gleam in the rain like Venice, and the
shop with the little elephant statue on the corner still sells
bottled peas. On the second evening, after a long storm, it became
dry enough to explore the layered, ancient structures behind
Sopron's little courts and doorways. These include the intact
shells of two medieval synagogues, one of them identified only in
the 1950s. One of Europe's sleeping beauties, Sopron is also the
best base for visiting Eszterhaza, the apricot-colored palace that
brought cutting-edge music to a marsh at the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   This was my fourth visit to Eszterhaza in 17 years. It exerts a
deep spell, yet its neglect by Hungarian governments before and
after 1989 is a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   True, they have fixed the wiring, the water supply and the roof;
there are concerts in Haydn's frescoed music room, and a festival
every July. But the air of a management that does not know what it
is dealing with, and would rather not deal with it at all, remains
overwhelming. The gardens are shabby, the park overgrown. There is
no imagination and no love.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Rococo palace still take the guided trudge round
two dozen or so underfurnished rooms in felt slippers that are
falling apart. Minimal information (``On the Baroque table are a
clock and two candlesticks from France'') is still delivered with
an indifference bordering on revulsion. No one is encouraged to
enjoy the Haydn exhibition, which, new in 1982, has now faded to
lifeless sepia; as you go around, you don't even hear any music.
And yet, I return because I love the music of Haydn, who made a
revolution here, and because, even with mass tourism now virtually
at the gates, the elegiac spell survives.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of love and imagination a few miles down
the road in the whitewashed manor house of Nagycenk.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference!
</P>
<P>
   This was the home of Count Szechenyi, Hungarian radical patriot
and conservative rival of Kossuth, who built the Chain Bridge
between Buda and Pest, transformed the waterways of Hungary, and
went mad after the failed revolution of 1848. The rooms are full of
interest, and the story is movingly told on English-language
headphones.
</P>
<P>
   Driving deeper into Hungary, we reached Sarvar, halfway between
Sopron and Lake Balaton, where we stayed in a spa hotel _ the best
for miles around _ almost entirely occupied by gentle seniors of
Austria, Germany and Switzerland who consumed fiercely
prescriptive, calorie-counted meals.
</P>
<P>
   Nearer Balaton, at the ruined fortress of Sumeg around which
battles between Christianity and Islam swirled for half a
millennium, history is now privatized, replayed as kitsch, and
served by a new village of tawdry shops and holiday homes.
</P>
<P>
   The real village of Sumeg is half a mile round the corner, and
miraculously intact. The bishop's palace and garden, combining
Turkish wooden balconies and a Chekhovian terrace with the sassy
ease of Hungarian baroque, is being brought back to life.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Austria, Schlaining was the first of four massive former
Hungarian fortresses that we saw in a fizzy last 24 hours.
Bernstein, home of the aviator and Arabist Count Almasy (the hero
of ``The English Patient'') and now partly a hotel, was the most
patrician of the four, overgrown but cherished, with the family
still around. We stayed in a third, Lockenhaus, a few miles away,
where we slept in a Gothic bedroom with the wind literally moaning
under the door.
</P>
<P>
   A glorious new road, the S31, sped us north 20 miles across the
hills of central Burgenland on our last morning. The fourth and
last fortress was Forchtenstein, where the Esterhazys display
priceless family treasures and memorabilia that ring with the
Hapsburg, Hungarian and Ottoman histories of this borderland: a
Turkish officer's tent, paper-thin ivory vessels, a heron's feather
from a magnate's hat. Plus walls full of male Esterhazys portrayed
with massive gun dogs swooning loyally at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Before this, we had stopped in Raiding at the cottage,
embellished by scarlet geraniums, roses and vines, where Liszt was
born. White chairs were grouped round a little stage in the garden,
for a recital that evening. We longed to stay. The house was given
to Austria by the Esterhazys on Liszt's birthday in 1971. It has
only two rooms, but they were filled _ to bursting _with great
recorded performances of his music.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
