<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-$ADV27     08-15 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-$ADV27-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: his music. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   We rented an Opel Astra automatic from Avis at the Vienna
airport, total cost $763 for 10 days. There are several taxes
included, among them an airport surcharge of $61, and it probably
would be cheaper to arrange a rental in the United States. Prices
are calculated with a dollar valued at 15.45 Austrian schillings or
293 Hungarian forints.
ACCOMMODATIONS
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: On the Neusiedler See, we stayed at the family-run
Kloster am Spitz in Purbach, telephone (43-2683) 5519, fax
(43-2683) 5519 20, for the excellent food; our room was simple,
spacious and quiet with private bathroom and shower. Doubles:
$27.75 a person, with full breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vila Vita near Pamhagen, (43-2175) 21800, fax (43-2175)
2180 444, www.vilavitahotels.com, a basic, modern double room is
$64 a person with breakfast, and a range of sports and leisure
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   A comfortable Gothic bedroom with genuine moaning wind at
Lockenhaus Castle, Gunserstrasse 5, Lockenhaus, cost $70 for two,
breakfast included. The rooms have private bath, phone and cable
TV; (43-2616) 23 94, fax (43-2616) 27 66.
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY: In Sopron, we were disappointed by the Palatinus. Best
Western's Pannonia Med on Varkerulet 75 looked like a good bet,
although we didn't stay there. A double with private bath is
$55.40; (36-99) 312180 or 312181, fax (36-99) 340 766.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 miles out of town, I liked the Hotel Kastely, Nagycenk,
where we had lunch. In this comfortable wing of the Szechenyi
family mansion, a double room with bath is $44.60 a person;
telephone and fax (36 99) 360-061.
</P>
<P>
   In Sarvar, the Danubius Thermal Hotel, (36-95) 323 999, fax
(36-95) 320 406, on the Web
www.danubiusgroup.com/danubius/sarvar.html, is '80s-modern, with
rooms in back overlooking an arboretum. Service is fairly efficient
but impersonal. Our double room was $102 including breakfast for
two, thermal baths and spa facilities. Treatments are extra.
RESTAURANTS
</P>
<P>
   Food is still seasonal and celebratory in Austria. May and June
is Spargelzeit (asparagus time), June the season for
Eierschwammerl.
</P>
<P>
   In Purbach we also dined at the posh Nicholauszeche, Bodenzeile
3, in the village, part of the Romantik chain. It was good, and
cost only about $44 a person; (43-2683) 5514.
</P>
<P>
   Our last _ and excellent _ lunch was at Johann Reisner in
Forchtenstein, Hauptstrasse 141, (43-2626) 63 139, where I took the
$15.85 menu, and had Eierschwammerl soup, rabbit and a fantastic
coffee-flavored pot de creme with sour cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Our best meals in Hungary were at the Hotel Kastely, Nagycenk,
and the HBH restaurant in Sarvar. At the hotel, I went Hungarian
with bean soup and veal paprika, followed by cherry, cottage
cheese, raisin and poppy-seed strudel ($4.90). The HBH is the
restaurant of a revived private brewery with historic Bavarian
links, and, as the singer swung into ``Blueberry Hill'' while we
tucked into inexpensive, tasty platefuls of tender, lean meat and
vegetables, we might never have left Munich.
</P>
<P>
   MAPS
</P>
<P>
   Map aficionados like me will be tempted by the Austrian
government's meticulous 1:50,000 series, which covers the
Neusiedler See in four sheets, virtually recording every path,
reedbed and ditch. You need No. 78 for Rust and Neusiedl, 108 for
Deutschkreutz (including Sopron) and 109 for Pamhagen. They cost $2
to $5 each in bookstores.
MORE INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   For information on the palaces and fortresses, contact the
Austrian National Tourist Office, (212) 944-6880, www.anto.com, and
the Hungarian National Tourist Office, (212) 355-0240,
www.gotohungary.com.
</P>
<P>
   Neusiedler See-Seewinkel National Park Center, Hauswiese,
Illmitz; (43-2175) 3442, fax (43-2175) 34424.
</P>
<P>
   Via Imperialis, based in Vienna, represents major palaces,
castles and abbeys in Austria some of which take paying guests;
(43-1) 581 5318, fax (43-1) 581 5350; on the Web at
www.viaimperialis.at.
</P>
<P>
   The Haydn Festival at Eszterhaza is in July; (36-1) 326 6152.
The Haydn Festival at the Esterhazy Palace in Eisenstadt is Sept. 7
to Sept. 17 this year; (43-2682) 61866, fax (43-2682) 61805.
</P>
</TEXT>
