   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with DEM-PROTESTS-NYT; story on FOLD (skedline
above).
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-CONCORDE (London) _ British Airways grounded its entire
fleet of Concorde supersonic airliners on Tuesday after French and
British investigators said they would urge the withdrawal of the
airplane's airworthiness certification following last month's fatal
Air France Concorde crash near Paris. It would be the first time in
more than 20 years that an airworthiness certificate for a
commercial airliner had been revoked by any country. The
investigators said they would not spell out their reasoning until
Wednesday, and so it was unclear what steps would have to be taken
to reverse the recommendation. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KIPP-EDUC (Undated) _ Successful schools for the poor have long
been written off as desert flowers dependent on charismatic leaders
or particular ideology. But Kipp Academy, a pair of extremely
successful middle schools in poor areas of Harlem and Houston, is
something different. Started by two Ivy League idealists and
honored by groups on both the left and right, Kipp is seen as a
model for replication. And now the owners of The Gap have donated
$15 million to create Kipp clones around the country. The process
is starting with a unprecedented year-long training period for the
principals. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 8 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
