<P>
   PHONE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ A federal appeals court on Tuesday
struck down part of a government order that had broadly expanded
the ability of law-enforcement agents to monitor cell phone
conversations of criminal suspects. The decision was considered a
partial victory by privacy groups that had challenged the order and
was a clear setback for law enforcement agencies, which must now
consider revising the rules for electronic surveillance of wireless
communications. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
