<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OKAMATO-ART-MUSEUM-$A     08-15 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKAMATO-ART-MUSEUM-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREATHING LIFE, POSTHUMOUSLY, INTO JAPAN'S ART SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release Sunday, August 20)  
 By EDWARD M. GOMEZ  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ On the Japanese art scene, as in real estate, finance
and employment, the baburu (economic bubble) burst long ago. Today,
the friends and contacts a Western visitor encounters here are sure
to recollect, with incredulity and undisguised embarrassment, the
heady days of the 1980s, when Japanese corporations spent tens of
millions of dollars on Impressionist paintings at overseas
auctions, and when new museums, public and private, seemed to pop
up every month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the '90s, Japan's overheated real estate market
collapsed, which in turn affected other sectors of the economy. Art
sales slumped. Some commercial galleries closed. Companies that had
bought artworks primarily as investments but had rarely, or never,
displayed them saw their values plummet. (It did not help that many
of those works were lesser Marie Laurencins or Maurice Utrillos of
the old School of Paris calendar-art variety.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, against a backdrop of lingering art-world
doldrums, the new, city-financed Taro Okamoto Museum opened late
last year in Kawasaki, not far to the southwest of central Tokyo.
Housed in a typically monumental new building in a wooded public
park, it honors one of Japan's most influential modern artists. And
with some 100,000 visitors already, it has quickly become a hit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Okamoto, who died just shy of his 85th birthday in 1996, was
also a photographer, an ethnographer and a prolific author. In his
later years, he became known as an eccentric television personality
who turned up in commercials declaring, ``Art is explosion!'' In
Japan, he was also one of the few household names in art of his
generation. Okamoto was born in Kawasaki in 1911. His father,
Ippei, was a well-known cartoonist for Asahi Shimbun, a leading
national newspaper. His mother, Kanoko, was a poet and novelist
known for artistic and personal style. Taro was the Okamotos' only
child; in 1929, the family traveled to Europe, where Ippei had been
sent on an assignment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before they left Japan, Taro had begun studying at the Tokyo
School of Fine Arts. He resumed his studies in Paris, where he
learned to speak French and came of age as a serious young artist.
Okamoto lived there for 12 years, during which he befriended
Alberto Giacometti and Jean Arp, took part in the
Abstraction-Creation group and later showed his work with the
surrealists. In Abstraction-Creation's 1934 almanac, Okamoto held
his own in a climate of passionate polemics and manifestoes about
art, offering bons mots like: ``We must create form that is not
form and color that is not color.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Okamoto was moved by the folk and tribal arts on view
at the Trocadero Museum of Ethnography (which later became the
Museum of Man). He absorbed the ideas of the sociologist and
anthropologist Marcel Mauss (1872-1950), who examined the role of
gift giving and magic in society and propounded a theory of
``totality''; that is, of examining the actions of a total human
existence rather than a fragmented one. Okamoto also became
associated with Georges Bataille's College of Sociology.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During Okamoto's long Paris sojourn, his paintings featured
abstract, biomorphic forms set against empty backgrounds with a
surrealist air. Forced to head back to Japan in 1940 as the war in
Europe spread, Okamoto was stationed in China with the Japanese
army for five years. Returning home, to the politically charged
atmosphere of American-occupied Japan, Okamoto created some of his
most memorable images.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These included the large oil paintings ``Heavy Industry'' (1949)
and ``Law of the Jungle'' (1950). Produced at a time of social
unrest, when Japanese railway workers were being laid off, ``Heavy
Industry'' was an indictment of reckless capitalism. In ``Law of
the Jungle,'' a huge, mysterious animal with a zipper mouth lunges
forward menacingly as smaller creatures scurry out of its way, and
a trio of hear-no-evil, see-no-evil, speak-no-evil monkeys huddles
in a corner. Okamoto called the picture's central monster a symbol
of fascism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what he had learned in Europe and experienced back in
Japan, Okamoto developed the idea of `polarism' that he tried to
express in his art,'' said Keinosuke Murata, the director of the
Taro Okamoto Museum. Murato spoke recently in his office, which is
situated at the tapered end of a wing of an oddly laid-out building
that he refers to with amusement as ``a fortress.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He explained that polarism allowed Okamoto to address both
abstract and surrealist values at the same time within a single
work. It offered him a way to grapple simultaneously with
avant-garde art values and the complicated social reality he saw
emerging amid the physical destruction and spiritual void of
postwar Japan. Okamoto, who once asserted that ``content has
priority over form,'' recalled in 1959 that he had been interested
in how his art ``would have an effect on society, not only as
something aesthetic, but also as a cry or movement in everyday
life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese art critic Ichiro Hariu has described Okamoto's
polarism as ``a philosophy that called for venturing into the
depths of contradictions without trying to bring them together with
easy solutions or compromises.'' It lay at the heart of Okamoto's
art-making and his outlook on life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For younger Japanese artists like Ushio Shinohara, who was born
in 1932, Okamoto's attitude was especially inspiring. Shinohara
helped found the Neo Dada Organizers, a short-lived
anti-establishment group, in 1960 and has been based in New York
since 1969. Hiswork has evolved from found-object, junk-assemblage
pieces to exuberant, crosscultural paintings in a rollicking
pop-art mode. ``Okamoto's energy was like Picasso's,'' Shinohara
said. ``It was big and infectious, and it liberated us.''
</P>
<P>
   Shinohara recently showed a mural-size painting in an ``Homage
to Taro Okamoto'' exhibition at the Kawasaki museum. A riot of
writhing, cartoonish figures, it was entitled ``Taro Okamoto
Working Outdoors, From Arizona Sunrise to Bermuda Sunset.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Okamoto published books on traditional and modern art. He did
extensive research on the pottery of the Jomon era, dating back
more than two millenniums; experts regard the era as one of the
most important sources of Japan's indigenous culture. Okamoto
admired hand-shaped Jomon pots for the crude beauty of their
ropelike designs, seeing in them the confrontation of aesthetic
values that so intrigued him. He also traveled south to Okinawa,
photographing folk festivals, ceramics and local costumes along the
way. Carp-shaped banners fluttering above working-class
neighborhoods, a baby asleep in a handmade basket, a shaman
absorbed in her candlelit incantations: his pictures make a record
of Japanese folk life as vivid as any of Japan's black-and-white
movie classics of the postwar period. The Okamoto museum now holds
thousands of these photographs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, Okamoto began making sculpture, and it is in
his vast outpouring of three-dimensional works that his main themes
and interests probably assumed their most engaging forms. Evoking
the flicker of a sorcerer's ceremonial flame, tribal totem poles
and the streamlining principles of classic modernism, he created
the imposing ``Tower of the Sun'' for the Expo '70 world's fair in
Osaka. He also made bronze temple bells, lighting fixtures,
molded-plastic sofas and cocktail glasses etched with masklike face
designs. (Okamoto served as artistic director of Expo '70. An
exhibition focusing on his ``Tower of the Sun'' and related designs
for the fair will be on view at the Kawasaki museum from Oct. 28
through Jan. 28, 2001.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Life-affirming bright red, a symbol of good fortune in much of
East Asia, was Okamoto's favorite color. The entrance to the
permanent collection of his work in Kawasaki is a futuristic
tunnel-corridor painted hot red and bathed in red light. Multilevel
galleries display paintings, drawings and objects of various sizes
and materials; each room is part stage set, part design showroom,
where spindly tentacles and bulbous growths sprout from Okamoto's
nature-inspired sculptures. Visitors are even encouraged to sit on
some of the artist's flower- or hand-shaped chairs. Murata, a
former senior administrator at the National Museum of Art in Osaka,
said: ``Until recently, most Japanese museums have not tried to be
aesthetic experiences in themselves. But this one definitely
has.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
