<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-LIEBERMAN16-COX     08-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LIEBERMAN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIEBERMAN ACTS TO REASSURE BLACK DEMOCRATS
 &HT;    By MARK SHERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman told black Democratic
activists Tuesday in Los Angeles that he supports affirmative
action, trying to erase perceptions that he is too conservative for
a key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me talk about affirmative action because questions have
been raised,'' the Democratic vice presidential candidate told
several hundred black delegates to the Democratic National
Convention. ``I want to talk very specifically about it. I have
supported affirmative action. I do support affirmative action. And
I will support affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Grumbling among Democrats had increased in recent days as
Lieberman's past statements questioning the preference program for
minorities and his support for using public money to pay for
private schooling got a fuller public airing.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to say whether his remarks succeeded in generally
reassuring concerned African-Americans. But Rep. Maxine Waters,
D-Calif., who had pointedly raised questions about Lieberman's
selection, said she was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman ``has said enough, he has done enough and he has
demonstrated his willingness to deal with issues of concern to the
black community,'' Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   The level of enthusiasm among African-Americans is of more than
passing importance to Vice President Al Gore and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   There is little worry that black voters will turn to the
Republicans, but substantial concern that more African-Americans
may decide to sit this one out.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters are very supportive of Democrats, and a decrease in
black support for Gore and Lieberman could prove decisive in states
such as Georgia, where Democratic candidates traditionally count on
overwhelming support from blacks to overcome a Republican edge
among white voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's choice of Lieberman has reinforced a view of the vice
president among some Democrats that he is not liberal enough or
committed enough to social justice issues.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours after Lieberman was chosen as the Democratic vice
presidential nominee last week, an NAACP official in Dallas
referred to him as a ``Jew person'' whose selection should raise
suspicions among African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP and a host of African-Americans were quick to pounce
on the words of Lee Alcorn, the president of the organization's
Dallas chapter, as inappropriate and offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But the subject had been broached nonetheless, and black and
Jewish leaders worried about a new eruption of tension between
their groups.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been no other ethnically tinged comments, but
neither has there been universal acclaim among African-Americans
for Gore's decision to make Lieberman his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Lieberman's Orthodox Judaism so much as his politics
that could cause trouble for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any angst about Lieberman, it will be because he
represents the right wing of the Democratic party,'' said Ronald
Walters, a political science professor at the University of
Maryland. ``This is the second ticket of DLC origin, and it
confirms the rightward movement of Democratic party.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of the situation is that the first ticket to come
out of the DLC, the centrist Democratic Leadership Council, was the
pairing of Clinton and Gore. Clinton has been immensely popular
among black Americans, perhaps never more so than during his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   That point was not lost on Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., and the
leaders of the NAACP, who praised the Connecticut senator.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman made meeting with black delegates his first order of
business after arriving in Los Angeles Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He had voiced support California's Proposition 209, a 1998
ballot initiative to ban state-funded affirmative action programs.
He has spoken out against affirmative action, although his staff
has recently sought to clarify his position as merely opposed to
quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said Tuesday he never campaigned for the ballot
measure, although he had been asked to do so. He added that he made
crucial votes in favor of affirmative action in 1995 and 1998 in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator's stands on a number of social issues
was threatening to disrupt the Democrats' celebration of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Waters, Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., also has
raised questions and his father, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who warmly
praised Lieberman's selection last week, offered a more measured
assessment of the Gore-Lieberman team Monday when he said, ``If it
means we have to hold our noses and take castor oil, do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, most black voters will side with the Democrats,
predicted Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP. Bond made the point
that elections are choices, and ``the choice isn't between the
perfect and the terrible, but between really good and awful. That's
an easy choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was striking that President Clinton reminded his
convention audience Monday night that Lieberman, then a college
student, had journeyed south in 1964 to register blacks to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman went to Mississippi, where that same year members of
the Ku Klux Klan brutally murdered Andrew Goodman, Michael
Schwerner and James Cheney, two northern Jews and a southern
African-American, for their work on behalf of civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bond noted that Lieberman received a 100 percent rating from the
NAACP last year. And Lewis said he went at Lieberman's invitation
to the Connecticut Democratic convention last month at which
Lieberman was nominated for a third time as the Democratic Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the issues of values, hard work, dignity of work, he tends
to touch a responsive chord within the African-American
community,'' Lewis said. ``He's not a perfect man, but it's a good
match and the African-American community is going to go all out.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bositis, who studies voting trends among African-Americans
for a Washington, DC think tank, said Lieberman's past statements
will not be damaging because as vice president, he will be forced
to follow the president's wishes. ``What Joe Lieberman's position
is, is pretty irrelevant,'' Bositis said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman's e-mail address is msherman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
