<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-OLDER-DANCERS-$A     08-15 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OLDER-DANCERS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE AGE 40 DOESN'T MEAN THE END OF EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada, the Netherlands)   (For release Sunday, August 20)   By HARRIS GREEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, Americans have become more accepting of older
dancers. Whether this attitude is a result of aging baby-boomers or
has been imposed by political correctness, it is expanding the
concept of dancing. The United States now has several organizations
that present performances by older dancers, Dancers Over 40 _ the
traditional retirement age _ and the 40Up Project among them, or
mingle the generations onstage, as does Liz Lerman's Dance
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Canadian documentary ``Can't Stop Now,'' which Channel
13 will broadcast on ``Great Performances'' on Wednesday night at
8:30, reports on how the Netherlands Dance Theater has extended the
careers of dancers by creating NDT3, a company that commissions
works specifically for those over 40. No other troupe offers such
opportunities. Of course, classical dancers gifted in mime have
continued onstage for decades as Drosselmeyer or Dr. Coppelius or
Giselle's mother, but most companies have not sought new roles for
them to perform.
</P>
<P>
   NDT3 was spun off in 1991 by the main company's artistic
director, Jiri Kylian (now its principal choreographer), at the
urging of his wife, the dancer Sabine Kupferberg, and the veteran
NDT member Gerard Lemaitre, the oldest of the troupe at 62. (NDT2
is an experimental company for dancers from 17 to 22.) Despite its
size _ it has never consisted of more than a handful of dancers _
and considerable turnover, NDT3 has drawn worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
   The writer and director Eileen Thalenberg has built ``Can't Stop
Now'' around the arrival in The Hague of Karen Kain, a former
principal of the National Ballet of Canada, to replace Martine van
Hamel, a ballerina from American Ballet Theater who had moved on to
NDT3. The sequence in which Kain learns Kylian's snaky pas de deux
``No Sleep Till Dawn of Day,'' set to a Solomon Islands lullaby, is
a triumph for all concerned, including the film editor, Michele
Hozer. (The cameraman, Neville Ottey, however, sometimes cuts off
feet later in the film.)
</P>
<P>
   Although she dwells on Kain's unease about this transition,
Thalenberg avoids any chauvinistic, local-girl-makes-good approach
by giving equal time to van Hamel's thoughts about turning 50.
``Dancing with NDT3 has given me lightness in a way,'' van Hamel
says. ``I can't, still can't, imagine really having a life without
dancing.'' Such expressions of loss by NDT3 members are a constant
throughout this moving film.
</P>
<P>
   What also comes across is how often the choreographers fall back
on gimmickry, hyperactivity and calculated cuteness, and how they
talk better dances than they deliver. Patrick Delcroix, for
example, deplores the practice of giving older dancers something
``dramatic'' just so they can move slowly; he wants ``to do
something happy and have some fun.'' Delcroix may have had a ball
creating ``Grain de Folie,'' but for anyone familiar with the heady
high jinks of Jerome Robbins (``The Concert,'' say, or the
percussion section of ``Fanfare'') or the balletic romps of Charlie
Chaplin, the mugging, flailing and shimmying he foists on his
dancers seem rather desperate.
</P>
<P>
   In this film, Kylian is particularly articulate, but his works
for NDT3 can be disconcerting. Last summer, when all three
Netherlands Dance Theater companies appeared in the Lincoln Center
Festival, his eclectic recent works suggested that his artistic
goal had changed; instead of matching movement to rarely used
composers like Janacek and Haydn, he was trying to match his fellow
European choreographers in the exploitation of oversize props,
disco-style seizures, cacophonous amplification or intermittent
chaos. It was not surprising that in ``A Way a Lone,'' one of the
first works he made for NDT3, he fell back on the familiar
distraction of having dancers compete with projected images, in
this case of themselves viewed from above. He had no idea, he tells
Thalenberg, how different a dancer would look from that angle.
Given that sensibility, it shouldn't come as a surprise when we see
the men as well as the women in one section of Kylian's
``Arcimboldo'' don misshapen black tutus that look like wind-sprung
umbrellas and slip in and out of these encumbrances to selections
from Bach's noble suites for unaccompanied cello, waggling their
tongues on the trills. NDT3 costumes are generally striking _ watch
for the dancing jellyfish _ but some viewers may sense that using
such outre garb indicates an attempt to bolster a performance the
dancers can't quite give.
</P>
<P>
   Kylian puts Bach to better use when the ``Goldberg Variations''
accompany Kupferberg, Lemaitre and the ever-striking Gary Chryst as
they employ sign language to ``speak'' their own haikulike eulogies
of departed friends _ effective and touching, but also reminiscent
of the way in which some choreographers, notably Bill T. Jones,
rely on something beyond mere movement (like, say, death) for extra
impact.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to use sign language was Kylian's, but he can't claim
the result, for neither the words nor the gestures are his
creation. What this documentary reports most forcefully is that
gifted older dancers with presence and command of gesture can have
extended careers once choreographers meet them on an equally high
level of dedication. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
