<HEADLINE>
CAMBRIDGE TECHNOLOGY, RIVAL START-UP SETTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. has settled a lawsuit over a
former executive's launch of a rival start-up in Florida, company
officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, Semtor Inc. has promised not to hire
any more employees from Cambridge Technology, which has struggled
with recent losses, a slumping stock price, and a flood of
departures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to focus on our business, which is not in the legal
field,'' said Semtor chief executive Harold Gubnitsky, a former
Cambridge Technology vice president who left the company in late
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gubnitsky and Cambridge Technology officials declined to provide
further details of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in January, Semtor has a staff of 85 that includes about
10 employees who once worked for Cambridge Technology. The Fort
Lauderdale firm, also a technology consultant, recently opened
offices in Burlington, Mass., where it plans to employ 30 people by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Cambridge Technology began to strike back at
Gubnitsky and several other former executives. It accused them of
violating nonsolicitation agreements by hiring away valuable
technology employees to feed their own start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   In a testier battle, Cambridge Technology filed suit in April
against its former chief executive, James K. Sims. The suit also
named his new Boston company, Gen3 Partners Inc., and Arthur M.
Toscanini, a former Cambridge Technology chief financial officer
who now works for Sims.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Sims and Toscanini countersued.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side has shown signs of backing down.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Cambridge Technology asked a judge to bar Gen3
Partners from ``raiding on Cambridge employees,'' said Hal Thayer,
a Cambridge Technology spokesman. The judge held a hearing on Aug.
8 but has not ruled on the motion.
</P>
</TEXT>
