<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MESSIAEN-MUSIC-$ADV20     08-15 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MESSIAEN-MUSIC-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIANIST WHO MEETS, AND REFINES, MESSIAEN'S CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 20)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is very much Messiaen's year _ as most years now tend to
be. First, there was the Brooklyn Philharmonic's presentation of
three scenes from ``St. Francois d'Assise,'' followed quickly by
the Lincoln Center Festival's offering of four big Messiaen pieces
in quick succession. And now comes a thoroughly spectacular
recording of his greatest solo piano work, the ``Vingt Regards sur
l'Enfant-Jesus,'' played by Pierre-Laurent Aimard (Teldec).
</P>
<P>
   As Aimard points out in an interesting note _ more interesting
than the proper program note _ ``this vast fresco brings together
everything that made up the composer's world at that time: his
spiritual, cultural, musical and technical world.'' These ``Twenty
Gazes on the Child Jesus'' are religious illustrations, but made by
an artist for whom religious subjects did not imply a limitation.
Messiaen saw no reason why everything he could musically imagine
could not be brought into his scenes of veneration and praise:
crashing dissonances as well as the sweetest harmony, hectic dances
as well as gentle meditations, and a huge range of sounds, some of
them weird, some bewildering.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is magnificently present in Aimard's playing.
Indeed, there is more of it than he knows. Aimard, like the
composer, declares that the one thing omitted from the ``Vingt
Regards'' is human love _ despite the fact that his own
performance, time and again, reveals that the work is an immense
love song. It is the ``Turangalila Symphony'' of the piano, with
joyous movements of love music, bounding or still, punctuated by
sequences that are more abstract or bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   With Messiaen's music it is not possible to separate sacred and
secular love. Composed in 1944, ``Vingt Regards'' was one of the
first works he wrote after meeting the pianist Yvonne Loriod _
later his wife, who performed and recorded the work _ and the music
is as much a personal as a professional paean. It is furiously
virtuosic, conceived for a musician whose hands could skid and slam
and tremble to produce an enormous variety of colors. But it is
also, on the composer's part, like the mating display of a colossal
bird.
</P>
<P>
   Aimard meets the full measure of its vigor and its brilliance _
though it is not easy to know what is most impressive here: the
vividness of so many different piano sounds or the exemplary
directness with which they are executed.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen wrote large. The new piano vocabulary he was building
up in this work was also an old one, drawn from the most
exhibitionist music of Liszt and his successors, such as Ravel and
Albeniz. But the self-projecting rhetoric of the virtuoso is
eliminated. This is not the music of a pianist addressing an
audience, but that of a composer addressing God _ and addressing,
too, as a fellow child of God, the woman he imagined at the
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   An odd kind of self-effacement is therefore required from the
performer _ and splendidly supplied by Aimard. In the most
demanding pieces, such as ``Par Lui Tout a Ete Fait'' (``By Him Was
Everything Made''), he brings on a formidable repertory of big
effects. He greets the arrival of the ``theme of God'' at the main
climax with thunder and lightning, tearing down into the bass with
force, then throwing off quick, luminous festoons in the upper
treble, then doing both at once.
</P>
<P>
   This is superb, even awe-inspiring, and all the more so because
Aimard puts us in the presence of the music, not of himself. It is
not that he performs objectively. Where a lot of French Messiaen
playing is thin and mechanical, however glittering, Aimard is
strong and imbues the music with strength. There is a person here.
But that person is not asking for applause.
</P>
<P>
   Rhythm and accentuation are crucial. Aimard does not curve and
shape the music so that it fits his hands to show off his skill.
Rather, he fits his hands to the music, even if this means going a
little against what comes naturally. There are points in ``Par
Lui'' that sound awkward and alien. But they sound as if they have
to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   Also impressive in this movement is the way Aimard subtly alters
color, balance and phrasing as he rotates through a figure again
and again, so that there is nothing automatic in the repetition.
These small but telling changes seem like signs of a motive force
driving the repetition.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the two-hour cycle there is no relaxation of musical
thinking and acting. Where there is mercurial birdsong figuration,
Aimard treats it not just as decorative but finds in it real
musical sense. Where the music is slow and long, it is still
active, as if in demonstration of the line from the Song of Songs
that Messiaen took as the title for one of these pieces: ``I Sleep
but my Heart Waketh.''
</P>
<P>
   Aimard's wakefulness in another of the big slow movements, ``Le
Baiser de l'Enfant-Jesus'' (``Child Jesus' Kiss''), has
extraordinary results. Messiaen's daring recipe for intimacy here
was to withdraw into the world of the lounge pianist, with song
phrases, soupy harmonies and arpeggios at every opportunity. Often
the movement sounds just vulgar, and one has to accept its
vulgarity as part of Messiaen's sublime frankness.
</P>
<P>
   Not on this recording, though. Aimard shows that the music
transcends its sources. It is calm. It is graceful. It breathes
freely. Again, the effect comes partly from not jumping to
immediate conclusions about style and treatment but, instead,
finding what is particular in the detail. Aimard's approach also
brings him the means to build toward a fearsome culmination in this
movement, where the music becomes hard as nails. Jesus' kiss is not
soppy: it stings.
</P>
<P>
   Aimard is a musician who takes his time. His solo recordings are
few; this is his first since his wonderful contributions to Sony's
Ligeti series. And in this case he has been working on the music
for more than three decades, since he learned it as a pupil of
Loriod. The wait was worthwhile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
