<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CELERA-PROTEOMICS-BOS     08-15 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELERA-PROTEOMICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENOME PURSUER TURNS ATTENTION TO HUMAN PROTEINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After your company has decoded the human genome, what
do you do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   J. Craig Venter, founder and chief scientific officer for Celera
Genomics Group, said Tuesday he's turning his attention to
identifying proteins in human cells. But he expressed concern that
current computer technology may simply be too slow.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Drug Discovery Technology 2000 conference at
Boston's World Trade Center Tuesday, Venter said proteomics _
identifying networks of cell protein _ will require faster
commercially available computers that simply don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to sequence 1 million proteins a day,'' said
Venter, whose Celera Genomics, a unit of PE Corp., is based in
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But achieving that result soon won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computers today are way too slow,'' Venter said. He said
Celera's requirements have ``moved past what is available'' to
process its analysis.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, Venter joined Francis Collins, head of the
government-funded Human Genome Project, to jointly announce the
first assembly of the human genome _ the location and order of the
3.12 billion letters of genetic code. With about 85 percent of the
``map'' completed and expectations for a more complete publication
by year's end, the biggest challenge is determining how many genes
there are and discovering what they do.
</P>
<P>
   Venter's concern for computer hardware speed stems from an
improvement in Celera's ability to identify genetic code. The
company recently identified 1.15 billion letters of code of mouse
DNA in less than two months. By contrast, Celera's first draft of
the human genome, begun last September, took almost 10 months to
reveal 3.12 billion letters of code.
</P>
<P>
   Venter wants faster computational results. Over the next 10 to
50 years, researchers at biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies
will seek to turn the scientific treasures of the human genome into
medical advances and commercial profits. Those efforts require
looking beyond genes to identifying and understanding networks of
proteins and how they can be turned into drugs or become targets
for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But identifying all of the proteins emanating from a cell is a
far more complex task than mapping the genome. Proteins within a
single person can change from moment to moment. Some are produced
in high concentrations while others are rarer and found in only
small amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Venter said this complexity requires computer and robotics
technology far more sophisticated than the banks of supercomputers
Celera has used to parse the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, academic researchers can identify hundreds of
proteins a week; Celera wants to dramatically speed up the
sequencing of proteins to gain a better understanding of the
interrelated cellular pathways that can lead to disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
