<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CONFAB MORE LIKE AN MTV VIDEO SHOOT THAN POLITICAL
CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Republicans didn't throw a convention. They
threw a four-day crash course in diversity training.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats aren't throwing a convention either.
</P>
<P>
   They're throwing an MTV video shoot.
</P>
<P>
   We're only the extras. The stars of this show aren't Al Gore and
Hillary Clinton. They're Barbra Streisand and Cher and Melissa
Etheridge.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed like part of the script Monday night when the
street outside the convention compound erupted into a mob shoving
match _ not long after a concert by the political rock band Rage
Against the Machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built this city, and we can tear it down!'' shouted lead
singer Zack de la Rocha. Rage's current hit album is ``The Battle
of Los Angeles.'' On the antiestablishment band's corporate World
Wide Web site, the concert was called an event ``for all the people
who feel left out'' of an election between ``two weak candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the band works for the very establishment corporate
machine at Sony Music Entertainment Inc.
</P>
<P>
   About the time rubber bullets and tear-gas cartridges were
flying outside, President Clinton was making his entrance inside. A
camera followed him as he strode dramatically down a long hallway
to the arena, cheers building with every step.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee co-chair Patricia Harrison rolled
her eyes. ``It reminded me of World Championship Wrestling,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no use trying to separate politics from showbiz here. In
LA, its all showbiz.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Schiff Gore and Kristen Gore, the oldest daughters of
presidential nominee Al Gore, campaigned in Burbank as guests on
``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno.'' They wound up as comedy foils,
swapping wisecracks with fellow guest Jon Stewart of Comedy
Central's ``The Daily Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest line in Hollywood might be the line to see
``Politically Incorrect.'' On Monday, host Bill Maher joked that
Clinton's speech was like the president himself _ ``very
touching.''
</P>
<P>
   Maher was in the crowd for a press party Saturday night at the
six-acre mansion of ``Playboy'' magazine publisher Hugh Hefner.
CBS' Bryant Gumbel and Fox's Bill O'Reilly also lurked among the
Bunnies, all beneath red-white-and-blue bunting labeling the party
``A ``Playboy'' Salute to America 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the political newspaper ``National Journal'' devoted
Page 3 of its special daily convention edition to ``The Hunt for
Hollywood Celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody goes out hunting for Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   They're out to see Madonna. Or Jennifer and Brad. And where's
Shaq?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of shallow, did anyone catch ``CNN Larry King Live''
Monday night? After former candidate Bill Bradley, King interviewed
that sage political commentator, Cher.
</P>
<P>
   A multimillionaire, she called the Democrats ``the party of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a woman, a minority, a working person, gay,
anything that doesn't fit in with the Republican white, rich-guy
stereotype, then you cannot do anything but vote Democrat this
year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Texas of Republican nominee George W. Bush, she said,
``more women are starving'' than in any other state. ``More
children are going to bed hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   King nodded and smiled. ``Thank you, Cher,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back with more of our interview with Hillary Clinton. Don't go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll be back in a moment with more real politics.
</P>
<P>
   After this message from the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
