<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2587 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-15 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON PASSES THE TORCH &HT;    By MARIANNE MEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the Democrats opened their convention,
President Clinton demonstrated he is no mere crippled water fowl as
he galvanized the delegates into repeated rafter-rattling roars
that told the world he still owns the hearts of the party faithful,
no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   The crowded convention in the Staples Center here launched the
president Monday on the road to retirement on a wave of such
partisan pride and affection that it seemed certain the delegates
would have gladly renominated him if he hadn't been barred by the
Constitution from seeking a third term. Take that, narrow-minded
House impeachment goons!
</P>
<P>
   All that advice to Clinton about not stealing the show from his
protege and successor, Vice President Al Gore, was wasted. The
president did it simply by opening his mouth and uttering the
joyous words of partisan battle. He does love a good scrap, this
guy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said all the right things about Gore, but the delegates
were interested only in thanking the leader they already knew. Gore
they will take, but this was not Gore's night. The cheers rose and
the placards waved for Bill and for Hillary too. The decibel level
of the noise prompted by punch lines on behalf of Gore registered
decidedly lower.
</P>
<P>
   The president clearly reveled in the affectionate outpouring
that marked his dignified transfer of power to Gore. With a long
recitation of legislative and executive achievements, he demolished
the silly Republican charge that he had been ``coasting'' for two
terms and had nothing to do with today's economic prosperity. He
milked his audience for every dramatic moment, and there were many.
It was one of his best performances.
</P>
<P>
   He is like the little girl with a curl in the middle of her
forehead in the nursery rhyme: ``When she was good, she was very,
very good. When she was bad, she was horrid.'' And this time he was
very, very good.
</P>
<P>
   He was also unstinting in his praise for Gore and his desire
that Gore replace him in the White House. But will the Democrats
transfer their love and loyalty to the cerebral Gore once the
Personality Kid has left the podium? That will be mostly up to
Gore, although not entirely. His own speech on Thursday will be a
key test, bound to be compared with Clinton's masterful
performance.
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible for Gore to elbow past the overpowering
presence of Bill Clinton before the nomination formally transfers
the mantle of party leadership Thursday. And it won't be easy even
now, as the excited eruptions from fans during Clinton's farewell
speech demonstrated. Many Democrats here are plenty nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be around making speeches and policy in Washington,
supplemented by high-visibility trips abroad, for the rest of the
campaign. He is itching to finish his political wrestling match
with the Republican-controlled Congress. He is going out slowly on
a high, with his party's enthusiastic gratitude ringing in his
ears. Leaving center stage is difficult for a man whose whole adult
life has been one long campaign to gain office or hold onto one.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Republican efforts to make the memory of Monica Lewinsky
the only thing about his administration voters will remember in
November, Clinton, at this convention, is much admired for his
endurance and good will in the face of adversity. And while his
morals are deplored, his job approval ratings remain remarkably
high for a president in the waning days of power.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got another Monica mea culpa out of the way a few days
before the convention, when it attracted attention but did not
distract from the upbeat message he delivered to his party on
Monday. He said he was ``trying to totally rebuild my life from a
terrible mistake I made ... You just have to hope you're getting
better every day.'' He has previously apologized for his affair
several times, but never acknowledged that his statements under
oath in the Paula Jones lawsuit were deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   And he did what he could to spare Gore the fallout from his
behavior, although some polls indicate it may be impossible to
successfully immunize his protege no matter what he does. Clinton
urged voters not to fault Gore for failings that were his alone. At
least here in Los Angeles that is all that will be said on the
subject. The convention is scripted to stick to serious policy
issues and not detour into the vague moralizing of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton once again sent the message that she has
forgiven her husband, introducing his speech by talking about what
``we'' have done over the last eight years to produce ``the most
peaceful, prosperous, promising time in our nation's history'' She
dutifully promoted the virtues of Gore and his running mate, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman. But she also made a pitch for her own race for a
New York Senate seat, which prompted great whoops from the audience
and the frantic waving of masses of blue placards crying
``Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   The president too gave her a campaign plug, calling her ``a
great first lady'' who had an abiding passion to help children and
who would always be there for families in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Given her prominence here, no wonder poor Rep. Rick Lazio, her
GOP opponent, refused to take the brief, obscure speaking slot he
was offered at the Republican National Convention. The dramatic
contrast between her stature and his in their respective parties is
telling.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Clintons have been a formidable team. They were
mocked when they announced in 1992 that if Bill were elected, the
country would get two workers instead of one. But it has actually
turned out that way. If New Yorkers agree, Bill Clinton will be
history, but she will go on to bug conservatives some more in a new
role. Hooray.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
