<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-15 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CLINTON SAID `DON'T STOP' AND HE DIDN'T
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It has been obvious from the beginning. And it's
obvious at the end.
</P>
<P>
   From the first moment he entered politics, right up to when he
made his last Democratic National Convention speech Monday night,
there has been no doubt:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton never _ not ever _ knows when to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was appropriate, but also ironic the president's
nearly last words to the convention here were: ``Don't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't stop,'' he cried to roars of applause, as he harked back
to the campaign theme he and running mate Al Gore used in their
1992 campaign and beseeched all the delegates, alternates,
volunteer staffers and guests jammed into the convention hall:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't stop thinking about tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt about it, that was a swell _ if fairly subtle _
way to end his evening's plea for America to continue his
administration by electing his vice president to succeed him in the
Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, it was a long, long time in coming.
</P>
<P>
   For a fellow who never knows when to stop, Bill Clinton can _
and quite often does _ do a hell of a beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the opening to his speech at what is supposed to be
Al Gore's convention was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Some think it was his wife, the Democratic Senate candidate in
New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who introduced him to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense. Except for some awfully nice words about her husband _
and to her credit, Gore and his choice of a running mate, Joe
Lieberman _ Hillary Clinton didn't introduce Bill Clinton to the
convention. Harry Thomason, a television producer and maker of
whiz-bang movies about his friend Bill, introduced him.
</P>
<P>
   This year's film, something of a sequel to the terrific 1992
filmed convention-introduction to the Man from Hope, was boffo.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it splendid theater, Clinton's broadcast walk down
a long, incredibly long, bare corridor was dynamite theater _
theater so dynamite the crowd grew increasingly wild and, fairly,
can be said to have been emotionally amok by the time the prez
emerged onto the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he started to talk.
</P>
<P>
   And he talked and he talked and, then, he talked some more.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, his beginning was great. He had the crowd _ most of
whom had been issued signs saying ``Thank you, Mr. President'' _ in
the proverbial palm of his presidential hand.
</P>
<P>
   Although his whole speech was only 41 minutes _ an awfully short
time for Clinton, actually _ it seemed as though he talked for
hours about what he views as his accomplishments of the last nearly
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of (BEGIN ITALIC) his (END ITALIC) ideas and values and
plans for the future when he and Gore assumed office.
</P>
<P>
   Bless Al Gore's heart, the emphasis on almost the entire Clinton
speech was on what Clinton has accomplished, including, not
incidentally, his selection of Gore to be his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gave me the chance to turn those ideas and values into
action after I made one of the best decisions of my entire life,
asking Al Gore to be my partner,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Even the convention crowd, which was totally enthralled with
Clinton, began to flag in their shouted approval of him and his
accomplishments as the prez droned on and on about them.
</P>
<P>
   Only when he gave a signal _ false as it turned out _ that he
might be going to wind down, did his audience revive, for a moment,
its fervor.
</P>
<P>
   But, when he hit his true praise of Gore and his choice of a
running mate, Lieberman, Clinton roused the audience once again and
they stuck on fever pitch to the end.
</P>
<P>
   And, so, Bill Clinton left the convention that is supposed to be
Al Gore's, urging the American people to ``choose wisely'' when
thinking of their future, but, also, telling them to ``remember,
whenever you think about me, keep putting people first. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, this convention was to be a passing of the torch _ the
political torch _ from Clinton to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   If it happened _ and it isn't, by any means, certain it did _
Clinton certainly didn't stop soon enough to clearly, unequivocally
pass the torch to the man he wants elected to preserve his own
political legacy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
