<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK-0816-COX     08-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK-0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONVENTION NOTEBOOK: OF CONVENTION BUTTONS AND BOTTLE CAPS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A hot-selling button on the streets around the
downtown Staples Center where Democrats are holding their
convention: ``Read My Lips: No New Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The concession stands inside the Staples Center remove the tops
from bottled water they sell to delegates and members of the press.
Why? Vendors say those are the rules. Seems there was a problem in
the past with rowdy basketball fans throwing the bottle tops at
players _ a practice that surely must have ended when the Los
Angeles Lakers, who play at Staples Center, won the NBA
championship. Reminded that conventioneers are not grumpy
basketball fans, vendors were unmoved. Rules are rules, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish shuttle buses threw Georgia Democrats' carefully
crafted convention schedules out the window early this week. As
much as a two-hour ride to cover the roughly 12 miles from the
convention site to their hotel kept many delegates from attending a
salute to Gov. Roy Barnes at a fashionable LA restaurant late
Monday. And some delegates waited as long as three hours for a
shuttle to get to the opening day
</P>
<P>
   ceremonies at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped on a stationary bus teeming with impatient but
good-humored delegates Monday night, Georgia Labor Commissioner
Michael Thurmond resorted to a bit of trickery to try to get the
shuttle underway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pregnant woman on the bus,'' Thurmond joked,
gesturing randomly at any female seated. ``She needs to get to the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus finally moved, but not always in the right direction.
Delegates eventually disembarked and walked several blocks to get
to their lodgings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference between Democrats and Republicans?
Georgia's Gov. Barnes told the Florida delegation that Democrats
are constantly re-examining long-held beliefs and changing them
when
</P>
<P>
   necessary. On the other side, Barnes said, ``Republicans are
nothing but lemon-sucking sour folks who won't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the Staples Center _ through the slanted
view of the opposition _ Republican leaders are ready with their
early reviews of the Democratic National Convention. So far, they
don't like it. And they are very, very concerned about the
negative, destructive tone they perceive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just 11 minutes into the convention a speaker by the name of
Miller of Maryland was already launching into a tirade against
Republicans and against Governor Bush,'' said Rep. Henry Bonilla of
San Antonio, a co-chair of the recent GOP convention. ``And that's
the kind of thing America is tired of listening to.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``tirade'' Bonilla referred to was offered by Maryland state
Sen. Mike Miller, head of the Democratic Legislative Campaign
Committee and one of the first speakers on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   The tirade: ``Will we have Democratic policies that save our
water, our air, our health and our children _ or laissez-faire,
let-industry-set-their-own pollution standards, like those down in
Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore, a co-chairman of the GOP's Victory
2000 operation, made fun of Tuesday's convention theme, which was
``You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about right,'' said Gilmore. ``We couldn't have said it
any better than that. We ain't seen nothing yet over the last eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's morning-after response is part of an effort that
includes nationwide efforts to get their side heard during a week
when the Democrats will have the nation's ear. The effort includes
daily news conferences from five Texas Democrats who back George W.
Bush's bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo, U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development,
gave Ohio Democrats a kind of working definition of the new
direction the Democratic Party has taken since President Clinton
took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to call us the 'tax and spend Democrats,' `` Cuomo
told the Ohioans at their breakfast meeting Monday. ``Now they have
to call us the budget-balancing Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Ohio Sen. Howard Metzenbaum had his state's Democrats
howling for more when he spoke at the delegates' breakfast Tuesday
morning. After a warm-up behind the podium, Metzenbaum, 83,
strolled Oprah-like through the audience, exhorting the Democrats
to get out the vote this November for Al Gore and Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get off your butts and go out and vote,''
Metzenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator urged them to tell their friends to avoid the
temptation of voting for consumer advocate Ralph Nader, who's
running for president with the backing of the Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ralph Nader has done a good job. He doesn't have a
snowball's chance in hell of getting elected,'' said Metzenbaum,
who served three Senate terms before retiring in 1994. Every vote
Nader gets, said Metzenbaum, would be a vote taken away from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contributing were reporters Ken Herman, Kathey Pruitt, Larry
Lipman and Bill Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
