<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAYING SO LONG TO THE CLINTON CHARM, FOR BETTER OR WORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOMBARD, Ill. _ Just as Robin Wilson settled into her sofa to
watch President Clinton's speech to Democrats on Monday, her
telephone rang.
</P>
<P>
   It was Howard Ellis, an old co-worker, calling so he and Wilson,
a 67-year-old retired postal employee, could talk about the speech
as they watched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That charisma just shines,'' Wilson told her friend as the
president spoke about his humble roots and how grateful he was for
his time in office. ``It's a shame that he can't run again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure is,'' Ellis responded.
</P>
<P>
   The dedicated Democrats in the convention hall in Los Angeles
were not the only people who might have grown a bit wistful as they
listened to President Clinton on Monday night. In the living rooms
of Chicago's western suburbs, even independent voters said the
speech made them a bit nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was witty, funny, to the point,'' Wilson said, moments
after the speech, which she had taped for her grandchildren. ``I
like what he said about building one America. And I think he really
means that. I feel kind of sad, really.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the half-dozen viewers who were interviewed seemed to
share the warmth of Clinton's vision of the last eight years, they
were more subdued about their hopes for the Democrat vying to be
his successor, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I suppose I'll vote for Gore,'' Wilson said with a labored
sigh that spoke more ambivalence than enthusiasm. ``But my heart's
not in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a Republican like David King, though, a 35-year-old
computer software worker, sounded like a fan of Clinton's after the
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I was really impressed,'' King said. ``The way he
rebutted every single point at the Republican convention _ saying
the good economy was a choice, not a chance _ that was awfully
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   In King's view, the Democrats can scarcely take credit for all
the nation's prosperity in recent years. The ascension of the
Internet, he said, probably had more to do with soaring stock
prices and dwindling unemployment than any policies directed by the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton's closing argument, as he called it, could make
even a skeptical juror think twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just very persuasive,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Not every convention viewer was so inspired. Dr. Ann Gose, a
62-year-old cardiovascular surgeon, said she was mostly struck by
what she considered the president's profound self-centeredness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes on and on about his wife and Gore, but it eventually
comes back to himself, like it always does with this guy,'' Gose
said. ``You watch him, and it's like he couldn't let go. He needs
all this. I feel sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   And Charles Grimm, an engineering salesman in his 60s, was
throwing no bouquets at his television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at him makes me ill,'' said Grimm, an ex-marine who
said he detested Clinton from the start of his presidency, and grew
to loathe him even more since. ``He gives a good speech, no doubt
about it,'' Grimm said. ``But it's all sound-bites. And I just
can't believe anything he says.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech by Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for the
United States Senate in New York, did not seem to provoke such
visceral reactions, positive or negative, among the Chicago
suburbanites. But several said they were a bit surprised to find
her likable as a person, especially in light of the portrait her
detractors paint as a conniving, bloodless power-monger.
</P>
<P>
   Teri Turek, a 36-year-old insurance clerk, said she was struck
by Mrs. Clinton's sense of compassion. ``I didn't really like her
before,'' said Turek, a political independent. ``But when she
talked, she seemed so totally for family, for children. And she was
sincere. She looked you in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Turek added, ``And you've got to respect her for being such a
go-getter, considering everything that he's put her through.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Grimm, the Republican who cannot stomach the president, had
nice things to say about Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came across a little better than I thought she would,
strong and sincere,'' Grimm said. In particular, he gave Mrs.
Clinton high marks for praising Sen. Joseph Leiberman of
Connecticut, the Democratic vice-presidential candidate, who had
been critical of the president's sexual relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On one point, each viewer agreed: It was a relief that neither
the president nor Clinton talked about the scandal that nearly
drove him from office. None of them wanted any displays of
contrition or public appeals, as one put it, ``for some kind of
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie Addison, 44, who owns a convenience-store franchise,
groaned at the mention of Clinton's moral lapses. ``We've had
enough about that,'' Addison said. ``It's over and done with.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether these voters considered Clinton to be a star or a
villain, it was clear that they saw him as the headline attraction,
drawing attention from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As Grimm saw it, ``Clinton is going to completely overshadow
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the president's repeated mention of Gore as his full
partner in the White House, these voters expressed skepticism that
White House policies were much influenced by the second-in-command.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that were put through, that was President
Clinton,'' Wilson said. ``And you get the feeling that's all over
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
