<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola turning marketing strategy on its ear
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - After 114 years, Coca-Cola is turning its marketing
strategy on its head.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based beverage giant, known as one of the world's
premier marketers, believes its old formula is out of date in a new
world order in which consumers and technology are the driving
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our old model, Coke was at the center of everything we
did,'' Steve Jones, the company's chief marketing officer, said
Tuesday. ``We created lots of reasons to draw people into the world
of Coke.''
</P>
<P>
   But that won't work anymore, Jones said, especially since
consumers feel empowered to change their buying habits as they see
new products and experience new things.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our new model, consumers are at the center of the wheel,''
Jones said. ``We're developing relationships with consumers, and
getting Coke and other beverages into their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Those relationships, Jones said, need to be established and
re-established every day of the year _ year after year.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the reasons Coca-Cola announced Tuesday that it is
entering into a unique partnership that could help consumers cover
college costs.
</P>
<P>
   The company signed a letter of intent to team up with UPromise,
a Massachusetts firm organizing a college savings network. When
it's up and running in the fall or winter, kids, their parents and
grandparents will be able to establish a tax-deferred college
savings account financed by purchasing certain Coke beverages, as
well as other products to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of each purchase will be rebated into such loyalty
accounts, which will grow through continued purchases, as well as
through investments made by professional money managers. Down the
road, that money can be used to help pay for college.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one example of how the company intends to connect
with consumers in the future if it is to grow as rapidly as it
wants to, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Coke veteran, who was promoted in January to the
company's top marketing job, is a practitioner of Chairman Doug
Daft's ``think local, act local'' strategy. Each of the company's
26 operating divisions around the globe are free to take risks,
come up with new ideas and implement them in a much streamlined
approval process.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big change, Jones said, from the centralized marketing
strategies and bureaucratic approval process that existed before
Daft took the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke has a big challenge,'' said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``As a huge beverage company, it must
continue its powerful core brands, such as Coke and Sprite. But at
the same time, it must also become a small, entrepreneurial local
beverage company. Given Jones' record in Japan, where he helped the
company with rapid-fire innovation, he is well- equipped to help
make that happen on a global basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, Jones insists, is to know what consumers want in a
timely fashion in each market and then give it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about knowledge,'' Jones said. ``The more you've got, the
more you'll do. We've opened up the windows and doors to ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Coca-Cola, like some of its rivals, has es said. The
trick is to tap into them, market by market.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, for example, the company recently found out that it
was not sufficiently targeting young people fraternizing at clubs
at night. As a result, it designed specific ``enjoy the chill'' ads
and marketing programs to better capitalize on thirsty,
out-of-breath dancers at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, the company recently found out that kids like the
tanginess of juice and the texture of milk. So it introduced
Sonfil, a juice-milk combination that Jones said is doing well so
far, althou
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
