<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COKE-EXEC0816-COX     08-15 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EXEC0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - His title says it all.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Bishop was named Tuesday to be vice president of ``consumer
connections'' for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, by contrast, was just called director of
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   While Bishop, 38, will be responsible for creating Coca-Cola's
overall advertising strategy, his job will be more in keeping with
the company's new emphasis on building relationships with
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from advertising, those relationships will be cultivated
through the Internet, interactive television, and wireless and game
technology.
</P>
<P>
   After an overall strategy is developed for the company's main
brands, each local market will be free to execute it in ways that
make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much to do to improve the quality of our
communications,'' said Bishop, who will report to Steve Jones,
chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, an Australian, will take over Oct. 1. Currently, he is
managing director of the McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L ad agency in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 of his 15 years at McCann-Erickson, Bishop worked on
Coca-Cola business in Sydney, New York, London, Amsterdam and
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick Bishop comes to the table with an impressive array of
communications experience and demonstrated ability to bring about
positive change, ... invent new solutions and just plain make
things happen,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop replaces Ian Rowden, who left the company in May.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Quinn replaced Rowden on an interim basis. Quinn will now
become director of global brand communications, reporting to
Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
