<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tab-z
u p BC-ARAB-REACTION-NEWHOUS     08-15 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-REACTION-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN MUSLIMS SEEK REASSURANCE ON LIEBERMAN'S APPROACH TO
MIDEAST
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Uneasy American Muslim leaders say Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., must move quickly after his nomination
Wednesday as the Democratic vice presidential candidate to reassure
them that he will be fair on the Mideast or risk losing millions of
votes in crucial states to Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalence toward Lieberman is evident even among strong
Democrats of the Muslim faith, and among Arab-American delegates of
other faiths, who are attending the Democratic National Convention
in record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim leaders are urging Lieberman, the first Jewish candidate
named to a major party's national ticket, to meet with them to
discuss a wide range of issues, but said they have received no
response yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to engage with the Muslim community in a public
setting,'' said Salam Al-Marayati, executive director of the Muslim
Public Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the signal is he has no interest in such engagement, then,
yes, I expect Muslims to shift their attention to the Bush-Cheney
ticket,'' Al-Marayati said. ``If there is no definitive response
within a week of the convention, then I'm afraid time will be
running out and people will be making up their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Hooper, spokesman of the Council on American-Islamic
Relations, said Al Gore's choice of Lieberman to be his running
mate has stirred deep apprehensions among Muslims, who believe the
United States has always tilted in favor of Israel and that a
Jewish vice president would make changes in that policy unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   But some Muslims are wondering if an administration with
Lieberman as vice president might feel politically safer about
making foreign policy adjustments that might otherwise rile Jewish
voters. They cite President Richard Nixon's opening to China as an
example because only a Republican could have taken that risk.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's selection also stirs hope that if Jews are able to
crash important cultural barriers and run for high office, Muslims
eventually can follow.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy issues aside, other Muslims fear Lieberman may be
too conservative on domestic and social issues of concern to
Muslims, such as due process under anti-terrorist laws they feel
victimize them, as well as federal spending on housing and health
care for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we ask of Lieberman and Gore is that they reach out
to the Muslim community to discuss these issues,'' Hooper said.
``It's really up to him. The initiative is in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans see an opening. GOP National Chairman James
Nicholson, in Los Angeles as a critical observer, said his party is
already ``reaching out to Muslim voters and meeting with their
leaders.'' If they are 8 million strong, Nicholson said, they are
at least as numerous as Jewish voters. ``The Bush ticket has a good
chance to carry that vote'' in the swing states of Michigan, Ohio,
Illinois and California where there are significant numbers of
Muslims, Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews at the Democratic convention, many
Muslim delegates said they will vote to nominate Lieberman for vice
president Wednesday -- some grudgingly -- but they acknowledge that
he has ``work to do'' to win the votes of the Muslim community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will vote for Mr. Lieberman, not with all my heart, but I
will vote for him, yes,'' said Jumana Judeh of Detroit, who was
born ``in the holy city of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   One of 55 Arab-American delegates here, not all of them Muslim,
Judeh said she is troubled because Lieberman has been a firm
advocate of moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem, a step that would demonstrate U.S. support for Israeli
sovereignty over Jerusalem when the Palestinians also claim rights
to the city. ``I'm not in love with Mr. Lieberman because of his
past voting record,'' she said. ``I'm a Palestinian and the embassy
issue is very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Chafic Hatoum, 66, a retired insurance executive and
Lebanese-born Muslim from Sylvania, Ohio, said a Jewish vice
president could be good for Muslims. ``I've heard that because he
is a Jewish American means there is potential for some doors to be
opened that wouldn't have been opened otherwise. That's certainly
possible,'' said Hatoum. ``The other is also possible, that this
could set us back a bit,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   While Muslims claim as many votes as Jews, Hatoum said, ``we
certainly don't have the financial resources that they have -- but
in the end the votes count. The unity of Muslims will affect
national policy and the administration will act in a responsive
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Maya Mohamad Berry, 31, of Dearborn, Mich., born in
Beirut, Lebanon, said, ``For me, the problem with Lieberman is not
that he's Jewish and that he would support Israel, but that he is a
Democratic Leadership Council man and I wish he was more liberal on
education and the plight of the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he is a fair man with a balanced view who, once he
no longer represents just the voters of Connecticut, will have a
somewhat different position on foreign policy questions in the
Mideast,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Terry Ahwal, an executive assistant in Wayne County,
Mich., said she had just returned from a visit to Palestine where
the peace process has reached a new low of ``hopelessness.''
Lieberman might change that, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is saying that because of his Jewish background we
need to be wary,'' Ahwal said. ``I say because of his Jewish
background we need to be hopeful. If nothing else, you need peace
not because of Palestine but for the security of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Morshed Alam, 43, an environmental chemist from Queens,
New York, and a Muslim born in Bangladesh, said he wants to see
Jerusalem be a neutral city but that ``religion is not the
important issue -- to me the important issue is bread and butter
and who tries to address equality and inclusion of minorities, and
public education and affirmative action. I have concerns but don't
look at Lieberman as Jewish, I look at him as a human being and a
senator. Foreign policy will be up to Gore. He knows what he'll do
and Lieberman will comply with the position Gore has.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Ismael Ahmed, 52, director of an Arab community center
in Dearborn, Mich., said he was caught by surprise when Gore chose
Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a mixed record on the Mideast,'' Ahmed said, ``but he's
done things like co-chairing Builders for Peace, a group of Arabs
and Jews who worked to build businesses on the West Bank so the
level of existence there would be one that would make for peace. I
think that's a positive thing. And he co-sponsored the Egyptian
foreign aid bill. I will vote for Lieberman because I'm a Democrat.
He is not where I would like to see him on Jerusalem, but he's not
been an enemy to the peace process either.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Ahmad Nawab, 63, of St. Petersburg, Fla., an
Indian-born Muslim, said he will back Lieberman despite misgivings
within his community.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very strong supporter of Israel and I would like
to see him moderate somewhat,'' Nawab said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lieberman's most outspoken admirers among the
Arab-American delegates is James Zogby, president of the
Washington-based Arab American Institute, who said, ``He helped us
when we needed somebody to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Arab-American Democrats initially were not welcomed into the
Clinton-Gore campaign in 1992, Zogby said; ``They were rebuffed.''
He said a prominent member of the pro-Israel lobby, whom he
declined to name, who was active in the Clinton campaign bluntly
told him: `We're not going to let you in. Go join the Republicans.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Joe Lieberman,'' Zogby said. ``I told him they were
trying to keep us out, that they were saying they don't want Arabs
in this campaign. Lieberman said, `That's outrageous.' He picked up
a telephone and called George Stephanopoulos (then a senior Clinton
aide) and said, `I want the Arab-Americans in the campaign.' The
next day we were invited to the campaign headquarters in Little
Rock and we were greeted there with open arms. It was Lieberman who
made it happen. He said what was happening to us was wrong and it
was not the kind of politics he would support.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby is spreading that story about Lieberman over and over
here, but he said it is not an easy sell among Arab-Americans and
Muslims. ``They are nervous and uneasy about Lieberman,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-OBITUARY-WATSON-BOS &LR;      08-15 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WATSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT B. WATSON, 86, WORKED AS DEAN OF STUDENTS AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert B. Watson, dean of students at Harvard
University during tumultuous anti-war demonstrations in the 1960s
and later the university's athletic director who oversaw the start
of a multimillion-dollar building campaign, died Saturday in his
home in Cataumet. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Watson grew up in Wellesley and attended St. Mark's School.
At Harvard, Mr. Watson lettered in football and crew and was
graduated in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Mr. Watson served in the Navy and was the
executive officer on board the destroyer USS Leary. On Christmas
Eve 1943, the Leary was patrolling in the North Atlantic Ocean
about 700 miles from France when a German U-boat sank the ship. Mr.
Watson clung to a two-by-four for five hours in the frigid waters
before being rescued. ``It was just beginning to get light when we
were picked up by another warship,'' he said after returning to the
United States. ``I never was so glad to see another vessel in my
life.'' Of the 277 men on board, 57 survived.
</P>
<P>
   After the war Mr. Watson became a dean at Harvard and was made
dean of students in 1958. His style was to treat people with
courtesy and respect, while maintaining a sense of order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kindest man I ever met,'' said Jay Stack, a former
Harvard student who became a family friend. ``He was always
gracious and made you feel like you were the only person on his
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   As anti-war protests increased on campuses throughout the
country in the 1960s, Mr. Watson was caught up in the events at
Harvard. In 1969, students took over University Hall and forcibly
ejected Mr. Watson from his office on four occasions. Trying to
maintain order, Mr. Watson made more than two dozen court
appearances, as the administration's only representative, as
assault cases were brought against students.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970 Mr. Watson became athletic director at Harvard, a
position he held until his retirement in 1977. During his tenure,
he was instrumental in helping to start the renovation of the
university's athletic facilities, which at the time were the worst
in the Ivy League. It was under Mr. Watson's tenure that
construction began on Blodgett Pool and the Gordon Track. ``It is
important to give him credit for that; he was instrumental,'' said
Jack Reardon, Harvard's director of alumni affairs.
</P>
<P>
   At his retirement, each of the Ivy League schools presented Mr.
Watson with a varsity letter.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, he enjoyed spending his summers at the family
house in Cataumet. ``He used to joke that he never wanted to get in
a boat smaller than a destroyer,'' said his daughter Joanne Watson
Spievack. Mr. Watson would spend several hours each day in his
vegetable garden.
</P>
<P>
   He was a past president of the board of Belmont Day School and
served on the board of the Beaver Country Day School. He was a
member of the Brookline country club.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Polly (Blodgett) of Boston and Florida;
three daughters, Gail Barber of Bedford, Jeannie of Weston, and
Joanne of Cambridge; two sons, Peter T. of Bainbridge Island, Wa.,
and Robert Jr., of Richmond, Va.; a brother, Edward of New
Hampshire; and nine grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2599 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-ARAB-REACTION-NEWHOUS     08-15 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAB-REACTION-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN MUSLIMS SEEK REASSURANCE ON LIEBERMAN'S APPROACH TO
MIDEAST
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
