<SLUG> BC-CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME DEMS SAY GORE SHOULD RUN WITH CLINTON RATHER THAN AWAY FROM
HIM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore, after officially taking
the baton from President Bill Clinton in Michigan yesterday, comes
here today to begin the last leg of the presidential relay.
</P>
<P>
   As he heads toward the finish line, clearly behind Republican
nominee George W. Bush, political pundits keep suggesting that Gore
must continue to distance himself from the man he has served (and
worked closely with) for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe what Bill Clinton said in his farewell speech
Monday night, when he listed a plethora of this administration's
accomplishments, then it is reasonable to ask: How can Gore run
away from that when he was a partner in making it all happen?
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, ``Why'' would he run away from the man to
whom the American people still give high marks for his performance
in office?
</P>
<P>
   There are many delegates here who say Gore should run ``with''
Clinton, not away from him.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Al Edwards of Houston said that, with the record the
Clinton administration has amassed, there is no reason for Gore to
sever his relations with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be his own man,'' Edwards said, ``and that's what
he's been doing. But he doesn't have to separate himself from his
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   One person with a unique perspective on the campaign, partly
because of his friendship with Clinton and Gore and partly because
he has run his own race against Republican Bush, is Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, ignoring the counsel of some advisers, proudly proclaimed
his friendship with the president when he ran against incumbent
Bush for governor in 1998. He even asked Clinton to come to Texas
and campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't hurt Mauro during that campaign, but he couldn't
help him either. No one could have beaten Bush that year.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Gore is exactly where Bush's father was in 1988, when
the elder Bush came out of the Republican convention with hopes of
succeeding Ronald Reagan in office.
</P>
<P>
   In that campaign, Mauro recalls, then-Vice President Bush was
behind in the polls. He was being called a ``wimp'' without a clear
message and people wondered if he could ever get out of Reagan's
shadow.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Bush won in 1988, Mauro said, because ``ultimately
the American people wanted to keep Reagan in office because of his
record _ his perceived record.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks that kind of sentiment will come into play when
Americans go to the polls in November. But while he believes that
Gore and Joseph Lieberman have a good chance of overtaking the
Republican ticket and seizing victory in November, Mauro was
cautious not to be over confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any Democrat who underestimates George W. Bush would
be making a huge mistake,'' he said. ``I won't make that mistake
twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Clinton is ``Gore's 800-pound gorilla'' just
as Reagan was Bush's oversized primate, Mauro said the Bush
campaign was making a big mistake by harping on the
Clinton/Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have forgiven Bill Clinton for his past
indiscretions,'' Mauro said. ``They're still made at him _ I'm
still mad at him _ but they have forgiven him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said the ``single most reason Bush ought to be defeated''
is because he, instead of spending $1 billion to provide universal
kindergarten for Texas children, ``would rather give a crummy
$12-a-year tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who got married again last spring and is expecting twins,
said he's enjoying private life for a change, but you can expect
him to back in politics. He wouldn't predict when.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
