<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN RECEIVED DEFERRAL DURING VIETNAM DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dick Cheney and Senator Joseph I. Lieberman have
something in common beyond the fact that both hope to become vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cheney, Lieberman received a deferment from the military
draft during the Vietnam War because he was a father. And like
Cheney, Lieberman, under rules in effect at the time, received the
deferment before the child was born.
</P>
<P>
   According to Selective Service records, Lieberman held a student
deferment from 1961, when he was a freshman at Yale, until May 24,
1967, as he was preparing to graduate from Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, Lieberman was granted a coveted 3-A deferment,
meaning he could not be drafted because he was the father of a
child. His first child, Matthew, by his first wife, was born Aug.
16, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who was also a graduate student in the 1960s, was
granted the same kind of deferment in January 1966, about 10 weeks
after his wife, Lynne, became pregnant, and just after the
Selective Service made childless married men as vulnerable to the
draft as single men.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney would have remained protected from the draft even without
the fatherhood deferment because he remained in school until after
he turned 26, when men became exempt from conscription.
</P>
<P>
   But because Lieberman was finishing law school, he would have
been subject to the draft almost immediately without the 3-A
deferment, according to Richard Flahaven, a Selective Service
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman did not turn 26 until Feb. 24, 1968. Flahaven said
that under Selective Service rules, the oldest eligible men were
drafted first.
</P>
<P>
   With their exemptions, Cheney and Lieberman were part of a large
cohort in their age group: The number of men who were exempt from
the draft because they had children exceeded the number of men, 2.6
million, who served in Vietnam from 1964 to 1973.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
