<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos from the Democratic National Convention
have moved as part of Tuesday night's New York Times Photo Package.
</P>
<P>
   Additional photos will move throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   (CVN5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- DEM-PROTESTS -- Members
of the Los Angeles Police Department, Mobile Field Force, arrive to
the Staples Center, site of the Democratic National Convention,
Tuesday. On Monday night, hundreds of demonstrators threw rocks and
fired steel balls from slingshots at police, who answered by firing
rubber bullets and beanbags from shotguns. (Monica Almeida/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (CVN4) MONROE, Mich. -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- DEM-CLINTON-GORE-2--
With a campaign embrace, President Clinton passed the mantle of
Democratic leadership to Al Gore on Tuesday, saying his vice
president was ``at the heart'' of every achievement of his
administration. Gore turns to a crowd of supporters as, from left,
President Clinton, Gore's wife Tipper, and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton look on, Tuesday. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (CVN3) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- DEM-LIEBERMAN -- Sen.
Joseph Lieberman appeared to win over some wavering black delegates
Tuesday when he told them he supports affirmative action. The
Democratic vice presidential candidate is welcomed to a meeting of
the Congressional Black Caucus and the Democratic National
Committee's Black Caucus by Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., right,
Tuesday. Looking on at left is Secretary of Labor Alexis Herman.
(Monica Almeida/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (CVN2) MONROE, Mich. -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- DEM-CLINTON-GORE-- With
a campaign embrace, President Clinton passed the mantle of
Democratic leadership to Al Gore on Tuesday, saying his vice
president was ``at the heart'' of every achievement of his
administration. Gore and Clinton embrace as Hillary Rodham Clinton
looks on at right, Tuesday. At left, Gore's wife Tipper waves to
the crowd of supporters. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (CVN1) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- DEM-CAROLINE-KENNEDY --
Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and his niece, Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, the daughter of the late President John F.
Kennedy, during a sound check on the floor of the Democratic
National Convention, Tuesday. Caroline will introduce her uncle to
convention delegates Tuesday night, whose mission at Democratic
conventions has always been to remind the party of its liberal
heritage. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
