<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2606 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-LILEKS-DEMS-NEWHOUSE &LR;      08-15 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-DEMS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FOR THE FAITHFUL, POLITICS IS WATERED-DOWN KOOL-AID 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, Aug. 15, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic Convention appears to have achieved its
objective: absolutely everyone in the Staples Center will vote for
Al Gore. Winning over the delegates, however, doesn't mean you've
won the heart of America.
</P>
<P>
   The more close-up experience one has with conventions, the more
one believes that the right to vote should be withdrawn entirely
from delegates. People this enthusiastic should be manacled and
placed in a small dim closet until the election has passed _ if
only for their own safety. If Bill Clinton had concluded his speech
by going all Jim-Jones on the Stapleites, announcing that the
forces of darkness were coming and they had to drink this Kool-Aid
to move on to a better place, they'd have lined up and asked for
Big-Gulp portions.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not everyone. Hillary won't drink Bill's Kool-Aid. Oh,
she'll put the cup to her lips and make sipping noises, but she'll
spit it out when no one's looking. Her opening night speech proved
three things:
</P>
<P>
   1. She'll never again be content to cool her heels in Bill's
long shadow. Her speech concluded with a list of people she had to
thank for the last eight years; her husband was not among them.
Perhaps it was a trick. Perhaps if he later said, ``Thanks for the
acknowledgment, hon,'' she'd know he'd yanked a toothsome campaign
worker into the green room, locked the door and turned off the TV.
Or at least turned down the sound.
</P>
<P>
   2. She'll never be half the leader Bill is. She's a dud on the
stump. The nation really hasn't seen a full-strength feature-length
Hillary speech before. We've been served thin pink slices of Rodham
over the years, but it's been years since she's given a purely
political speech for national consumption. Her opening night speech
answered the question: Can someone nag in a shouting monotone? Yes.
Through a novacaine smile, no less.
</P>
<P>
   3. She doesn't buy this new moral Democrat stuff, either.
Hillary had a litany of concerns she'd personally experienced
during the last eight years -- to our surprise, it turns out she
hasn't been in D.C. at all. She's spent the time on porches and
factory floors, holding the hands of people, ordinary people,
decent people, who would all be decomposing skeletons now if Bill
hadn't been elected. With every sob story she told, she got a
cheer, as if people were applauding for the continued existence of
misery.
</P>
<P>
   Then she brought up the difficulty of raising children in a
world saturated with media violence. She seemed to be bolting down
the sentence like a child eating beets to get to the pudding. The
crowd hardly mustered a cheer. This is Lieberman's territory, and
it either bores the faithful or makes them nervous. Honest Joe,
after all, has worked with Bill Bennett, whom the hard left regards
as a roly-poly ayatollah intent on stuffing all women back into
Donna Reed dresses and making sure children memorize Robert Service
poems while they get flat-top haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   The left doesn't share Lieberman's Silver Sewer crusade; to the
left, the real villains are those who question public funding for
transgressive art, or radio talk-show hosts like Dr. Laura. She's
spent about 3 percent of her shows airing a religious view of
homosexuality drawn from the same faith as Joe Lieberman, and this
makes her a threat to civilized society. Let a rapper such as
Eminem announce that he hates gays, and that's different. If your
Hollywood contributors make money from the sale of hate, it's
artistic license.
</P>
<P>
   Let us quote from the artist himself: ``My words are like a
dagger with a jagged edge that'll stab in you head whether you're a
fag or a les.'' Do Democrats support these sentiments? No. But they
can't support the people who worry about Eminem, because they think
they're fun-killing Gingrichian cads in Snidely Whiplash cloaks,
eager to jail Teletubbies for violating sodomy laws.
</P>
<P>
   So the Dems' new family-friendly, post-Clinton pro-morals
incarnation regards cultural rot as just an unfortunate form of
weather. And as a wise man once noted, everyone engages in
meaningful dialogue about the weather, but no one efforts any
actionable positions. The entertainment medium could stand a little
shaming now and then, but the left can't bring themselves to do it,
any more than the right can pretend they're doing jumping-jacks
over Bush's pro-government talk. It's a rough year for the
hard-core faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but Kool-Aid -- and watered-down stuff, at that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
