<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS &LR;      08-15 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREANS SEPARATED SINCE '50S WAR TEARFULLY REUNITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ A half-century's worth of pent-up emotion, long-buried
hopes, and unforgotten love poured out in a torrent of tears and
desperate embraces Tuesday as 200 families torn apart by war came
together for a few hours in the capitals of South and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Live television coverage of the heart-wrenching meetings
mesmerized a nation torn in half by ideology and Cold War-era
conflict, spurring hopes for the eventual reunification of the
Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred North Koreans, citizens of the world's last
hard-line Stalinist nation, flew to the southern capital to meet
sobbing parents, children, siblings, and spouses. The long-lost kin
hugged for minutes at a time, moaning and repeating each other's
names, touching faces in disbelief, clutching each other as if they
would never let go.
</P>
<P>
   Cries of ``Mother!'' ``Where have you been?,'' ``We thought you
were dead!'' ``Oh! How I've missed you!'' and ``Sweetheart, it's
me,'' filled the air in the vast convention hall where the reunions
took place at 100 separate tables.
</P>
<P>
   In Pyongyang, the scene repeated itself, as 100 southerners were
showered with tears, interminable embraces, and yelps of joyful
recognition tinged with pain. ``Is that you, my brother? Are you
the real one?'' one woman cried, holding her brother and patting
his back again and again, as if to make sure he was really there.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the emotion of seeing the son she long believed
dead, one elderly woman in Seoul collapsed and had to be carried
out on a stretcher. Another woman hugged her brother so hard that
both fell to the ground, arms intertwined, sobbing hysterically.
Others burst into tears repeatedly, drinking bottles of herbal
medicine to calm down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shivering and shivering,'' whispered Lee Dok Soon, 86, at
the sight of her 65-year-old son An Soon Hwan, who went to school
one day 50 years ago at the outbreak of the war and never came
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother!'' he cried, grasping her knees and prostrating himself
before her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon Hwan, my son, where have you been?'' she sobbed.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of southerners are believed to have been abducted
during the chaos of war, forced into the North's army or kidnapped
for their special skills. Many others joined the northern side by
choice. They never saw their families again when the war ended with
a permanent division along the 38th parallel.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, more than 1 million northerners fled
south or were taken prisoner. They, too, were never able to return
home.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, the 70 million people on either side of the
world's most militarized and impregnable border were denied any
contact, even letters or phone calls, and the vast majority have no
idea what happened to missing relatives. This week's brief
reunions, carefully monitored by North Korean officials and
restricted to no more than five relatives for each visitor for a
few hours a day, will end Friday morning. The families will then
say goodbye, perhaps never to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   These are only the second-ever official reunions. In 1985, 50
families from each side met, but have not been permitted to contact
each other since.
</P>
<P>
   The pain was palpable for those excluded from the reunions; one
woman who was not among the five relatives permitted to meet with
her brother stood vigil outside his hotel with a placard bearing
his name. When Kim Yong Hwan, 68, marched out in step with the
North Korean delegation and heard his youngest sister's voice, his
mouth froze in a grotesque expression of pain, and he faltered on
his way to the waiting bus. The two were prevented from greeting
each other by a security cordon, and sister Kim Yong Soon collapsed
in tears, crying, ``Older brother! Older brother!''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the chosen didn't make it to the big day. Mun Byong
Chul, 68, learned that his 90-year-old mother died three days after
learning last week that he was alive and might be permitted to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least before she passed away, she was told her son was
still alive and was seeking his mother,'' Mun's sister told him.
``She asked, `Can I meet him? Can I meet him today?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so betrayed when you left us and went to North
Korea,'' his sister continued, until Mun, holding back tears,
begged her to stop, saying, ``Let's meet up again tomorrow and only
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   At another table, Hong Kil Soon, 87, grabbed her daughter, Kim
Ok Bae, an aspiring dancer who disappeared on her way to high
school one day during the war and is now the North's best known
teacher of dance and gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Kim and her family clasped each other in a group embrace, crying
out each others' names. Like others who met their parents, Kim
bowed before her mother, knelt down, and put her face in her
mother's lap. The family pulled out black-and-white baby photos and
class pictures of Kim, presented her with a huge diamond ring
belonging to her mother, and asked her why she disappeared. Kim,
67, told them she went to North Korea to perform for soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed Tuesday night after the reunions broke up for the
evening, Kim Sook Bae, 64, said she still believes her sister was
kidnapped because of her fame as a promising young dancer, but
added quickly, ``We're only guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   After a dinner in which the families were oddly separated again
in the banquet hall, Kim's brother, Kim Yu Kwang, 57, said he would
feel empty when his sister leaves on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now I feel empty,'' he confided sadly. ``It feels like I
got a rain shower _ when it first hits you, it feels cool and nice,
but when it's over, you feel cold and clammy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a bittersweet day for spouses who were separated
when husbands were conscripted into or joined the North Korean
army. ``She was so young and lively at 23. She's just the same _
she hasn't changed a bit,'' Kim Hi Young, 72, said quietly of his
wife. He later remarried in the North.
</P>
<P>
   It was painfully clear, however, that Jeong Chun Ja, 73, could
not rejoice, because of her guilt over having remarried seven years
after her husband Kim disappeared. ``I didn't have any money. I
couldn't survive on my own. If I had a father and brothers to
support me, I would never have remarried,'' she repeated again and
again in apology. She was widowed 10 years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sorry you remarried,'' Kim reassured her. ``I
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 77,000 applicants in South Korea, 100 were chosen by a
lottery to go north. North Korea apparently chose its 100 delegates
on the basis of their accomplishments and loyalty to the regime.
The northern visitors wore lapel pins featuring their late ``Great
Leader'' Kim Il Sung, and whenever officials listened in on
conversations, the visitors sat up, thanked the North's current
``Dear Leader,'' Kim Jong Il, and made impassioned, if stiff, pleas
for national reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Though the reunions are fleeting and restricted to hotel rooms
and escorted tours, they are arguably the most important outcome of
the landmark summit between the leaders two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, an apparent detente has blossomed in countless ways;
Tuesday, South Korean President Kim Dae Jung called for the
creation of a North-South military hotline and echoed Kim Jong Il's
vow to repair a defunct railroad link.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jong Il has called for more reunions in September and
October and suggested families might be able to visit their
hometowns next year.
</P>
<P>
   The communist North and democratic South remain technically at
war, since a peace treaty was never signed to end the 1950-53
conflict, and as recently as last year, the North provoked a naval
battle with the South. But South Koreans' hopes for peaceful
reunification were bolstered by the successful summit, and even
more so by Tuesday's reunions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2002EDT &QL; 
