<P>
   David Bositis, an expert on black politics with the Joint Center
for Political and Economic Studies in Washington, said he thought
that in the context of attracting black votes, Lieberman was
``probably the least desirable choice'' among the names on Gore's
short list. ``I don't know what the consequences are going to be,
quite frankly,'' said Bositis. ``I have a hard time imagining it
would be a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican efforts to present a much more multiracial face to
America at their convention in Philadelphia were aimed primarily at
attracting white swing voters, Bositis said. But, he said, it is
not beyond the realm of possibility that Republicans could
marginally improve their standing with black voters over their
performance in the last four presidential cycles when they won
about 10 percent of the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, Democratic presidential nominee Al Gore's
choice of Lieberman, who built his reputation as a Democrat who was
unafraid to depart from party dogma, may have brought home to some
people just how much more conservative their party has become in
the Clinton era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius of Bill Clinton was that he stole Republican
thinking and gave it a liberal bent,'' said Michael Eric Dyson, a
cultural critic and one of the leading voices of the black left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that Gore is any more dead center or right of center
than Clinton, but he doesn't have Clinton's intimate contacts with
black people that allowed him an entre that Mr. Gore simply does
not possess,'' said Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that black people are very nervous,'' said Dyson, who
teaches at DePaul University in Chicago. As a seminary student in
Hartford, Conn., when Lieberman was first elected to the Senate in
1988, Dyson voted for Lieberman's incumbent opponent, the
independent Republican Sen. Lowell Weicker. ``The problem with
Lieberman is that he is a Republican masquerading as a Democrat,
and that's a profound problem,'' said Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton managed to support the death penalty, enact welfare
reform and transform the Democrats into the balanced-budget party
while becoming more popular with black Americans every step of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   But, Walters said, Gore does not have that ``magic.'' And
Lieberman, like Clinton and Gore, is prominently associated with
the Democratic Leadership Council, which was formed to move the
party toward the middle and away from what was seen as the party's
overweaning devotion to minority causes.
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters of Los
Angeles, who has raised questions about the Lieberman choice, the
rest of the black political establishment has lined up behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest source of concern about his record centers on
affirmative action. On Tuesday, Lieberman said he regretted what he
characterized as a naive expression of support back in 1995 for
Proposition 209, the California ballot initiative that did away
with racial and gender preferences in the California public sector.
</P>
<P>
   Both Tom Wood, the co-author of 209, and Ward Connerly, the
black businessman who led the successful effort to enact it, said
they thought Lieberman's explanation -- that he didn't understand
the implications of what he was saying -- is disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   But Wood acknowledges, as Lieberman now brags, that he has
consistently voted to defend affirmative action in the Senate.
Lieberman said he shared the Clinton and Gore sentiment that
affirmative action should be ``mended not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman has also been criticized for supporting the
experimental use of school vouchers in order to offer what he
described as a ``lifeline'' to poor students trapped in lousy
schools. But, while most black leaders oppose vouchers, they are an
idea that polls have indicated blacks as well as whites tend to
favor.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance before the Black Caucus, Lieberman noted, as
Clinton did in his convention speech the night before, that he was
a Freedom Rider,helping to register blacks in Mississippi in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   But Dyson said, ``Too many people point to their glorious past
to cover up their problematic present.'' And, fairly or not, his
record may suggest comparisons with those of influential Jewish
neoconservatives whose intellectual trajectory has taken them from
'60s liberalism to contemporary conservatism, particularly on
issues of race.
</P>
<P>
   Conflict over ``racial quotas'' -- which most everyone agrees
are bad, though they may sharply disagree on when and whether they
exist -- has proved to be the fulcrum of that controversy, and has
helped to fuel some tension over the years between blacks and Jews
(many of whom continue to support affirmative action).
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The first voice raised in criticism of the Lieberman choice came
from Lee Alcorn, the head of the Dallas NAACP, who said Jews could
not be trusted because of their obssession with money (he was
immediately fired by the national NAACP), and Nation of Islam
minister Louis Farrakhan, who wondered whether Lieberman's firt
loyalty would be to Israel or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has been critical, demanding that Lieberman reassure
black voters of his commitment on racial justice issues. While many
other members of the black caucus sat on the dais with Lieberman
Tuesday, Waters sat in the front row. Early in his remarks,
Lieberman noted that it was Waters' birthday and led the singing of
``Happy Birthday.'' Afterward, Waters joined him on stage and they
briefly held hands.
</P>
<P>
   James Clyburn, who chairs the Congressional Black Caucus, and Al
Edwards, the chair of the DNC Black Caucus, said they already had
been reassured by Lieberman and enthusiastically back his
nomination. Many black leaders followed the lead of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, who recalled the historical alliance of blacks and Jews in
the civil rights movement, and suggested that breaking the barrier
against Jews holding national office would hasten the day a black
might serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't be far behind,'' said Eleanor Holmes Norton, the
District of Columbia's non-voting delegate in Congress, who
introduced Lieberman at the Black Caucus meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   One source of tension between blacks and Jews in recent decades
has been how successful Jews as a group have been in America since
the Holocaust, compared with the continuing struggle of many blacks
in a nation that was the source and site of the slavery that some
call ``the Black Holocaust.''
</P>
<P>
   Bositis said he thinks Lieberman's being a Jew may contribute to
his problems with some black voters.
</P>
<P>
   A national survey of black and white Americans by the Joint
Center last year found that 39 percent of blacks felt Jews have too
much influence. Only 19 percent of white respondents felt the same.
Those feelings among blacks were, interestingly, strongest in the
Northeast and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lynch, a veteran political organizer from New York who is
vice chair of the national Democratic Party, said he thought some
people were attempting to stir black-Jewish animosities to
undermine the Democratic ticket, but that it would not work.
``Lieberman vs. (Republican vice presidential nominee Richard)
Cheney? No comparison,'' said Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Cora Masters Barry, wife of former Washington Mayor Marion
Barry, agreed. She is directing voter registration efforts for the
National Coalition on Black Civic Participation and for the Million
Family March that Farrakhan has called for Washington in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are so high, any reservations they may have about
Lieberman are going to be neutralized,'' said Barry. For starters,
she said, while in Congress Cheney voted against a resolution
calling for Nelson Mandela's freedom. And, she said, with the death
penalty so frequently invoked in Texas, ``Gov. Bush fries an
African-American a month.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think we are going to state that?'' said Barry.
``We're going to get down with it. We have to take the gloves
off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
