<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2619 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIAN-SUBMARINE-BOS     08-15 1400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-SUBMARINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER HAMPERS RESCUE OF RUSSIAN SUBMARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With oxygen dwindling aboard a stricken Russian
submarine and the frantic tapping of SOS by the trapped sailors
inside growing faint, rescue vessels Tuesday braved an icy Arctic
gale to launch a desperate undersea rescue mission.
</P>
<P>
   But the rescue efforts were thwarted repeatedly by the foul
weather, and the outlook for saving the 116 sailors trapped 354
feet below the surface was growing bleak, Russian navy officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is that there are still people alive, and they are
signaling SOS,'' said Admiral Vladimir Kuroyedov, the chief of
Russia's navy. ``What remains is our hope, which leaves us fewer
and fewer chances every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The tapping has been the only way the crew of the Kursk, one of
Russia's most modern submarines, have been able to communicate
since an accident during naval exercises last weekend forced them
to shut down the reactor, sending the craft to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The drama in the Barents Sea took on a increasingly grim cast
Tuesday as Admiral Kuroyedov confirmed that the first two
compartments of the submarine had been flooded at the outset by
what appeared to have been an explosion on board. Normally, 60
percent of the crew and most of the commanders on Oscar-2 class
submarines like the Kursk are in these two compartments, although
naval officials said they still do not know whether there had been
any casualties on board.
</P>
<P>
   A navy spokesman said one rescue attempt had failed once because
of a 30-knot winds and 12-foot waves on the surface. The storm,
typical August weather far above the Arctic circle in the Barents
Sea, hampered efforts to lower a rescue capsule to make contact
with the hatch of the stricken sub.
</P>
<P>
   Navy analysts said the most difficult task, maneuvering the
capsule to latch on to one of the submarine's cargo hatches, was
complicated further by strong currents on the sea floor and the
position of the Kursk, which is resting on the bottom at a 60
degree angle. That caused the capsule to slide off as soon as it
made contact.
</P>
<P>
   As the weather improved slightly, the capsule was lowered again
late Tuesday, but Navy spokesman Igor Dygalo said there was no word
on whether the attempt had been any more successful. It it failed,
Kuroyedov said, the backup plan was to try to lift the crippled
vessel to the surface by strapping 400-ton pontoons to both sides
and inflating them under water with highly pressurized air.
</P>
<P>
   The race to save the 107-man crew, along with nine senior
officers of Russia's Northern Fleet who were on board to observe
the exercises, became all the more desperate when the Russian navy
disclosed that the accident had occurred Saturday, not Sunday, as
officials had earlier reported.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency air supply on the Kursk is designed to last for
five days, meaning that in the best case scenario _ assuming that
no air escaped during the as yet unexplained explosion that caused
the accident _ the supply would run out Wednesday. However, Admiral
Kuroyedov said he did not expect the air to run out until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the crew's woes is the likelihood that the backup
system that purifies the air on the vessel in an emergency has most
likely stopped functioning, said one former submarine captain who
has been following the submarine drama. The rising carbon dioxide
level from the crew's own exhalations would make it harder for the
men on board to help rescuers _ if they are able to successfully
complete the tricky docking maneuver with the submarine _ to open
hatches and prepare themselves for the grueling ascent, which takes
up to seven hours to avoid decompression sickness, or ``the
bends.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the attempt is successful, it would not be possible to
rescue the entire crew. The rescue capsule Russia is using can only
carry up to 20 crew members at a time.
</P>
<P>
   This led the former submarine captain, who spoke on condition he
not be identified, to suggest that at least some of the crew would
not make it _ assuming that none had died in the explosion or
during the subsequent flooding of the two compartments.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the survivors, he said, would probably have been in the
aft of the submarine, although some may be trapped in the fifth
compartment in the middle of the vessel. Reaching them from the
stern would mean going through the compartment which holds the
Kursk's two reactors. Although they have been shut down, the former
captain said, the reactors are probably not being cooled, since the
pumps that do this have most likely been damaged, meaning that
temperatures in the compartment could be higher than 170 degrees
Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to have been an explosion in the torpedo
compartment in the nose of the submarine, sending it crashing to
the sea bottom, Admiral Kuroyedov said. Earlier he had said that
the Kursk had collided with something.
</P>
<P>
   Russian state television showed Kuroyedov pointing out damage to
the bow of the craft on a diagram that showed a torpedo hatch wide
open on the starboard, or right, side and damage to the sail, or
conning tower, that rises out of the rounded hull. The illustration
also showed bits of the vessel were scattered on the sea floor
outside the port side. Other naval officials said it appeared that
water was getting into the sub.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion inside the torpedo chamber, which contains
conventional warheads, would probably have caused extensive
casualties in the nearby main compartment and the command center,
analysts said. But officials were giving little firm information
about the cause of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will know when they get at least one survivor up to the
surface,'' the former captain said.
</P>
<P>
   As the navy briefed relatives of the men on the stricken boat
behind closed doors at a naval base in Murmansk, the head of the
Russian Orthodox Church, Patriach Alexy, called for prayers for the
crew at a service in Moscow. In Kursk, the southern Russian city
which gave the submarine its name and has proudly sent dozens of
draftees to serve on the vessel, NTV television showed anxious
relatives waiting for news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to hope this terrible nightmare will end,'' said
Valentina Staroseltseva, who said her son was on the distressed
submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk, one of eight giant aircraft-carrier destroying
Oscar-2 class submarines in the Russian fleet, was commissioned
only five years ago and is considered the pinnacle of Russian
submarine technology. Over the past decade, Russia's once mighty
nuclear submarine fleet has deteriorated with neglect as the
military budget was slashed, but many naval specialists expressed
surprise that this particular boat sank the way it did.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Arkady Yefanov, who commanded another Oscar-2 submarine
from 1987 to 1993, told NTV television that the Kursk was designed
to float to the surface in the event of an accident, even after
sustaining a hit from a torpedo. He said it was odd that the Kursk
went to the bottom and that it failed to launch its own rescue
capsule, which is capable of taking up to 130 men to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The chief designer of the submarine, Igor Baranov, was quoted by
Russian news agencies as saying ``something extraordinary beyond
the imagination of an engineer'' must have happened to the
submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of Russia's parliament, Gennady Seleznyov, called on
the military to seek assistance from abroad, but Moscow has so far
declined offers of help from the United States and Britain. Both
countries have miniature submarines that are designed to rescue
crew members from sunken subs. Kuroyedov said a group of naval
officers would go to NATO headquarters in Brussels Wednesday to see
what help the alliance could offer.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has said the stricken submarine poses no threat to the
environment, as it was carrying no nuclear weapons and the reactor
that powers it had been shut down. In Norway, which closely
monitors Russian submarines operating off its coastal waters in the
Barents, said there was no sign of a radiation leak. Russian
officials said that the main worry now was saving the crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to absolutely find out the situation on board,''
Dygalo, the navy spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
