<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LABOR LEADERS HERE EMPHASIZE AGREEMENTS WITH GORE
 &HT;    By WILLIAM HERSHEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When President Clinton passed the Democratic torch
to Al Gore in Michigan on Tuesday, Clinton went out of his way to
praise a labor leader who until last week was anything but a
Clinton-Gore pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank Steve Yokich and the UAW for being here,'' said
Clinton, singling out the president of the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question for Gore as he arrives here Wednesday to
claim the presidential nomination is whether Yokich, the UAW and
the rest of the nation's nearly 16.5 million union members will be
with him on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the 4,368 delegates to the Democratic
National Convention are union members.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., his running mate, are
counting on union members for grass-roots help in getting out the
vote this fall, particularly in battleground states such as Ohio
and Michigan with big union memberships.
</P>
<P>
   There has been virtually no mention here at the Democratic
National Convention of the issue that has cooled relations between
labor and the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Labor opposes normalizing trade relations with China, but
Clinton and Gore won House approval in May of a bill to do just
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The China vote was terrible,'' said William Burga, president
of the AFL-CIO in Ohio, where there are about 1 million union
members. Burga is a convention delegate.
</P>
<P>
   When Richard Trumka, the sometimes fiery national AFL-CIO
secretary treasurer, spoke to the convention Tuesday, he didn't
mention trade but gushed about the ties that bind Gore and American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats know and Al Gore knows working people are the engine
that propels the American economy,'' Trumka said
</P>
<P>
   The national AFL-CIO endorsed Gore for president last October,
contending that the issues they agreed on far outweighed their
disagreement over trade.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW withheld its endorsement until last week, and even
flirted with the idea of backing consumer advocate Ralph Nader,
who's running under the Green Party banner.
</P>
<P>
   Burga, the Ohio AFL-CIO president, said his greatest fear is not
that union members will back George W. Bush but that they will sit
out the election, as many of them did in 1994 when Rep
</P>
</TEXT>
