<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENDANT-AVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENDANT'S MOVE TO RE - AQUIRE AVIS LEAVES THE MARKET UNIMPRESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Silverman, the chief executive of the Cendant Corp., made
a bid Tuesday to regain control of the Avis Group Holdings Inc.,
the nation's second largest rental car company, at a price the
market immediately deemed too low.
</P>
<P>
   The bid marks his return to the acquisition trail following two
years of accounting problems that grew out of his biggest merger,
with CUC International.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman offered $29 a share or a nearly 14 percent premium
over Avis' previous-day closing price, but investors bid up the
shares of Avis $5 to $30.50, their highest point in more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was, in the words of Robert P. Napoli of ABN
Amro a ``ridiculously low'' bid for a leader in an extremely
undervalued industry. Before the offer, Napoli said he had expected
Avis shares to be trading at $52 a year in 12 to 18 months; Jeffrey
A. Diamond of Credit Suisse First Boston had a target price of $43.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole sector is under appreciated,'' said David Riedel of
Salomon Smith Barney. ``It's trading at 6.5 times next year's
earnings compared with 28 times earnings for the S&AMP;P index as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Faulhaber, a spokesman for Avis, of Garden City, N.Y.,
said the board would be meeting in the ``next day or so to
consider'' the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal would bring back control over Avis to
Silverman after a four-year hiatus. Through a predecessor of
Cendant, HFS, he took over Avis in 1996, then spun it off as a
separate company a year later. But Silverman's organization
retained a stake of 18 percent and the Avis brand for which it
receives 4 percent of the rental car company's annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman's latest overture, Riedel said, could well serve as a
catalyst for higher share prices for the whole car rental business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very misunderstood business,'' said Diamond of First
Boston. ``The market thinks of it as highly cyclical like the
airlines and lodging.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and other analysts said Avis and the other big car rental
companies like Hertz, the industry leader, National and the
Dollar-Thrifty Group have developed considerable flexibility that
should help them through an economic downturn since the days when
many of them were operated as subsidiaries of the big car
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Avis and the others, the analysts said, have deals that permit
them to return cars to the manufacturers without penalty when
business slows down and they have implemented computer programs,
similar to those used by the airlines, that enable them to shift
cars and prices to different locations according to demand.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, Riedel said, annual revenue growth
for the industry leaders has averaged 17 percent; net income has
been growing at 40 percent and return on equity has jumped to 18
percent from 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very strong, profitable industry,'' Riedel said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman built an empire of well-known franchise companies like
Holiday Inn and Century 21 real estate through a series of
acquisitions. He joined his company, HFS Inc., with CUC
International, an online telephone and shopping services company,
to form Cendant in late 1997. A few months later, on April 15,
1998, Cendant announced the discovery of widespread accounting
irregularities in CUC units.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Cendant has agreed to a $2.8 million settlement with
shareholders and three former CUC executives have pleaded guilty to
inflating profits to keep share prices high.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman suggested last month that the worst was past and that
he was on the hunt for acquisitions to inject new vigor into
Cendant. The Avis bid is his first move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
