<SLUG> BC-GOTUIT-SONGCATCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
START-UP TO OFFER SOFTWARE FOR RECORDING RADIO BROADCASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's more fuel for the raging debate over free music:
</P>
<P>
   Gotuit Media Inc., an Andover, Mass. start-up with high-profile
backers, is raising money to launch its SongCatcher software, which
lets users record songs from their favorite radio stations directly
to their computers.
</P>
<P>
   Gotuit announced its angel round of venture capital Tuesday:
$2.1 million from a group that includes Berkshires entrepreneur Bo
Peabody. Gotuit was founded a year ago by Jim Logan, former chief
executive of MicroTouch Systems Inc., a $150 million touch-screen
maker.
</P>
<P>
   Logan said his company is not following in the controversial
footsteps of Napster Inc., which lets users download and share
music files over the Internet _ a practice the record industry
calls stealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a copyright perspective, we feel we're on pretty solid
ground here,'' Logan said. After all, people have been able to tape
songs from the radio and programs from television for years.
</P>
<P>
   Gotuit's software works like a stereo or a VCR and is meant to
create a kind of personal jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   Music lovers can plug a home radio into a PC's audio or
microphone jack to record music. The SongCatcher software,
available free on the Web, periodically fetches data from Gotuit to
identify the songs and artists and indexes the material.
</P>
<P>
   The recorded songs are delivered to the users e-mailbox and can
be deleted or saved easily, the company said. There is a
``NeverAgain'' button, so listeners can request that a certain song
or artist never be recorded in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Sutin, a lawyer in New York who is with the law firm
Greenberg Traurig, said Gotuit will avoid the Napster problem as
long as users record songs for personal use only. Sharing music
files is the practice that has angered the record companies and
many artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all they're doing is making (songs) available for
time-shifting and personal use, then it appears that it's probably
legal,'' Sutin said. But if there's file-sharing in the plans, he
added, ``They can expect to have trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotuit has hired Mark Fischer as its lawyer. He is an expert on
recording-industry law at the Boston law firm Palmer &AMP; Dodge and
has been widely quoted on the Napster battle.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Gotuit says it plans to offer a service that
lets users download their radio recordings to portable players.
</P>
<P>
   Logan calls SongCatcher ``artist friendly'' and says users can
click a button to purchase CDs when they hear songs they like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this might open up music to audiences that don't have
time to listen to the radio,'' he said, particularly
thirtysomethings who may be losing touch with new bands.
</P>
<P>
   Gotuit is also tackling the TV market with its software. It's
rolling out the same indexing capability for television that it's
introducing for radio, so that viewers can scan through recordings
on a set-top box to find the shows they want to see and delete the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   The company's board includes a slew of industry experts, among
them Harvard Law School professor Terry Fisher; Quantum Corp.
cofounder Joel Harrison; and Brian Zisk of iCast, who is also
cofounder of Green Witch Internet Radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-PROTESTS16-COX     08-15 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTESTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROTESTERS, POLICE TRADE CHARGES AFTER CLASH
 &HT;    By MIKE WAGNER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ricky Manuel pointed to the three-inch cut above
his eye and glared across the street at two police officers
patrolling outside the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the cops hadn't charged into the crowd with their guns,
rubber bullets and horses, none of that stuff would have
happened,'' said Manuel, a 24-year-old protester from New York
City. ``Everything was cool, and then all hell broke lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Guay, one of the officers in Manuel's view, shook his head
in disagreement at the accusation that police acted too quickly
when a Monday night demonstration turned violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were throwing large rocks, bottles, signs and setting
things on fire,'' said Guay, a Los Angeles officer for seven years.
``It's easy to blame us when something happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute clash between protesters and police continued to
be a hot issue Tuesday for many people at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was a day of peaceful demonstrations for more than 8,000
protesters until the melee erupted just as President Clinton took
the podium for his convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-authoritarian Los Angeles band Rage Against the Machine
had just concluded its concert outside Staples Center when several
demonstrators climbed the 12-foot fence keeping them away from the
convention facility.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they told the crowd it had 15 minutes to disperse,
and after two more warnings began moving in.
</P>
<P>
   Officers, some on horseback, used pepper spray and rubber
bullets to disperse the crowd. Some of the 300 protesters responded
by throwing pylons, cans, bottles, asphalt and a
handicapped-parking sign. Other signs were set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   At least four people were hurt, none seriously. Most convention
delegates were kept inside the Staples Center until the protesters
were cleared away and there was no threat of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Video taken by an amateur photographer, aired on local
television, captured one incident where several officers charged
one man who didn't appear to be a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were already walking away when the police came
rushing in. It was ridiculous,'' said Marie Hammonds, a 34-year-old
demonstrator from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police officials didn't comment on the video, but
defended the actions of their officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of the crowd inside the area became very
violent,'' said Cmdr. David Kalish, spokesman for the Los Angeles
Police Department. ``It became necessary for our officers to move
in.''
</P>
<P>
   A few people who found themselves in the middle of the protest
after leaving the convention also defended the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was out of control when we were walking by, and when
they're acting like that, the police had do something,'' said
Audrey Love, a 60-year-old delegate from West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators earlier this month also protested at the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, but police were
able to set up barriers at least a mile from the convention. In Los
Angeles, the area designated for protesters is about 50 feet from
the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials tried to keep the protesters farther away,
but lost a battle in court.
</P>
<P>
   Another judge blocked police from making any preconvention raids
on the demonstrators' headquarters to seize protest materials. The
American Civil Liberties Union, accusing police of harassing
demonstrators, had sought the court order.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the brief clash, the convention demonstration was a far
cry from other high-profile riots, such as the anti-globalization
protests at the World Trade Organization conference in Seattle last
year. In that demonstration, protesters went on a rampage on city
streets and caught unprepared police by surprise. No one was
killed, but scores were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles demonstrators represent a diverse collection of
causes and political stripes. Many are protesting corporate
globalization, the death penalty, the and treatment of the
homeless. One small group was even calling for an end to women
breast-feeding their children, saying it was ``immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon's demonstrations were calm, and included fewer
than 100 protestors for most of the day. But police say more
violence is possible Wednesday at a large demonstration against
``police brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it stays peaceful, but that one could be a lot worse
than what's happened so far,'' Guay said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
