<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-LOBBYISTS-NYT &LR;      08-15 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LOBBYISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBYISTS HEDGE THEIR BETS BY SUPPORTING BOTH PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On Tuesday night, the lobbying firm Patton Boggs
hosted a cocktail hour and supper buffet at the Sunset Room in
Hollywood. Not much of a surprise: The firm's chairman, Thomas H.
Boggs Jr., is the son of the legendary Democratic congressional
leader, Hale Boggs of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Republican convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago,
Patton Boggs also had a very visible presence, sending a dozen
partners and associates _ all recently hired Republican lobbyists.
The firm hosted two lavish receptions in Philadelphia, including a
party honoring the Republican Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the same lobbyists who helped underwrite the Republican
convention are out in force in Los Angeles. With close races
anticipated for the White House and control of the House of
Representatives, the brigades from Washington's K Street, the
corridor filled with capital lobbyists and lawyers, are being more
careful than ever to cover both party bases with their largess.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyists' active schedules at both conventions represent a
growing trend of ``pragmatic political donors'' who aggressively
court both parties to insure they will have access and influence no
matter who emerges victorious in November. The urgency of such a
strategy is even greater this year, as lobbyists confront the
possibility that new parties will take control of both the White
House and Congress next January.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic firms first hurried to hire well-connected
Republicans shortly after Republicans won control of the Congress
in 1994. This year, however, lobbyists say they have noticed that
the city's largest firms are working hard to have a large presence
at both national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clearly an advantage when approaching possible
clients to have a political bookend to my Democratic
affiliations,'' said Lanny J. Davis, a Patton Boggs partner who
worked as a special counsel in the Clinton White House. Just
recently, Davis said a new client was pleased that he and a
Republican colleague _ Benjamin L. Ginsberg, a firm lobbyist and
the counsel to Gov. George W. Bush's campaign _ would work together
on a legislative issue.
</P>
<P>
   Patton Boggs has company among powerhouse lobbying firms who
have invested heavily in both national conventions to ensure
continued access to party leaders and to court and impress clients
with their bipartisan clout. Two other predominantly Democratic
lobbying and law firms _ Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld, which
hosted a brunch at the Bevery Hills Hotel on Tuesday in honor of
the firm's founder and former Democratic Party chairman Robert
Strauss, and Verner, Liipfert, Bernard, McPherson &AMP; Hand _ are also
sponsoring receptions here, as they did in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Verner Liipfert gave a late-night party for
the Democratic National Committee at the Mondrian Hotel's Sky Bar
on Sunset Boulevard in West Hollywood. Two weeks ago, in
Philadelphia, the firm sponsored a tribute to former Sen. Bob Dole
and Elizabeth Dole. Dole, the Republicans' 1996 presidential
nominee, is special counsel at Verner Liipfert.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's bipartisan roster of senior partners includes former
Sens. Lloyd Bentsen and George Mitchell and former Govs. James J.
Blanchard of Michigan and Ann W. Richards of Texas, all Democrats.
It also includesformer Sen. Daniel R. Coats and Leonard Garment,
the former White House counsel in the Nixon administration,both
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beverly Hills Hotel on Tuesday, a veritable who's who of
the Democratic establishment turned out for a brunch of bagels and
fresh fruit in honor of Robert Strauss, who built both the
Democratic Party and Akin, Gump into financial powerhouses. Milling
around a large reception room were an assortment of Democratic
pols, including the Senate minority leader, Thomas Daschle, Sen.
John Edwards, former Democratic National Committee co-chairman
Donald Fowler and former Commerce Secretary Mickey Kantor.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, a squad of Republican lawyers and lobbyists
hired in the past few years by Akin, Gump, led by former Rep. Bill
Paxon and Frank J. Donatelli, a longtime Republican political
operative, co-sponsored receptions for Republicans with their
clients.
</P>
<P>
   David Geanacopoulos, a lobbyist in Akin, Gump's Washington
office, said the bipartisan effort is a growing trend at most big
firms. ``Clients want to know that you have both Democrats and
Republicans who can help them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Patton Boggs, a firm with deep Democratic connections, has been
especially aggressive in attempting to transform itself into a
bipartisan lobbying shop. Besides Ginsberg, the firm also hired
Brian C. Lopina, the firmer director of governmental affairs for
the Christian Coalition; Darryl D. Nirenberg, the fomrer chief of
staff to Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina; and Edward J.
Newberry, who worked for seven years for Rep. Frank R. Wolf, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Partners and associates at the three lobbying firms have
increased the level of their political giving to Republicans in
this election cycle, which began in January 1999. The political
action committee for Akin Gump, has even given 54 percent of its
$296,000 in donations to Republicans. Verner Liipfert's political
action committee gave 55 percent of its $161,000 in donations to
Democrats. Patton Boggs does not have a political action committee
but its members have given $390,000 in campaign contributions this
election cycle, 63 percent to Democrats, 36 per cent to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lobbyists are also bulking up their Democratic
credentials. The United States Chamber of Commerce, the nation's
largest business lobby, reflects the trend toward ambidextrous
convention entertaining. In 1996, the Chamber sent its top
officials to the GOP convention in San Diego; it did not
participate at all in that year's Democratic gathering in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the Chamber has sponsored parties at both
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great place for us to be,'' said Thomas J. Donohue,
the Chamber's president. ``My contention is when all the interest
groups and business leaders and media have moved out here, I'd be a
damn fool if I didn't bring my assets to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Washington's lobbying firms are becoming bipartisan.
Some are fiercely partisan, like Barbour Griffth &AMP; Rogers, a
Republican firm whose leaders brag that they do not give a single
dollar to a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works for us,'' said Ed Rogers, one of the firm's partners.
``We have made the conscious decision to be that way and make a
virtue out of it. When we are on the hill or dealing with an
elected official, we want them to know there is not someone down
the hall from us committed to removing them from office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
