<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-15 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STILL A BABY BOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL KRUGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's economic miracle _ which Bill Clinton claimed as
vindication in his Monday speech, but George W. Bush insists was an
act of God _ didn't begin when Clinton took office in 1993. And no,
it didn't begin with Ronald Reagan either. In fact, it didn't
really start until 1996 or so. In other words, this boom is still
in its infancy; and like all infants, it remains vulnerable.
Clinton's greatest achievement is that during his second term he
avoided the fiscal irresponsibility that might have strangled our
``new economy'' at birth _irresponsibility that his opponent in the
1996 election would have practiced. Will his successor emulate his
example? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton prefers to think that everything good that
happened these past eight years was his own doing. You can see why:
Republicans confidently predicted that his 1993 tax increase would
produce disaster _ a recession, an even worse budget deficit. So
Clinton has an understandable urge to crow over the fact that even
in his first term things turned out pretty well.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking analysis here, not poetic justice; and the
truth is that growth from 1992 to 1996 _ like growth from 1982 to
1989 _ was just an ordinary business cycle recovery, with no sign
of an upturn in the economy's sluggish long-term trend. And
business cycles have very little to do with the administration that
happens to be in office; they are determined mainly by the actions
of the Federal Reserve, not the president. Jimmy Carter and George
Bush got blamed for the recessions that happened on their watches,
Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton got credit for the recoveries that
happened on theirs; but neither the credit nor the blame was
deserved.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was only in 1996 _ even as the right was comparing Clinton's
recovery unfavorably with Reagan's _ that things really began to
change. Productivity, which had grown at a snail's pace for two
decades, began to accelerate _ and accelerate, and accelerate, with
recent numbers so high they take one's breath away. Unemployment
began falling to levels not seen since the inflationary years of
the late 1960s _ but this time without inflation. And from these
fundamentals many other good things flowed, from falling poverty
and plunging crime rates to a record budget surplus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did the Clinton-Gore administration create this miracle? Of
course not. The best guess is that a long process of technological
innovation finally reached critical mass, creating new
opportunities that American business was uniquely ready to exploit.
But the right question isn't whether the policies of this
administration gave birth to the new economy; it is whether
different leadership would have killed it. Not to put too fine a
point on it: What would have happened if Bob Dole had won? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've been going back over Dole's economic program _ which,
remember, was centered on huge tax cuts _ and trying to calculate
what today's economy would look like if those tax cuts had been
enacted. One clear conclusion is that even if the economy had grown
as fast as it actually did, the federal budget _ certainly the
non-Social-Security budget, and probably the whole shebang _ would
still be in deficit. And it seems to me that our morale, not to
mention business confidence, would be a lot lower if that budget
were still out of control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the economy surely wouldn't have grown as fast as it
did. Our soaring productivity didn't come out of thin air; an
important, perhaps crucial ingredient was an amazing surge in
business investment, especially in information technology. And this
surge didn't have to happen. In a full-employment economy like that
of America in the late 1990s, budget deficits mean that the
government is borrowing money that would otherwise have been
invested. This drives up interest rates, depresses asset prices and
crimps business plans. Had Dole's tax cuts been enacted, the
resulting deficits would surely have crowded out a lot of
investment _ and quite possibly have crowded out the productivity
boom.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago America faced a choice between sober, sensible
fiscal discipline and huge, irresponsible tax cuts. We chose
discipline, and were rewarded with growth beyond our wildest
dreams. So why would anyone today propose exactly the kind of
irresponsibility we were lucky to avoid four years ago?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-MIDEAST-305     08-15 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-MIDEAST-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN PRESIDENT PROPOSES PLAN TO RESOLVE JERUSALEM DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ In the face of seemingly intractable
separatist and sectarian conflicts of his own, President
Abdurrahman Wahid plunged into Middle East politics Tuesday,
offering a complicated formula he said could resolve the deadlock
over the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attempt to break the ice,'' he told reporters,
referring to the collapse last month of Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks at Camp David. ``If they invite Indonesia to participate in
the discussions, that will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The overture was the latest surprise move by the unpredictable
president, coming in the middle of a fast-paced game of domestic
power politics in which he is battling a wide array of opponents in
a special parliamentary session.
</P>
<P>
   He offered his power-sharing ideas after meeting in Jakarta on
Monday with former Prime Minister Shimon Peres of Israel, an old
friend. Wahid plans to meet on Wednesday with the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, who is on a tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting his own analysis of the Camp David talks, Wahid said
the problem was that ``only one kind of sovereignty was discussed''
for Jerusalem, which both Israel and the Palestinians claim as
their capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view we'd better differentiate between administrative
sovereignty, which will be in the hands of the Israelis, and
political sovereignty,'' which he said would be under control of a
seven-member committee.
</P>
<P>
   Such a committee, he said, would be made up of Egypt, Jordan,
Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian entity and Israel as well as the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel had offered
the Palestinians limited control over Arab areas of East Jerusalem,
which Israel occupied in the 1967 Middle East War. But Arafat
demanded full sovereignty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since becoming president 10 months ago, Wahid has taken a
particular interest in foreign affairs _ which is not shared by
most people here _ traveling to 30 countries, sometimes on the spur
of the moment and without a clear agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, under pressure from his opponents in Parliament, he
agreed to hand over some of his day-to-day duties to his vice
president, Megawati Sukarnoputri. He said this would free him to
concentrate more on foreign policy and suggested that Indonesia
could play a greater role in mediating international conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   His approach to Indonesia's own separatist and religious
conflicts, including recent violent episodes in the Maluku Islands,
has been one of mediation and conciliation rather than
confrontation. In some cases his efforts have had only limited
success; in others they have been disastrous failures.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, the world's most populous Muslim nation with 210
million people, has not played a significant role in the Middle
East in the past. It has never recognized Israel and has supported
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But Wahid, a moderate Muslim cleric, has a longstanding interest
in the Middle East and has called for normalizing relations with
Israel. He studied for a time in Egypt and for years has had a
friendly relationship with Peres.
</P>
<P>
   As one of his first acts as president, Wahid defied public
sentiment here by opening trade relations with Israel. Following
widespread criticism, he said formal diplomatic relations would
have to wait until the peace efforts with the Palestinians are
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid signaled his intention to become involved in Middle
Eastern politics on Saturday, when he called for an end to the
trade embargo that was imposed on Iraq after the Persian Gulf war
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see the blockade on Iraq lifted soon,'' he
said during a meeting with President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela.
Chavez visited Jakarta after a trip to Baghdad, where he became the
first head of state since the end of the war to meet with the Iraqi
leader, Saddam Hussein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
