<HEADER>
A2634 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-15 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMA IS ALL ON THE SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   You didn't have to like Dick
Cheney to still wince at him being called boringly steady and
unexciting. Here, the guy agrees to run for vice president and
right away they call him white-bread and a grind. Like he'll never
make Prom King.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Both presidential candidates have been faulted for not being
exactly magnetic, which if you're only electing on personality,
makes it a race between Dull and Duller. But how important is it,
really, for a president, or for that matter, a mayor or city
councilwoman, to be irresistible?
</P>
<P>
   It's nice, of course, when that happens. It enlivens the budget
hearings. But haven't we got enough professionally cute and clever
people to allow a little blandness in our leaders?
</P>
<P>
   Government is not supposed to be full of cutups. Washington,
D.C., is not known as a fun place. Those people are there to do
serious work for us. We give them lots of power and money to keep
us out of nuclear war and ensure that all Americans get a fair
shake. They don't have to be TV personalities.
</P>
<P>
   We don't require other bureaucrats to charm us. You walk into
the post office and are lucky to get the clerk with the pony tail
who's always in a good mood. But if he never had stamps and your
package didn't make it to Denver, his smile wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need hip people running the country. We need good
people. Maybe it would be different if the White House really
worked like ``West Wing,'' the TV show where the staff is witty and
stylish, although Martin Sheen's president does get to be a bit of
a square.
</P>
<P>
   Serious and intense are probably good qualities for the
day-to-day running of a country. You imagine that some days the job
is so overwhelming a presidential head must ache over all the
things that need fixing, and couldn't come up with a witty line
even with Robin Williams whispering in its ear.
</P>
<P>
   Cute candidates are supposed to lure women to the voting booth,
as if all you need to get the girls is to have a straight nose and
nice hair. Give us a wink and we'll let you attack Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Bush tried that with Dan Quayle, foolishly thinking
his young good looks would turn fence-sitting women into Republican
groupies.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Republicans, if Cheney is a bad choice it should
have nothing to do with him being stuffy. It should be because he
thinks guns are no biggie and still believes that women shouldn't
control their own bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Personality contests get in the way of the real thing. Polls
show that only one in four Americans can articulate what the
candidates really stand for. But we know some voters don't like one
candidate's eyes and some don't like the other's wooden speech and
worry that neither squeezes out much charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Charisma is frosting. We've got three months to figure out
what's inside the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, charisma has its limits. Joe Eszterhas, who's written a
sleazy tale about the Clinton scandal, compares Clinton to a rock
star. He calls Clinton a dude, a lousy thing to say about a leader.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
