<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2635 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSEUMS-ON-WHEELS-$AD     08-15 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUMS-ON-WHEELS-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOARD FOR A MUSEUM THAT ROLLS ON AND ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Okla, Tenn., Ga., Kan., Mich., Fla., Minn., Nev., Ill.,
Ind., Va., N.M., Pa., Calif.)   (For release Sunday, August 20)   By JONATHAN MANDELL  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Jeff Jewell, from Watertown, Tenn., (population
2,000), had never attended an art exhibition, and he had boarded a
train only once before in his life, when Artrain rolled into town.
When it left after a week, he left with it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two months and three towns later, he was helping to set up
here, along with the other members of Artrain's staff, who also got
hooked in their hometowns. Kim Kapalka, the tour manager, had
hopped aboard in Lawrence, Kan., leaving her job at a library.
</P>
<P>
   Since it began 29 years ago, Artrain USA, one of the oldest of
an increasing number of museums on wheels, has brought original
artworks by Picasso and Warhol, Calder and O'Keeffe, Rockwell and
Rauschenberg, to more than 600 towns and cities in 44 states. It
has gone to big cities like Baltimore, Detroit, Pittsburgh and
Washington, but more often its destination isn't even a whistle
stop anymore _ places like Zeeland, Mich.; Plant City, Fla., and
Parkers Prairie, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``All a community needs is railroad tracks,'' Kapalka said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell's official title is facility technician, which means he
does the heavy lifting. His folks back home kid him that he's a
modern-day carny. ``It is like the circus,'' he admitted. ``Just
move along, set something up, then get going again.''
</P>
<P>
   Becky Schutt doesn't see it that way. ``I prefer the rock tour
analogy,'' she said. Schutt, from New Jersey, signed up for Artrain
while she was attending the University of Michigan and it was
resting in Ann Arbor, its home base. ``I tell my friends, `I'm on
tour,''' she said, ``so it sounds like I'm a rock star.''
</P>
<P>
   She is in the right town at the moment for such a fantasy;
Athens is best known as the college town that gave birth to the
rock bands REM and the B-52s, a place where young people go to
become rock stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athens has always been very, very supportive of people
creating stuff,'' said Michael Stipe, an actual rock star (with
REM) and a former art student. He was standing with friends outside
the Flicker Bar, which was having an art opening _ some half-dozen
photographs on a wall. ``In the mid-'90s, people began coming out
as much for the art as for the music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Artrain was on railroad tracks near the University of Georgia's
Lamar Dodd School of Art, which has 60 full-time faculty and is
named after a painter, educator and long-time resident of Athens
who had two works in the Artrain exhibition. This was a major
reason the people of Athens, especially C.L. Morehead, a collector
who owns hundreds of Lamar Dodds, sponsored an Artrain stop here.
</P>
<P>
   Athens is not typical of the places Artrain visits; in most
towns, its exhibition is often the Big Cultural Event. But no town
is really typical, staff members say. ``It might all be small-town
America, but each town is different,'' said Sheila Debrunner.
Another staff member, Kelly Raymond, added, ``We're often in towns
much smaller than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond and Debrunner were in the first of the train's five
cars, where Debrunner was reading a light meter in front of ``Earth
Crust,'' a lithograph by Robert Rauschenberg as Raymond made
notations on a clipboard. They moved to Andy Warhol's silkscreen
``Moon Walk (1),'' then to an oil painting by Peter Max, some
watercolors by James Wyeth and finally to another car, this one
full of works on paper. They were making sure that the paintings
and drawings were not exposed to too much light; the rocking of the
train can sometimes rattle the carefully calibrated track lighting,
knocking it off kilter. The works of art themselves were all bolted
into the walls and fronted by Plexiglas at the beginning of the
tour more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   This helps protect them not only from possible damage but also
from vandalism and theft. Artrain's adherence to standard museum
practice in climate control (to keep a steady temperature and
humidity), the handling of art and security has enabled it to
attract some high quality art, much the same as that lent to any
museum; Artrain has no collection of its own.
</P>
<P>
   A few cars down, Kapalka, the tour manager, had unpacked gift
items and shelved them in the gift shop, which also serves as an
art studio. There, local artists demonstrated their skills, whether
painting or pottery making. Kapalka soon moved to the office, at
the end of the fourth car, and phoned ahead to make arrangements in
Woodward, Okla., a stop more than a month in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Jewell and Emily Hewitt were setting up a canopy in the
parking lot next to the train and raising flags on the sides of the
railroad cars. Hewitt's official title is facility manager; she is
the only one of the seven staff members who actually rides on the
train as it travels from town to town. She also lives in the little
red caboose for as long as three weeks at a stretch. The others
drive vans and stay in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   This is not fun time. ``I'm not a railroad buff,'' Hewitt said.
Having no locomotive itself, Artrain must rely on the kindness of
railroad companies to move it along their tracks. Only rarely does
a railroad connect two small towns directly, so Artrain must often
travel a painfully circuitous route with many delays. It is
completely normal for a 14-mile trip to take 6 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing about their life on the road _ traveling 11 months out
of 12, eating on the go, rarely knowing where they will be from
week to week, having no permanent place to live _ one begins to
think of the Artrain workers as a group of art-history hobos.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell, a 22-year-old computer science major working on Artrain
for the summer, was also one of the few on the staff without a
background in art history. And even he can't help being influenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few nights ago in my hotel room,'' he said, ``I got a little
bored, and I started doodling. I wouldn't have done that before. I
would have just watched TV.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Artrain USA bills itself as the only art museum on a train, but
there are an increasing number of such museums in vans, buses,
recreational vehicles and tractor-trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everyone seems to want one,'' said Lee Skolnick, an
architect who designed two Movable Museums for the American Museum
of Natural History in New York and is working on four more such
mobile museums. One is for a new collection of antiquities in Las
Vegas, Nev., another for a children's museum in Chicago; the others
will be based in Indiana and Beirut, Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, Va., last year, the Newseum, a museum about the
news media, introduced NewsCapade, a rolling exhibition of such
artifacts as a fragment of the Berlin Wall and Bill Gates'
autographed keyboard. The show is lugged by custom-designed trucks
to locations in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Most mobile museums travel within a limited region, often a
single state. The Museum of New Mexico sends out some of its
collection to rural areas in the state in a bus it calls the Van of
Enchantment. The Susquehanna Art Museum in Harrisburg travels the
state of Pennsylvania with a mobile museum it calls VanGo.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural History Museum of Los Angeles operates both an
Earthmobile, which looks at a coastal Native American culture, and
a Seamobile, about the marine sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The American Museum of Natural History's two mobile museums
travel within the city limits. ``We've been in Winnebagos since
1992,'' said Jenny Lando as she drove one of them to a community
festival in Two Coves Park playground in Astoria, Queens. The
vehicle, almost as long as a city bus, held an exhibition about
dinosaurs. ``But the museum has had movable museums for a long
time,'' Lando said. ``They started with a suitcase. They were on
motorcycles in the 1920s. In the 1930s and 1940s, they used
converted ambulances.''
</P>
<P>
   Artrain itself began small, as a temporary program of the
Michigan Council for the Arts with the aim of reaching rural areas
of that state. But demand, and a grant from the National Endowment
for the Arts, turned it into a nationwide nonprofit arts
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward mobile museums is partly a result of modern
technological advances. Vehicles can now come with better climate
control and security and portable interactive computers. It also
coincides with the renewed popularity of museums. ``People are
going to museums for more things than ever before, not just to see
objects; they've become in some ways akin to malls,'' Skolnick
said. ``So it's not so surprising that these institutions are
looking for new ways to reach their public.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that is new about the phenomenon, there is also
something old-fashioned about what is going on, especially on
Artrain. ``Some of the draw is just the excitement of boarding a
train, the nostalgia of that,'' said Jean Steppe, a staff member.
``About a quarter of our visitors are railroad buffs who get an
education in art sort of accidentally.''
</P>
<P>
   At Artrain's opening reception in Athens, the first of four days
here, staff members have changed from their work clothes to evening
wear and welcome the local VIPs to the exhibition, the
organization's 14th, entitled ``Artistry of Space.'' Scheduled to
tour for two more years, the show offers a selection of 78 artworks
on space travel from the hundreds that the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration has commissioned over the last four decades as
part of NASAs art program.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA had hundreds of cameras photographing every nut and bolt,
but there was something missing,'' said James Dean, a retired
federal official who flew down from Washington. ``You had all the
facts, but you didn't have any of the emotion.'' Dean started the
agency's art program 38 years ago and is now himself a painter with
works in the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artistry in Space'' harks back to a time when the space
program offered a new and exciting landscape for Americans to
explore, in the way that the trains offered Americans a fresh
landscape in the 19th century. Though the art in the exhibition is
varied _ one car is devoted entirely to abstract work _ paintings
like Attilla Hejja's ``Light Ship,'' which depicts the launching of
the Space Shuttle Challenger, recall the kind of detailed,
theatrical landscapes captured by 19th-century American artists
like Frederick Church. The fiery vapor, smoke and cloud bursting
from the booster rockets even bear some resemblance to the
billowing steam and smoke in 19th-century art featuring early
locomotives.
</P>
<P>
   Walking through Artrain, the students from Ben Bridgers'
intermediate drawing class at Lamar Dodd are impressed. ``People
don't even ride trains anymore,'' Bridgers said, ``much less expect
an art exhibition on one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
