<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-DAUGHTER-2TA     08-15 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-DAUGHTER-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POLITICAL DAUGHTER STRIDES INTO THE SPOTLIGHT FOR HER FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff reached into her purse and pulled out a
clump of typewritten pages. They were pockmarked by harsh X's
through several paragraphs, dashes through words and arrows to the
margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess!'' she lamented. ``Here it is. It's like this, and
I'm trying to figure out this and I do it down here and I cross out
and then I've got all this and I'm not sure if I should add this,
and maybe it's too long, and I'm going this afternoon to type it up
again and ask someone to look at it, whoever has time.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiff was going through a few unsurprising moments of panic as
she prepared to do something no other young woman has done:
nominate her father for president.
</P>
<P>
   However daunting the speech-writing process _ a task that, like
her father, she is doing herself _ she has a keen sense of her
purpose as one of her father's most trusted advisers. ``I care very
passionately about these issues, I really do, that's why I'm
involved in the campaign,'' she said in an interview in a hotel
room between campaign stops, referring to campaign finance, the
environment and matters of social justice. ``But I know that's not
why I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   She will be there, on the podium Wednesday night at the
Democratic National Convention, because she is Al Gore's best
witness. The last year has been a coming out party, of sorts, for
Schiff, who, at 27, was only recently steeped in a self-described
``rebellious'' stage, in which she gave herself over to punk bands
and all-black outfits before and after attending Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   And as a result of her extensive work with her father, more than
a few Democrats have speculated that she will one day begin her own
political career, a notion she does not reject out of hand, but
does not relish talking about. Because she lives in New York, where
loads of Democratic campaign money can be found, Gore makes
frequent detours to the city. There, his daughter's Upper East Side
apartment serves as a kind of unofficial campaign headquarters, the
scene of cocktail receptions and strategy sessions and reunions
with his 1-year-old grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says his oldest daughter has ``perfect pitch, or very
nearly perfect pitch.'' And that trust has led to her involvement
in most of the major decisions of her father's campaign, from the
controversy over high-priced hiring of Naomi Wolf, the feminist
consultant and friend of Schiff's, to the selection of Sen. Joseph
Lieberman as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But on at least one occasion, that pitch veered off-key, largely
because of her uncritical devotion to her father. A senior Gore
aide has said that it was Schiff who urged her father in March 1997
to hold a news conference at which he said seven times that there
was ``no controlling legal authority'' over whether he could make
fundraising calls from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff did not come up with that unfortunate phrase, advisers
say, but, because she so thoroughly believed in her father's
innocence, she pushed him to speak to the cameras before others
felt he was ready.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   She has also been exposed to the chaos that can come from being
so close to the action. One searing experience occurred in February
at a hastily arranged meeting between her father and the Rev. Al
Sharpton, whose political blessing Gore wanted before the New York
primary _ but without pictures directly linking him to the fiery
figure.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharpton rendezvous, stealthily conducted at Schiff's
apartment under the guise of a family visit, turned into a media
frenzy with television cameras staked out at her building and her
privacy threatened in a way she usually avoids.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a new wife (she married Dr. Andrew Schiff in 1997), a new
mother (son Wyatt was born July 4, 1999) and a newly minted
law-school graduate, she possesses important demographic
credentials. She has raised money for her father among women and
the under-30 set (she heads GoreNet, an outreach effort to young
voters) while growing ever more comfortable in speeches and the
chit-chat with strangers that accompanies such events.
</P>
<P>
   Her ease of manner, the hair elastic that she slips around her
wrist when she shakes out her ponytail and her exuberance at
extolling the virtues of the George Foreman Grill, as seen on
late-night infomercials, all lend her an air of authenticity that
the campaign hopes rubs off on her father. The not-so-subtle
thinking: If Gore can have a daughter who seems natural and
appealing, he must be a good guy himself.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One striking scene earlier this year was when Schiff graduated
from Columbia Law School and her father spoke at the ceremony at
Lincoln Center. Gore shook hands with every graduate who collected
a diploma, and when his daughter strode across the stage, the vice
president formally stuck out his hand again, as if she were just
another graduate. No, Dad. (Or, as he might say in one of his
attempts to show he is with it: Hellll-o?) She pulled him close and
wrapped her arms around him.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His daughter is also Exhibit A in conveying to working mothers _
a crucial voting bloc _ that Gore understands their needs and their
lives. He mentions his new grandson in nearly every speech, and the
campaign eagerly alerts reporters when Gore is babysitting, as he
did while Schiff attended the Million Mom March on behalf of gun
control. She also happily discusses the concerns of new mothers,
like breast-feeding. ``I am totally supportive of nursing in public
or wherever the hell it's necessary,'' she recently told
``thatglow.com,'' an online magazine about pregnancy. ``I remember
nursing in Central Park, and I fantasized about getting arrested
and thrown in jail for nursing; then I could lead a massive picket
line of nursing mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage for Schiff, evident this week during several
pre-convention activities, is that she provides an instant story
line as a made-for-the-media counterpart to George P. Bush, Gov.
George W. Bush's 23-year-old nephew, who is storming the youth
culture for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff, the granddaughter of a senator and the daughter of a man
who has served in the House (he was first elected on her third
birthday), the Senate and the vice presidency, can match the Bush
political lineage, although talk of being her father's political
heir-apparent makes her uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she might run for office some day, she rejects talk of
a Gore dynasty and shows a flash of anti-elitism. ``I just think
that there are so many other people who are really qualified and
care about the country, and no one asks them, and it doesn't occur
to them to run for office, and I think people all shouldn't come
from the same family,'' she said. ``I really honestly don't see
myself running,'' she added, a somewhat surprising conclusion since
she has on other recent occasions left the door more open.
</P>
<P>
   More immediate, she said, are plans to study for the New York
bar exam and to have more children.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was she who made the decision to take a public role in
her father's campaign (``It felt right for me'') and who emerged as
a natural political partner for her father. One of her younger
sisters, Kristin, 23, a comedy writer in Los Angeles, is
tentatively following her lead and making a few public appearances
at convention activities this week. But the other two siblings,
Sarah, 21, and Albert III, 17, remain in the background. Because
Gore felt so directed from an early age by his own father, friends
and family say that he has studiously avoided exerting the same
pressure on his own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really honestly never asked me to do anything, and I don't
think he ever would,'' Schiff said. ``He's very kind of protective
of us, and he doesn't want to force us into anything. He's very
conscious of not putting pressure on us.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I could just go off and be a quilter in the
mountains, and that would be more than fine with them. But it just
turns out that I actually am quite stimulated and engaged and
interested and really moved by this political moment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
