</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION TRIES TO HINDER BARAK'S NEGOTIATIONS WITH PALESTINIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's main opposition party used a depleted
special session of Parliament Tuesday to push through a resolution
aimed at impeding new peace talks with the Palestinians, but Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's government brushed the move aside as
political grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Ariel Sharon, the hawkish former general who leads the
right-wing Likud Party, opponents of the peace negotiations called
Parliament into a special session that interrupted the summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 39-1, with only a third of the 120 members present,
they approved another special session, tentatively set for Aug. 28,
to debate a resolution that would declare any attempts by Barak to
renew the peace talks without new elections illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition move came during a flurry of new peace maneuvers
aimed at bridging the deep differences on Jerusalem that caused
negotiations for a final peace treaty at Camp David to collapse
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who did not attend the parliamentary session, spent part
of his day meeting with top aides to discuss talks said to be set
for Wednesday between high-ranking Israeli and Palestinian
officials.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli television report, not confirmed by the government,
said that Shlomo Ben-Ami, who was named acting foreign minister
last week and who was one of those who met Tuesday with Barak, is
to meet with two top aides who accompanied Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian officials were named in the television report as
Mohammed Dahlan and Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian
Parliament and a man regarded as one of the most powerful figures
in the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The talks would be the highest-level contacts the two sides have
acknowledged holding since Camp David and seemed likely to focus on
Jerusalem. Since Camp David, both sides have marked out seemingly
irreconcilable positions on the city, with Arafat demanding that
Israel hand over sovereignty for all of east Jerusalem, and Barak
and his aides vowing that Israel will go no further than the
compromises suggested by President Clinton and tentatively accepted
by Barak at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by Israeli and Palestinian officials, those
compromises would involve a limited Palestinian foothold over the
Muslim holy sites in the Old City as well as control of the old
Arab quarter and some Arab villages on the city's eastern
periphery.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was also said to have agreed that Arafat could establish a
presidential headquarters for a Palestinian state in east
Jerusalem, allowing the Palestinians to declare it their new
capital.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's parliamentary session, Sharon sought to stir a
public groundswell against Barak with a highly charged speech that
depicted Barak as a usurper ready to trade Israel's control of
Jerusalem in return for a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon contended that Barak, who lost his parliamentary majority
when three parties quit his coalition government immediately before
the Camp David talks, has no mandate to govern or to negotiate
peace with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak does not have the right to give up Jerusalem, which the
people received as a legacy,'' Sharon said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Barak dismissed the parliamentary vote as largely
irrelevant to the peace efforts, saying that Barak, elected prime
minister by a wide margin in the popular vote 15 months ago, has a
constitutional and political mandate to continue peace negotiations
unless ousted in a new election.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides, they said, Sharon and his right-wing parliamentary
allies failed to force early elections only two weeks ago, when a
no-confidence vote against Barak's government fell three votes
short of the 61 votes needed.
</P>
<P>
   The no-confidence vote was followed by another vote on Aug. 2 in
which opposition parties succeeded in mustering 61 votes in favor
of dissolving Parliament, which would lead to new elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Israel's basic law requires such a vote to be approved
afterward by a parliamentary committee, then again by the full
Parliament, before becoming law _ a process not likely to be
completed, if at all, until Parliament ends its summer recess and
resumes on Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sharon and his aides have been working to win over some
members who voted against the no-confidence vote, with a view to
trying to topple Barak during the recess, most Israeli politicians
believe that the prime minister will survive at least until the
fall session. Even if he is defeated then, either in a
no-confidence vote or by passage of a law mandating new elections,
Barak would have 90 days before an election to seek a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli political commentators said that Sharon, lacking the
numbers for a no-confidence vote, appeared to have settled for the
time being on a course intended to undermine public confidence in
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   In this context, they said, the parliamentary debate later this
month seemed likely to be largely a forum for more impassioned
opposition denunciations of Barak. All the same, commentators said,
the parliamentary drumbeat against the peace talks was not likely
to encourage progress in the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
