u i BC-ARGENTINA-MENEM-NYT &LR;      08-15 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-MENEM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ARGENTINE PRESIDENT ISSUES DIRE ECONOMIC FORECAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ At a time of deepening concerns about
the Argentine economy, former President Carlos Saul Menem has
predicted that Argentina faces a devaluation and a depression
unless President Fernando de la Rua either changes economic
direction or adopts the dollar as the national currency.
</P>
<P>
   Menem retains a strong reputation among some Argentine
executives and Wall Street analysts for reengineering the Argentine
economy in the early 1990s, so his public comments Monday propelled
a debate on Tuesday in the Argentine business press and sent
shudders through the government.
</P>
<P>
   Since De la Rua took office eight months ago, he has
concentrated on cutting government deficits to lower interest
rates. But with the prices of wheat and soybeans at record lows,
and the Argentine peso tied 1-to-1 to a strong dollar, the
country's exports and economy have stagnated.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in tax revenue and a decline in public spending this
year have pleased the International Monetary Fund, but unemployment
has increased to 15.4 percent, a three-year-high.
</P>
<P>
   Only five months ago, government officials said the economy
would grow at least 4 percent this year _ following a 3 percent
decline in 1999 _ but now most economists say the country will be
lucky to reach a 2 percent growth rate.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness is especially startling when compared with the
performance of Latin America's two other huge economies _ those of
Brazil and Mexico. Last week Brazil reported its best quarterly
growth rate in three years at nearly 4 percent, and there are
widespread expectations it will grow 4 percent for the year in a
robust recovery from its own economic crisis in early 1999. And
today, Mexico, where the economy is in its best shape in years,
said its second-quarter growth rate reached 7.6 percent, far above
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, by contrast, seems mired in bad economic news. Even
Argentine beef, one of the country's most promising exports, is now
jeopardized by fears of a possible outbreak of foot-and-mouth
disease. Demand from new markets in Asia has fallen, and experts
are predicting a loss of $130 million in foreign beef sales this
year.
</P>
<P>
   With confidence sagging, De la Rua is putting the final touches
on a new $50 million jobs program to alleviate poverty in the
provinces, but the plan is being greeted with skepticism since
salaries would be as low as $200 a month. Analysts hope that a
continued expansion in Brazil and an eventual strengthening of the
European euro could help boost Argentine exports by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue on this path, I think there will be a
devaluation, or a dollarization of the economy,'' said Menem, who
is the leader of the opposition Justicialist Party and says he will
run for president again in 2003. ``If things go on this way, we are
heading into a depression that could be dramatic for Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina long suffered from cycles of devaluations and
hyperinflation until Menem redesigned the currency system in 1991
pegging the peso 1-to-1 to the dollar. The policy quickly toppled
inflation to a rate that is near zero today, but growth has been
slow and choppy over the last five years. Menem began floating the
idea of a complete dollarization during his final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Dario Loperfido, the government secretary of culture and
communication, bitterly criticized the former president Tuesday for
attempting to ``create a bad image of the country abroad.'' He
added, ``He's not doing the country any good.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the former president's dire prognosis came as
Economy Minister Jose Luis Machinea traveled to Washington Tuesday
to consult with international bankers and as De la Rua prepared to
be host of a two-day visit by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Molano, head of research for BCP Securities, a
fixed-income brokerage firm based in Greenwich, Conn., said Menem's
comment ``reflects a sense among the opposition that there is blood
in the water'' and it is now time to begin attacking the
government's economic policies in a more forthright manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are coming to a head in Argentina,'' Molano added.
``They are running out of rabbits to pull out of their hats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
