a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     08-15 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUT CAN YOU SING A DUET WITH A PORCUPINE AFTER 6 P.M.?
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was glad to read that two women in my hometown of Sarasota,
Fla., had been arrested for cursing in front of children.
</P>
<P>
   The women were charged with violating a 1939 city law that makes
it illegal to utter the f-word and several other choice invectives
within earshot of children. If convicted, they each face up to 60
days in jail and a fine of $500.
</P>
<P>
   It is my position that children should not be exposed to
profanity unless they are at the movies, watching TV or listening
to popular music. In those situations, coarse language is
considered ``art'' and is not to be confused with the common,
gutter-variety obscenities one hears on the streets or at Little
League games.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that I have not ``slipped'' occasionally and
uttered a bad word in the presence of our 14-year-old, who for many
years thought his given name was Dammitmichael. Now that the cops
are listening, I will have to clean up my act.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Michael leaves his bicycle behind my car, chops a
sprinkler line with a shovel, or forgets to tell me until the night
before that he has a science-fair project due tomorrow, I will not
lose my temper and turn the air blue with four-letter words. I will
wait until he is out of earshot, or has his headphones on, then
curse.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger question here, I think, is: What other 60-year-old laws
are hanging around, waiting to trip us up in publicly humiliating
ways over and above fines and jail time?
</P>
<P>
   Florida, as you might expect, is a national leader in goofy
laws, some of which may or may not still be on the books. (For a
more comprehensive treatment of this subject, go to
www.dumblaws.com.)
</P>
<P>
   One antiquated law states that women can be fined for falling
asleep under a hair dryer, as can the owner of the salon.
</P>
<P>
   This seems like a perfectly reasonable law to me in that it is
not good public policy to have sleeping women's heads burst into
flames, particularly if they don't have insurance. To protect
themselves from prosecution, salon owners might want to give their
drowsy customers a brisk slap every now and then, or maybe whang on
their hair dryers with a curling iron every so often to keep them
alert.
</P>
<P>
   Another Florida law states that it is illegal to have sexual
relations with a porcupine.
</P>
<P>
   Again, I see nothing wrong with this law, though I seriously
doubt that porcupine sex is now, or ever was, such a problem that
it needed to be addressed by statute. The way I look at it, anyone
who attempts to have sex with a porcupine is going to be punished
enough without any further involvement on the part of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another law states that it is illegal to sing in a public
place while attired in a swimsuit. This, too, strikes me as a good
law, though you've got to wonder what kind of circumstances led to
its passage. Did people object more to the singing or to the
swimsuits? Or was it the combination that finally drove honest
citizens to seek legal sanctions? Who, for that matter, would want
to sing in a public place while attired in a swimsuit? Instead of
arresting these people, shouldn't we be showing them compassion and
perhaps help them get counseling? I've got to think the Republicans
were behind this one.
</P>
<P>
   Another law that must have strange origins is the law that
states you may not break wind in a public place after 6 p.m. on
Thursdays. Were people breaking more wind after 6 p.m. Thursday
than before? Why? Doesn't this law seem to encourage people to
break wind in public places on days other than Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   How would police go about collecting evidence? Isn't this whole
subject rather disgusting?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but not to the point that I'd want to curse. At least not
if there are children nearby.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
