<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUSTRALIA-QUICK-LUNCH     08-15 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-QUICK-LUNCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN HABITS REACH ACROSS THE PACIFIC TO CHANGE THE WAY A NATION
LUNCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BECKY GAYLORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Chalk up another victim of America's
eat-on-the-run workplace culture.
</P>
<P>
   First it was the French. Traditionalists watched in horror as
white-collar drones in the homeland of haute cuisine, caught up in
the pressures of the global economy, began abandoning the
wine-soaked three-hour lunch in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But who would have thought Australians _ that
independent-minded, fun-loving lot Down Under _ would also succumb
to the capitalist credo that productivity and profit-making
constitute a higher calling than a leisurely midday meal?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the evidence of the Australian office worker's apostasy is
everywhere. Start with the upscale rotating Summit restaurant,
located atop a skyscraper in the heart of the business district,
where lunchtime business bustled a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to fill the buffet from one to three,'' said
Jenny-Lee Stefas, referring to lunch business. She took over last
year as sales and marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   How times have changed. By 1999, even after a refurbishment that
included funky red carpet, sleek white chairs and a minimalist
``Space Odyssey'' theme, business had dropped off so much that on
some days only three or four customers showed up, Stefas says. That
left room for 347 more.
</P>
<P>
   To lure more business people, the restaurant took aim at their
weak spot and advertised a rich repast in one hour. Business has
tripled _ to an average 75 diners. They are able to sit down at
noon and order, say, warm chili prawns with mango and cucumber
relish, followed by crisp-skin Tasmanian salmon with green-pea
puree, tomato provencale and olive oil, all of it washed down with
a good wine, and be out the door by 1 p.m. And if the Summit fails
to deliver on the one-hour guarantee, customers win a one-night
stay at a country resort.
</P>
<P>
   Other top restaurants have begun speeding things up. Late last
year, the highly regarded MG Garage restaurant formulated a
quick-lunch special for 25 Australian dollars, or $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can come here with a main course and a glass of wine
already chosen to go with it, and that alone cuts the time of
having to look at the menu and decide,'' said Janni Kyritsis, MG
Garage's head chef.
</P>
<P>
   For years, American business people have avoided wine at work
day lunches. In Australia, the trend is newer, but growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out for a boozy lunch, you write your whole
afternoon off,'' said Leigh Anderson, a manager at Morgan &AMP; Banks,
an executive recruitment firm here. ``People can't afford to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Anderson is a stranger to the long lunch. He said that
at the company he worked for six years ago in London it ``was
almost a condition of your employment to take people out for
lunch.'' And they could be fairly liquid affairs, he confessed.
Now, at Morgan &AMP; Banks, he said, ``we tend to discourage that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harland Koops, a partner at the law firm of Henry Davis York,
has also weaned himself of long lunches, though he says he was
never a regular player on the lunch circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calvinistic instincts seem to be reasserting themselves,''
Koops said.
</P>
<P>
   Clients, he added, ``really have their heads down making money,
and they're not playing as much as they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, Australian business people claimed a leisurely
lunch of several courses and accompanying wines, followed by
dessert and coffee, as a national privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Until late last year, even the bond market closed for a
respectable hour and a half _ one of only a handful in the world to
cease business in the middle of the day. Throughout the 1980s and
into the early '90s, that shutdown created the occasional
phenomenon known as the claret run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when a market would go on a seemingly inexplicable
rally,'' one money market dealer explained. ``And it was based on
the fact that a few people would come back from lunch all liquored
up and decide they liked the market and start buying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they would not come back at all, and the business
lunch would slide into dinner. Such epicureans were known as FTRs,
for ``failed to return.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? What drove Aussies toward midday temperance?
</P>
<P>
   Time-poor, cholesterol-rich executives cite not just the global
economy and the competitive pressures it has unleashed, but also
fitness concerns. An increasing number are heading out for a
lunch-hour jog or a session with a personal trainer. Or else they
are eating at their desks so they can leave early for some surfing
or golf.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the government's elimination of tax-deductible
lunches in two stages _ the first in the 1980s, the second in the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bilson, director of the chic Ampersand Restaurant, called
that change a ``body blow.'' It was followed by a new 10 percent
tax on restaurant meals, that began July 1, presaging even leaner
times to come. The trade at midday is so thin on some days that
Bilson occasionally mulls shutting Ampersand for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The same gastronomic drama has been playing itself in other
parts of the world, notably France, where long, liquid lunches had
been a sacred ritual for years. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone goes out to the boulangerie, and comes back with
bread, or cheese or something, and eats together as a group,'' said
Capucine Favet, 26, a designer of street events for W.M., an
outdoor-event company in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward faster midday meals has been long in the making
in France, but got a fresh nudge in January with a law that bans
salaried employees from putting in more than 35 hours a week. In
response, many companies have stopped counting lunch hours in the
figure, said Patrick Lenain, an economist with the Organization of
Economic Cooperation and Development based in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people who take two or three hours are executives, and
it's business lunches with clients,'' Lenain said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is giving way on the lunch front. Back in
Australia, there are still die-hard diners. ``I work with a fellow
who's known as Sir Lunch a Lot,'' Koops said. ``They're still out
there, mate. They're just lunching on.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at 3:30 on a recent afternoon, Koops' colleague could
not be reached at his office. He was, his secretary said, still at
lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
