<HEADLINE>
POLITICS SMILES ON THE NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (p and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ratings picture was generally positive for the TV networks
for opening night of the Democratic National Convention, with most
networks notching increases when compared with the convention four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, however, viewers continued to show a decided preference
for nonpolitical programs. For instance, 80,000 Boston-area
households switched from WHDH-TV (Channel 7) when ``Dateline'' gave
way to convention coverage. On WCVB-TV (Channel 5), more than
45,000 households tuned out when ``Monday Night Football'' ended
and convention coverage began.
</P>
<P>
   The first night of the Democratic conclave was a made-for-TV
spectacle whose headliners didn't appear until just a half-hour
before the end of prime time. President Bill Clinton did not begin
his speech Monday night until 10:52 EST, 40 minutes later than
party officials had planned. His wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, did
not start her own speech until nearly 10:30 p.m. That could have
damaged the Democrats' chances of reaching a large audience,
especially on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   But collectively, according to Nielsen Media Research, coverage
on the ``Big Three'' drew a combined audience of 17.2 million
viewers Monday night, nearly a million more viewers than tuned in
to the first night of the Democratic convention in 1996. NBC and
ABC both increased their audiences from four years ago, though CBS
was down slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was a bigger draw four years ago, when his acceptance
speech on the final night of the convention was watched by more
than 20 million viewers on the Big Three networks.
</P>
<P>
   NBC did not cover the first night of the Republican convention
last month, but the audiences for ABC and CBS Monday night _ 5.99
million viewers and 5.2 million viewers, respectively _ were
roughly the same as their opening-night audiences at the GOP
conclave.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of viewership, ABC won by a whisker, followed by NBC,
with 5.95 million, and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Broadcasting Service increased its audience Monday
night to 3 million viewers from the 2.3 million who tuned in for
its coverage of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three all-news cable networks improved on their
performance from day one of the Republican National Convention. CNN
drew 1.8 million viewers Monday night for Clinton's speech,
compared with 1.2 million who tuned in to hear retired General
Colin Powell kick off the GOP convention. CNN's audience was also
up substantially from the first night of the Democratic convention
in 1996. However, the CNN audience for Clinton's speech was much
smaller than the 2.7 million who tuned in for his acceptance speech
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The audience for Fox News Channel dropped from 676,000 viewers
at the kickoff of the GOP convention to 420,000 viewers for the
Democratic conclave. The third all-news network, MSNBC, enlarged
its audience, increasing to 632,000 viewers from the 516,000 it
drew for the first night of the Republican convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
