<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LIEBERMAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LIEBERMAN TELLS BLACK CAUCUS HE SUPPORTS AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DAN FREEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES_ As he prepared his acceptance speech before the
Democratic National Convention Wednesday night, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., was busy putting out a brush fire over his
civil rights record, telling African-American delegates: ``I have
supported affirmative action, I do support affirmative action and I
will support affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after his arrival here Tuesday, Lieberman found
himself placating Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., a prominent black
lawmaker, who said she could not support Vice President Al Gore and
Lieberman until they had clarified their positions on affirmative
action, education and criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   She singled out Lieberman, who in the past has questioned
affirmative action and supported school vouchers for children in
failing inner-city schools. Because other black leaders including
the Rev. Jesse Jackson, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, and Rep.
John Lewis, D-Ga., had praised Gore's selection of Lieberman,
Waters appeared isolated in her skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, concerned about party unity during the convention,
Lieberman went right to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questions have been raised about my record ... and I want to
deal with it right directly,'' Lieberman told a meeting of the
Democratic National Committee Black Caucus. He compared the process
of scrutinizing his record to ``getting a medical procedure without
an anesthetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman launched into a lengthy explanation of his civil
rights record, starting with his attendance at the historic 1963
march on Washington, D.C., where Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. gave
his ``I have a dream'' speech. The Connecticut senator said his
commitment to racial equality ``begins with my religion, because I
believe as a matter of faith, not just that God created all of us,
(but) I believe that every human being is created in God's image,''
he said. Lieberman is an orthodox Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also told the audience:
</P>
<P>
   __ As a student in 1963, he traveled to Mississippi to register
black voters.
</P>
<P>
   __ Since winning election to the Senate in 1988, he has been a
consistent supporter of civil rights legislation as well as an
opponent of Republican attempts to dismantle U.S. government
affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   __ He had questioned whether some federal affirmative action
had, in effect, sanctioned quotas in the mid-1990s. But he
concurred with President Clinton's ``mend it, don't end it''
approach to affirmative action in 1995 that essentially left the
program intact.
</P>
<P>
   __ He didn't actively support California's Proposition 209, a
1996 ballot initiative that effectively ended affirmative action in
all state and local hiring, college admissions and awarding of
contracts. He attributed confusion over his stance on Proposition
209 to a one-time positive response to a reporter's question on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   __ He agreed with Clinton that ``affirmative action was never
about having unqualified people take jobs from qualified people. It
was about qualified people (getting opportunities).''
</P>
<P>
   On his support for vouchers that would enable parents to
transfer their children to private schools, Lieberman said he
thought a pilot program would be worth trying until public
education could be fixed. But he added he had never retreated from
basic support of public education, and that public schools had
helped him rise out of limited circumstances in Stamford, Conn., to
attend Yale University and Yale law school. Lieberman did not talk
about criminal justice and the concern of many blacks that
African-Americans receive unequal justice when it comes to
prosecution and sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent black political leaders D.C. Delegate Eleanor Holmes
Norton and Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater hailed Lieberman
as a champion of minority rights.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Waters told reporters she would work for the
Gore-Lieberman ticket, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman ``seemed consistent with what I think the Democratic
Party ideals are all about,'' she declared.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spent a large portion of the day preparing his
Wednesday night prime-time speech.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki McLean, a campaign spokeswoman, said Lieberman would talk
about himself, ``the Al Gore he knows,'' and voters' ``choices for
the future ... It's not an attack speech, but he will draw sharp
contrasts'' between the Democratic ticket and Republican
challenger, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's speech would be a particular source of pride to
Jewish-Americans, said Rabbi Marvin Hier, founder and director of
the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, which operates the
city's Museum of Tolerance featuring displays that teach about
hatred and bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a moment of historic importance,'' said Hier, who is
non-partisan and spoke briefly at the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia earlier this month. ``Whatever the
demographics (of Americans watching or not watching Lieberman's
speech), Jewish Americans will tune in in record proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he added, ``it's important to recognize that Gore
didn't go out looking for some Jew. He selected Joe Lieberman
because in addition to going to a synagogue, he is a man of great
integrity. That's why it's really a moment of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
