<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 30-DAY REPRIEVE, DNA TESTS SEND TEXAS INMATE BACK TO DEATH
ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ricky Nolen McGinn, the only inmate ever granted a
stay of execution by Gov. George W. Bush, is headed back to death
row.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of raping and murdering his 12-year-old stepdaughter,
McGinn, 43, came within minutes of being executed on June 1 when
Bush granted him a 30-day reprieve to allow for a series of new DNA
tests. But the results of the tests, made public at a court hearing
Tuesday, further incriminated McGinn and prompted the presiding
judge to reschedule the execution for Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the results were consistent,'' said Brown County District
Attorney Lee Haney, the prosecutor in the case. Asked if he was
relieved, Haney said, ``I'm certainly not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers had hoped that testing semen found inside the
victim would clear McGinn of the rape conviction. It was the
combination of rape and murder convictions that qualified him for
the death penalty. But each of the DNA tests conducted by the Texas
Department of Public Safety, the FBI and two defense experts,
served to further implicate McGinn.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has presided over 139 executions since taking office
in 1995, the most of any governor in the nation, had never granted
a reprieve until the McGinn case. In a statement Tuesday, the
governor said he granted the stay ``because it was important, in
this case, that biological evidence be tested to help determine the
defendant's guilt or innocence of the rape charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district court action today also demonstrates the
safeguards present in our system,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurie Levin, one of McGinn's lawyers, credited Bush for
allowing the DNA tests, but disputed the belief that the results
should be interpreted as an endorsement of the death penalty system
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She aid that ``numerous exonerations, in capital and non-capital
cases, have been achieved through the use of DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a Texas inmate, Roy Criner, was released Tuesday after
DNA tests proved he had been wrongly convicted of rape. Criner
spent 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature is expected to debate a host of death
penalty reforms in its 2001 session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
