<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GIBBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES GIBBS, DIABETES GROUP LEADER, DIES AT 105 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Mex., N.Y.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Charles Brooke Flint Gibbs, a Rochester internist who was
the last survivor of the founders of the American Diabetes
Association 60 years ago, died on Aug. 4 in Rochester. He was 105.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs was one of 32 founders of the association in 1940. Since
then, it has grown to 280,000 members, with a staff of more than
800 and an annual budget of $88 million.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gibbs, a native of Black River, near Watertown, N.Y.,
graduated from Syracuse University College of Medicine. He was its
oldest living alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   His own care of diabetics left an imprint on a number of
institutions. He was among the researchers at the University of
Rochester who worked to isolate insulin in the 1920s. The
university formed its medical school in 1925, and Gibbs organized
the region's first diabetes clinic that year at Rochester General
Hospital. He was named head of the first such clinic at Strong
Memorial Hospital the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The medical school named the library of its endocrinology
division in honor of Gibbs several years ago. He was a past
president of the Rochester Academy of Medicine and founding
president of the Rochester Regional Diabetes Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs made house calls almost daily for 59 years, retiring from
active practice in 1980. He died in his sleep at a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Blanche Haynes Gibbs, died in 1998 after 76 years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs is survived by two daughters, Molly Gibbs King of Syracuse
and Nancy Zaenglein of Penfield, N.Y.; a son, Dr. Carl Gibbs of
Santa Fe, N.M.; 12 grandchildren; and 14 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     08-15 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT URGED TO HEAR MICROSOFT APPEAL QUICKLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declaring that the outcome of the Microsoft antitrust case could
affect nearly every person who uses a computer, the Justice
Department on Tuesday urged the Supreme Court to hear the company's
appeal quickly so ``that justice is not denied through delay.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court can hear direct appeals in civil antitrust
cases brought by the federal government if it thinks the expedited
review is in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing Tuesday, the Justice Department argued forcefully
that the Microsoft lawsuit is surely such a case. ``A lengthy
appeals process,'' the government stated, ``could irreparably harm
competition in a vital and rapidly evolving sector of the national
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Microsoft asked the court to let its appeal go first
to the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit,
which had ruled for the company in a related case. Microsoft said
the appeals court was the proper place for an initial review
because the company's appeal raised many technical issues and
argued that the trial judge made a series of procedural errors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will file a legal brief with the Supreme Court next
Tuesday, seeking to undermine the government's arguments.
</P>
<P>
   With its filing, the Justice Department essentially tried to
make it more difficult for the Supreme Court to decline a direct
review. It characterized Microsoft's arguments as all but an insult
to the court's competence. Microsoft, the government stated,
``overstates the complexity of this case'' and ``underestimates
this court's capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also suggested that if the court declined, it
would leave the antitrust Expediting Act of 1903, which was amended
in 1974, as a dead letter.
</P>
<P>
   From 1903 until 1974, all appeals of civil antitrust cases
brought by the government went directly to the Supreme Court, but
the 1974 amendment gave the court more discretion in which appeals
it heard directly. The standard, under the 1974 amendment, is that
the case should be of ``general public importance in the
administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In pointed language, the government told the court: ``The stakes
in this case for the national economy are immense. If this case
does not qualify for direct review under the Expediting Act, it is
difficult to imagine what future case would.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who heard the lawsuit in U.S.
District Court, ruled this year that Microsoft was a monopoly that
had repeatedly violated the nation's antitrust laws. And he ordered
that the company be split in two, an order he later shelved pending
appeals. Microsoft is appealing both Jackson's ruling and his
breakup order.
</P>
<P>
   The votes of four of the Supreme Court's nine justices would be
needed for the court to hear an expedited appeal. If the case went
directly to the Supreme Court, it could be resolved in a year. If
it went first to the appeals court, the resolution could take up to
two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision on whether to hear the appeal
directly could well be crucial to the outcome and the impact of the
Microsoft case, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   If the court proceeded with a direct appeal, they say, it would
be a favorable sign for the government. The government would avoid
a federal appeals court where Microsoft has done well in the past.
And a move for expedited treatment would suggest that the court
wanted to resolve a pressing problem quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Supreme Court's instinct is that Microsoft is a
monopoly whose activities are costly to society, it will be more
likely to take the case directly,'' said Herbert Hovenkamp, a
professor at the University of Iowa law school. ``But if not, then
the cost of lingering is not so high, and then it will be more
likely to let the appeals court review the case first.''
</P>
<P>
   The effect of any sanctions against Microsoft, assuming it lost
the case on appeal, would probably be dulled by an additional year
of delay. ``For that reason, this is a decisive moment in the
litigation,'' said William Kovacic, a professor at the George
Washington University law school.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing, the government addressed that issue, noting,
``Delay will postpone, and likely complicate substantially, the
restoration of competition in the affected high-technology
industries, which evolve at an extraordinary pace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
