<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PHONES-PRIVACY-NYT &LR;      08-15 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONES-PRIVACY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT LIMITS MONITORING OF CELL PHONES BY LAW-ENFORCEMENT AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Tuesday struck down part of
a government order that had broadly expanded the ability of
law-enforcement agents to monitor cell phone conversations of
criminal suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was considered a partial victory by privacy groups
that had challenged the order and was a clear setback for law
enforcement agencies, which must now consider revising the rules
for electronic surveillance of wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision by the the appeals court here gave the
authorities some of what they had sought. It upheld a provision of
the order that enabled federal agents to determine the general
location of a cell phone user by identifying which phone-company
antenna was used to transmit the beginning and end of a call.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit, which set out important statutory and
constitutional parameters for electronic surveillance, suggested
that agents seeking to monitor the location of suspects through
cell phones must first meet a high burden of proof to obtain a
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The court struck down a provision of the year-old order by the
Federal Communications Commission that had required companies to
install equipment to detect telephone tones after a call is placed,
enabling agents to monitor the use of cell phones to make banking
transactions, get voice-mail messages, or send paging messages.
</P>
<P>
   It also struck comparable provisions that had required the
companies to install equipment to enable law enforcement agents to
monitor conference calls, call forwarding, call waiting and
messages left on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was filed last year by a coalition of telephone
industry groups that had complained that the government order was
too costly to implement and privacy rights organizations that said
the order had violated the constitutional rights of cell phone
users.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission issued the order last
August in an attempt to make it easier for law enforcement
authorities to monitor conversations on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The agency issued the order after years of fruitless
negotiations by the government, industry and privacy groups to
implement a 1994 law, the Communications Assistance for Law
Enforcement Act.
</P>
<P>
   That law required telephone companies and equipment makers to
build their networks in a way that enabled law enforcement to
intercept certain kinds of communications. It also imposed privacy
contraints and ordered regulators to implement standards in manner
that was least costly to industry.
</P>
<P>
   The issue posed by the appeal, U.S. Telecom Association v.
Federal Communications Commission, was whether the agency, in
issuing the order, exceeded its authority or failed to consider
privacy concerns and the financial costs of the new standards
adequately.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion written by Judge David S. Tatel and joined by
Judges Douglas H. Ginsburg and A. Raymond Randolph, the appeals
court found that in four instances that the FCC had failed to
explain the basis for its order properly. The judges also found
that the commission had failed to examine whether the standards
were too costly.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said that when the commission required that the
companies install equipment to monitor tones after phone calls are
made, the agency failed to consider the possible privacy
implications of its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers had defended the provision on the
grounds that after a telephone call is made, some callers use
``dial-around'' services like 1-800-CALL-ATT to then charge long
distance calls, a procedure that can be used to circumvent
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   But the court accepted the concerns the privacy groups had that
the effect of the standard was to permit agents to also monitor
such activities as banking and paging by using the keyboard of a
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers on both sides of the case said that they had not decided
whether they would appeal Tuesday's ruling. If it is not appealed,
then the FCC must begin new proceedings to reconsider and possibly
rewrite its rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, government lawyers said, law enforcement
agencies will be constrained in their ability to monitor certain
kinds of communications through cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes amid growing concern by some lawmakers and
privacy groups that the government has been increasing its
electronic surveillance, and by competing concerns at the Federal
Bureau of Investigation that cannot keep up with advances in
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, that debate has focused on a new computer
application called Carnivore that the FBI says it uses to sift
through millions of e-mail in order to monitor communications of
criminal suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tuesday's decision did not directly address the issues
posed by the use of Carnivore, some privacy experts said that it
had important implications for how that computer application was
being used. The opinion generally upheld government surveillance of
digital communications through cell phones, a technology similar to
what is used for e-mail. As such, the opinion suggested
surveillance of e-mail would also be upheld.
</P>
<P>
   But the court also reiterated that to monitor the content of
those communications, federal agents must meet the same legal
standard as traditional wiretaps, and that innovative kinds of
surveillance cannot be used to circumvent those rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This imposes significant privacy protections on the use of
these capabilities and requires law enforcement to meet the highest
legal standards before using them,'' said David Sobel, general
counsel of the Electronic Privacy Information Center, a
privacy-rghts group that was one of the organizations that had
challenged the rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
