<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBRAER-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMAND FOR REGIONAL JETS BOOSTS EARNINGS AT EMRAER OF BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Benefiting from a vibrant demand for
regional jets, Brazilian aircraft maker Empresa Brasileira de
Aeronautica SA, or Embraer, reported a 35 percent gain in
second-quarter earnings Tuesday on a 54 percent surge in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Brazil's largest exporter of manufactured goods and
an emblem of Brazilian corporate success, earned 112.9 million
reais or $63 million compared with 83.6 million reais the year
before. Quarterly sales rose to 1.2 billion reais.
</P>
<P>
   The results reflect the demand for Embraer's short-haul regional
jets, the fastest growing segment of the commercial aviation
market. The planes seat 30 to 110 people, with a range of about
1,500 miles, and are more profitable to operate on many routes than
larger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of the year, Embraer delivered 72 planes in
the 30- to 50-seater ERJ 135/145 family to airlines around the
world, up from 38 in the first half of 1999. In an effort to meet
increasing demand, Embraer has accelerated its production cycle to
14 planes a month and plans to speed up to 16 planes a month by
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   The company's current backlog of undelivered airplanes is valued
at $20.7 billion, of which $15.5 billion are firm orders and $12.2
billion are options, Embraer said.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer's president, Mauricio Botelho, has said that the company
plans to invest about $1.4 billion between 2000 and 2004, with $1.1
billion going into development of new models and $300 million into
the construction of a new plant and research center. Embraer
recently began making the 44-seater ERJ 140, and is developing a
new family of jets in the 70 to 110-seat category.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of 2000, Embraer earnings more than doubled
to 210.4 million reais or $117 million on a 62 percent increase in
sales to 2.2 billion reais or $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's positive results helped draw attention away from
Brazil's recent loss at the World Trade Organization to Embraer
rival, Canada's Bombardier. The WTO, which arbitrates disputes
between member nations, is expected to rule in the next couple of
weeks over the value of sanctions the Canadian government can levy
on Brazilian imports.
</P>
<P>
   Embraer shares fell 2.3 percent to 10.7 reais on the Sao Paulo
exchange after having risen 5.8 percent on Monday. On the New York
Stock Exchange, Embraer's American Depositary Shares, which began
trading at $18.50 on July 21, fell 13/16 or 3.3 percent to $23
11/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-PAINTER-NYT &LR;      08-15 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PAINTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARTIST AND HIS MOUNTAIN GAIN NEW ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ The muralist, painter and author Tom Lea is
probably the only person, dead or alive, who can say he has been
threatened by Pancho Villa, interrupted by Chiang Kai-shek and
regaled by Franklin D. Roosevelt. Oddly enough, Lea was mostly
forgotten until he was quoted this month by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lea, who is 93, is sitting in the living room of his house on
the slope of the Franklin Mountains, the same simple home where he
and his wife, Sarah, have lived for decades above the dun-colored
streets of El Paso and its Mexican sister city, Ciudad Juarez. The
Texas folklorist J. Frank Dobie once surveyed the desert terrain
and complained that Lea did not even have a tree in his yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't have a mountain in yours,'' Lea answered.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lea, Bush was impressed with that mountain. Lea was
spending an evening at home when the telephone rang from the
Republican National Convention with the news that Bush planned to
mention him in his speech. Lea switched on the television and
watched the Texas governor quote a passage from his book ``A
Picture Gallery,'' in which he wrote of living ``on the east side
of the mountain:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the sunrise side, not the sunset side. It's the side to
see the day that is coming, not to see the day that is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech and subsequent national attention have sparked a
happy, if modest, renaissance for Lea. He has always had passionate
admirers, and his drawings and paintings are displayed in museums,
including a gallery carrying his name at the El Paso Museum of Art.
But he was largely forgotten outside Texas. Now, a national art
magazine has inquired with his dealer, Adair Margo, about a
profile. The wire services ran stories of his emotional response to
the speech. Friends called with congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very moved,'' Lea recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He is fiddling with a hand-carved cane embossed with his name, a
gift from a fan. He can no longer see well enough to paint or read,
and even when he could, he always kept his distance from the modern
art world with its infatuation with introspection and
experimentation. The world that inspired him lay outside his
window.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would give an aspiring artist or writer,
Lea responded without hesitation, ``I'd tell them I hope they'll
study from life.''
</P>
<P>
   His own beginnings in El Paso, where he was born in 1907, came
when the city was little more than a dusty passageway north from
Mexico. Once, Lea's father, who served as mayor in 1915, jailed the
wife of Pancho Villa for gun running. Infuriated, the Mexican
bandit and revolutionary put a bounty on the mayor's head and
promised to kidnap Tom and his brother, Joe _ a threat that got the
boys a police bodyguard to and from school.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso sparked his imagination but offered Lea little in the
way of artistic training, so he went to the Chicago Art Institute
and studied under the muralist John Warner Norton. Lea illustrated
for magazines and painted murals, like ``The Nesters,'' for the
Benjamin Franklin Post Office in Washington. By World War II, his
work attracted the attention of Henry Luce, the Life magazine
publisher who hired him as an illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   He traveled more than 100,000 miles, painting the sinking of the
aircraft carrier Wasp in the North Atlantic and landing with the
marines on Peleliu Island in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Luce once dispatched him to paint a portrait of Chiang Kai-shek,
then the nationalist leader of China. Chiang, Lea recalled, arrived
with a sofa pillow and a miniature Big Ben clock. He placed the
pillow behind his back for support and set the clock ticking as Lea
began his profile. When 25 minutes passed, the clock rang clanged
and Chiang abruptly left. Lea then went upstairs, where Madame
Chiang proved a more willing subject. As she posed, Chiang entered
the room in an evening robe, bowing toward his wife, then to an
aide and then to Lea before leaving without a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' she told Lea, ``my husband would be quite handsome
if he would keep his teeth in.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the war, Luce dispatched Lea to the White House to
present a collection of Life war paintings to Roosevelt, who spent
20 minutes chatting about how such works too often ended up in the
offices of one admiral or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Henry Luce and I have solved that,''' Lea recalled
of the president's deal to take control of the works. His painting
of the sinking of the Wasp remains on display at the U.S. Army
Center of Military History in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When the war ended, Lea returned to El Paso, where he has
remained, even as interests broadened. He went to Mexico to study
the fighting black bulls and wrote and illustrated his first novel,
``The Brave Bulls,'' which became a best seller and a movie. His
subsequent novel of the border, ``The Wonderful Country,'' became a
best seller in 1952. In the movie, which starred Robert Mitchum,
Lea played the barber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving old Mitchum a shave, and he needed one,'' Lea joked.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote other books, including ``The King Ranch,'' a two-volume
account of Texas' most famous ranch that established him as a
historian.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1992, when he joined with Margo, Lea never had an art
agent or dealer. Patrons simply inquired, and he put their names on
a list. When he finished a painting, Margo said, he would call the
next person on the list and invite the person to El Paso to take a
look. One painting not for sale, now or ever, is a portrait of his
wife of 62 years, ``Sarah in the Summertime,'' that hangs in the
living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stand by that one,'' he says. ``Destroy all the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Leas were introduced to Bush and his wife, Laura, a few
years ago by Margo. A friendship ensued, and Bush honored the
couple at a dinner at the governor's mansion. Bush also quoted
Lea's passage from ``A Picture Gallery'' in one of his State of the
State addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The El Paso outside Lea's window is very different now. The
cowboys are harder to find, and the dusty border town is part of a
metropolitan area of more than 2 million people. Lea's yard now has
a tree, an Arizona cypress, and a carpet of green grass. His only
regret is that he can no longer paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I ever lifted a brush, I hoped I would make a
better painting,'' he said. ``That's my true wish: that I would be
a better painter than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the vantage point of the east side of the mountain, he
was more than good enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
