<SLUG> BC-DEM-TV-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS UPSTAGING GOP ON GRASP OF CONVENTION AS SHOWBIZ 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The moment to savor from the first days of the Democratic
convention did not come from any speech or from the uninspired
passing-of-the-torch from Bill Clinton to Al Gore in the Midwest
Tuesday in a photo-op that left Gore looking diminished.
</P>
<P>
   No, it was the irresistible moment when Clinton hoisted an Oscar
in his hand, given to him by California's governor, Gray Davis, at
a party at Paramount studios after Clinton's triumphant convention
speech on Monday. The image, which popped up on the cable news
channels and ``Entertainment Tonight,'' was almost too telling:
Bill Clinton is a once-in-a-lifetime political performer, at home
at this Hollywood convention.
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than Clinton's star presence that has made the
Democratic convention more effective as television than the
Republican meeting was two weeks ago. Simply by lining up Caroline
Kennedy to speak in prime time, the Democrats revealed their grasp
of the convention as show business.
</P>
<P>
   She is the kind of personality who might attract viewers who
care nothing about politics (just as Christopher Reeve was the name
attraction at the Democratic convention four years ago). And she
provided the ripple effect of publicity few can, as she gave bland
interviews on Tuesday night's ABC, CBS and NBC evening news
programs alongside her uncle, Sen. Ted Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Caroline factor is more emotional than high-minded, more
practical than political, and good marketing: viewers who come to
gawk at a celebrity may pick up a bit of the party's message along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Going in, the Democrats had more glitter to work with than the
Republicans. It was amusing to see stars line up to be interviewed
by the floor reporters, then evade the Joe
Lieberman-meets-Hollywood question. Christie Brinkley, a New York
delegate, was on CNN and Fox News; Sarah Jessica Parker was on
MSNBC. Asked about Lieberman's criticism of Hollywood as
irresponsibly loaded with sex and violence, they said it was great
that America allows for different opinions.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Clinton's farewell speech that made him the
convention's true name above the title, demonstrating that he can
do what none of the presidential and vice-presidential candidates
on either ticket can: engage the camera and maintain a visceral
connection with his audience even when he's saying something
serious.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, Lieberman and George W. Bush can all manage that emotional
contact in casual, close-up television appearances. (Dick Cheney
has trouble even with that much.) When making a serious point,
their own eyes seem to glaze over; imagine what happens to ours.
</P>
<P>
   But when Clinton said in his speech that it would be a mistake
to underestimate American military strength, he looked into the
camera ominously, as if staring down an enemy with his glare.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton's mastery of political theater includes a shrewd
grasp of how it has changed in the age of talk-show confessions. By
talking about his need for forgiveness before an audience of
ministers and television cameras last week, he got the Lewinsky
affair out of the way before the convention. But even the famed
Clinton compartmentalizing only goes so far.
</P>
<P>
   His contrite appearance before the ministers was not quickly
shuffled to the video archives. Clips have been played so
relentlessly that it must be at least as familiar to viewers as any
snippet of his convention speech. In the end, even Clinton can't
completely control his image.
</P>
<P>
   And if he, with his supreme mastery of the media, can't do that,
what hope is there for a media mortal like Al Gore? His iconic
moment boomeranged Tuesday. In the joint appearance in Michigan,
Clinton spoke briefly, then relinquished his place behind the
podium with the presidential seal to the Gore, who took off his
jacket as he stepped forward. Maybe he was hot. But there has been
so much publicity about the reconstructed Gore images that the move
seemed calculated to show him in a more casual light and to
distinguish him from the president. Clinton would have made such a
gesture seem natural, even if it wasn't. Gore made it seem false,
even if it was genuine.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that while Gore was giving a typically stiff
speech, Bill and Hillary Clinton, and even Tipper Gore, stood
behind him waving to the crowd, whispering to each other, looking
as restless as a group of bored schoolchildren. If he couldn't keep
his friends and family interested, what will he do in his big
acceptance speech on Thursday?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
