<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: WITH SKIES CHOKED, A RAIL ALTERNATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication notice: also sent with `t' code) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Daily Mail of London noted in an article this week that some
airlines in Europe are ``manipulating timetables'' _ arbitrarily
adding minutes to schedules to buy time against flight delays. One
flight from London to Paris that took 50 minutes in 1975 now is
scheduled for 95 minutes. That's five minutes longer than the same
flight took in 1947, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   On some days, as air traffic systems strain under the increased
demand, a third of the flights in Western Europe are delayed. Yet,
as annoying as this undoubtedly is, there is none of the same sense
of crisis in Europe as in the United States over mounting gridlock
in the skies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that there are alternatives. In Europe, the
railroads remain vital components of the transportation system.
Experienced American business travelers, traveling through Europe
on those itineraries that flip them rapidly from one city to
another, have learned that the train is almost always a better bet
on a trip of 400 miles or less.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed trains traveling at speeds up to 200 miles an hour on
new networks of dedicated track have become major competitors to
airlines for the short-haul business travel market, said Joseph M.
Fiorenza, vice president for business travel services of Rail
Europe, a joint venture of the French and Swiss national railroads
that sells European rail services in the United States
(www.raileurope.com or 888 382-7245).
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of business travelers, the whole air-to-rail
equation is changing now that they can get from London to Paris,
say, in about three hours _ and that's downtown to downtown, not
outlying airport to airport,'' Fiorenza said.
</P>
<P>
   Eurostar passenger trains now make as many as 24 departures a
day from London to Paris (three hours) or Brussels (2 hours and 36
minutes). On other European rail systems, trains are taking market
share from planes. High-speed rail now accounts for 17 percent of
all western European passenger traffic. In France, the figure is 48
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, can we expect ever to see anything
approaching that kind of rail service as the air travel system
reaches capacity?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we have a long way to go, on bumpy roadbed,
before more than a relative handful of frequent travelers will
regard trains as a practical alternative to planes. While European
train lines persevered and improved over the years, the
once-awesome U.S. rail system degenerated into a comparative
Toonerville Trolley operation.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak, the government-subsidized national rail company created
in 1970 to salvage some intercity rail service, has swallowed an
estimated $25 billion in subsidies since its inception. Some
critics say the money hasn't bought anything approaching a
first-rate rail system.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Amtrak's costly and much-heralded Acela Express,
promising 150-mile-an-hour trains cutting about an hour off the
more than four hours travel time between New York and Boston, has
been delayed for more than a year because of track problems and
design problems with the trains themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are some small signs that, here and
there, trains are hauling at least a handful of people who
otherwise might be adding to sky-crowding. Last week, Amtrak said
that ridership on the heavily traveled Northeast corridor route was
up 6 percent in July. Travel to the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia accounted for some of that, but Amtrak said that
some appears to have come from passengers who took the train
because they were disgusted with routine flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   About 17 percent of the passengers on the Northeast corridor in
the 1998 fiscal year were business travelers, said Rick Remington,
an Amtrak spokesman. Critics of Amtrak as a sluggish bureaucracy
might find it interesting that the latest demographic information
Amtrak would provide for its ridership is two years old. Rail
Europe was able to readily produce current figures.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Amtrak eventually gets its Acela high-speed trains to
run, it remains to be seen whether more than a handful of American
business travelers will follow the patterns in western Europe,
where a three-hour trip has become the point at which the scale
tips between air and rail.
</P>
<P>
   Even with 1998 numbers, though, the prospects are interesting
for the 18.3 million passengers Amtrak says traveled by train or
air on Boston-New York-Philadelphia-Washington routes. Of that
number, the train got about 71 percent of all passengers traveling
between New York and Washington, a trip that takes about three
hours maximum.
</P>
<P>
   But between New York and Boston, a trip that now takes over four
hours by train, ``the figures really flip-flop,'' Remington said.
On that route, planes get about 71 percent of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The three hours is the tipping point here as well, he said,
adding, ``That's what high-speed rail is all about _ to get our New
York-Boston market share closer to what we are between New York and
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it would be a start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
