<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-GORE-DUKAKIS-ROG     08-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-GORE-DUKAKIS-ROGERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WON'T BE A DUKAKIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Wednesday, Aug. 16, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By EDWARD M. ROGERS JR.    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once before, an incumbent vice president who had
loyally served a popular two-term president ran against a
successful governor with little national campaign experience. By
midsummer, he, too, found himself faced with a deficit in the
polls, struggling to define himself beyond the shadow of the
president he served.
</P>
<P>
   Having worked on Vice President George Bush's campaign in 1988,
I can see the similarities to this year. Al Gore's advisers have
certainly studied them, too, but does no one in the his camp think
it's a bad sign when your rallying cry is ``Remember Dukakis''? And
have these advisers forgotten that Gov. George W. Bush might have
learned a thing or two working on his father's 1988 campaign?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the differences between then and now should serve as a
cautionary tale for Gore, not a source of hope.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Vice President Bush came limping out of the primaries.
He had faced a bitter fight against Sen. Bob Dole and attacks from
Pat Robertson on the right. This year, by contrast, Vice President
Gore's challenger, Bill Bradley, wilted after New Hampshire, and
Gore went on to easy wins in state after state. Shouldn't the vice
president have been stronger after his painless primaries than Bush
was in 1988 after his bruising battle?
</P>
<P>
   Also, in 1988 Michael Dukakis defeated his rivals stealthily,
remaining relatively unknown until he was the last man standing
against the left-wing candidacy of Jesse Jackson. George W. Bush,
by contrast, had to slug it out with Sen. John McCain in New
Hampshire, South Carolina and Michigan before his later victories
in New York, California and across the South. Shouldn't he be
weaker than Dukakis was at this point in the 1988 campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Some recent polls have Bush ahead now by roughly the same
percentage as Dukakis was at this point in 1988. Atwater and I were
skeptical then of Dukakis' lead. Today, though I believe that
Bush's true lead is probably not the 10 percentage points that some
polls estimate, I believe it is solid and durable.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis was what Lee Atwater called a ``phenomena candidate.''
He came out of nowhere and quickly went somewhere in the polls,
capturing attention and imagination in the process. But his lead,
although intimidating, was weak and frothy. Instead of solidifying
his edge after the primaries, he squandered it by running an
unfocused and defensive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater always said, ``In politics, never kick a man when he's
up.'' The obvious corollary is to attack when your opponent is
weak. Dukakis took his lead for granted and failed to go after us
when we were at our weakest.
</P>
<P>
   After the conventions were over in 1988, we felt Dukakis had to
solidify his lead and go on the offensive to keep Vice President
Bush on the ropes. Much to our surprise, he did neither.
</P>
<P>
   Bush headquarters in 1988 had a giddy moment during the
Democratic Convention when Dukakis said the election was about
competence, not ideology. This was an unmistakable sign that he
would run a dry campaign for chief clerk, not for leader of the
free world. We soon knew that Bush could be on his way to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore wants to say, ``I'm like Bush in '88.'' But take it from
someone who was there: he looks more like Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   (Edward M. Rogers Jr., vice chairman of the lobbying firm
Barbour Griffith &AMP; Rogers, was deputy to Lee Atwater, the campaign
manager for Vice President George Bush in 1988.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
