<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE BLAMES BIAS IN PROSECUTION OF LOS ALAMOS SCIENTIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.M.)   By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ In the first of two days of potentially
pivotal hearings in the case of the scientist accused of
mishandling important nuclear weapons secrets, defense lawyers
offered evidence Tuesday suggesting that the scientist was singled
out for prosecution largely because he was Chinese-American.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for the scientist, Wen Ho Lee, who has been held for
eight months on charges that he improperly downloaded some of the
country's most sensitive nuclear secrets, offered affidavits and
interviews from a number of top intelligence officials suggesting
that Lee was made the target of the investigation at least in part
because of his ethnicity, while some whites who might also have
come under suspicion were not pursued.
</P>
<P>
   Although the prosecutors have denied these allegations, the
defense contentions are among the reasons that Asian-Americans, the
American Civil Liberties Union and some other legal groups have
embraced Lee's case as an example of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the arguments in U.S. District Court here Tuesday
are not expected to be known for several days at least as the
judge, James Parker, decides whether to allow the defense to gain
access to reams of government documents regarding investigations of
Asian-Americans on security matters. If the defense is given access
and is able to prove that Lee was unfairly singled out for
prosecution, the judge could order that the charges in the 59-count
indictment be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   A potentially more significant hearing is scheduled for
Wednesday, in which the defense will argue again that Lee, who is
60, be released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was denied bail twice, in December and again in January,
largely because government experts contended that he had mishandled
what amounted to the ``crown jewels'' of the country's weapons
program and that if the secrets found their way to a foreign power
they could alter the international balance of military power.
</P>
<P>
   A number of portable computer tapes on which Lee stored the
secrets are missing and, though Lee has said he destroyed them, the
government has insisted he may be able to pass them to a hostile
country if he is released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has affidavits from a former Los Alamos director and
some other experts arguing that much of what Lee downloaded from a
secure to an unsecure computer at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory was either already available publicly, would be of
modest or no use to most countries, and was not even given a secret
classification until after Lee had been fired last year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the judge earlier appeared to have relied heavily
on government allegations that Lee deceived another Los Alamos
scientist by using the other person's computer for downloading. The
defense says it now has evidence that no such deception took place.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors have indicated with their filings that they
still believe Lee presents a grave risk and that bail is not
justified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
