r s BC-GOLF-ELS0816-COX     08-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-ELS0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As weather warms, Els would like to turn up heat on Woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - Ernie Els navigated the steep hill from the
18th green to the clubhouse Tuesday afternoon, signed a few
autographs and immediately sought shade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough week, especially with the heat, and I
think it's going to get warmer,'' Els said. ``It's already in the
90s, and it feels like it's 120.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried to acclimate himself last week by practicing at
mid-afternoon in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Els has been the runner-up in all three of this year's majors so
far, twice to Tiger Woods, in the U.S. Open and British Open. But
the South African hopes for a different forecast beginning Thursday
at Valhalla Golf Club. The obvious goal is to turn up the heat on
Woods in the 82nd PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will try for three majors in a season for the first time
since Ben Hogan in 1953. But Els has won two of his last three
events the European Tour's Loch Lomond Invitational before the
British Open and then the International on the PGA Tour after St.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not complaining about my year,'' said Els, who won U.S.
Opens in 1994 and 1997, before Woods started his major championship
pillage. ``I'm not feeling like a loser out there. . . . But I
still believe if I play my best golf, I can really give it a
shot.'' Else doesn't want to complete an Avis Grand Slam on Sunday.
``I've had a pretty good year, even if I don't play well from here
on, which I don't want to do,'' Els said. ``I think the guy that
won obviously just played unbelievable. You're playing a guy that's
just playing out of this world. . . . But, hopefully, this week I
can play at a little higher level, and let's see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Greg Norman shared the lead after 54 holes of all four
majors but won only the British Open. Norman has been the runner-up
in six Grand Slam events.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he was asked if he had ``given Els any advice on
finishing second in majors.'' The old, less mellow Norman might
have jumped over the interview table at the reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any advice for him, but I think he dropped that
hurdle at the International,'' Norman said. ``Sometimes, you just
run into an unusual shot or a hot player. I think if Jack Nicklaus
had the same question asked about how many seconds he had at major
championships (19), I'm sure (he'd say) you can't control what
other people do and feel. I'm sure Ernie feels the same way. He
can't control what other people do. So, sometimes second is better
than 10th.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said, ``I think Ernie has had one of the greatest years in
golf, for not winning a major, like what Greg (Norman) did in '86
-- the Saturday Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very similar to that,'' Wood said. ``He's played
absolutely wonderful golf. It's just that unfortunately he has come
up second. He's proven that he's a great player, and, by finishing
close to winning, you learn a lot. I'm sure he has learned, and
he'll probably apply it this week.''
</P>
<P>
   With every mound, hump and collection area the 30-year-old Els
visits at Valhalla, his comfort zone could be growing. A winner 10
days ago in the International at Castle Pines, another Jack
Nicklaus course, Els sees some of the same target lines and can
visualize shaping the same shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite a major championship golf course, meaning that
it doesn't quite live up to Pebble Beach and St. Andrews,
history-wise, but it's a very good golf course,'' Els said. ``It's
a good golf course to play a major championship at. The condition
of the course is brilliant. It's much better than it was four years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a venue that should bring more players into contention
than might normally be the case at a major. Not overly long at
7,167 yards and running faster by the day, Valhalla has more of a
TPC feel than traditional major sites. For the longer hitters, the
four par-5's are reachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put it in the fairway, the long hitters definitely have
a chance to turn their rounds around,'' Els said, ``but generally
speaking, you've got to put the ball in play. The longer hitters
can do that with 2-irons and 3-woods. Other guys might have to use
drivers, but if they're straight enough, they can play with the big
guns this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
