<SLUG> BC-UGA-ADMISSIONS0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Georgia to halt using race in borderline
admissions cases
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The University of Georgia will no longer consider
race in borderline admissions decisions, president Michael Adams
said Tuesday, while it appeals a ruling by a federal judge that the
practice is discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement many considered inevitable, Adams focused on
the university's decision to take the July 24 ruling by U.S.
District Judge B. Avant Edenfield to the 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta _ and possibly to the U.S. Supreme Court
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to use race in admissions decisions would only invite
more lawsuits, Adams said, a position echoed by Chancellor Stephen
Portch. Many on the UGA campus and in the state legislature
expected the university to appeal. Attorney Lee Parks, who sued UGA
over the policy, said Adams has a lot of constituencies to answer
to, including politicians, the Board of Regents, alumni and
faculty, who expect him ``to pursue what they consider the high
moral ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Appealing was the university's only political option, Parks
said, calling it ``window dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits focused on the Total Student Index, or TSI, an
evaluative tool used in about 1,200 admissions cases. It assigns a
numeric value to various factors, including economic and academic
disadvantage, Georgia residency, academic factors, leadership,
whether parents attended college, whether immediate family members
are UGA alumni and _ until Tuesday _ ethnic origin.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of previous litigation, UGA dropped gender from the
TSI last year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the university's 23,000 undergraduates were admitted on
academic merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These decisions that I announce today are in keeping with our
goal stated last year to continue to act both aggressively and
responsibly in this area,'' Adams said. ``It is clear that the
State of Georgia must do all it can to make the benefits of higher
education available to the broadest possible segment of its
population.''
</P>
<P>
   The university has agreed to comply with the court's order by
offering admission and paying damages to three women _ Jennifer
Johnson, Aimee Bogrow and Molly Ann Beckenhauer _ who sued UGA over
its admissions policies.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, who represents the three, said they are ``getting their
books'' and are happy not to wait another year to enroll. He
praised the university for admitting the women and not using the
appeal to block them from attending UGA.
</P>
<P>
   Adams wouldn't discuss how much money was paid inthe settlement,
saying such issues were better left to attorneys. But he did say
the university has spent more than $400,000 in its defense. Parks
said he has submitted a $500,000 bill for his legal services, which
span three years.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he consulted extensively with Gov. Roy Barnes, Portch
and the regents, ``looking at as many options as possible,'' and
that they reached ``near unanimity on the decision to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents has vowed to pursue an ``extremely
vigorous'' legal appeal to allow UGA to use race in admission
decisions. The Georgia policy was devised after the 1978 Supreme
Court ruling in Regents of the University of California vs. Bakke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate on the use of affirmative action in promoting
diversity on the nation's college campuses for educational purposes
has reached the critical point where a clear-cut decision must be
reached,'' said Portch. ``The University System of Georgia and
other universities throughout the nation face continuing litigation
on this issue. We are willing to assume a leadership role if it
will help resolve this issue definitively. It is in the interest of
the state, the nation and the academic community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents met behind closed doors last week to
discuss the case. Chairman Glenn White said the board considers the
issues important enough to continue the fight and is prepared ``to
take any and all steps necessary to resolve this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
