<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF SPORTS GAMES ARE A BUSINESS, COLLEGES INVITE PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One autumn day in the 1970s, when Harold L. Enarson was
president of Ohio State University, he attended a football game in
which Ohio State was pitted against one of its traditional rivals.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, Ohio State lost. And, as even worse luck
would have it, Enarson encountered a reporter for the student
newspaper as he left the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter asked for his reaction to the defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Enarson shrugged and said, ``After all, it's only a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, a banner headline in the newspaper screamed
``AFTER ALL, IT'S ONLY A GAME!'' and an editorial thundered against
the president for being destitute of team spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That remark was never forgotten and never forgiven,'' Enarson
recalled recently. ``No matter how dutiful I was in attending
athletic events, which I hugely enjoyed, any hint that I wasn't a
true jock was held against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Intercollegiate football _ the players are already in training
for the new season _ demands absolute devotion. Not just from
players, coaches and presidents, but from students, faculty,
administrators, alumni and fans. And that is why abuses in the
system so often go unreported and uncorrected, and why the game _
now more a fixture of the national entertainment industry than
higher education _ is allowed to spread a corrupting influence.
</P>
<P>
   Standards of admission and academic performance are routinely
cast to the winds for star football players, according to Linda
Bensel-Meyers, a Renaissance literature scholar at the University
of Tennessee, who has challenged her university on those practices
and is now embroiled in a bitter legal dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, athletes are not infrequently accused of theft and
the physical abuse of women, and the authorities are notoriously
reluctant to punish them.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview shortly before his death a year ago, Michael
Hooker, who was chancellor of the University of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill, said that corruption was widespread in intercollegiate
football.
</P>
<P>
   But little is done about the problems because of this need for
total devotion to the sport, and because so many colleges and
universities have allowed themselves to become dependent on
football for two vital commodities: money, from donors and from
lucrative television contracts, and a flood of choice students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're in the midst of a major fund-raising
campaign,'' explained the trustee chairman of a large Midwestern
university, ``and the entertainment value of football has a way of
helping by keeping our name before the public.''
</P>
<P>
   As for recruiting students, admissions officers talk with awe
about ``the Flutie spike'' _ the phenomenal increase in
applications at Boston College in the mid-1980s tied to the
heart-stopping performances of a quarterback named Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions officers know that a star player can attract many
more students than half a dozen Nobel Prize winners on the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any deliverance from this situation, it may be found
in the work of Harvie Branscomb, the former chancellor of
Vanderbilt University who died two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his inauguration as chancellor, Branscomb recalled in
his memoir ``Purely Academic'' (Vanderbilt University Press, 1978),
how he set out to ``de-emphasize'' intercollegiate football. He
decided to ``build up a countertradition, one of playing
prestigious institutions not eminent for their athletics but for
their academic accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan backfired when Vanderbilt crushed Yale, dashing all
hope of a rematch with any Ivy League school. A few years later,
Branscomb urged the Vanderbilt trustees to put into practice a
series of reforms, including reducing the number of athletic
scholarships. But three days later, the Vanderbilt football team
once again unwittingly sabotaged his effort. The team scored a
sensational victory over Alabama, 22-20, which created such
excitement in Nashville that all thought of reform evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   In his memoir, Branscomb made a final stab at the problem, which
merits consideration today.
</P>
<P>
   Academic institutions that feel the need for semiprofessional
sports teams, Branscomb said, should establish a school of
athletics much like ones for dentistry and agriculture. The schools
should offer preparation for sports careers and should also recruit
the players needed for strong teams. And, responding to the
concerns of people like Bensel-Meyers, these specialized schools
should relieve their academically oriented counterparts of the
pressure to compromise admissions and other standards in order to
produce championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll be the first to give it a try?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
