<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GLOBE TO UNVEIL FOUR NEW SECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston Globe next month will unveil four new
sections, expanded business coverage, and a graphic redesign of the
entire newspaper, publisher Richard H. Gilman announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Thursday, Sept. 28, a 16-page ``Globe West'' section
will focus on Boston's western suburbs. It will cover 35 cities and
towns west of Boston, providing more local news coverage for
readers in that growing region.
</P>
<P>
   Town and school news will receive greater attention in the new
section, as will local voices, and information on dining and
entertainment, events, and real estate. There also will be coverage
of issues related to senior citizens and youth, as well as expanded
high school sports news. It will be published in four different
editions, each covering six to 11 communities. There will be two
advertising zones to allow local stores the ability to target their
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important new program that will make the Globe more
useful and informative for readers in the growing metrowest area,''
Gilman said. ``It will provide more local news coverage for readers
and more marketing opportunities for local advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   The section will replace the existing Sunday ``West Weekly''
section and run on Thursdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said having two zoned editions would benefit local
merchants, who will be able to better target advertisements to
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   In other initiatives:
</P>
<P>
   --The redesigned pages of the Globe will make their debut
Wednesday, Sept. 13. The redesign will feature new typefaces
throughout the paper for a cleaner, more readable look on the
narrower 50-inch pages the Globe adopted earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   --The Globe also is introducing ``Life at Home'' and
``Marketplace.'' The first will be a revitalized version of the
current ``At Home'' section and will appear on Thursdays, starting
Sept. 14. It will focus on decorating, lifestyles, entertaining,
gardening, and home renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Marketplace, set to launch two weeks later, will be a
stand-alone classified advertising section that also runs
Thursdays. It will be published in six editions and will feature
articles on real estate, jobs, and cars.
</P>
<P>
   --Business coverage also will be expanded significantly.
Beginning Sunday, Sept. 17, a new section called BostonWorks will
add stories and columns on careers and recruiting issues to the
current Help Wanted section. The Sunday business section will be
enlarged and redesigned, and the reporting on the biotechnology
industry will be increased in the daily paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
