<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BO-DIDDLEY-CARS-ART-N     08-15 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BO-DIDDLEY-CARS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BO DIDDLEY USES HIS CLASSIC CARS _ AS WELL AS HIS GUITAR _ TO REACH
YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By BOB ARNDORFER   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRONSON, Fla. _ Stretched around the circular drive outside
Ellas McDaniel's home near Bronson, the three lanky cars conjure
images of opening night at The Apollo.
</P>
<P>
   One imagines Jackie Wilson or the Isley Brothers sliding out of
the back of the white-on-brown Lincoln limo. Or Ruth Brown and
Chuck Berry being ushered out one of the eight doors of the
too-long Mercury. And God only knows who might emerge from the
stern of the purple Caddy hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Why, it's none other than the man in the know, Bo Diddley.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cars represent the real roots of rock 'n' roll,'' said
McDaniel, known professionally as Bo Diddley, the Chicago-bred Rock
'n' Roll Hall of Famer who for years has made his home, and music,
in rural North Central Florida. ``These cars helped us survive.
Cats who couldn't afford the big buses rode in these things to get
to their gigs.''
</P>
<P>
   The energetic 71-year-old rock legend has added a trio of
unusual cars to his eclectic fleet, which varies from a motorless
'53 Chevy to a motor home he said is difficult to park. With one of
his grandsons and a family friend, McDaniel has resurrected three
aging cars that are at once an eye-catching archive of rock history
and a billboard to his vision of a drug-free opportunity for
youths.
</P>
<P>
   His pride and joy may be the stretched 1978 Mercury station
wagon he found this past fall in near-by Chiefland. At 25 feet
long, he thinks it might have been used by a funeral home to
transport the bereaved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all rotted out,'' McDaniel said, tapping the wagon's
right rear corner with thick fingers that have strummed some of the
most influential guitar notes in music history. ``We put all new
metal in there. There's very little Bondo,'' he said, referring to
a type of plastic filler used in body repair.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a building McDaniel built on the family compound, he and
his helpers rebuilt the Mercury's engine and transmission, brakes
and other parts. They re-covered the vinyl top and painted the car
lime green.
</P>
<P>
   To the sprightly canvas McDaniel added a litany of titles from
his catalog of hit songs and, on both front doors, graphics of his
signature ``square-headed'' guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Don't Know Diddley,'' ``Gun Slinger'' and ``Say Man''
adorn the Mercury's hood. ``This is real Rock and Roll'' reads the
left front fender. Down the block, doors are embellished with ``I
Am A Man,'' ``I Am Sorry'' and ``Diddley Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't It Good to Be Free'' decorates the right rear fender.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something everybody in America should cherish,''
McDaniel said, rubbing the letters made for him by a friend. ``Good
to be free. These kids today should understand that, but they
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed among the mobile library of hits are messages aimed at
young people. For years McDaniel has crusaded for youths, and has
played many free concerts devoted to helping at-risk youths choose
alternatives to lives of drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids Being in a Gang Is Lame,'' ``Keep Kids Drug Free'' and
``Down With the Pusher'' are among the body-panel slogans. A ``Keep
Kids Drug Free'' specialty license plate rides the Mercury's rear
bumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message for children is to see that you can be constructive
and not destructive,'' McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1977 Lincoln limousine he has rebuilt, he said, was similar
to one he and other rock pioneers used to ride in 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie Wilson had one just like it,'' he said. ``Or was it
Ruth Brown?''
</P>
<P>
   A work in progress is the '69 Cadillac hearse painted purple.
It's a year newer than the hearse McDaniel used a generation ago to
travel from gig to gig, towing a U-Haul trailer for the
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   With help from his wife, Sylvia, McDaniel is fitting the
hearse's cavernous interior with a mobile recording studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ripped all the casket junk out of it,'' said McDaniel, who
noted that he never attends funerals. ``Yeah, I plan to do some
recording in there. I'm thinking about putting `Wanna make a
record? Climb In' on the side ... I'd like to be able to help some
of these young kids _ not the bad ones _ make their own CDs.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel said he's always been fascinated with automobiles and
motors. His first car was an air-cooled 1920s Franklin given to him
by an uncle who owned an auto salvage yard in Chicago. He has
always been a tinkerer, he said, and enjoys woodworking and auto
mechanics as a way to relax.
</P>
<P>
   He's mindful, though, of taking care of his hands when he's
working on cars. For a man who still plays music all over the world
dozens of times a year, his hands are his livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel demonstrated that _ after rain drove him away from
showing off his cars _ in a tiny studio where he continues to make
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've created a new beat,'' said McDaniel, whose unique rhythms
45 years ago helped transform popular music. ``I call it the
Bounce, the Bathroom Bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel cued up a 16-track tape, tinkered with some buttons and
levers on his new mixer and produced an unfinished version of his
new sound. The driving beat was infectious, and when he cranked up
the volume, even the motorless '53 Chevy out back almost came to
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you do, to show fans that you're not finished
yet,'' McDaniel said after playing a sampling from another of his
new projects, a lengthy, hard-driving ode to the Book of Genesis he
has titled ``The Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   On occasional trips around the region or farther _ ``I could
head to California in the Mercury right now,'' McDaniel said _ he
hopes his classic vehicles might inspire some thoughts about what
it was like for the hard-working leaders of the rock movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cars are some of where I came from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These latest additions to McDaniel's fleet may have been
inspired by a car he found in the late 1960s along side a road in
St. Louis, a stretched 1957 Chevy wagon. He named it ``Betsy,'' and
it took him and his band, Bo Diddley &AMP; Co., all over the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '57 Chevrolet put us over the hump,'' McDaniel said. ``It
never failed me ... We had a rack on top where we put our
instruments. That '57 carried us everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel will probably never find another Betsy, but he seems
just as happy with his purple hearse, chocolate limo and especially
the eight-door Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
