<SLUG> BC-NAVISTAR-LAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVISTAR CUTS 1,100 JOBS, CITING TRUCK ORDER DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Responding to a slowdown in heavy-truck orders in
North America, Navistar International Corp. said Tuesday that it
would lay off 1,100 employees, or about 15 percent of its
white-collar work force.
</P>
<P>
   The company, one of the world's largest makers of heavy trucks,
buses and diesel engines, said that after several years of
spectacular growth, the company had to act because orders for big
trucks in North America had been falling steadily, largely because
of higher interest rates, soaring fuel prices and a glut of used
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Navistar, which is based in Chicago, comes
just a day after Freightliner, a unit of DaimlerChrysler AG and the
world's biggest maker of heavy trucks, said that it would cut 3,475
jobs, or about 19 percent of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Paccar, the world's No. 2 truck maker, based
in Bellevue, Wash., said that it would lay off 430 workers at a
big-truck plant in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Though the economy remains strong, and demand for diesel engines
and buses is robust, Navistar and other truck makers are trying to
head off a cyclical downturn after what some industry experts said
was two years of ``excessive demand'' for heavy-duty rigs. Higher
interest rates have made it more expensive to finance the purchase
of a new truck, and higher diesel prices have forced some trucking
companies to park their rigs.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, over the last year, orders for heavy-duty trucks _
which often cost $80,000 to $100,000 _ fell nearly 30 percent.
Freightliner said Tuesday that it expected heavy-duty truck sales
in North America to drop about 25 percent from 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And earlier this year, Navistar laid off 800 employees in
Canada, where its heavy-duty trucks are made, and the company says
it may cut 500 more jobs. The company, which markets its big trucks
under the International brand name, has 19,000 employees worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Navistar announcement was contained in its third-quarter
earnings release, which reported profits excluding special items of
$76 million, or $1.27 a share, compared with $77 million, or $1.17
a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue edged up to $1.92
billion from $1.88 billion. The results slightly beat Wall Street
projections of $1.24 a share, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Navistar, which have been weak for much of the last
year, fell $1.9375 Tuesday, to $37.125.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Horne, the chairman and chief executive of Navistar,
said in a statement that the company was working to become less
cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steps we plan will allow us to continue to build a healthy
business in the downturn,'' he said, ``and come out even stronger
when the market turns up again.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would also take a charge in the fourth
quarter related to the 1,100 job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Though heavy trucks orders, which make up about a quarter of
Navistar's sales, are in decline, orders for medium-sized trucks
are more stable, and sales of Navistar's diesel engines, which are
used in UPS, U-Haul and pickup trucks, continues to grow. The
company is also supplying diesel engines to Ford Motor Co., which
uses them in its sport utility vehicles. The company also said its
school bus division is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that they were not surprised by the
Navistar announcement. Many investors have been warned about a drop
in orders going back more than a year, and the stock prices of many
of the big truck and engine makers have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the ninth inning in the stock prices,'' said Tobias
M. Levkovich, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. ``This news has
all been discounted and we think we might see a recovery by next
spring in the order patterns.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
