u a BC-NJ-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      08-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. HIGH COURT STRIKES DOWN BILL REQUIRING PARENTAL NOTIFICATION
OF ABORTION
</HEADLINE>
  By LAURA MANSNERUS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Rejecting the State Legislature's attempt to
join the growing list of states that restrict abortion for
teen-agers, the New Jersey Supreme Court on Tuesday struck down a
law requiring parental notice for unmarried girls under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   The court's 4-2 decision held that the notice requirement,
enacted and signed by Gov. Christie Whitman last year, violated the
equal protection guarantee of the New Jersey Constitution by
imposing a burden on minors seeking abortions that it did not
impose on those who continue their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision signaled that even with many new appointees, the
court continues to give individual liberties more expansive
protection than the federal courts, as it has for decades. And
lawmakers complained on Tuesday, as they have for decades, about
the court's readiness to overturn legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, a Republican from Salem County,
said the decision ``stretches the imagination.'' He added: ``This
court, as they continually do, decide what they want the laws of
this state to be.''
</P>
<P>
   By relying on the State Constitution, the court was more
protective of abortion rights than the U.S. Supreme Court, which
has upheld parental notification statutes as long as they provided
for a waiver of the requirement by a judge.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 states have enacted laws requiring parental
involvement, and in some cases a parent's consent, in a minor's
abortion decision.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision cannot be appealed, as the State Supreme
Court is the final arbiter of the New Jersey Constitution. The
court had blocked enforcement of the law pending its full review.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed on Tuesday that the court's strong language
left little if any room for the Legislature to amend the statute.
Rather, opponents of abortion said they would work toward a
constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Marie Tasy, an official of New Jersey Right to
Life, said, ``I think the decision is outrageous, that it defies
common sense and ignores the integrity of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, some legislators called for a reconsideration of
the judicial selection process here and even for impeachment
proceedings against the four justices who joined the majority.
</P>
<P>
   The decision relieved abortion rights advocates, who had been
surprised by the legislation and alarmed by Whitman's quick assent
to it, at a time when she was currying support from conservatives
in preparation to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just delighted that the Supreme Court reaffirmed New
Jersey's strong commitment to reproductive choice and recognized
the substantial burdens this placed on New Jersey teen-agers,''
said Jennifer Dalven, a lawyer for the American Civil Liberties
Union Foundation, who argued the case for Planned Parenthood and
abortion providers.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to the decision by Whitman, a Republican, was
muted. The governor said in a statement that the administration was
reviewing the opinion and that when she signed the legislation, ``I
believed that the bill struck a common-sense balance'' between the
rights of parents to be informed and the rights of minors to choose
whether to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the court's majority opinion, Chief Justice Deborah T.
Poritz said that the State Constitution ``does not permit the state
to impose disparate and unjustifiable burdens on different classes
of young women when fundamental constitutional rights hang in the
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenora Lapidus, legal director of the ACLU in Newark, noted that
the justices, most of them appointees of Whitman, ``did nothing out
of line here but continued the long tradition of interpreting our
state's Constitution protectively and broadly to guarantee
fundamental rights.'' Lapidus said parental notice statutes had
been struck down on similar grounds by state courts in Florida,
Montana, Alaska and California.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey law, passed in June 1999 by a vote of 59-17 in
the Assembly and 31-8 in the Senate, was supposed to have been
saved by its ``judicial bypass'' provision. That provision allows a
judge to waive the notification requirement if it would not be in
the girl's best interest or if she is ``sufficiently mature'' to
make her own decision. But the court held that the hearing
procedure itself was a burden that could not be justified by the
state's interest in requiring notification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
