<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BROGNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND SLAM LIFTS A WEIGHT OFF BROGNA'S SHOULDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are so many unforgiving winter mornings, when it
would be so easy for him, as a baseball player, to still be in bed.
Instead, he is in a gym, lifting weights and running laps, alone
with his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the times,'' Rico Brogna said Tuesday, ``when you
think and dream of moments like this. That's why you really play.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the day after Brogna, a child of New England, hit a
game-winning grand slam for the Red Sox, a bottom-of-the-ninth
slice of high drama Monday night that not only instantly leaped to
the top of his personal highlights list but also made the uniform
he is now wearing feel so much more comfortable than it had.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest,'' he said, ``I now feel like I have been here a
lot longer than I have, even though it's just been a couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a definite feeling of bonding that goes to another
level after a moment like that. You really feel like you're a part
of something. The reception I got from the fans and my teammates,
I've never experienced anything like that. It was fantastic, really
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox claimed Brogna on waivers just 13 days ago from the
Philadelphia Phillies. He and his wife, Melissa, and their
soon-to-be 3-year-old daughter, Alexa, are staying in a Boston
hotel, debating whether they should remain there for the balance of
the season. In the offseason, they live in Watertown, Conn., the
town to which Brogna's family moved from Turners Falls, Mass., when
he was 7 years old, but he is a free agent after this season, and
where he fits in the Sox' long-term plans is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   But those concerns can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``A moment like this doesn't last long,'' Brogna said. ``It's a
new day, there's a new game. But you only have a few moments like
this, and there's no question you enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day you go to the ballpark, you dream of that kind of
scenario playing itself out. In this day and age, people have this
misconception that ballplayers play for other reasons, like
monetary and whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play for two reasons: To win, and to have moments like
(Monday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brogna came to the ballpark on a gloomy, soggy Monday
afternoon, he wasn't even in Jimy Williams's starting lineup. He
was on the bench until the eighth inning, when he entered as a
pinch runner for Brian Daubach. He remained in the game at first
base, and was in the dugout in the ninth, the score still tied at
3, when Darren Lewis was hit by a pitch and stole second. A fly
ball by Trot Nixon advanced Lewis to third, but the Sox were down
to their final out after Jason Varitek struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild then elected to walk Carl
Everett and Nomar Garciaparra, preferring to take his chances with
Brogna. Brogna said his legs were shaking when he went to the
plate, a sellout crowd screaming, ``Ri-co, Ri-co,'' as he strode to
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   You know that stuff about players blocking out all sound when
the place is going nuts? Maybe that's true for some guys. Brogna
heard it all, and it left his palms slick with perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Taylor, the Devil Rays' reliever, threw four straight
fastballs, running the count to 2-and-2. Brogna guessed he might
get a breaking ball. He guessed right, and drove the ball over the
head of right fielder Jose Guillen. Brogna had taken just a few
steps when the ball landed in the visitors bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Grand slam, great win.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-off home run? Hardly. Brogna was greeted at home plate by a
swarm of teammates who formed a laughing, screaming circle that
bounced up and down and transported him off the field in a crazy,
impromptu dance of joy. And the roar that Brogna heard from the
crowd as he made his way back to the dugout, his arms triumphantly
raised, was the same roar he once imagined in his backyard, as a
child of Red Sox Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To feel that electricty first hand,'' he said Tuesday, ``was
amazing. Everyone was standing, just going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he talked by phone to his mom and dad and Melissa's
parents, back in Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family said everyone back there was going berserk,'' he
said. ``I saw it on the highlights on TV a couple of times. I still
got chills watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a great way to start a homestand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can build on something like this,'' said Brogna.
``I've seen teams gain momentum from wins like this, regardless of
who gets the hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he was in the starting lineup, but Brogna has no
promises from Williams that he'll be playing every day. Last
weekend in Texas, Williams pulled him aside and told him he'd be
sharing time with Daubach. And Jose Offerman will soon be off the
disabled list, which could cut even more into his playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still going to take the same approach,'' said Brogna.
``That this is the way it's going to be the rest of the year. I'm
just a spoke in the wheel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
