<SLUG> BC-UNDERWATER-RESCUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVING BELL OLDEST UNDERWATER RESCUE DEVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using diving bells to rescue crewmembers from a downed
submarine, as the Russians are trying to do, is the oldest method
around, but _ conditions permitting _ it is a method that is known
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander the Great took a dive in a kind of diving bell in 330
BC.
</P>
<P>
   There are newer rescue devices, such as the small submarines
developed by the US Navy, but they have yet to be used in a real
rescue situation. Diving bells, on the other hand, have been used
with success, including in 1939 when most of the crew of the US
submarine Squalus was rescued after the vessel went down off
Portsmouth harbor following the failure of a valve.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three of Squalus' crewmembers safely reached the surface.
Twenty six others died onboard before the rescue vessel arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The situation those submariners endured for more than 24 hours
before the rescue was eerily similar to that faced by the Russian
crew now: They were in the dark, it was cold, oxygen was dwindling,
and the only way they could communicate with the outside world was
by banging on the hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would tap on the hull with a hammer to send messages,''
said Gerald McLees of Portsmouth, N.H., one of the Squalus
survivors. ``They would reply through underwater sound gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cold and darkness, the survivors at least were able
to tell exactly what was going on around them because of the
sounds, McLees said. ``Noise carries forever, seems like, under the
water. They sent Morse code, and you could hear it underwater.''
And when the rescue ship Falcon came near, he said, ``We could hear
their engines perfectly clearly. When a diver came down and was
walking around on the deck, we knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the long hours before the rescuers arrived with the
diving bell, McLees said, there was no panic whatsoever, because
they knew help was coming. ``We had to wait in the dark. Some of us
went to sleep. We laid in our bunks and covered up to keep warm.
There was very little talking, because they told us to conserve
oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those appear to be essentially the same conditions faced by the
Russian sailors now, except that there are two additional problems
faced by their rescuers: The weather at the surface, and the angle
of the submarine itself.
</P>
<P>
   The surface weather is a major issue, because stormy seas can
make it difficult or impossible for the surface ship to keep its
exact position over the downed submarine while the bell is lowered
and raised by cable.
</P>
<P>
   The other big problem is the angle of the submarine itself as it
lies on the bottom. Reports say the sub is tilted in two
directions, both nose down and turned on its side 60 degrees from
the vertical. Since the diving bell has a hatch on its bottom that
must line up with the sub's rescue hatch on top, and the bell has
little or no maneuvering ability, it may be impossible to make a
secure seal between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Rioux, the diving safety officer at Woods Hole (Mass.)
Oceanographic Institution, served aboard a US Navy submarine rescue
ship until 1975. He said trying to line up the craft with a tilted
sub would be ``very difficult. You need it to be vertical.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher van Alt, an engineer at the Woods Hole institution,
agreed that the angle poses a real problem. The rescue bell is
``hanging from a wire, and it's like trying to screw the lid on a
jar, and the jar is tilted.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's impossible to attach the hatch, he said, it might be
possible for the crewmembers to swim out to the rescue bell, but at
such a depth and in frigid water that would be a highly risky
last-ditch effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood of its working is pretty slim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Persico of Amsterdam, N.Y., another of the Squalus
survivors, was only 20 and the youngest crewmember to survive the
1939 accident. He came out in the last of four rescue trips by the
diving bell, and during that last trip the cable that was used to
lower the bell became snagged on something on the way down, and it
took four hours to get it clear. In the end, the last part of the
ascent was accomplished by sailors hauling in the damaged cable
hand-over-hand, he said, and when they got to the top they found
that all but two strands of the cable had broken. They were almost
literally dangling by a thread.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky there,'' Persico said laconically. But he agreed
with McLees that there had been no sense of panic. ``You're
encouraged to think positive in a submarine,'' he said. ``If you're
chicken, that's not the place for you to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Until they knew that a rescue ship would be coming, McLees said,
officers had discussed the possibility of having the crew leave the
sub through an escape hatch and make a ``free ascent'' to the
surface. But from the depth of 250 feet where the sub lay, and in
frigid water, that would have been a risky effort. ``A lot of
people probably wouldn't have made it,'' McLees said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Russian submarine, 100 feet deeper, the risks of such an
escape would be even greater, and the chances of rescue are
dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks bad,'' Persico said of the situation aboard the
Russian sub. ``I hope they just hang in there. I hope they make
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
