<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-GYM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER ALLOWED TO COMPETE IN TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shannon Miller took a giant step toward a return to
Olympus Tuesday, her petition accepted to compete in the Olympic
Gymnastics Trials that begin at the FleetCenter Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The most accomplished and decorated gymnast in US history,
Miller was among four women who competed in front of a panel of
four judges at the Fleet, their routines marked as if they were
participating in international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, Jeanette Antolin, and Amanda Stroud all were proclaimed
fit to compete in the trials. Robin Phelps, hindered by an
Achilles' tendon injury, was unable to complete the tryout.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Magnificent Seven who won the team gold medal at the
'96 Olympics in Atlanta, Miller has been recovering from a hairline
fracture in her shin and was unable to compete fully during the US
championships last month in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Antolin is recovering from an ankle injury and Stroud injured a
knee at the nationals.
</P>
<P>
   The women will make their first appearance Friday night in the
preliminaries, beginning at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Miller competed in bars at St. Louis, but was reluctant to do
more for fear of reinjuring the shin and compromising her chances
to compete here. After the nationals, Bela Karolyi, team
coordinator for the women's squad, was guardedly optimistic about
the possibility of Miller making the US squad again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' said Karolyi, ``she has to prove in three other events
that she will be capable to sustain a strong and strenuous
competition for several, several days, in the Olympic
competitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi is a big believer in the value of experience and what
someone with Miller's maturity could mean to what likely will be a
very young squad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The men's squad held an evening workout at the Fleet and will be
back Wednesday for another session, part of media day festivities.
The women take the floor for their first tuneup Wednesday night . .
. There is a slight but significant difference in how the men's and
women's squads will be picked. The four men with the highest
combined scores, factoring in the nationals (40 percent) and trials
(60 percent), will go to Sydney. Two other members will be
handpicked by head coach Peter Kormann and USA Gymnastics
officials. None of the women is guaranteed a ticket to Australia,
no matter what their combined scores, although the top three will
receive prime consideration. In the end, Karolyi and USAG directors
will make all six choices . . . Miller's medal count: 16, in world
and Olympic competition. She won two golds in Atlanta, including
team and balance beam . . . John Roethlisberger, now 30 and the
squad's senior statesman, finished seventh in the all-around
competition at the Games in '96. Blaine Wilson ranked 10th . . .
Kormann, who grew up in Braintree and won a bronze medal in floor
exercises at the '76 Games, on Wilson: ``Blaine Wilson has been the
undisputed best male gymnast in the last five years. But that is
different than winning every single time. I added up all the times
Blaine has been undefeated in the United States, and it's 110
gymnastics competitions, that he has yet to lose to another
American. That's rare. Even if you're the best guy, to go out 100
times and five consecutive USA (national) championships and prove
it on the floor _ that's extremely rare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
