<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2701 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BIOTECH-0816-COX     08-15 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biotech `gold rush' taking dot-com funds
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ You'd expect an office like Lew Shuster's at a
budget-conscious growing technology company.
</P>
<P>
   His walls are bare, dominated by a pair of mismatched
bookshelves containing financial documents and company catalogs.
His office furniture is cheap and nondescript. All he really needs
sits on the credenza behind his desk: A laptop, a Palm Pilot and a
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Around him, his business is bustling. After raising nearly $53
million in an initial public offering a year ago, the company has
just moved into one new building and has another _ its third _
under construction. Last month, it completed a string of
acquisitions and its stock is soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's company has nothing to do with dot-coms or the
Internet. His Invitrogen Corp. is in biotechnology, an industry
that is booming these days. The boom is being driven by interest in
the human genome project, new drugs coming to market and investors
looking for a new place to put their money after the dot-com
cool-down.
</P>
<P>
   The biotech sector is outperforming the overall Nasdaq market
4-to-1. Venture capitalists, including many burned by biotechs a
decade ago, are pouring money into them again. There were more
initial public offerings last month of biotech companies than of
Internet-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gene mapping companies like Celera Genomics and giant drug
makers like Amgen Inc. may grab the headlines but behind them are
hundreds of companies such as Invitrogen, which makes testing kits
used in gene analysis and other research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the gold rush,'' explained Shuster, chief operating
officer of Invitrogen, based in Carlsbad, Calif., just north of San
Diego. The region has become one of the nation's hotbeds for
biotechnology. ``And we're selling the picks and shovels and
wheelbarrows.'' Though Invitrogen made $9 million last year, just
as with dot-coms, biotechs don't have to make money to make it on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Testing equipment company Luminex Corp. of Austin, Texas, isn't
expected to make a profit until sometime in 2001. But its stock
price, currently around $36, is double what it was when it went
public in March. Chief Financial Officer James Persky attributes
interest in his and other biotech stocks in large part to the
dot-com fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just so much money that went into dot-coms,'' he
said. ``When money started moving out of there and they were
looking for someplace else to put their money, biotechs became a
hot area.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors aren't bypassing everything else to get into biotechs,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   While dot-coms are generally down, stocks of companies that
drive the Internet _ fiber-optics, Internet software and hardware
makers _ still rule on Wall Street. And the amount of venture
capital being sunk into biotechs is still just a fraction of the
money going into Internet-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disproportionate amount of action continues to be in the
(other) tech-related issues,'' said Gail Bronson, a Silicon Valley
Internet start-up executive who also is an analyst for the
publication IPO Monitor. She predicts Internet-related companies
will continue to dominate the market for new stock issues this
year.
</P>
<P>
   That said, despite one of the worst stetches on Wall Street this
year, several new biotech issues hit the floor running in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Molecular Evolution Inc., a gene therapy company, saw
its stock shoot up $11.88, or 62 percent, during its IPO a few
weeks ago. Medical products company Rita Medical Solutions Inc.'s
stock rose 20 percent on its first day of trading. Several other
biotech companies had strong IPOs in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology drugs are those based on cells, genes and other
living matter, as opposed to chemicals. While many chemical drugs _
asprin, for instance _ treat symptoms, biotech drugs _ such as
Epogen or Newpogen, which help create blood cells _ typically are
designed to treat the underlying causes of medical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is hot and there's a lot of attention on it,'' said
Tracy Lefteroff, global managing partner for consulting firm
PricewaterhouseCooper's venture capital and private equity
businesses. ``People are very excited about the completion of the
human genome project and all that it means.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first quarter of this year, more venture capital went
to biotech than in any other quarter in history. According to
figures from the National Venture Capital
AssociationOTECHFIRMS-0816-COX 08-15  &UR; BC-BIOTECHFIRMS-0816-COX
</P>
<P>
   Start-ups key to growth of biotechnology sector
</P>
<P>
   By Michael E. Kanell
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - If biotech is to grow, the sector must be fed with a
stream of start-ups coming out of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, two of the more likely sites for those labs
are Emory University and Georgia Tech, which have partnered with
state officials and the Georgia Research Alliance to start the
Emory-Georgia Tech Biotechnology Center Initiative, now being
referred to as EmTech BioSciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to build in Atlanta is critical mass,''
said Anthony J. Shuker, executive director of EmTech.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deepening relationship between Emory and Georgia
Tech,'' he said. ``There is an increasing prominence of Emory in
the health care arena. And also the Georgia Research Alliance has
raised the ability to do biotech to a new level. These three things
really come together in this project.''
</P>
<P>
   Located on Emory University's 42-acre West Campus on Briarcliff
Road, EmTech is to be housed in modified trailerlike facilities
known as ``modular units.'' With about 8,000 square feet of space,
the trailers can house eight to 10 companies, said Rebecca
Kaufman-Gessner, associate director of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Emory contracted with Ayers Saint Gross Architects and Planners
of Baltimore, which developed a master plan for the site that
included a number of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite more ambitious hopes for the facility, ``We simply don't
have the resources identified to build permanent facilities,'' said
Charlotte Johnson, senior vice provost for administration at Emory.
``I wish I could tell you when that will happen, but I cannot. But
it is an evolving project, and the first stage is modular units. We
have to see if this baby can crawl before we ask it to walk and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, the kind of start-up companies sought by EmTech are
not likely to expect the most lavish home or to be thinking of
settling at Emory as they grow. ``We would certainly hope, if we do
our job properly, that no company starting at EmTech would be there
longer than three years,'' Shuker said.
</P>
<P>
   EmTech got a boost several weeks ago, landing its first tenant:
Nu-Tec Services shifted its headquarters to Atlanta from a suburb
of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Nu-Tec is in bioinformatics, selling supercomputer analysis that
can be used to solve biotech problems like gene design. It has just
six employees here, although it plans expansion to 30 by the end of
2001, according to Chief Executive Michael S. Keehan. The center
has been searching for other tenants, Shuker said. ``We are in
negotiations with a number of different folks, really three or four
companies. I am hoping there will be results soon.''
</P>
<P>
   And how long after that will incubators begin churning out
success stories? ``We would love to see research projects coming
out of Georgia institutions in the next 12 to 18 months be turned
into thriving enterprises,'' Shuker said. ``That would be
spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
