<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NORMAN0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armed with a repaired hip, Norman hopes to contend in the PGA
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Just two weeks after Greg Norman underwent hip
surgery June 28, he was back at his club, the Medalist, in Hobe
Sound, Fla. Not to play, not to hit balls, not even to walk the
course.
</P>
<P>
   He just wanted to smell the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like someone who's about to walk away from the
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him with such a buzz about his game in a long
time,'' said David Leadbetter, his swing coach. Two weeks after his
smell-the-blades walk at the Medalist, and just a month after
surgery to repair a torn labrum in his right hip, Norman was fourth
at the International, matching his best finish on the PGA Tour
since his third at last year's Masters.
</P>
<P>
   That showing has fueled speculation that Norman, at 45, can be a
factor this week at the 82nd PGA Championship at Valhalla Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like my chances,'' Norman said Tuesday. So do others. ``I
think he's one of the 10 players to beat this week,'' Mark
Calcavecchia said. ``Greg still has a lot of golf left in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Enough golf left that Norman says he has shelved his
``seven-year plan'' to step away from competitive action after this
season to devote his energies to his Great White Shark Enterprises
and his family. His Jupiter, Fla.,-based business, which ranges
from designing courses to designing yachts, from growing grass to
making wine, will have to wait a few more years to get Norman's
full attention.
</P>
<P>
   There is time to make up for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I have missed out on a couple of years of
the prime of my golf because of a pathology problem in my body,''
Norman said. ``But now it is gone and I feel great, and hopefully I
can just keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in at least six years, Norman says he can
swing a club without pain. His left shoulder was surgically
repaired in 1998 and now his right hip can drive through shots
without causing him to wince. He can even bend over to line up a
putt without pain shooting through his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him practice as much,'' said Pete Draovitch,
his personal trainer. ``He can't wait to get out there to hit
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadbetter said the most recent surgery has enabled Norman to
return to the swing that won two majors (the British Open in 1986
and '93) and more than 70 tournaments worldwide. The operation was
shown on Norman's Web site (shark.com)
</P>
<P>
   But for Norman to finally win his first major in America, he
will have to beat the odds. Only four players have won a major at
45 or older: Julius Boros, Jack Nicklaus, Old Tom Morris and Hale
Irwin. Norman pays no attention to this bit of trivia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 45 is just a number for me,'' Norman said. ``I think
my body tells me I am probably 10, maybe seven years younger. It
gives me the belief in myself that I can continue on past 45. I
know right now I can definitely compete.'' Like Nicklaus, who
underwent hip-replacement surgery last year, Norman said he had
reasons other than golf to get his body in better shape. There was
also a quality-of-life issue such as being able to scuba-dive with
his two children, go hiking with his wife or even be able to eat
breakfast sitting at a table (he had to eat standing up because if
he sat down, it would take several minutes before he could put
weight on his hip).
</P>
<P>
   Norman had millions in the bank, but he didn't have one of the
things he treasured most: his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give up golf and I would give up everything to feel
the way I feel . . . to go hiking in the mountains and
fly-fishing,'' he said. ``There are times when I would just sit on
the boat while my children were scuba-diving because it hurt so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the surgery, it's unlikely Norman would be able to carry
the Olympic torch across the historic Sydney Harbor Bridge on its
final leg before next month's opening ceremonies of the Olympic
Games in his homeland. Norman said that moment will rank just
behind his British Open victories as the biggest sports moments of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big honor for me to be able to do that at the 2000
Olympics in Australia,'' he said. ``I just wish golf was an Olympic
sport. It should be.''
</P>
<P>
   But Norman will have his mind on other things this week. He
knows it has been 16 months since he contended in a major, but he
thinks he remembers how.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like riding a bike,'' he said. ``Once you put yourself
back in that position, a competitor is a competitor. You know to
feel the feel.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: craigdolch(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
