<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2-year-old died from heat, officials find
 &HT;    By Maurice Tamman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - An examination of the body of a 2-year-old who died
after being left in his grandmother's car all day Monday indicated
he probably died of excessive heat, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said they found no evidence of any other injury or illness
that could have caused the boy's death.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the head of the day-care center the boy, Hezekiah
Silvester Welch, usually attended described him as a ``nice,
playful'' child. She said the boy's grandmother, Deborah Welch, 41,
appeared to be an attentive guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Welch found her grandson's body in her car at 4:15 p.m. Monday
after leaving work at the Social Security office at South DeKalb
Mall. The locked car, its windows closed, had been parked in the
mall lot since 7:30 a.m, when she reported to work, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Welch apparently forgot to drop off the youngster at the Decatur
preschool before work and didn't realize he was still in the car,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators questioned Welch Monday and Tuesday, but she was
not charged. DeKalb County police spokeswoman Mikki Jones said a
decision about charges, if any, will be made today.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kelhofer, chief investigator with the DeKalb Medical
Examiner's Office, said the boy's body showed no evidence of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Stuckey, family education director of YMCA Family Place,
said the toddler had attended the Flat Shoals Road preschool since
May. Stuckey said Welch told her she needed day care near her
office.
</P>
<P>
   Welch works as a service representative at the Social Security
Administration office in the mall, administration spokesman William
DeBardelaben said.
</P>
<P>
   Stuckey said Welch dropped the boy off and picked him up daily.
``She was a very friendly parent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her records showed Welch and her husband were the boy's
guardians. Stuckey said she did not know the name of the boy's
mother but had talked to her on the phone. Jones said Welch and her
daughter had an informal agreement that Welch would care for the
boy. Jones also could not identify the boy's parents A man came to
the scene late Monday identifying himself as the child's father and
was taken away by police.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
