<SLUG> BC-DEM-BASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FACE LEFT TO APPEASE LIBERAL WING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Mich., Ark., Minn., D.C.)   (Eds.: Will update or expand as necessary.)  
 By JAMES DAO and KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Faced with an undercurrent of grumbling about the
centrist tone of its ticket and platform, the Democratic Party
devoted much of its convention Tuesday to reassuring its liberal
base, while its vice-presidential candidate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
appeared before black delegates to declare his unequivocal support
for affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was for affirmative action, am for affirmative action and
will be for affirmative action,'' Lieberman, who has been critical
of racial preference programs, told the convention's Black Caucus.
Immediately afterward, Rep. Maxine Waters of Los Angeles, who had
voiced strong doubts about Lieberman this weekend, declared she
would support him wholeheartedly.
</P>
<P>
   But other leading liberals continued to express doubts about
Gore himself. Mayor Willie Brown of San Francisco said in an
interview Tuesday: ``The most important thing to me is that Gore is
not emotionally in touch with the party's base. He will have to
find ways to repair that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown added, ``If he's smart, he'll go to a black church every
Sunday from now until Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to gauge the depth of discontent among black
voters, union members and other core Democrats with the ticket and
its agenda. But Gore's selection of Lieberman, a Connecticut
senator who has staked out centrist positions not only on
affirmative action, but also on school vouchers, military spending
and Social Security, seems to have crystallized their worries that
Gore is taking them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments pose a potentially significant problem for Gore
because black voters and union members are among the party's
largest and most loyal constituencies. And while some of those
voters might defect to Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, the
Democrats' greater fear is that their base will simply stay home on
Election Day, making it difficult to win closely contested swing
states like Michigan and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying, `We don't see the Democrats standing for
us,' '' said Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota Democrat, a leader of
the party's liberal wing. ``It is a hurdle to overcome. And the
vice president needs to do it soon.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood Tuesday, one movie star well known as well for
championing liberal causes, said he and his friends were very
dissatisfied with Gore. He said they planned to wait a few days,
during which time Gore and Lieberman would address the Democratic
Convention, and then decide whether to support Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the current chairman and Gore a former chairman of
the party's leading centrist organization, the Democratic
Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign moved swiftly Tuesday to address worries
within the party, not only through Lieberman's appearance before
the Black Caucus, but also by dispatching two black Cabinet
secretaries, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman, and other prominent black Democrats to
declare their strong support for Lieberman on television and in
meetings with black delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased whenever a barrier is broken,'' said
Eleanor Holmes Norton, the delegate from the District of Columbia,
said before the Black Caucus of Lieberman, the first Jewish
candidate for vice president. ``Because when they break a barrier
for somebody excluded, we cannot be far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the list of convention speakers Tuesday night
was almost a Who's Who of leaders from the party's liberal wing,
including two union presidents, a prominent environmentalist, gay
rights and abortion rights leaders, and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
Four Kennedys, including Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, spoke to the
convention Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That liberal lineup represented a sharp contrast from the
Republicans, who carefully choreographed their convention two weeks
ago to keep conservative activists backstage, making it easier for
their presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush, to reach out to
moderate swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats say that the Republicans appeased their core
voters in other ways: with the party platform, which remains
staunchly conservative on issues like abortion, gay rights and
military spending, and in the selection of Richard Cheney, who
compiled a consistently conservative record in Congress, as the
vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore reached toward the political center with his
selection of Lieberman, a leader of the party's centrist ``New
Democrat'' wing. And his aides rebuffed repeated efforts by
liberals to insert language into the platform calling for universal
health care, cuts in defense spending, a moratorium on capital
punishment and increased spending on the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
