<SLUG> BC-DEM-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS CELEBRATE THEIR LIBERAL HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs to update and change byline; another sub will follow
shortly)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forty years after John F. Kennedy accepted the
Democratic nomination in this city, his daughter, brother, niece
and nephew sought to revive the liberal hearts of his party Tuesday
night by recalling the slain president's legacy and tying Vice
President Al Gore to it.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has offered himself as a president for a new century,
the Democrats, on the second night of their national convention,
staged a festival of the past. It was a carefully choreographed
program intended to reassure loyalists that despite Gore's
overtures to moderates, their party was not drifting from its
principles of inclusiveness and tending to the downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   The evening featured a parade of liberal stalwarts, from Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy to Jesse Jackson, to former Sen. Bill Bradley,
Gore's vanquished foe. There were also speakers representing
important Democratic constituencies: union members, abortion rights
advocates and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The leftward tableau on stage was at odds with the platform that
the delegates approved Tuesday night, which was a decided play for
the middle, calling for a more potent military, expanded global
trade and for schools to be more accountable for student
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If America is to secure prosperity, progress, peace and
security for all,'' the platform proclaimed, ``we cannot afford to
go back.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most stirring speeches were about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was here, in this City of Angels, on a warm summer night 40
years ago, that America first looked across the New Frontier,''
said Kennedy, the most prominent liberal in Congress, in his
prepared remarks. ``A New Frontier, as my brother said, where there
were `unsolved problems, unconquered pockets of ignorance and
prejudice, unanswered questions of poverty and surplus.'''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his brother, Kennedy said, ``How proud he would be
of Al Gore and our party and the new barrier of bigotry we are
breaking down with the choice of Joe Lieberman as the next vice
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was introduced by his niece, Caroline Kennedy
Schlossberg, the late president's daughter, who in her first
speaking appearance before a Democratic convention said she was
proud that Gore's running mate, Lieberman, had been inspired by her
father to enter politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``So as I look out across this hall and across the country,''
Kennedy said in her prepared remarks, ``I know that my father's
spirit lives on.'' Her address was particularly poignant because
she is the sole survivor of the late president's immediate family.
Her mother Jacqueline, died in 1994, and her brother, John F.
Kennedy Jr., was killed in a plane crash last summer.
</P>
<P>
   For all the sentimentality, the symbols of the party's liberal
wing were on stage to address one of Gore's most frustrating
political problems: He is not particularly popular with the base
voters of his party, and, according to surveys, is not nearly as
well liked in his party as Gov. George W. Bush is among
Republicans. Gore is counting on loyal Democrats to flock to the
polls in November. But the longer he has to worry about energizing
those voters, the less attention he can pay to the swing and
independent voters who are crucial for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The calvalcade of liberals was a decided contrast to the
Republican convention in Philadelphia, when conservative figures,
the most steadfast party loyalists, were largely kept off stage as
the party sought to broaden its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Republicans put Bush's primary opponent, Sen. John
McCain, on center stage, the Democrats on Tuesday night gave a
prime time spot to Bradley. Offering some of his most lavish praise
thus far for the vice president, Bradley said in prepared remarks:
``I learned that Al Gore is a man of wide-ranging intellect, with a
deep desire to serve, profound preparation for the job, a strong
sense of loyalty, and a life infused with tolerance and roots in
religious faith. What strikes me is that what we share is so much
more than what we disagree on.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments were not as anticipated as McCain's had been,
perhaps because Bradley _ who did not win a single state in the
primaries _ is not viewed as much as a force in his party. And
Bradley devoted most of his speech to delivering a pitch for his
party and excoriating Republicans as impostors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't window-dress diversity, we're the party of
diversity,'' Bradley said in his prepared remarks. ``Don't read our
lips. Watch what we do. Watch what we have always done, what our
party values have always been.''
</P>
<P>
   In hewing to the old-guard theme of the evening, he went on,
``The convictions that Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and Lyndon
Johnson stood for, that Jimmy Carter is living for even now, that
Bill Clinton still works for, the ideals that Jack and Bobby and
Martin died for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
