<HEADER>
A2713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEACHER-EVALUATION-NY     08-15 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-EVALUATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM RECOGNIZES TEACHERS' EXTRA EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Caffrey had been teaching English for 31 years
when he heard about a new way to gain recognition for his skills,
one available to teachers nationwide. The hitch: Applicants had to
pass a rigorous and time-consuming assessment that included videos
of their teaching, samples of their students' work and essays
analyzing their classroom techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Caffrey, who was teaching middle school in Williamsburg,
Brooklyn, was not the type to mind the extra work. He already had
two master's degrees and was eager for another credential, even if
it did not mean higher pay or career advancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply wanted to be recognized as an expert in my field,''
Caffrey said last week. ``I wanted the confidence that affirmation
like that could bring.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1995, Caffrey became one of the first New York City
teachers to earn advanced certification from the National Board for
Professional Teaching Standards, an independent panel that sets
standards for experienced teachers. The board, created in 1987, was
recommended in a landmark report, ``A Nation Prepared: Teachers for
the 21st Century,'' by the Carnegie Forum on Education and the
Economy. National board certification does not replace state
certification, which remains an entry level requirement for all
teachers. Instead, it helps teachers with at least three years of
experience measure their skills using benchmarks set by the panel,
which is mostly made up of teachers but also includes school
administrators, union officials, lawmakers and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It recognizes people who go beyond what is expected,'' said
Karen Zumwalt, a professor at Columbia Teachers College, ``and it
motivates people who want to grow professionally but aren't sure
how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a record 2,967 teachers earned national board
certification, bringing the total to 4,804 nationwide since 1995.
But only 62 teachers in New York State have earned the credential,
and of those, only 25 work in New York City. Randi Weingarten,
president of the United Federation of Teachers, said the program
has been slow to catch on here because there were few financial
incentives attached and because city teachers were overextended as
it is.
</P>
<P>
   But as education has become a crucial election issue and states
have scrambled to attract teachers in the face of a shortage, New
York has joined several dozen other states in creating incentives
for teachers to get national certification. The state now pays the
$2,300 application fee for most teachers. And starting this year,
the state plans to give $10,000 a year for three years to teachers
who earn the advanced certification and agree to work in
low-performing schools. In New York City, that means the 99
``schools under registration review,'' which have been designated
by the state as failing.
</P>
<P>
   City teachers who earn national certification also can get a
$3,700 raise. But those who have earned 30 credits beyond their
master's degrees _ about 44 percent of the city's 78,000 teachers _
already have received that increase and cannot get more for
certification. Weingarten said this lack of an additional incentive
was the main reason so few city teachers have gone through the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The new incentives may be working. This spring, 100 teachers in
New York state submitted applications to the national board, up
from 59 in 1999. Those teachers will find out in November whether
they passed the assessment. Meanwhile, about 50 city teachers are
applying for national certification in the coming school year, up
from 20 this spring. Typically, slightly more than half of each
year's applicants are certified .
</P>
<P>
   During the school year, applicants videotape their classroom
instruction, submit lesson plans and student work samples, and
write essays reflecting on how they help students learn. They also
have to write extensively about their work outside the classroom
with colleagues, parents and the community. In the summer, they
finish the process with written exams on the subject they teach, as
well as teaching techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes up all the extra time that you possibly have,'' said
Beverly Tinort, who teaches first grade at C.S. 21 in Brooklyn and
earned national board certification last year. ``But it's so worth
it. Teachers in New York are so burdened, we never get a chance to
stop and reflect on how we're doing our job. This is a blessing
because it forces us to stop and reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the assessment, Tinort had to sit with colleagues and
watch a video she had made of herself teaching sixth-graders. Her
colleagues picked apart everything from her body language to why
girls seemed more engaged in the lesson than boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on it was very painful to watch yourself with that
critical eye,'' Tinort said. ``But you pick up so many things that
you never would have realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really pick up on your weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Caffrey, said the national certification process
did not improve their skills but simply affirmed that their
teaching methods were on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go into classrooms now I have a sense of
accomplishment,'' said Caffrey, who now runs a union-sponsored
teacher training center in Brooklyn's District 14. ``I always felt
teaching was a noble profession and I worked so hard every day, and
it just didn't seem to me that people in the management system
recognized that. Now I have some recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics question whether nationally certified teachers are
really better. Chester E. Finn Jr., an assistant secretary of
education under President Ronald Reagan, said there was no data on
how the students of these teachers performed compared with their
peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years and gazillions of dollars and an awful lot of
states being wooed to give bonuses to these folks, all we know is
that other teachers admire their teaching,'' Finn said. ``I need to
see some proof that these teachers are more effective in terms of
student learning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
