<SLUG> BC-CVN-ALTERNATIVE-CONVENTION-1STLD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
JESSE JACKSON CALLS DRUG WAR RACIST; DEMANDS MORE TREATMENT
PROGRAMS &HT;    (EDs: UPDATES with 6th graf showing Jackson speaking at the
Democratic convention, edits to conform.)
 &HT;    By MARK HELM
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES The Rev. Jesse Jackson, speaking at a so-called
Shadow Convention here, called Tuesday for an end to the country's
war on drugs, which he said unfairly targets minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader likened the government's antidrug
program to ``friendly fire (that) is killing Americans rather than
helping Americans, a policy driven by fear, race and greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said African Americans comprise nearly two thirds of all
drug offenders admitted to state prison although their rate of drug
use is roughly equal to that of whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are poor, brown or black or don't have a lawyer, there
is no category called youthful indiscretion,`` he said in a veiled
reference to questions about whether Republican presidential
nominee George W. Bush used cocaine in his past, questions that the
candidate has refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who unsuccessfully ran for the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1984 and 1988, called, as he has in the past, for
loosening state and federal drug laws and increasing drug treatment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although he criticized both parties for not addressing the
issue, Jackson addressed the Democratic National Convention here
five hours later and praised the party for its diversity and
presumed presidential nominee Al Gore for his promises to fight for
working families.
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers at the Shadow Convention, which is running in
tandem with and often counter to the Democratic conclave, included
New Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson, Salt Lake City Mayor Rocky Anderson
and Reps. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., and
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., who is the Republican candidate for Senate
against incumbent Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also attacked the nation's war against drugs as a
failure. He said that while government spending on enforcement of
drug laws has increased from about $1 billion in 1980 to more than
$40 billion this year, the availability of illegal narcotics has
increased dramatically and the price has fallen over the past 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a 1999 report by the U.S. Health and Human Services
that found that 88 percent of 12th graders said marijuana was easy
to get, 47 percent said cocaine was easy to get, and 32 percent
said heroin was easy to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think drug and alcohol use is a terrible thing, which is
exactly why I'm not going to keep pretending that a policy that
doesn't reduce drug use or the availability of drugs is working,''
said Johnson, who does not smoke or drink. He also called for the
legalization of marijuana and for treatment programs for first-time
drug ofenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Shadow Convention, which is being held a few blocks from the
Democratic gathering, is also taking up such subjects as campaign
finance reform and the gap between rich and poor. The first Shadow
Convention, which addressed the same issues, was held in
Philadelphia during the Republican National Convention two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of controversial columnist Arianna Huffington,
the counter-culture conclaves have been billed as the
``un-conventions'' and antidotes to what organizers call the
scripted coronations of the Republican and Democratic
nominees.``There's no competition anymore, no question of the
outcome,'' said comedial Bill Maher, host of the television show
``Politically Incorrect.'' ``The other conventions are infomercials
and bad ones,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Along with discussions on political issues, the Shadow
Conventions also offer comedy and political satire. ``Our goal is
to put some well-known people out in the morning to talk about the
issues that are being ignored by both parties, and then in the
evening focus more on entertaining people,'' said Ethan Nadelmann,
a Shadow Conventions organizer and director of the New York-based
Lindesmith Center, a drug policy institute. ``Politics does not
have to be serious all the time,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)earstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
