<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGANOTES0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back problems force Duval to withdraw from PGA Championship
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLe, Ky. - David Duval won't suffer another disappointing
Sunday finish at a major championship this year. This time it
happened on a Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still in search of his first major title, the world's No. 3
player has withdrawn from the PGA Championship at Valhalla Golf
Club because of a continuing back injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stinks,'' Duval said from Sun Valley, Idaho, where he is
attempting to rest an injury that has forced withdrawals from three
consecutive tournaments. ``My mind is saying, `Let's go play, let's
get after it. You're fit. You can work through this.' But as much
as I think this way, I know deep down the right thing to do is not
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Georgia Tech player said he has not hit a shot since
walking off the course six holes into the International two weeks
ago in Colorado. He also withdrew from last week's Buick Open. An
MRI has been taken on Duval's back, with the injury described as
``a ligment issue'' in his lower to middle back region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about, more than anything, just teeing off,'' Duval
said of the PGA. ``In the long term, that would have been a poor
decision. With the adrenaline and a strong desire, I might have
kept going and set myself further back and ended my year.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who has not yet won a major, played in the final group at
both the 2000 Masters and British Open, where his back went into
spasm.
</P>
<P>
   He was replaced in the field by Craig Stadler.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Elkington, who last week underwent hip surgery, was
replaced in the field by Edward Fryatt.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville native and past PGA champion Bobby Nichols also
withdrew. His spot was taken by Greg Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus pro Gill having heady time
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gill of Columbus' Maple Ridge Golf Club, the Georgia
Section's only representative in the PGA field, spent a memorable
practice round Tuesday, finding a game with Masters champion Vijay
Singh, two-time PGA champion Nick Price and two-time U.S. Open
champion Ernie Els. ``You can't believe how much fun I'm having,''
said Gill, who is playing his first PGA and also will represent the
organization in the PGA Cup in Wales.... Australian Greg Norman,
who will carry the Olympic torch in Opening Ceremonies in Sydney
next month, said it's ``a crying shame'' that golf is not an
Olympic event. ``It's time to take off the blinders and just see
how popular golf is on a global basis,'' Norman said, ``and it
deserves to be in there.'' Going just a bit overboard, Norman said,
``The Berlin Wall came down with a lot of chat, a lot of dialogue.
Why not get golf in the Olympics?''... Atlanta resident Billy
Andrade, who is 160th on the PGA Tour money list this year with
$131,827, is missing his first PGA since his first year on tour
(1988).... Augusta's Charles Howell, who probably will be attending
many PGA Championships in the future, has signed a three-year
contract with Callaway Golf for more than $1 million a year to wear
the company's logo on his bag, cap and clothes and play its clubs
and ball.... Tiger Woods, on Valhalla as a major championship
venue: ``I mean, you have Augusta, you have Pebble Beach and you
have St. Andrews and I don't think anyone is going to say that
Valhalla is in the same caliber as those three golf courses, but
this golf course is going to be a test and we can't ignore that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
