u k BC-EDIT-MURDOCH-NYT &LR;      08-15 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MURDOCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DIVERSITY IN NEWS AND ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 16:
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch proposed this week to add to his already vast
media holdings by buying WWOR Channel 9 in the New York City region
and nine other television stations across the country from
Chris-Craft Industries. The purchase would give his company, News
Corp., ownership of stations that reach more than 35 percent of the
viewing public in the nation, violating a rule of the Federal
Communications Commission. Murdoch plans to satisfy the commission
by selling as many stations as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the proposed purchase would create a troubling
concentration of media outlets. It would give him two television
stations each in New York, Los Angeles, Phoenix and Salt Lake City.
The commission allows for owning two stations if diversity of
expression is preserved. That means it requires that at least eight
independent TV stations survive in each market and that no one owns
more than one of any market's four top-rated stations.
</P>
<P>
   These rules would require Murdoch to sell one station in Salt
Lake City. But even in some of the cities where the ownership rules
are not violated, the commission might reasonably decide that
Murdoch's proposal, by eliminating competition between two
independent sources of news and entertainment, would not serve the
public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever pros and cons owning two stations may pose in other
cities, however, the commission should firmly reject it for New
York. There Murdoch owns not only another television station,
Channel 5, but also The New York Post, one of the city's four major
daily newspapers. Commission rules forbid joint ownership of
television stations and newspapers in the same city except in
emergencies. No such emergency exists that would warrant the
commission's waiving rules designed to preserve the diversity of
news and entertainment on which democracy thrives.
</P>
<P>
   The commission granted Murdoch a waiver in 1993 so he could buy
The New York Post despite the fact that he already owned Channel 5.
It reasoned, correctly, that the rule had to be waived to keep the
newspaper from going out of business. But this time there is no
such threat. Neither The Post nor Channel 9 is in danger of
collapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
