These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Wednesday, Aug. 16 on the New York Times wire.
For questions, please call Harry Mok at (415) 777-6206 or the
business desk at (415) 536-5172.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EBENEFITS:  &LR; When Andy Kurtzig read ``Profiles of Genius'` as a
college sophomore and discovered that most of the 13 featured
`change masters` _ including Apple's Steve Jobs, Microsoft's Bill
Gates, FedEx's Fred Smith and CNN's Ted Turner _ never graduated
from college, he decided to drop out of the University of
California at Berkeley. ``I wanted to start a business and thought
if I finish college, it would be suicide,'' Kurtzig recalled. Then
he talked to his mother, Sandra Kurtzig, who founded Ask Group, one
of Silicon Valley's early software success stories. She persuaded
him to switch majors to business from engineering and start a
venture on the side if he desired. Family businesses in the United
States are the rule, not the exception. Ninety-five percent of all
businesses are family owned or controlled, and they produce close
to 60 percent of the gross domestic product. Four years ago, the
Kurtzbig's co-founded eBenefits in San Francisco. Andy Kurtzig, 27,
is CEO chief executive officer of the company, which links small
businesses to human resources, payroll and benefits management
services via over the Internet. Sandra Kurtzig, 53, is chairman.
 &UR; By Peter &LR; 
 &UR; Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; FREELANCE:  &LR; A lawsuit filed in San Francisco on Monday is
continuing the debate sparked by San Mateo's Napster Inc. over who
should profit from intellectual property distributed on the
Internet. This time, the works in question are not songs, but
articles written by free-lance authors and resold on the Internet
by three database companies, including the search engine Northern
Light.  &UR; By Carrie Kirby &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LINUX:  &LR; Backed by a growing parade of computer-industry
heavyweights, the Linux movement rallied yesterday in San Jose for
its biggest-ever trade show. LinuxWorld Conference and Expo was in
past years the province mainly of little-known distributors and
developers of the upstart computer-operating system, but this year
the show floor is dominated by giant booths sponsored by the likes
of Compaq, Dell, Hewlett-Packard, IBM and even Sun Microsystems.
 &UR; By Henry Norr &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; HAMBRECHT:  &LR; WR Hambrecht, the San Francisco investment bank that
pioneered public stock offerings over the Internet, extended its
Web auction system yesterday with the completion of a $300 million
sale of five-year debt securities for Dow Chemical Co.  &UR; By &LR; 
 &UR; Sam Zuckerman &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NETWORTH:  &LR; Thanks to the deteriorating euro _ which has fallen 22
percent against the dollar since its introduction _ vacationing in
France and most European countries has been downright affordable
this summer. And things will get even cheaper in the fall, when
hotel rates and airfares go down.  &UR; Column by Kathleen &LR; 
