<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGGIE LEWIS' WIDOW FILES TO REOPEN MALPRACTICE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One month after a judge rejected her appeal of a jury
verdict clearing cardiologist Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. of negligence in
her husband's death, Donna Harris-Lewis has a new team of lawyers
and is asking that the case be reopened, claiming that her former
lawyer failed to pursue her appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis also claims that attorney Neil Rossman, who
represented her during the retrial of her medical malpractice
lawsuit, was ``personally'' responsible for a $10,000 court
stenography bill sent to her _ a debt made public by unhappy court
reporters waiting for payment _ because she had previously paid him
$1.5 million in ``case costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's legal maneuver is the latest in a saga that began
seven years ago when her husband, Celtics captain Reggie Lewis,
collapsed and died of a heart ailment while shooting baskets at a
Brandeis University gym. Harris-Lewis accused Mudge, Lewis's chief
cardiologist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, of misdiagnosing her
husband's heart disorder in concluding that he suffered from a
benign fainting condition.
</P>
<P>
   Two high-profile trials followed, the most recent ending in May
with Mudge cleared of negligence in Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Harris-Lewis hired three new lawyers, including a
lead attorney from New Jersey, Anthony J. Macri, and two others
from Boston, Pamela Harris-Daley and Krista M. Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, they filed a motion in Suffolk Superior Court
asking Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith, who presided over both
malpractice trials, to revive the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's new lawyers also asked Fremont-Smith to
reconsider his ruling last month ordering Harris-Lewis to reimburse
Mudge's lawyers $52,000 in court costs and deposition expenses.
Rossman had not opposed the reimbursement request.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he had not done so, Rossman replied, ``Well,
they're entitled to it, right?'' according to an affidavit filed by
Lewis's new lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's lawyers have filed papers in court opposing
Harris-Lewis's motion to reopen the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply, enough is enough, and it is time for this case
to be at an end,'' wrote William J. Dailey Jr., Mudge's lawyer.
``The attorneys who represented Mrs. Harris-Lewis were top-notch,
they gave their all, and in at least one instance apparently
suffered financially,'' an apparent reference to the bankruptcy of
Harris-Lewis's former law firm, Harley &AMP; Brown, after the first
trial, which ended in a hung jury last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply by flailing around and apparently finding some attorney
who will now take a swing at a trial record that has already been
reviewed by an experienced trial attorney (Mr. Rossman) and found
to be without errors,'' Dailey continued, ``is not enough to serve
as a basis for the court to reconsider the decisions which were
appropriately made.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home, Dailey called the developments
``disappointing,'' and said that ``it's really time that everyone
moved on with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Daley and Larsen, who are criminal defense attorneys,
referred all calls to Macri.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his New Jersey office Tuesday, Macri said
Harris-Lewis had been ``deprived of a fair trial'' and that her
appeal ``should never have been allowed to be dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Macri said there were several legal errors made during the
retrial that satisfy grounds for appeal, including the introduction
of testimony about Lewis's alleged cocaine use and the $12
million-plus in insurance payments Harris-Lewis received after
Lewis died. That testimony was ``legally irrelevant'' and ``very
prejudicial to Donna,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the retrial, after the close of testimony, Fremont-Smith
told jurors they could not consider Lewis's alleged cocaine use
during deliberations because there was no evidence that drugs
played a role in his death.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home Tuesday, Rossman declined to comment on
Harris-Lewis's allegations that he had missed deadlines required to
continue her appeal. But he called her claim that she had paid him
$1.5 million ``palpably and pathologically false.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is in a court pleading, it's either a typo or it's an
attempt to perpetrate a fraud on the court,'' Rossman said. ``If it
weren't so ludicrous, it would be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rossman would not discuss his dealings with Harris-Lewis,
her lawyers claim in their court filing that Rossman told them he
had informed Harris-Lewis that he would not represent her on appeal
and had filed the initial paperwork only to preserve her legal
rights.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Macri, Rossman said he had searched for issues to
appeal but had found none. He also said he delayed filing appellate
documents in order to give Harris-Lewis time to find a new lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Macri said Tuesday that Harris-Lewis ``certainly has a right to
have her appeal heard on its merits and not have it dismissed on
procedural grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was prepared to try the case for what would be its
third round in court, Macri replied, ``Absolutely. And I think it
should be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
