<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN-LAWYER0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge says gag order applies to Al-Amin
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - For now, a judge is ordering Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin to
keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, defense attorneys asked the judge in Al-Amin's death
penalty case to allow him to talk publicly. Al-Amin is accused of
shooting two Fulton County sheriff's deputies, killing one. It
could be up to two years before his trial begins.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Superior Court Judge Stephanie Manis barred everyone on
the defense and prosecution from talking to members of the media
about Al-Amin or the evidence against him. Manis wants to prevent
publicity from influencing potential jurors.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, Manis said the restrictions apply to Al-Amin,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the right to say, `I'm innocent; I deny the charges
against me,''' said Jack Martin, Al-Amin's lead defense attorney.
``He has the right to describe and explain his political and
religious beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Martin does not want Al-Amin to discuss the evidence in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, who ran a Muslim mosque in Atlanta's West End, was a
leader of the Student Non-violent Coordinating Committee in the
1960s and, for a short time, a member of the Black Panthers. While
a member of those groups he used the name H. Rap Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Manis said she will look at other court rulings about a
defendant's right to free speech. She could rule in two to four
weeks. In the meantime, Al-Amin cannot give interviews, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an obligation to ensure a fair trial,'' Manis said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Martin complained he has not received notes
written by GBI forensic experts about DNA and ballistics evidence.
A GBI ballistics report says a rifle and handgun found in Alabama
where Al-Amin was arrested were the firearms used in the March 16
shooting in West End.
</P>
<P>
   The report and the surviving deputy's statement that Al-Amin was
the shooter are crucial to the state's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run the risk of having your reports excluded'' during
trial if the notes are not turned over, Manis warned prosecutor
Thomas Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Manis did not rule on the matter and told Martin to file a
motion about the notes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also barred New York lawyer Michael Warren from
sitting next to Al-Amin during the hearing. Al-Amin's family wants
Warren to join the defense team. Manis said she wants Warren to
apply in writing first. Currently, Martin and Bruce Harvey
represent Al-Amin. Both are white.
</P>
<P>
   Warren is black and Muslim. He is known for his work with
William Kunstler in the successful defense of El Sayyid A. Nosair,
who was acquitted in 1991 of murdering Rabbi Meir Kahane in New
York. Warren argued the case against Nosair was a conspiracy.
Al-Amin, in his sole statement about his case, said it was a
government conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
