<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMS-KENNEDYS-BOS &LR;      08-15 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-KENNEDYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW FRONTIER' TIMELESS, CAROLINE KENNEDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD AND YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She's a very private person who shuns the
spotlight, but the torch has been passed and the legacy belongs to
her alone. So Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the only surviving
member of President Kennedy's immediate family, came forward
Tuesday night to commemorate the anniversary of her father's
historic nomination here 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look out across this hall and across this country, I know
that my father's spirit lives on, and I thank all of you,''
Schlossberg told more than 4,000 delegates to the Democratic
National Convention. ``Now it is our turn to prove that the New
Frontier was not a place in time, but a timeless call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are the New Frontier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Schlossberg was a child when her father inspired
Americans to reach beyond their private space and commit to public
service. Ironically, the woman who depended on her dashing,
celebrity brother to be the Kennedy family's public face has been
thrust by yet another family tragedy out of her own private life
and Tuesday night, onto a very big national stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is, there is a sense in each of the Kennedys that you
take up where the last one left off,'' said historian Doris Kearns
Goodwin. ``With her brother, John, gone, Caroline has accepted the
mantle that has fallen on her to keep the story alive.''
</P>
<P>
   In television interviews Tuesday, Kennedy Schlossbery joked that
she agreed to speak at her first convention because she could not
say no to her uncle, US Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
Indeed, she has always been close to her father's youngest brother,
and in introducing him at the convention Tuesday night, she called
him ``a light and a life force in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``No uncle could be better,'' Kennedy Schlossberg said in
remarks prepared for delivery. ``No senator has ever achieved
more.''
</P>
<P>
   But the woman many Americans remember as a little girl romping
around the Oval Office, or as the brave child who tenderly kissed
her father's casket, had a serious political message to deliver. In
good times, Americans must redouble their efforts to help children,
the elderly, and the poor, Kennedy Schlossberg said, adding that
the best way to guarantee that is to elect Al Gore president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president who is not afraid of complexity, who
believes in an open and tolerant society,'' Kennedy Schlossbery
said. ``We need a president who knows that the world can be made
new again _ and that president is Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends insisted this was not a tryout for another Kennedy
political career. Foremost, Kennedy Schlossberg is devoted to her
children _ she and her husband, Edwin, have three school-age
youngsters and live an almost antisocial, family-centered life in
Manhattan and eastern Long Island. Trained as a lawyer, though she
never practiced law, Kennedy Schlossbery has co-authored two
scholarly books on the individual and privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks, which lasted about 10 minutes, Kennedy
Schlossberg said the nation had to be vigilant, as her father was,
in working to protect civil and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we believe in the freedoms guaranteed by the Constitution
and the Bill of Rights _ including the right to privacy _ that our
personal financial and medical information should not be up for
grabs, and we should be able to make our own reproductive
decisions, that is up to us,.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also head of the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum
Foundation in Boston and is on the panel that selects winners of
the Profile in Courage award, which is conferred annually on public
officials who act on principle over politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a very smart and sincere person who tries to do the
right thing while maintaining a very private life,'' said a friend
did not want to be identified. ``She is not a public person and has
no intention of becoming one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Schlossberg, who carries herself with the dignity of her
mother but has the skill to deliver a speech like her father, noted
Tuesday night that she did have a special kinship with Gore. His
parents, Senator Albert Gore, Sr. and Pauline, were Washington
matchmakers in bringing her parents, Jack Kennedy and Jacqueline
Bouvier, together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, in more ways than one, I wouldn't be here if it
weren't for the Gore family,'' the 42-year-old Kennedy Schlossberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone in the big Staples Center knew, too, that she
probably would not have been on the podium if her brother had not
been killed a year ago July in a plane crash off Martha's Vineyard.
John Kennedy Jr. spoke at the 1988 convention and was on the scene
in Chicago in 1996 as editor of George magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank all Americans for making me and John and all our
family a part of your families, for reaching out and sustaining us
through the good times and the difficult ones and for helping us
dream my father's dream,'' Kennedy Schlossberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy Schlossberg's appearance moved many delegates in the big
Los Angeles arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe she's old enough to be doing this,'' said Kate
McKenna, 51, of Syracuse, N.Y. ``I saw her and her brother as
little kids. The life she's led. The tragedy she's endured. It must
be very painful and poignant for her to speak, especially so close
on the heels of losing her brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Though delegates could muster scant details about her life, many
felt they knew her, just as they knew all the Kennedys. Their
lives, after all, had been punctuated by so many of the sometimes
cataclysmic events in hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with the Kennedys,'' said Bill Bryan, 55, of
Bowdoinham, Maine. ``I remember the election of Jack, and it was
really a wonderful kind of hope. Being Afro-American, I didn't
always feel a part of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pulling for Caroline,'' said Michael Lane, of
Dryden, N.Y. ``She speaks to something inside us. It's nostalgia,
it's sadness, it's happiness, it's hope for a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane remembers the convention of 1960, when her father was
nominated, and his assassination and funeral. He remembers hearing
when her uncle Robert Kennedy was killed. And when her brother's
plane went missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, the nation held its breath for the family
again,'' he said. ``I can't think of another family that has that
effect on the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there another family that has the magnetism to attract a
crowd or the mystique to lure paparazzi. At an event Monday in Los
Angeles honoring a Profile in Courage winner, Kennedy Schlossberg
was swamped by dozens of elbowing cameramen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not forget that this family has been the bread and
butter of the newspapers, magazines, and television for almost 40
years,'' said Carl Sferrazzi Anthony, a biographer of first
families. ``After her mother died, and now that her brother is
gone, the obsession settles on her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
