<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIRE-SUV-ART-2TAKES-N     08-15 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-SUV-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRE DEATHS ARE LINKED TO ROLLOVERS OF SPORT VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Story is also being filed in `w' category.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government data released Tuesday evening showed
that virtually all the recent deaths linked to Firestone tires now
being recalled occurred when sport utility vehicles, most of them
Ford Explorers, rolled over after the tires failed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators said that they had received more than 750
complaints about the failure of Firestone tires, involving 62
deaths. That is significantly more complaints and more deaths than
previously announced, and more deaths than for any other safety
recall involving autos or any kind of auto parts. The only recall
of a comparable number of tires, another Firestone recall in 1978,
followed far more complaints to regulators _ 14,000 _ but fewer
deaths _ 41.
</P>
<P>
   Why have the recent tire failures been unusually deadly? The
tires recalled in 1978 were on cars; the tires at issue now are on
sport utility vehicles and a few pickup trucks, which are harder to
control when a tire fails.
</P>
<P>
   Safety groups and lawyers representing crash victims are urging
automakers to make changes, like redesigning the tires and the
suspensions, so that their sport utilities will be less likely to
go out of control and roll over when a tire fails. But automakers
have mostly rejected these ideas as they try to satisfy customers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, putting nylon coatings inside would help hold the
tires together when the tread peels off, as has happened with the
Firestone tires. But that produces a bouncier ride, which few
drivers choose at showrooms, so automakers seldom request the nylon
from tire makers, said Brook Lindbert, the engineering director for
tire and wheel systems at General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Recommending a high inflation pressure for tires, which the Ford
Motor Co. did not do for the Explorer, reduces the likelihood of a
tire failure. But more fully inflated tires produce a bumpier ride,
said Tom Baughman, Ford's engineering director for North American
trucks. If the recommended pressure is fairly low to begin with,
there is less of a safety margin to protect against leaks that may
cause tire pressure to fall to dangerously low levels, he
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Most sport utility vehicles still use the stiff suspensions of
the pickup trucks on which they were based. These shared
suspensions hold down the cost and improve performance on rough
terrain, which many drivers cherish even if they never leave the
asphalt. But stiff suspensions also produce a bouncy ride that is
hard to offset without soft tires.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing these often conflicting demands is difficult. The
question now in court cases and for regulators is whether too much
safety has been compromised, and whether automakers have set a
balance too far in the direction of customer desires and too little
in the interest of safety.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Ford, which installed most of the recalled Firestone
tires on its Ford Explorer sport utilities, automakers say that
they have set an appropriate balance between customer satisfaction
and safety. Even with the deaths blamed on Firestone tires,
Explorers have a 22 percent lower death rate in rollovers than
other midsized sport utilities and a 24 percent lower death rate in
crashes over all, said Ernie Grush, Ford's manager of safety data
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   While sport utility occupants have high death rates in
rollovers, their overall death rates are no higher than for car
occupants. This is because sport utilities fare well in collisions
with lower-riding cars, he said, adding that, ``Customers should
look at and consider the overall accident rate in all types of
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   While the deaths now being attributed to tires might seem
numerous to Explorer owners and are large for a recall of tires or
auto parts, they represent a smaller problem by traffic safety
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The tire-related deaths spread over the last several years are
just a tiny part of the much bigger problem of rollovers, which
kill 9,500 Americans a year. Rollovers, in turn, are just part of
the overall problem of automobile crashes, which claim 41,000 lives
annually.
</P>
<P>
   The high incidence of rollovers in the tire incidents could,
however, focus attention on a move by Senate Republicans and the
auto industry to block publication by the government of rollover
ratings for cars and for light trucks, a category that includes
minivans and pickup trucks as well as sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   After 27 years of study and numerous objections by the auto
industry, federal regulators announced plans on May 25 to begin the
ratings this autumn. But after strenuous auto industry lobbying,
the Senate inserted a little-noticed provision in the
transportation budget this summer barring regulators from issuing
the rules and ordering the National Academy of Sciences to conduct
a one-year study of the regulators' technique for the ratings. The
House version of the transportation budget does not contain this
provision, and House and Senate conferees are scheduled to work out
the differences in the budgets early next month.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stanton, the senior lobbyist for the Washington-based
Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers, said the regulators' proposed
rating system was too imprecise. The system compares a vehicle's
width to the height of its center of gravity. The system does not
take into account high-tech features like roof-mounted air bags, or
the computerized vehicle stability systems that Ford said last week
that it would start offering on all sport utility and pickup truck
models.
</P>
<P>
   But Ricardo Martinez, the administrator until last autumn of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, which regulates
vehicle safety, said that the rating system was reliable and should
be adopted quickly. The system assigns vehicles one to five stars,
like government crash test ratings. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Sport utilities are more prone than cars to roll over if they
lose a tire, although rollovers also depend on variables like
driver skill, Lindbert of GM said. The higher a vehicle's center of
gravity, the more the vehicle and its occupants tend to lean
forward during braking, and this makes it important to retain as
much traction as possible on the rear tires to keep the back end of
the vehicle under control, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If a rear tire develops problems, Lindbert said, ``in many
regards you have the potential to get sideways on the road,'' which
tends to produce rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's government data showed that while front and rear
tires are subject to failure, rear tire failures caused all but two
of the 131 rollovers reported to regulators. Not all rollovers
resulted in death. Calculating the frequency of rollovers when
tires fail is almost impossible because no one knows for sure how
many tire failures there are. The government does not collect the
data and tire makers do not share their data on their own brands.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of federal data on deaths in tire-related accidents
from 1990 to 1997, the most recent year available, shows that 91
percent of the deaths of occupants in Ford Explorers involved
rollovers. Only 28 percent of the tire-related deaths in cars
involved rollovers, said Leon Robertson, a retired Yale University
epidemiologist who analyzed the data and who has also worked for
plaintiff lawyers over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The government data included public complaints of 52 deaths in
Explorers that rolled over after Firestone tires failed, and five
more deaths in Explorers for which the complaints did not mention
whether rollovers occurred. Only two Explorers did not roll over.
All of the remaining deaths also involved rollovers, mostly in
sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Firestone tire problems, automakers had begun to
make changes to their sport utilities. The next generation of Ford
Explorers, which will go on sale in January, has a softer, car-like
suspension of coiled springs instead of a truck suspension of steel
bars that flex when the vehicle goes over bumps.
</P>
<P>
   With the new suspension will go new tires. Ford decided several
years ago that the new Explorers will no longer use 15-inch tires
but will have 16-inch tires instead. The 16-inch size has not been
recalled, although some plaintiff lawyers have called for this, and
is already used on the more expensive Explorers now. The tire has a
recommended inflation pressure of 30 pounds per square inch, four
pounds more than the 15-inch tires being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Sherwood, a Ford spokesman, said Tuesday night that even
before the current problems, Ford was considering a pressure of
more than 30 pounds for the next generation of Explorers,
particularly for the rear tires.
</P>
<P>
   But safety experts caution that the biggest safety gains will
come not from tire changes but from motorists' buckling their seat
belts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Government statisticians say that halving the frequency of
unbuckled motorists, to one-sixth of front-seat occupants from
one-third, would save several thousand lives each year and would
provide the greatest benefits for people in vehicles that roll
over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
