<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENDANT OFFICIAL MAKES BID TO REGAIN CONTROL OF AVIS
</P>
<P>
   Henry Silverman, the chief executive of Cendant, made a bid to
regain control of Avis Group, the nation's second largest rental
car company, at a price the market immediately deemed too low.
</P>
<P>
   The bid marks Silverman's return to the acquisition trail after
two years of accounting problems that grew out of his biggest
merger, with CUC International. Silverman offered about $740
million, or $29 a share, but investors bid up the shares of Avis
$5, to $30.50.
</P>
<P>
   FATAL SUV ROLL-OVERS LINKED TO FAULTY TIRES
</P>
<P>
   Government data released Tuesday evening showed that virtually
all the recent deaths linked to Firestone tires now being recalled
occurred when sport utility vehicles, most of them Ford Explorers,
rolled over after the tires failed.
</P>
<P>
   NAVISTAR TO LAY OFF 1,100
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a slowdown in heavy-truck orders in North America,
Navistar International Corp. said Tuesday that it would lay off
1,100 employees, or about 15 percent of its white-collar work
force.
</P>
<P>
   SUIT ACCUSES BET OF EVADING TAXES
</P>
<P>
   A former chief financial officer for Black Entertainment
Television plans to file a lawsuit contending that the company, its
chairman, Robert L. Johnson, and its president, Debra Lee, made
extensive efforts to evade the payment of some taxes. Johnson and
Lee could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   FAST APPEAL URGED IN MICROSOFT CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, declaring that the outcome of the
Microsoft antitrust case could affect nearly every person who uses
a computer, urged the Supreme Court to hear the company's appeal
quickly so ``that justice is not denied through delay.''
</P>
<P>
   COURT LIMITS CELL PHONE MONITORING
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court struck down part of a government order
that had expanded the ability of law enforcement agents to monitor
cell phone conversations of criminal suspects.
</P>
<P>
   POOR RETAIL EARNINGS SLOW MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined on weakness in retail shares after Home Depot
reported earnings that fell short of the most optimistic
expectations. The Dow dropped 109.14 points, or 1 percent, to
11,067.00. The S&AMP;P 500 fell 7.13 points, to 1,484.43. The Nasdaq
composite index was up 1.97 points, to 3,851.66.
</P>
<P>
   AMF IS PUSHED TO REORGANIZE
</P>
<P>
   AMF Bowling, the largest operator of bowling alleys, has been
given seven weeks to come up with a plan for reorganizing its debts
or risk being pushed into bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   EMBRAER REPORTS 35% GAIN IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian aircraft maker Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica,
or Embraer, benefiting from a vibrant demand for regional jets,
reported a 35 percent gain in profit.
</P>
<P>
   MENEM SEES THREAT FOR ARGENTINA
</P>
<P>
   The former president of Argentina, Carlos Saul Menem, has
predicted that the country faces a devaluation and a depression
unless President Fernando de la Rua either changes economic
direction or adopts the United States dollar as the national
currency.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNS RAISED ON SEC PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Ernst &AMP; Young, the accounting firm that has
supported the Securities and Exchange Commission's effort to
tighten rules on auditor independence, said the commission's
proposal goes too far and would create too much uncertainty about
what would be permitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
