<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-CAROLINE-KENNEDY-     08-15 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CAROLINE-KENNEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST KENNEDY TO OCCUPY THE WHITE HOUSE RECALLS CONVENTIONS
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Invoking the themes her father delivered here 40
years ago this summer, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg stepped out of
her guarded private life Tuesday night to lend the family name to
Al Gore's presidential campaign and to thank the nation for its
support in yet another difficult year for the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank all Americans for making me and John, and all of our
family, a part of your families _ for reaching out and sustaining
us through the good times, and the difficult ones, and for helping
us dream my father's dream,'' Schlossberg said, according to
prepared remarks released Tuesday evening. ``As I look across this
hall, and across this country, I know that my father's spirit lives
on _ and I thank all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it is our turn to prove that the New Frontier was not a
place in time but a timeless call.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a poignant moment for Schlossberg. Her simple agreement
to appear before the convention _ she disappeared from public view
almost from the moment of her father's assassination _ was a
reminder that she is now the only surviving member of the Kennedy
family that occupied the White House from 1961 through 1963.
Schlossberg's brother, John Jr., who welcomed a starring role at
the 1996 Democratic convention, died in an airplane accident last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg was one of four members of the Kennedy family who
spoke here Tuesday night, and her official task was to introduce
``Uncle Teddy.'' But her prepared remarks were filled with
allusions to her father, who died when she was three years old, a
reminder of the continuing power the Kennedy family in general, and
John F. Kennedy in particular, wields at a convention where many of
the delegates were not even born when Kennedy served as president.
</P>
<P>
   The setting itself was striking; Los Angeles was the city where
Kennedy was nominated to run for president, with Lyndon Baines
Johnson as vice president, in 1960. But it was also the place where
Schlossberg's uncle, Robert F. Kennedy, a senator from New York,
was shot, just a flew blocks from where the convention is taking
place, on the night of the California primary in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   She alluded to the losses that her family has suffered through
violence, saying: ``If we believe that we have seen enough gun
violence in our land and in our lifetimes _ that guns should no
longer takes the lives of those we love _then it is up to us'' to
elect Gore, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg said that she and Gore had both been raised ``to
believe that we can make the world new again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why my father sought to do 40 years ago, in this city,
when he stood before you and declared the opening of the New
Frontier,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg directly used her father's words as she suggested
that his call today was as fresh as it was 40 years ago. ``Our call
is to the young at heart, regardless of age,'' he said. ``A whole
world looks to see what we will do. We cannot fail their trust; we
cannot fail to try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
