<SLUG> BC-CVN-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR, ACTIVISTS SEEK PROBE OF VIOLENT CONFRONTATIONS BETWEEN
PROTESTERS, L.A. POLICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Activists, lawyers and a California state senator
Tuesday called for an independent investigation into violent
confrontations between protesters and the Los Angeles Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the melee, only a few hundred peaceful demonstrators
marched through downtown Los Angeles on the second day of the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers were far less than the estimated 8,000 Monday
night who were herded away from a fenced protest area by mounted
police and officers on-foot firing firing rubber bullets and
canisters of pepper spray into the fleeing crowd. Ten people were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters and their lawyers Tuesday said the show of force was
not necessary and abusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened last night, make no mistake about it, was
nothing less than an orchestrated police riot,'' said Dan Tokaji a
lawyer with the American Civil Liberties Union Foundation of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Tokaji and California state Sen. Tom Hayden, a member of the
``Chicago 8'' protesters during the 1968 Democratic convention,
called for an investigation by the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said his son was hit by rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that I saw on television were literally being hosed
with pepper spray in violation of any sensible guidelines,'' Hayden
said. ``This is part of a pattern and practice of overkill
accompanied by false public relations from the police department.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD has come under fire for corruption and mishandling of
rioters, most recently after the Lakers won the NBA championship
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles officials are weighing whether to fight the Justice
Department in court over the management of the LAPD or to cut a
deal that would require a series of changes demanded by federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the police in Los Angeles this week has been to
try to convince the citizenry that their excessive force is
necessary in order to build public support to get out from under
the reforms,'' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU already has won twice in court against the LAPD. One
court decision allows protesters to gather near the Staples Center.
The other prohibits police confiscating the activists' banner and
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the LAPD's third strike and it's time for them to be
out,'' Tokaji said. ``The LAPD cannot control itself and it's time
for the United States of America to come in and take control of a
department that no one else can control.''
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman said Tuesday the officers were justified when
they began herding the crowd away from the designated protest area
because several people had begun throwing objects at police and
were setting fires to piles of trash and hand-made signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our strategy was to use a lot of resources,''
Commander David Kalish said. ``You saw a lot of police officers
saturate the downtown area. The reason for that is to ensure public
safety. And it worked ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If people got pushed out of the way, sorry about that. That
was not the intent. The intent was to maintain public safety and
clear the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of delegates and reporters were knocked down and trampled
in the crowd as police moved in on horseback. Several were injured.
</P>
<P>
   After the area was cleared the Rev. Jesse Jackson walked amid
the debris, criticizing the ``excessive show of force'' employed by
police. He called it ``provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson argued that under such circumstances the police should
have concentrated on crowd control instead of creating ``a climate
for a showdown.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
