r f BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHR     08-15 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMIGHTY DOLLAR MAKES VACATIONING A BARGAIN IN LAND OF THE EURO  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER 
</HEADLINE>
   c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I just returned from a couple of weeks in
France, where almost every shop had big, bright signs in the window
screaming  &LR; Soldes &LR; , French for ``Sales.''
</P>
<P>
   What was really on sale, though, was France itself.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the deteriorating euro _ which has fallen 22 percent
against the dollar since its introduction _ vacationing in France
and most European countries has been downright affordable this
summer. And things will get even cheaper in the fall, when hotel
rates and airfares go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Europe in fall and winter is going to be
sensational,'' says Carol Kaminsky, editor of Bestfares.com.
``Airfares (to Europe) have been ridiculously high this summer.
They should start settling down in September and really get
attractive in October and November.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``You can travel in Europe for much less than you'd
ever dream of paying in Chicago, New York or San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, my husband and I stayed mostly in three-star hotels
and never paid more than $100 per night, even on the Cote D' Azur
during the  &LR; haut &LR;  (high) season.
</P>
<P>
   Our hotel room in Paris' popular Latin Quarter _ small but cute,
clean and cabled for CNN _ totaled $200 for three nights, including
taxes and the 3 percent fee tacked on by our credit card company.
(Some card issuers charge less; check before you leave.)
</P>
<P>
   Three-course dinners for two with a bottle of wine that might
cost $100 (conservatively) in the Bay Area cost half that in
Provence.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar buys more than 7 French francs, the strongest it has
been since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The greenback is at or close to 10-year highs against most other
European currencies, especially those tied to the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven countries _ Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany,
Italy, Ireland, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain _
are converting to euros.
</P>
<P>
   The big holdout is Britain, and the pound has held up better
against the dollar than the euro, making England less of a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Since it premiered in January 1999 at $1.17 per euro, the euro
has slumped to 91 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies in the euro countries have been trading in lockstep
with each other against the dollar for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   So prices in dollars are rising and falling by essentially the
same amount in all the euro countries. There are still some price
differences between countries, but they should start to disappear
as most of Europe becomes one big market.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border banking, government and most business transactions
are already taking place in euros, but you can't tuck a euro in
your money belt just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The currency won't premiere until January 2002, although most
merchants are pricing their items in euros as well as their home
currencies, which will be phased out.
</P>
<P>
   The indefatigable dollar has surprised just about everyone, and
it's all a result of ``the unexpected, continued strength of the
U.S. economy,'' says Robert Friedman, manager of the Mutual
European mutual fund. ``Generally, currency strength follows
productivity. The U.S. economy continues to be strikingly
productive. Meanwhile, France and Germany have been somewhat weaker
than anticipated,'' Friedman says.
</P>
<P>
   As foreign investors pour money into the booming U.S. financial
markets, they must buy dollars, and that makes the buck even
brawnier against scrawnier currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was dealt another blow when hedge-fund giant George
Soros said he was unwinding his euro position. That knocked the
euro from 95 cents to 90 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's not clear how European authorities will manage
their joint economy. ``Inflation is less than 2 percent in France
and Germany, but 6 percent in Ireland. If you raise rates to dampen
inflation in Ireland, you hurt growth in France and Germany,''
Friedman says. ``It's an unprecedented situation, and as a result,
people see the euro as a riskier venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does the euro belong? The Economist magazine says the euro
should be worth $1, based on purchasing-power parity. But nobody
sees it getting there overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the U.S. convincing the world it can come into a soft
landing, and continue to grow without inflation, it probably
prolongs the period of relative U.S. dollar strength,'' says
Michael Levy, manager of the Deutsche European Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   Before, he says, people were thinking the euro might reach $1
within three to six months. Now, he says, it's more like six to 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Ho, co-manager of the Wells Fargo International Equity
fund, says that the euro eventually will stage a convincing
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think the weak euro is bad. But it's not. It helps
the export structure,'' because European goods get cheaper on the
world market. ``If you have a weak euro and restructure (the
economy) at the same time, you can have economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1999, Ho explains, the dollar fell by half against
major currencies. ``This helped the U.S. to export. We also
restructured.'' Companies reduced junk debt, pared their workforces
and eliminated non-core businesses. ``That's why our economy is so
strong now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Ho predicts that ``this could be the European decade.'' But ``as
a traveler, you have at least a 12-month horizon'' before Europe
starts looking expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Some people aren't taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very smart young man in my office is getting married in the
spring and honeymooning in Italy,'' says Friedman. ``He's buying
lira now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MORE ON FULL DISCLSOURE: In response to Friday's column on the
Securities and Exchange Commission's new full-disclosure
regulation, dubbed Reg FD, I got this e-mail from Charles Boucher,
managing director of equity research at Bear Stearns in San
Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``Interesting article, but I think it exaggerates the impact of
Regulation FD on leveling the playing field for small investors.
While companies may be less likely to call an analyst or (portfolio
manager) at a large fund like Fidelity or Putnam, it's not the
management guidance that moves stocks anymore, at least technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large investment funds, hedge funds and sell-side analysts
that do their homework discover material information well in
advance of management disclosure. That's why so many stocks move in
front of earnings conference calls or other significant events. In
fact, most analysts (good ones, anyway), use management as the
information source of last resort, and the conference call is
usually only an affirmation of whether the analyst has done their
job right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual investors that think that Regulation FD will give
them the same edge as large investment firms are deluding
themselves. The only way an individual investor can compete on a
level playing field is if they sweat the details the way that good
analysts and investors do, which is by calling plant managers,
customers, competitors, salespeople and other sources of primary
research.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Net Worth runs Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail Kathleen
Pender at kpender(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
