<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LINUXWORLD GOES MAINSTREAM  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Backed by a growing parade of
computer-industry heavyweights, the Linux movement rallied
yesterday in San Jose, Calif., for its biggest-ever trade show.
</P>
<P>
   LinuxWorld Conference and Expo was in past years the province
mainly of little-known distributors and developers of the upstart
computer-operating system, but this year the show floor is
dominated by giant booths sponsored by the likes of Compaq, Dell,
Hewlett-Packard, IBM and even Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Notably but not surprisingly absent was Microsoft. Linux, which
is developed cooperatively by thousands of developers around the
world and available free to anyone who wants to use it, is posing
an increasingly credible threat, at least in some markets, to
Microsoft's Windows operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of Linux's changing role was a keynote speech by
Michael Dell, chief executive of the Dell Computer, who has long
been considered one of Microsoft's most loyal supporters in the
industry. In past years, most LinuxWorld speakers were gurus in the
open-source movement, the worldwide network of volunteer developers
who cooperatively maintain and enhance Linux and related software.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said his company, now the No. 1 supplier of personal
computers in the U.S. and No. 2 in the server market, is ``very
committed to Linux.''
</P>
<P>
   The open-source development model,'' Dell said, ``is built to
succeed in the Internet age.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing not only the low cost of the system but also its
stability and flexibility and the ease with which customers can
make modifications, he declared that ``the open-source model makes
a lot more economic sense than the proprietary model some other
companies use.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point, Dell invited Bill Parducci, a
programmer working for Toyota, to explain why the auto company had
decided to use Linux rather than Windows on multimedia presentation
systems it is installing at dealers nationwide. Parducci explained
that Toyota had asked its previous operating-system supplier, which
he did not name, but said was ``out of Redmond,'' to make some
changes to its product to make it easier to keep large amounts of
multimedia data in readily accessible ``cache'' memory so dealers
wouldn't need to download it over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spent 18 months on it and still couldn't get it into
their product,'' Parducci said. He and one other engineer, using an
old PC, finally went to work trying to add the capabilities they
wanted to Linux, and two weeks later, they had a working prototype.
</P>
<P>
   Some keynote attendees, however, greeted Dell's conversion to
their cause with some skepticism. During a question-and-answer
period after his speech, several demanded to know why Dell often
charges more for Linux systems than for comparable hardware running
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Dell gave no clear response but insisted his company had
``absolutely no secret obligations to Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from technical users and some college students, Linux has
made only limited inroads into Windows' domination of the desktop
on home and business PCs _ in part because it hasn't been as easy
to use and far fewer Linux applications for mainstream users have
been available.
</P>
<P>
   Linux supporters announced several initiatives intended to make
the OS more appealing to nontechnical users. Eazel, for example, a
Palo Alto, Calif., startup staffed largely by Apple alumni, showed
off new tools that make it easier to manage files on Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Gnumatic of Austin, Texas, previewed GnuCash, a personal-finance
program it called a ``quick and intuitive'' alternative to Intuit's
Quicken. And Helix Code of Cambridge, Mass., showed Evolution, a
new e-mail and personal-information management program designed as
an alternative to Microsoft's Outlook on Windows.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen companies, including Compaq, HP, IBM, Sun
Microsystems and several Linux leaders, also joined forces to form
the Gnome Foundation, a group that will steer and promote the
development of Gnome, one of several graphical user interfaces and
application frameworks for Linux. Despite the corporate support,
the new group's board will be elected by the hundreds of volunteer
developers who've contributed to the project.
</P>
<P>
   In all, some 200 companies are strutting their stuff at the
show, and show organizers said they had to turn away 50 others for
want of space at the McEnery Convention Center. Next year, the show
will move to San Francisco to take advantage of the roomier Moscone
Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Henry Norr at hnorr(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
