 MOTHER-AND-SON TEAM RELY ON EACH OTHER IN BUILDING EBENEFITS  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; When Andy Kurtzig read ``Profiles of Genius''
as a college sophomore and discovered that most of the 13 featured
``change masters'' _ including Apple's Steve Jobs, Microsoft's Bill
Gates, FedEx's Fred Smith and CNN's Ted Turner _ never graduated
from college, he decided to drop out of the University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to start a business and thought if I finish college,
it would be suicide,'' Kurtzig recalled. Then he talked to his
mother, Sandra Kurtzig, who founded Ask Group, one of Silicon
Valley's early software success stories. She persuaded him to
switch majors to business from engineering and start a venture on
the side if he desired.
</P>
<P>
   Family businesses in the United States are the rule, not the
exception. Ninety-five percent of all businesses are family owned
or controlled, and they produce close to 60 percent of the gross
domestic product. Many, though, don't have such well-known or
successful mothers as mentors.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurtzigs have enjoyed a good personal and professional
relationship. Four years ago, the two co-founded eBenefits in San
Francisco. Andy Kurtzig, 27, is chief executive officer of the
company, which links small businesses to human resources, payroll
and benefits management services via the Internet. Sandra Kurtzig,
53, is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kurtzig caught the entrepreneurial bug early. His mother
started Ask in 1974 when she was 27. It began in a spare bedroom
and grew as Sandra Kurtzig persuaded Hewlett-Packard to let her and
her programmers use one of the company's minicomputers after hours
from 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. to create their manufacturing management
software.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kurtzig's father studied engineering under transistor
pioneer William Shockley at Stanford and started and sold a
touch-screen company called Personal Touch.
</P>
<P>
   Though born to two entrepreneurs, Andy Kurtzig's early ideas did
not fly.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a teenager, his father nixed his plan to produce
molded jumps for bicycle motocrosses because of potential liability
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Andy's notion of putting little flaps on the sides of airplane
tires so they would spin when hit by wind and thus reduce rubber
lost to skids when wheels touched the tarmac didn't take off,
either. Then someone beat him to a patent on an accordionlike
expandable PC keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   However, one of Kurtzig's notions as a senior at UC Berkeley was
moderately successful. Anser Corp., a play on the name his mother
chose for her company, developed software to automate calendar
listings for newspapers. In 1995, a year after he started the
venture, Kurtzig sold the software to one of his customers, the San
Francisco Bay Guardian, for nearly $500,000 and took a long
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, he kept thinking about human resources, the
part of the business he liked least. It was ``the biggest pain in
the neck'' for him at Anser and, Kurtzig reasoned, many of the
country's other 8 million small businesses with two to 100
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sandra Kurtzig was looking for investment
opportunities. She had left Ask Group in 1992 after leading it to
$500 million in annual sales in her second stint as CEO. Two years
later, the company was acquired by Computer Associates
International.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Family Business
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, Sandra Kurtzig recalls her son asked if she
wanted to set up a company together. ``It was every mother's
dream,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During the past four years, she said they have had only one
fight. It was about whether to provide free human resources
services. ``I never understood the concept,'' said Sandra Kurtzig.
``I thought companies that gave away everything for free were
nonprofits.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kurtzig argued that providing a free version of eBenefits'
service was necessary to win attention and market share. His mother
relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good working agreement,'' Andy Kurtzig recalls. ``I
did all the work; she did all the agreeing.'' That included Sandra
Kurtzig agreeing to invest $500,000 to get the company up and
running in a year.
</P>
<P>
   The initial plan was to provide health-insurance quotes online
to small businesses. But the cost of acquiring customers was high,
and the market was developing slowly. By the end of 1997, eBenefits
was low on cash, and Andy Kurtzig recalled his mother telling him,
``You're on your own. Either close up shop and find a real job or
make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Andy Kurtzig broadened the scope of eBenefits to let
small businesses outsource not just health insurance, but payroll
and other HR services.
</P>
<P>
   Through eBenefits, employees can turn to the Web instead of the
business owner to compare and select health benefits, insurance
plans, payroll deductions and mutual funds for their 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Andy Kurtzig went out to raise venture capital. His
mother did not go with him, although she helped him practice his
pitch and peppered him with questions that VCs were likely to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Only after her son won commitments from venture-capital firms
Draper Fisher Jurvetson and W.R. Hambrecht did Sandra Kurtzig
advise him to also talk the New Enterprise Associates. Within 24
hours, eBenefits had taken in $8 million from three VC firms
instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   EBenefits also has developed important strategic partnerships
with Automatic Data Processing Inc., the largest automated payroll
services company, as well as with the U.S. Small Business
Administration, AT&AMP;T and others.
</P>
<P>
   Outsourcing human resource services has become a huge business.
Dataquest estimates the market will grow from $900 million in 1999
to more than $12 billion by 2003 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The largest HR outsourcing companies, such as software vendors
SAP, Oracle and PeopleSoft and consultants Mercer and Hewitt, focus
on larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Banc of America Securities analyst David Scharf notes that
several Web-based companies such as Employease, EmployeeLife.Com,
iBenefits and eBenefits are providing online solutions to small and
midsize businesses that have been plagued by time-consuming and
cumbersome HR chores.
</P>
<P>
   For example, iBenefits in El Segundo, Calif., is developing
Web-based employee-benefits enrollment and administration tools for
companies with more than 200 employees. The company has raised more
than $53 million in venture capital since last year, including $41
million last month.
</P>
<P>
   BenefitPoint, a San Francisco company that started in 1998,
raised $52 million in venture capital in May and recruited former
McKesson Corp. CEO Mark Pulido in June to lead the company. The
company focuses on benefits procurement and administration for
companies with 100 to 5,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although eBenefits hardly has the field to itself, Andy Kurtzig
sees his company as the ``leader in the small-business segment of
two to 100 employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks, eBenefits expects to get a boost when about
2,000 ADP payroll services employees begin selling eBenefits' HR
services to their clients. That should expand eBenefits' customer
base of close to 14,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
   One satisfied eBenefits customer is Netiverse. The San Jose,
Calif., company that was just acquired by Cisco Systems used the
free version of eBenefits' product to track personal information
such as vacation days and health benefits for its 34 employees.
``We were able to create a virtual HR department and create links
to other sites,'' said Netiverse office administrator Bridget
Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sandra Kurtzig went along with the idea of offering a
free version of eBenefits' service to some small businesses, that
is coming to a stop. By the end of the year, all small-business
clients will be charged $30 to $200 a month. In addition, eBenefits
receives a small commission from health-insurance and other
companies that sell services to its clients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of EBENEFIT (40314 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
