<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBRECHT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HAMBRECHT HELPS DOW CHEMICAL OFFER DEBT ONLINE  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; WR Hambrecht, the San Francisco investment
bank that pioneered public stock offerings over the Internet,
extended its Web auction system yesterday with the completion of a
$300 million sale of five-year debt securities for Dow Chemical Co.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht officials said the sale marked the first time an
investment bank has carried out a debt offering for a client
entirely via an Internet auction. In the only previous online debt
auctions, two investment banks recently sold their own debt.
</P>
<P>
   Dow's notes pay a 7 percent interest rate based on their face
value. They sold in the auction for $995.54 for a $1,000 note,
bringing their actual yield to 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That is 1.01 percentage points higher than the yield for U.S.
Treasury notes of comparable maturity and is at the high end of the
range of 0.92 to 1.02 percentage points over the government notes
that Midland, Mich.'s Dow sought.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht has previously held Internet auctions to sell stock in
four initial public offerings. The investment banks Bear Stearns,
HSBC Securities and Williams Capital Group co-managed the Dow debt
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Online debt auctions ``could become as big a deal, if not a
bigger deal, than (Internet) IPOs,'' said Hambrecht Chief Operating
Officer J.D. Delafield.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hambrecht's auction system, investors submit online bids
for stock or debt securities. The offering price is set at the
highest level the issuer can get and still sell all the securities.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dow offering, Hambrecht received bids from 62
institutional or individual investors, 57 of which were accepted.
The auction took place over a two-hour period yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, securities prices are set by the issuer and
underwriters rather than by auction. Proponents say the auction
method is fairer because it uses a market-based system to determine
offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(at)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
