<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-DIARY-NYT     08-15 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND THE GHOSTWRITER; CHAOS IN THE LIEBERMAN SUITE; WHAT'D HE
SAY?; JUST TWO PALS; THE FIRST FRIEND'S REPORT; STOPPING TRAFFIC
</HEADLINE>
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Shrum, the Gore strategist who has written some of the
most eloquent speeches of his generation, said Tuesday that Gore
was ``literally, truly and unquestionably involved'' in writing
acceptance speech to the Democratic convention on Thursday night.
With no help at all from Shrum, who wrote much of Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy's ``dream shall never die'' speech that ignited the 1980
Democratic convention in New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``He is writing his own speech,'' Shrum repeated by phone from
Michigan, where he was traveling with Gore. Shrum added that Gore,
a former journalist, was ``an excellent writer. He's got a very
real sense of imaging and the sounds and balance of language.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shrum did advise Kennedy on his convention speech Tuesday
night. Shrum also said that when he wrote Kennedy's most famous
oratorical line _ ``the dream shall never die'' _ the idea
``basically just came out of the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaos reigns at Hadassah Lieberman's office at the Biltmore
Hotel. Phones keep ringing. Calls are unanswered. An abrupt
decision by the Gore campaign asking her to nominate her husband,
Joseph, as vice president at the convention has thrown her small
staff into turmoil. Interviews are being canceled or rearranged as
speechwriters toil in the Lieberman suite.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lieberman's role in the upcoming campaign is still under
discussion by the Gore and Lieberman staffs. But, they say, Mrs.
Lieberman, 52, will probably move out alone on the campaign trail,
without her husband, just as Lynne Cheney, the wife of Dick Cheney,
the Republican vice-presidential nominee, has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hadassah's got a great story to tell, a really compelling
story,'' said Dan Gerstein, her husband's spokesman. ``She's the
daughter of Holocaust survivors. Her mother was liberated by
American GI's at Dachau. The fact that she'll be on the stage at
this convention is a powerful testament to the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as Lieberman was selected, the Gore campaign
asked Sally Aman, who had worked more than four years as Tipper
Gore's communications director, to serve in a similar role with
Mrs. Lieberman. Before this, Mrs. Lieberman had never had a staff
of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Is Mrs. Lieberman, who has not spoken much publicly, nervous
about appearing before the convention? ``It's perfectly normal to
be nervous, and she is,'' said Aman. ``But she's talking about a
subject she knows very well. Her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The coda of President Clinton's speech to the convention Monday
night carried an unscripted _ and unexpected _ phrase that not only
seemed enigmatic but also confused some newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Departing from his prepared text _ as he often does _ Clinton
added a sentence in the final paragraph of his speech, saying,
``And remember,  &UR; whenever  &LR; you think about me, keep putting people
first.'' The White House quoted Clinton as making the comment. And
people listening to the speech agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But others who heard the speech said that was not correct. They
said they had heard Clinton say: ``And remember,  &UR; whatever  &LR; you
think about me...'' The word itself sounded blurry.
</P>
<P>
   The one-word difference, of course, carries an entirely
different meaning. One White House aide said he was fairly certain
that Clinton said ``whatever.'' If so, that would be the only
reference in the speech to the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said, ``It
means `whether you think well of me or not, what's important is the
future of the country.' It means `don't get distracted by what you
think of me personally.'''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers like The New York Daily News and The St. Louis
Post-Dispatch also used the phrase ``whatever you think of me.''
The New York Times, in its published transcript of the speech, also
had ``whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the White House issued its official transcript of
the remarks, and it said ``whenever.'' A team of New York Times
editors also listened to the tape of the speech and agreed that the
president said ``whenever.'' Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Certain East and West Coast eyebrows were raised when Sen.
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., was spotted walking across the
convention floor on Monday night with his onetime close friend
Patricia Duff, former wife of the Revlon billionaire Ronald O.
Perelman and the former Tristar Pictures chairman Mike Medavoy.
There had been numerous tabloid reports of a Torricelli-Duff split.
</P>
<P>
   Were they back together? Torricelli would not say. ``There is a
bond between all the Democrats who were on the convention floor,''
Torricelli pleasantly replied, ``but it is something short of
marriage.'' Duff, who has been through an ugly, highly publicized
child custody battle with Perelman, was one of Bill Clinton's first
and biggest fund-raisers in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Terry McAuliffe, Clinton fund-raiser extraordinaire and close
presidential pal, got the first hug after Clinton finished his
convention speech. Holding court with reporters Tuesday after
speaking to a breakfast meeting of the New York delegation at the
Century Plaza Hotel, McAuliffe said that after Clinton leaves the
presidency, ``he has no interest in making money.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark may be of some interest to Hillary Rodham Clinton,
who has worried about the couples' extraordinary legal bills.
McAuliffe also said that the retired president would spend a third
of his time at his presidential library in Little Rock, Ark., a
third of his time traveling and a third in New York. As to whether
the Clintons would keep their home in Chappaqua, N.Y. _ the loan
for it was temporarily guaranteed by McAuliffe _ the presidential
fund-raiser replied: ``You'll have to talk to the first lady and
the president about their plans. They've got their own mortgage
now. They don't need me.''
</P>
<P>
   The model Christie Brinkley, a member of the New York
delegation, caused such a traffic jam of television cameras on the
convention floor on Monday night that security guards finally asked
her to move into the hallway so they could clear the aisles. ``I
wonder why,'' New York state Comptroller Carl McCall dryly
observed. Eliot Spitzer, the state attorney general, was one of
hundreds of New York delegates and elected officials left in the
shadows with the departure of Brinkley and her klieg lights. ``This
shows the proper media understanding of how politics works,''
Spitzer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
