<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, AUG. 21 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 14
about Hillary Rodham Clinton's speech at the Democratic National
Convention referred incorrectly to Senator Robert G. Torricelli's
relationship with Patricia Duff, with whom he watched the speech.
The two are not married.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 13
about the scaling back of network television coverage of the
Republican and Democratic political conventions misstated the name
of a series that NBC showed on the Republicans' first night. It was
``Third Watch,'' not ``First Watch.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 13
about an effort by Linux software developers and computer
manufacturers to compete with Microsoft's Office applications
misspelled the surname of the chairman of the Eazel Corporation. He
is Mike Boich, not Boiche.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 14
about the retracing of Louis Armstrong's roots in New Orleans by
the writer Tad Jones misspelled the surname of a jazz writer and
Armstrong biographer for whom Mr. Jones also conducted research. He
is Gary Giddins, not Giddens.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the article also misspelled the
surname of Mr. Jones's great-grandfather. He was Jacinto Bunol, not
Buno.
</P>
</TEXT>
