<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HN     08-15 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GORE HITS POPULIST NOTE EN ROUTE TO CONVENTION &HT;    (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES Democrat Al Gore, taking party leadership from
President Clinton Tuesday, headed toward the waiting limelight at
the Democratic National Convention here with promises to ``stand
up`` against ``powerful interests'' that he said are aligned with
Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took the helm of the Democratic party from Clinton at a
boisterous campaign rally in Monroe, Mich., where the vice
president cast his contest with Bush as a struggle between an
experienced, hard-working populist ally of ``working families''
pitted against a Republican beholden to so-called ``special
interests'' and who wants to enrich the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we've got a hard-fought race ahead,`` Gore warned
placard-waving supporters, with his wife Tipper, Clinton and first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton standing nearby. ``I know the powerful
interests are going to fight against us with everything they've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore headed toward a Democratic convention that had been fired
up Tuesday night by speeches by the Rev. Jesse Jackson, and four
members of the Kennedy clan, led by Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg,
daughter of the late President John F. Kennedy, and Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., who lost brothers John and Robert to assassins'
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the veteran civil rights leader, scoffed at what he
termed the ``inclusion illusion'' staged by Republicans at their
convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago. He urged Americans to
``stay out of the Bushes'' when it comes to choosing the next
president. Jackson warned that President George Bush had named
Clarence Thomas to the Supreme Court; Florida Gov. Jeb Bush had
dismantled affirmative action; and the GOP nominee _ when he was a
candidate in the Republican primaries _ had chosen ``the
Confederate flag over the American flag'' in the dispute over
banners flying over the South Carolina state house.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy coined the term ``the New Frontier'' at the
1960 Democratic convention in Los Angeles; his daughter, Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, rallied the delegates Tuesday night with her
challenge that it was now time ``to prove that the New Frontier was
not a place in time but a timeless call'' to action to clean up the
environment, end gun violence and protect human and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   With so many Americans ``doing so well,'' Kennedy Schlossberg
declared, ``it is time once again to ask more of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the senator from Massachusetts who inherited his
brother's Senate seat in 1962, urged Americans to support Gore
because ``he's fighting for you'' to expand health care coverage
against plans by a Republican rival who is willing to ``look inward
(and) look backward'' in order to ``comfort the comfortable.''
Kennedy, who lost his own presidential bid against Democratic
President Jimmy Carter in 1980, urged the nation to ``not turn back
to old policies and old ways that favor the few at the expense of
the many.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Kennedy-Townsend, the 49-year-old daughter of Robert
Kennedy and the lieutenant governor of Maryland, who plans to seek
the state's governorship, voiced the family's commitment to the
downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move forward we cannot leave anyone behind,''
Kennedy-Townsend said. ``We Democrats stand not just for the
success of the few but for opportunity for all.'' Robert F.
Kennedy, Jr., also spoke to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Harold Ford Jr., D-Tenn., the convention keynote speaker,
said the nation is at a crucial juncture. ``Will the amazing
advances of tomorrow be fenced off for the few _ or will they be
tools for all of us to build better lives?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Late polls showed Gore had plenty of work ahead of him to close
in on Bush, the second-term governor of Texas who waited out the
Democratic convention at his 1,500-acre ranch in Crawford, Texas,
before planning to take the fight to Gore in his native Tennessee
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide surveys by the Los Angeles Times and for Voter.com
showed Bush holding a 9-percentage point lead over Gore. The Los
Angeles Times survey spotlighted problems Gore has with Democrats,
capturing only 78 percent of Democrats compared to Bush's 18
percent. Bush also holds a 16-percentage point edge over Gore among
independent voters, the constituency expected to decide the outcome
on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, 52, who served 16 years in the House and Senate before
joining Clinton's ticket in 1992, appeared to be banking on his
tough-edged populism to help him rebound. Gore warned the Michigan
rally that ``all the powerful interests are lined up against'' his
succession, including big oil, big tobacco, big drug companies and
big polluters. Gore used the word ``fight'' no less than 13 times
in his brief remarks, adding: ``As president, I'll stand up to them
and stand up for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' aggressive us-versus-them populist rhetoric
recalled the GOP primary campaign of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who
unsuccessfully challenged Bush for the Republican presidential
nomination. Campaign advisers said Gore must seize his first
moments outside Clinton's shadow to dramatically introduce himself
to the nation as a leader of the future rather than the trusted,
loyal sidekick to one of the most controversial and popular
presidents of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Democratic delegates approved a party platform
that reflected Gore's priorities and heard the unambiguous
endorsement of Gore by his defeated rival in the Democratic
presidential primaries, former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore-crafted party platform built upon the fiscal caution of
the Clinton-Gore years that transformed the political landscape
from political fights over deficit spending to disagreements over
how to distribute the federal budget surplus. The Democratic
document opposes school vouchers and partial privatization of
Social Security. The document vows to pay off the publicly held
national debt in 12 years, provide prescription drug coverage under
Medicare and tax cuts targeted to the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
stewarthearstdc.com )
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
