<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos have moved as part of tonight's New York
Times Photo Package moving Tuesday, 08/15/00.
</P>
<P>
   We continue to move photos from the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   A separate budget, slugged BC-DEM-PHOTO-BUDGET-NYT, listing the
photos moved from the convention, will move at the conclusion of
tonight's events.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HURON, Ohio -- August 15, 2000 -- OHIO-GARDEN-2 --
Restaurants from around the country look to the Chef's Garden in
Ohio to deliver their uniquely grown vegetables. The 70-acre farm
is on a flat, humid plain west of Cleveland. In less than 24 hours
these vegetables, meticulously cleaned and gathered in bouquets,
will be shipped overnight to one of the country's top kitchens.
Chef's Garden produce, clockwise from top left, includes basil in
many varieties; garlic roots, boxed and in a beaker; carrots in red
and white as well as orange; feathery popcorn shoots; and tiny,
vibrant peppers. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HURON, Ohio -- August 15, 2000 -- OHIO-GARDEN-1 --
Restaurants from around the country look to the Chef's Garden in
Ohio to deliver their uniquely grown vegetables. Velvety spinach
and multicolored miniature peppers are among the specialty
vegetables grown in the garden. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- CEO-TENURE-- A new study has
put a kink in the widely held conventional wisdom about executive
tenure. The study concludes that not much has changed in the second
half of the 1990's in a chief executive's longevity in office. From
left, C.F. Knight, Chairman &AMP; CEO of Emerson Electric; Maurice
Greenberg, chief executive of A.I.G.; Walt Disney Company CEO
Michael Eisner; and Edward E. Whitacre Jr., chairman of SBC. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- INVEST-INTERNET --
Although Michael Nadel is just getting started as an investor, he
says the mutual fund industry has already lost him as a customer.
Nadel, 26, a Washington lawyer, says he grew frustrated a few
months ago when he could not determine what was causing the sharp
decline in the value of his shares of an Internet stock fund.
Because most mutual funds disclose their complete holdings only
twice a year and with a significant time lag, he said, ``I don't
know what they own or how they make decisions.'' Nadel in his
Washington office. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- SUBMARiNE-TOUR-COX -- This
year the U.S. Navy is celebrating the 100th anniversary of its
submarine forces. A crewman takes a look at surrounding traffic
before the USS Hampton dives on a mission in July. The Hamptom is a
Los Angeles-class fast attack sub, 330 feet long, 36 feet in
diameter and almost impossible for the enemy to find. (Paul
Reid/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) OSSINING, N.Y. -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- SUN-RETURNS -- Joseph
Fiorentino, a retired railroad engineer, welcomes back the sun on
the dock at Engel Park, along the Hudson River, Tuesday. Tuesday's
bright sunshine brought a happy relief to the cloudy skies and rain
which have prevailed for the last several days throughout the
state. Along with enjoying the sun, Fiorentino's sunny river-side
corner is near another of his passions, the railroad tracks.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BOSTON -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- AIR-WOES-BOS -- No one who
flies with any regularity has been immune from the delays and
cancellations that are plaguing an air system that is bursting at
the seams with travelers. Kamrom Gibson, 11, of Atlanta, catches up
on his sleep at Logan International airport last Wednesday. Gibson
and his mother were returning to Atlanta after a visit to Boston
but were delayed five hours because of weather along their route.
(Justine Ellement/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- FLAVORED-ALCOHOL-2 --
Restaurants are borrowing a page out of the Absolut book and
infusing their vodkas and other alcohol with an array of flavors.
Ginger, left, and peper vodkas in the bar at the Hilton Hotel in
Manhattan. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 2000 -- FLAVORED-ALCOHOL --
Restaurants are borrowing a page out of the Absolut book and
infusing their vodkas and other alcohol with an array of flavors.
Dan Perlman, the beverage director at AZ, in the Flatiron district,
mixes his creations in the restaurant's bar. (James Estrin/The New
York Times)
</P>
