or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SABRINA TAVERNISE with CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Battling stormy seas and time, Russian seamen tried
again in the early hours Wednesday to lower a rescue capsule to the
nuclear-powered submarine lying broken and powerless on the floor
of the Barents Sea with 116 men aboard. An attempt on Tuesday
failed, and there was no immediate information whether the later
attempt was more successful.
</P>
<P>
   But with high seas, poor visibility and strong underwater
currents, and with the submarine lying at an angle at a depth of
350 to 480 feet, the chances for a rescue seemed to grow dimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we know is that there are still people alive and they are
signaling SOS,'' said the Russian navy's commander, Adm. Vladimir
Kuroyedov. ``Every day the chances are slimmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The only communication with the submarine, the Kursk, was from
inside, from crew members tapping on the hull, Russian officials
said. There were reports that the tapping had grown fainter and
less frequent.
</P>
<P>
   During much of Tuesday, rescue efforts were hampered by winds
that reached 45 miles an hour and whipped up waves of 13 feet.
Water temperatures near the submarine hovered at 39 degrees.
Visibility under water was extremely low, as little as five feet,
the navy said.
</P>
<P>
   But the winds quieted in the night, enabling another rescue
attempt. At least two small bell-shaped rescue capsules, each able
to hold 10 to 20 people, were lowered to the scene of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The capsules are equipped with video cameras and powerful
searchlights and are normally run by three or four people,
according to the RIA news agency. The agency said docking with the
submarine required a high degree of precision.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they succeed in docking, the rescuers would probably
have to carry out exhausted and injured crewmen. Some reports said
that raising the rescue capsule, a simple chamber that hangs from a
ship, could take several hours to avoid potentially fatal
complications from decompression.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfax news agency quoted Kuroyedov as saying that if this
plan failed, the navy might try to raise the 14,000-ton submarine
with 400-ton inflatable pontoons.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts doubted that this could work, given the depth
and the enormous weight of the Kursk and the water that has entered
parts of the submarine. The experts also fear it might take too
long to attach pontoons to the submarine, given what is thought to
be the perilous state of the men inside.
</P>
<P>
   Though information about what happened remained fragmentary and
often contradictory, the Kursk was apparently damaged by an
explosion and partly flooded on Saturday during training maneuvers
of Russia's Northern Fleet. Some earlier reports said the accident
occurred on Sunday, but it now appears that the crew has been in
trouble since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk is one of Russia's newest and most modern submarines,
and the navy press office said that several high-ranking naval
officers were on board to monitor the exercise along with the
regular crew.
</P>
<P>
   After examining the outside of the submarine, navy officials
said the most likely reason for the accident was an explosion,
possibly from a torpedo carried in the front of the vessel. Russian
officials insisted that there were no nuclear weapons on board and
that the submarine's reactors were shut down. Russia has been
accused of contaminating the Barents with radiation from discarded
nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two Russian vessels were reported in the region
struggling to find ways of saving their comrades.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that oxygen supplies were likely to last only
till Friday and that they had not succeeded in attaching oxygen and
fuel lines to the Kursk. They said that the only power on the
submarine was a battery, which cannot be recharged underwater,
condemning the men to a slow death of asphyxiation if they were not
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that there was no information about the plight of the
seamen and officers. Submarine experts could only speculate why the
crew was not able to release an antenna, or how much of the vessel
was flooded, or what exactly went so terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Senior American officials in Washington said two American
submarines had been monitoring the Russian exercise, which began
last Thursday and involved a variety of vessels and aircraft, with
test firings of missiles. The officials said it was one of the
largest exercises held by the Russians in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The American submarines detected a large explosion at about 7:30
or 8 on Saturday morning, the officials said, apparently from the
Kursk. The source was not clear, but the sound was not that of a
collision, they said. American officials ruled out any collision
with an American submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The officials were skeptical of a rescue, noting that the Kursk
was resting at a 60 degree angle, making it unlikely that a rescue
craft could successfully dock.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although American and other NATO navies offered to help, Russia
initially refused the offers, and in any case it was not
immediately clear what they could do.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Russian military officers met at NATO headquarters in
Brussels, Belgium, on Tuesday night to see if there was anything
the Western alliance could provide. A NATO official said the
Russians discussed technical details in a telephone conference with
naval experts in Northwood, England, where NATO has its naval
headquarters for the eastern Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate indication whether the discussions led to
any concrete action. The British and American navies have various
underwater rescue craft, and Norway and Germany have extensive
undersea oil exploring experience, but it was not clear whether any
Western vessel could link up to the Kursk's hatches.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen sent a letter to the Russian
defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, offering ``any assistance you
need.'' There was no immediate response.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Craig R. Quigley, a spokesman for the U.S. Navy, said
the Navy had informed other countries in the past of the dimensions
of escape hatches that would be compatible with American rescue
capsules. But he did not know whether the Russians had adopted
those standards.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Quigley said the 60-degree list of the Kursk put it
``beyond the design parameters of the U.S. deep submergence rescue
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle A.H. Trost, a retired admiral who was formerly chief of
naval operations, said that even if the Kursk had a fully charged
battery when it went down, the power would probably last only two
or three days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere must be fouling very rapidly,'' said Trost, who
once commanded a nuclear-powered submarine. And ``lights last only
a very limited time.''
</P>
<P>
   The plight of the trapped seamen dominated Russian news. On one
radio call-in show, a former professor demanded to know what could
be done to persuade the authorities to seek outside help: ``What
signs to we need to draw, to whom must we appeal to get them to
accept help?''
</P>
<P>
   At least six seamen from the southeastern Russian city of Kursk,
for which the submarine was named, were on board. One, Dima
Staroseltsev, 20, had finished a training course in June and wrote
home to say he was happy to be leaving for sea, his mother said by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``His last letter was so joyful,'' the mother, Valentina
Staroseltseva, said. ``He said, mama, there's a great crew on board
here, a bunch of guys from Kursk. We're like one big family.''
</P>
<P>
   The submarine's commander, Gennadi Lyachin, 45, has served in
the Northern Fleet since 1978, according to Russian news reports.
The navy refused to give any details about the rest of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The crew's plight horrified Russians. ``They are sitting and
waiting,'' said Aleksandr Nikitin, an environmental activist who
once was an engineer on a nuclear submarine. ``This accident
sketches a pretty accurate picture of the state of the navy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of concrete information, experts said it was not
possible to say how long the men could go on. They could slowly run
out of oxygen, succumbing to mental dullness and possibly
convulsions before sinking into a comas and dying.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a buildup of carbon dioxide, the brain would
gradually stop functioning, the men would slip into unconsciousness
and their hearts would weaken and stop. Or, if the electrical
system had failed, they could freeze to death. Or they could perish
from a lethal buildup of nitrogen, sulfides and toxic gases.
</P>
</TEXT>
