<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CERABINO16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WAR ON DRUGS? LET'S CUT TO THE CHASE
 &HT;    By FRANK CERABINO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I spent the day Tuesday listening to people talk
about drugs, both prescription and non-prescription.
</P>
<P>
   But first let me tell you about the freeway chase.
</P>
<P>
   They really know how to do car chases here. The driving is
crisp, the police pursuit worthy of Hollywood standards, and the TV
news coverage top-notch.
</P>
<P>
   There was a great one here Monday night, right after the
convention broke up. A guy stole a Geo Prism, and for the next
hour, he drove it all over L.A.'s freeways.
</P>
<P>
   The local FOX affiliate broke away from its convention coverage,
using a helicopter reporter, an anchor in the studio, and another
reporter at the Democratic National Convention to give play-by-play
(or maybe it's turn-by-turn) coverage to the meandering 110 m.p.h.
highway chase for the whole hour.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never watched a highway chase in such detail, so I was
impressed by the station's police specialist, Rod Bernsen, who was
kind enough to explain the intracacies of freeway chase etiquette
for all the convention visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you usually don't see _ I know there are a lot of
visitors here for the convention _ is for 10 or 15 cars to be in
pursuit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernsen explained that the police preferred to illuminate the
stolen car with a million-candlepower light, and hang back,
allowing the other motorists to make way for the pursuit parade.
</P>
<P>
   The TV station was kind enough to show superimposed highway maps
on the screen and make predictions about where the fleeing felon
might go next.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, he's westbound on 10, let's see if he's going over to the
101,'' the helicopter reporter says.
</P>
<P>
   And later: ``He didn't get off on the 405. He's going to run out
of exits here.''
</P>
<P>
   They gave ``oh boy'' comments when the car blew through red
lights and bumped cars. When the driver did two laps around Los
Angeles International Airport, zooming by pedestrians and shuttle
buses outside the terminal, the anchors felt obliged to add: ``This
person obviously needs to go to jail,'' and ``This guy's an
idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   They contrasted this chase with other freeway chases they've
covered too, giving the first-time convention visitor a little
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``John, we've covered a number of these pursuits,'' Rod says.
``This would would be the first one where we have someone in the
trunk.''
</P>
<P>
   But, alas, it turned out that no one was in the trunk. And the
chase came to a happy conclusion when the driver lost control in a
turn, spun the car, hit the curb, and was caught making a run for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to our scheduled programming.
</P>
<P>
   I was talking about the chase Tuesday with three convention
delegates from Florida, Phyllis Lapidus of Boca Raton, Marna
Davidson of Boynton Beach, and Maurice Sussman of West Palm Beach.
We were at an event called the Senior Power Fiesta held to get
seniors excited about, among other things, the Democrats' plan make
Medicare include prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Graham echoed the need for the prescription drug plan
during his convention speech later in the day, calling it ``a test
of our values.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are smart to thump on senior issues. But the most
intriguing talk about drugs Tuesday happened a few blocks away from
the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   This was about non-prescription drugs, and how the routine
imprisonment of drug offenders has swelled the prison population in
America, creating a jail-industrial complex full of recidivist drug
addicts who continue to commit crime because treatment isn't as
available as punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted felons, unlike seniors, don't vote. So you won't hear
about it, unless you attended the Shadow Convention _ a sort of
unconventional convention that is being held here, as it was in
Philadelphia during the Republican Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's topic was that the so-called war on drugs has been a
disaster in both human and economic costs, and that sensible
leaders should have chosen a different course long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood stars Susan Sarandon and Tim Robbins recited a litany
of cases of people serving life sentences for non-violent drug
convictions, often involving small amounts of drugs. Using the
South Central neighborhood of Los Angeles as an example, Robbins
said: ``Drugs are easier to get than education. There are no Betty
Ford treatment centers. Are we fighting a drug war ... or is this
just America's version of ethnic cleansing?''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Maher, the host of the television show ``Politically
Incorrect,'' called the Partnership for a Drug Free America an
absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is swimming in drugs,'' Maher said.
</P>
<P>
   The question isn't eliminating all drugs, he said, but making
some acceptable while outlawing others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prozac doesn't want to go up against marijuana,'' Maher said.
``It would lose.''
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I'm going to scan the channels for more televised
freeway chases.
</P>
<P>
   That's something I could get addicted to.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino's e-mail address is
frank(underscore)cerabino(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
