A2775 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-LIVINGBANKRUPTCY0816-     08-15 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGBANKRUPTCY0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once-promising startup living.com files for bankruptcy
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - Living.com Inc., one of the richest and most
promising startups to emerge from Austin's high-tech community in
the past few years, closed its doors and filed for bankruptcy
Tuesday, the first major failure among the scores of fast-growing
Internet companies hatched here.
</P>
<P>
   In just two years, living.com had raised $68 million in venture
capital, launched a national ad campaign, attracted millions of
visitors to its online furniture store and allied itself with
e-commerce leader Amazon.com. But it was not enough to gird the
company against increasingly wary investors and a growing concern
that consumers are not embracing online shopping in all forms.
</P>
<P>
   At an emotional mid-afternoon meeting at the company's downtown
headquarters, founder Andrew Busey, Chief Executive Shaun Holliday
and other executives broke the news to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Workers had heard rumors for weeks and been anticipating the
closure since a grim meeting Friday. But the decision to close was
not made until the board of directors gathered late Monday, a
company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, living.com was able to attract $35 million in what
was at the time the biggest round of funding in Austin history from
some of the premier venture capital firms. But now, the stock
market has turned against Internet retailers and private investors
have followed suit, refusing to put more money in companies like
living.com. The fact that the company had burned through most of
its venture capital and was a long way from being profitable made
it an even tougher sell.
</P>
<P>
   Busey and Holliday were not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the company stopped taking orders on its site, laid off
its 275 employees in Austin and North Carolina and began the
processing of selling its assets. Another 63 workers at Shaw
Furniture Galleries in Randleman, N.C., a furniture store bought by
living.com in 1998, also lost their jobs. None of the employees
will receive severance.
</P>
<P>
   In the current job market, many employees will likely find jobs
quickly, although the closing puts an unusually large number of
people out of work.
</P>
<P>
   The company said customers would find more information about the
status of their orders on the site in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Andrew Springate said he did not know what would
happen to the company's assets, which include an inventory of
goods, a database of customers, a lease on about 40,000 square feet
of office space at Congress Avenue and Third Street, as well as a
125,000-square-foot warehouse the company owns in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But its most valuable real estate, a ``tab'' on Amazon that
directed online shoppers to living.com, vanished late Tuesday,
leaving no trace of what both companies hoped would be a lucrative
relationship. In February, Living.com had agreed to pay Amazon $145
million over five years for the privilege of being its ``Home
Living Store,'' and Amazon had taken an 18 percent stake in the
startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this caught (Amazon) by surprise,'' said Heath Terry,
an analyst who follows the online retailer for Credit Suisse First
Boston in San Francisco. ``It wouldn't surprise me too much if the
situation at living was being presented in a better than reality
light in an effort to encourage Amazon to buy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he was not surprised that Amazon declined to rescue
living.com, though. Amazon has had its own problems lately
convincing investors that its way of selling everything from books
to garden supplies on the Internet is sound, and the demise of
living.com may be one more sign that the bloom is off the
e-commerce giant's rose. ``Amazon was always viewed as capable of
giving their blessing and that being a guarantor of success,''
Terry said. ``We realized for along time that was not necessarily
true and this, if nothing else, proves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he also questioned the high price of the Amazon deal.
Originally it would have cost living.com far more than the company
was collecting in revenue, though the two companies renegotiated
the deal recently, Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts disagreed, saying that Amazon's 20 million
shoppers could have kept living.com afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had they been able to stick around longer, that deal would
have paid off,'' said Seema Williams, an analyst at Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``The unfortunate thing that happened
for them is the . . . market kind of bottomed out before they were
ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, living.com has not been the only one to struggle in its
industry. Framingham, Mass.-based Furniture.com, living.com's chief
rival, flirted with bankruptcy this summer before a last-minute
bail-out. Furniture.com has canceled plans for an initial public
offering, laid off 41 percent of its staff and is now facing
complaints from the Better Business Bureau. All of the startups
that have tried to sell furniture online have struggled with how to
handle merchandising, shipping and returns of products that often
weigh hundreds of pounds and cost thousands of dollars. Both
living.com and its subsidiary, Shaw Furniture Galleries, had
recently been the target of complaints about their customer service
filed with the Better Business Bureau in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the correction, it looked like anything that had a
dot-com on it was going to go stratospheric,'' said John Doggett,
an adjunct professor of management at the University of Texas.
``Now the fundamentals of business are dominating, and people are
asking these questions about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And living.com was not the only local dot-com hanging by a
thread in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The stock prices of publicly traded companies such as
drkoop.com, garden.com and pcOrder.com are near record lows and
privately held companies are fighting to stay afloat. On Monday,
Mall.com laid off half its workforce in an attempt to salvage its
fledgling online retailing
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
