<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS REPORTED IN VERIZON TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Updates with new graf between 1st and original 2nd graf; revises
original 3rd graf)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unions representing more than 86,000 customer service workers
and technicians at Verizon Communications continued to wrangle with
the company over several issues Tuesday, extending a telephone
strike now in its 11th day.
</P>
<P>
   Progress appeared to be made late Tuesday, however, at a meeting
between the company and union negotiators for the region that
includes New York and New England. According to a person close to
the talks, Verizon addressed some concerns over job security in a
development that could lead to the end of the strike in the next
several days.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon and the Communications Workers of America and the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers are debating issues
that include job stress, mandatory overtime and the transfer of
work in response to the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE, which
formed Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   The unions and the company met for formal talks in Washington on
Tuesday morning, said people close to the negotiations, and sidebar
discussions continued into the night.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are largely in agreement over wages, benefits and
a concession from Verizon allowing the unions to organize more
easily in the company's wireless division. But the differences over
work-place stress and the possible loss of job security because of
the merger have emerged as sticking points during the last few
days.
</P>
<P>
   As the strike drags on, Verizon has attempted to deal with a
growing number of requests for telephone service, for repair of
existing service and vandalism. The company said it has had to
focus on repair requests instead of installations of new service
and has asked customers having problems receiving help from
directory assistance to look up numbers on its Web site
(www.bigyellow.com).
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, though, Verizon had to shut down a separate site to
which the company had been directing customers need to report
service problems, after an online magazine, SecurityFocus.com
alerted the company of a security breach that made it possible to
use the site to get access to customers' unlisted telephone
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with other problems, Verizon has deployed about 30,000
non-union employees including managers and other staff such as
secretaries and attorneys to fill in for the 86,000 striking
workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the first few days of the strike, the company had reported a
rash of vandalism, including severed lines. Those reports had
dwindled, but late Monday telephone service for 1,600 residential
and business customers in Massachusetts was knocked out after
vandals cuts three major cables at a pole in Tewksbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which managed to restore service by about noon
Tuesday, offered a $25,000 reward for information leading to the
arrest and conviction of people involved in the cable cutting.
``Whoever did this knew what they were doing,'' said Jack Hoey, a
Verizon spokesman in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it was receiving about 80,000 requests for
repair each day, and dealing with as many of them as the fill-in
managers could handle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
