<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COREL-FOUNDER-RESIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF CANADIAN SOFTWARE DEVELOPER COREL RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Michael Cowpland, the founder of the Corel Corp.,
abruptly resigned Tuesday from all his executive positions at the
ailing Canadian software developer, and put its future in the hands
of a new chief executive and a revamped board.
</P>
<P>
   Cowpland resigned as CEO, president and chairman, but he said he
would remain a director.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Burney, formerly Corel's executive vice president for
engineering and chief of technology, has been appointed interim
chief executive and president.
</P>
<P>
   James Baillie, a well-known Toronto lawyer, has taken over as
chairman of Corel and will head a committee to review the
composition of the board and Corel's survival plan.
</P>
<P>
   The British-born Cowpland, 57, started Ottawa-based Corel 15
years ago after he and a partner, Terence Matthews, sold their
interest in a telecommunications equipment maker, the Mitel Corp.
Corel developed graphic design software like Coreldraw, and
acquired other office software products, like Wordperfect. Its
stock traded as high as $44.50 on the Nasdaq in 1999. But investor
confidence collapsed as the company continued to lose money and
failed to meet promised profit forecasts. On Tuesday, its shares
closed at $3.66, up 6.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   With sales of its older graphics design products in decline,
Corel tied its future to the Linux operating system, but the
collapse of a merger earlier this year with the Inprise Corp. left
it short of cash, and Linux has yet to build a substantial
commercial base among PC users. In June, 350 jobs were cut _ 21
percent of the staff _ as part of a plan to trim costs by $40
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, ended June 30, the company reported
lower-than expected sales of $38 million and a higher-than expected
loss of $24 million. Cowpland, who owns about 10 percent of Corel
and recently said he expects the company to be profitable by the
fourth quarter, said he would pursue start-up opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides failing to steer Corel back to profitability, Cowpland
is facing three charges of insider trading brought by the Ontario
Securities Commission last fall for selling $14 million worth of
shares in 1997 shortly before unexpectedly poor earnings were
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
