u p BC-NY-LIBERMAN-THREAT-NY     08-15 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIBERMAN-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADIO-SHOW CALLER ARRESTED IN LIEBERMAN DEATH THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A caller to Howard Stern's radio show was arrested
Tuesday at his home on Long Island and charged with saying on the
air that he wanted to kill Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic
candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The caller, Lawrence C. Franco, 23, phoned the talk show around
6:25 a.m. on Monday and, according to a complaint issued by federal
prosecutors in Brooklyn, made several anti-religious remarks before
saying: ``So that Lieberman guy has gotta go. He is gonna take my
bullet. He's going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the first Jewish candidate to run on the
presidential ticket for either of the two major political parties.
Even so, Franco, who identified himself on the show as
``Nazarene,'' repeatedly made remarks like: ``I hate churchgoers. I
hate them all,'' according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   When Stern asked Franco whether he was actually threatening
Lieberman, Franco said, ``I'm telling you right now, you got the
killer on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Secret Service, which has been protecting Lieberman
since he was chosen last week to be Vice President Al Gore's
running mate, checked the records of calls to the station and
traced the number to a house in Farmingdale, where Franco lives
with his father, who is also named Lawrence. Although Franco
boasted on the air that he would have ``guns out the window'' if
federal agents came to get him, members of the Secret Service who
searched his bedroom found only a pellet gun.
</P>
<P>
   Franco earns his living assembling newspapers for Newsday, said
his lawyer, Abraham Klott. Appearing before Magistrate Joan M.
Azrack of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, Klott said there was no
evidence that his client was truly a danger to Lieberman or anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was `The Howard Stern Show,''' Klott added. ``This is an
example of what happens with talk radio going out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Azrack released Franco on $200,000 bail and placed him under
house arrest. Outside the courtroom, a man who introduced himself
as the defendant's uncle said: ``It was the wrong thing to do. It
was a joke gone wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Gerstein, a spokesman for Lieberman, who is in Los Angeles
at the Democratic National Convention, declined to comment on the
incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
