<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MAHOMES IS `MR. ANY ROLE' ON METS STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You're starting tomorrow,'' someone said to Pat
Mahomes Monday in the New York Mets' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' replied the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valentine said so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did? I gotta go in and ask him about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bobby Valentine, the Mets' manager, had also said
something else about Mahomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of our hidden secrets,'' Valentine offered.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes is such a secret, apparently, that there are times when
even he doesn't know about it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, there had been rumors but, in the best tradition of
cloak-and-dagger, the mystery took time unraveling. In the end,
Mahomes started.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Mahomes' fourth start this season in this, his
second year with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be a good team without someone like Pat Mahomes
doing his job and doing it well,'' Valentine had said. ``His
contributions are at times overlooked. He doesn't have a defined
role. We only turn to him when we're in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was one of those times. Mahomes has generally come
out of the bullpen in long relief, in short relief and everything
in-between. If the nachos or knishes vendor called in sick, it
wouldn't be a surprise for heads to turn to Mahomes for help. So
the Mets had been riding a hot streak. Now a doubleheader with the
Colorado Rockies came up because of a previous rainout and someone
was needed to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. Jones, a veteran starter, was to pitch one of the two
games, the second. Who's to pitch the other? Well, the vendors were
all present and accounted for, which freed up Mahomes.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Valentine turned to Mahomes only when necessary,
but, added the manager, ``He's done exactly what we needed.'' In
Mahomes' three previous starts this season _ his last was May 13 _
his record was 0-0, but his earned run average was a superb 2.76.
His record as a reliever is 4-1, good but not quite as good as last
season when it was perfect, 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   When starting help was needed this season, the Mets called up
Class AAA pitchers. They were treated harshly by opposing hitters.
Now, Valentine looked not again to Norfolk but to the corner of his
clubhouse where Mahomes, the 6-foot-4-inch right-hander from Tyler,
Texas, sat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, most guys like a definite role,'' said Mahomes, ``and
for most of my career I was a starter, but I'm thrilled to be with
the Mets, with a contender, and in the big leagues, period. And I
like Bobby. When I look him in the eye, I know what he's saying. I
feel his trust in crucial situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes, who turned 30 last week, has been around, usually on
the big-league fringes. He came up with the Twins in 1992 and was
sent down to the minors, came up, and was down and up and down
again. He was traded to the Red Sox and the story was similar. In
1997 and 1998 he pitched in Japan. The Mets gave him another shot.
Called up from Norfolk in early 1999, he was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday the hidden secret was only partly revealed. Mahomes
pitched six and two-thirds innings, gave up five hits and left the
game with the Mets behind, 4-2. If it had not been for a pair of
run-involving doubles by Todd Helton, who was suffering with a .394
batting average entering the game, Mahomes would have fared even
better. But Mahomes did keep the Mets in the ball game, which is as
much as Valentine could have wished. And in the seventh, they came
back with four runs to take a 6-4 lead, en route to a 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes also distinguished himself with the bat and the glove.
He laid down a lovely sacrifice bunt that led to the Mets' first
run. And he caught a hard bouncer with his bare hand to force a
runner at second. If a team is going to win, it also needs such
professional executions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mahomes had spoken of visions of postseason play. He
said he remembered vividly the disappointment of the Mets losing in
the playoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the World Series from home, and thinking: `We're not
scared of the Yankees. We can beat 'em,''' he said. ``Nothing this
season has made me change my opinion. We can get there. We've
improved ourselves in a few positions, like starting pitcher. Guys
like Robin Ventura and Darryl Hamilton are healthy again, and our
bullpen is rested. Going down to the wire is going to be
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dennis Cook relieved Mahomes in the seventh, the fans gave
him a handsome round of applause. For them, it was as sweet as
having found a shiny prize in their Cracker Jack box.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
