<SLUG> BC-TOWEL-FITNESS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMBERS MUST BRING OWN TOWELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DERECK ANDRADE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ L.A. Fitness is throwing in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to soak up the annual $800,000 loss of its towels,
L.A. Fitness has told its members they'll have to show their own
towel to get in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members were taking the towels home,'' said David
Rodriguez, general manager at L.A. Fitness in Pasadena. ``They pay
dues, but they aren't entitled to take the towels home.''
</P>
<P>
   One member even sued the company because an L.A. Fitness towel
she used to dry her car scratched the paint.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule affects all 75 L.A. Fitness locations, including
those in Sherman Oaks, Van Nuys and Woodland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez admitted there are members upset with the club's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   But some L.A. Fitness facilities had been ordering hundreds of
replacement towels each month, at 85 &UR;  &LR; cents each.
</P>
<P>
   The losses, either due to theft or members inadvertently taking
them home, have frustrated gym owners everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ablondi, director of publishing at the International Health,
Racquet &AMP; Sportsclub Association in Boston, said it's a massive
expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. Fitness is a large chain, and it wouldn't surprise me in
terms of their loss,'' Ablondi said.
</P>
<P>
   Some health clubs have even taken the extraordinary steps of
asking towel manufacturers to sew magnetic devices into towels that
can trigger sensors at club exits to reduce shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
   But Ablondi said most upscale health clubs continue to provide
towels for for their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even want to hint to their members they may be
stealing,'' Ablondi said. ``They just eat the costs rather than
raising an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
