<SLUG> BC-BET-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL LAWSUIT BY BET'S FORMER CFO ALLEGES CORPORATE MISSPENDING AND
TAX EVASION 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former chief financial officer for Black Entertainment
Television plans to file a lawsuit in Washington Wednesday that
includes allegations that the parent company's chairman, Robert
Johnson, and its president, Debra Lee, made extensive efforts to
evade the payment of some taxes.
</P>
<P>
   BET is a subsidiary of BET Holdings II based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations appear in a wrongful-termination suit by the
former employee, Dwight Crawford, who is seeking $21 million in
damages for financial loss and emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, made available Tuesday by the Washington law firm
of Bernabei &AMP; Katz, describes a variety of misappropriation of
corporate funds for personal use, and strategies to reduce
corporate taxes by some top-level executives.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's suit contends that corporate officers used corporate
funds and credit cards for personal purchases, and then deducted
the purchases as business expenses. In one case, the suit states,
Johnson used company funds for expenses related to his daughter's
horse show.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also contends that BET made an agreement with the
American Federation of Television and Radio Artists, a labor union,
for production and broadcast of movies and television programs that
required hiring union staff. But rather than BET hiring union
members, the company arranged with a friend of Johnson's to create
a dummy company that would hire staff and supply them to BET as
independent contractors. That strategy, the complaint states, would
let BET ``evade liability for withholding of taxes from wages of
these employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Johnson nor Lee could be reached Tuesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Marchant, general counsel for BET, a network with four
cable channels, said, ``The company has not yet been served with a
complaint, so we don't have official notice of the suit, and I
cannot comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that in knowingly deducting personal expenses
as business expenses, BET violated federal and state law. The
executives, the suit adds, also avoided paying income taxes on the
value of the goods they had acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also contends that a 1999 audit by
PricewaterhouseCoopers found that BET was planning to take an
illegal $6 million tax deduction for 1998 when it had distributed
that amount in profits to Johnson, who owns 65 percent of BET, and
Liberty Media, which owns the balance. BET falsely reported the
payment as an expenditure for salary and consulting, rather than as
a dividend, according to the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said he could not enforce financial compliance
standards without the support of top management. And as disputes
between him and other company managers mounted, Crawford said, Lee
made it clear that his services were no longer wanted. However,
Crawford said he did not resign, despite Lee's requests, and was
dismissed in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
