<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-HISPANI     08-15 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-HISPANICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: BUSH AND GORE BOTH SEEK VOTES WITH SALSA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDRES MARTINEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Still exulting in President Clinton's performance,
delegates and party faithful celebrated on Monday night at the
Latino Committee 2000's block party in downtown Los Angeles,
featuring the queen of salsa, Celia Cruz. The bash felt like a
neighborly small-town festival, to the extent that an event brought
to you by AT&AMP;T, SBC Communications and Verizon _ to mention only
the phone companies chipping in _ can manage to feel neighborly.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is wooing the Hispanic vote for the same
reason Gov. George W. Bush has gone bilingual on the campaign
trail. Indeed, if America were a corporation, Wall Street would be
crying for a spinoff of its Hispanic subsidiary, its hottest growth
prospect. Over the next 30 years, Hispanics, now 12 percent of the
population of the United States, will account for 47 percent of its
growth, according to Census projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Latino vote will be increasingly crucial,'' said Gloria
Molina, chairwoman of the Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors,
``and both parties will have to pay attention to Latino issues.''
But then Molina added a caveat that bedevils all political
strategists seeking to capitalize on the demographic boomlet: ``Our
issues are essentially all-American issues like education, housing
and health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Rodriguez, a Los Angeles-based fellow with the New
America Foundation, calls the Latino community in the United States
``the least ethnocentric group of voters.'' Polls consistently
show, for instance, that immigration does not rank high among
Hispanics' leading concerns. He also believes that the Latino
community, which at 32 million is now larger than the population of
Canada, is too heterogeneous to be counted on as a monolithic
voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   It encompasses Mexican immigrants in Los Angeles, Puerto Ricans
in New York, and Cubans in Miami. Among the latter, Bush leads Vice
President Al Gore by more than 50 points in recent polls. Among all
Hispanics, Bush's convention in Philadelphia, a veritable diversity
feast, cut the vice president's lead from 34 to 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   But while it is not easy to generalize about what Latinos as a
whole stand for today, polls do point to some general trends.
Hispanics are more likely than the population as a whole to believe
in an activist, compassionate government, and while their standard
of living lags behind that of other demographic groups, they
consistently have the most optimistic views about the future.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics also tend to be more socially conservative, which is
one more reason that Democratic Party officials were incensed at
Rep. Loretta Sanchez's decision to play host at a fund-raiser at
the Playboy mansion this week. Public Policy Institute of
California surveys show that only 42 percent of the state's
Hispanics favor an unrestricted right to abortion, compared with 67
percent of non-Hispanic whites. Separate surveys show that
Hispanics favor school vouchers by a wide margin, and they were the
staunchest supporters of California's Proposition 22, a pre-emptive
strike against any move to recognize gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   This makes the former Republican governor Pete Wilson's strident
anti-immigrant rhetoric all the more baffling. Wilson won 44
percent of the Hispanic vote in 1990 before he and his party
embarked on their suicidal mission of alienating Hispanics. In
1998, their share had dropped to 17 percent. ``We really miss
Wilson,'' said Mary Rose Ortega, a hometown delegate and California
director of the National Education Association, reveling at
Monday's block party. ``I know many people who had previously not
been involved in politics who became citizens simply to vote
against the Republicans after Proposition 187,'' she said,
referring to the California voter initiative that deprived illegal
immigrants of public services. Like many Hispanics here, Ortega was
most offended by the tone of the debate at the time, not the
measure's specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Democrats, however, they will face not Pete
Wilson but George W. Bush in November. Bush could not have adopted
a more different tone than Wilson towards his state's immigrant
population. When he ran for re-election in 1998, his share of the
Hispanic vote was more than twice as large as his party's share in
California that year.
</P>
<P>
   This raises the question troubling Democratic Hispanic
officeholders in Los Angeles: Will Bush be able to replicate this
success nationwide? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' said Mayor Carlos Ramirez of El Paso, in a
telephone interview. Elected as a Democrat, Ramirez opted to miss
out on all the fun in Los Angeles and instead go to Philadelphia to
nominate Bush, whom he calls an ``inclusive, moral leader.'' He
says the governor's education policies have proven especially
beneficial to Hispanics. He also believes Democrats have fallen
short on traditional family values that Hispanics hold dear, by
going too far on issues like gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Molina, the Los Angeles County supervisor, concedes that if
Gore's campaign does not make a passionate pitch to the Latino
voter, Bush could make serious inroads, and win as much as 35
percent of the Latino vote in California. ``I think,'' she said,
``there is a real danger that the Democratic Party will take our
vote for granted.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
