<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r p BC-JAYWALK-QANDA-LADN     08-15 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAYWALK-QANDA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY REMAINS A RIDDLE FOR DNC DELEGATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A delegate from Connecticut thinks The Big One is
a wave. Another out-of-stater guessed that Staples Center is home
to the Yankees. And the only thing some Democratic National
Convention delegates seem to know about the San Fernando Valley is
-- omigod! -- the Valley girls live there.
</P>
<P>
   In the style of L.A.'s own Jay Leno, the Daily News cruised the
convention hall Tuesday quizzing delegates from across the nation
about their host city. There were no lifelines. No one won a
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And let's just say the delegates were, well, good sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a John Riordan, but not a Dick Riordan,'' said delegate
Mike Teefy of Vancouver, Wash., when shown the Los Angeles mayor's
name and asked to identify him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the Capital City of the 21st Century -- the DNC
host committee's adopted nickname for Los Angeles -- Brown Miller
of Hattiesburg, Miss., guessed: ``I'm not sure on this one; I'll
say Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   New York delegate Barbara Jackson didn't hesitate. ``It's New
York, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of delegates, from Alaska to Florida, knew that The
Big One is the much-dreaded, long-predicted massive earthquake in
Southern California. Others didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Shaq,'' said Nick Blondin, who was trying to help his
mother, Connecticut delegate Audrey Blondin. But his mom had her
own idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big wave,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were equally puzzled when asked to name two of the
four professional sports teams that play in Staples Center, the
sparkling new arena they were standing inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers? The Yankees?'' asked Emma Edwards of South
Burlington, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Mississippi delegate, got it half right. ``The
Lakers, and I think you have a professional women's basketball
team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Lakers share Staples with the Clippers,
arena football's Avengers and hockey's Kings. The professional
women's basketball team -- the Sparks -- plays at the Forum in
Inglewood.
</P>
<P>
   Other Los Angeles trivia questions baffled the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the Yankees fan, pondered what a SigAlert might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that a Hollywood star that's making some kind of fashion
faux pas?'' she wondered.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Carter of Anchorage, Alaska, figured it was ``somebody
smoking a cigarette when they aren't supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Correct answer: A freeway tie-up in which one or more lanes will
be blocked for at least 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Teefy tried to remember exactly where the San Fernando Valley
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that where all the Valley girls are from?'' Teefy asked.
``I just assumed it's a Valley outside of L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the Valley is still a part of the L.A. family, but is
talking separation.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News also asked delegates a nontrivia question: What
was their perception of Los Angeles before the convention?
</P>
<P>
   ``Floods, earthquakes and riots,'' said Travis Souza, of Reno,
Nev.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers,'' Teefy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Damn, I have to go to this horrible place,' ''
Edwards said. ``But at least I have relatives there so I can kill
two birds with one stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Blondin, of Connecticut, said she had a strong opinion of the
city before she arrived for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people here.''
</P>
<P>
   And after?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people here.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
