<HEADER>
A2795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DEPORT-NYT &LR;      08-15 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS MAN DEPORTED FOR SERVING AS NAZI GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBRA WEST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An 85-year-old Rockland County man faces deportation
for having served as an armed guard in a concentration camp where
42,000 Jews and other prisoners were tortured and killed.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. immigration judge in Manhattan ruled on Monday that
Michael Gruber, a retired auto mechanic who lives in New City,
concealed his Nazi past on his immigration application more than 40
years ago and should be deported to Austria, where he holds
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Gruber's lawyer, Robert A. Murtha, said he planned to appeal.
``I was very unhappy with the decision,'' Murtha said. ``For one,
the client was too sick to cooperate in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   During the yearlong legal proceedings, Gruber admitted that he
served as a Waffen SS guard during World War II, but denied that he
had served inside the Sachsenshausen concentration camp or that he
had participated in the murder and torture there.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert D. Weisel, however, wrote that Nazi records
gathered by the government proved beyond a doubt that Gruber had
served at the camp from January 1943 to September 1944. Service in
a concentration camp is a legal basis for deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was part of the machinery of brutalization and annihilation
at the Sachsenshausen concentration camp,'' said Eli M. Rosenbaum,
director of the Office of Special Investigations, the Justice
Department unit that tracks down and prosecutes Nazi war criminals.
``The job of all of the guards there was to enforce this regime of
ghastly persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruber, who is being treated for kidney cancer, was an auto
mechanic at Volkswagen in Queens until he retired in 1979. He lived
a quiet life in Rockland County with his wife of 65 years in New
City until news of his Nazi past spread, Murtha said.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Special Investigation first contacted Gruber six
years ago, Murtha said. Gruber, who was born in Croatia, admitted
from the beginning that he had served in the elite armed guard
unit. He said that he had been drafted into the SS in 1942. Gruber
also admitted that he had served in the region around
Sachsenshausen, but said that he had guarded prisoners at the train
station, not the concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha argued in court that no direct evidence proved that
Gruber had participated in any persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I argued that without evidence of direct participation in any
acts of persecution, that he was not deportable,'' Murtha said.
``The judge disagreed. That will be the basis of the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   In harsh language, the judge wrote that concentration camp
guards ``shall be consigned until the end of human history as the
ultimate in the personification of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Special Investigations seeks out Nazi criminals
who have hid their wartime activities and prosecutes them for
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood has this conception that survivors recognize someone
on the street and that starts the investigation'' Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rosenbaum said, his department gathers information on
70,000 Nazis and Nazi collaborators from archives throughout Europe
and then compares the records with U.S. immigration records. The
office, which was formed in 1979, has had 53 people deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is like virtually all of the others, `` Rosenbaum
said. ``It's like looking for a needle in a haystack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000815.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKL-SPARKS-PREVIEW-LA     08-15 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS, COMETS GEAR FOR SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It may be called the Western Conference
Finals, but it is widely believed the matchup between the Sparks
and the three-time defending champion Houston Comets is the
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks and Comets finished the regular season with the best
records in the 32-game season, losing a combined nine games _ fewer
than any (ital)single(endital) team. The two teams were 21-1 _ New
York beat Houston _ against Eastern Conference teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it at the beginning of the year and I still believe it
now, Houston is the team to beat,'' said Sacramento Monarchs coach
Sonny Allen after his team was eliminated by the Comets 75-70 on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets have run this league from the beginning, and the only
team that appears ready to unseat them is the Sparks, who are 3-0
against Houston this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is like a preview of the finals,'' Houston guard
Janeth Arcain said. ``I think whoever loses or wins Thursday will
be the champs of the WNBA. Because both teams, Houston and L.A.,
have played so good all season, I think both teams could be the
champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knew that the road to the championship would go through
Houston. The dynamics of the team has changed somewhat with Sheryl
Swoopes raising her game to take the attention away from Cynthia
Cooper. But that's nothing new. This team has dealt with negative
energy in the locker between the two since the league's inception
and it hasn't interfered with the Comets winning three consecutive
WNBA titles. Cooper added to the animosity when she announced her
retirement at midseason and failed to tell the coaches or her
teammates beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks, who swept Phoenix in the first round, have the edge
with a bench that Houston lacks. Not that the Comets have needed
one, at least until now.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sparks have the home-court advantage in this
best-of-three series, Game 1 on Thursday is in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely the biggest game of both of our seasons thus
far,'' Sparks center Lisa Leslie said. ``It's very important who
wins the first game, I think. Obviously we're looking to steal one,
and they're looking to get a win at home since they're going to be
back here on the road for two games. I think it's going to be a
great game, very intense. We're looking forward to it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
