<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHIC-PHONE-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING WOMAN ACCUSED OF CALLING PSYCHIC LINES ON EMPLOYER'S
PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, N.Y. _ A cleaning woman who was upset about breaking up
with her boyfriend made $6,131 worth of phone calls to psychic hot
lines from an employer's home here, police said. She got plenty of
relationship advice, they said, but no warning that she would soon
be behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the joke around here this week,'' said Detective
Gerald Locascio of the Kent Police Department. ``We asked her if
the psychics told her we'd catch her, and she said no, but that she
had a feeling we would.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Patricia Ann Garofalo, 39, was charged Tuesday with
two counts of fourth-degree grand larceny in the Town of Kent
Justice Court. Police said she used her employer's telephone and
credit card numbers to make the calls over the last several months.
She is being held in the Putnam County jail in Carmel with bail set
at $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The employer, Margaret Hutcoe, 52, hired Garofalo last fall to
clean her small two-story house in Carmel, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, MCI Worldcom cut off Hutcoe's long-distance service,
saying she owed about $1,000, mostly from calls made to psychic hot
lines. ``I told them I live by myself and I've never called a
psychic hot line, nor would I,'' she said Tuesday. ``It's just
ridiculous. I have three big dogs, and I know they're not calling
psychic hot lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she found that more than $4,700 worth of calls had been
made over a two-month period on a second phone line that she had
had installed in May for her computer but had not yet used.
Apparently, Garofalo had plugged a phone into that line and had
been intercepting the bill for it, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, Hutcoe said, her stepmother called saying similar
calls had been charged to her credit card number, which Hutcoe had
recently used and left scribbled on a notepad in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcoe called detectives, who obtained phone and credit card
records that showed calls being made from her home during
Garofalo's regular cleaning visits, when Hutcoe was at work.
Garofalo was arrested on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Locascio said that Garofalo called many hot lines, including
Eclipse Psychic, which offers insights from a clairvoyant for $4.59
per minute, and the Voice of Astrology, which offers personal
astrology consultations by phone, costing $95 for 30 minutes, and
weekly chart readings for $249 per month.
</P>
<P>
   He said Garofalo told him she started calling the hot lines
after her boyfriend broke up with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to feel bad for her,'' he said. ``She was in rough
shape and looking for some guidance. She had just gone through a
breakup and was living with clients and friends, in her car and in
a tent at the campgrounds. She needed a lot of advice.''
</P>
<P>
   The detective said he was still investigating whether Garofalo
used other employers' telephones for the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Prince, a spokeswoman for MCI Worldcom, said decisions
about how customers settle fraudulent bills are determined only
after investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcoe said she hired Garofalo last fall after calling a phone
book listing for her business, Dust Bunnies. She had had difficulty
finding a cleaning woman, Hutcoe added. The few she had already
interviewed declined after seeing her dogs, two boxers and a pit
bull.
</P>
<P>
   But Garofalo agreed, and charged $40 per cleaning visit every
two weeks. Hutcoe said she never checked Garofalo's references
before giving her a house key. They talked regularly, and when
Garofalo was moving recently, Hutcoe agreed to let her stay in a
guest room for three days, she said, ``but then it became five, six
days, and I told her `That's it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hutcoe said she learned an important lesson: ``There's
definitely something to be said for cleaning one's own house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
