u p BC-CVN-GAYS-ABORTIONS-HN     08-15 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GAYS-ABORTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION HIGHLIGHTS GOP DIFFERENCES ON GAY AND
ABORTION RIGHTS &HT;    By JUDY HOLLAND
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Rep. Jim Kolbe, the only openly gay
Republican House member, spoke at his party's national convention
in Philadelphia this month, he caused a stir among a dozen or so
delegates. They showed their disapproval of his sexual orientation
by removing their hats, bowing their heads and praying for his
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Democrats are parading six avowed homosexuals
before the cameras at their national convention here this week to
show that they welcome homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In an election year when the distinctions between Republicans
and Democrats on such issues as education, race relations and
health care are fuzzy, the two parties have starkly contrasting
positions on gay and abortion rights. On Tuesday, the Democrats
sought to highlight those differences.
</P>
<P>
   They gave a prime-time speaking slot to Elizabeth Birch, a
lesbian mother of twins and president of the Human Rights Campaign,
the nation's largest gay and lesbian political group.
</P>
<P>
   Birch delivered an impassioned plea for equality for and broader
acceptance of homosexuals as many delegates waved placards saying
``Gays for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We seek simple equality _ the equal right to work, raise a
family, serve our country in every way and be free from the
shackles of brutality and hate,'' she said, citing the murder of
21-year-old Matthew Shepard, who in October 1998 was pistol-whipped
and hung on a fence to die near Laramie, Wyo. because of his sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we dedicate ourselves to healing the fractures _
soothing the wounds _ to making our American family truly whole,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Birch also addressed parents who have not been able to accept
their homosexual children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that your gay children are gifted and
strong,'' she said. ``All are heroic in the way they have conquered
barriers to their own self respect. Many have suffered cruelty or
violence. Some serve their communities with leadership and grace.
Many are rich in faith, and have a deep love for this nation and
democracy. Tens of thousands have served with distinction in the
armed services. Many have lost their lives. ''
</P>
<P>
   She also praised Vice President Al Gore's ``forward thinking
leadership'' on gay issues and cited his support for legislation
that would ban job discrimination based on sexual orientation and
for ending the ban against gay and lesbian military service members
revealing their sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Birch called the Republican platform ``shameful'' and charged
that GOP candidates George W. Bush and Richard Cheney ``forego
invective but embrace indifference and call it compassion.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Democratic Party positions, the Republican
platform opposes the current ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' policy for gays in the miltary, saying they should not be
able to serve at all, and says federal anti-bias laws should not be
extended to include gays.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tammy Baldwin, D-Wisc., the first successful candidate for
Congress to campaign as an avowed homosexual, also spoke Tuesday,
calling for better health insurance for the grandmother she cares
for. She did not mention her own sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   One of 200 openly gay delegates among 4,368 at the convention
here, Baldwin said afterward that the Democratic officials'
invitation for her to speak shows that the party is inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita Owens, a lesbian and a San Francisco School Board member
and candidate for the city's Board of Supervisors, stood on the
podium and praised the efforts of Gore and the party to make it
illegal to discriminate against gay workers. ``When Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman occupy the White House, they will put an end to unfair,
unproductive and un-American persecution in the workplace,'' Owens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other avowed homosexuals schedueled to speak this week are Rep.
Barney Frank, D-Mass., Andrew Tobias, national treasurer for the
Democratic National Committee and Gloria Nicto, a Democratic
committeewoman at-large from New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   David Elliot, spokesman for the National Gay and Lesbian Task
Force in Washington, called the speaking invitations to gays ``a
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more visible than we've ever been before,'' Elliot
said.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion rights, the Democrats invited Kate Michelman,
president of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, to speak after Birch.
</P>
<P>
   Mkichelman warned that the 1973 Roe v. Wade Supreme Court ruling
that legalized abortion could be overturned if Bush is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman's right to choose took a century to win,'' she said.
``But it could be lost in only one day _ Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``Today, that freedom hangs in the balance of a
closely divided court. If he has the opportunity, George W. Bush
will appoint enough Supreme Court justices to overturn Roe v. Wade
and end legal abortion. At every opportunity, Governor Bush has
made clear his intent to restrict a woman's right to choose. He is
one of the nation's most anti-choice governors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has consistently opposed abortion. But in the past he
favored allowing abortion in cases of rape, incest or where the
health of the mother is at risk. Yet this year he supported
retaining the Republican Party platform language calling for a
constitutional amendment to ban abortion. The Republican platform
makes no mention of the exceptions that Bush had previously
supported.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
