</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she has not discussed the matter with the Gore
campaign, but believes he will visit California frequently during
his campaign. As vice president, Gore visited the Golden State more
than 40 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election will be won or lost depending on how California
goes,'' Feinstein said. ``If we take this election for granted, we
will lose.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was the first to recognize the value of the
state in his 1992 campaign, with Democrats winning it for the first
time since 1964. Since Clinton's election, California Democrats
have been on an upswing, now holding all but one statewide
constitutional office.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein is also up for re-election this year, facing a
challenge from Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Campbell. Polls show her
comfortably ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   She has campaigned on her record on favoring abortion rights --
an issue she said she considers one of the major ones in this
election -- as well as her support for stronger gun control
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, she said it is one of the defining issues between
Gore and Republican nominee George W. Bush and one she fears that
no longer motivates many women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you, I remember how bad it was before abortion was
legal,'' Feinstein said of her days serving on the California
Parole Board. ``I had to sentence abortionists and I remember the
horror of back-alley abortions and the morbidity and mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of women take it for granted on the right to
have an abortion. But it's only one vote away on the Supreme Court.
I don't want to see a return to those old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also talked of her desire to one day see a woman
elected president, saying she was sorry former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole dropped out early in the Republican
presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to see her go the distance,'' Feinstein
said. ``At some point, we have to pierce that barrier. Women can be
a potent force in this country and can decide elections.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Feinstein had been mentioned as a potential Gore
running mate, but she said she had never been directly contacted
and would have had no interest in the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know Al Gore that well and I'm running for
re-election,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would be interested in such a job in the future or
running for president, she replied: ``I'm keeping my options
open.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
