<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-LIEBERMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN PREPARING FOR MOMENT IN SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos CVN3, CVN12 and CVN13 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He calls it ``my new life,'' a life of arriving at
airports after midnight and finding 25 reporters waiting, of being
whisked about in motorcades as if lifted on a magic carpet, of
carrying the full measure of expectation that comes from being the
first Jew to be a presidential running mate of a major party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is as if you've been touched, called,'' Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut said Tuesday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Nine days ago he and his wife, Hadassah, awoke to reports that
he had been chosen as Vice President Al Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Lieberman said, the notion comes as a sort of surreal
surprise, one that seemed beyond reach. And yet Thursday night,
Lieberman will stand before the nation and deliver the most
important speech of his life, one, he said, that he hopes a
lifetime in politics has prepared him for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though the scope is obviously enormously larger, in many ways
my 30 years of public life have prepared me for this moment,'' he
said. ``I don't mean that anyone is ever fully prepared, but I feel
as if all the experiences, all that I've learned are coming
together, are being tested, and frankly I find it exhilarating. ''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, when he walked to the convention podium for a
brief rehearsal, he grinned broadly and spread his arms, as if
eager to embrace this strange new life. ``An only-in-America
moment,'' he said to a group of photographers.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday evening, Lieberman, 58, conveyed a sense
of easy anticipation as he relaxed in an easy chair next to an
untouched tray of tomatoes and black olives.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said that he would use his address to foreshadow the
various roles he intended to fulfill in the campaign. But his first
task, he said, will be to introduce himself to the American public,
``who I am, what my values are.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that while he would not hesitate to ``respectfully''
point out differences with the Republican Party, he would not play
attack dog, the traditional role of the running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Al about this, and we're very intent on talking
about progress, not partisanship,'' he said. ``This is not going to
be a campaign of personal attack.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Gov. George W. Bush and Dick Cheney ``decent and
likable people,'' who nonetheless represent ``a step backward for
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he would seek to turn his campaign into ``a
conversation with the American people,'' one that emphasizes what
is at stake in the years ahead. ``The choices here are very
clear,'' he said. ``And these choices I think will significantly
affect the future of the people of this country. Government doesn't
do it all, but government sets a tone, sets a direction.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would help Gore reach for the political center by
talking about values and his faith, and said he would try to
neutralize years of White House scandal by vouching for Gore's
character. And, perhaps most difficult of all, he said he would try
to redirect his party's enthusiasm for Clinton toward Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, though, is just now discovering how difficult it can
be to stay focused on those roles. In forging a reputation as a
centrist Democrat, he has taken positions and made statements that
are unpopular among the party's more liberal members. Tuesday, for
example, he found himself defending his views on affirmative action
and school vouchers to several hundred members of the Democratic
National Committee's black caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Senate colleagues have been known to grumble about his
occasional flashes of self-righteousness. Tuesday, he blamed
inaccurate news coverage and Republicans for blowing minor policy
differences out of proportion. ``Don't let the press or our
opponents divide us,'' he told a cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the criticisms had been raised _ and raised loudly _
by members of the black caucus. ``I and others raised the
questions,'' Rep. Maxine Waters of California said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
