<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CLINTON-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXTOLS GORE IN SYMBOLIC `PASSING OF THE TORCH' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Adds 3 grafs, After they left ..., with the Clintons stopping
at a McDonald's.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos CVN2 and CVN4 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Mich. _ With a bear hug and a slight nudge, President
Clinton pushed his understudy, Al Gore, to center stage Tuesday,
relinquishing the limelight to the man he hopes will succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a metaphoric ceremony that the vice president has longed
for as Clinton has effortlessly dominated news coverage and
captured public attention _ and overshadowed Gore's efforts to
present himself as a leader in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried to pass that torch Tuesday to Gore here before a
crowd of more than 15,000 people, the largest audience Gore has
seen since he officially announced his campaign more than a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nominee of the Democratic Party, my partner and friend for
the last eight years, understands where we are, where we're going
and how it will affect ordinary citizens more than any other public
figure in this country over the last 20 years,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Vouching for Gore, Clinton, who was operating on three hours of
sleep after delivering his valedictory speech in Los Angeles on
Monday night, added: ``I hope you'll take my word for this, because
I spent most of my adult life studying economics and the
development of our country. The things that have happened in the
last eight years _ the good things _ are nothing compared to the
good things that can happen in the next eight years. Nothing!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who had been standing ramrod straight behind the president
with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and his wife, Tipper, then
embraced the president and shed his jacket as he moved to the
lectern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank you, Mr. President, for giving me a chance to
serve my country for the last eight years, by working to help
strengthen your hand,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   He introduced his wife as ``the woman I love,'' and went on to
tell the stories of several people whose lives had been improved by
programs of the Clinton administration. He said Clinton had built a
strong foundation for the nation and that the question in the
election was whether voters wanted to build on that foundation or
allow it to erode. Gore did not mention the name of his Republican
opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, but he did refer to the
governor's proposal for an across-the-board tax cut of $1.3
trillion over 10 years. Gore himself has proposed tax cuts of about
$500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Bill Clinton worked hard to get this economy
right,'' Gore said. ``And I'm pledging to you here today, I am not
going to let the other side wreck it and take it away from us.
We're going to keep the prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether this ceremony would usher in for Gore a
transfer of attention _ and an enhancement of his standing with the
electorate _ or whether Clinton would continue to steal the show.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Clinton upstaged Gore as soon as the symbolic
``passing of the torch'' was over. (No object was actually passed,
as television producers had been led to believe might happen.) As
Gore began speaking, eyes were diverted by Clinton draping his arms
around Mrs. Clinton and Mrs. Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After they left, the Clintons stopped at a McDonald's, an event
that made a huge splash with local residents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton marked the moment with a crispy chicken sandwich and
fries. Whether he was anticipating one of the advantages of being
an ordinary citizen or downing some comfort food to soothe his
angst over the dimming of the limelight, he seemed cheerful enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to be a citizen again, I'm going to have to start
getting used to it,'' the president said as he shrugged and then
slipped a $20 tip to the teen-age waitresses, telling them to ``go
out and have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign picked small-town America _ and a battleground
state _ for the ceremony, a hot, confetti-strewn affair that drew a
mass of more than 15,000 people, according to local police
estimates. This was by far the largest crowd that Gore has seen in
the last year and a half of his presidential campaign, and several
people said they mainly had come to see the president.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, a town of 22,600 people near Lake Erie, was chosen
because it represents the challenge ahead for Gore. It is in a
swing district that includes both rural and suburban voters, both
high-tech and low-tech workers and an equal number of Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a bellwether area of the state, having voted for
winners in most presidential elections in modern history. A survey
from earlier this month, after Gore picked Sen. Joseph Lieberman as
his running mate, gave Bush 45 percent of likely voters and Gore 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Gore can win here, he can win the state'' and the national
election, said Ed Sarpolus, a pollster in Lansing. ``This is one of
Gore's toughest audiences. His problem is still Bill Clinton the
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The area also underscores the major theme of both the Clinton
administration and the Gore campaign, which is the economic success
of the last eight years. As Clinton noted, unemployment here was
8.8 percent when he took office in 1993; it is now 2.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
