<SLUG> BC-LASKAWAY-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEC IS ASKED TO AMEND A NEW PROPOSAL ON AUDITOR
INDEPENDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of Ernst &AMP; Young, a major accounting firm that has
been supporting the Securities and Exchange Commission effort to
tighten rules on auditor independence, said Tuesday that the SEC's
rule proposal goes too far and would create too much uncertainty
about what activities were permitted.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the American Accounting Association meeting in
Philadelphia, Phil Laskaway of Ernst &AMP; Young said the proposed rule
``would make it impossible'' for audit firms ``to enter into
strategic alliances or joint ventures, including with companies
that are not audit clients.'' Such allegiances are needed, he said,
because they help the firms gain expertise to do their jobs better.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that he still hoped the SEC would amend the
proposal in a way that would be acceptable. He suggested a rule
might ban firms from performing large amounts of internal audit
work for audit clients, but still allow smaller tasks to be
performed. The SEC has said it fears that outside auditors might be
reluctant to question internal auditing work if it was done by
people employed by the same accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Laskaway added that a new rule could provide for disclosure of
the total audit fee and the total fee for other services to the
company, to help investors ascertain whether there was reason to be
concerned about the auditor's independence.
</P>
<P>
   No disclosure is now required on nonaudit services, a fact that
makes it impossible to even begin to compile statistics that would
indicate whether audits that prove to be faulty are more or less
likely to involve companies that used their auditing firms for
other services.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young and PricewaterhouseCoopers, each of which is
getting out of consulting in any case, have been relatively
supportive of the SEC effort, while the other three major firms _
KPMG, Arthur Andersen and Deloitte &AMP; Touche _ have been harshly
critical. The SEC hopes that it can find a rule that the two firms
will support, and Laskaway's speech indicated that effort has not
yet borne fruit. If the SEC is going to pass a rule that has
support from major auditing firms, it will probably have to tone
down the proposal substantially.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview after the speech, Laskaway said, ``I
tried to lay out a blueprint that will get something done.'' He
added, ``I have hopes this will be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Turner, the SEC's chief accountant, said the commission
would consider the suggestions and voiced the hope that other firms
would also make suggestions for a rule that would ``insure that
investors will continue to trust the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the other big firms have indicated they will
fight the rule, whose most significant aspect would be to ban
accounting firms from doing certain types of consulting work for
audit clients, and have so far shown little indication they want to
reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   One effort under way, according to some people who have talked
to Congressional aides, is to persuade Congress to attach a rider
to an appropriations bill in the current session. Such a rider
would bar the SEC from acting on the rule before February, by which
time the opponents hope that a new president will have appointed a
new SEC chairman who will drop the idea. It is not clear if such a
legislative move will be made.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Laskaway said ``heightened scrutiny of auditor
independence'' had led some clients to demand that auditors not
perform other services for the company. He said it would be good
``if the SEC could provide greater certainty'' regarding what was
permitted. That would give firms the ``opportunity to move forward
with our clients'' and ``would also hopefully restore civility
between the profession and the regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the proposed rule, by adopting four
``overriding principles'' regarding independence, would create too
much uncertainty. Such principles should be modified, he said, if
they are kept at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
