<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT     08-15 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT BAFFLED, FLUSHING GREETS A CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With an eye toward reaching constituencies not
traditionally thought of as Republican, Rep. Rick Lazio on Tuesday
took a subway line nicknamed the immigrant express to Flushing,
Queens, a predominantly Asian community that his party is courting.
</P>
<P>
   When he stepped off the No. 7 line, he did not seem fazed that
some people who shook his hand, like Huan Lee, a restaurant
delivery man, did not know who he was; Lee, being a citizen of
China, also cannot vote. But there were plenty of other people
toting signs advertising Lazio's Senate candidacy who promised
support in November.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Serphin Maltese, chairman of the Queens County
Republican Committee, and Mei Lin Tan, a real estate broker and
vice chairwoman of the committee, escorted Lazio as he strolled
Roosevelt Avenue and adjacent streets in the heart of a Chinese
immigrant neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He was also accompanied by supporters who tried to outshout a
group of counterdemonstrators backing his Democratic opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a young man dressed as Uncle Sam repeatedly barked
at Lazio to release his income tax returns, reprising the role he
played at a news conference on Monday. Again, Lazio said he would
release the returns sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio pressed on with a smile as Tan introduced him to
residents, occasionally translating their remarks into English and
doing some cheerleading as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, come on!'' she shouted as she marched into a seafood
restaurant, motioning diners to clap their hands for Lazio, which
some did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be in the community, to take the type of
transportation every New Yorker takes here into the community and
to be walked around and get this level of support,'' Lazio said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The response from people, he added, was ``a terrific sign of
support for who we are and the inclusive campaign that we have and
the fact that our message is spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   Maltese said the party was aggressively courting Asian-Americans
in Flushing, who, he said, were undergoing a political awakening as
they developed stronger bonds to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said many shopkeepers enthusiastically agreed to wave
placards and put campaign signs in their windows.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's appearance was in line with what his campaign staff has
said would be a serious effort to woo minority voters. Lazio has
visited black and Hispanic neighborhoods and plans to begin a bus
tour across the state Wednesday with a stop at the National Black
Theater in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio drew many well-wishers, though some offered no more than
polite handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they don't know him,'' Tan said later of people's
familiarity with Lazio. ``But I tell them he will be the next
senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Mei Jin, who works in a clothing shop on Roosevelt Avenue, said
she had seen Lazio on television but had not formed an opinion of
him or of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know enough about either candidate, but it's good he
came here to meet us,'' Jin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
