<HEADER>
A2957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      08-15 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES MAKE A MESS, LETTING METS CLEAN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets' recent tear was not paved with mistakes,
but it was still filled with potholes. Again Tuesday night, the
Mets patched up their gaffes. Using a fill-in starting pitcher and
playing without their best hitter, they survived a messy game in
the opener of a doubleheader against Colorado at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense was inefficient but productive enough to outlast
the Rockies for a 7-5 victory. The Mets, who rallied from a 3-0
deficit, won for the 17th time in 21 games. They have not lost
consecutive games since July 20 and 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets used a four-run seventh inning to recover from a 4-2
deficit. But the Rockies' relievers were as responsible for that
comeback as were the Mets, who rested Mike Piazza. The go-ahead run
and the Mets' final run both scored on wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this game was as filled with individual highlights as it
was with mistakes. The spot starter Pat Mahomes pitched into the
seventh inning and provided the Mets with the foundation for their
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's come up big for us,'' said manager Bobby Valentine. ``He
gave us exactly what we needed and so did the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo drove in the Mets' first two runs with a double
in the fifth inning and then scored their sixth run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But if anybody needed redemption in this game, it was Todd
Zeile. He struck out in the fourth inning as the Mets failed to get
a run in after loading the bases with no outs, and he was thrown
out trying for a double leading off the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile was given the perfect vantage point for the Rockies' low
point. In the seventh inning, he watched Jose Jimenez's 2-2 pitch
bounce in front of the plate, off the chest protector of catcher
Brent Mayne and down the first-base line. Darryl Hamilton broke
from third base and scored the run that put the Mets ahead to stay
when Mayne's throw from foul territory bounced off Jimenez's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Pratt's leadoff double and Lenny Harris' pinch-hit single
had put runners on the corners with no outs. Rockies starter Pedro
Astacio left for reliever Craig House, whose first four pitches to
Hamilton missed the strike zone, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell struck out on three pitches, but Alfonzo, who hit a
two-out double in the fifth inning, drew a full-count walk to force
in the third run and cut the Mets' deficit to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Myers, a side-arming left-hander, replaced House and walked
Robin Ventura on a 3-2 pitch that sailed outside. Harris trotted
home with the tying run. After Jimenez's wild pitch scored
Hamilton, Zeile walked and Jay Payton's groundout scored Alfonzo.
Jimenez allowed another run in the eighth after making two throwing
errors and throwing a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes, making a start for the first time since May 13, did his
job. He allowed four runs in six and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we didn't have a long man because I was the long man,''
Mahomes said of his usual relief role.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahomes was at the mercy of Astacio, who was teasing the
Mets by putting runners on base and escaping jams.
</P>
<P>
   But after Astacio, the Rockies' underbelly remains their relief
pitching, and the Mets exploited it. Colorado led by 4-2 when he
walked off the mound in the seventh inning but even he must have
sensed that lead evaporating quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets appeared to have a rally brewing in the fourth inning,
when Bell and Alfonzo led off with walks and Ventura singled to
right to load the bases. But Astacio again turned stingy. He fell
behind Todd Zeile by 3-0 before striking him out on three straight
pitches. Payton followed the same course, flailing at Astacio's
fastball for the final strike. And Mike Bordick lined a 1-2 pitch
straight to shortstop Neifi Perez to end the inning to loud boos
from the afternoon crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was more life on the bench after we left those guys on
than before,'' Valentine said. ``Some teams say, `That was our
chance, we muffed it and we'll get 'em tomorrow.' This team says,
`That was our chance, we'll get 'em the next inning.'''
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd was not appeased until Alfonzo delivered a two-out
double in the fifth inning to score Todd Pratt from third base and
Bell from first. But the Mets did not look sharp, and Alfonzo was
no exception. He tried to score from second on Ventura's infield
single but was thrown out by first baseman Todd Helton.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, one of the slowest players on the Mets, led off the sixth
with a hit down the right-field line and into the corner. But he
was easily thrown out by Rockies right fielder Larry Walker as he
tried to stretch the single into a double.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mahomes turned around his career as a reliever for the
Mets last season, he has had far better success as a spot starter
this season. He has a 4.82 earned run average as a reliever, his
primary duty, but entered Tuesday's doubleheader with a 2.76 ERA in
three starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been careful not to turn to Mahomes each time
there is a need in the rotation. Valentine values Mahomes'
durability and his flexibility out of the bullpen. He can pitch in
long or middle relief. The last time the Mets needed a starter for
a doubleheader, they promoted the rookie Grant Roberts from Class
AAA Norfolk and survived his shaky start to sweep two games from
the Expos.
</P>
<P>
   With a deeper bullpen since they traded for reliever Rick White,
the Mets did not need to take that risk again Tuesday and Mahomes
provided them with the innings they desperately needed. His biggest
problem was surviving Juan Pierre's sharp grounder in the seventh
inning that he grabbed barehanded. Mahomes remained in the game for
one more batter, and allowed one more run.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets trailing by 3-2, Mahomes allowed Perez to drive a
2-1 ball off the right-field wall for a run-scoring double. Mahomes
was removed for Dennis Cook, who allowed six runs in a third of an
inning in Monday's 11-1 loss to San Francisco. Cook got Walker to
ground out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets fell behind, 3-0, on two Rockies rallies manufactured
by Helton, who went 2 for 4 and raised his average to .395.
</P>
<P>
   After Jeffrey Hammonds led off the second with a bloop single
and stole second base, Helton grounded a double down the left-field
line for a 1-0 lead. Mahomes escaped further damage.
</P>
<P>
   But Helton's next at-bat led off the fourth inning, and he drove
a double over Hamilton in left field. The ball fell on the warning
track, and Helton soon scored when Todd Walker doubled over Bell's
head in right field. Walker eventually scored on a groundout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
