<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SHOOTING FOR HOME-FIELD ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Galaxy, disappointed with a 1-1 draw with
Kansas City over the weekend, is going to plan B, according to
coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   A week after beating the Wizards 5-1 at Arrowhead Stadium, the
Galaxy could have pulled to within a point of the Wizards on
Saturday at the Rose Bowl. Yet even with the Wizards playing a man
down the entire second half after Matt McKeon was ejected, the
Galaxy couldn't pull out a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The tie left the Galaxy (11-7-8, 41 points) four points behind
the Wizards (13-6-6, 45 points). Kansas City has seven games left
to the Galaxy's six, so winning the Western Division will be no
easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid is concerned with earning the fourth seed, which would
guarantee home-field advantage in the first round of the playoffs.
The Galaxy is tied with Chicago (12-8-5, 41 points) for that
seeding.
</P>
<P>
   After playing host to the Colorado Rapids (11-12-3, 36 points)
tonight at the Rose Bowl, the Galaxy travels to meet Chicago on
Saturday at Soldier Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously disappointed we blew a tremendous opportunity
with K.C.,'' Schmid said. ``When you give them away, they don't
keep coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now our goal is not to win the division. We first have
to win the No.4 spot for the playoffs. If K.C. falters then we have
a chance, but the only thing we can control is the four seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid will have to do without Mauricio Cienfuegos (El
Salvador), Cobi Jones (U.S.) and Ezra Hendrickson (St. Vincent &AMP;
the Grenadines), who are lost because of World Cup qualifying
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Striker Luis Hernandez was also scheduled to miss the game after
participating in Mexico's 2-0 victory over Canada on Tuesday
afternoon, but Schmid said Hernandez is flying back to Los Angeles
this morning and could play in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he would choose between Brian Kelly, Jorge Salcedo,
Zak Ibsen and Ivan Polic to replace the three missing starters.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Kevin Hartman, who has been sidelined the past three
MLS games and two U.S. Open Cup games after minor knee surgery,
will be activated tonight. Matt Reis, who has filled in nicely for
Hartman, will get the start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
