<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BARBER-FAMILY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BARBERS, GOLF IS A FAMILY AFFAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With two holes remaining in the latest chapter of
Tommy Barber's most excellent golf adventure, the June graduate of
Sherman Oaks Notre Dame High felt he needed two pars to guarantee a
berth in the U.S. Amateur Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The first had to come from off the wrong fairway and the next
from out of deep rough under trees.
</P>
<P>
   No problem for the grandson of 1961 Ryder Cup captain Jerry
Barber, whose closing skill carried him to that year's PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Young Barber pulled off his par-par finish, punctuated by a
66-yard wedge shot to within six inches of the flagstick on No18,
and shared the best score at 70-66_136 in last week's U.S. Amateur
qualifier at Hillcrest Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nice ending to a nice day,'' said Barber, who shot 30 on the
first nine of his second 18 and finished 6-under par to earn a
berth in next week's centennial U.S. Amateur at Baltusrol GC in
Springfield, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew 136 was in low, and I knew I needed that for
co-medalist,'' he said. ``And, who knows, maybe I needed it to get
into the Amateur without going to a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished, and with the kind of scrambling success
that this year has overshadowed Barber's remarkable length off the
tee.
</P>
<P>
   At the Southern Section championship, Barber hit his first drive
out of bounds and missed eight greens, but shot a 3-under-par 69 to
finish in the top five, bouncing his final approach of the day off
the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   During another top-five finish in the CIF/SCGA championship _
the closest Southern California high school golfers get to a state
final _ Barber secured an early tap-in par after escaping a bunker,
hitting a tree and hacking out of rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bunker, tree, stoney,'' deadpanned Griffith Park head
professional Tom Barber, in the gallery that day to track his son's
progress, as he always does, from on course or afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has marvelous hands, very similar to what dad had,'' Tom
Barber said of Tommy. ``The kid has wonderful imagination and a
very delicate touch. It's amazing that someone who hits the ball
that far has that kind of feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy appreciates the never-pushing paternal encouragement that
dates back to his early struggles with the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't come easy,'' he said. ``I wasn't very good when I
was younger.''
</P>
<P>
   But he could always discuss his game with a pro who had Tommy's
interest at heart well beyond golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to go home and have my dad there to support me, good
round or bad. Either way, he's there smiling or trying to cheer me
up if I haven't played well. Lately, I've been going home with some
pretty good news.''
</P>
<P>
   No area high school golfer was hotter down the stretch of the
2000 season than Barber, whose run started with the second of two
consecutive Mission League titles in May. He followed that with six
successive sub-par rounds _ in section team qualifying, section
individual qualifying, both rounds of a first-place effort in a
Catalina tournament and in the section and CIF/SCGA individual
finals.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes the U.S. Amateur at historic Baltusrol, which has
hosted seven U.S. Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been awesome,'' Barber said. ``I pretty much did
everything I wanted to do in high school golf in terms of making it
to where I wanted to be, and I played well when I got there. The
U.S. Amateur tops it off. It's unbelievable _ I still wake up
shocked sometimes that I qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the family tree, and maybe it isn't all that
surprising that the latest Barber golf sensation is playing in a
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   His grandfather is a two-time Ryder Cup member, and his father,
who has played on the PGA and Senior PGA tours, is a Southern
California PGA stroke and match-play champion.
</P>
<P>
   Four other members of Tommy's family are PGA professionals,
including great-uncle Willie Barber, who three times won the U.S.
National Senior championship _ the forerunner to the Senior PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's cousins Bill Barber and Bob DeVore are PGA club pros and
brother Jeff is a PGA apprentice, teaching at Griffith Park, where
the Barber family has been running the pro shop since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's mother Diane has won the last two women's championships
at Lakeside Country Club, uncle Roger Barber plays to a 2 handicap,
and younger brother Danny was No.4 on the Notre Dame High team this
year as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Tommy literally grew up at Griffith Park, where he
took his first swing on the practice range at age 11 months, where
he learned to drive the ball nearly 300 yards and where he won last
year's men's club championship at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been a lot of fun around here,'' he said Saturday,
after bouncing a few tee shots off the fence at the end of the
Griffith Park range, tuning up for next week's family trip to
Baltusrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys have befriended me here and played golf with me.
It's a whole family over here _ pretty much everybody, not just my
parents and brother. I've been here all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And helping churn the Griffith Park inventory in the process,
according to his father, who had this response when Tommy told him
_ at the Southern Section final in Palm Springs _ that he'd been
admiring a new putter in that pro shop:
</P>
<P>
   ``Son,'' the elder Barber said, ``I don't know it you know this,
but your father runs a pro shop, and he has 92 used putters there _
and they're all yours.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
