<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN SAYS SIDE IS FINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Kevin Brown said his right side is fine, and manager
Davey Johnson took it a step further by saying he would push the
Dodgers' right-hander up a day for a Friday start against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   That is, provided everything goes fine with a bullpen session
today.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown said there are no lingering effects from the soreness
on the right side of his rib cage that forced him to have a
cortisone shot Friday, and he wasn't experiencing any pain or
discomfort during his start Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' said Brown, who allowed nine runs in 11/3 innings
against the Marlins. ``I'd rather be hurting and getting people out
than pain-free and not getting people out. Unfortunately, you don't
get to choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The side) is not an issue. It would be nice if it were that
easy to blame something on, but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time this season Brown's health has been an
issue. He missed two weeks in April with a broken right pinkie,
then experienced stiffness in the back of his shoulder after a July
6 start in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers trainer Stan Johnston said Brown had irritation around
the rib cage after his start last Wednesday against the Chicago
Cubs, but the cortisone shot eased that pain.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is winless in his last four starts, going 0-2 with a 5.57
ERA. And though four of the runs the Marlins scored off Brown were
unearned because of three errors, he allowed seven hits and threw
46 pitches to record four outs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, several of the Marlins remarked that Brown's sinker, which
is usually devastating, didn't have its usual bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game that started off wrong and it wasn't going to
get corrected,'' Dodgers pitching coach Claude Osteen said. ``He
said he felt fine and I believe it because you don't throw the way
he did in the bullpen with an injury.''
</P>
<P>
   HUNDLEY SCRATCHED: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley, who's played in
only 60 of the Dodgers' 118 games, was scratched from the lineup
because of tightness in his right knee. He had trouble squatting,
which could cause problems for a catcher, and was replaced by Chad
Kreuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know how it happened,'' Johnson said. ``He woke up
and it was stiff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's already been on the disabled list twice this season,
missing most of June with a strained oblique muscle and three weeks
in July with a broken thumb. But Johnson said he was optimistic
Hundley could return Friday. He will get today off because Chan Ho
Park pitches, meaning Kreuter will catch, and the Dodgers are off
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   BELTRE BANTER: Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre continues to
confound, and Johnson said it's because of inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre entered Tuesday second among National League third
baseman with 19 errors, including miscues in three straight games.
However, the 21-year-old also makes extremely difficult plays look
relatively easy, especially charging in, bare-handing slow rollers
and throwing out runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexperience, youth,'' Johnson said. ``Unfortunately, a
gifted athlete doesn't immediately do everything like a Gold
Glover. He's young defensively and offensively.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
