<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-NELSON-0816-COX     08-15 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELSON-0816-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National party has high hopes for Nelson in Senate race
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ten years ago, Bill Nelson was miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders had abandoned him. His quest to become
Florida's governor, first hailed by party leaders, fizzled when
Lawton Chiles, then a retired U.S. senator, decided that Nelson
could not defeat the incumbent Republican. Chiles challenged Nelson
for the party nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles defeated Nelson and Republican Gov. Bob Martinez. It was
a humiliating time for Nelson. The former Orlando congressman and
shuttle astronaut would spend the next four years in political
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a decade later, a much weakened Democratic Party is
counting on Nelson to win a U.S. Senate seat and help salvage a
battered state party desperate for success in the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, the popular Florida insurance commissioner, leads in
current polls against his Republican rival, U.S. Rep. Bill McCollum
of Altamonte Springs. It will be a costly and hotly contested race.
Each side is expected to spend up to $10 million. In addition,
millions more will be spent by the Republican and Democratic
parties, which consider this race to be one of the most important
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats need to win just four seats to reach a 50-50 split in
the Senate. If Vice President Al Gore wins the White House, his
vice president, Joe Lieberman, would cast the tie-breaking vote for
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that this is a very important race for
us,'' said U.S. Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. ``Florida is a state
where we believe Democrats have a very strong candidate in Bill
Nelson and where there is every reason to believe we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Nelson and McCollum have used the national conventions to
advance their campaigns. Both won afternoon speaking moments at the
convention. And both made the rounds of important political
gatherings hoping to keep the interest in their campaigns high.
</P>
<P>
   For Nelson, this could be a career-ending campaign. If he fails
to win this seat, once held by Chiles and now being vacated by
retiring Republican Connie Mack, Nelson will once again be banished
to political oblivion. Nelson is determined not to go back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be one tough race,'' Nelson said Tuesday.
``You have their state party chairman already promising to do
everything they can to stop me from winning. I think they've made
it pretty clear that they are going to come after me and I'm going
to respond back as hard and as forcefully as I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson insists, however, that he has no intention of taking the
low road. ``People are tired of that kind of politics,'' Nelson
said. ``This is going to be a campaign of character and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   He bristles at McCollum's new campaign warning ``Bill Clinton,
Bill Nelson, Al Gore'' they're all the same. But Nelson insists
he's not backing away from the Clinton presidency, ``and some of
the remarkable things they have done for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum's tactic will backfire, said Nelson, because, ``it will
remind people of McCollum's sanctimonious image'' during the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Both men will be clashing on issues about Social Security,
Medicare, HMO reform and a host of other key Florida issues, Nelson
said. ``There are clear differences between the two of us and in
the coming weeks I believe the voters are going to see those
differences very clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Democrats also believe Nelson's campaign is helped by
Gore's choice of Lieberman as his running mate. Lieberman, the
first Jew on a national ticket, has generated considerable
excitement in Florida's Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lieberman is a great choice for Florida because I think the
enthusiasm for him will help Democrats all the way down the ballot,
and that includes Bill Nelson,'' said Bob Poe, chairman of the
state Democratic Party. During his Senate campaign announcement in
May, Nelson said he was particularly touched when Rhea Chiles,
Lawton Chiles' widow, spoke to the crowd and told them that she
wanted Nelson to have Chiles' old senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it showed that if you do things right and hold your
head high,'' Nelson said, ``you can move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
