<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2962 &Cx1f; tad-z
b p BC-CVN-MAIN16-1STLD-COX     08-15 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MAIN16-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PARTY'S LIBERAL LIONS ROAR FOR GORE
 &HT;    Eds: Recasts top, adds fresh quotes throughout.
 &HT;    800&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats recalled their party's progressive past
Tuesday, emotionally linking the ``New Frontier'' of John F.
Kennedy to the ``New Heights'' they envision under Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It was a night devoted to the champions of the party's liberal
wing, in eclipse for decades after a string of presidential defeats
and the ascendancy of Democratic centrists.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they trooped to the podium to declare that the
ideals they embodied were alive and well _ and would be in good
hands under a President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even keynote speaker Harold Ford Jr., at age 30 the youngest
member of Congress, told the delegates, ``I also stand here
representing a new generation _ a generation committed to the
ideals of the past but inspired by unshakable confidence in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, the only surviving member
of Kennedy's immediate family, stirred memories of her assassinated
father with a rare appearance before the convention that will
formally nominate Gore on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are the New Frontier,'' she said, making the
connection between her father's generation and Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Strains from the Broadway musical ``Camelot'' greeted
Schlossberg as she reached the podium to add her voice to the
chorus of praise for Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg followed other members of the Democratic Party's
most famous family to the podium in the standing-room-only Staples
Center in the heart of the city where Kennedy was nominated in
1960.
</P>
<P>
   Her uncle, Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, and two
cousins, Robert F. Kennedy Jr., an environmental activist, and
Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, the lieutenant governor of Maryland,
also addressed the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. Kennedy Jr., who was 6 years old when his uncle became
the Democratic standard-bearer in 1960, noted that ``at that
convention, our party launched the new frontier with a Democratic
frontier.'' He added, ``This year, we will launch a new millennium
with a great national leader who will make history by validating
our nation's legacy for world leadership and environmental
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Townsend said the Democratic Party ``made history (in 1960) by
summoning the best of our country, challenging Americans to
serve.'' This year, she added, ``with renewed resolve, we'll make
history again.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Jesse Jackson, the most dynamic and most recognized
liberal voice of the party today, also electrified the delegates on
the so-called ``New Heights'' night of the convention with spirited
rhetoric that ridiculed the Republican Party's recent convention as
an ``inclusion illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also roused the delegates with a harsh critique of
Republican nominee George W. Bush's record as governor of Texas and
a reminder that ``Papa Bush,'' the governor's father, former
President George Bush, had elevated Clarence Thomas, a conservative
foe of affirmative action, to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   At several points, Jackson led the more than 4,000 delegates in
chants: ``Stay out of the Bushes,'' ``More with Gore'' and his
signature ``Keep hope alive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson also reminded his fellow Democrats of the ``moral
disgrace'' of one in five American children living in poverty in a
time of unprecedented economic wealth and the ``great divide''
between the affluence of Beverly Hills and the poverty of South
Central Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He also blessed the Democratic ticket of Gore, a Southern
Baptist, and Lieberman, a Jew, as ``the All-American team.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman paid a surprise visit to the convention floor Tuesday
night, and convention organizers immediately broadcast a video of
Kennedy declaring in 1960 that his religious beliefs _ he was
Catholic _ were ``not relevant'' to his campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket also got the blessing of former Sen. Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, who carried the liberal wing's banner in the Democratic
primaries against Gore this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who was highly critical of the vice president during
the primaries, vowed to ``work hard'' for Gore and other Democrats
this fall because ``our country needs a Democratic president, a
Democratic Congress and most important, a Democratic conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his former opponent, he said, ``When you run against someone,
you get to know him very well. I learned that Al Gore is a man of
wide-ranging intellect, with a deep desire to serve, profound
preparation for the job, a strong sense of loyalty, and a life view
infused with tolerance and rooted in religious faith.''
</P>
<P>
   But like Jackson, Bradley urged the party on to new heights,
specifically to ending child poverty in America and vanquishing
``the insidious bond between big money and political decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russ Feingold of Wisconsin, the co-sponsor of campaign
finance reforms with Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Bush's chief
opponent in the GOP primaries, urged the Democratic Party to
prohibit the raising of so-called ``soft money'' at future
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot stand before you ... without mentioning my concern
and dismay that soft money fund-raising has become so much a part
of this convention,'' Feingold said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who campaigned Tuesday in Michigan with President Clinton
in a symbolic passing of the torch, arrives in Los Angeles on
Wednesday to claim the party's presidential nomination, the
culmination of his 24 years in public office.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day gathering of Democrats, which began Monday, is not
confined to the nomination of Gore and Lieberman and an approval of
a platform of principles on which they two will run this fall: It
also an unusually ripe opportunity for the party to raise funds
with the help of powerful friends in the city's entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The party platform vowed to make the McCain-Feingold bill ``the
first piece of legislation in a Democratic administration.'' It
also committed the party to support ``a public-private, nonpartisan
endowment to raise money to finance congressional elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The platform, approved by the state delegations voting on sleek
iMac computers donated by Apple, also pledged support for abortion
rights, affirmative action, increasing the number of police, DNA
testing in some death penalty cases, putting 1 million new teachers
in classrooms, mandatory child safety locks for guns, expanded
health insurance for families, using budget surpluses to shore up
Social Security and Medicare and tax cuts targeted to middle class
families.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
