<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-KENNEDY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KENNEDYS SHINE AT DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was a night filled with the echoes of Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the Kennedy family spoke Tuesday to the
Democratic National Convention, culminating in a ringing
endorsement of Al Gore and Joe Lieberman by Sen. Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has only been three times in my life that I have
supported anyone as early and enthusiastically as Al Gore. Two of
them were my brothers,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But it may have been the family member who introduced the
Massachusetts senator, Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg, who was most
affectionately welcomed by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of the late President John F. Kennedy, Schlossberg
has been the most reluctant of her family to seek the spotlight.
But she stepped to the Democratic podium Tuesday to introduce her
uncle, inheriting the public role played by her brother, John
Kennedy Jr., until his death in a plane crash last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it is our turn to prove that the New Frontier was not a
place in time but a timeless call. Now, we are the New Frontier.
And now, when many of us are doing so well, it is time once again
to ask more of ourselves,'' said Schlossberg, evoking the rhetoric
of the Camelot era.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg told the Democrats that Gore's parents had been
matchmakers who helped bring the late president and her mother, the
late Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, together.
</P>
<P>
   And Ted Kennedy poignantly recalled how Caroline told her father
he'd been elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember election night in November of 1960. The results
were so close that my brother went to bed still not certain that he
had won. It was nearly dawn when victory finally became clear. And
here is how Jack learned about it _ from 3-year-old Caroline, who
woke him up by jumping on his bed and shouting, ``Good morning, Mr.
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time he ever heard those words from anyone,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the last one left. This is like a sentimental journey
for me to come back and see her in the same place where her father
was nominated,'' said Mike Vinich, a Wyoming delegate whose Marine
company was rescued in the Pacific during World War II by three PT
boats, including the one captained by JFK.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles holds bittersweet memories for the Kennedy family.
John F. Kennedy accepted the presidential nomination at the 1960
convention here, and the late president's connections with
Hollywood through Peter Lawford and other stars added to the
glamour of Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   But the late president's brother, Robert Kennedy, was
assassinated in a hotel near the hall whether the Democrats
gathered this year on the night he won the California presidential
primary in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many comparisons with the 1960 convention this
week, because Kennedy was the first Roman Catholic to be nominated
by a major party, and Lieberman, who will accept the
vice-presidential nomination Wednesday night, will be the first
Orthodox Jew on a major party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``How proud he would be of Al Gore and our party and the new
barrier of bigotry we are breaking down with the choice of Joe
Lieberman as the next vice president of the United States,'' Sen.
Kennedy said of his late brother.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Maryland Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend,
42, a member of the party's platform committee, spoke on technology
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've re-established America as a lighthouse of prosperity and
hope. But this didn't happen automatically and there's no guarantee
it will continue,'' said Ms. Townsend.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Robert Kennedy Jr., also spoke Tuesday night. He,
too, invoked images from John Kennedy's administration to discuss a
contemporary concern, the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time that I was in Los Angeles for a convention was
in 1960 when I was 6 years old,'' he said. ``At that convention,
our party launched the new frontier with a Democratic president.
This year, we will launch a new millennium with a great national
leader who will make history by validating our nation's legacy for
world leadership and environmental responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kennedy's son, Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island, 33,
spoke in the convention's opening session Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The program brought back memories of the 1960 convention to
Georgia Agriculture Secretary Tommy Irvin, the dean of the state's
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from the South, we were pledged to Johnson. But when
Kennedy came and spoke to our delegation, he turned me around. The
thing about Kennedy was he so energized me that as a second-term
legislator, I felt I had to go home and do everything,'' Irvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely a meaningful day to me. Because I think
that time really was Camelot. For people our age, it was the dream
age for politics, for family, for everything that was great. It was
just like a glorious era, and I think a lot of us want it to come
back,'' said Miki Pavelonis, 58, a delegate from Harrisboro,
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
