<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-DEM-HNS &LR;      08-15 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DEM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DEMOCRATS' LIBERAL LIONS GIVE GORE ROAR OF APPROVAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN &QL; 
C.2000 Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democrats promoted their traditional cause of
social equality Tuesday, striving to unify liberals behind
presidential candidate Al Gore and rekindle the inspiration of
President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton off the national convention stage and
Gore yet to arrive, the podium bustled with the adoption of a
platform and speeches by four Kennedys, three labor union
presidents, abortion and gay rights activists, former Gore foe Bill
Bradley, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a featured, young black
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   In lockstep, they touted Gore as the standard-bearer for the
Democratic mission of making sure that rights and riches spread
beyond the privileged few. It was a message that laid the
groundwork for Gore to tell middle-of-the-road voters that there is
a difference of vital substance between the Democratic and
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the day's energy was also spent on uniting the
party's left wing behind the relatively moderate message of Gore
and vice-presidential nominee Joseph Lieberman. National voter
surveys continued to indicate Tuesday that Republicans are more
solidly behind GOP nominee George W. Bush of Texas than Democrats
are behind the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman himself worked the unity message Tuesday. He met here
with black delegates and congressmen _ some of whom had blasted his
stances on affirmative action and school vouchers _ and earned
standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   At a Michigan campaign rally, Clinton, Gore and their wives
presented Gore as the key to continuing the country's economic
growth. It was a symbolic political handoff, with Gore making his
way to the convention and Clinton heading off to the final months
of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ford Jr., a 30-year-old congressman from Gore's home
state of Tennessee, said in the prepared text of his keynote
address that the Democratic ticket ``believes the future is for
everyone'' while Republicans ``would have us go back to a past
where prosperity touches only the well-off and well-connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who ran for the Democratic presidential nomination in
previous years, denounced Bush and his family's political record _
``Stay out of the Bushes,'' the civil rights leader chanted _ and
portrayed the White House contest as a stark economic choice.
</P>
<P>
   Infusing the convention with an indignation that few speakers
displayed at the GOP convention, Jackson said Bush and running mate
Dick Cheney would give most of the federal budget surplus ``to
those who are already doing just fine (while) the Gore-Lieberman
team says the money should be used to make America stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This contest is not about race or religion,'' Jackson
continued, ``but about resource distribution and budget
priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who lost a bitter primary contest to Gore, delivered an
unrestrained endorsement of Gore and said he would work hard for a
Democratic victory.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the party to take up the cause of campaign reform and
said his differences with Gore were small compared to their harmony
on policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't read my lips _ watch what we do,'' the former senator
and basketball star said, arguing that the Democrats practice
diversity and quality while the Republicans only preach it.
</P>
<P>
   But speeches by U.S. Sen. Edward Kennedy and his niece, Caroline
Kennedy Schlossberg, provided the emotional center of the
convention's second day.
</P>
<P>
   President Kennedy _ brother of Edward and father of Schlossberg
_ was nominated for president at a Los Angeles convention in 1960.
JFK was assassinated three years into his White House term. His
other child, John F. Kennedy Jr., died in a plane crash last year.
</P>
<P>
   Schlossberg, making her first speech to a Democratic convention,
invoked her father's policy agenda, called the New Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are the New Frontier,'' she said. `` ... As much as we
need a prosperous economy, we also need a prosperity of kindness
and decency'' that Gore would strive to install.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that my father's spirit lives on and I thank all of
you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kennedy said Gore, in contrast with the Republicans,
would expand health care benefits and related consumer rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us not turn back to old policies and old ways that favor
the few at the expense of the many,'' the Massachusetts senator
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just after Lieberman entered the convention hall to hear
Schlossberg and the senator speak, the convention displayed a film
of JFK telling voters in 1960 that he should not be judged by his
religion. He was the first Roman Catholic president; Lieberman is
the first Jew on a major party presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland Lt. Gov. Kathleen Kennedy Townsend and environmental
lawyer Robert F. Kennedy Jr., also spoke Tuesday. They are the
children of U.S. Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, who was assassinated in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Democrats stand not just for the success of the few, but
for opportunity for all,'' Townsend said, sounding the evening's
theme of economic equality.
</P>
<P>
   On-scene Republican officials criticized the Democratic
proceedings Tuesday, just as Democratic leaders slammed the GOP
gathering in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore said the Democratic convention has not
seen Gore yet because there is an attempt to downplay Gore's
desire, as expressed in his book ``Earth in the Balance,'' to
eliminate the internal combustion engine or tax fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the candidate? He's a shadowy figure in the background
that they seem to want to hide as long as they can,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer criticized Jackson's speech as
``old-style attack politics'' and said that if Gore ``was serious
about renouncing personal attacks and unkind words, he shouldn't
have allowed his surrogates to do it for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is campaigning on the idea that the GOP would spread
economic prosperity to all levels of society, not conform to the
stereotype of Republicans serving only the upper class.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the downtown sports arena where the Democrats met,
political protesters carried out peaceful demonstrations under the
watch of hundreds of police officers equipped to suppress riot.
There were 45 arrests Tuesday _ mostly of animal-rights advocates,
who banged on windows and painted over signs at clothing stores
that sell fur. On Monday night, police and demonstrators clashed
violently at the end of a rock concert in the designated protest
area.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic platform, tracking Gore's agenda, calls for an
expansive federal role in education, a Medicare prescription drug
benefit, more health insurance programs for children and tax
credits for retirement savings and college savings.
</P>
<P>
   The ``targeted tax cuts'' and programs that would be funded with
the surplus contrast with Bush's call for across-the-board tax
cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The platform supports affirmative action, gun control, a
stronger military defense and stronger enforcement of environmental
laws. It reaffirms support for abortion rights and says that
abortion opponents are welcome into the party.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, told the convention that ``a
value at America's heart is threatened'' because Bush would appoint
Supreme Court judges who would outlaw abortion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
