<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LINEMAN GETTING KOSHER TREATMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA can sell recruits on sunshine, Hollywood and
academics. Now the the Bruins have added a new sales pitch: We've
got kosher.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big reason why Eyoseph Efseaff, a freshman guard from
Porterville, chose UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Efseaff's family are Russian Molokans, who not only follow the
New Testament of the Bible like most Christians but also all tenets
of the Old Testament, as traditional Jews do. Hence, the kosher
diet.
</P>
<P>
   Efseaff, who said he was recruited by most Pac-10 schools, said
UCLA was one of the few schools he could attend. There are a
handful of small Molokan communities in the Southland, but a large
Jewish community on the Westside will make keeping a kosher diet
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Kosher principals were formed as a way to maintain sanitary
eating conditions. Bottom-dwelling fish, for example, are thought
to be unhealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use the word unclean,'' Efseaff said. ``We can't eat pork
or shellfish or catfish (animals that are deemed unclean in the Old
Testament). It has to be prepared in a clean pan. It also has to be
killed a certain way. You have to cut the throat and bleed the
animal. You can't hit it over the head or shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has provided Efseaff with a list of restaurants that
prepare and/or deliver kosher food. At last week's beach barbecue
for incoming freshman, a box of kosher food was brought for
Efseaff.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Taylor, UCLA's Director of Football Operations, said the
team has had Muslims who wouldn't eat pork, but never had to
accommodate a kosher diet before
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't eat everything that's at the dorms,'' said Taylor.
``He's not real demanding _ he'd eat bagels all day _ but it's
important for him to maintain good nutrition to keep his weight up
(as an offensive lineman). It's our responsibility to take care of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Efseaff, his ethnic name notwithstanding, is a third-generation
American. His great-grandparents emigrated to the United States in
1902, at a time when the Cossacks were persecuting religious
minorities in Russia. About 2,500 Molokans _ who refused to join
the Russian Orthodox Church in the 1600s _ came to America at the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   There are about a dozen Molokan families in Porterville. Efseaff
said the distinguishing characteristics are a strong elder system
and that all church business is conducted in Russian, a language he
hopes to be fluent in by the time he leaves college.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line coach Mark Weber said Efseaff, who is 6-foot-3
and 282 pounds, has had little trouble distinguishing himself, both
on the field and off, where he carried a 3.9 GPA at Monache
(Calif.) High.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of things to learn,'' Weber said. ``But he's
got all the intangibles, he's smart and he plays hard. He's got a
lot of discipline. He's very business-like for an 18-year-old. He's
very committed to his goals, whether it's personal, in football or
spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   TOLEDO RESPONDS: Bob Toledo denied a claim by a USC freshman
that the UCLA head coach lied to him about the way the Trojans were
recruiting him.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Kenechi Udeze said in Tuesday's Daily News
that he chose USC because Toledo told him, ``I was no longer
(USC's) No.1 prospect. ... I knew it wasn't true. So I knew I
couldn't go there after he said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Toledo: ``I never said what he said. I don't lie and I
don't negative recruit. I have no idea if he was their first
recruit or their 10th. That comment really bothered me ... for
someone to call me a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he wouldn't use the comment for motivation when UCLA
plays the Trojans in November because Udeze ``won't even be
playing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
