<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAL STATE NORTHRIDGE HOPES TO IMPROVE LINE PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The hope is that Cal State Northridge quarterback
Marcus Brady won't have to scramble so much this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors offensive line didn't offer much protection last
year. Three returning starters and a couple of newcomers have CSUN
coach Jeff Kearin hopeful this group will make marked improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have big guys, they're more athletic, more agile and
definitely stronger and in better shape,'' Kearin said. ``It's
refreshing. Where we're weak is depth. We're two or three injuries
away from being desperate. If we lose two or three on either side
of the ball we could be in trouble. But our job as coaches is to
make sure that doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier Ortiz (6-foot-3, 285 pounds), Keith Kincaid (6-4, 285)
and Johnny Acosta (6-5, 300) were part of a line that allowed 37
sacks, an average of 3.4 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were young and inexperienced and we really didn't
connect,'' Ortiz said. ``There was no unity. Now we have unity. We
know how to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was a disaster last year. CSUN managed to average
450.3 yards per game, including 313.2 yards through the air. Even
though the starting running back position is open following the
graduation of Jaumal Bradley, Ortiz hopes CSUN will run more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year everybody was emphasizing the pass because our line
blocking wasn't that good,'' Ortiz said. ``This year we'll try to
run the ball more to catch them off guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz _ a transfer from Fresno State _ walked on the team last
year but received a scholarship this season.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Jamar Ikpi out of Pomona High and freshman Tyrone
Tutogi of Hueneme Oxnard are expected to battle for starting spots.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR A RUNNING BACK: Returning running back Alan Taylor,
Terrelus Wright _ a transfer from Arizona Western College _ and
redshirt freshman Bruce Molock are expected to compete for the
starting running back spot in the Matadors' one-back offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wide open,'' Kearin said. ``We have a lot of good
players, but we don't have a true speed guy. (Taylor) played some
last year and he ended the spring as the heir apparent. But he has
some big shoes to fill with Jaumal Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER GARDNER INJURY: Isaac Gardner _ who's moving from
linebacker to defensive back _ left Tuesday morning's practice with
a bruised right quadriceps muscle. Gardner iced the injury and is
expected to be OK. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
