<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS D-LINE GETS A BOOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC's depleted defensive line received a boost
when incoming freshman tackle Malcolm Woolridge decided to play for
the Trojans and was scheduled to arrive in training camp Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge (6-foot-2, 290 pounds) committed to USC two years ago
but did not academically qualify. He then committed to Miami but
ended up attending prep school in Virginia last year.
</P>
<P>
   He was cleared by the NCAA this week and accepted a scholarship
offer from the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like about him, back then he was 340 (pounds) and
could move,'' defensive line coach Ed Orgeron said. ``He has great
feet. He has to come in and develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge was scheduled to fly in Tuesday from his hometown of
Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He will probably redshirt, but his presence will help offset the
losses of freshman Sagan Atuatasi, who did not qualify
academically, and freshman Jamaal Williams, who is out four to six
weeks with a broken right leg.
</P>
<P>
   It will also mean the Trojans will not have to move another
player to defensive line for practice drills.
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge's arrival is not a reaction to the failure of Atuatasi
to be admitted, because USC had offered Woolridge a scholarship
provided he meet the necessary requirements following prep school.
</P>
<P>
   PAPADAKIS OUT: Tailback Petros Papadakis will miss today's
closed scrimmage at Orange Coast College and probably be out two
days after his foot ``locked up'' and became stiff. He was wearing
a boot during Tuesday's afternoon practice and is still recovering
from last season's broken foot. He and offensive guard Trevor
Roberts (sprained foot) are the only players expected to be held
out.
</P>
<P>
   NO FULLBACK CONTROVERSY: There might some question as to who
will start at tailback, but senior Charlie Landrigan is the clear
choice at fullback, with sophomore Chad Pierson the backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landrigan, he's a bulldog waiting to bite your head off,''
running backs coach Kennedy Pola said. ``He will be the starter.''
</P>
<P>
   KICKING CONCERNS: Today is a D-day of sorts for the kicking
game, as Hackett expects to narrow the kicking field from three to
two or possibly award the position to junior David Newbury, who is
the leader.
</P>
<P>
   How the kickers perform in today's scrimmage will play a large
role in who wins the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll make a decision,'' Hackett said. ``Last year, we
took the position to wait before the first game, and I don't think
it was the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett would like to choose a kicker to allow more time for
holder Ife Ohalete and snapper Joe Boscovich of Westlake High to
become comfortable with whomever wins the job.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of today's scrimmage will be special teams and the
running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be a running team, and we have to stop the run,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said the scrimmage will last around 100 plays, and he
will again take a long look at the freshmen and reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really important is that the young guys have a chance
to show what they can do,'' Hackett said. ``And where they fit
in.''
</P>
<P>
   NO LONGER A WEAK SPOT: Strongside linebacker Kori Dickerson has
received positive reviews from Hackett in training camp and
continues to hold the starting position even though he was a
defensive end his first two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has improved as much as anyone on the defense,'' Hackett
said. ``Had we done this two years ago, there's no telling where he
could be. But we didn't. Thank goodness he has two years left.''
</P>
<P>
   KELLY REBOUNDS: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly (strained knee) has
resumed practicing and is scheduled to participate in today's
scrimmage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
